<HEADLINE>
MUSTANGS ARE YOUNG, HURT, NOT HOPELESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The SMU Mustangs discarded their unpopular red jerseys with the
New York Jets sleeves and returned to conventional blue last
weekend, not that it did much good.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hawaii discarded two ugly losing streaks, including one
of 15 in a row on the road and another involving 24 consecutive
road losses in WAC play that dated to a time when no one outside of
Arkansas had ever heard of the Clinton family. The 20-0 romp was
the third consecutive victory for the Rainbow Warriors (3-1), who
had previously snapped the nation's longest losing streak at 19
with a home victory against NCAA Division I-AA Eastern Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   This one was witnessed by 15,131 mostly distraught fans at the
Cotton Bowl, and if matters do not improve quickly, the next home
throng might be closer to 1,500. The Mustangs are 0-3 and have been
shut out twice and outscored, 99-19.
</P>
<P>
   Is SMU really that bad?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly, but the view from The Hilltop is not a cheery
one at the moment. In the finest tradition of American soap opera,
the Mustangs are young, hurt, and riding a string of bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Before the season's opening snap, three of the team's best
players _ a defensive lineman and two veterans of the offensive
line _ were lost for the year through surgery. Linebacker Vic
Viloria, the WAC defensive freshman of the year in '98, is
academically ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   In the season opener against Arkansas, 26 Mustangs played their
first college game. Tackle to tackle, the offensive line consisted
of five players who had never played their respective positions.
</P>
<P>
   In the debacle against Hawaii, the Mustangs fumbled a scoring
chance at the 2-yard line and had two touchdowns _ a 70-yard run
and an interception return _ erased by penalties. Thus far,
freshmen and sophomores have accounted for 90 percent of the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously have a long way to go,'' SMU coach Mike Cavan
said. ``We've been through this before, and as coaches we just have
to keep our heads up and hope the kids will follow. But I don't
think I've ever had a team where this many things went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a win, and about all I can say is, hope is never
lost.'' Around the WAC Although his team is involved in a presumed
``showdown'' with Fresno State this week, TCU's Dennis Franchione
says there might not be a farthing's difference between top and
bottom in the WAC. ``I wouldn't be surprised if the eventual
champion has two (league) losses,'' he said. ``Right now, it looks
like anybody can beat anybody any time.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Hawaii. June Jones turned down a chance to
coach the San Diego Chargers to return ``home,'' brought in 25
fresh players, installed the run-and-shoot (NFL version), hired
Greg McMackin (Seahawks) as defensive coordinator, and is 3-1 at a
program generally regarded as Doormat of the Foreseeable Future.
``It's not always how good you are,'' Jones said. ``It's a matter
of putting 11 guys out there all going in the same direction.'' If
so, it's a new direction for the Rainbows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a tough road trip out there,'' says UT-El Paso's
Charlie Bailey, whose Miners (2-2) will make the trip this week.
``I don't think we've got anybody on the squad who's ever been to
Hawaii _ but they've all heard about it, and that's the problem.
While you're out there lookin' at the beach, they roll you under.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bailey, who began coaching when the Beatles were young
(1964) and never met a Lost Cause he couldn't love, does not roll
under easily. Last year he was the old WAC's Pacific Division coach
of the year in ``The Sporting News'' for going 3-8 (with several
near-misses) at a program suffering from long-term futility and
loss of scholarships through NCAA penalty. Last week, he dragged
his team 45 miles up the road for a grudge match in Las Cruces
against an ancient arch-foe (New Mexico State) that was 3-0 and had
just whipped Arizona State by four touchdowns. He won, 54-23. ``We
got (running back) Elzie Johnson back, and we just kinda
exploded,'' he explained, innocently.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Rice (1-3), fresh off losses to Michigan and _ by
five points _ Texas, displaying signs in Saturday's victory against
Navy that it has abandoned its mistake-prone mode of the first two
weeks and is back to normal Owls football. One quarterback got hurt
and the other ran for 105 yards. Rice won with one turnover and 37
minutes in time of possession. This would not normally be
remarkable except that the foe was fellow spread-option devotee
Navy _ which should know how to handle this stuff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
