<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets top Braves, halt skid at seven
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets registered a pulse on Wednesday night just
in time to flatline Greg Maddux's chances of 20 wins, kill the
Braves' eight-game winning streak and save their own postseason
hides with a 9-2 win.
</P>
<P>
   Jarring themselves out of a seven-loss spiral with a seven-run
fourth inning, the Mets chased Maddux with the kind of inning that
they had to figure was a long time coming.
</P>
<P>
   It started humbly but just wouldn't stop. All eight batters
Maddux faced collected hits, some of which barely made it out of
the infield. But by the time John Olerud came to the plate, Maddux
couldn't keep the ball in the yard. Olerud drove the sixth grand
slam of his career to the Mets' bullpen in right field to complete
the worst inning of Maddux's season and possibly his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give them credit,'' Maddux said. ``They put the
ball in play and found some holes and Olerud got the big hit. I
wasn't really too upset with how I pitched in that inning. I was
upset with the outcome. I thought that was a pretty good pitch (the
fastball to Olerud), bad pitch selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud's homer made it 8-2 Mets and basically 19-9 on the season
for Maddux, who left the game a Mike Piazza single later for his
earliest exit of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had scored nine runs in their previous four games
against the Braves _ all losses. The win kept them 1 1/2 back of
both the Reds and Astros in the wild-card standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were due, I think,'' said Brian Jordan, who drove in the
Braves' runs. ``We've been fortunate. They got the bounces
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the night, the Braves needed three wins in their final
five games to guarantee themselves home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The loss broke a string of six consecutive wins Maddux has had
against the Mets going back to 1996 and meant the Braves won't have
a 20-game winner for the first time since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go figure,'' Maddux said. ``Probably my worst year in a while
and I have a chance to win 20. I'm disappointed about it. (But) I
think I'm ready for next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux has lost three of his past four starts after winning
eight in a row. Not much of a postseason tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to end the way I ended today,'' Maddux said.
``But I feel good about the way I've thrown the ball, felt good
about the way I threw the ball tonight. Everybody knows our season
starts next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
