<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTROS DRAW EVEN WITH REDS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MELANIE HAUSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The race is back even.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it seemed as though the red-hot Cincinnati Reds might
be too much for the wilting Houston Astros, Mike Hampton, the
Astros' best pitcher, stepped up and the Houston bats woke up.
Before 52,242 fans in the Astrodome Wednesday night, the Astros
erased the one-game lead the Reds had grabbed the night before and
regained a tie in the National League Central with a 4-1 victory,
ending Cincinnati's six-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams now lead the New York Mets by a game and a half for
the wild-card spot and both will take Thursday off before closing
out the regular season. The Astros will be home against the Los
Angeles Dodgers in a three-game series, while the Reds finish up
with three games in Milwaukee against the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling at the plate Tuesday, the Astros made the most
of seven hits, including a two-run home run by Daryle Ward. But the
real key was on the mound, where Hampton looked every bit the Cy
Young award winner he should become.
</P>
<P>
   As another Astros 20-game winner, Jose Lima, who lost the first
game of the series, said before Wednesday night's game: ``We're
human, but we don't need to be losing ball games at this time of
the year. We need to do the things we did early in the year _ go
eight innings and give the ball to Billy Wagner to close the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton went eight innings and gave up one run on seven hits,
striking out eight, in running his record to 21-4 before letting
Wagner close it out. With one out in the ninth, Wagner got Mark
Lewis to line out to him, then doubled up catcher Jason LaRue at
first to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's 21 victories matches an Astros mark set in 1979 by Joe
Niekro. Wagner recorded his 38th save and 100th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the best part of the season?'' Hampton said after the
game. ``No, that'll be when we win the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Into the fourth inning of Wednesday night's game, there was a
World Series atmosphere in the Astrodome, which closes after this
season and has never been host to a Series. Although Hampton, who
is now 11-2 in the Astrodome this season, gave up a single off the
left-center-field wall to Sean Casey in the first inning, he shut
down the Reds after that. And Cincinnati's Steve Parris didn't
allow a hit until the third, when Tony Eusebio singled.
</P>
<P>
   In the Astros' fourth, with the game scoreless, Jeff Bagwell got
a three-run rally going when his sharp grounder spun shortstop
Barry Larkin around and forced a high throw _ and error _ to first.
Carl Everett then slammed a one-out double into the right-field
corner, sending Bagwell to third. Bagwell came across with the
first run of the game on a groundout by Ken Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ward took Parris' 1-2 pitch over the right-field wall for
his eighth home run of the year and the Astros' 166th of the season
to make it 3-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
