<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU DEFENDER TAKES LIFE EASY, PLAYS LIKE A WHIRLWIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When discussing defensive end Aaron Schobel, TCU coach Dennis
Franchione adopts a reverential tone, his voice filling with awe
and admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron,'' he says, ``has figured out in life how to do only as
much as is necessary to get the job done, in every situation. And
that's it ... there is absolutely no wasted energy.''
</P>
<P>
   After observing this phenomenon for three seasons, safety Curtis
Fuller is prepared to offer further evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see Aaron walking down the sidewalk,'' he said,
laughing, ``he looks like he's been sedated.''
</P>
<P>
   Schobel himself insists that this is a simple misconception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not lazy,'' he says. ``I only ``appear'' to be lazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, this approach seems highly effective for the 6-foot-4,
244-pound junior from Columbus, who was an All-Western Athletic
Conference selection last year and seems destined to become TCU's
all-time sacks leader. With four in three games this year, he has
18 1/2 career sacks, chasing the school record of 22 set by Royal
West from 1991-94.
</P>
<P>
   Schobel, however, is no mere sack specialist. After forcing
three fumbles and blocking a kick last year, he has caused a fumble
and a safety this season. His two high-tackle career games came
against option teams, Rice and Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a good football player,'' Franchione says. ``He has
instincts a lot of people don't have about getting to the ball.
He's our pride, a tremendous competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Franchione adds, laughing, ``He'll make a tremendous play
and then look like he's so tired he'll never make another.''
</P>
<P>
   Schobel, who is joined on the team by brother Matt, a sophomore
wide receiver, and cousin Bo, a freshman defensive end, admits that
in most circumstances, he's not exactly hyper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate running,'' he says. ``It's such a nuisance. And I
absolutely dread practice ... 24 periods out there just doesn't
appeal to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even like to take notes in class. I'd rather just sit
there and listen, but the professors don't like it when you do
that. I walk real slow, I a guess I dress kind of sloppy, but it's
just the way I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm faster than I look, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Schobel's speed has been his major trademark as a
defensive end. After Arizona rushed for 14 yards and allowed six
sacks and two safeties, Wildcats coach Dick Tomey observed, ``Aaron
Schobel is a tremendous football player, he has such great speed.''
</P>
<P>
   He was fast enough to catch 98 passes during a high school
career in which he was variously a wide receiver, tight end,
defensive end and linebacker. Many of the passes were thrown by his
brother, an All-American high school quarterback who was originally
at Texas A&AMP;M but transferred to TCU last year and switched to wide
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``A&AMP;M also recruited me, as a tight end,'' Aaron Schobel says,
``but I wanted to play defense, and that's a big reason why I came
to TCU. I did OK at linebacker in high school but defensive end is
my position. I can see the field better from that spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Cousin Bo, a widely recruited defensive end and the son of
former TCU player Bob Schobel, arrived this year and now the three
Schobels share a house with backup quarterback Jeff Dover.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two families are partners in Schobel's Restaurant in
Columbus, so we were all pretty close growing up,'' Schobel says,
although he adds that this did not interfere with the usual
brotherly scrapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably had about a hundred,'' he says. ``I always won, of
course. Well, I guess he (brother Matt) finally won one, but it was
because someone was holding me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all making out OK now. We keep the house pretty neat,
although the yard may not always be mowed. We cook pretty well but
we don't do much of it, because our folks keep sending us food that
we just heat up.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Schobel is prepared to take some aspects of life as
they come, he has now become focused on at least one goal on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I never thought about at first,'' he says.
``But now, I really want that sack record.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
