<SLUG> BC-RUN-TEXAS-ARLINGTON-RUNNER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS-ARLINGTON RUNNER'S COMMITMENT PAYING OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Mishael Bertrand said it might have looked
like a lazy afternoon jog, when she ran up and down a two-way road
in her hometown of Pottsboro.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists honked their horns as they drove by. Sometimes, they
would wave, and Bertrand would wave back. Bertrand, a track athlete
at Texas-Arlington, said it was actually fun to see a lot of people
in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   But the road (Farm Road 120), which Bertrand calls ``the only
main one in town'' was her place of work, and she spent this past
summer being anything but lazy. Bertrand had measured distances
with her car and marked lines on the road.
</P>
<P>
   She started and stopped at different intervals to mix things up.
</P>
<P>
   Bertrand, much to the delight of Mavericks track and field coach
John Sauerhage, made an unexpected commitment to cross country. An
800-meter specialist, she started to see results halfway through
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called coach Sauerhage and told him I was excited about the
cross country season, and I don't think I've ever said that
before,'' Bertrand said. ``I felt like, last year, I let the cross
country team down. I wanted to prove this year that I could do it.
This time, I actually put a lot of effort and hard work into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two meets into the 1999 cross country season, Sauerhage could
see Bertrand's work on that road was paying dividends.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing 57th _ seventh on Texas-Arlington's team _ at
last season's Southland Conference Cross Country Championships,
Bertrand has opened her junior season with a bang. She was seventh
overall _ first on Texas-Arlington's squad _ at the Texas-Arlington
Invitational at Vandergriff Park on Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   One week later, she showed it wasn't a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Bertrand led the Mavericks again with a 12th-place finish at the
SMU Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Sauerhage said Bertrand's improvement, combined with a solid
recruiting class, has helped change his mind about his team's
chances this fall, and he has gone from waiting for the indoor
season to thinking his team could win the SLC title.
</P>
<P>
   Texas-Arlington has three meets before the Nov. 1 SLC meet.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are scheduled to compete Friday at the UNT
Invitational in Denton.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I get so fired up about her is that I've
seen her do some things that are borderline world class,''
Sauerhage said. ``This is world class, the way she has decided to
step up and commit herself to doing whatever it takes to improve.
Some people talk and daydream about doing great things. Mishael is
actually doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   A better season in cross country is the immediate goal at the
end of Bertrand's road, but she said it's not the ultimate one.
Bertrand's specialty is the 800 meters, and she said she considers
herself more of a sprinter than a distance runner.
</P>
<P>
   She was the 1997 Class 3A state champion in the 800 meters and
the runner-up in the 400.
</P>
<P>
   During the last outdoor track season, Bertrand ran a season-best
time of 2 minutes, 9.72 seconds at the Texas-Arlington Open. She
went on to win the SLC title, but she finished below the NCAA
automatic qualifying time of 2:05.00.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a lot of speed and a lot of endurance in the
800,'' Bertrand said. ``I've always had speed. What I've lacked is
the endurance to last two laps. Training for cross country will
give me a lot of strength in the 800.''
</P>
<P>
   Sauerhage said Bertrand could trim five seconds off her time,
enough to qualify for nationals.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said he can see a 2:04 or 2:03 in Bertrand's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has to be stronger, and it's apparent that she has
recognized that,'' Sauerhage said. ``When you have speed, strength
and confidence, you can pop a big race. The first thing for her to
do is be an NCAA qualifier, and that's not dreaming. She has that
kind of talent. Cross country is just a bonus. No matter how she
finishes in that, she is laying the groundwork for a great track
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertrand laid that groundwork on that road in Pottsboro, the
``only main one in town.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
