<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OKLAHOMA-LINEMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA LINEMAN HAS SEEN BAD TIMES, SOME GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ Oklahoma offensive guard Jay Smith couldn't be
blamed if he was bitter toward the Sooners' football program.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the 6-foot-4, 295-pound senior signed with
Oklahoma out of Lamar High School. Smith said he was impressed with
the Sooners' tradition of winning, especially in 1993 when Oklahoma
defeated five Southwest Conference teams.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sooners have been anything but traditional during his
time at Oklahoma. And Smith has had anything but a conventional
career with the Sooners.
</P>
<P>
   He's experienced two near-debilitating injuries, seen a
revolving door of coaches and languished through three consecutive
losing seasons. But when No. 23 Oklahoma takes the field Saturday
against Notre Dame in South Bend, Ind., Smith will see the Sooners
return to the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the turmoil, Smith said he doesn't regret his decision
to play here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned more as a person about life, about playing for so
many coaches, assistant coaches, position coaches and learning all
their different philosophies,'' he said. ``This year, they're
working hard to turn this thing around. I don't think I would have
learned this much about life playing at one place with one coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's six-year tenure at Oklahoma has earned him the
distinction of being the first football player in NCAA history to
have played for four head coaches. With one redshirt year and one
medical hardship year, he's also been around long enough to
experience the Sooners' early resurgence this season. It is as if
he's come full circle.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is an experienced veteran lineman in a dynamic
pass-oriented attack that has the 3-0 Sooners leading the nation in
scoring, total offense and passing. Smith's primary job at left
guard is to protect quarterback Josh Heupel and give the nation's
total-offense leader time to throw the football.
</P>
<P>
   Simply getting to play in the nationally televised game against
a team steeped with tradition is motivation enough for Smith, who
has battled through two Achilles' tendon injuries at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I'd be around for this game,'' he said. ``I
worked hard all summer to get ready to play in this game. It's an
important game for the program _ and for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Losing seasons haven't gotten to him as much as missing games
after undergoing surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if I was ever going to play again,'' said Smith,
who was on crutches for four months. ``The changing of coaches
hasn't been a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith played for Gary Gibbs, Howard Schnellenberger, John Blake
and now Bob Stoops. The constant for Smith has been former
assistant coach Merv Johnson, who recruited Smith and remains with
the Oklahoma program as director of football operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Johnson) was an old-time coach and I wanted to play for him
and I wanted to play in the Big Eight and play in the Orange
Bowl,'' Smith said. ``The tradition here is huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he had no desire to play for a SWC school, but he
didn't realize the Big 12 Conference was forming until he arrived
at OU in the fall of 1994. ``If I'd known, I would have looked at
the Texas schools in the Big 12,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith isn't looking back. He's happy with the medical
hardship ruling that allowed him the sixth year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a chance to prove to everyone that I could come back
from two major injuries in the same place,'' he said. ``I've proven
to everyone that I can come back and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith takes some kidding for his longevity.
</P>
<P>
   Junior fullback Seth Littrell calls Smith ``one of our old men
around here.'' Offensive coordinator Mike Leach said Smith
``probably has played for more coaches than I've worked for.''
</P>
<P>
   But offensive line coach Mark Mangino, who works with Smith on
the Sooners' new blocking techniques, said he appreciates Smith's
experience: ``He really brings some age to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL fades in and out of his reality, said Smith, who's
working on a masters in business administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some days when I'm thinking about wanting to make
the NFL. And there are other days I think about wanting to make a
difference in the business world,'' he said. ``If I keep playing
and don't get injured, there could be some places where I can fit
in in the NFL. If not, I can complete my graduate school.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he's been part of the Sooners program for so long
amazes even Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``A weird thing dawned on me the other day out on the practice
field,'' Smith said. ``I leaned back and looked around and realized
that I'm about two months from being 24 years old and here I am out
here with guys 18, 19 and 20 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys playing football might play two or three years in
the NFL and they can be done at 24. Here I am still playing.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
