<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-NYT     09-30 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LAS VEGAS, GIULIANI RAISES $100,000, PLUS $29 AT CRAPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ As New York's City Hall was locked in a tense
standoff with the Brooklyn Museum of Art, New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani raised $100,000 for his almost-certain Senate campaign in
a casino hotel where the fountains dance in nightly shows to the
voices of Gene Kelly and Luciano Pavarotti.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was a preview of the pressures the mayor will face as
he simultaneously governs New York City while preparing for a
campaign that is expected to be the most expensive and brutal in
recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, city officials have been trading legal threats with
the Brooklyn museum over an exhibition, set to open Saturday, that
includes artwork the mayor has declared offensive. But Giuliani
himself is far from the escalating conflict, in the middle of a
three-day jaunt through Washington, Nevada and California that is
expected to be his single most lucrative fund-raising trip to date.
</P>
<P>
   His stop in Las Vegas also created some slightly incongruous
tableaux, as the mayor who boasts of curbing crime and banishing
sleaze from New York discussed his adventures at the craps table _
he won $29 _ and lauded the local casino magnates for their civic
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The host of Wednesday afternoon's fund-raiser, in Le Cirque
restaurant of the $1.9 billion Bellagio hotel, was Stephen Wynn,
the chief executive of Mirage Resorts and a major donor to both the
Republican and Democratic parties. The lunch for Giuliani, which
included Las Vegas' major casino owners, had been arranged by
Revlon billionaire Ronald Perelman, a supporter of Giuliani's and a
friend of Wynn's.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks at the lunch, Giuliani praised the guests for
helping to bring about the resurgence of Las Vegas, where gorgeous,
fake European hotels rise above the dust of the bad old hotels that
the Rat Pack made famous.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has boasted of curbing crime and banishing sleaze
from Times Square, also said he was not at all uncomfortable
raising money in a restaurant that was directly across from row
upon row of slot machines and blackjack tables, all under the
casino's yellow- and pink-fringed awnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the gambling industry in Las Vegas makes a tremendous
contribution,'' the mayor said in brief remarks to reporters after
the lunch, as the slot machines clanged in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor added that during his nearly 24-hour stay in Las Vegas
he had played craps for about an hour Tuesday night at the Bellagio
with Peter Powers, a former deputy mayor and Giuliani's longtime
friend. Giuliani reported that as he and Powers each won $29, a
patron of the casino had told him that he hoped the mayor would win
_ not at gambling, the mayor said, but in his pursuit of statewide
office.
</P>
<P>
   The lunch came in the middle of the three-day political trip by
the mayor to four fund-raising events that were expected to raise
$350,000 for his unannounced Senate race next year against Hillary
Rodham Clinton. Mrs. Clinton's aides say her goal is to raise $25
million for her campaign, and possibly $10 million of that by the
end of the year. Giuliani said this week that he expected to raise
$15 million to $20 million for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn, one of the most powerful men in Nevada, contributes
heavily to both major parties, although in the last five years he
has leaned toward the Republicans. During the last presidential
campaign, however, he attended a $25,000-a-plate Democratic Party
fund-raiser. And last spring, Rep. Charles Rangel, the Democrat
from Harlem, flew to Las Vegas to accept a $250,000 check from Wynn
for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn owns four casino hotels in Las Vegas as well as half of
another, the Monte Carlo. He is building a new casino in Atlantic
City, tentatively called Le Jardin, and spends enormous amounts of
time wooing politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn praised Giuliani after the lunch for his ``fearless
approach'' and his ``very keen mind,'' but at the same time did not
appear to rule out having a fund-raiser for Mrs. Clinton. ``Well, I
haven't been asked,'' he said, when he was questioned about
planning any event for her. ``But this was a pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wynn at his side, Giuliani said he was in favor of
legalized gambling in New York City, and added that ``both New
Jersey and Nevada offer very good models of how to do it.'' In
Washington this week, Giuliani also said that he was in favor of it
as long as there is ``a commission to make sure that organized
crime stays out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani in fact established a commission in 1997 to investigate
the background of applicants for casino licenses, and through that
has made it difficult and expensive for struggling gambling boat
operators using the city's offshore waters.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has mentioned the federally owned Governors Island as
the possible site of a future casino, but only as a idea for years
in the future. A spokesman for Wynn said Wednesday that the casino
owner had no plans for any developments in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday evening Giuliani spoke at a Los Angeles fund-raiser at
the Beverly Hills Hotel, attended by 40 local Republican officials
and businessmen, where he was asked about the museum dispute in New
York. The mayor made no mention of his deputies' allegations that
the museum conspired with a private auction house to inflate the
value of the art displayed, and instead repeated that his primary
objection to the exhibit was its use of public money for what he
called a ``disgusting'' show.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he particularly objected to a painting of the
Virgin Mary surrounded with elephant dung and what he described as
``private parts of a woman's body splattered all over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
