<SLUG> BC-WM-MORRIS-AGENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WILLIAM MORRIS CHIEF DISMISSES 10 TALENT AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ At least 10 motion picture agents in New York and
Los Angeles were dismissed Wednesday by the William Morris talent
agency.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissals were made by Jim Wiatt, who recently became
president and co-chief executive of the 101-year-old agency.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Wiatt, who has been in the job only several weeks
after working at International Creative Management for 22 years,
stunned talent agents at William Morris as well as rival agents and
studio executives.
</P>
<P>
   Several longtime New York-based agents were among those
dismissed, including Gene Parseghian _ whose clients included Judi
Dench, Daniel Day-Lewis and Joseph Fiennes _ as well as Johnnie
Planco. Those two agents had worked for William Morris for more
than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear why Wiatt had moved so quickly to trim back the
agency, whose movie division had been overshadowed in recent years
by its highly successful music, television and literary units. In
the last week, at least four other talent agents had quit at
William Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt, and the agency, declined to comment. But a William Morris
executive close to Wiatt said the dismissals were not related to
cost-cutting as much as seeking to ``redefine'' the agency. ``It's
about Jim's vision of the future and the people with whom he wants
to grow the company with,'' said the executive, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But rivals in the talent-agency business were scathing in their
comments, speaking of ``the bloodletting'' at one of the most
stable, successful and enduring agencies in the entertainment
business.
</P>
<P>
   The head of one rival agency said executives at his company had
already received phone calls late Wednesday for jobs from some of
those dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Several rival agents said the central reason for the departures
seemed to be the influx of the new, high-priced agents to William
Morris from ICM _ besides Wiatt, an associate, David Wirtschafter _
and that this had led William Morris to oust some veterans.
</P>
<P>
   But the suddenness of the dismissals of agents in their 40s and
50s, who may now have trouble finding work, surprised rivals of
William Morris in Hollywood. ``Johnnie's been there for more than
25 years _ how do you do that to someone?'' a rival agent remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt quit his No. 2 position at International Creative
Management on Aug. 6, and took over the top motion-picture job at
the film side of William Morris only a few days later. His
departure was the biggest talent agency upheaval since Michael
Ovitz left the Creative Artists Agency to take on the presidency of
Walt Disney Co. in 1994. Ovitz was later dismissed by Disney
chairman Michael Eisner, and is now a talent manager.
</P>
<P>
   At William Morris, Wiatt succeeded Arnold Rifkin, who resigned
as president and co-chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   He brought over most of his clients, among them Eddie Murphy and
Sylvester Stallone. William Morris' top money makers include Bruce
Willis _ whose status is now unclear because he was represented by
Rifkin _ as well as John Travolta, Bill Cosby, Clint Eastwood and
Arnold Schwarzenegger.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, several agents announced that they were
leaving William Morris. These included Frank Frattarol, the co-head
of talent on the East Coast, and Jim Crabbe, a senior literary
agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
