<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME WITH ORIOLES A RAINOUT, BUT YANKEES MOVE CLOSER TO CLINCHING
DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Umpire Durwood Merrill walked on the field and waved
his arms dramatically, indicating for all fans at Camden Yards that
Wednesday night's game between the Yankees and the Baltimore
Orioles was postponed. There was something missing from the
picture, however: rain.
</P>
<P>
   There was no rain when the umpires made their decision, which
was based on ominous forecasts of heavy showers expected to deluge
the city at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Orioles will play a makeup game Thursday, as
part of a day-night doubleheader. Roger Clemens will pitch against
the Orioles' Mike Mussina in the first game, at 1:05 p.m., and
Orlando Hernandez faces Baltimore's Matt Riley in the second game,
at 7:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill surprised manager Joe Torre of the Yankees with the
postponement because of how he handled the hour leading to the
decision. The game was scheduled to start at 7:05, but at 6:45,
Merrill told Torre that showers were expected shortly and that the
chances of getting the game in would be better if the starting time
was backed up to 7:35. Clemens and Mussina did not warm up.
</P>
<P>
   But as Merrill learned more about the forecast, he changed his
course of action, even though it was not raining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to take the heat,'' Merrill said. ``I know it's not
raining, but all I can go on is the best information I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill said he did not want to start the game and then have to
stop it after only two innings, particularly since the rain was
expected to last all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to lose a game with Clemens and Mussina,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even without playing, the Yankees' clinching number in the
American League East dropped to one after the Boston Red Sox lost
the second game of a doubleheader Wednesday night. A Yankee victory
or Boston loss would mean the Yankees had won the division.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
