A1610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WEB-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-30 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: `DOT-COM' COMMERCIALS OFTEN SKIRT BOUNDS OF GOOD
TASTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One television commercial for Outpost.com featured gerbils shot
out of a cannon. Another, for Ecampus.com, featured a college kid
belching the alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   This is dot-com _ home of some of the best and worst advertising
in the industry. Dot-com advertising seems to be the place where
practically no bodily function is too private and no rude behavior
too coarse to be featured in a spot. It is also the habitat of
clever and ingenious creativity that takes risks in the high-stakes
race for category dominance on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost the job of dot-com advertising is to gain
top-of-mind awareness,'' said Brian Mulhern, senior vice president
at Cliff Freeman &AMP; Partners in New York, a unit of Saatchi &AMP;
Saatchi PLC that creates Outpost.com advertising. ``When I sit down
to buy on the Internet, if I don't remember the actual name of the
site and remember it first, then there's no chance that that
company is going to get my sale.''
</P>
<P>
   And, appropriate for the Internet, speed is everything. The
speed at which an Internet company can establish brand awareness is
key. Some 5 million new households will come online this year,
bringing the number of Internet-accessible households in the United
States to 39 million, according to Charlene Li, senior analyst with
Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to establish brand awareness right now,''
said Ms. Li. ``It's all about capturing and retaining customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Whle taking risks is anathema in the corporate world, dot-com
advertisers say there is little choice. They have a lot of money
from venture capital and initial public offerings and an edict from
investors to acquire customers fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are companies that need to create brands within very
short order,'' said Ellis Verdi, president of DeVito/Verdi in New
York, which creates the Ecampus.com advertising. ``Wall Street is
expecting results in months, and that almost requires that they
push the envelope. There's a sense that there's one big gold pile
out there and everyone is running for it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first six months of 1999, companies advertising
online services spent $755 million, up from $230 million for the
first half of 1998, according to Competitive Media Reporting, which
tracks advertising spending. More spending is projected as the
fourth quarter shapes up to be a crucial time for many dot-com
retailers that are trying to grab holiday shopping sales for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``With increased competition among Web sites _ and there seems
to be a million of them _ you have to be out there in the
marketplace just to be seen, and whoever shouts loudest will come
out on top,'' said Eric Goldberg, a media planner with DeWitt Media
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg predicts that heavy dot-com advertising will contribute
to a tight media inventory next year, which could push up prices.
</P>
<P>
   Because Web companies and services are new, Ms. Lee said the
advertising did not have to protect existing brand images. And
because the companies are part of the Internet, Ms. Lee said
consumers understand that Web advertisers have more ``license to be
wacky.''
</P>
<P>
   A sampling:
</P>
<P>
   _ A commercial for Beyond.com, tagged ``the place to buy
software,'' features a corporate drop-out who works at home in the
nude, much to the chagrin of neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   _ To get its tag _ ``Textbooks and stuff. Cheap'' _ across,
Ecampus.com shows a college student so broke that he resorts to
frying a pet goldfish for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a spot for Outpost.com, a pack of wolves is released among
a high school marching band after it forms the word Outpost.com.
The reason? To get viewers ``to remember our name,'' according to
an announcer.
</P>
<P>
   The companies do not seem overly concerned about offending
people. Mulhern said Outpost.com received about 17,000 letters
concerning the spot that featured the gerbils, with 60 percent
expressing support for the ad. Only a handful of consumers even
commented on the band commercial, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one inherent danger of bizarre advertising is that
viewers will not know what is being advertised, Verdi said.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Mulhern said that Outpost.com's second flurry
of ads _ spoofs of 1950s science-fiction movies _ promotes various
benefits that the company offers, including free overnight delivery
of goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seeded our name with the original campaign, now we really
need to differentiate the company from everyone else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the advertising needs to be sharp because it is
intended to reach hip, young people. Boo.com, a site that will
begin operations later this year, will sell sports apparel and
footwear and offer advertising that features anti-fashion figures:
computer geeks. TV ads to be shown in November will depict geeks
trying desperately to participate in sports. Print ads, taken from
the television spots, feature scenes like a geek in running shorts
on a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Shapiro, Boo.com director of marketing, says geeks are
cool and the perfect anti-status image. NBC recently began a TV
series called ``Freaks and Geeks.'' ``Geeks have become heroes;
they're chic,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The outrageousness of some dot-com advertising has forced
brick-and-mortar companies like Staples Inc. to reconsider whether
their online advertising is outrageous enough _ and they haven't
always opted to go that extra step.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we looked at the landscape of on-edge advertising, we saw
that they were doing things to get people's attention and perhaps
shock them into logging on,'' said Jeanne Lewis, president of the
Staples.com unit. ``But we realized we didn't need to do that
because we already have a creative strategy with our existing
advertising that does get noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Lewis said she appreciated a lot of the dot.com
advertising for its edginess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ideal is to combine the newest techniques out
there with some good basic marketing fundamentals that can't be
forgotten,'' Ms. Lewis said. &QL; 
 &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0059EDT &QL; 
