<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING SAME RX FOR DEATH IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - Doctors at the Arizona State Hospi tal must deal
every day with the criminally insane, so they know the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   A patient first loses touch with reality. Simple logic
disappears from conversation and is replaced by ranting about
justice, conspiracies and the need to eradicate evil de mons.
</P>
<P>
   In the most serious cases, like the one facing doctors here, a
deranged subject makes meticulous plans to kill the perceived
guilty party.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment is available, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Advancements in psychiatry and pharmaceuticals now make it possi
ble to better care for the mentally ill, often restoring them to a
function ally rational condition through use of newly developed
wonder drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the problem facing local shrinks is:
</P>
<P>
   How do you medicate an entire crazy state?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult time for us, to have the government
taking this position,'' said Dr. Jerry Dennis, the State Hospital's
chief medical officer. ``I'm trying to let others sort out the
political stuff. Mental health has always been one of these areas
that are highly political. But I'm going to abide by what I need to
do as a physician. That's what I am. I'll let the political chips
fall where they may.''
</P>
<P>
   What the good doctor means but can't come right out and say is _
Arizona has gone nuts. &QL; 
CASE IN POINT
</P>
<P>
   Residing currently at the State Hos pital in Phoenix is
convicted murderer Claude Maturana.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1990, Maturana and a man named Stephen Ballard convinced
16-year-old Glenn Estes that there was a party in the desert to
which they were all invited.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the men drove Estes to a remote location west of
Tucson, where Maturana shot him a dozen or so times and Ballard
slit his throat with a machete.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard got life.
</P>
<P>
   Maturana got the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   What state officials found out over Maturana's time on death
row, how ever, is that he's completely off his rocker. He's been
certified a schizo phrenic by a couple of different doctors.
</P>
<P>
   According to Arizona law, the state cannot execute someone who
isn't competent enough to know what's about to happen to him.
However, if a condemned lunatic were to receive enough medical
treatment to make him reasonably lucid, he then could be killed.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Maturana was shipped off to Phoenix, where
doc tors at the local laughing academy were told to tighten up a
few of his loose screws then graduate him magna cum dead.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dennis wouldn't do it. FIRST, DO NO HARM
</P>
<P>
   For months, physicians at the State Hospital have given Maturana
enough medication to keep him relatively stable, but not enough to
restore him to legal competency.
</P>
<P>
   Until they do, he can't be executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are ethical requirements we must meet as doctors,''
Dennis said. ``One of them tells us that anything contributing to a
patient's ultimate execution is unethical.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, the state is trying to hire an outside health
professional who'd be willing to give Maturana enough drugs to make
him legally compe tent, something I'd go along with if officials
here agreed to have them selves chemically elevated to the same
level.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe then they'd see the insanity of a law that says we must
make a killer well before we kill him.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Pardons and Paroles could recommend that the
governor commute Maturana's sen tence to life without parole, after
which he'd get treatment. But that hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem isn't going away,'' Dr. Dennis said. ``I'm aware
of at least one other death-row inmate who may be coming here after
being declared incompetent. We must deal with this.''
</P>
<P>
   But how? It now may be possible for doctors to stabilize the
criminally insane, but not in a state suffering from an incurable
lack of common sense. E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978
or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
