<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZONE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY NEAR BEATING OZONE RAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - The Phoenix area is on the verge of completing its
third straight summer without any violations of federal ozone
standards.
</P>
<P>
   It's a feat that is a boon for public health and business alike.
</P>
<P>
   The summer ozone season ends today. The three-year clean sweep
gives more breathing room both to people with respiratory problems
and to manufacturers, who risked severe limits on expansion if air
quality did not meet federal health standards.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone, an air pollutant caused mostly by auto exhaust, stayed
low, state environmental officials said, because of several
factors: favorable weather, cleaner fuels, emissions tests and a
concerted effort to reduce driving on days when officials feared
ozone levels could rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something the community should congratulate itself
for,'' said Nancy Wrona, director of the air quality division of
the Arizona Department of Environmental Quality. ``Many of these
(smog-reducing efforts) were voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, employees of PSI Group Inc., a round-the-clock,
south-central Phoenix mail sorting business, cut their driving
between 10 and 15 percent on each of six ozone alert days, said
Tina Esparza, the firm's project manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make this small effort, we might all feel better in the
long run,'' Esparza said of the company's motivation.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley had risked having its air quality downgraded to
``severe'' from ``serious'' if it couldn't meet U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency standards.
</P>
<P>
   By completing three straight summers without a violation, the
Valley can move to have the EPA determine that it now meets ozone
standards.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; While that is encouraging news, a more-stringent standard that
measures ozone over an eight-hour period will be impossible for the
Valley to meet, local officials have determined. That standard
currently is tied up in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   If next summer produces ozone violations, the Valley could be
back in the same jam it faced this year, said Colleen McKaughn, the
EPA's Arizona-based representative.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the steps that air quality officials credit for the
clean showing the last three summers must remain in place, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the controversial vehicle emissions test gets a lot
of credit for helping reduce ozone-forming pollutants from cars'
tailpipes, McKaughn said. And the cleaner fuels used in the Valley
since 1997, as well as the trip reduction efforts, also will
remain.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining a good-air record is like following a diet, McKaughn
said. After losing weight, there must be a maintenance plan, or
things revert to their former state.
</P>
<P>
   Wrona said local air quality officials will begin work soon on a
maintenance plan. Gov. Jane Hull, who spearheaded a clean-air
challenge this summer to local businesses, is expected soon to
petition the EPA for a reclassification.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley has not had ozone problems during each of the three
summers since the clean-fuel program was introduced.
</P>
<P>
   But the cleaner fuel, which relies on MTBE to make it burn
cleaner, is controversial because the additive has been detected in
groundwater supplies at various spots throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to precisely measure the effect of such voluntary
activities as the don't-drive campaign championed by the governor
on high-pollution days, Wrona said. But that program had to help
keep ozone levels at bay on those days, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the DEQ, employees far exceeded the governor's goal of
reducing driving by at least 10 percent. In late May, 55 percent of
DEQ's 700-plus employees cut their driving, according to agency
records.
</P>
<P>
   Their lowest compliance level was 37 percent, recorded on a
high-pollution day in August.
</P>
<P>
   Even while ozone woes subside, air quality officials are
wrestling with ways to curb particulate pollution. The tiny bits of
soot and grime, which give the Valley's ``brown cloud'' its
distinctive color, is a vexing problem that is still begging for a
solution. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at (602) 444-8963 or at
maryjo.pitzl(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
