<HEADLINE>
STICKING WITH STARS GRATIFYING TO MODANO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ When the Stars raise the Stanley Cup banner at
their season opener tomorrow night, center Mike Modano says he will
probably experience a wide range of emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Modano has spent his entire career playing for the Stars,
starting when they were the Minnesota North Stars and surviving
through the lean years in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I feel very fortunate to still be here after 11 years,''
Modano said. ``The changeover, the personnel that have come and
gone in this organization. The different faces year in and year
out. We've had some major face lifts over the years, but it is
really gratifying to still be here and to win and to accomplish
what the team set out to do when they drafted me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what hit me the hardest last year when we won
it, to still be here, to still be alive in this organization.''
Enforcer, not fighter Stars defenseman Jamie Pushor said he isn't a
fighter. He can be an enforcer. There is a difference.
</P>
<P>
   His job isn't to start fights, but to defend his players. His
weapon isn't his fists. It's his body. A big check sends the same
message, and it doesn't get a player to the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
   He realizes that's his role with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played in Detroit when they didn't have a real enforcer,''
Pushor said. ``The role was played by their big defensemen.''
Chambers returns Stars defenseman Shawn Chambers is expected to
return to practice today after missing the past two.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing to worry about, coach Ken Hitchcock said. rest was
designed to prevent any problems with a lingering knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to get behind the eight-ball with him,''
Hitchcock said. ``When he was playing 12 minutes, it wasn't as
crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers will be playing about 25-30 minutes a game with Derian
Hatcher as the Stars' No. 1 defensive pair. Hatcher's usual
partner, Richard Matvichuk, remains unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk's agent Art Breeze said yesterday that he didn't see
an end in sight to the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never in all the years I've known Rich seen his resolve
so steely,'' Breeze said.
nn
</P>
