<HEADLINE>
THE GALL OF PEOPLE, LINKING BUSH TO FATHERLY FAVORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(UNDATED) - The gall of people, linking Bush to fatherly favors 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The influence of famous political fathers has often helped their
kids.
</P>
<P>
   John Quincy Adams, the country's sixth president, was the son of
the second. John F. Kennedy wouldn't have made it to the White
House without his father's clout. Vice President Al Gore's career
got a boost from Al Gore Sr., a U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   Given the number of privileged sons whose dads have given them a
leg up, it's predictable that some malcontents would grumble about
Texas Gov. George W. Bush owing much of his success to special
treatment as the son of a president.
</P>
<P>
   From keeping out of active military duty during the Vietnam War
to getting rich in the oil business to becoming lead owner of the
Texas Rangers baseball team, George W. has used his father's
political influence to cut in line, they squawk.
</P>
<P>
   The gall of these people.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with how he got into the Texas Air National Guard in
1968 after his graduation from Yale. The war was at its height, and
the draft was at full throttle. But George W. was able to secure a
spot in the Guard, also known then as ``Air Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his father was then a Texas congressman, some people
wondered if strings were pulled. What cynics! As George W. has
assured us repeatedly, he received no special favors.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Ben Barnes, who was speaker of the Texas House of
Representatives, now says he called the head of the Texas Air
National Guard in 1968 and recommended George W. for a Guard slot.
Barnes said he did so at the request of the late Sidney Adger, a
Houston oilman and friend of the elder Bush. Soon after, George W.
got the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Some doubting Thomases have deduced that George W.'s dad,
wanting to stay in the background, probably asked his pal Adger to
urge Barnes to grease the skids. Any fair-minded person, of course,
couldn't believe such a far-fetched scenario.
</P>
<P>
   In business, too, skeptics say George W. had all the breaks. I
can't imagine why.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, he started an oil company called Arbusto Energy with
money from his trust fund and wealthy friends of his father. The
company struggled through years of low oil prices, and he merged
twice, the second time in 1986 with Harken Energy.
</P>
<P>
   Harken didn't give George W. a management position, but aware of
his father's connections, made him a director and gave him 212,000
shares of stock worth $500,000, or about $2.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he sold that stock for $4 a share, or $848,560. Eight
days later, Harken finished the second quarter with a stunning loss
of $23 million. Its stock ended the year barely above $1 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Critics howled that he must have illegally used inside
information to sell before the loss was reported, but what do they
know? Regulators found no evidence that he had done anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Before the stock was sold, it was collateral for a $500,000 bank
loan he obtained to invest in the Texas Rangers in 1989. Getting
the franchise proved to be his most lucrative business deal and a
launching pad for his campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Though several people wanted to buy the team, George W. was
given preference because owner Eddie Chiles was a longtime friend
of his father, who was then president. But George W. was unable to
line up enough money until Peter Ueberroth, then baseball
commissioner, persuaded Fort Worth billionaire Richard Rainwater to
come into the deal. Ueberroth asked Rainwater to join George W.
partly ``out of respect for his father,'' the New York Times
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise, bought for $86 million, soared in value with the
construction of a new stadium, funded mostly by a half-cent sales
tax increase that some sourpusses complained was corporate welfare.
Last year, the team was sold for $250 million, and George W. got
$14.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some say he was born on third base. They say he's led a charmed
life filled with political favors. They say if his name were George
W. Bosh, he'd be a political nobody.
</P>
<P>
   They're jealous. Asked about his paternal advantages, George W.
said all he can do is ``play the hand I've been dealt.''
</P>
<P>
   It just happens to be aces. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at (602) 444-8775, or at
steve.wilson &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
