<SLUG> BC-TEN-CONNORS-SENIOR-TOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNORS STILL FEISTY AFTER ALL THIS YEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CALVIN WATKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The hair has no signs of graying.
</P>
<P>
   The face, maybe a few wrinkles here and there, is still one of
the most noticeable in sports.
</P>
<P>
   The body is still average-looking _ slim, nothing special.
</P>
<P>
   But the attitude of 47-year-old Jimmy Connors, no matter what
the age, will never change.
</P>
<P>
   Connors, a winner of eight Grand Slam tennis titles before
retiring for the senior tennis tour, met the media yesterday before
the first round of the PricewaterhouseCoopers Champions Senior
tennis event at the Four Seasons Resort and Club in Las Colinas.
</P>
<P>
   Connors, who defeated archrival John McEnroe in last year's
final, said he's surprised to be playing in the Worldwide Senior
Tennis Circuit at his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would be playing in my mid to late 20s, let
alone my later 40s,'' Connors said. ``I don't do it like I used to,
and I don't play a lot of tennis. The amount of time I do play, I
do enjoy it and it keeps me in shape and I enjoy that. I'm used to
feeling a certain way and looking a certain way, and I enjoy
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors also enjoys throwing his opinion around. Especially when
it comes to the ATP Tour's No. 1 player in Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with British reporters last week, Connors
bristled when asked if Agassi deserved to be linked with Pete
Sampras and retired greats like himself, McEnroe and Bjorn Borg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't mention his name in the same breath,'' Connors was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday, Connors tried to defuse the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about it,'' Connors said. ``I do a
one-hour and 15-minute interview and they pull \Rstuff\S like that.
I mean that's why I got away from tennis. I couldn't stand being
scrutinize and having them write what they want to. But how do you
know what context it was taken in? You don't know if it was a
different part of a sentence or if they just pulled that into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons why I don't talk anymore. I know
what it's like over there. The first question they asked me is `Why
haven't I been over there the last few years?' Well, now you
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors is here now and is best remembered for a spirited match
with McEnroe, in which both players nearly yelled at each other. At
one point during the match, Connors walked off the court and
McEnroe exchanged harsh words with fans.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's tournament, there is no McEnroe, Connor's fierce
rival from the 70s, but that didn't stop Connors from talking about
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't swap spit,'' said Connors, who has won two senior
events this year. ``He hangs with his buddies and I hang with mine.
It's an all-right relationship. But as far as \Rlast year's match\S
goes, I forgot about it two seconds after it was over. I think it
still bothers him. But like I said, he has his friends on the tour
and I have mine. But I would say we are friends.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as Connors is on the senior tour, a tour which he helped
start in 1993, he is still a marquee name for fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, this tour is for the fans,'' said Mel Purcell, who
opened first-round play last night against Jimmy Arias. ``It's
built around the fans and it needs great players like Jimmy on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Connors said he was burned out on the ATP Tour and feels that
way on this tour sometimes, but he still loves the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career has been over for eight years and this is an
extension of something I like to do,'' said Connors, who received a
first-round bye and is expected to play today at 7 p.m. ``If I'm
trying to add to my career, then I didn't do it right in the first
place.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
