<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTHY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUPILS JUMP AT CHANCE TO REPAY DISASTER KINDNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DENNIS MCCARTHY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's payback time for Danube Avenue Elementary School in Granada
Hills. Time to repay an old debt to a tiny elementary school in
Tarboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Two schools 2,300 miles apart, both hit hard by natural
disasters, leaning on each other again for support _ five years
later.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, it was the kids and teachers at Stocks Elementary
School in Tarboro who rallied to help Danube, where people were
reeling from the Northridge Earthquake, which caused nearly
$1million in damage at the small school.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's Danube rallying to help the kids at Stocks, whose
whole town, Tarboro, has been virtually under water more than a
week from 30 inches of torrential rain brought by Hurricane Floyd
and other storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have ever thought?'' Danube principal Rosemary Enzer
said Wednesday, answering her own question.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, that's who.
</P>
<P>
   It was Enzer who took the call more than five years ago from Ed
Scarborough, a teacher at Stocks. He told her the kids at his North
Carolina school were moved by the scenes of earthquake devastation
they saw on TV and wanted to help.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it was Scarborough who took the call from Enzer,
saying it was time to pay them back.
</P>
<P>
   His kids were already talking about the earthquake in California
when Ed Scarborough walked into his second-grade classroom at
Stocks Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to do something to help the kids at Danube they
had seen on TV,'' Scarborough said Wednesday by phone from the Red
Cross emergency headquarters in the gym at Tarboro High School.
</P>
<P>
   Things are still far from normal in his small, eastern North
Carolina hometown ravaged by floods. But the end of the nightmare
is in sight, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he was helping and comforting 3,000 people who had no
other place to go but this gym. On Wednesday, there were 300. A
good sign, he felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids and I did some brainstorming after the Northridge
Earthquake, and we came up with the idea of collecting pennies to
help the kids at Danube. We raised over $3,800 in pennies from
people in town, plus boxes of books, crayons and games for the
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, each of our kids picked out one child from Danube and
sent them a card telling them to be brave,'' the teacher said.
</P>
<P>
   As if that wasn't enough, in March 1994, Scarborough and a
couple of his students flew to California to present Danube with a
friendship quilt from all the kids of Stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Enzer walked by that quilt hanging on the school's
library wall last week, anxious to tell her staff what she had just
heard on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   People were being plucked off roof tops and out of trees in
Tarboro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have to tell them; they already knew,'' Enzer said.
``We all agreed we had to do something fast.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the kids at Danube in 1994 is there now, so the parents
of the current pupils didn't know of the generosity and concern
Tarboro had shown for their school after the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Enzer immediately had a letter explaining the special friendship
sent out to every parent. Then, she got on the phone trying to
track down Ed Scarborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said it was horrible, worse than anyone could imagine,''
Enzer said. ``Caskets were floating down the streets, and the
stench from dead animals was terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarborough said two schools were destroyed, and a lot of the
high school was gone. His school, Stocks, was damaged, but should
be OK. With some luck, maybe even the friendship quilt the kids
from Danube had made for them to say thanks had survived.
</P>
<P>
   If the weather doesn't get any worse, they were hoping to have
the kids back in school next Monday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a blessing in all this, it's that the community
will be stronger for it,'' Scarborough said. ``Blacks, whites and
Hispanics havebeen pulling together, and we're all a lot closer
now for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Enzer told her friend to hang in there, that Danube would be
sending Stocks as much money as her school could raise _ so far a
little more than $1,000 _ along with a care package of school and
coloring books.
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what Danube was doing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While Enzer was meeting with parents to coordinate the fund
raising, students like Michelle Pearson, 10, and David Bentley, 9,
were talking to their classmates about how the Stocks kids had
helped their school after the earthquake, and now it was their
turn.
</P>
<P>
   He was only 4 in 1994, David said, but he remembers how scared
he was when the ground shook and all the adults were running around
with fear in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks the kids in Tarboro are scared now, too, and maybe the
cards his classmates are sending _ telling them to be brave _ will
help.
</P>
<P>
   But, it's money more than anything the adults in Tarboro need
now, Scarborough said. ``Over 2,000 families who didn't have much
to begin with have had their homes destroyed by the floods just in
our county,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in donating should send it to Danube Avenue
Elementary School, 11220 Danube Ave., Granada Hills, CA 91344.
Checks should be made out to the Danube Ave. Student Body
Fund-Tarboro.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
