<HEADLINE>
MAVS TRADE ANSTEY TO BULLS FOR 2000 2ND-ROUND PICK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Once dubbed ``the best running big man in the NBA'' by
Mavericks coach Don Nelson, Chris Anstey will now be running with
the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson traded Anstey to the Bulls yesterday for Chicago's
second-round draft choice in 2000. Because the Mavericks are
crowded at center with Shawn Bradley, Sean Rooks and John ``Hot
Rod'' Williams, and at power forward with Gary Trent, Dirk Nowitzki
and possibly rookie Leon Smith, Nelson said playing time was not
available for Anstey.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Anstey will be a free agent after this season, and
Nelson already said he wasn't going to offer the 7-footer from
Australia a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for Chris to get some much-needed
consistent playing time,'' Nelson said. ``We like Chris very much
and think he can be in this league for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, at the present time we have no playing time for him.
With the acquisition of Sean Rooks and having Hot Rod Williams as
backup centers, we don't anticipate any time available for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season Anstey averaged a mere 3.3 points, 2.4 rebounds and
11.5 minutes per game. As a rookie, he averaged 5.9 points, 3.8
rebounds and 16.6 minutes per game.
</P>
<P>
   Anstey plans on putting his past struggles behind him as he goes
to a Bulls team that is a mere shell of their former selves. He
talked to fellow Australian and former Bulls center Luc Longley _
he now plays for the Phoenix Suns _ about his days in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity for me to come and be part of a team
that's rebuilding,'' Anstey said. ``I spoke to Luc, and just from
talking with people involved with the program, it's really a
professional organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to developing my game in Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Anstey's departure means the Mavericks only have a second-round
pick to show for two recent first-round draft picks. Samaki Walker,
the team's first-round pick in 1996, signed a free-agent contract
last month with the world champion San Antonio Spurs, and the
Mavericks got nothing in return. Anstey was obtained in a swap of
first-round picks at the 1997 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Anstey's departure also means the Mavericks are searching for a
power forward. Either Ben Davis, Kebu Stewart or Zendon Hamilton _
all free agents _ could wind up making the final roster.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Anstey will be competing against Will Perdue, rookie
Lari Ketner and journeyman Brett Robisch for playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see Chris as a young player with size and speed,'' Bulls
general manager Jerry Krause said. ``He's a good shooter, and
someone who likes to compete. Those qualities will put him in the
mix to earn a roster spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Anstey is slated to make $1.1 million this season.
\Nsubheds:Briefly The three-year contract rookie Leon Smith plans
to sign next week shapes up like this: Smith will be paid $450,000
this season, $480,000 next season and $517,000 during the 2001-2002
season.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Steve Nash returned to the court yesterday after
suffering a sprained right ankle in a pickup game last week.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Sasser, a Dallas Kimball High School and Texas Tech
product, decided yesterday to add his name to the Mavericks'
training camp roster.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
