<HEADER>
A1642 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-ART-2NDLD-W     09-30 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-1,100&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN MUSEUM ACCUSED OF TRYING TO LIFT ART VALUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs grafs 1-3 for extensive rewriting to sharpen focus; subs for
new 9th graf with statement by Giuliani; Subs for new grafs 13-16
with new details of city's strategy and timetable for legal
action.) (ART ADV: Photos [NYT18,20,32) are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Broadening its legal case to try to take over the
Brooklyn Museum of Art, the administration of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani on Wednesday accused the museum of violating its lease and
state law by conspiring with an auction house to inflate the value
of the private art collection featured in a controversial
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation was the latest effort by the city to show that
the museum's board was misusing a public building and public funds.
Senior City Hall officials vowed on Wednesday to use the charge as
part of a lawsuit to be filed in State Supreme Court in which they
will seek to foreclose on the museum and take control of its board.
</P>
<P>
   The new allegation accuses the museum of conspiring with
Christie's auction house, a sponsor of the show, to inflate the
value of the artworks to be displayed, which are all privately
owned by Charles Saatchi, the British advertising executive. The
city officials said they would not try to stop the opening of the
exhibition on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they said they were preparing for a tough legal battle
on two fronts. On Tuesday, the museum filed a lawsuit in federal
court accusing Giuliani of violating the First Amendment by
threatening to cut off the museum's city financing, which is about
$7.2 million this year, about one-third of its total budget.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Wednesday afternoon, Deputy Mayor Joseph
J. Lhota, Deputy Mayor Randy L. Levine and the city's corporation
counsel, Michael D. Hess, accused the museum of ``hucksterism'' and
of perpetrating a ``scam'' by conspiring with Christie's to enrich
Saatchi by inflating the value of his art collection.
</P>
<P>
   Lhota accused Christie's of planning to profit from the
controversy surrounding the show. ``I guarantee you,'' he said,
``immediately following this exhibition, Christie's will have an
auction wherein the artwork that is being proposed to be shown at
the Brooklyn Museum will be sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's swiftly rebutted the allegations. ``We are aware of
these bewildering accusations,'' the auction house said in a
statement. ``They have absolutely no substance, are not true.
Christie's has a long history of sponsorships of exhibitions in the
United States and internationally. Nothing in this exhibition is
for sale, nor is their any expectation for any of the works from
the exhibition to be sold by Christie's.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum, too, rejected the allegations and characterized them
as a bizarre attempt by the administration to quash the museum
show, called ``Sensation,'' which Giuliani has denounced as
``disgusting'' and offensive to Catholics because it includes a
painting of the Virgin Mary surrounded by elephant dung and
pornographic pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who was in Beverly Hills, Calif., on Wednesday night
to raise money for his prospective campaign for U.S. Senate, called
the allegations against the museum ``an important issue to
examine.'' But he told reporters that his main objection was the
use of taxpayer money for the show and that the museum had not
sought his permission for it under the terms of the lease.
</P>
<P>
   With Giuliani away, officials at City Hall were clearly seeking
to retake the offensive in the museum dispute. The administration
had been on the defensive since late Tuesday, when the museum
abandoned its efforts to resolve the dispute through negotiations
with City Hall and announced that the show would go on as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that every day, the city comes up with a new
pretextual claim,'' said Floyd Abrams, the First Amendment lawyer
who is representing the museum in its federal suit against the
city. ``Now they have come up with another argument. Each and every
one of them is nothing more or less than further pretext in an
effort to punish the museum for the exercise of its First Amendment
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has also argued that under the terms of the museum's
lease, which dates back to 1893, it should have sought the mayor's
permission to deny access to the show to children without an adult
companion. The museum has since agreed to admit children but the
mayor has maintained that the exhibition is improper.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, through a spokesman, issued a statement calling the
city's accusations ``preposterous and misleading.'' It said, ``The
mayor's latest charge simply reflects the depths to which he will
go to undermine the First Amendment.'' The spokesman, Fred
Schroeder, said Christie's financial contribution to the show
represented a small fraction of its total cost.
</P>
<P>
   In making the allegations of conspiracy, city officials
capitalized on news reports that noted the dual role of Christie's,
which is a promoter and financial supporter of the exhibition as
well as a purveyor of artwork belonging to Saatchi, who is a major
collector and an important client. Christie's also supported an
installation of the exhibition at the Royal Academy in London.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid conflicts of interest, some museums do not exhibit
private collections unless they have been promised to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a scam, and taxpayers' dollars should not be used to
support that,'' Hess, the corporation counsel, said at Wednesday's
news conference. ``Taxpayers' dollars should be used for educating
children, for building roads, for supporting the homeless, not for
pushing up the value of a private art collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess said the city would pursue ``a variety of goals'' in its
lawsuit, which will be filed in either Brooklyn or Manhattan. ``We
will be asking for numerous remedies, including their funding will
be cut off and they should vacate the premises because their lease
has been breached and their lease is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual courtroom wrangling is expected to begin sometime
after Friday when the museum is supposed to receive its city
stipend for October _ a check for $497,554 that the mayor's office
has said will most certainly not be in the mail. While the mayor
can hold up the check, by law the City Council has final authority
over spending and the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Once the check is withheld, the museum is expected to ask Judge
Nina Gershon of Federal District Court in Brooklyn, who has been
assigned the case, to order the city to make the payment. The
speaker of the City Council, Peter Vallone, said on Wednesday that
legislators would support the museum's effort to get the money.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy reached as far as Capitol Hill yesterday, when
the Senate passed a nonbinding resolution sponsored by a
conservative senator, Bob Smith from New Hampshire, who recently
left the Republican Party. The resolution calls for an end to
federal financing for the Brooklyn Museum unless the exhibit is
immediately canceled. The measure, which passed on a voice vote,
has no bearing on federal spending.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the museum yesterday, workers were racing to finish
preparations for the exhibition, about 90 pieces of contemporary
art from a crop of young British artists. Silk-screen artists were
completing labels for the pieces while electricians put the final
touches on the lighting and senior museum officials were
considering adding more security officers and surveillance cameras.
</P>
<P>
   In part, this was out of their concern over possible attempts to
vandalize some of the artwork, as happened when the exhibition was
first shown at the Royal Academy of Arts in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say what is possible,'' Arnold Lehman, director
of the museum, said. ``Our phones are ringing off the hook, and
everyone is saying, `We'll be there, we'll be there.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
