<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1644 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-BELFOUR-TEX     09-30 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-BELFOUR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS NOT SURE THEY WANT A MR. NICE GUY IN BELFOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Two words from Stars jester/forward Brian
Skrudland brought goalie Ed Belfour to a halt after a recent
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey Eddie,'' he bellowed.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour paused, cautiously turning to face Skrudland.
</P>
<P>
   ``How come you aren't practicing like you play?'' Skrudland
asked. ``There were guys in the crease and you didn't hit them over
the melon like you usually do.''
</P>
<P>
   A second, maybe less, of awkward silence followed before being
shattered by a long, deep laugh. Belfour, chuckling like a child,
then turned and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses swore he had a smile on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Laughing? Joking? Smiling? OK, who is this guy and what has he
done with Belfour?
</P>
<P>
   He's Belfour all right, post-Stanley Cup Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just normal,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said, sounding a
bit concerned. Normal and Belfour were long thought to be
contradictory terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can he still stop the puck and be a normal guy? I don't
know,'' Hitchcock continued. ``What do they call that? A young
Frankenstein? Does he have to go back to being abnormal again to be
good?''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   His answer to Hitchcock's theory, like most answers on this day,
begins and ends with a single word: ``Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How am I supposed to know how I am going to be? I've never won
a Stanley Cup before,'' Belfour said. ``We'll have to see, won't
we?''
</P>
<P>
   Preseason results were affirmative.
</P>
<P>
   His usual I-have-on-my-game-face-four-days-in-advance demeanor
has changed. His just-try-and-slip-a-puck-past-me Stanley Cup
performances haven't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he smiles a little more,'' Skrudland said when asked to
compare Belfour '98 to Belfour '99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' Belfour conceded, evidence bursting onto his face in
the form of another smile. He can't stop.
</P>
<P>
   As last season ended, so this season begins.
</P>
<P>
   When we last saw Belfour, he was a happy-go-lucky goalie running
around Reunion Arena, bowing to the crowd and just being an
all-around emotional guy. He had that long elusive Stanley Cup in
his grasp, and he wasn't looking to let go. He had finally achieved
a goal many critics said would always elude him and reveling was in
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he got here, he had a lot of pressure on his back and
that weighed a lot on his shoulders. He had a lot of pressure to
win a Cup,'' Stars backup goalie Manny Fernandez said. ``So, I
think he's a lot more relaxed since he proved everybody wrong and
that he fits in that No. 1 category.''
</P>
<P>
   Move over Dominik Hasek, Martin Brodeur and Patrick Roy, you
have company.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour proved he's not just a good regular-season goalie (a
35-15-9 record, a 1.99 goals-against average and a .915 save
percentage last season); he proved he's also a good postseason
goalie, (a 16-7 record, a 1.67 goals-against average and .930 save
percentage last season.)
</P>
<P>
   Heck, if it wouldn't have been for Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk
doing that Wayne Gretzky impersonation through the Stars' Stanley
Cup run, Belfour might have won the Conn Smythe Trophy, given to
the playoff MVP.
</P>
<P>
   So, deal with it. Belfour's happy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if the Stars aren't happy for him. They just aren't
sure what to make of the transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you have success, you get so happy, happy, you
forget to perform and that's the challenge Eddie has,'' Hitchcock
said. ``He's reached a goal that he's set for himself. Now, some
people reach that and they just say, `That's it,' and they can't
focus for the rest of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen that a lot, but I've also seen people get into a
zone and never leave it either.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock is talking about the Haseks and the Brodeurs and the
Roys of the world. He considers Belfour in that category or, at
least, capable of getting into that zone. Hitchcock still isn't
used to the Belfour who is capable of having a conversation at 9:30
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it this way,'' Hitchcock said, ``at 9:30 in the
morning having a conversation with Ed is not normal. He was already
in the routine, in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour said he's just not a morning person.
</P>
<P>
   And since Hitchcock brought it up, Belfour said he'd like to
suggest evening practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe 4 p.m.,'' Belfour said. ``Yeah, suggest that to Hitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour's chuckling again, a big, fat smile creasing his face
despite his best efforts to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   So, is the new, improved Ed Belfour here to stay?
</P>
<P>
   Skrudland, who sees a punch line in everything, has his own
theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as the first guy rolls along and parks in his crease,
Ed Belfour No. 20 will be back in his Eagle-has-landed mask,''
Skrudland said. ``You've always heard these goaltenders are a
little cuckoo. Well, Ed Belfour is.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
