<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SEEK GRAZIANO SUCCESSOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The firing of Dodgers president and CEO Bob
Graziano is expected to signal a beginning rather than an end to
the changes in the nonbaseball front office of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   According to team officials, who asked to remain anonymous, the
finance, accounting, marketing and community-affairs departments
will be scrutinized as Fox Sports Enterprises president Rick Welts
searches for and names Graziano's successor.
</P>
<P>
   Welts said leadership was one of the reasons Graziano was
terminated. Among the reasons Welts listed for Graziano's dismissal
were the club's desires to become more immersed in the community
and its wanting to find more creative ways to produce revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Welts, who said he would not be the Dodgers' next president and
CEO, said he would use his contacts from his NBA days in his
search. He was the public-relations director for the Seattle
SuperSonics before joining David Stern's team in taking the NBA
from relative weakness to global supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a nut on this idea of community service,'' Welts said.
``Also, it's got to be someone who has to be a sports fan. Sports
is like that. It's not like selling pasta or automobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Welts said he had a list of six candidates, though the interview
process is yet to begin. He a~f\wtU|
</P>
