<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1646 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-30 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
If the Astros are fortunate enough to reach the playoffs for the
third year in a row, they should remember the elements of
Wednesday's game and do their best to duplicate them.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Hampton delivered one of the biggest pitching performances
of his career and Daryle Ward chimed in with what undoubtedly is
the highlight of his brief career in the Astros' 4-1 victory over
the Cincinnati Reds before a playoff-caliber crowd of 52,242 at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros avoided a sweep in the two-game series and moved back
into a tie with the Reds atop the National League Central Division.
The victory cut the Astros' magic number to clinch the division
title to four, and to clinch a playoff berth to three.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was a playoff atmosphere at the Dome, the Astros
were everything they usually are not in games of this magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   They needed a big game from their starting pitcher, and Hampton
answered the call. They needed to simply put the ball in play in
crucial situations, and Ken Caminiti was there, driving in two runs
without a hit.
</P>
<P>
   They needed to drive a dagger into the hearts of their
opponents, and Ward all but did it himself with a two-run homer
that gave the Astros a lead they never relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another game that could have gone either way, the Reds
didn't make many mistakes. But when they did misfire, the Astros
seized the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   A critical throwing error by Reds shortstop Barry Larkin paved
the way for the Astros to score three unearned runs in the fourth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the other team makes a mistake, you have to take
advantage of it,'' Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``That's
what we haven't done when we've been in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros also avoided losing ground in the wild-card race to
the Mets, who snapped a seven-game losing streak by beating the
Atlanta Braves 9-2. The Mets remain 1{ games behind the Astros and
Reds in the wild-card sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker's team is off today and will host Los
Angeles over the weekend, while the Reds travel to Milwaukee for a
weekend series against the Brewers. The Mets host Atlanta tonight
and Pittsburgh over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds would seem to have an easier weekend draw than the
Astros, but it won't matter if the Mets don't finish strong. Then
again, most of the Astros don't seem to be interested in
scoreboard-watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could care less about the Mets,'' said Astros center fielder
Carl Everett, a former Met. ``I hate the Mets. I hope they lose
every game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros aren't likely to lose many games when Hampton pitches
the way he did Wednesday. After one mediocre outing and another
that was downright bad, Hampton rediscovered the form that has
earned him a spot in the upper echelon of major-league pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (21-4) held the Reds to seven hits in eight innings to
earn his 21st victory, tying Joe Niekro's franchise record. He
punctuated his outing with a rare outburst of emotion after
striking out pinch hitter Dmitri Young to end the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big one,'' said Hampton, who also was 2-for-3 to
raise his batting average to .310. ``I'm not going to downplay how
big it was. We needed this one. I don't usually show a lot of
emotion out there, but it was late in the game, and I needed to
shut the door and not let any cheap runs in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton's teammates got a kick out of his Jose Lima-type
reaction, and at least one wondered if there was another reason for
Hampton's joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was really excited because Pappasitos had, `Go get
'em, Bulldog!' on the marquee,'' Bagwell kidded.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner pitched a scoreless ninth inning to earn his 38th
save of the season and the 100th of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any better than this,'' Wagner said of
Wednesday's atmosphere. ``This is just the type of environment we
need to get prepared for the playoffs. This was a great game for
the fans and a great win for us. We needed this win to give us some
motivation and let us know that we can get back in it and still win
the Central Division.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are 80-0 when leading after eight innings, the only
undefeated team in the majors in such situations.
</P>
<P>
   For three innings, it appeared the Reds would use good pitching
and solid defense to foil every opportunity the Astros had for the
second day in a row. But suddenly, the Reds' airtight defense
sprung a leak in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell reached on a rare error by Larkin, whose glove saved at
least two runs in the series. Larkin's .979 fielding percentage is
third-best among starting NL shortstops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball didn't slip, I didn't trip, and the turf didn't bite
me,'' Larkin said. ``I just threw it high. I'm human.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti drove home Bagwell with a ground ball that would have
been the third out if not for Larkin's error. And Ward, the next
batter, smashed a two-run homer off Reds starter Steve Parris
(11-3) into the Coca-Cola Club just beyond the right-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Ward was so pumped up, he didn't remember hearing the roar of
the crowd as he rounded the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to ask someone what it was like,'' the rookie left
fielder said. ``To be honest with you, I don't even know what kind
of pitch I hit. I just know that it was something straight and that
I was trying to shorten my swing and try to make contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting for someone to do something big. Anyone in
our lineup could have done it. I was just fortunate to be in that
position. Hopefully, we can keep it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Pokey Reese's RBI single in the sixth provided the only Reds
run. The Astros reclaimed a three-run lead on Caminiti's sacrifice
fly in the bottom of the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
