<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA GOES WITH SCRIPTED PERFORMANCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On second-and-9, UCLA quarterback Cory Paus
retreated from center and saw Fresno State's blitzers charging
toward him. Paus looked left, to receiver Freddie Mitchell, and saw
no opening. Then he looked to receiver Brad Melsby over the middle
_ and wide open.
</P>
<P>
   Melsby had started on the right side, ran toward the middle,
then cut back to the right, almost parallel to the line of
scrimmage. Paus threw a strike, and Melsby raced 24 yards for a
touchdown to give UCLA a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was a perfect play for the situation. A play specifically
designed to counteract Fresno State's blitz. A play that Paus
executes well. And a play that, through a process known as
scripting, was called long before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Scripting is the art of selecting plays (and their order)
several days before the game. It was popularized by former San
Francisco 49ers coach Bill Walsh in the early 1980s; it's used
throughout the NCAA and NFL and in some high schools. Because
scripting enables teams to rehearse in the comfort of practice, it
makes offenses more effective during games. There's far less chaos
after kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   `It's made it easier for coaches to call plays early in the
game, because you take the emotion out of it,'' Bruins coach Bob
Toledo said. ``I've seen coaches start games and say, `OK, what
play are we going to run?'
</P>
<P>
   ``As a signal caller, it gets you into the flow of the game. You
know what you want to do. Your coaches know what you want to do,
and the players know.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Texas A&AMP;M (where Toledo was the offensive coordinator for
five years), one year we scored on our first drive of the game in
nine games, and a lot of that was because we scripted what we
wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Scripting is remarkably complex. Each Wednesday evening or
Thursday morning, Toledo and offensive coordinator Al Borges select
the first 10 or 20 plays, in specific order, for the upcoming game.
The selections are based upon consultations with the offensive
staff, evaluation of the opponent and UCLA's personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Once an agreement is reached, Borges returns to his office and
creates two lists. One details the scripted first- and second-down
plays. The other includes plays to run on third-and-short,
third-and-long, red zone (inside the opponent's 20 yard line) and
goal line.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins follow the master script until they come to
third-and-long, for instance. Then they jump to the secondary list
and call the first scripted play for third-and-long. Borges has one
deadline: He must have the script ready for Thursday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that every play the Bruins run early in the game
has been carefully rehearsed _ and, if necessary, tweaked _ several
days before the game. Substitution patterns are also rehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think scripting has made it a better game,'' Borges said.
``Walsh was a big believer in beating the other team to the punch.
If you have a nice opening series and use plays that are
attack-oriented, you've done that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins outscored opponents 125-71 in the first quarter last
year. Using scripted plays, they hammered Texas for 21 points in
the first quarter of the season opener. This year, scripted plays
resulted in the impressive first-quarter scoring drives at Ohio
State, when the Bruins took a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Borges and Toledo often use plays to set up other plays, and
scripting establishes a foundation on which to build later in the
game. For instance, the biggest play of the 1998 season _ a 64-yard
touchdown pass from Cade McNown to Danny Farmer that broke open the
crucial victory at Arizona _ was an offshoot of two similar plays
run earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   There are other benefits to scripting:
</P>
<P>
   _It increases the quarterback's comfort level. Paus, a freshman,
must deal with the crowd and the pressure and the defense. Why add
to his load? Rehearsing plays is like studying for an exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it a lot easier,'' Paus said. ``Coach Borges tries to
script the worst-case scenarios. Most of the time it's not that
hard in the game, so it seems easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, you know the first 10 plays before the game starts, so
you can think about them and be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   _Scripting guarantees specific plays will be called and certain
players will get the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way,'' Borges said, ``you don't sit down Sunday and say,
`We never ran that play,' or, `We never go this guy the ball
against that defense.'''
</P>
<P>
   _Scripting lets coaches test defenses and evaluate their
responses. Many teams, including UCLA, keep a running chart of what
works and doesn't work. Often, they'll return to successful plays
in the second quarter or second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a play comes up, you just dial it up,'' Arizona State
coach Bruce Snyder said. ``When you script, it frees everybody up
to really look at the defenses and not worry about the play.''
</P>
<P>
   _Scripting eliminates capricious playcalling and forces teams to
implement its gameplan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Boise State, we planned to run (tailback) DeShaun
(Foster),'' Borges said. ``It wasn't working as well as we wanted
it to, but because it was scripted into the gameplan, we were
locked into it. We didn't run him once and decide it wasn't
working.''
</P>
<P>
   _It's one of the few offensive innovations that defenses cannot
counteract.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you scripted the eighth play to be a nickel defense, and
all of a sudden it's third-and-1 and there are three tight ends in
the game, the defense is in trouble,'' defensive coordinator Bob
Field said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scripting really makes a defense be on its toes, because the
offense can throw everything at you. It's amazing on those early
drives how many teams gain chunks of yards. It's really made it
harder to play good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the way Walsh scripted it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0136EDT &QL; 
