<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GET SALLEY, BENJAMIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Typecast as young and brash, the Los Angeles
Lakers are aging rapidly with their latest offseason acquisitions.
On Wednesday, they reached into the past to grab 35-year-old John
Salley and 34-year-old Benoit Benjamin _ a reflection of their
desperate need for big men.
</P>
<P>
   Salley hasn't played since 1996. Benjamin, a Clippers draftee in
1985 and a bust with the Lakers in 1993, has played with eight
teams in a spotty career and played just six games for the
Philadelphia 76ers last season.
</P>
<P>
   That both will be in training camp next week is attributable
more to the Lakers' thin frontcourt than anything else. But the
team is hopeful the pair can contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've told both these guys, there's an incredible chance for a
big man to make this team,'' general manager Mitch Kupchak said.
``If they can't, we'll figure something out.... Right now, this is
the best we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Both received one-year contracts requiring them to make the team
to earn the bulk of the money.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers also signed rookie Melvin Levett, acquired in the
Derek Harper trade, and they continue to pursue a veteran point
guard, with Ron Harper and Brian Shaw among the targets.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson wants to bring 18 players to camp. Sixteen
are now under contract, not counting first-round pick Devean
George.
</P>
<P>
   With only four big men guaranteed roster spots, the 6-11 Salley
and 7-0 Benjamin have a legitimate opportunity to win a job. The
Lakers have been scouting them for weeks and saw enough to roll the
dice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if one of them (made the team),''
Kupchak said. ``Short and simple, Benoit looks good. We've had
Benoit before, we know him, he knows what he has to do. We're
talking about a one-year deal and he's certainly going to have to
earn a spot on the team. His weight is down and he seems motivated.
John Salley is the same way. He desperately wants to play. He came
to us and really encouraged us to come watch him play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
