<SLUG> BC-BEATTY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEATTY MAKES NO DECLARATION ON PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ In a discursive, sometimes impassioned
half-hour speech to the Hollywood A-list and liberal advocates,
Warren Beatty on Wednesday denounced the conservative drift of the
Democratic Party, the rise of corporate greed, the influence of
big-money campaign contributions, lingering poverty and social
injustice. And he suggested that he would ``keep talking'' about
them loud and long.
</P>
<P>
   But Beatty did not come close to declaring his own candidacy for
president, as some of his supporters among the disaffected of both
major parties had hoped he might do.
</P>
<P>
   Calling himself ``an old-time, unrepentent, bleeding-heart,
tax-and-spend'' liberal, Beatty said, ``We don't need a third
party, we need a second party.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty made his speech in accepting the annual Eleanor Roosevelt
Award of the Southern California chapter of Americans for
Democratic Action. Sometimes speaking off the cuff, with humorous
asides to his celebrity friends in the audience, and sometimes
rattling off reams of statistics about economic inequality, he
seemed by turns confident and fidgety.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty described both contenders for the Democratic presidential
nomination, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, as
worthy men of high character. But he demanded, ``What is this
insurgency of a centrist against a centrist all about?''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``What we're in danger of experiencing is a
slow-motion coup d'etat of big money's interest over the public
interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
