<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-VICTIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: VICTIMS AND THE CONSTITUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Sept. 30:
</P>
<P>
   The so-called victims' rights amendment slated for a vote today
in the Senate Judiciary Committee trifles with the Constitution. It
is also unnecessary. Just about everyone agrees that victims of
crime deserve sympathy and respectful treatment in the criminal
process, and most states and the attorney general are already
experimenting with various approaches to making the justice system
more sensitive to victims. But adding a wordy and complex amendment
to the Constitution could actually harm victims by interfering with
what is undeniably their foremost right _ the right to the fair
prosecution and conviction of the guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Wilkinson, a leading member of the prosecution team in the
Oklahoma City bombing cases, made this point compellingly when she
testified last March before the committee. She noted that the
amendment alters the delicate balance between the accuser and
accused in ways inadequately explored by the committee. As a
result, it could well end up subverting just convictions by
watering down defendants' rights, fostering lengthy litigation that
delays trials, and torpedoing legitimate plea deals devised by
prosecutors to obtain testimony necessary to prove other, more
serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   These are risks that lawmakers should not take lightly.
Respecting victims does not require disrespecting defendants'
rights or the Constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
