<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS BEAT DODGERS, BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Los Angeles Dodgers had this plan to start
Kevin Brown on three days rest to give him a shot at 20 wins, but
there was a catch.
</P>
<P>
   To do it, Brown needed three wins in three starts.
</P>
<P>
   It goes like this: The Dodgers had a plan. They thought it was a
good plan. But even with a handful of games left, they continue to
remind everyone they are the Dodgers, and thus, the plan won't
work.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for the first and only time in his career, Brown left
Candlestick Park with a loss. The Giants scored early and beat the
Dodgers 5-1 in their next-to-last game at the 40-year-old ballyard.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Stick's 40-year era ends today with the Dodgers and Giants
closing it out with an afternoon tilt followed by a two-hour
celebration, though it's open for debate whether they're
celebrating the past 40 years or knowing they'll never have to play
here again.
</P>
<P>
   The wind and cold of the ballpark played some eerie roles in the
Candlestick, making pop flies an adventure and adding the
unexpected almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   However, as the two hated rivals close out one of former
President Richard Nixon's favorite ballparks, the weather was
wondrous. It was merely the result that was unforeseen.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (18-9) dominated in his previous starts at
Candlestick/3Com Park. He was 5-0 with a 0.63 ERA in his first five
starts at the `Stick.
</P>
<P>
   Not only had Brown dominated in the Bay Area, he owned the
Giants. In eight career starts he was 7-0 with a 0.78 ERA. It
included five complete games, three shutouts and a 1997 no-hitter
while he pitched with Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He also came into the game 8-2 with a 1.69 ERA in his last 13
starts, and pitching better than anyone in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first inning against the Giants, Brown trailed
2-0. Bill Mueller reached first on a wild-pitch strike out and
Barry Bonds, two days away from arthroscopic surgery on his right
knee, homered to right .
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later the Giants eclipsed their number of runs they
scored off Brown in his five previous starts here. Mueller singled
with two outs, Bonds walked and Jeff Kent singled deep in the hole
to shortstop to load the bases. J.T. Snow then singled to right to
drive in a pair of runs and give the Giants a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' $105 million man allowed four runs on six hits in
his shortest outing since a no-decision Aug. 25 at Milwaukee. Brown
also struck out nine, his highest total since fanning 12 Cincinnati
Reds on May 25.
</P>
<P>
   Brown could pitch in Houston, but after logging more than 250
innings for the second straight year, manager Davey Johnson said he
wouldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' loss could be Houston's win. Johnson said prior to
the game that if Brown lost, right-hander Robinson Checo would
start Sunday's game. The Astros may need that win to reach the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brown's had a great year,'' Johnson said. ``I'm not going to
ruin that by bringing him back on three days rest when it doesn't
mean anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's won 18 games in each of the last two seasons, but this
one is nothing like the 18-7 campaign he experienced in helping
rejuvenate baseball in San Diego last season. The Dodgers have been
out of the playoff race for three months.
</P>
<P>
   His only 20-win season came in 1992 when he went 21-11 with the
Texas Rangers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
