<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-OAKTREE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDROZA, NEW VIEW IMPRESS AT SULTRY SANTA ANITA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Alex Solis was hot on opening day of the Oak
Tree thoroughbred racing season at Santa Anita, riding a surprise
stakes winner and an impressive maiden-breaker. Martin Pedroza was
hotter, riding winners returning $40.40 and $80.40 to blow out the
pick-six bettors.
</P>
<P>
   But hottest of all was Santa Anita, and not only because the
late-summer heat registered 100 sweaty degrees Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita's controversial new management had a strong
afternoon as a smallish on-site crowd voiced overwhelming approval
for the landmark racetrack's $20 million facelift.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact they didn't change everything, meaning the paddock
and the hillside (turf course), makes me happy,'' said Helen
Gardner, 77, of El Monte, in a typical fan response. ``So far I
like what he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'' is Santa Anita chairman Frank Stronach, whose Magna
International bought the track in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of positive response all the way around,'' said
Stronach, who spent the day walking the grounds, altered with the
installation of elevator towers in the paddock-gardens area,
terraces in the trackside standing area and a drive-in
theater-style video screen in the infield. ``People can see we're
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   Stronach assumed the weather forecasts held down the attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some calls so we'd have no smog. I forgot to ask about
the temperature,'' the Austrian-born auto-components magnate joked.
``I do have good connections.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans watched an interesting if not high-quality program that
included jockey Pat Valenzuela's comeback from a nearly two-year
suspension; a seven-length maiden victory by the 2-year-old filly
Classic Olympio; and 14-1 Hula Queen's sweeping rally in the
$112,900 Sen. Ken Maddy Handicap for fillies and mares on that
popular hillside grass course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to be back,'' said Solis, the 1998 Oak Tree
riding champion, who spent the past two weeks traveling with his
family in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Hula Queen's win and the huge upsets by recent Fairplex Park
riding champion Pedroza aboard 19-1 Fit for a King (coming off a
40-length defeat at Del Mar) and 39-1 Disguys Dalimit (back from a
10-month layoff) produced a $107,230 pick-six carryover for today.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, 36, thinning hair and a long suspension rap sheet
proving his boy-wonder days are long gone, was cheered by the
paddock crowd when he mounted Enabru before a sixth-place finish in
the third race.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela went winless in four races in his first competition
since an October 1997 ban for an unexcused absence assumed to be
drug-related. But he was in his customary position on the lead in
the early furlongs in the first two efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe the (fans') response,'' Valenzuela said.
``Just riding, it felt like I won. I felt strong. I surprised
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an emotional day all around for the Santa Anita jockeys,
who stood shoulder to shoulder in the winner's circle following the
third race to lead the fans in a moment of silence for J.C.
Gonzalez, the 23-year-old rider trampled to death when the horse he
was aboard broke down and fell Sept. 9 at Fairplex. Gonzalez's
parents, brother and sister were present for the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Gonzalez had ridden Hula Queen in 1997, when he
was an apprentice and she was a maiden.
</P>
<P>
   Hula Queen was winless in two starts at the stakes level before
her 3{-length victory over favored Desert Lady in Wednesday's turf
sprint. Trainer Luis Seglin, a native of Argentina, hadn't trained
a stakes winner since moving to California four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Did Seglin worry about how Hula Queen would handle the heat?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``She sweats well.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita and Oak Tree executives sweated out the past few
days as construction and maintenance crews worked 24 hours to get
the facility ready. The major work in progress, the new restaurant
and bar scheduled to open in December, was hidden behind a tasteful
green tarpaulin that stretched the length of the clubhouse box
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here at 7 o'clock (Tuesday) night, and I'd have given
you 1-to-5 we wouldn't have been open today,'' said Sherwood
Chillingworth, executive vice president of the Oak Tree Racing
Association, whose season runs to Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Chillingworth hopes the attendance dip _ from 14,641 on-site in
1998 _ will be offset by a big Saturday as female turf champion
Fiji returns in the Yellow Ribbon Stakes, Oak Tree guarantees a $1
million pick-six pool and the popular collectible steins giveaway
is held.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-BELL-ATLANTIC-NY     09-30 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BELL-ATLANTIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BEFORE BELL ATLANTIC WINS APPROVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, Sept. 30:
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic deserves eventually to become the country's first
regional phone company to enter long-distance service, with the
potential to provide customers a combination of local and
long-distance services at lower prices than its competitors. But
Bell Atlantic's application yesterday to the Federal Communications
Commission is premature. Bell Atlantic has not yet satisfied the
precise performance standards required by the New York State Public
Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   True, Bell Atlantic has cleaned up most of the flaws in its
systems for switching customers to other carriers, thanks to its
hard work and close monitoring by state authorities. But if only
one system fails, a customer who wants to switch local service from
Bell Atlantic to, say, MCI Worldcom could wind up with no dial tone
or no directory assistance or with aggravating delays.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act of 1996 invited the Baby Bells to
provide long-distance service and invited long-distance carriers to
go after the Bells' local customers. But the Bells control the only
phone wire serving most homes and businesses _ a wire that AT&AMP;T,
MCI Worldcom and Sprint must lease to provide local service. That
poses the danger that once the Bells enter long distance, they will
exploit their local choke hold by overcharging rivals for the use
of wire and other equipment or providing them degraded service,
making it impossible for AT&AMP;T, MCI and others to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Congress wisely put the FCC in charge of administering the new
law. It turned over some of the task to state authorities. The New
York Public Service Commission tackled the task with tough-minded
innovation. For example, it had a consulting company create a fake
telephone company and seek access to Bell Atlantic's wires to see
if Bell Atlantic could switch customers without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bell Atlantic's systems have improved dramatically,
seeming deficiencies remain. MCI Worldcom and others offer local
service to households by renting nearly all of Bell Atlantic's
network. Switching customers is supposed to be done electronically
to cut out mistakes, but manual interventions are needed about half
the time.
</P>
<P>
   To switch business customers, Bell Atlantic needs to disconnect
a wire from its network and reconnect it to, say, AT&AMP;T's. Bell
Atlantic says it performs this task correctly over 90 percent of
the time. AT&AMP;T says the rate falls below 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What is to be done? The FCC, under heavy pressure from Congress
to prove that the 1996 act works, could approve the application,
but that could undermine years of diligent work by the New York
commission to upgrade Bell Atlantic. Or the FCC could reject the
application, but that would be shabby treatment for a company that
has worked hard to qualify. An artful middle ground would award
approval conditional on fixing up however many flaws the FCC
identifies. Then the company could be given an expedited review
limited to those problems. That way Bell Atlantic would get into
long distance promptly, as it deserves, and phone customers would
get the competition they deserve. More important, the FCC would set
a high standard for other Bell applicants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
