<HEADER>
A1664 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN     09-30 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S VAN RAAPHORST NEEDS ONLY STAMINA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst already has the
experience to be the Trojans' starter. Now he just needs the
endurance.
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst's only adjustment this week in practice is getting
in better shape, because he is not used to taking the majority of
the snaps that previously went to Carson Palmer, who is sidelined
with a broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to get my stamina back,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``I
get tired. When that happens, my feet aren't in the right spot and
the ball doesn't go where you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst got a vote of confidence Wednesday from coach Paul
Hackett, who continues to marvel at Van Raaphorst's performance in
the second half of the Oregon game, when he threw for 227 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had the sense this guy was in a panic or unsure,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Soward speaks:!off! After trying unsuccessfully to avoid
public comments this week, wide receiver R. Jay Soward said there
is no added scrutiny on the Trojans' wide receivers because Palmer
is probably out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no pressure,'' Soward said. ``We know we just have to
step it up. And I think we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Fearless attitude: Cornerback Kris Richard was flagged for three
penalties last week and is expected to share time with freshman
Darrell Rideaux against Oregon State, but that hasn't changed his
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Richard said he won't try to ease up to avoid any more
pass-interference or holding penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to play tentative. That's why I earned the
position,'' Richard said. ``When you're tentative, bad things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   After three interceptions in the first two games, Richard said
he expected things would get tougher against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody told me there would be a game where they would pick
on me,'' Richard said. ``As far as the penalties, whether I thought
they were real or not, I have to accept the calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Tired team: Hackett said he will ease up today, because the
Trojans are fatigued from the three-overtime game in Oregon.
Linebacker Zeke Moreno was in for more than 90 plays; Soward played
85.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired. That's a long trip up to Oregon and we didn't get
back until 4 a.m. We're going to back off,'' Hackett said. ``But
this team has a great resilience.''
</P>
<P>
   Denmon rests: Center Eric Denmon did not practice and will sit
out today to rest his nagging knee injury. He is expected to play,
but a decision will be made Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Another starter, left guard Donta Kendrick, is hobbling with a
sprained ankle and will not practice today.
</P>
<P>
   Vandermade to play?: If Denmon is unable to suit up, Hackett
said he will be forced to use freshman Lenny Vandermade, who is
slated to redshirt, but USC would need someone to alternate with
Matt McShane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to. I don't intend to,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Can McShane play the whole game? ``I hope so,'' Hackett added.
</P>
<P>
   Bumps and bruises: Defensive lineman Aaron Williams missed
practice with a sore Achilles' tendon and safety DeShaun Hill was
out with a sore foot. Cornerback Eric Reese suffered a mild ankle
sprain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
