<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1675 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN     09-30 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY PROBLEM IS THE SECONDARY FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last year, when opponents riddled UCLA's
secondary, the problem was strategic. This year, it's personnel.
Injuries, attrition and poor performance have left the secondary in
shambles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't have enough guys,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995-97 the Bruins signed nine defensive backs. These
players _ seniors, juniors and redshirt sophomores _ should be the
heart of an experienced secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine, only one is contributing:
</P>
<P>
   _The 1995 recruiting class (Terry Donahue's last) produced Ali
Abdul Azziz, Ryan Roques and Eric Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   Azziz is a reserve linebacker. Roques, who started six games
last year, was moved from safety to cornerback this week. Whitfield
is a longtime reserve whose play has never matched his talent.
</P>
<P>
   _The 1996 class, Toledo's first, was compiled in one month. It
produced Damian Allen, Jason Bell and Jason Zdenek.
</P>
<P>
   Allen is running track. Bell is injured (heel) and might not
play this season. Zdenek is struggling.
</P>
<P>
   _The 1997 class produced Marques Anderson, Ryan Nece and Jason
Stephens. Anderson has been suspended from school for the fall
quarter. Nece is a linebacker and Stephens has been benched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephens and Whitfield aren't playing like we thought they'd
play,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: three years, nine recruits, and only one
healthy, full-time starter for the secondary (Roques).
</P>
<P>
   That's a .111 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Man in white: Injured quarterback Drew Bennett shed his red (no
contact) jersey Wednesday and practiced with the receivers in a
white uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett can't throw deep passes because of a strained throwing
elbow suffered at Stanford. But he's one of UCLA's best athletes _
big, fast, great hands _ and might play receiver in certain
situations at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at the bottom of the depth chart for quarterbacks (because
of the injury), so I thought I might as well work at receiver to
see how it feels and if I'm any good,'' Bennett said. ``I think I
could do it and I'd love for it to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   News from Tempe: Arizona State quarterback Ryan Kealy (bruised
ribs) did not participate in contact drills Wednesday and is
questionable for the game. Tailback J.R. Redmond, one of the best
players in the Pacific-10, is also questionable because of a
separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan's chances are probably better than J.R.'s,'' ASU coach
Bruce Snyder told reporters. ``But neither is guaranteed to play or
start.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally: One current player (Whitfield) and five former
Bruins, Cade McNown, Craig Walendy, Skip Hicks, Larry Atkins and
Brendon Ayanbadejo, will be arraigned today at L.A. municipal court
for their participation in the handicapped-parking scandal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
