<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1690 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-WHITESOX-B     09-30 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPEAT IS SWEET FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-WHITE SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The party didn't begin and end with Pedro Martinez's
attempt at a cartwheel near the mound. It only seemed that way.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to celebrate winning a playoff spot when there's
still the second game of a doubleheader to be played.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it goes beyond that. Perhaps it's because the Red Sox,
qualifying for the postseason in back-to-back years for the first
time in 83 years, felt the same way as their shortstop, Nomar
Garciaparra, who doubled, homered, and had a hand in the final five
outs of the Red Sox' 6-2 win over the White Sox at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely happy,'' Garciaparra said. ``We're definitely
not content.''
</P>
<P>
   A season that began with a winter of discontent fostered by the
subtraction of Mo Vaughn, continued with a spring of uncertainty
created by the elbow injury to closer Tom Gordon, and survived a
summer of skepticism that this team would return to earth like so
many of its underachieving predecessors. Now, an autumn of greater
expectations remains. How far can the Red Sox go?
</P>
<P>
   ``How far?'' Garciaparra repeated. ``We've got to believe we can
go all the way. That's the attitude you have to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumped from the first round in all three of its previous trips
to the postseason in the 1990s (1990, 1995, 1998), the Sox still
don't know the identity of their first-round opponent this
go-round, although Boston's 4-2 loss in the second game of
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's doubleheader assured the Yankees of no worse
than a tie for the division title. The Yankees, rained out
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night in Baltimore, will win the AL East outright with
one more win or Sox loss.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cleveland, which eliminated the Sox in both '95 and
'98, still hadn't locked up the best record in the league, which
would assure a rematch against the Sox that would begin next
Wednesday in Jacobs Field. The Indians are two games ahead of the
Rangers with four games left for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   All three of those teams enjoy a higher profile than the Sox,
their lineups rippling with an abundance of All-Stars. But the Sox
are conceding nothing. Maybe that's why you didn't see Dan Duquette
pumping up the volume like he did last season. This time, he stood
up in the press box when Garciaparra caught Mike Caruso's liner and
stepped on second base for a game-ending double play, quietly
clapped his hands, and said, almost to himself: ``There it is. All
right. Way to go, men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys understand they're not going to be on the back of
Wheaties boxes if they do good,'' said lefthander Kent Mercker, who
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night started what Rod Beck, another late-season
Duquette acquisition, finished. ``But they don't care. They just go
out and play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you looked, there was a sense of unfinished business.
And while Mercker didn't see too many of his teammates making an
appearance on the breakfast table, the Sox do have this: a pitcher
whose name may be inscribed on both the Cy Young Award trophy and
MVP trophy, and Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro probably will pitch Game 1,'' said Mercker, when asked
about his own playoff pitching chances. ``After that, who knows? If
he keeps his pitch count down, maybe he can pitch Game 2, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker was with the Cardinals during the summer of Mark
McGwire, when the St. Louis strongman hit his record 70 home runs
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McGwire is a great player,'' Mercker said, ``and he's not
one-dimensional, but Nomar can help you do a lot more things to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nothing against Mark, but Nomar is a great defensive
player, too, with great range, and he can steal a base, too. I'm
glad he's on my side.''
</P>
<P>
   The doubleheader began with a crowd better suited for a Newton
North field hockey game. There were no more than 200 spectators in
the stands, and most of them were Red Sox fans, clustered behind
the visitors' dugout. ``They weren't mine,'' said Brian Daubach,
the basher from Belleville, a four-hour drive away. ``I didn't
leave any tickets tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like Legion ball in a tournament game,'' Mercker said.
``I heard a guy whisper who was making fun of me. I actually heard
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who had missed the last Sox game with a sore right
wrist, would have sat out Tuesday, too, if the Sox hadn't been
washed out. He made his presence felt immediately in
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's clincher. In the first inning, one out after
Jose Offerman blooped a single to right, Garciaparra doubled to
left. Offerman scored on Mike Stanley's sacrifice fly, and Butch
Huskey's double down the third-base line made it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   After the White Sox tied the score in the fourth on three
singles against Mercker, Garciaparra quickly restored the lead in
the fifth with a 400-foot, two-run home run that followed a single
by John Valentin.
</P>
<P>
   Damon Buford's two-run double in the eighth eliminated the
remaining suspense, as Beck, almost a year to the day he clinched
the Cubs' playoff spot on the north side of this town, followed 2
1/3 scoreless innings by Rich Garces and Derek Lowe with a save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a special year so far, it really has,'' Red Sox
manager Jimy Williams said. ``We know what lies ahead of us, but we
relish the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the hell we are (wild-card team or division
winner), but we're in the playoffs. It's a very good feeling, a
very special feeling. It could be an emotional feeling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
