<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER HAPPY TO BE BACK IN POSTSEASON 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MERCKER-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It had become such a staple of his existence that Kent
Mercker could mark it on his calendar at the start of every year,
like the Fourth of July, Christmas, or the tax deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``OCTOBER: Baseball playoffs. Probably World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   As a young Atlanta Braves lefthander, he found the extended
schedule, the national spotlight, the premium stakes numbingly
routine, as if they were a guaranteed contract clause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got a little spoiled over there early,'' he said.
``It was almost just assumed that the playoffs were going to be
part of the season. It's not that we took it for granted, but when
you're expected to win, it's not as exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's reached the same destination, but there is more
appreciation attached to this journey. With 5 2/3 yeoman innings in
the opener of a doubleheader Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, Mercker beat the
White Sox, 6-2, and put Boston back in the playoffs as, most
likely, the American League wild card for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-year drought, marked by ineffective pitching that
cost him jobs with playoff clubs Baltimore and Cleveland in 1996
and then a sentence to also-ran purgatory with Cincinnati and St.
Louis, Mercker realizes that the postseason is a privilege, not a
birthright.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun,'' he said of the clincher. ``Any time you can go
out and contribute to a game with so much meaning, it's special.''
</P>
<P>
   With Atlanta, it was a given. During his first six full seasons,
Mercker, 31, was on four playoff teams, three World Series clubs,
and one world champion. In fact, his biggest challenge was
surviving the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 when the Braves won the National League pennant, Mercker
was wounded in the aftermath. ``Somebody hugged me,'' he said.
``Then Lonnie Smith tackled us. I pulled some cartilage away from a
rib.''
</P>
<P>
   That cost him a spot on Atlanta's World Series roster, but what
the heck, there were plenty more where that came from.
</P>
<P>
   But after he was traded to the Orioles in 1996, he discovered he
had plenty of free time in October. His most notable moment during
the next three years came as a spectator. ``I got to see Mark
McGwire hit 70 homers last year,'' he said. ``That was something.''
</P>
<P>
   But he had come to realize that nothing matched the exhilaration
of the postseason. So when Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette
acquired him from the Cardinals Aug. 24, he felt rejuvenated. ``Any
time you go from fourth place to a contender,'' he said, ``it's
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mercker, it was a reprieve. For Duquette, it was a
necessity. ``We needed a lefthander for our rotation,'' said the
GM, who had gone the season without such a commodity. ``Playoff
experience was a key factor in getting Mercker, because at this
point of the year, you need players who have been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker got the Red Sox there Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, allowing six
hits and two runs before giving way to Rich Garces, and it was
almost as if he were destined for this moment.
</P>
<P>
   He had just come off the disabled list last week, having been
sidelined by a rib injury since Sept. 6. The opportunity to pitch
the clincher had been scheduled to go to Pat Rapp Tuesday. But when
that game was rained out, necessitating the doubleheader, manager
Jimy Williams flip-flopped his starters. ``We decided (Tuesday) he
was going to be the guy,'' said Williams. ``We could just as easily
have gone with Rapp.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rapp became the postscript and Mercker became a part of
Boston baseball lore. As a bonus, the Red Sox had to be out on the
field at Comiskey Park 20 minutes later for Game 2, so Mercker
didn't have time to get hurt celebrating. Instead, he spent the
interlude reflecting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for me because I haven't been here that long,'' he
said. ``When those guys want to celebrate, I'm going to stand off
in a corner. These are the guys who have been here all year.
They're the guys who gave me a chance to pitch the wild-card
clincher.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, a wiser and battle-scarred Mercker will tell you, is
no everyday treat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
