<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX FOUND A WAY TO GRIND IT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Remember when the Celtics dragged Red Auerbach into
the showers after they won their eighth consecutive championship?
Red's cigar, like the Celtic fire, was never extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when beer flowed on Causeway Street after Bobby Orr
flew through the air on that Sunday afternoon in May, delivering
the Stanley Cup?
</P>
<P>
   Remember when a dying Tom Yawkey drank champagne from a Dixie
cup in the Oakland Coliseum after the Sox swept the three-time
champion A's from the American League playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   This was nothing like any of those moments. At 6:56 p.m. Central
Standard Time Wednesday, Nomar Garciaparra gloved a line drive off
the bat of Mike Caruso, stepped on second base to complete a double
play . . . and then Pedro Martinez bounded out of the dugout and
did a cartwheel on the Comiskey Park infield. ``I enjoyed that,''
said Pedro. There was hardly anyone in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Red Sox _ the grinders and muckers of Yawkey Way _ are
going to the postseason. Their 6-2 victory over the moribund White
Sox in the first game of a doubleheader Wednesday put Boston in the
American League playoffs with the Yankees, Indians, and Rangers. A
Sox edition that was ridiculed (by me, among many others) in the
offseason is going back to the tournament for the second straight
year. The Sox have not made it to postseason play in consecutive
seasons since 1915-16 when they had a crafty lefthander named Babe
Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   It was a weird clinch night, and Boston's wild-card celebration
was postponed for nine innings. The Sox had already taken the field
for Game 2 by the time equipment czar Joe Cochran unloaded a case
of Le Domaine California champagne. They celebrated the playoff
clinching after the 4-2 second-game defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs in the press box, oft-maligned Dan Duquette (three
playoff teams in five years) resisted the urge to tweak his
critics. Asked if this was sweeter than the others, he deadpanned,
``It's a good accomplishment for the organization, a good
reflection on the depth of the organization. A lot of people did
good things to get us into the playoffs . . . Even though we lost
one of our most recognizable players (we think he means Mo Vaughn),
we were still able to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought Jimy Williams should be Manager of the Year,
but when asked if he should be Executive of the Year, answered,
``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   How about a little gloating, Dan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking forward to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonderboy Garciaparra was happy to fire back at the preseason
wiseguys. The shortstop hit a double and game-breaking two-run
homer in the clinch game, then said, ``We're good, and people who
said (otherwise) don't know anything. If we listened to them, we
wouldn't have gone out there. But we believed what we had. We don't
listen, we just go out and play hard . . . Tell people not to read
or listen. It's not them (reporters) that know. It's us that
know.''
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that these Sox would clinch in such unremarkable
fashion. It's a team with little star power, excluding Nomar and
Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck called his new teammates ``a bunch of grinders who
don't take anything for granted. A bunch of guys who hit .270.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he was heartened by the show of team solidarity
Tuesday night when 28 of the fellas gathered at the ESPNZone saloon
to watch the midnight special between Oakland and Anaheim _ a game
that could have clinched for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing that makes me feel good,'' said Williams. ``To me,
that's just another indication that this is, in fact, a team. We're
together eight months and you've got to get on each other's nerves
once in a while. But certainly at this juncture, it's nice to hear
that . . . That's a pretty good meeting especially not even being
in the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no more than 200 fans in the Comiskey stands when Jim
Parque pitched to Jose Offerman to start clinch night at 4:07 p.m.
It had the feel of a mid-March simulated game at the Sox' minor
league complex in Fort Myers, Fla. All we needed was Johnny Pesky
hitting fungoes between innings.
</P>
<P>
   A small, but loud band of Sox fans cheered the wild-card winners
after Nomar's game-ending double play, and it was then that Jimy
finally let the air out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've accomplished something that we set out to do,'' he said.
``It's been a special year for us. I don't know what the hell we
are but we're in the playoffs. We're one of four. We have attained
something that's special.''
</P>
<P>
   Now what?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely happy, but we're not content,'' said Nomar.
``We've got to believe we can go all the way to the World Series
and win it all. We're not going to let up.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck added, ``I know the history of baseball on the North Side
(Cubs), and this doesn't seem much different. They've waited a long
time for a championship. There's nothing better than winning in
those cities. They deserve a championship. And I'm a firm believer
that things happen for a reason.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
