<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1698 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-BOS &LR;      09-30 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFOE'S PITCH TO BRUINS: TRADE ME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Byron Dafoe said he's going to sell his North Shore
home since he figures his playing days in Boston are over.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' holdout goalie attended a three-hour meeting
Wednesday with his agent, Ron Salcer, president/general manager
Harry Sinden, and assistant general manager Mike O'Connell in an
effort to end his contract impasse. Dafoe left the meeting angry,
disillusioned, and determined to leave town, saying he has asked to
be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do I go from there?'' he said. ``I said, `Well, then
trade me,' if they're not willing to try to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said management's response was vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their response was, `OK, but we'll do what's in the best
interest of the Boston Bruins.' Well, I think what's in the best
interest of the Boston Bruins is to sign me. I'm serious on this
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sinden) really pissed me off at the end and I got up and
left. I couldn't take it anymore. For him to be crying poverty and
to say I'm going to bankrupt the team with what I'm asking for, I
think that's ridiculous. I came home, called the real estate agent,
and the sign is going up (Thursday).''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only push a person so far. This started four months
ago. (Sinden) indicated I might have to sit. Well, if that's the
best for the Boston Bruins, I'll be glad to go somewhere else. How
can that benefit a hockey team?''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said Sinden told him that paying him what he was asking
for, or even less, would cause financial hardship for the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``To quote Harry, he said, `If I were to pay you what you were
asking for, the Boston Bruins go bankrupt,' '' said Dafoe. ``It
went on from there. He agreed (on Dafoe's worth). He said I was in
the top three or four goalies in the league and they said they
can't afford it. This is the way the Boston Bruins are run, and he
said, `I'm not going to be like these other teams and run my team
into the ground.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said he feels his case is simply a harbinger of things to
come with Joe Thornton, Sergei Samsonov, and other Bruins up for
new contracts next summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, after seeing what I've gone through, looking
into the future of the Boston Bruins, what about Joe and Sergei?
You've got me holding out this year; next year you're going to have
six or seven. I'm not happy about being on an adequate team or a
team that's just good enough. I play this sport to win and if
there's no intention of going for a Cup, then trade me.''
</P>
<P>
   The goalie said Sinden offered him $2 million for a one-year
contract, but Dafoe turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to recall (Los Angeles Kings goalie) Stephane Fiset was
awarded $2.1 million (in arbitration),'' said Dafoe. ``No offense
to the other goaltenders, I'm not saying I'm a better goaltender
but going by the numbers, which most arbitrators do, it doesn't
make sense. That's what put the final straw on it and I got up and
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meeting was just the latest in a string of
negotiations begun when the 28-year-old Dafoe, a restricted free
agent, turned down arbitration after last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back when Harry and I met before, he said, `Byron, you show me
why you're worth what you're asking for and I'll pay it,' '' said
Dafoe. ``We went over for quite a period of time different numbers,
and Ronnie had everything prepared. We showed them why we're asking
for what we are. Harry said, `Byron, you're right, you should
probably be asking for more money. But the Boston Bruins can't
afford that. You're not in the Boston Bruins' marketplace.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to give our new proposal. We came down considerably. I
took myself out of the marketplace and they made absolutely no
effort, no movement, they had nothing to come back with. They just
did not accept it. They said they were staying right where they
were.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said the entire experience has left a sour taste in his
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it is, is lip service,'' he said. ``He had absolutely no
intentions of getting it done. Their original offer was their final
offer, going back four months. I've moved considerably. I've
compromised. I've gone beyond what I feel (I'm worth) because I'd
love to stay in Boston. The fans are unbelievable. The city is
unbelievable. My teammates are great and Pat Burns is the best
coach I've had. It's a superb situation but the bottom line is you
can only go so far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
