<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1706 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BEATTY-CANDIDACY-SFCH     09-30 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATTY-CANDIDACY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR BEATTY FALLS SHORT OF AN ANNOUNCED RUN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS _ In a moment of high drama worthy of the silver
screen, movie star Warren Beatty brought his film character
Bulworth to life Wednesday night, telling a crowd of Hollywood
glitterati that he intends to ``speak up for the people that nobody
speaks for.''
</P>
<P>
   But Beatty's reprise of his plain-spoken movie politician took a
twist when he failed to address the question on everybody's mind:
Will he challenge Vice President Al Gore and former U.S. Senator
Bill Bradley for the Democratic presidential nomination?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Beatty delivered a passionate, often entertaining and
sometimes rambling speech that left many of the 200 reporters from
around the world scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 Hollywood stars and political insiders held their
collective breath as Beatty took the stage at the Beverly Hilton to
receive the Eleanor Roosevelt Award for political activism from the
Southern California chapter of Americans for Democratic Action, a
Democratic liberal organization.
</P>
<P>
   But the star of such movies as ``Splendor in the Grass,''
``Reds'' and ``Shampoo'' made no mention of any presidential
aspirations, and he even told his celebrity-studded audience at one
point, ``I like making movies, and I'm going to keep making them.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty's political tease about a possible 2000 presidential run
_ preceded by weeks of printed foreplay _ began weeks ago, after
columnist Arianna Huffington ruminated in print on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz about a possible Beatty run soon swelled to
bigger-than-life Hollywood proportions, making the actor's
appearance in the International Ballroom here last night the
hottest ticket in town _ maybe in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Limos pulled up at the Hilton, dislodging stars and political
luminaries as a herd of paparazzi vied for their attention. Young
women in the liberal Democratic crowd wore shirts saying, ``I ain't
voting for that S.O.B. (son of Bush).''
</P>
<P>
   Among the stars who showed up were Jack Nicholson, Faye Dunaway,
Courtney Love, Morgan Fairchild, Dustin Hoffman, director Penny
Marshall and TV stars Lara Flynn Boyle and Garry Shandling.
</P>
<P>
   Guests paid $175 each to sit in the packed ballroom _ the site
of the annual Golden Globe Awards _ to hear the words from Beatty's
own mouth about his political future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that he's shaking up the system,'' said
Hustler publisher Larry Flynt, who entered the dinner as ``Beatty
2000'' stickers were being handed out. ``With Bradley and Gore,
it's dumb and dumber.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty entered the hotel accompanied by his wife, actress
Annette Bening, amid an explosion of flash bulbs. The actor
blinked, appearing stunned at the crush of reporters and
photographers. ``This,'' he said in awe, ``is a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But once on stage, he forcefully delivered an entreaty for the
Democratic Party to return to its roots,saying it has become
``more interested in profits than people, investments but not
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for campaign finance reform and universal health care,
and he wasted no time lambasting both  &LR; Gore and Bradley, saying
that the Democratic centrists have struck ``political bargains''
while 100 million Americans have been left behind during economic
boom times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party is drifting,'' he said. ``It's enslaved by big
money; it's lost its purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty was met with a standing ovation when he closed his
address with a quote from ``Bulworth'': ``Keep the spirit alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends like State Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, who had
a table for eight, said that the actor-director was well aware of
his celebrity spotlight and wanted to use it to push Democratic
issues he felt were being ignored. The huge turnout to hear Beatty,
Burton said, ``means there is a craving for excitement in the
campaign, a craving for someone to talk like a real Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The progressive wing of the Democratic Party has been shut
out, and the air in that shut room of conservative Democrats
becomes stale,'` said Lila Garrett, president of ADA. ``Warren
Beatty has opened that door slightly, and the rancid air is moving
out and the fresh air is moving in.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said the Beatty buzz was simply a moment of relief from
the deadly serious _ and often deadly dull _ rivalries of the 2000
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have known Warren since I've been a waitress in this town,''
laughed actress Sally Kellerman, ``and he's always created a buzz
in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls suggest that if Beatty ran for president as a Democrat he
would draw support, but he wouldn't dramatically alter the race. In
an ABC poll of 452 Democrats and Democratic-leaning voters in
mid-August, Gore was supported by 61 percent, while 24 percent
backed Bradley and 9 percent endorsed Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   When it was all over, even the actor himself didn't seem to have
a clue to where all the hoopla will lead. Asked by a reporter if he
was leaving the door open for a future run at the White House,
Beatty threw up his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like that,'' he shrugged. `I'm not saying no.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Ken Hoover and Chronicle news services
contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
