<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-RAPIDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY BEATS RAPIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It's hard to figure how Steve Jolley worked
his way to the Los Angeles Galaxy bench _ going from a regular
mainstay at central defense to the back of Sigi Schmid's dog house.
</P>
<P>
   He accepted his demotion with mixed feelings _ believing he had
earned his role with the best defense Major League Soccer has to
offer.
</P>
<P>
   So with a rare start Wednesday, replacing struggling defender
Paul Caligiuri, Jolley came out flying, added a back-flip as an
exclamation point and gave Schmid something to think about with the
playoffs around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   In just his third start in the past 12 matches, Jolley used his
30-something-inch vertical leap to finish a beautiful header in the
fifth minute against Colorado. The quick start fueled a rare 4-0
rout over the defensive-minded Rapids in front of 10,098 at the
Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The victory lifted Los Angeles (19-11, 51 points) to a
four-point cushion over the second-place Rapids (19-10, 47 points)
_ and it guaranteed the Galaxy would finish no worse than second
with two road games remaining in the Western Conference title race.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jolley, it meant he might actually be around for these
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been sitting on the bench for the last month,'' said
Jolley, who missed the previous three games. ``For the first time
in my career I was questioning myself, and that's not always good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was an opportunity before the playoffs to at least
have a chance to show what I'm made of. If anything, it creates
more questions in his (Schmid's) mind who he wants to play there.
It's not a matter of me or Cal, but more than anything I wanted to
show I can perform in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to get that goal becomes sometimes you can
play a great game and they can overlook you. But when you score a
goal, especially one like that, it leaves a lasting impression.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly left an impression with Schmid, who started Jolley
and midfielder Clint Mathis because he felt the team had gone stale
after its 2-0 loss to D.C. United on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the decisions I came to after D.C. was that I felt we
had a very good run in August but that maybe some guys were feeling
too comfortable in the starting lineup,'' said Schmid. ``We needed
fresh legs, came with Clint and Jolley and it worked for us. As for
Jolley, I was very pleased, it was a great goal and a great header.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives me something to think about. This team is 15 or 16
players deep. For a while we hesitated doing it (changing the
lineup), but I think for us to win the title we need to keep fresh
legs out there.''
</P>
<P>
   If Schmid was looking for a genuine playoff effort after two
consecutive shutout losses, he certainly got it against a Colorado
team coming off three straight shutouts. And the four goals was a
nice reward because the Rapids came to spectate, hoping to steal a
point in the shootout. In the second half, they basically shut down
and quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they felt they had a game in hand on us, and just said
let's bag this one, this is not the one we're going to go get,''
said Schmid. ``Certainly I don't think they played with as much
intensity as normal, but part of that was our defending.''
</P>
<P>
   Up 2-0 at the half, Jones added his eighth goal of the season in
the 56th minute and UCLA's Seth George finished it with his goal in
the 89th minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
