<HEADLINE>
GIANTS BEAT DODGERS, BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The plan was to start Kevin Brown on three days
rest in Houston to give him a shot at 20 wins, but to do it, the
right-hander needed three wins in three starts.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Dodgers 101: They have a plan, think it's a good plan,
but then it crumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for the first and only time in his career, Brown left
Candlestick Park with a loss. The Giants scored early and beat the
Los Angeles Dodgers 5-1 Wednesday in their next-to-last game at the
40-year-old ballyard.
</P>
<P>
   Even Brown conceded it was his last start in the first of a
seven-year, $105 million deal. He finishes 18-9 with a 3.00 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great season,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``There's no reason for him to come back. When he came out, I shook
his hand and said, `Great year.' It really was.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the second straight season Brown won 18 games, but this one
ends much differently than his run to the World Series while
helping rejuvenate baseball in San Diego last season. His lone
20-win season came in 1992 as a member of the Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what it is,'' Brown said in summing up his season. ``It
could have been better. I felt like I could have thrown the ball
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The 'Stick's 40-year era ends today with the Dodgers and Giants
closing it out with an afternoon game followed by a two-hour
celebration, though it's open for debate whether they're
celebrating the past 40 years or the fact that they'll never have
to play here again.
</P>
<P>
   The wind and cold of the ballpark played some eerie roles in the
Candlestick saga, making pop flies an adventure and adding the
unexpected almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   However, as the two hated rivals battled at one of former
President Richard Nixon's favorite ballparks, the weather was
wondrous. It was merely the result that was unforeseen.
</P>
<P>
   Brown dominated in his previous starts at Candlestick/3Com Park.
He was 5-0 with a 0.63 ERA in his first five starts at the `Stick.
</P>
<P>
   Not only had Brown dominated in the Bay Area, he owned the
Giants. In eight career starts he was 7-0 with a 0.78 ERA. It
included five complete games, three shutouts and a 1997 no-hitter
while he pitched with Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He also came into the game 8-2 with a 1.69 ERA in his past 13
starts, and pitching better than anyone in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brown) was good (this season), but he wasn't dominating like
I've seen him dominate,'' said Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield,
who played in Florida with Brown. ``If you have an off year and
shell out 18 wins, that says something about you. I can say that
because I've seen it. You wouldn't believe what he can do. He can
take over a game.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first inning against the Giants, Brown trailed
2-0 because Barry Bonds, two days away from arthroscopic surgery on
his right knee, homered to right. Two innings later, the Giants, on
J.T. Snow's two-run single, eclipsed the number of runs they scored
off Brown in his five previous starts here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made two bad pitches,'' Brown said. ``I made a lot of good
ones, but I made two bad ones and it cost me four runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' loss could be Houston's win. Johnson said prior to
the game that if Brown lost, right-hander Robinson Checo would
start Sunday's game. The Astros might need that win to reach the
playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 0324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
