<HEADER>
A1709 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-GOLF-COLUMN-LADN     09-30 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEAKING OF BAD SPORTS ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Those wild and crazy Ryder Cuppers sure knew how
to party. They made the 18th green at the venerable course look
like the back yard of a frat house, what with the team's leader
fizzing up a huge bottle of champagne, then hosing down his mates.
Then there was the table-top tap-dance routine featuring the team
captain and one of its young stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   I'm referring to the European team's high jinks after their
first win on American soil at Murifield Village in 1991. The
Europeans took special glee in rubbing salt into the American
psyche then because the U.S. team was led by Jack Nicklaus, the
game's best player ever; the match was held at a course he designed
and the home team had bragged before hand how great it was.
</P>
<P>
   So the postmatch festivities featured Champagne Seve Ballesteros
and Dancin' Captain Tony Jacklin and his partner Jose-Maria
Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday, that was the Ryder Cup victory party for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   And now the Europeans, led by their captain Mark James, have
shown the world that they are just as lousy at losing as they are
at winning.
</P>
<P>
   So is the British press, which presented a unified front this
week in bashing America. They did the same thing back in 1991 after
Team Europe won the cup and of course they are the same jokes, er
blokes, that have referred to the wives of American players as
bimbos.
</P>
<P>
   To all their self-righteous blathering I say, too bad.
</P>
<P>
   Deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   You lost the cup, and not because of the American dog pile on
the 17th green after Justin Leonard sank a put that was longer than
Paul Revere's ride.
</P>
<P>
   You lost because your team performed one of the greatest
collective chokes in the history of golf. They should nickname
these guys the Billy Joe Pattons.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans are also lucky the American team did not get in
their faces about the pace of play. In what was obviously Mark
James' strategy to rattle the Americans, the European team
routinely took its time conferring over shots and reading putts.
</P>
<P>
   It was so bad there was a real possibility the whole thing might
not get finished until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If a flag were thrown for unsportsmanlike conduct it should have
been directed at the behind of Padraig Harrington, who was playing
Mark O'Meara one hole ahead of Leonard and Olazabal. With his ball
in the middle of the fairway and O'Meara in trouble, Harrington
paced off the yardage to the green and took a look at the pin
position. It took him almost 10 minutes to make a swing. Do that on
a public course and someone will be calling 911.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara stewed, but said zip. He should have throttled
Harrington. And team leader Colin Montgomerie should have given
Harrington a stern lecture on the the difference between
sportsmanship and gamesmanship, not carp about the American crowds.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there was sportsmanship on both sides Sunday, with
the grandest gesture coming from U.S. Open champion Payne Stewart,
who took his cue from Nicklaus. In the 1969 matches Nicklaus
conceded a putt to Jacklin, giving Britain a rare tie at the time,
much to the dismay of the American team. Nicklaus later lobbied to
include all of Europe in the matches.
</P>
<P>
   So on Sunday, with the outcome decided, Stewart conceded his
match to Montgomerie at the 18th hole, keeping the Scotsman's
winning streak in singles intact and apologizing for any bad
behavior on America's part.
</P>
<P>
   But Monty fumed. This is the same Montgomerie who dissed some
U.S. players before the 1997 Ryder Cup at Valderrama, noting that
Brad Faxon might not play well because he was going through a
divorce and Scott Hoch had missed a short putt to blow the 1989
Masters so he probably could not deal with Ryder Cup pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Monty later apologized and the American team accepted it.
</P>
<P>
   Now he says any apology from America is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   And the sulking and ranting from from across the Atlantic
continued into the week, with James offering up the possibility of
a future boycott.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday some American players had heard enough.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval fired back on ESPN's ``Up Close,'' noting he
believes much of the European team's anger is focused at American
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (James) was making reference to the U.S. team, then he
is a very sore loser, is what he is,'' Duval said. ``This is my
first Ryder Cup, but I have watched it on television and nothing
different happened this time than has happened in the past Ryder
Cups.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we lost two in a row, David, including an embarrassing
defeat at Oak Hill in Rochester, N.Y. after starting play Sunday
with the lead.
</P>
<P>
   So if Europe is ticked off about excessive celebrating, James
and his team should remember they started it.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, we ended it on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
