<HEADLINE>
FINLEY'S FINAL ANGELS START TONIGHT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Tonight could be Chuck Finley's final start in
an Anaheim Angels uniform -- or it could be just another in long
career by the lanky left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Finley is a free agent at the end of the season and, along with
general manager Bill Bavasi, has agreed to hold off any contract
talks until after the season. Finley, who was nearly traded to the
Indians just before the July 31 trading deadline, had been seeking
a two-year deal worth $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   If tonight's start is his last as an Angel, Finley hasn't gotten
sentimental about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't allowed myself to go down that road,'' said Finley,
who leads the team with 12 victories. ''I don't want to get caught
up in the emotion of something that might not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Angels interim manager Joe Maddon said he hasn't
contemplated the possibility of the team. He has no plans to save
the lineup card as a keepsake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't collect autographs or memorabilia or newspaper
articles,'' Maddon said. ''The only thing I've saved along those
lines is a St. Louis Cardinals program from 1964 with a bunch of
autographs in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddon said he grew up as a Cardinals fan.
</P>
<P>
   Percival's status: There has been no decision yet on the status
of closer Troy Percival, who has an inflammed right shoulder.
However, team medical director Dr. Lewis Yocum is expected to make
a decision today.
</P>
<P>
   Percival has said he wants to continue to pitch through the end
of the season, but Maddon said: ''If there is any risk we won't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own admission, Maddon is a touchy-feely kind of guy. When
he makes a trip to the mound to visit his pitcher, he'll put his
hand on the pitcher's arm or shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like to go out there and look them in the face and put my
hand on them,'' Maddon said. ''I can tell how fast his heart might
be pumping and I can tell if he's under control. It's the way I've
always been, it's just a natural reaction. I love working with
pitchers because I was a catcher. It was something I did as a
catcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Schedule: The Angels and A's will play the final game of their
three-game series tonight at 7:05. Finley (12-11, 4.41 ERA) will
start for Anaheim against Oakland's Gil Heredia (13-8, 4.78).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
