<HEADLINE>
KARIYA IMPROVING, PLANS TO PRACTICE TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Paul Kariya skated on his own and took part in
one non-contact drill on Wednesday, but once again the Aanheim
winger didn't participate in a full practice. Kariya hasn't
practiced with the team since reaggravating a left quad injury 1
1/2 weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomer Ladislav Kohn, acquired from Atlanta for eighth-round
draft choice on Monday, skated with the first line in Wednesday's
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, however, said he is improving, plans to practice today,
and still has hope he can play in the regular season opener
Saturday night in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the mindset that I'm going to play until I'm proven
wrong, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya said he hasn't had much pain ``the last 3-4 days, but
admitted he doesn't want to ``take one step forward and then 10
back, by pushing things too fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to listen to my body, Kariya said. ``I know it pretty
well. If I had listened before I wouldn't be in this situation.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Kevin Haller practiced for the first time in training
camp and like Kariya is hoping he can play in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not 100 percent, but it felt pretty good, said Haller,
who had arthroscopic knee surgery on Sept. 8. ``I'm almost a week
ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Haller said his lack of timing, not reinjuring the knee is his
main concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to play gritty and aggressive, he said. ``I might
favor it (his knee), but I'm not going to worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   Haller was paired with his partner of last seson, Jason
Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Other defensive pairings included Oleg Tverdovsky playing with
Ruslan Salei and the Swedish duo of Fredrik Olausson and Niclas
Havelid.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   As expected the Ducks sent Russian prospects defenseman Vitaly
Vishnevski and winger Maxim Balmochnykh to Cincinnati of the AHL.
Anaheim also sent forwards Bob Wren and Pete LeBoutillier and
defenseman Dan Trebil to Cincinnati. Goalie Tom Askey was sent
Kansas City of the IHL.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Matt Cullen scored three goals in the Ducks' final two
exhibition games, but it wasn't scoring that pleased the Anaheim
center the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to score goals, but I also thought I played a lot
better all-round game, he explained. ``I didn't think I had being
playing that well. I wasn't comfortable on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg was also pleased to see his No. 1
line center pick up his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have had good games even if hadn't scored, said
Hartsburg. ``The goals were the result of his effort. He's going in
the right direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
