<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 03:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1712 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-OREGONSTATE-LADN     09-30 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OREGONSTATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING'S COMING UP ROSES FOR 3-0 BEAVERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dennis Erickson is doing his best to make sure his Oregon State
football team maintains proper perspective concerning the Beavers
3-0 beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that an Oregon State football team hasn't captured
the first three games in a season since 1967. Never mind that this
week's opponent USC has chiseled out a 7-52-4 lifetime record
against Oregon State and the Beavers don't own a winning record
against any Pac-10 member.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the last bowl appearance was the 1965 Rose Bowl
and the postseason resume consists of two trips to the Pineapple
Bowl, one to the Liberty Bowl and three journeys to Pasadena. Never
mind that, according to Erickson, the hunger to win in Corvallis
has turned to starvation.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement needs to be tempered by that fact that the three
wins have come against Big West member Nevada, WAC member Fresno
State and I-AA participant Georgia Southern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, nothing against our opponents, but we haven't
played anybody as close to the caliber of a USC or anyone else in
the Pac-10,'' Erickson said. ``We really don't know where we're at
right now. I'm happy with the three wins. That's important to us.
But we'll find out a lot more about our team and where we are in
the Pac-10 after we play USC on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, what does Oregon State's best player
sophomore running back Ken Simonton think when he hears that there
could be a journalist out there somewhere who already has the
Beavers pegged for New Year's Day in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would shake that man's hand and tell him he has vision,''
said Simonton, a 5-foot-7, 175-pound flash, who played at Pittsburg
High for former Poly co-coach Thomas Whiting. ``We are capable of
doing that. You don't have to be the most dominant team. It's a
matter of week in and week out going out there and executing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers in the Rose Bowl? Sounds about as farfetched as a
slightly-recruited player like Simonton leading the nation in
rushing. Yet, after four weeks, it is indeed Simonton, with 185.67
yards per game, leading Iowa State's Darren Davis (185.00), and
Wisconsin's Ron Dayne (174.67) in the national rushing rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern is helping us win,'' said Simonton, whose 18
points per game ties him for the second in the country with
Alabama's Shaun Alexander and behind San Jose State's Deonce
Whittaker (18.67). ``But my main concern is to help us win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring a lot of points the Beavers average 40 points per
contest is how Oregon State has won its first three.
</P>
<P>
   ``They throw the ball well,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
``(Quarterback) Jonathan Smith is playing well. He's got
confidence. They've improved the receiver corps. But let's face it.
Ken Simonton is the guy. He's going to run the ball and run the
ball and you better be able to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Simonton is averaging nearly 33 carries per game. That's a lot
of pounding for a player like Dayne, who weighs nearly 260 pounds,
much less for a guy with the slight frame of Simonton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazes me a big guy can take 30 carries,'' said Simonton,
who has 557 yards and nine touchdowns rushing and four catches for
64 yards. ``A guy like Dayne has great feet, but he doesn't make
people miss. I have to make people miss. I don't take a lot of
(solid) hits. Even in 30 carries, I haven't taken a pounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Simonton would have done his pounding on the baseball field if
he would have followed family tradition. His father, brother and
cousin have all played professionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my family loves different sports,'' Simonton said. ``My
favorite is football.''
</P>
<P>
   A shoulder injury during his senior season at Pittsburg cost
Simonton an opportunity to pursue football in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a box full of letters from all over the country,''
Simonton said. ``It was a stack three feet high from Tennessee to
USC to Washington. But when I hurt my shoulder, most of them (took)
me off their list.''
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State was the only school which offered a scholarship and
Simonton gladly joined Mike Riley's program.
</P>
<P>
   After a redshirt season, Simonton stepped into the starting
lineup and became only the fifth player in school history to rush
for 1,000 yards when he eclipsed that mark by 79 yards. He was part
of a team that finished 5-6, but had narrow losses to UCLA (41-34),
Washington (35-34) and California (20-19). However, soon after
beating Oregon to end the year, Riley bolted to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard Riley was going to leave, I was like `Man, what
our we gonna do?','' Simonton said.
</P>
<P>
   In stepped Erickson, who directed Miami to national
championships in 1989 and 1991 and was the Seattle Seahawk head
coach for the previous four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Riley was a great coach, but bringing in Erickson brings
us to another level,'' Simonton said.
</P>
<P>
   Now we'll see just what level that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing our players know is, to be competitive in
the Pac-10, we've got to play well the next eight weeks,'' Erickson
said. ``I don't look at it as much as the USC game as our next
eight football games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
