<HEADER>
A1714 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-BAUER-AFFAIR-SFCHRON &LR;      09-30 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAUER-AFFAIR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BAUER AGAIN DENIES AFFAIR WITH STAFFER  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Surrounded by his wife and three children,
Republican presidential candidate Gary Bauer vehemently denied
Wednesday having an affair with a young campaign aide, obliquely
accusing a rival campaign of spreading ``vicious allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's trash-can politics. It's evil,'' Bauer said at a hastily
called Washington news conference, insisting, ``I have not violated
my wedding vows made 27 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer is a dark-horse candidate who has based his campaign on
courting the Christian right. He is battling millionaire Steve
Forbes to be the conservative challenger to front-runner George W.
Bush, and he implied that the Forbes campaign was spreading the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations first surfaced in an interview published Tuesday
in The Chronicle. Bauer was asked if he was the target of gossip
column items alleging a GOP presidential candidate was having an
affair with a ``twentysomething'' woman.
</P>
<P>
   The former adviser to President Ronald Reagan told The Chronicle
that he believed the item was written about him _ and that he had
been the victim of a smear campaign by a rival candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer Wednesday charged that reporters ``were getting this spun
to them frequently, continually, by the operatives of one
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forbes campaign fiercely denied the charge. ``That's
absolutely untrue,'' said Forbes spokesman Greg Mueller. ``We don't
engage in that kind of political game. If there's one thing our
campaign engages in, it's issues and substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer's former campaign chairman, Charles Jarvis, left Bauer two
weeks ago to join the Forbes campaign as an unpaid adviser. He said
in a telephone interview that he had warned Bauer several times
privately that the candidate's behavior toward a young aide was
creating a bad appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a post Clinton-Lewinsky world, pro-family leaders cannot be
spending hour after hour after hour behind closed doors with a
young staff person,'' Jarvis said. But he stopped short of accusing
Bauer of having an affair and said that before Wednesday, he had
not talked publicly about his concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis said nine members of Bauer's staff have left in the last
month, ``primarily'' because they ``could not agree with a lower
standard for a leader of pro-family causes in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer denied being confronted by any aide about any questionable
personal behavior. ``No, I cannot imagine that anybody in a
campaign would object to me having a meeting behind closed doors
with a professional woman,'' he said. ``Such meetings take place
all over Washington, D.C., every day. ... Is somebody suggesting
that it's 1899? It's 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis called Bauer's denial ``absolutely untrue.'' Jarvis said
he urged Bauer to avoid ``even the appearance of impropriety ...
especially by someone claiming the mantle of moral leadership and
the pro-family movement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bauer aide Frank Cannon seized on Jarvis' statements, saying
they were significant because ``finally, someone in the Forbes camp
(is) willing to go on the record with these baseless allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Cannon said Jarvis' allegations of improper conduct illustrated
that the Forbes campaign is now engaged in ``desperate tactics,''
because ``they've spent $50 million in five years, to end up in the
margin of error (in the polls) with us.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle Political Writer Carla Marinucci contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
