<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 09:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1783 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-HOMELESS-BOS &LR;      09-30 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HOMELESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSING ADVOCATES FEAR HOMELESS FACE THE WORST WINTER YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The number of people who sought emergency shelter this
summer in urban communities, most of them driven by the high cost
of housing in Massachusetts, signals what housing advocates fear
may be the worst winter yet for the state's homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating an onslaught as cold weather sets in, housing
advocates are requesting 700 more beds from the state's Department
of Health and Human Services. The number of people seeking
emergency shelter during the summer jumped 5 percent over to last
year's figures, according to the advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It indicates that it's going to be worse than last year and
last year was the worse year ever,'' said John O'Brien, director of
the Shattuck Shelter in Boston. ``When you overflow in the summer,
when people can be outside, the anticipation is there is going to
be a greater need for additional beds in the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   The tremendous increase in the number of people looking for
emergency shelter during the warmest months of the year caught
shelter providers off guard and sent them scrambling in July,
August, and September to convert offices and hallways into
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never before in the summer have the shelters overflowed,''
said Philip Mangano, executive director of Massachusetts Housing
and Shelter Alliance. ``That was always the time for respite for
shelter providers.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, homeless shelters have experienced high demand
during the winter, but the situation has usually eased as the
weather warmed.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, many homeless people prefer to live in parks
or under bridges rather than in cramped shelters, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, however, so many people needed shelter due to the
lack of affordable housing that shelters experienced the sort of
overflows usually seen only in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   With fewer people able to move out of shelters because rents are
so high, and more moving in because they're priced out of the
rental market, ``there were more people in the system and the
shelters overflowed,'' said Mangano.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless community was hit hard last winter when seven
alcoholic street people in Boston died from the cold weather. At
the same time, the federal government slashed funding for the
homeless in Massachusetts by 40 percent. Homelessness in Boston
alone increased by 5 percent from 1997 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Shelter workers from across the state are planning to meet with
state officials next week to discuss what can be done to prepare
for the expected crunch this winter.
</P>
<P>
   According to housing statistics, 22,000 people across the state
will experience homelessness this year, with 4,000 sleeping in an
emergency shelter on any given night.
</P>
<P>
   During past winters, shelters needed 500 additional beds a night
to handle increasing demand, but officials don't think that will be
enough this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need will be much greater,'' said Mangano.
</P>
<P>
   The United Homes for Children Boston, Dorchester, for instance,
which normally accepts the overflow from other shelters, often
reached its capacity of 88 men throughout the summer, said
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, during the summers we have a lull, but this August
about 20 of the nights we were full by 9 p.m.,'' said Philip
Wright, director of adult services for the shelter. ``That's very
unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials say one reason for the increase could be the number of
young adults hanging out in public city areas during the day who
have nowhere to sleep at night. Others say the state is also seeing
an increasing number of elderly people seeking housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing more elderly and more young people who are using
heroin,'' said O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   Others blame the increase on a housing market where rents are so
high that families are doubling up in some places.
</P>
<P>
   The increased demand for emergency shelter is also seen in
Springfield and Worcester, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Springfield, shelter workers saw more people in July than
they normally do in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing for us out West is that our numbers
rarely deviate from month to month, '' said Frank Keough, director
of the Worthington Shelter in Springfield. ``But the number of
people seen this summer was staggering.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
