<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN03-CO     09-30 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: SUV sighted; up periscope!
 &HT;    (For release Oct. 3, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lease on my automobile soon running out, I am in the market
for a car. As I prowl between intensive salesmen who want my name,
address and phone number before they'll allow me to open the
driver's side door of a showroom car, I have come to the
realization that the auto industry _ both foreign and domestic _
does not meet my needs.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the cars drive well, and they're quieter than they used to
be, and you can play CDs in them, but there's more to a car than
torque, looks and sound.
</P>
<P>
   When I say a ``car,'' I mean a traditional car; a sedan, four
doors, seats five or six.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with these cars are those monster sport utility
vehicles and their elongated cousin, the van. This has been written
before. SUVs are an intimidating factor to anyone who drives just a
car. Everything from blinding lights in the rear-view mirror to
zero visibility in parking lots make coexistence between just cars
and SUVs as difficult to achieve as a lunch date between Bill
Clinton and Monica's mom.
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry has not sought my advice on how to deal with
this, but I will offer it anyway. Were I designing a sedan-sized
car, either compact, mid-sized or the Cadillac and Town Car types,
I would include these in the factory-installed features:
</P>
<P>
   _ A periscope somewhere near the rear of the exterior that could
be raised and lowered, when trying to back out of a parking space
when you're pinned between two SUVs and hardly can see the
sunlight.
</P>
<P>
   _ An LED functioning proclamation facing out from the rear
window that, when activated by a steering-wheel based button,
reads: ``Please turn off your brights.'' After a 10-second wait,
the LED would read: ``Dammit, turn off those brights!''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, however, the problem is not solved as most often the
lights on an SUV are not on bright; the vehicle itself sits too
high and its lights burn into the rear-view mirror and your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   If drivers of SUVs can appreciate our problem, then we can
proceed with pressuring the auto builders to meet those needs.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of studies that show the physical dangers of
SUVs to sedans, and studies that show that some SUVs can't even
withstand a punch in the nose themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In the world in which I travel, so many of those SUVs are being
driven by mothers, either taking their children to school or dance
class. In some stretch vans, entire teams can be transported. The
drivers rightfully argue that they feel very safe in those
behemoths. I'm sure they are, but I feel threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Back more than 30 years ago, when my wife was hauling four small
children around, she didn't have an SUV. They all were stuffed into
a Volkswagen Beetle and lived to tell exaggerated stories about it.
This clearly was unsafe but nobody knew it then.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has delivered the SUV to the public. While its
original intent may have been to haul cattlemen through rocky and
hilly terrain, it has evolved into an urban chariot.
</P>
<P>
   I am not unsophisticated about large vehicles. For several
years, I owned a small motor home. Thus, I already have experienced
the thrill of a strong crosswind, that sucking sound from the gas
tank and the humiliation of emptying potty cisterns. I also did my
share of tailgating guys in little cars, oblivious to their
discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   But now I'm a sedan-only man. For a while, I fought the
unsuccessful (and unrealistic) argument that SUVs should be banned.
But I've grown up. I understand the needs of some for those. So
rather than call for their expulsion, I want some features added to
my sedan that will better allow me to coexist with those beasts.
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry constantly strains to create new features for
its vehicles. By this writing, I am propositioning them to do
something for the beleaguered sedan. If this is too impractical for
their minds, then how about an optional rear-mounted, air-cooled
machine gun?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
