 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 445 -- Sept. 29, 1999, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. DESPERATE TO SEEM 16 For the entertainment industry, the
money is in teenagers. Never has there been so much opportunity for
the young and the hungry. There are huge numbers of viewers,
spearheaded by teenage girls, who will pretty much see or watch
anything as long as the actors and actresses look like teenagers
too. Networks are convinced that the teenage audience is a highly
desirable niche, mostly because advertisers think so -- boys and
girls are making many of their own consumer choices before they are
out of puberty and advertisers want to reach them. For aspiring
actresses and actors, making it in Hollywood means making it right
now - before you look 20. By Lynn Hirschberg. From The New York
Times Magazine. Full-length (8,200 words) + edited article
available.
_____________________________________________________________ 2.
GEORGE CLOONEY GOES FOR GOLD ON THE SILVER SCREEN George Clooney
thinks he's a good actor. Sometimes, anyway. One of the failures
that he frankly admits is ``Batman and Robin'' (1997.) ``I saw part
of it the other day on cable and cringed through it.'' Clooney, the
handsome and charismatic former star of the television series
``ER,'' has yet to score on the big screen. He's trying again with
``Three Kings,'' an ambitious mix of black comedy, action and drama
set amid the chaos of the Gulf War. Clooney believes that Hollywood
is mistaken in assuming that moviegoers want only bland, easily
digested fare. By Ian Spelling. 1,300 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
MOLLY SHANNON : FINDING LAUGHTER IN TEARS A hospital waiting room
doesn't seem like the place to get your start in stand-up comedy,
but 4-year-old Molly Shannon didn't choose it. That choice was made
by the driver who killed her mother. She spent her time in the
hospital waiting room trying to make the other kids laugh. ``I
thought they had it worse than me,'' she recalls. ``I come from a
sad place and the only way I could make peace with it was by making
others laugh. She has achieved success on ``Saturday Night Live''
and is currently riding a hot streak with a role in the Dr. Seuss
classic, ``The Grinch Who Stole Christmas.'' By Cindy Pearlman.
1,200 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
HOG HELL : A LIVE-ACTION 'ANIMAL FARM' HITS A TIMELY NOTE During
more than 25 years of covering Hollywood, Ivor Davis has
interviewed hundreds of personalities, but this summer he found
himself in an ornate ballroom at Pasadena's Ritz-Carlton hotel
putting questions to a 300-pound pig. This state-of-the-art
animatronic pig called Napoleon is the star of the formidable
``Animal Farm,'' a remarkable film version of George Orwell's
classic 1945 satiric novel in which an animal revolution gradually
devolves into a ruthlessly repressive system worse than that of the
humans they have overthrown. (The London-based Creature Shop has
used sheer technological magic to create an entire barnyard of
talking pigs, donkeys, horses, geese, dogs and sheep for the film.)
Napoleon even answered reporters' questions - slightly better and
more articulately than the average television starlet. By Ivor
Davis. 1,500 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 5.
HOLLYWOOD DISH ``I love food,'' says Matt Damon. ``Everything bad -
I love pizza, beer, chocolate and spaghetti.'' Sounds like a case
for Carrie Latt Wiatt, nutritionist to the stars. She is the
founder of Diet Designs, Hollywood's most high-profile calorie
counter. Her custom-made meals have been delivered to many
Hollywood types who need help staying svelte between movies. When
Alicia Silverstone couldn't get into her catsuit for the last
``Batman'' film, director Joel Schumacher called on Wiatt for help.
Aside from her skill at preparing restaurant-quality, nutritionally
balanced food in moderate but satisfying portions, Wiatt's secret
lies in tailoring her daily menus to suit the celebrity's
individual tastes and she takes into account the dieter's sweet
tooth. By Louise Farr. From W magazine. 1,000 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 6.
CHRIS CARTER GETS VIRTUAL ``Harsh Realm'' is virtually here. This
is ``X-Files'' creator Chris Carter's latest excursion into the
dark and bizarre, following the relative failure of ``Millennium''
and just as ``X-Files'' enters its final season. Carter found
inspiration for his new saga in James Hudnall's comic book ``Harsh
Realm,'' the 1982 sci-fi classic ``Blade Runner'' and such war
epics as ``Stalag 17'' (1953) and ``Saving Private Ryan'' (1998.)
``Harsh Realm'' is a parallel world that provides allegorical
potential. It's a world without God, without codes, standards and
morals and a man who is trying to change this world. By Ian
Spelling. 1,000 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________ 7.
STAR WARS : THE PHANTOM MENACE This film opens in October in
Holland, Portugal, Belgium, France, Greece, India. Please contact
us for details of available ``Phantom Menace'' articles.
