<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-COLUMN-1003-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAKING THE LONG VIEW INTO THE FUTURE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (k) commentary categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ancient Egyptians buried their dead inside massive
pyramids built to last forever. Medieval architects designed
churches that took centuries to construct. The Founding Fathers
drew up a constitution to guide this nation for eternity.
</P>
<P>
   For these visionaries, the future stretched far into the
distance. But today, accepting an invitation to a Super Bowl party
would amount to long-term planning for most Americans. With cell
phones, microwave ovens, electronic mail, jet planes and other
technologies speeding up daily life, our time horizons seem to be
getting shorter.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps nowhere does the future seem nearer than in the
nation's capital where lawmakers' internal clocks are set by the
nightly newscast and the next election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, before this millennium ends, Congress must make decisions
that could affect the people who will be wearing party hats and
blowing horns on Dec. 31, 9999. (CQ) The issue involves the safe
storage of nuclear fuels, which remain lethal for thousands of
years.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear waste storage legislation, to be taken up this week in
the Senate, will set radiation-exposure standards for Yucca
Mountain, a 6,000-foot-high mountain ridge northwest of Las Vegas.
The Energy Department wants to use the interior of the mountain to
store 70,000 metric tons of high-level waste from nuclear power
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The waste would be put into steel containers designed to last
10,000 years. That seems like very long-range planning, until
scientists point out that the peak dose of radiation may not occur
for another 300,000 years, after the nuclear waste has had time to
cook the surrounding walls of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   How can Congress set standards for a storage facility that will
have to work well for hundreds of thousands of years?
Environmentalists point out that earthquakes frequently rumble the
earth not far from Yucca Mountain, which is ringed by volcanoes.
Will earthquakes, eruptions, global warming or other factors allow
water to enter the storage area and carry radioactive materials
into the water table?
</P>
<P>
   The irony of our age is that while we are making more products
for short-term use, from electricity to Styrofoam cups, we are
generating wastes that will last longer and longer.
</P>
<P>
   To help people think about the long-term impact of their
choices, a group of ``futurists'' in northern California is raising
money to build a clock to last 10,000 years. The Clock of the Long
Now, as the non-profit foundation calls the contraption
(www.longnow.org), would be built somewhere in a high desert and
would tick just once a day to remind fast-living Americans to think
about future generations. To be built on a scale similar to the
stone pillars at Stonehenge, the giant clock would have chimes that
ring once each millennium.
</P>
<P>
   For the millions of Americans who have yet to make plans for
this year's New Year's Eve, the Long Now planners may seem to have
a few cuckoos already in their clocks.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
