<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hair today, gone tomorrow; will it grow back?
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ My mother is going to kill me. I know, I'm
too old to worry about what my mother thinks, but we all do as long
as they're alive. And when she sees what has happened to my head,
she will not be happy. As it happens, she'll be down this weekend
for a visit. Great timing, considering my parents come down this
way maybe twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   To explain, the past few years I've taken to wearing what's left
of my hair fairly short. Low maintenance, cooler outside, and I'm
not one to care much about appearance anyway. My mother hates it,
wants my hair back to combable length all around and not buzzed on
the sides. This, understand, is the same woman who used to force me
to get hair cuts in high school when I was bent on growing it down
to my shoulders. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happened. In a weak moment, I made a pledge to
volunteers with the Nacogdoches County Chamber of Commerce, which
held a membership drive last week. I'm about to take over as
chairman next month, so I promised that if we got more than 200 new
members _ a 33 percent increase _ I would allow someone to buzz my
hair down to the scalp on stage at the finale party. The paid
chamber executive also agreed to do so, but he has hardly any hair
and gets paid to do this stuff, so don't waste pity on him.
</P>
<P>
   Waste it on me. I look like a short, bespectacled version of
Woody Harrelson in ``Natural Born Killers.'' We signed up 208 new
members, nine more than I was hoping for. Do the math. I did and
started looking for an exit, but I was caught like a rabbit in a
briarpatch. I was escorted on stage by two women, one of whom works
for me, and they proceeded to take off the safety guard on the
clippers and buzz my noggin down to the kind of stubble a man feels
if he quits shaving for a day, two at the most.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who works for me took far too much delight in turning
me into Elmer Fudd in front of about 75 wildly cheering
ne'er-do-wells. First thing I said to her the next day was, ``So,
how's the job search going?'' She didn't take me seriously, as well
she shouldn't _ good help being hard to find, and my hair fairly
likely to grow back.
</P>
<P>
   I say fairly likely. Remember what happens if you cut your lawn
_ which is already barely hanging on because of the heat and
drought _ too short in the dog days of August. You can kill that
sucker quicker than you can say Yul Brynner. What if that happens
to me? I'll be joining the Hair Club.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, I've either been out of the office or on
vacation, so I've taken to wearing a floppy fisherman's hat I
bought at Wally-World. It's khaki and has a Dallas Cowboys star in
the center. I love this hat, though my affection is apparently not
shared with anyone who has opted to comment on it. Most remarks are
along the line of, ``What's up with that weird hat?'' I lift it,
show my skull and elicit some type of strong reaction _ gasps,
shrieks of laughter, looks of horror. It's great to provide some
small measure of amusement to others.
</P>
<P>
   One of my golfing buddies took a look at me, sans hat, and said,
``You know, I never realized you had such a peculiar looking
skull.'' With friends like that ...
</P>
<P>
   There are some fringe benefits. Women love to rub my head. I
don't know why. Maybe they think a genie will pop out of my ear and
grant them three wishes. Old women, good-looking women, little
girls, nearly every female I've run across that knew me before the
Great Buzz, has immediately reached out (or in most cases down) and
rubbed my head. I'm starting to worry that all that rubbing is
going to impede hair growth.
</P>
<P>
   The other benefit is obvious, though I still can't quit the
habit. I jump out of the shower each morning and immediately reach
for a brush to comb my hair. Never have used a hair dryer, or hair
spray or any other foo-foo stuff, but I always attempted to get as
much of my hair going in the same direction as possible. Without
exception, each morning since this happened, I've reached for the
brush and then realized there was no need. Another 12 seconds saved
in the morning rush to get out the door and to work.
</P>
<P>
   It is growing back, though slowly. My forehead with stubble is
now even with my ears, something that was slightly less obvious
with a half-inch or so of hair up top. I'm thinking about growing
it long enough where you can't see my scalp from 50 yards away and
then keeping it at that length, so I still don't have to mess with
combing it.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't tell my mother. I plan on selling her on that scalped
lawn theory I mentioned a while back.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
