<HEADER>
A1816 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN01-COX     09-30 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is gun control a defining issue?
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the wake of mass murders in a Fort Worth
church and a Littleton, Colo., school, gun violence and gun control
are politically hot.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democrats' leading presidential
candidate, hopes to use gun control as a club against the GOP
front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who does not want to
strengthen existing gun laws but thinks enforcement must be
improved.
</P>
<P>
   While allowing licensed people to carry handguns is still
popular in Texas _ 62 percent favored it, according to The Texas
Poll in April _ gun control wins more backers, particularly among
women and minorities, in national polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats obviously hope public opinion has shifted enough
to turn Bush's position from a political advantage in Texas, the
South and parts of the West to a larger disadvantage elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's position on guns resemble those of his father, former
President Bush. In the elder Bush's race for president in 1988
against Democrat Michael Dukakis, Bush got enormous support from
the National Rifle Association and other anti-gun control
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's October 1988 magazine featured a purported quote by
then-Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis, saying that he wanted to
``disarm'' gun owners. The quote was actually from a Republican
supposedly quoting Dukakis in 1986. Dukakis said he was for
cracking down on cheap handguns, but not rifles and shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   But that issue alone was enough for Dukakis to lose the votes of
a lot of Democrats in places like East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, George W. was running against incumbent Democratic Gov.
Ann Richards. He and the gun groups made much of Richards' veto the
year before of a bill to allow a nonbinding referendum on licensing
people to carry concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the Texas Police Chiefs Association he'd not only have
signed the right-to-carry bill, but also would have voted ``yes''
in the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   It helped Bush that his effort to unseat Richards coincided with
two other political forces:
</P>
<P>
   _ A big anti-Clinton effort nationally by Republicans in the
1994 congressional elections that won them control of the U.S.
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ An assault by the Gun Owners of America on incumbent
congressmen they considered even mildly anti-gun _ such as House
Judiciary Committee Chairman Jack Brooks (D-Beaumont), who, even
though he opposed gun control, had compromised on the Clinton
administration's crime bill, which included a waiting period for
handgun purchases.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, after his victory, Bush honored his pledge, signing a
bill to allow people to carry concealed weapons with a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Bush's dad quit his life membership in the NRA after
the group's spokesman called members of the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms ``jackbooted thugs'' who harass gun owners.
Gov. Bush didn't have that option or problem, since he ``is not and
never has been a member of the NRA,'' his office says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he signed a bill amending the right-to-carry law to
remove a ban on carrying concealed weapons into places like
churches.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, he signed a bill limiting the ability of Texas
municipalities to file lawsuits against gun manufacturers for
injuries caused by their products.
</P>
<P>
   He also refused to help revive a stalled bill that would have
required instant background checks at gun shows. Bush said he
supports such checks, but maintained that the federal government,
not the states, should take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Bush had a joint press conference with Texas Attorney
General John Cornyn and federal U.S. attorneys from around Texas to
announce a program to coordinate federal and state prosecution of
criminals who use guns, to maximize their punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his support for the effort began weeks before the Fort
Worth church massacre _ a statement echoed by U.S. Attorney Paul
Coggins of Dallas, a Democrat and Clinton appointee.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats may be able to excite voters against Bush on guns.
Yet while national polls show a majority would favor more gun
control, only a handful of pro-control voters consider it a
defining issue. Meanwhile, the pro-gun forces take gun ownership
rights very, very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
