<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1818 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-MILNER01-COX     09-30 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MILNER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Want to read a dirty, silly book you can't put down?
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new novel by Austin, Texas, writer Neal Barrett Jr., titled
``Bad Eye Blues'' (Kensington Books) is outrageous, downright silly
in places, has an impossible plot and often unbelievable
characters, but I couldn't put the darn thing down until I'd
finished it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to all the above, this book is filled with vulgar,
bad taste situations, language and episodes that made me want to
throw the darn thing into the fireplace and burn it. But not until
I'd finished reading the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   What caused me to pick it up and start reading it? That's always
a good question unless a book is by an author one has previously
read and enjoyed or been severely provoked by, neither of which was
the case here. I think what piqued my curiosity, besides the title,
was the book's dedication, that read: ``With love and respect, this
one's for Joe R. Lansdale, my evil twin.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lansdale, as you may or may not know, is a writer of really
funny mysteries who lives in Nacogdoches. I've read a couple of his
books and think they are unusual and worth spending time on,
although for some unknown reason I have yet to review one in this
column.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad Eye Blues'' is one of a series by Barrett starring bug
artist Wiley Moss. That's right, bug artist. He draws bugs for such
publications as National Geographic and other magazines that
glorify insects. He draws them anatomically correct, you see, if
anatomical is the right word for bug parts.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it is this talent and job that gets Wiley Moss in
trouble at the outset of this particular Wiley Moss adventure. He
is just beginning what promises to be a wonderful evening with the
wonderful and lovely aeronautical engineer Claire de Mer when he is
kidnapped by two dangerous looking mugs who transport him all the
way across country to Idaho, by plane, limo and bus.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving in this small out-of-the way Idaho resort, or what
purports to be a resort although there doesn't seem to be anyone
there but a group of prostitutes and a couple of gangster types who
seem to be in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The chief gangster explains that he has kidnapped Wiley and had
him brought there so he can draw portraits of the whores, who love
to frolic in the resort's pool. Naked.
</P>
<P>
   Being kidnapped for this purpose is, of course, not all bad, but
Wiley soon begins planning to escape, perhaps with Laurel, his
favorite naked prostitute. But escape is not easy. A raging forest
fire breaks out as Wiley and his new friends begin their complex
escape plan which is complicated by the fire and several mysterious
shoot-outs that kill several strangers and some people who are
known to Wiley and his friends.
</P>
<P>
   One of their temporary hiding places is a topless domino parlor.
Another is Bob's Marmot City &AMP; Rattlesnake Farm.
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. As I said above _ outrageous, downright
silly/often unbelievable characters and lots of vulgar, bad taste
dialogue and action.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like your cup of tea, rush right to the nearest
book store and get a copy of ``Bad Eye Blues.'' You'll love it.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I was disgusted, all the way to the last outrageous
page.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
