<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, October 1,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week. This
layout is now available.Art includes several color photos
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0928 -- Old San Juan, Puerto Rico _ a
20-square-block district of cozy streets, shady plazas and Spanish
colonial architectural gems _ beckons with Caribbean lore and
legend, a window into the fascinating early years of European
discovery and conquest. (Williams, Cox Washington Bureau) Art
includes a 3-column color photo of a man walking a street, a
1-column color photo of a man feeding the birds, a 2-column color
photo of a historic fort and a 2-column color photo of birds making
nests in the fort wall.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IF YOU GO BOX -- A list of things to look for when in Old
San Juan. (Williams, Cox Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BEAUTY IN THE BERKSHIRES -- In his famous song ``Alice's
Restaurant,'' Arlo Guthrie immortalized a hole-in-the-wall
restaurant in Stockbridge, Mass. But the refrain applies to all the
Berkshires. You can get anything you want here. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- The Paris Metro company and the national
railway company, which together manage suburban train service in
Paris, have decided to eliminate the first-class option. (N.Y.
Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-YURTS _ NANTAHALA GORGE, N.C. _ Yurts _ canvas huts
modeled after the living quarters of ancient nomadic Mongolian
tribes _ are to tents what the Ritz-Carlton is to Motel 6. Each of
the eight fat, round, rust-colored dwellings at the Falling Waters'
Adventure Resort yurt village, near North Carolina's Nantahala
National Forest, boasts amenities that would make your average
flannel-clad woodsman spit in disgust: A polished Douglas fir
floor. A comfy canopy bed flanked by Pottery Barn-style side tables
and lamps. A refrigerator, coffee maker, ceiling fan, space heater,
chest-of drawers. If one must be camped in the woodsy recesses of
Western North Carolina, fending off Blair Witch-type sounds at
night, one could do far worse.(Hamilton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)WITH COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BLUEMOUNDS _ LUVERNE, Minn. _ Minnesota's 1,500-acre Blue
Mounds State Park offers visitors a pioneer vision of natural
beauty _ wildflowers, cliff swallows and dickcissels, bison,
head-high teasel and big bluestem. (McCarthy, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LEAFSPOTS _ The temperatures are dipping. The days are
shortening. And the trees are getting ready for their closeup.
</P>
<P>
   Every fall, the leaves put on their colorful pageant, and
Atlantans flock to sites where the show is the most dramatic. We
provide a list of places around the South where you can get your
fall color fix. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ LITTLE HAVANA, Fla. _ Little Havana (pop 1,500), 12
miles north of Tallahassee, has grown into the art and antiques
center of North Florida. Besides great shopping, there's a cozy B&AMP;B
within two blocks of town and the regionally famous Nicholson
Farmhouse Restaurant. The big doings coming up Oct. 2-3 is the 4th
Annual Havana Bead and Jewelry Festival. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AROUND-WORLD _ Around the world on the cheap. My best
friend Chad and I spent four months and $7,000 each (including the
$2,000 I had to get wired to me) hauling our backpacks around the
world. We traveled by plane, train, motorcycle, bike, felucca (an
Egyptian sailboat) _ you name it. We used a Eurail pass to explore
England, France, Belgium, the Netherlands, Germany, the Czech
Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Austria, Italy, Spain, Switzerland and
Greece. And onward by air _ to Cairo, Bangkok, and Hong Kong. Chad
found an online travel agency called Ticket Planet
(www.ticketplanet.com) that specializes in around-the-world air
fares for budget travelers. We stayed in hostels and lived cheap.
(Nuttle, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-SHOWS _ MILAN _ A. Scott Walton reports from Fashion Week
in Milan. Combo of main runway revue, notes and occasional
postcards. (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-WEB _ A look at fashion-related web sites in which
individual sites are critiqued on basis of merchandise, prices,
shipping, etc. illustrated. (Mikkileni, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15. WITH ILLUSTRATION.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-EDITORS _ New York _ Fashion editors live in a sort of
perpetual Australia. When everyone else is talking fall _ football
rivalries, new classes, possible Halloween costumes _ they're
thinking spring. Ask them to discuss the present, and they look a
little confused. (When pressed, can you recall details of what
occupied your thoughts six months ago?) (Sturrock, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   FASHION _ NEW YORK _ Who floated to the top and who sank to the
bottom during Fashion Week in New York? (Sturrock, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-TREND _ NEW YORK _ If you prefer charting your own
course to following the fashion crowd, Spring 2000 will offer
plenty of itineraries to choose from. At the recent New York shows,
designers traveled in a dozen different directions. But what most
of them shared was a sense of adventure and fun and femininity.
Black? Largely banished. Simplicity? Buh-bye. (Sturrock, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available today after 2 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0930 _ Through his gentle, all-too-human
comedy, Charles Schulz has brought the world to the ``Peanuts''
party for half a century. (Schwan, Palm Beach Post) Art includes a
4-column color illustration of the ``Peanuts'' characters,'' an
18-pica B&AMP;W photo of Charles Schulz, a 4-column B&AMP;W comic strip
from 1950.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GROWING UP PEANUTS BOX _ Let's imagine what might become of
Charlie Brown and Co. when they grow up. (Schwan, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY: BIG EGO _ Dear David E. Kelley: You've come down
with a nasty case of Big Head Disease, and you need to treat it
before your considerable talents are wasted. (Holloway, Austin
American Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS _ Just because ``The Mummy'' has desert scenery, a
hunky action hero (Brendan Fraser), hissable bad guys and
supernatural hoodoo doesn't make it an Indiana Jones movie. (Staff,
Cox News Service) Art includes 2-column color photo from ``The
Mummy.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ Nine Inch Nails' Trent Reznor wants you to feel his
pain. And there are oceans of it. Also, reviews of the new releases
from Tori Amos and Brooks &AMP; Dunn. (Staff, Cox News Service) Art
includes 6-pica color mug of Tori Amos.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTNEY _ A visit to an Atlanta drug store earlier this year
inspired Paul McCartney to write a title track ``Run Devil Run''
and to picture the store on his album cover. Obviously, it's no
ordinary drug store. (DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   PIANIST-FLANAGAN _ A Q&AMP;A with noted jazz pianist Tommy Flanagan,
who performs in metro Atlanta with his trio this Saturday. (Dollar,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   Q&AMP;A-GILL-MESSINA _ Q&AMP;A's with Vince Gill and Jo Dee Messina,
pegged to their Friday night concert in Atlanta. (MLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 43.
</P>
<P>
   RONDSTAT _ An interview with Linda Ronstadt, pegged to her
appearance with Emmy Lou Harris in Atlanta Sunday. (MLongino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 31.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Discography. 9.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   TURNER-SOUTH _ Today the TV empire that Ted built is launching
yet another cable network: Turner South. This regional network will
include a country music show from Nashville, a TV edition of
Southern Living magazine ( a Time Warner property), a comedy
program featuring an Atlanta-based comedy troupe, and World Classic
Wrestling re-runs packaged as ``classics.'' The real hook here is
the sports programming which will include Braves, Hawks and
Thrashers games that will help Turner/ Time Warner compete for
advertising and eyeballs with their nemeses over at Fox. The
network will be available in Georgia, Mississippi, Tennessee, South
Carolina and parts of North Carolina. We talk to the people behind
Turner South (including outgoing wunderkind Bill Burke) to find out
why they expects this new venture to be a hit. (Harris, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TBS-CHANGES _ The network best known for bringing us Braves
games and Andy Griffith re-runs is re-inventing itself. There will
still be Braves games, but Andy's gone and TBS is moving forward
with male-driven programming like the Chimp Channel, off-network
sitcoms like ``The Cosby Show'', broadcast movie premieres such as
``Batman and Robin'' and original movies like ``The Timeshifters.''
We do a Q&AMP;A with Brad Siegel, the new man in the middle whose now
in charge of TNT, TBS, and the all-new Turner South. (Harris,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-ALASKA _ Movie review: ``Mystery, Alaska.'' Hockey movie
in which small town players take on the New York Rangers. From
David E. Kelley, TV's wunderkind (big Emmy winners Ally McBeal and
The Practice). Grade: C+. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
15.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-ELMO _ Movie review: ``The Adventures of Elmo in
Grouchland.'' Grade: C+. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
10.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-GUINEVERE _ Movie review: ``Guinevere,'' with Sarah
Polley (''The Sweet Hereafter'') falling for an older guy. Grade:
A-. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GUINEVERE-SMART _ Interview with Jean Smart (``Designing
Women''), whose dead-on scene in the new ``Guinevere'' is
reminiscent of the take-charge, scene-stealing moment that won
Beatrice Straight an Oscar for ``Network.'' (Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-KINGS _ Movie review: ``Three Kings,'' a Gulf War hero
flick with George Clooney and Mark Wahlberg as gold hunters turned
guys with a conscience. Grade: B. (Longino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-PLUNKETT _ Movie review: ``Plunkett &AMP; Macleane.'' about
18th century highwaymen. Grade: B-. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-SUGAR _ Movie review: ``Sugar Town,'' about the LA music
scene. Grade: B-. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BEAUTY _ Review of the movie ``AMERICAN BEAUTY.'' 4
stars. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post). 16.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-ALASKA _ Review of the movie ``MYSTERY ALASKA.'' 3 stars.
(Erstein, Palm Beach Post). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-KINGS _ Review of the movie ``Three Kings.'' (Erstein,
Palm Beach Post). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0928-- Look into the yellow eyes of the Blue Dog,
and what do you see? Loneliness. Confusion. Trust. ``It's looking
to us for answers,'' suggests George Rodrigue, the Louisiana artist
who created the haunting little dog. Rodrigue is preparing to take
off on a 27-city book tour for ``Blue Dog Man,'' his lavishly
illustrated new book. (Morris, Austin American-Statesman) Art
includes 2-column photo from book and a 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH -- FEMINIST ON MEN -- Feminist author Susan Faludi,
attempting to find the common thread running through the varied
tapestry of the male dilemma, has returned with ``Stiffed: The
Betrayal of the American Man.'' She blames male anguish and
alienation on a celebrity-worshipping, consumer culture _ not
coincidentally, the same forces which, she says, oppress women.
(Tucker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 6-pica color
photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DATING MR. WRONG -- Falling in love with a loser can be
avoided say two relationship experts, and they are offering some
advice in their new book. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post) Art includes
6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SOUTHERN RELEASES -- Capsule reviews of several new
releases in Southern literature. (Weaver, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes five 6-pica color photos of book
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- The strength of the left-brained, isn't
compatible with the new software of rapidly changing images. The
right-brained are again on top. You don't think so? (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column color photo of
columnist
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Like Michael Crichton, Tess Gerritsen discovered
that the pen is mightier than the scapel. Or at least more
lucrative. The former doctor has become a best selling author of
medical thrillers such as ``Harvest'' and ``Life Support.'' Her
latest novel, ``Gravity,'' about a disaster aboard the space
station, has been sold to New Line Cinema for a big-budget film
next summer. Dreamworks' Robert Zemeckis is producer. Also, Emory
adds two authors to its creative writing program. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-EYMAN-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Booksellers and
publishers struggling to stay alive have a new study that explains
why they're struggling to stay alive. The study informs us that
people ages 55 to 64 read for 53 minutes a day compared to those in
the 25 to 29 bracket, who read for only 24 minutes a day. While it
might be logical to focus on that portion of the market that reads
more, that would also mean having to constantly replenish said
market, which is in the process of dying off. (Eyman. Palm Beach
Post). 18.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ A new novel by Austin writer Neal Barrett, Jr.,
titled ``Bad Eye Blues'' (Kensington Books) is outrageous,
downright silly in places, has an impossible plot and often
unbelievable characters, but I couldn't put the darn thing down
until I'd finished it. (Milner, Lufkin Daily News). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
