<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1826 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i BC-RUSSIA-POTATOWARS-$AD     09-30 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POTATOWARS-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN POOR RUSSIA, A DEADLY FOOD FIGHT
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Vasiliyevka is about 100
miles north of Rostov-on-Don, near the border with Ukraine.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. Oct. 3 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VASILIYEVKA, Russia _ The killer was a neighborly grandmother
driven to carnage to protect her precious and meager livelihood, a
small plot of potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   The victim, unemployed since the town's only factory shut its
doors seven years ago, had turned to plundering local vegetable
fields in the dark of night to survive and stoke his addiction to
vodka.
</P>
<P>
   On a cool summer evening 64-year-old Valentina Dolgopyatova
caught her neighbor, Nikolai Sidorenko, 47, digging up her crops.
They wrestled over the burlap sack of potatoes in his hands. The
big man swung a spade. She lunged with a five-inch boning knife.
</P>
<P>
   It took only minutes for him to die face down in a pool of his
own blood at the edge of the potato patch.
</P>
<P>
   But it took a difficult decade of Russia's economic collapse to
reach this desperate condition in a country that has failed to
complete its transition from Communist rule to free-market
democracy.
</P>
<P>
   This story of dust, sweat and bloodshed in the southern Russia
village of Vasiliyevka, three hours by car north of Rostov-on-Don,
is not exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of millions of Russians depend on their small garden plots
for survival. Across Russia, almost daily, police in cities and
hamlets receive reports of thefts and, in some cases, violence in
the struggle for food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is very difficult,'' explained Dolgopyatova, whose eyes
welled with tears as she recounted the story of killing Sidorenko.
The authorities recently announced they would not prosecute her for
the homicide in late June, ruling that she acted in self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we grow is all we have,'' she added, standing at the spot
where her victim collapsed and died from the knife wound to his
abdomen, still gripping the bag of freshly unearthed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Vast numbers of Russians have been left behind in Russia's
troubled transformation since the Soviet Union disintegrated in
1991. Wages have fallen, industries and jobs have disappeared and
corruption has soared.
</P>
<P>
   In Belaya Kalitva (pop. 42,000), the regional center and nearest
city to Vasiliyevka, the average monthly salary is about US$25;
Pensioners get even less, about US$16 each month, said Alexander
Krug, deputy editor of the local newspaper. ``People are at the end
of their rope to survive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a vicious cycle of poverty, alcohol abuse among
men and a corresponding leap in the crime rate. Russia's swelling
ranks of poor _ four of every 10 Russians live below the poverty
line _ has turned pensioners and the under-employed into
subsistence farmers, growing vegetables, raising chickens and goats
on small plots of land.
</P>
<P>
   In rural Vasiliyevka (pop. 700), the cycle became a lethal
formula, resulting in a killing that resembles a barbaric tale of
medieval survival, not life at the edge of a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmother, Dolgopyatova, plows and sows her small field by
hand with her 72-year-old husband Andrei. He spent a lifetime in
the coal mines. She also worked the mines, before being trained to
do piecework in the local fabric factory.
</P>
<P>
   Together, their pensions total about US$32 a month. They depend
on what they grow in a field next to their clapboard house to get
them through the bitter winter. Still, she is filled with remorse
about the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would I do differently? I would run home right away. I'd
say to hell with it. If he wants to take them, let him take them.
I'll be able to plant again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Soviet times, while the economy was austere, people were fed
and cases of common theft was rare.
</P>
<P>
   But today police cannot keep up with similar food feuds across
the country. Police in the Volga River city of Ulyanovsk said that
at least eight potato thieves were killed there over the summer,
including two men savagely beaten to death by watchmen hired to
patrol the plots.
</P>
<P>
   In July in the Siberian city if Tomsk, a 75-year-old grandfather
shot to death his beloved 21-year-old grandson late one night after
he mistook the young man for a thief out to steal from his onion
patch.
</P>
<P>
   Near Ivanovo, a city northwest of Moscow, a 42-year-old woman
was spared her life, but endured a Scarlet Letter style punishment.
Several plot-owners caught her digging in their fields. They took
her to a nearby bus stop where they tied her to a post, stripped
her to her underwear and hung a sign around her neck reading: ``She
was stealing potatoes.'' Police discovered her the following
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Such pilfering of crops took place in Soviet times, too. But
then it was sporadic, not widespread and violent as today, said
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Rostov region is abundant with fertile farmland
that is laced with veins of coal deposits.
</P>
<P>
   But in Belaya Kalitva, eight of 10 coal mines have closed, as
have two out of three of the city's major factories. A
once-productive collective farm in Vasiliyevka is now overgrown
with weeds and the rusting hulks of machine equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely everything is dying here. There is no work to be
had anywhere,'' said Alexander Yemelin, the chief investigator who
worked the potato-killer case. Driving through the outskirts of
Belaya Kalitva and surveying the depressed landscape, Yemelin
added: ``NATO hasn't bombed us, even though it looks like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old investigator is overworked and underpaid. There
have been a record 20 murders in Belaya Kalitva so far this year.
Unless the economy improves and authorities can get crime under
control, there will be more, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The no-nonsense investigator has two pictures on his office wall
_ former Soviet leader and hard-line KGB chief Yuri Andropov and
actor Arnold Shwarzeneggar, wielding a high-caliber weapon in a
scene from the film ``The Predator.''
</P>
<P>
   But the system he works for cannot protect the people, he
conceded. After a two-month investigation, the grandmother known as
``Babushka Valya'' was not prosecuted because ``we decided she
needed to protect herself,'' said Yemelin.
</P>
<P>
   The gray-haired lady, her face bronzed and deeply lined, had
been sitting at the edge of her small field watching on the lookout
for thieves after a next-door neighbor's patch had been pilfered
the night before. The knife she carried was to slice small bits of
lard and bread, which she chewed on while on guard at 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   That's when she spotted in the distance a white figure bent down
in her field. She yelled to Sidorenko, but he kept on digging. As
she approached the man, she recognized him. They had both worked in
the nearby fabric factory and only recently she had given him some
food when he came by begging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kolya, how can you do this?'' she asked, now standing
face-to-face with him in the small field of potatoes, corn and
pumpkin vines. ``I help you, and now you have come to steal my
potatoes?''
</P>
<P>
   He told her to get lost and when she didn't, he reached for the
spade. She brought the knife up to her chest. He raised the spade
to swing. She lunged towards him, piercing his side and severing an
artery.
</P>
<P>
   It was over before she knew it, and he staggered away,
disappearing into the darkness. She wasn't even certain if she had
stabbed him. Most importantly, she thought, he was gone, though he
had taken the sack of potatoes with him.
</P>
<P>
   When morning broke, Dolgopyatova went to the police with the
neighborhood friend who also had been robbed of her crops. The
authorities went to Sidorenko's house, but he wasn't home.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, they found him face down, about 40 yards from where
he and Dolgopyatova had struggled, hidden from view from the potato
plot by a rocky knoll.
</P>
<P>
   The grandmother stares at the spot where his body was discovered
and shakes her head, her eyes once again going wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to give him bread and food and helped him. I don't know
what would make a man do something like that,'' she said. ``A man
loses his work, maybe that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
