<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-IOC-1001-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC BOARD TO MEET, QUESTIONS LOOM OVER BIDDING FOR 1996 ATLANTA
GAMES
 &HT;    725&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (s) Sports categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ At least one of Atlanta's competitors for the
1996 Games is expressing surprise and disappointment at the extent
to which Atlanta bidders flaunted International Olympic Committee
gift giving rules.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Bob Scott, the former head of the Manchester 1996 bidding
team, also rejected the assertion that Atlanta lobbyists were only
responding to the culture of the Olympic bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule was that you didn't go out and buy a gift worth more
than $200, and that was the rule we adhered to,'' said Scott in an
interview from his home in Greenwich, England. ``To say that it was
a rule that was generally disregarded by everyone is simply
untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who befriended many members of the Atlanta bidding team,
was disheartened to learn that his old rivals apparently played by
a different set of rules. ``We - the guys from Atlanta, Manchester,
Toronto and Melbourne - used to get together and complain bitterly
about the excesses of the group from Athens,'' Scott said. ``If it
now turns out that Atlanta was playing the same game, then I'm
rather sad.''
</P>
<P>
   A new report on Atlanta's bid details lavish gifts, personal
favors and travel offered to IOC members in the two years leading
up to Atlanta's surprise selection in 1990. The report, prepared by
former U.S. Attorney General Griffin Bell, also includes accounts
of Atlanta bidders' offering college scholarships, job assistance
and other perks to IOC members and their families. The report,
which was prepared as testimony for Congress, is being reviewed by
the IOC's new ethics commission. The report could also be discussed
by the IOC executive board, which begins meetings Friday here, the
site of the 2004 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch gave the ethics commission
a copy of the report on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   IOC Vice President Keba Mbaye is making a preliminary reviewing
of the report and will pass it on to the full ethics commission if
he finds substantial matters for the panel to pursue. ``If the
review of the report is completed, then that will be communicated
to the executive board, which will decide what to do next,'' said
Theo Chapman, an IOC spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what the IOC would do if it finds evidence of
wrongdoing in the Atlanta bid. However, many of the members
implicated in the Bell report have been ejected by the IOC
following an investigation of the Salt Lake City bid for the 2002
Winter Olympics. Six IOC members were expelled and four resigned in
the Salt Lake City vote buying scandal. IOC members and their
relatives were paid $1.2 million in cash, college scholarships and
other inducements.
</P>
<P>
   While Scott expressed disappointment with the Atlanta
revelations, another competitor said he was not bothered by the
report. ``Look, there was one city in North America that got
through the really terrible economic times of the early 1990s _ and
that was Atlanta,'' said Paul Henderson, the former head of the
Toronto 1996 bid. ``Why was that? Because Atlanta had the Olympic
Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, often a harsh critic of the 1996 Games and their
chief organizer, Billy Payne, said he was amazed at the complaints
over what Atlanta did to win the Olympics. ``It's kind of like
getting a tape of a hockey game and seeing a penalty and then
demanding to change the outcome of the game and investigate the
officials.''
</P>
<P>
   He compared the wining and dining to what civic leaders do
routinely to lure business to their cities. ``This is a $6 billion
prize, and you wanted to win it. When people came to Atlanta, Billy
took them to play golf at Augusta,'' he said. ``When they came
here, I took them sailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put them in the best hotels and feed them at the best
restaurants. You don't take people like this to McDonald's,'' he
said. ``We flew Samaranch and his party on a private jet, too. So
what?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no fan of Billy Payne, everybody knows that,'' Henderson
said. ``But he ought to be considered Atlanta's greatest hero
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson also said that Atlanta's win had little to do with the
special treatment afforded IOC members. The competition for the
1996 Games was held in uncertain political and economic times of
the late 1980s as the Soviet Union was breaking up and the world
was undergoing a dramatic transformation. ``At the time, the IOC
saw the USA as the only safe haven,'' Henderson said. ``That's why
Atlanta won.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed Congress's interest in Atlanta's bid as being
politically motivated to grab attention during an election year.
``And it's a very cynical kind of politics,'' said Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said he has been approached by representatives of the
U.S. House Commerce Committee's subcommittee on oversight and
investigations but he has not been asked to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm defending Atlanta, then everyone oughtta know that they
didn't do anything wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Athens was among the five cities Atlanta defeated for the 1996
Games. During the campaign, bidders from the other cities
frequently accused Athens of excessive gift giving, entertaining
and violating IOC policies meant to keep the campaign above board.
Athens bidders denied they did anything wrong at the time, but
abuses in the campaign for the 1996 Games prompted the IOC in 1991
to review the bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   No allegations have been made to the IOC about the conduct of
Athens during its campaign for the 2004 Games, which were awarded
in 1997. This is the IOC's first visit to Athens since the Games
were awarded. Organizers are eager to dispel reports of delays and
disorganization.
</P>
