<HEADER>
A1894 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-FREE-SPEECH-PRECIOUS-     09-30 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREE-SPEECH-PRECIOUS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 DATELINE: U.N. -- Can `Big Brother' Be Far Away?  
 &HT;     (This column by Linda Fasulo, a correspondent for NBC, NPR and
MSNBC.com, is the first one to be released by The New York Times
Syndicate. After this, her ``DATELINE: U.N.'' column will move over
the wire on alternate Thursday afternoons, slugged
BC-FASULO-(keyword)-NYTSF. For a photo, complete bio and rates _ on
individual columns or a contract _ contact:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By LINDA FASULO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    UNITED NATIONS _ Blue helmets decorated with U.N. flags, the
gleaming horizontal General Assembly building, feverish midnight
debates in the Security Council: These are well-known public images
of the United Nations at work. Behind the scenes, however, is an
equally far-reaching site of intense activity: the press room,
known as Room 226.
 &HT;    At the moment, Room 226 is under threat by a move that could
muzzle reporters.
 &HT;    In December, the General Assembly adopted a resolution, ``United
Nations Public Information Policies and Activities,'' which
contains a paragraph _ specifically, number 12 _ allowing diplomats
into the news briefings. A new resolution is calling on
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to enforce the December vote.
 &HT;    ``It's absolutely ridiculous,'' one Western diplomat said about
the measure, which was initiated by Algeria, and strongly supported
by Syria and Cuba.
 &HT;    I'm told that so far, no diplomats have tried to enter Room 226,
and that if they do, they'll be turned away.
 &HT;    To be perfectly clear, the press room is the site of conferences
on any number of hot issues of the day: Iraq, Kosovo, East Timor,
the World Bank, global crime, humanitarian relief, the threat of
landmines, famines and epidemics. The noon briefings are given by
Fred Eckhard, the chief U.N. spokesman, or a deputy. Other
sessions, which must be cleared through his office, are often
conducted by presidents and prime ministers, other top government
officials or U.N. experts on subjects ranging from nuclear weapons
to global infant mortality.
 &HT;    Within the U.N. press corps _ about 150 resident correspondents
and thousands of others accredited from international media
organizations _ there's the free press (major U.S. networks, the
BBC, The Times of India, etc.) as well as official government news
agencies (from China, Indonesia, Iraq, Yugoslavia, etc.).
 &HT;    I spoke to one Third World journalist who said she believes the
diplomats want to be in Room 226 to spy. She feels it would be like
Big Brother taking notes. She says that some reporters already feel
they're at personal risk for not always portraying their political
leaders in a glowing light.
 &HT;    Other colleagues, particularly from authoritarian regimes, fear
being isolated or tagged as traitors or troublemakers. They don't
want to be seen asking ``hostile'' questions whose answers might
put their states in a bad light. They say they fear that such
behavior might prompt a call to return home for reprisal or
dismissal.
 &HT;    In any country, government officials make their displeasure
known. For example, I got a call from a Western European diplomat
complaining about my characterizing his country as an ``ally'' of
Iraq. Instead, he said, it was merely a ``supporter.'' Other
correspondents have more frightening stories of harassment to tell.
 &HT;    The new measure is all the more ironic because the U.N.
briefings are not secret proceedings. A camera is posted in back of
the rows of chairs to broadcast events live over the U.N.-TV
system, on the Internet and on local cable television. Monitors are
scattered around the headquarters _ at the delegates' entrance, in
the main lobby near the newsstand. A live audio feed runs to the
diplomatic missions. Transcripts are on the Net at www.un.org.
Every afternoon Eckhard, or his deputy, repeats the sessions for
diplomats, including the questions asked by reporters and the
responses.
 &HT;    True, the live broadcasts do not show the journalists' faces as
they ask questions. Only their voices are heard. But isn't that
enough?
 &HT;    Even now, without a camera in their faces, the more vulnerable
reporters will pass a tough question to a Western colleague to ask.
They fear voice recognition or the chance that a diplomat will
check around later to find out who asked what.
 &HT;    If the doors to Room 226 were open to all, the news briefings
might well turn into battles between advocates of clashing points
of view on the most politically sensitive, life-and-death issues
facing the world's people, rather than a forum in which you can
gather facts, figure out what's news and try to find the truth.
 &HT;    At times, bureaucrats or lobbyists or people from
non-governmental organizations (NGOs) try to slip into the room,
but a U.N. staffer at the door rejects anyone without proper press
credentials. For security problems, a uniformed officer is shouting
distance away in the nearby diplomatic corridor.
 &HT;    The week of Sept. 20, when the General Assembly opened, there
were sessions on such issues as the death of a Western journalist
in East Timor, the rescue of Taipei earthquake victims, combatting
drug trafficking in Colombia, and Pakistan's case against India in
the International Court of Justice over the shoot-down of an
unarmed Pakistani aircraft. In a Sept. 22 meeting, journalists
questioned President Miguel Angel Rodriguez Echeverria about Costa
Rica's stance against the Cuban embargo.
 &HT;    Clearly these aren't lunch-time chats.
 &HT;    Should diplomats from Indonesia be at a news briefing on East
Timor, ready to challenge whatever the press spokesman is saying?
Should those from Pakistan be able to try to advance their own
national agenda at a briefing about India?
 &HT;    I asked one member of the Information Committee, the key U.N.
group that introduced the resolution, why his colleagues who
support a free press didn't refuse to go along with paragraph 12 or
try to negotiate it out of the whole package.
 &HT;    At the time, he told me, there was concern, but there were
``bigger fish to fry'' _ by which he meant, at least in part, that
it was more important to avoid a power struggle and keep the
committee on track and running smoothly by consensus than to stand
up and fight for press rights.
 &HT;    Historically, this committee has been a site of contentious
debate. The members from East and West, and First and Third Worlds,
who have been reared in traditions that range from censorship to
freedom of speech, hold widely divergent views on what sort of
information should be made public _ all of it, part of it, none of
it or an official version of it.
 &HT;    A few members of the U.N. Correspondents Association are trying
to raise a red flag because buried as paragraph 12 is in the
original resolution, the demand to open the press-room doors hasn't
even been read yet by the majority of people it would most directly
affect.
 &HT;    If the new resolution passes _ it's on track for adoption by
November or December _ it could well provoke a major confrontation.
High-level U.N. officials say that Annan _ who dearly respects
freedom of speech and has called press freedom ``a cornerstone of
human rights'' _ will never allow diplomats the press-room access
they seek.
 &HT;    If the secretary-general rides in on a white horse to save the
day, he should do it. The problem is, nobody knows what the next
secretary-general will be inclined to do.
 &HT;     c.1999 MSNBC.com  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Linda Fasulo is a journalist, an author and a speaker who
specializes in the United Nations and foreign affairs. She is U.N.
correspondent for NBC News, a columnist for MSNBC.com and a special
correspondent-U.N. for U.S. News &AMP; World Report magazine. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Her internationally syndicated news broadcasts can be heard
several times a week on National Public Radio (NPR). She is also
the author of ``Representing America: Experiences of U.S. Diplomats
at the U.N.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A frequent speaker and moderator on international issues,
Fasulo has recently addressed audiences at universities including
