<HEADLINE>
THOMAS AWAITS HIS TURN AT UNLV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jason Thomas clicked on the television set to see how some old
friends were doing when he got home to his Las Vegas apartment on
Saturday night. It didn't take long for him to realize that one of
his old buddies, namely USC quarterback Carson Palmer, wasn't doing
very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Mike (Van Raaphorst) in there,'' said Thomas, who
is sitting out a year after transferring to UNLV from USC, ``I knew
there was something wrong. And I knew it must be bad.''
</P>
<P>
   It was. Palmer is out for at least six weeks and possibly the
entire season after suffering a broken right collarbone while being
tackled by Oregon safety Michael Fletcher two plays before halftime
of USC's overtime loss to the Ducks. So, into the starting lineup
steps former starter Van Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas knows very well that it could have been him stepping in
for Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's human nature to think about coulda or woulda,'' Thomas
said shortly after the Rebels finished a Tuesday night practice.
``Sure I thought about it for a minute. But you can't live your
life like that. I made a decision and I've moved on. I was worried
more about Carson being OK than what it meant to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and Palmer were each recruited to USC by current UNLV
coach John Robinson. However by the February signing date, Paul
Hackett was the Trojans head coach. Although Thomas and Palmer were
the cornerstones of the recruiting class, they had distinctly
differ.niS3
</P>
</TEXT>
