<HEADER>
A1910 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-PLUNKETT-MACLEANE-REV     09-30 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLUNKETT-MACLEANE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Willfully anachronistic and geared toward an audience whose
knowledge of highwaymen extends all the way back to ``The Road
Warrior,'' the swashbuckler ``Plunkett &AMP; Macleane'' has visual
flair to spare. Unfortunately, that's about all it has. The movie
makes for pleasing enough eye candy, but it needed a little more
imagination and substance to avoid receding _ like its historical
subjects _ into the mists of memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plunkett'' marks the directorial debut of Jake Scott, son of
famed helmer Ridley Scott, and it's proof positive that the apple
doesn't fall far from the tree. The senior Scott certainly has made
his mark on modern moviemaking (``Blade Runner,'' ``Alien,''
``Thelma &AMP; Louise''), but, for the most part, his career has been
characterized by films that look great but play stupid (``G.I.
Jane,'' ``Black Rain,'' among many others).
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely the problem with ``Plunkett,'' a period
buddy movie about an odd couple of thieves whose ambitions are as
different as their personalities. Will Plunkett (Robert Carlyle)
comes from the lower classes of 18th-century London and simply
wants to steal enough money to fund a boat ticket to America. His
unlikely partner, James Macleane (Jonny Lee Miller), is a society
aspirant looking to finance his taste for the good life.
</P>
<P>
   Their method of operation is simple: Macleane, using his good
manners, infiltrates society events to find promising holdup
targets. After the gatherings, the two bandits make good on the
information, with Plunkett doing most of the dirty work.
</P>
<P>
   Director Scott, working from a slapdash screenplay credited to
four different writers (and it shows), stages much of the action in
the dark, which is just as well, given the number of unlikely
escapes the film's highwaymen make. Some of the robbery sequences
do have an undeniable visceral excitement, sustained by the
combative antagonism established between the two leads.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's key distinction is its blending of 18th-century
costumes and settings with modern-day attitudes. Examples: The
characters swear like Tarantino lowlifes. Revelers at a costume
ball dance to the strains of techno music. Video poster child Liv
Tyler attempts an English accent.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it works, some of it doesn't. The meshing of periods
isn't a bad idea, but the filmmakers shouldn't have confined their
ambitions merely to such optical flourishes. The story simply
doesn't go to many interesting places, and the mind begins to pay
more attention to Alan Cumming's purple suit than to superficial
events unfolding on the screen. (Cumming, playing a foppish lord,
is one of the best things about the movie.)
</P>
<P>
   So while it doesn't feel like highway robbery, ``Plunkett &AMP;
Macleane'' nevertheless comes off as a bit of a cheat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Plunkett &AMP; Macleane'' (R; strong violence, sexuality
and language). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Robert Carlyle, Jonny Lee Miller and Liv Tyler. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Jake Scott. Screenplay by Robert
Wade, Neal Purvis, Charles McKeown (based on an original screenplay
by Selwyn Roberts). Released by Gramercy Pictures. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 45 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
