<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1915 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HAPPY-TEXAS-REVIEW-LA     09-30 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAPPY-TEXAS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ That ``Happy, Texas'' was a sensation at this year's
Sundance Film Festival says more about the dearth of quality at
that independent showcase than it does regarding the small
pleasures of this uneven little movie.
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the screwball ``Happy'' certainly has an appealing
innocence and a fair share of laughs, it is handicapped by a
one-note premise and tedious last act that strains for madcap
zaniness. Lone Star state residents won't be bragging about this
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it could have been worse. Take the setup: Two
convicts escape from prison, steal a beat-up Winnebago and wind up
forced to assume the identities of the vehicle's owners _ two gay
beauty pageant producers. But what could have been precious instead
becomes fairly inventive in the hands of first-time director Mark
Illsley, who also wrote ``Happy'' with Ed Stone and Phil Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the movie works pretty well for its first hour, serving
up some solid homespun hilarity that showcases the comic abilities
of its cast. Brit Jeremy Northam (seen this year in ``The Winslow
Boy'' and ``An Ideal Husband'') plays Harry Sawyer, a charming con
man who sets his sights on Happy's vulnerable bank and its lovely
manager, Josephine (Ally Walker).
</P>
<P>
   This leaves Harry's greasy-haired partner Wayne Wayne Wayne Jr.
(Steve Zahn) in charge of turning the town's little girls into
finalists for the Little Miss Squeezed Pageant, something that
hasn't been done for more than 25 years. Wayne isn't exactly suited
for the job _ he offers one little girl a cigarette as a reward _
but he soon warms to the challenge of doing something nice for once
in his life. A sweet schoolteacher (Illeana Douglas) lends her help
to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   The film has its fun with small-town mores, but never in a
mean-spirited way. Northam displays a nice comic touch, and the
always amusing Zahn expands on the dim-bulb mannerisms he showed
off so well last year in ``Out of Sight.'' (His bushy moustache
alone is worth a few chuckles.)
</P>
<P>
   But it's William H. Macy who steals the movie, playing the town
sheriff who is determined to uncover various hidden identities,
including his own. Macy invests the character with the same winning
combination of humor and pathos that he used so memorably in
``Fargo'' and ``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   It's disappointing that the film itself can't maintain that same
satisfying balance. By its last half-hour, ``Happy, Texas'' has
overstayed its welcome, dissolving into dippy chase theatrics
wholly lacking in originality and, more crucially, fun. What it
feels like is somebody telling a bad joke _ repeatedly _ and then
nudging you in the ribs, making sure you know how funny it is.
</P>
<P>
   And that's too bad, because director Illsley shows some promise
here. A graduate of USC's film school, Illsley worked with Kevin
Reynolds as second-unit director three times before getting his
chance with ``Happy.'' On the strength of the movie's freshness and
sometimes silly fun, he deserves a second try. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film: ``Happy, Texas'' (R; language, sexual content and some
violence). &QL; 
The stars: Jeremy Northam, Steve Zahn, Ally Walker, Illeana Douglas
and William H. Macy. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Mark Illsley. Screenplay by Illsley,
Ed Stone and Phil Reeves. Released by Miramax. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 39 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
