<HEADER>
A1918 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TAXMAN-REVIEW-LADN     09-30 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXMAN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Our rating: 3 stars 
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _The world is full of Everymen who have a script in
their back pocket. Nearly all are destined never to see their dream
become a reality ... in most cases, for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   So it's remarkable that ``The Taxman,'' co-written by an actual
New York State tax investigator, got made in the first place. Even
more surprisingly, it's a very good mystery yarn: fast-paced,
exciting and fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work for the New York State Tax Department. Which is the
single worst job you could possibly have,'' says Al Benjamin (Joe
Pantaliano) in a gravelly, New York-accented voice at the opening
of ``The Taxman.'' He adds, ``I mean, let's face it: Everybody
hates the taxman. It's biblical.''
</P>
<P>
   The script moves deftly between irreverence and gripping drama,
never falling back on glib comments or stereotypes. Benjamin is a
burned-out tax investigator looking for a ``big break'' to give him
something to make him ``get out of bed every morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The character surely speaks for Roger Berger, the
taxman-turned-screenwriter behind the film (he was actually a
struggling actor before becoming a civil servant in the 1970s). The
script is apparently based partly on an investigation of Berger's,
which, according to his biographical information, ``exposed a
conspiracy between Getty Oil and members of the Russian Mafia in
Brighton Beach (a heavily Russian enclave of Brooklyn).''
</P>
<P>
   No one encourages Benjamin in his quixotic quest to take on
organized crime and a Fortune 500 company at the same time. His
supervisors reprimand him. The police tell him to get lost: When
the high-strung investigator shows up at the scene of a murder he
thinks may be linked to the conspiracy, he's unceremoniously shown
the door by NYPD officers who scoff at his credentials as an
investigator.
</P>
<P>
   But out of that encounter comes Benjamin's unlikely sidekick, a
stuttering Puerto Rican officer named Joseph Romero (Wade
Dominguez). Romero, like Benjamin, feels he has little to lose by
pursuing this case: Since he's bad at shooting a gun and driving a
car, he's not exactly tagged for glory with the NYPD.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a typical ``buddy movie,'' but these two misfits do
learn some important lessons together while working on the case. A
Russian named Andre Rubakov (Michael Chiklis, who played the title
role in ABC's ``The Commish'') becomes their key contact. Rubakov,
a hard-partying family man with a heart of gold, invites the pair
into his inner sanctum. Benjamin develops a crush on Rubakov's
daughter, played by ``Showgirl's'' Elizabeth Berkley.
</P>
<P>
   The strong ensemble cast is completed by Robert Townsend as
Peyton Cody, the crack prosecutor who is finally persuaded to take
the case to trial. The ending isn't typical Hollywood: Not all the
bad guys get jail time, and Benjamin doesn't get the girl. But
Benjamin, Romero and Cody all have a little bit more to live for
and celebrate in life, and the viewer is happy for that. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
The film: ``The Taxman'' (R; graphic violence and strong
language). &QL; 
The stars: Joe Pantoliano, Wade Dominguez, Michael Chiklis, Robert
Townsend, Elizabeth Berkley. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Avi Nesher. Written by Nesher and
Roger Berger. Produced by Nesher and Kathy Jordan. Released by
Phaedra Cinema. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 44 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
