A1919 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-STADIUM-TOUR-HNS &LR;      09-30 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-TOUR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS STADIUM OFFERS FANS AN INSIDE GLIMPSE OF THE COWBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Are you ready for some football? Nope, but it
happens every year without my participation. It invades my house
where a hardcore, Dallas Cowboy Football fan lives and breathes
football from September through January.
</P>
<P>
   I've lived in Texas for 20 years and have learned a little about
them Pokes, even if I can't quote statistics. Texas Stadium gleams
white and blue between state routes 183 and 114. On a recent
Saturday the parking lot wasn't overflowing, just a few cars were
parked near the Pro Shop. That's where shoppers check out the
latest in Cowboy goods and where the tours start.
</P>
<P>
   Every day but game day, from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., tours leave from
the Pro Shop and troop through the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Shirlee Waller is a rookie this year and one of six Texas
Stadium tour guides. She led our group of about a dozen through the
stadium as workers were scurrying to prepare it for the first
pre-season home game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been working for months to get ready for it,'' Waller
said. Earlier this year an Oliver Stone movie was filmed here.
Filmgoers may not recognize Texas Stadium in ``On Any Sunday,'' the
working title of a film about the fictional red-and-white Knights
coached by Al Pacino. Waller pointed to the field, with it's new
covering of Cowboy turf, the stands, the names of famous Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Want a piece of the old turf? It is $24.95 on a plaque in
Plexiglas at the store. This is the third covering of turf since
the stadium opened in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   There is a 2 1/4-acre hole in the dome ``so the players can play
in natural elements,'' Waller explained, ``and the fans are
protected.''
</P>
<P>
   But the myths are better than the official explanation. There's
a hole in the top so coach Tom Landry could wear his hat, or (every
fan's favorite) ``so God can watch his favorite team.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Stadium opened in 1971 at a cost of $35 million, the same
cost as defensive back Dion Sanders' contract.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium is immense. Waller pointed out the Diamond Vision
Screens high above and explained that they are three stories high
and weigh 20 tons each.
</P>
<P>
   Amy McGargill and her mother, Anne Benedict, two Troy Aikman
fans from Iowa, joined the tour. Both nurses, they joked about
getting jobs with the team. On the field, Benedict pointed to the
section where the two would watch the game the next afternoon. They
kidded around about holding signs saying ``Don't Do It Troy'' _
referring to his upcoming nuptials.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, the tour took in a suite, this one belonging to the
City of Irving and comfortable for about 16 people. Waller
explained that suites go for between $250,000 to a $2 million and
owners pay property taxes and decorate them to suit their own
tastes. That cost does not include catering or game tickets. A
suite package for a game runs about $3,500.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't afford that there is always a tailgate party, back
in the stadium parking lot after an absence of about 20 years. You
can buy the official Dallas Cowboys tailgate grill ($149) in the
Pro Shop and set the table with official Cowboy plastic cutlery
($4.99).
</P>
<P>
   The most expensive item in the Cowboys Pro Shop is a $3,700
bronze statue and the least expensive is a 75-cent helmet eraser.
Renate Kaa, the store manager, expects this year's big seller to be
the Troy Aikman cap, which at $19.99 is exclusive to the store.
</P>
<P>
   I'm partial to the Cowboy Cheerleader Dolls, a deal at $79.95,
because they stand out so smiling and girlie among the hats,
helmets, T-shirts and imitation Beanies with the names of Aikman
and Sanders emblazoned on them.
</P>
<P>
   The practice uniforms, at $99, are heaped in a bin with names
and numbers. ``Nope,'' Kaa said, ``you won't find anything with
Aikman's name on it in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get the fanatics in _ they go for a pair,'' Kaa said.
</P>
<P>
   The uniforms of the players and cheerleaders are very popular at
Halloween. What you won't find hanging about the Pro Shop are the
players, but you might encounter one along ``autograph alley,''
along the side entrances of the Dallas/Fort Worth Airport Marriott.
For about 10 years it has been the home game hotel for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Fran Fairchild, the hotel's director of marketing, sounds like a
big team booster. Three days before game day, autograph alley is
cordoned off with a fence along Royal Lane. Parking is plentiful
and fans stand outside the fence along a shady tree line.
</P>
<P>
   Most team members ``will make an effort for kids,'' Fairchild
said. Breakfast for the players is in a private dining room, not
where guests eat. But you might hear the sound of blenders as a
number of players mix up their own energy drinks. While you won't
find Michael Irvin or Richie Cunningham lounging by the pool on
Sunday morning, you might spot Emmitt Smith heading through the
lobby bound for church with his family.
</P>
<P>
   The 490-room hotel sets aside one floor, about 30 rooms, for the
Cowboys. Hotel security is stationed on the stairwells. Some fans
have made some odd requests. Fairchild laughed a little and
admitted that someone offered to buy Aikman's used sheets, and
occasionally a guest wants to move into a player's room before
housekeeping has cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Do the Cowboys have special requests for the hotel? Nothing
stranger than fried turkey legs or a midnight sweet snack and that
player will ``talk room service into bringing him stuff,''
Fairchild said. Then there is the player who has to have flip
charts in his room so he can do plays ``over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information about Irving, contact the Irving Convention and
Visitors Bureau, 3333 N. MacArthur Blvd., Suite 200, Irving, Texas
75062; telephone 800-2-IRVING or 972-252-7476. On the Web at
www.irvingtexas.com
</P>
<P>
   A number of hotels offer Dallas Cowboys weekend ticket packages.
See your travel agent or contact the Irving Convention and Visitors
Bureau for information.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Cowboys Pro Shop is located at Texas Stadium, 2401 E.
Airport Freeway, Irving, Texas 75062; telephone 972-785-4780.
Stadium tours are from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. Monday through Saturday
and 11 a.m. to 3 p.m. Sunday on non game days.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to tour the stadium are $5 for adults, $3 for senior
citizens and children 5 to 12. Tours are half price the Saturday
before home game day because they don't include tours of the locker
rooms and time on field.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas/Fort Worth Airport Marriott, 8440 Freeport Parkway,
Irving, Texas 75063; telephone 927-929-8800.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
