<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKING DOCUMENTARY GIVES FOES ANOTHER REASON TO FUME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
Our rating: 2 stars 
By MARLA MATZER 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; If it's true that, as Joseph de Maistre said,
every country has the government it deserves, we're one sorry lot.
That is the overwhelming impression ones gets from the documentary
``Smoke and Mirrors: A History of Denial.''
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette manufacturers as obfuscating corporations that are
interested mainly in profits? Old news. But the fact that Congress
apparently forestalled any action against the tobacco companies for
decades _ in the face of clear evidence that smoking caused cancer
_ is appalling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke'' was funded by the American Lung Association, a fact
which is rightfully made clear at the outset of the film. The
tobacco industry would otherwise no doubt accuse the film of having
a hidden agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, virtually everyone has an agenda of some sort. The
agenda of a good documentary film is generally to expose a truth.
By that measure, ``Smoke'' is a success. It makes a case that both
independent research and research funded by the tobacco companies
themselves has for decades linked smoking to cancer and premature
death: Documents kept secret by the cigarette firms for decades are
discussed, and we see footage of mice experiments done 40 years ago
that linked smoking with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The film's downfall, however, is its dry earnestness and its
curious lack of more material that is entertaining, dramatic or
fresh. Aside from some interesting historical discussion of how the
cigarette companies overcame the social stigma against smoking in
the teens (they wrapped themselves in the flag, by supplying smokes
to American soldiers fighting World War I) and the aforementioned
history of inaction on the part of our government, there's not much
here that catches the viewer by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few old TV ads for cigarettes, along with a few
anti-smoking spots _ though not even the most dramatic ones, such
as the haunting spot where a cancer victim with a tracheotomy still
puffs on a cigarette through the hole in her neck. The fact is,
this movie preaches to the converted: It will surely stir those who
are fervent anti-smokers already.
</P>
<P>
   But for jaded, rebellious young people, those who are now being
targeted by tobacco companies, this documentary probably won't cut
it. Yul Brynner talking about cancer means nothing to them, and
they've never known a time when anyone trusted the government. How
do we reach them? Maybe MTV is a better venue for that. For that
matter, maybe television would have been a better venue for this
respectably done but slight movie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Smoke and Mirrors: A History of Denial'' (not rated). &QL; 
bold! &UR; The stars: &LR;  Narrated by Sharon Gless. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Torrie Rosenzweig. Produced and
written by Rosenzweig and Elise Pearlstein for the American Lung
Association. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 15 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
