<HEADER>
A1950 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBN-CANDLESTICK-HNS &LR;      09-30 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CANDLESTICK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARM, FUZZY FEELINGS ABOUT CANDLESTICK PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The honored guest missed the start of its own
farewell party. For the last night of baseball at Candlestick, an
impostor stepped in to play the role of the old ballyard. Everyone
spotted the fake right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so disappointed that it's not windy and cold,'' said
Eileen Regan, who came down with a group from the Napa Valley. She
wore a spaghetti-strap sundress tucked into a pair of blue sweat
pants. A sweat shirt was tied around her waist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fashion statement,'' Regan said. At any moment, she was
expecting the real 'Stick to show up. It never did. Tank tops ruled
on Wednesday night. Parkas stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   The flags over the stadium remained perfectly still, as if
finally worn out by 37 years of dancing a wind-driven Funky
Chicken.
</P>
<P>
   There was no dust swirling in the outfield. There were no
plastic bags skipping along the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Near the left-field foul line, Tom Leathers of Lafayette sat
quite comfortably without his hollow binoculars, filled with
contraband brandy to ward off the chill. Instead, he ate a cup of
ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've ever done it,'' Leathers said,
glancing at the melting Ben and Jerry's. ``Oh wait, I take it back.
My son and I eat Drumsticks to start rallies.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, they think consuming pre-fabbed ice-cream cones
increases run production for their team. In other words, they are
the perfect Giants fans, well-suited to the goofiness that is, and
always has been, Candlestick baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the ornery pile of concrete had to turn up one more
quirk before its demise. On its way to baseball obsolescence, it
decided to act like a stranger. It decided to act like a baseball
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans weren't completely surprised. After all, the last
night game was bound to come in late September, when summer finally
blooms in San Francisco. But Wednesday's warmth couldn't be
explained as an ordinary change of seasons. The 'Stick was in rare
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this was the weather gods' way of saying, `Sorry for
punishing you all these years,''' Giants manager Dusty Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants handed out their final batch of Croix de Candlestick
pins to the crowd of 47,343 on Wednesday night. The pins, decorated
with the snow-capped letters SF, have traditionally saluted the
fans who stayed through extra-inning night games. On the final
night at the 'Stick, the Giants finished off the Dodgers in nine,
and J.T. Snow capped the evening with a brilliant point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If every night was like this,'' the first baseman said,
``there would have been no need to build a new stadium, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   He was smiling when he said it, but the last laugh belonged to
the 'Stick. It didn't give 100 percent. It didn't come to play.
</P>
<P>
   A night game at the 'Stick has always been the best antidote to
San Francisco's sublime beauty, its finesse football, cutting-edge
restaurants, darling coffee shops and general proximity to the
idyllic life. In a place smothering in its own charm, a night game
at the 'Stick breathed a different kind of life into San
Franciscans.
</P>
<P>
   OK, sometimes, it blew us over, too. But it was fresh,
different, a testament to grit. Naturally, the park had to pull off
some mischief at its going-away party.
</P>
<P>
   Leathers, eating his ice cream, brought a sweater with him in
case the Bay Area's warmth turned cold during the game. He knows
the 'Stick too well to count on anything. He remembered how proudly
he had detailed the rigors of Candlestick night games to a pair of
out-of-towners attending the 1989 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The father and son came from Milwaukee, and Leathers told them
they don't know what real cold was. ``I was explaining to them how
windy and miserable it can get,'' he said, ``and then the
earthquake hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
