<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1969 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      09-30 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE, PALMER IN RITE OF PASSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bill Parcells may have got into his head,
but Chris Palmer got into his socks.
</P>
<P>
   Back when the Cleveland Browns head coach was quarterbacks coach
on Parcells's Patriots staff, he once was the target of a practical
joke played by Drew Bledsoe and backup Scott Zolak in which the
quarterbacks poked fun at Palmer's height _ or lack thereof _ by
placing a milk cart near a men's room urinal with a sign that read,
``Reserved For Chris Palmer.''
</P>
<P>
   The assistant coach got back at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the FBI dye they use on ransom money that you can't see
until it gets wet, and he put it in our socks,'' recalled Bledsoe.
``So I ended up where my feet were blue for about a month. That was
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Joking aside, there was and continues to be a lot of respect
between Palmer and Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's having an MVP season,'' said Palmer. ``He's got the
highest QB rating in the AFC. I'm happy for him because he's
accomplished so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Their working relationship began following the 1995 season, a
tough one for Bledsoe, who suffered a separated shoulder and had
trouble with passing accuracy. After the season, Palmer was moved
from receivers coach to quarterbacks coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``My accuracy had fallen off to a certain degree, and he took me
back to basics,'' recalled Bledsoe, who enters Sunday's game
against Palmer's Browns with a 104.5 rating and a 66 percent
completion rate. ``He got my videotape from the scouting combines
and he looked at my fundamentals and compared them to my '95
season. It was obvious I let a lot of things slide. No matter how
long I play in this league, I always have to be mindful of my
mechanics if I want to be accurate and be consistent from year to
year.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the tutelage, Palmer took Bledsoe aside and
told him he needed to enjoy playing football more. It was a
significant moment. From that point, Bledsoe has never taken
anything for granted and has consistently commented on how much
football means to him.
</P>
<P>
   It was those little things that convinced Bledsoe that Palmer
was someday going to be a head coach. ``I had a good feeling he'd
be a head coach,'' said the quarterback. ``The biggest thing is he
had the trust of the players _ offensive and defensive players.
They knew they could come to Chris and get a very straightforward
answer about what their role was and what their performance had
been like. He wasn't going to sugarcoat anything, and he was smart.
If someone had a question about something, he wouldn't answer it if
he didn't know it, but he'd come back to you the next day with an
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe especially appreciated Palmer's sense of timing. ``He
knew what I needed to hear and when to leave me alone and when he
needed to get on me a little bit,'' he said. ``There weren't too
many times he wanted to get after me, but they were the right
things at the right time. I also benefited greatly from Ray Perkins
(one of Palmer's offensive assistants), who taught me the game of
football.''
</P>
<P>
   So if ever Bledsoe wanted to perform at the height of his game,
it would be Sunday, to show his old coaches what he's become.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of a high quarterback rating and completion percentage,
Bledsoe hasn't been completely pleased with his play so far. ``I
have to find a way to start more quickly,'' said Bledsoe. ``In the
Jets game I was sharp at the beginning, but in the last two I
haven't been as sharp. In both games, I could have made it easier
for our offense and our defense. On the second play of (last Sunday
night's) game, I took a three-step drop instead of a five-step drop
and I missed Terry (Glenn, running a post). If we can get on top
early, we could change the complexion of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Through three games, the Patriots have managed only 3
first-quarter points, while their opponents have scored 28.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll is well aware of this, and in meetings and practice
this week his focus has been start strong and end strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to come out better than we have,'' said the coach.
``(Opponents have) been able to make first downs, and we haven't
been able to stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Bledsoe, he said, ``He's playing at a high clip, but he
hasn't had his best game yet. There will be a game when he'll hit
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's game plans have been conducive to winning football.
Sure, Bledsoe likes throwing the ball, but history suggests that's
not the best way for the Patriots to go. In games in which Bledsoe
has thrown fewer than 30 times, the Patriots are 16-3 (.842); when
he's thrown more than 30 times, they are 40-40 (.500). Obviously, a
running game helps tremendously.
</P>
<P>
   Although the running game has struggled, averaging only 3 yards
per carry, the Patriots have run the ball 83 times in three games
and passed it only 103 times. That's not a bad ratio, and the
Patriots would like to even it out even more.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have a goal of gaining 4 yards or more on at least
50 percent of their running plays. So far, they're done it only
around 31 percent of the time (on 26 of their 83 running plays),
while 17 plays have gone for no gain or a loss.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Cleveland defense trying to rush Bledsoe to slow
the explosive Patriots passing game, New England would appear to
have a chance to spring some big runs.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, however, is not counting on that. ``They're
improving,'' he said of the Browns defense. ``They're not extremely
complicated, but they have experienced players over there. They're
making more and more plays. We look for a tough game from them.''
</P>
<P>
   The important thing for Bledsoe is to not beat himself with
turnovers. In his last 78 pass attempts, he's not thrown an
interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to be perfect in my decision making,'' he said. ``I
don't expect to be perfect on every throw, but when I watch the
film again, I'd like to be able to say I made the right decision
every time. And it's been close. There were a couple of times I
could have gone to a different place with the ball. In this last
game, the second and third throws they gave me a (defensive) look I
hadn't seen all week. I got into too much of a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case when he's prepared for the Colts and Peyton
Manning's name would come up, everyone now wants to know what
Bledsoe thinks of Cleveland rookie Tim Couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim is going through something all young quarterbacks have to
go through,'' he said. ``It's a very difficult thing. He has to
have patience and continue to learn and maintain his confidence as
they go through the struggles. He has a great advantage in that he
has Chris Palmer, who puts him into a position to succeed. (Palmer
will) do a very good job to solidify his pass protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Couch has heard Bledsoe's name mentioned ad nauseum
by Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `I've seen Drew go through these stages and this
is how Drew handled it,' '' said Couch. ``(Him) helping develop
Drew has helped me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   While Couch considers Palmer a calming influence, he hasn't
tried any practical jokes on his head coach and he probably won't.
He doesn't want to end up feeling blue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1971 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-SILVER-ART-BOS &LR;      09-30 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SILVER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER AND STEEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAUNTON, Mass. _ Reed &AMP; Barton Silversmiths is 175 years old.
Appropriate noises have been made by the Massachusetts Legislature.
Men have just repainted the big front door its customary silver.
Although it did not make the original tennis trophy, the firm
recently reconfigured the Davis Cup in time for the United States
to play Australia at Boston's Longwood Cricket Club in July. The
silver plaques that Reed &AMP; Barton added will record the winners for
45 more years. The company made the medals for the 1996 summer
Olympics and will bid for the 2002 winter games. Designers are
working on silver tree ornaments for Christmas 2000. A glitzy
Manhattan hotel phoned on a Tuesday, in need of 5,200 pieces of
plated silverware for Friday delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Table silver is what Reed &AMP; Barton is really all about. They've
always done it in sterling, and in silverplate, and increasingly
they're doing it in stainless steel. Most of the stainless is made
in Korea. ``We taught them how,'' says Anthony D. LaChapelle. As
the firm's senior vice president for marketing and business
development, he's one of the people seeing to it that Reed &AMP; Barton
keeps competitive with the likes of Oneida, Towle, Gorham, and
Wallace. Once upon a time, the august names of those companies
would alone close the sale, with many a bride doting on Reed &AMP;
Barton place settings to be stored in a Reed &AMP; Barton silver chest.
Other brand names, however, are muscling in, names from fashion and
home decor. Reed &AMP; Barton makes flatware for Waterford, and, as
you'd expect, the patterns are heavy on the Celtic. One design
developed for Ralph Lauren Home is based on the great man's braided
leather belt. Clark L. Lofgren, Reed &AMP; Barton's director of design,
quite likes the effect. The less said the better about Lauren's
personal favorite, tableware with handles of chain links. If you're
in a nautical mood, you'll think anchor chain; in a mean mood,
chain-gang manacles. This is heavy stuff, so heavy, in fact, each
handle must be hand-cast. A five-piece place setting is $2,000. No
pablum spoons.
</P>
<P>
   Reed &AMP; Barton continues to do its own designing. These days,
much drafting is computer-assisted, such as the Christmas ornament
that Mark Tung was contriving the other day from gothic elements.
David Felix was at the modeling stage, building his ornament in
clay. Mal Baker was taking an eye break: Detailing on the knife
handle he'd drafted wasn't springing to life in 3-D. Lofgren's own
favorite modeling tool is a lemonwood stick, smooth and cool to the
touch. After so many years, it ``has become a Zen extension of my
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   For a visitor, Lofgren had pulled out five old Reed &AMP; Barton
spoons to show how tastes had changed since ``Francis I.'' A
bestseller since 1900, its elaborate spill of fruits and vegetables
simply spells sterling silver. But there were also spare modern
designs in the late '50s by the Italian architect Gio Ponti that
were so difficult to hold as to seem anti-food. And then there was
``Love Disarmed.'' That's a cupid on her shoulder, and she looks in
danger of losing her nightie. Soon to be reissued as large serving
pieces, she should be the life of the party.
</P>
<P>
   Large, by the way, is what people want in tableware today.
``More like the European scale,'' says Lofgren. And, an observer
thinks, more like restaurant cutlery, big and bold.
</P>
<P>
   The display shelves attesting to gracious living aside, Reed &AMP;
Barton is mostly a giant machine shop housed in century-old brick
buildings along the Mill River. The address is 144 W. Britannia
St., for a good and historic reason. ``Britannia'' was a pewterlike
English metal with the sheen of silver; it was compounded mostly of
tin, with bits of antimony and copper. In 1824, Taunton gadgetmaker
Isaac Babbitt and his fellow artisan William Porter succeeded in
making American Britannia.
</P>
<P>
   In the decades after metalsmith Henry Gooding Reed (1810-1901)
and solderer Charles E. Barton (1812-1867) founded their company in
1840, America was prosperous enough to move on to silverplate and
sterling silver, and Renee Garrelick's company history, ``Sterling
Seasons: The Reed &AMP; Barton Story,'' is a lively chronicle of the
good times and bad.
</P>
<P>
   It helped business that a Taunton newsboy named Ben Swig had
sold papers outside Reed &AMP; Barton. He founded San Francisco's
Fairmount Hotel in 1907, and ever since, it has used Reed &AMP; Barton
silverplate. (Boston's Ritz-Carlton is another hotel customer.)
During World War II, Reed &AMP; Barton did its part, making flatware
for the Navy as well as surgical instruments. Company president
John Wingate Weeks was secretary of war for Presidents Harding and
Coolidge, and another company president, Sinclair Weeks, was
Eisenhower's secretary of commerce; the Weeks family still owns
Reed &AMP; Barton.
</P>
<P>
   For all the glamour of the finished product, sterling starts
life as a dull metal blank. As metals go, silver is not expensive,
between $5.20 and $5.50 an ounce these days. Sterling, the highest
grade, is an alloy, requiring a bit of copper for strength. To most
people, silversmithing must be delicate, finicky work, judging by
the end product. Certainly, what the moldmakers do qualifies as
artisanal. What with silversmithing at Taunton and costume
jewelry-making at Attleboro, the area provides prime employment,
and Reed &AMP; Barton's LaChapelle says moldmakers ``who can do one can
generally do the other.''
</P>
<P>
   What comes as a surprise is the punishment silver must take on
its way to glory. No pain, no gain, as the saying goes, and silver
actually strengthens when subjected to high-pressure machines. The
air may be soft with oil and metal motes, but it's a noisy place,
too, with the hiss and whine and whirr of machines for cutting and
stamping and molding and shaping and buffing (with pumice and
grease). No wonder the whole place shuts down for lunch and an
ear-break.
</P>
<P>
   It's apparently a good place to work, one factor that keeps
employees loyal. There are so many members in the Quarter Century
Club, ``it's no big deal,'' says Raymond A. Gwozdz, new product
coordinator and second-generation employee. The other day, Jackie
Robino, whose current job is inspecting the finished product for
flaws, was vetting a sterling weapon called an ice cream slice.
With a red pen she drew a circle where the silver edge seemed thin.
(But not to a visitor's eye.) While the defective blade can still
cut the Haagen-Dazs, it didn't cut the mustard, and instead of
wooing brides at a jewelry or specialty shop, it may end up as a
second at the Reed &AMP; Barton Company Store. How long had Robino
worked for the company? asked a visitor. She sighed. ``That long?''
teased Gwozdz, her much-junior colleague. ``Forty years,'' Robino
admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
