<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORRYING ABOUT WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What if somebody overheard something scary at school,'' your
eighth-grader begins. ``What if he overheard a kid say he hated the
math teacher so much, he wanted to kill him?''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, you could have dismissed the overheard
conversation as boys' bravado and your son's reporting of it as
preteen hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   Not today. Schools take statements like these seriously and so
should we. Even if there's nothing to the alleged conversation,
</P>
<P>
   there's still your child's anxiety to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   The sad truth is there were weapons in schools long before
Littleton. In a 1997 Centers for Disease Control national survey,
13 percent of boys age 13 to 18 said they carried a weapon to
school _ a gun, knife, or club. Since Littleton, schools around the
country, suburban as well as urban, have initiated a range of
precautions, from requiring transparent backpacks and locking
school doors to beefing up conflict-resolution policies.
</P>
<P>
   As necessary as these measures may be, their very existence
affects our children. They need our help to cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see a raging epidemic of anxiety, but kids are aware.
Safety is on their minds,'' says psychologist Leon Rosenberg,
director of the Child and Adolescent Mental Health Center at Johns
Hopkins University in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Just because your preteen or teen doesn't talk about it doesn't
mean she doesn't think about it. ``Most of the time,'' says
Rosenberg, ``they practice denial: `What happens bad in the world
won't affect me.' '' But every now and then, something overwhelms
the denial. It could be overhearing a comment like the one above,
but it could also be something far more benign:
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day she passes locked doors and doesn't think anything
of it, but today, she looks at one and thinks, `The people who run
my school must be really worried to lock all the doors,' and she
comes home anxious and full of questions about safety,'' says
Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Vacillating between feeling invincible and threatened is
developmentally what being 10 to 15 years old is all about, says
middle-school researcher Margaret Sagarese. ``I tell parents it's
as if these kids have split personalities,'' she says. Indeed, they
are such a wealth of contradictions that the child who is
frightened by an overheard remark about wanting to kill a teacher
could easily say such a thing himself sometime.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the power of peer influence. Even though they know
better, that's how vulnerable they are to wanting to impress each
other,'' says Sagarese. She is a coauthor of ``Parenting 911: How
to Safeguard and Rescue Your 10- to 15-Year-Old'' (Broadway Books).
</P>
<P>
   The very fact that your child mentions something to you about
someone who might be violent is a clue she's worried.
</P>
<P>
   Most typically, she'll talk about it in the third person or
pretend it happened to a friend. That's self-protective behavior, a
way to distance herself not only from your potential anger but also
from her own fear. That she makes it hypothetical _ ``What if?'' _
is another clue: She's waiting to gauge how you react in order to
determine how scared she should be.
</P>
<P>
   Pooh-poohing it _ ``Kids always say things like that'' _ or
pretending it doesn't bother us leaves her open to thinking the
problem is worse than she thought: ``Dad can't even talk about it,
it's so bad.'' If we respond with an ``Oh-my-God-we're-next''
hysteria, she'll panic: ```Even my parents think this is really
scary!''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist James Garbarino, an international authority on how
children respond to violence, suggests a response that soothes and
validates _ ``You're right to tell me'' _ but he wouldn't go so far
as to say, ``You're right, this is scary,'' until he knew more. Ask
some questions: What do you know about this kid? Has he ever said
things like this before? Does he have a reputation for angering
easily?
</P>
<P>
   A child with this information is also grappling with a swirl of
feelings other than fear, says Sagarese. Name them for him, she
suggests: ``Do you feel upset to know this, or guilty because you
do? Do you feel responsible for this person, for his anger?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect him to admit to anything, but don't let that stop
you from continuing. ``Be explicit,'' says Rosenberg: `` `I want
you to know this boy's anger is not your responsibility. It is your
responsibility to tell an adult. You did. That's good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This gets to the crux of the biggest issue facing us, says
Garbarino. ``We need to resocialize children with a new message:
`Good friends share information when good friends say troubling
things.' '' Garbarino is the author of ``Lost Boys: Why Our Sons
Turn Violent and How We Can Save Them'' (Free Press).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a code of silence,'' agrees school
psychologist Terry Davis of Natick (Mass.) High School. ``They
don't want to squeal on a classmate. They're afraid of
retaliation.'' She promises anonymity to any student who shares
information.
</P>
<P>
   That's important, but to really change the culture we need to
start with preschoolers, says child safety authority Jan Wagner.
She urges parents to teach the difference between a secret and a
surprise: ``A secret is something that when you know it, it makes
you feel unsafe or uncomfortable. A surprise is something that when
you know it, makes you feel good.'' Wagner is the author of
``Raising Safe Kids in an Unsafe World'' (Nest Entertainment).
</P>
<P>
   She also recommends initiating conversations even with
fifth-graders: ``Is there anyone in your class you are concerned
about? Anyone who gets picked on a whole lot? Anyone who brags
about knowing how to make a bomb or having a gun?''
</P>
<P>
   To parents who are uncomfortable with that, she points out that
the typical 16-year-old classroom avenger began as a fifth-grader
who was picked on and never got professional help. To parents who
worry that such a conversation would unduly frighten their child,
she argues that it is in fact comforting, as long as we accompany
it with honest reassurances. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   `` `Your mother and I are doing everything we can to make sure
you are safe, including making sure the school does everything
possible to identify and prevent problems. We wouldn't send you to
a school we didn't think was safe. If there's a child in your class
who needs help, it's a good thing to help him get it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This is a message worth repeating, especially in the
middle-school years when a child is most likely to overhear a
threat against a teacher, see a weapon in someone's locker, or
simply be anxious about security. Don't put it on him to be the one
to decide whether to tell, however; it's your job as a parent to
evaluate the information. If it involves weapons or the threat of
violence, Garbarino and others say you must report it. But
brainstorm together who to tell and how, so that your child's sense
of control remains intact.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've told authorities, children typically feel relieved
at first. But then anxiety can reappear or get worse. ``We often
see residual or secondary anxiety, either from the child who first
spotted the problem or from other children who hear about it via
the grapevine,'' says Davis. ``There's a period where kids may
temporarily feel less safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The more concrete you can be, the better: ``I talked to the
principal about security. Did you know there are hall monitors to
make sure there aren't any fights? And if there is a fight, did you
know there's peer mediation? That's when kids help each other work
out conflicts peaceably so they don't harbor resentments. Now
that's a good way to keep a school safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck McAfee, principal of Edwards Middle School in Charlestown,
Mass., says children are so anxious about safety in the
middle-school years partly because their own self-control is often
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fights erupt over a blemish, over the score of a game,'' he
says. He places a strong emphasis on conflict-mediation skills for
students and on faculty-student interaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``To let them know we care,'' says McAfee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ARM YOURSELF WITH KNOWLEDGE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Keep a frightened child home from school only if you have serious
reservations about safety; it reinforces fearfulness. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Make sure your child knows that statements about guns, bombs, and
killing people can get anyone in trouble, even him, even if it's
just a joke. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--If your child talks or writes about violence and/or has a problem
with anger, talk to the school psychologist. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Find out what security measures your school has in place so you
know what your child is exposed to every day. Learning there are
random searches for weapons might explain heightened anxiety you
couldn't account for in your ninth-grader. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--It's not unreasonable to ask the principal to talk privately with
your child to reassure her if she's worried about safety. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--There is not necessarily a gender difference when it comes to
being worried about violence and safety at school, but girls are
more likely to talk about it than boys. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--If your child divulges information at midnight, don't wait until
morning to reach the school. Call the police. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Research shows that minimizing a young child's exposure to media
violence can reduce violent behavior later on. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Afterthought: Recommended reading for parents: ``Secrets of Feeding
a Healthy Family'' by Ellyn Satter (Kelcy Press, Madison, Wis.). &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz is author of ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell). She
welcomes letters and comments and can be reached via e-mail at
meltz(at)globe.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
