<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      09-30 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PICKER-UPPERS HELP IN THE WAR AGAINST DIRT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember those days in early spring, many years ago, when
everyone rolled up their sleeves and cleaned everything in sight in
their annual cleaning orgy?
</P>
<P>
   It was called spring cleaning. Pop washed the walls and
ceilings; they really needed it, they were a sight from a winter's
accumulation of coal dust.
</P>
<P>
   Mom did the floors and took the rugs outdoors, hung them on the
solar dryer (clothesline, that is) and beat them to a pulp with
that big old steel carpet whip.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody pitched in, turning mattresses, airing blankets,
cleaning out the basement and vacuuming everywhere. And, washing
anything that didn't move.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone do that anymore? I suppose they do, but the
activities are not quite so intense and concentrated. With all of
today's cleaning materials and supplies, the work is easier. And,
with soot-free fuels, at more efficient heating systems, things
aren't getting as dirty.
</P>
<P>
   But a house still has to be cleaned, or kept clean, and autumn
might be a good time to continue the battle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New super cloth
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are some new weapons in this battle. One is 3M Company's
Scotch Bright High Performance Cleaning Cloth, a special cloth that
picks up dust and dirt, not rearranging it as so often happens.
</P>
<P>
   The cloth acts as a magnet to hold dirt as you dust, reducing
the need for cleaning solvents and polishes. In fact, polishes
should be used as little as possible or not at all. Once a year,
maybe, and sparingly, is a good guideline.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturer claims the cloth is gentle and can be used on
antiques, collectibles, and computer screens. The manufacturer also
says the cloth can be machine washed many times. In fact, it should
be washed frequently, 3M says.
</P>
<P>
   The cloth comes in four colors and sells for $5.99 at
supermarkets, mass merchandisers, drugstores, and home centers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Super cloth on a swivel stick
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another super cleaning cloth is Procter &AMP; Gamble's Swiffer, a
cloth that picks up and holds dirt and dust with electrostatic
action. Such cloths can be used by themselves, but Swiffer also
comes with a lightweight, long-handled sweeper that the cloth can
be attached to. A swivel handle allows the sweeper to get under
beds and other hard-to-reach places.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiffer is an international product: The sweeper is made in
China, the cloths in the Netherlands. Procter &AMP; Gamble is the
distributor.
</P>
<P>
   And talk about your imprimatur! The handyman talked to a PR
person who brought the Swiffer to the Globe to show how it works
and how wonderful it is.
</P>
<P>
   When the interview ended, the PR person left, and as the
handyman returned to his desk, Swiffer in hand, not one but two
colleagues stopped him and said, ``Oh, I have one of those. I think
it's great.''
</P>
<P>
   As a product, you can't get much better support than that.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiffer costs $15 at supermarkets, mass merchandisers, and
home centers. It is recommended that the cloths not be washed, but
discarded when they get dirty. Refill cloths are available in lots
of 10, 16, and 32.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiffer, with its long handle, is particularly useful on
floors.
</P>
<P>
   So, armed with one or more of these cloths, you can clean
practically everything in sight. The big, dirty jobs still may need
detergents and water, solvents, and other cleaners, but the dry
cloths should help a lot in general cleaning _ and maintaining.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whoever does windows . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, it's a good time to tackle one job that
everyone has a love-hate relationship with: window cleaning. Now is
a good time because it will soon be time to put the storm windows
up or down and button up the house. And, clean windows will let in
more of the fading light and solar energy.
</P>
<P>
   Some people don't do windows, but if you do, you can make it
easier on yourself and do a good job with the right window cleaner
and the right technique.
</P>
<P>
   The right cleaner is a large dash of ammonia (half a cup) in a
bucket of warm water, or a spray bottle of Windex or other
commercial cleaner, which often contains ammonia and/or alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The right technique is to spray or sponge on the cleaner, wash
with a sponge, and dry with a squeegee. If you are any good at
this, and with practice you will get better, it's the only
technique that eliminates streaking.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to wipe the squeegee dry before making your second
sweep. A wet squeegee edge is a guarantee for streaks.
</P>
<P>
   Fall cleaning is important because we will be spending more time
in the house from now on, so it is best to have a clean place to
enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   You can make it even nicer after cleaning with these freshening
techniques: Cut up a lemon and put it through the disposal; it will
leave a light citrus scent. Sprinkle baking soda on carpets before
vacuuming to reduce musty odors. Light a few scented candles to
give rooms a warm glow and seasonal aroma.
</P>
<P>
   But go easy with candles; even the smokeless candles can produce
soot, and the cleaning chores start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   One more chore at fall cleaning time: Inspect and clean all
smoke detectors. A vacuum attachment will release dust; so will
feather dusting a bit. Dust can cause a detector to go off when
there is no smoke.
</P>
<P>
   And, while you're at it, change the batteries in your detectors,
and get in the habit of changing them each fall when you turn back
the clocks to standard time, on the last Sunday in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
