<HEADER>
A1979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS &LR;      09-30 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USE GREENBOARD FOR TILED WALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am redoing my bathroom with a shower stall, but no tub,
from the bare walls in. I know I should use WonderBoard for the
shower walls, then apply tile. What can I use for the rest of the
walls? Also, the plumber put in the shower pan, but what can I use
to fill it to the proper level so it will slope down toward the
center drain?
</P>
<P>
   DAVE CUNNINGHAM, Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. For the walls of the bathroom, use Blueboard and a skimcoat
or ordinary plasterboard if you are going to paint the walls. For
walls you plan to tile, use Greenboard, which is more water
resistant than plasterboard or Blueboard. But other than the shower
stall, there will no moisture to contend with except condensation,
and that can be handled by an exhaust fan. And since you have
gutted the bathroom, this is a good time to put in that exhaust
fan, exhausting to the outdoors either through the ceiling or
through the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the Wonderboard is a brand name for concrete
board; there are other brand names, all virtually the same, and
they are a wonderful base for tile applied with a thin-set mortar.
</P>
<P>
   For the shower pan, if it is not already finished and sloping
toward the drain, fill it with mortar, which you can buy as
Sakrete's Mortar Mix. Fill enough to accommodate a top layer of
ceramic tile installed with thin-set mortar. Since the pan will
slope down from four sides to the center drain, I suggest you
install small mosaic tiles because they will follow the slanting
surface of the mortar fill better than larger tiles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I know that you are supposed to put down deck boards with the
cup side down; that is, when you look at the end grain of the
boards you will see the grain forming a rainbow. I did that, but
now the edges are curling. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   DAVE CUNNINGHAM, Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You did right, although there is dissension in the ranks;
some wood people feel that it makes no difference whether the
boards are put rainbow side down or up. So, the boards could curl
no matter how they are laid. For the curling of your boards, if
they are curling up from the joists, I suggest you pull the
fasteners and drive deck screws closer to the edge (half an inch)
and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   And, over the years of cyclical expanding and contracting with
intake and loss of moisture, they might just settle down to a
minimum of curling, possibly none at all.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, turn the boards over to reverse the
curling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My double-glazed windows are only 10 years old and are
already fogging. The manufacturer has gone out of business. I heard
of a way of putting in new glass. It is called the BiGlass system.
Would that work? Otherwise, what can I do?
</P>
<P>
   D.P., Pembroke, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, BiGlass will work. It is a system that takes out the
glass of old windows, and puts in a double-glazed glass insert. The
system usually works with single-glazed windows, but it should be a
cinch to do it with your double-glazed windows. Alternatives? Yes,
there is at least one that does not require replacing the entire
window, which is not necessary anyway. And that is to have a
company replace just the sash, the movable part of the window, the
frame that holds the faulty glass. This will cost about $150 to
$200, give or take a few bucks. Still a bargain, compared to
replacing whole windows, casing, frame, and all, for much more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The galvanized nails in my deck are turning black. My brother
suggested setting the nails and filling the holes with wood filler.
What do you say?
</P>
<P>
   G.N., Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I say let 'em turn black. That is what galvanized nails do.
On a deck it probably isn't too bad, and may even add to the deck's
character. but if the nails start rusting, then you have to do
something. But setting the nails and filling the holes with filler
is not the thing to do. The filler may not last long, and will not
take a stain if you decide to stain the deck.
</P>
<P>
   If you really want to get rid of the galvanized nails, the only
recourse is to pull them and substitute stainless steel screws or
nails. Or pull the nails and refasten the boards with the new
no-show fasteners that hold the boards from below.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The toilet in my townhouse condo fails to flush properly
every other time. It has happened only in the past few weeks, but
it is a nuisance. How can I fix it? It's a Briggs brand.
</P>
<P>
   ANGRY, in Ashland, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That certainly is not a widely known brand, but its
construction is probably not the culprit anyway. I think it's a
partially blocked drain, either in the toilet itself or in the
drain under the toilet. You could try running an auger snake (long
wire with a little hook at one end) down the toilet, if you can get
to it. If that doesn't work, you might have to lift the toilet and
clear out the drain under it. This is best done by a plumber unless
you know a lot about toilets and plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   But before you do anything, bite the bullet, hang on to your
hat, and reach into the toilet to see if you can find that
blockage. Wear rubber gloves and wash thoroughly after doing this.
It sounds gross, it is gross, but the handyman did it (with his
bare hands, shudder shudder!) in an apartment many eons ago when
his toilet failed to work every time. And, sure enough, he came up
with a comb, which is just the thing that could cause a partial
blockage, rather than a complete one. You might find a comb, a
rubber ducky, or similar partial blocker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
