<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY WE LIVE SO LONG? THERE'S GROWING UP TO DO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there any reason for old age?
</P>
<P>
   We know that all living creatures have a simple biological
purpose _ to reproduce _ and that many species, like salmon, for
example, begin dying the minute they've fulfilled that requirement.
Why are most human beings forced to spend such a long stretch of
time at what might be considered the useless end of their lives?
Could there be something we're actually supposed to accomplish
here?
</P>
<P>
   I've been thinking about this subject since I began reading
James Hillman's ``The Force of Character and the Lasting Life.''
Hillman rejects the idea that old age is no more than a time of
losses, marked by a succession of senior moments, gray hairs, and
wrinkles. He prefers, he says, to entertain the idea that the
development of character requires additional years beyond those in
which we have spent striving and sacrificing. He believes that
older men and women, finally free from the yoke of conformity that
prevented their fullest development, require this time to grow into
their own unique selves.
</P>
<P>
   As the founder of the Marblehead Cancer Prevention Project, I
know I am a different person from the young woman who was once at a
total loss about how to become a leader. As a teenager, I failed to
figure out that there is a difference between popularity and
leadership ability. When I looked at the girls who seemed to be in
charge of everything, I thought it was looks or clothes or wealth
that elevated them above the rest of us. I envied the mysterious
confidence they seemed to possess and I clearly lacked. I hadn't a
clue that what it really takes is the ability to motivate others,
to keep one's word, to take on a project and complete it.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I entered my 20s, it had dawned on me that hard work
pays off, as mundane as that sounds. If you take on a task and do
it well, people turn to you when they need something else done.
They elect you to positions of responsibility. They respect you and
trust you. I learned how to enter an organization and play an
important role. I didn't realize it at the time, but I was still
seriously defective in the art of teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   In my 30s, as my husband puts it, I was a troublemaker rather
than a peacemaker. I had strong opinions and an uncompromising
stance on every issue. I was fierce in opposition. When confronted,
I tended to escalate my demands. I see now that I put more energy
into being angry than into getting results. I allowed the play of
my emotions to distract me from my goals. It hadn't occurred to me
that thinking I was always right was keeping me from being
effective.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was my ego to rein in. I had to stop thinking of
the work I was doing as a way of gaining recognition. I had to
realize that being organized wasn't one of my skills and become
willing to allow others to make up for my deficiencies. I had to
get over my impatience with people who dawdled, or couldn't get to
the point, or said they'd do something and then didn't deliver. I
had to give up judging other people and learn to appreciate the
interplay of personalities. I had to understand that I could
benefit from criticism. I had to recognize that assigning blame was
a total waste of my time.
</P>
<P>
   That took another 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that time etches itself into the lines of our faces,
but we don't often think of how it can improve our characters,
broaden our perspectives, or teach us the value of perseverance. I
like to think the members of the cancer prevention project, after
so many years of passionate advocacy, are by now ``well seasoned,''
or as the dictionary puts it, ``toughened by experience or by
exposure to difficult conditions.'' We have learned how to pace
ourselves, how to support one another, and how important it is to
keep from posing enemies. We are working on not taking ourselves so
seriously that we forget to have fun. Strangely, we find growing
older both humbling and empowering. At this point in our lives, we
know the burden of change does not rest only on our few frail
shoulders. We recognize that this fight spans many more years than
our lifetimes allow. We are dedicating ourselves to a cause whose
beneficiaries are not yet born.
</P>
<P>
   Years of experience have taught us that although we cannot
finish, we must continue. For if we do not, who will?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
