<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-NATURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECUPERATING FROM DROUGHT TO FLOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a difference a week makes! We were worrying about the
long-term damage to trees, shrubs, and mottled brown lawns from
this year's prolonged drought. Then the heavens opened up. Now
flooding from not so friendly Floyd is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad old Ma Nature can't get her act together using judicious
restraint and moderation. After Hurricane Floyd's drenching, the
grass is green anew so you may have forgotten all about the
drought, but let's talk about it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The effects of drought are interesting. All this past season
trees and plants have been so parched that they instinctively
thought they were going to die. This triggers a hormonal response
that tells them to make lots of flower buds to produce lots of
seeds and thus keep their genes going. So next spring, maybe, we
will have lots and lots of flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the plants were so, so dry that they didn't have enough
strength (technically a carbohydrate energy source) to make very
many buds at all. Because Ma Nature doesn't do things in
moderation, trying to predict her whims next year involves lots of
plant science, some guesswork, and a bit of plain dumb luck.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that this drenching came just at the best time
for plant recovery. Good roots are the key to good plant health,
and during periods of drought, many roots shrivel and die.
</P>
<P>
   The best new root growth takes place from September until the
ground freezes, when there is no competition from leaf expansion or
bud production. All of the energy source is marshalled into
expanding new roots.
</P>
<P>
   A good deep soaking wets the ground all the way down. As the
topsoil dries out, the roots continue growing downward as they
follow their underground water source. The result, especially with
grass, is deep roots, which will be less vulnerable to drought next
summer. Sprinkler systems, on the other hand, encourage shallow
surface roots, which are very vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   What does this mean in practical terms for the backyard
gardener? There is enough water in the soil for several weeks,
which will carry you into October, after which the plants should be
left alone to harden off for winter.
</P>
<P>
   So, turn off your sprinkler system right now. Use the manual
control shutoff until your sprinkler company can schedule your
winter turnoff appointment. You will, however, have to continue to
watch and maybe water some annuals and vegetables if their soil
dries out down to about an inch or two.
</P>
<P>
   While drought is one problem, too much water causes other
problems, the main one being fungi. (You just can't win.) When the
soil, leaves, and everything are damp and cool, various molds and
diseases appear on leaves, some flowers, and even on lawn grasses.
The worst hit are those that were heavily fertilized with high
nitrogen fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? Pull off the leaves that have gray, white, or black
coatings and blotches. Also ones with lots of brown. Pick up any
from the ground and throw the whole bunch away. Obviously, don't
put them in the mulch pile.
</P>
<P>
   When I do the fall cleanup, I generally throw out (in the
rubbish) my tomato plants, beans, phlox, peonies, plus rose and
lilac leaves. If you get asthma from mold wear a mask and take
something for allergy.
</P>
<P>
   As for the soil, do nothing until it dries out, especially if
you had any flooding. Working soil that is too wet ruins its
texture (called tilth). The classic test is to put soil in your
hand and squeeze it. If it makes a mudball, it's too wet. If it
crumbles and falls apart, it's OK to work.
</P>
<P>
   If topsoil runoff and flood waters buried any of your yard, wait
until it's quite dry before attempting repairs. Then rake or shovel
off the silt to the previous ground level. Two inches of soil
buildup in shrub beds isn't harmful if you remove the soil from
around the stems and trunks. Anything over 5-6 inches should be
removed. Rake the lawn and leave the little brown bits that remain.
Put the removed silt in the vegetable or flower garden because it's
good, rich topsoil.
</P>
<P>
   Saltwater damage is another matter. There are two kinds. One is
windborne salt spray, which can travel 10 and even 20 miles from
the ocean. The damage is mainly superficial leaf browning. Ignore
it. Those leaves were going to fall soon enough, and next spring
things will be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Saltwater flooding is another matter. If the salt content of the
soil gets too high, permanent root damage and death will happen to
vulnerable species, most of which are the common ornamentals we use
in our gardens. Instead, salt-resistant, low-maintenance plants can
be planted.
</P>
<P>
   However, most of them don't compare to roses, althea,
hydrangeas, our favorite perennials, and the flowers of summer we
love. As a matter of common sense, I think it's better to replant
what we love and consider this our tithe to Ma Nature's
irascibility.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ruth S. Foster has been a landscape consultant for many years and
has written numerous articles on gardening.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
