<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUXURIOUS MERCEDES SL500 WANTS TO DRIVE ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This car's got a mind of its own.
</P>
<P>
   I am coming into Boston from the north on a wet day, up on the
bridge just before the Fleet Center. Traffic's not bad, but there
are vast puddles.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell my last driving instructor this, but I do not have my
hands at the 10- and 2-o'clock positions on the wheel. I've got one
hand draped over the wheel, trying to gently coax the car through
the slop, feeling what it wants to do. But something else is
driving the car. I hit a puddle, and the car slows and corrects
itself to keep going straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   I hit a steel expansion joint on the bridge, and whatever slight
traces of spin that wet steel imparts to the rear-drive wheels is
picked up and the car goes into electronic stability mode. I notice
the same thing later on a loose gravel road. The Mercedes SL500
wants to drive itself. Even with electronic stability off, it does
its own braking when a rear wheel starts to slip.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe when you buy a Mercedes, this is what you are looking
for: straight-ahead power and the virtual certainty that you will
not get into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   This 8-cylinder (12 cylinders available in the SL600),
two-seater is the sports car for those who want hunkered-down
reliability, solid weight (more than 2 tons) that does not get
skittish on corners, and cruising almost like a luxury sedan's.
</P>
<P>
   It is a long, gorgeous wedge of car, made more eye-opening
because of the luxury of its special interior.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the 10 special-edition models in a new
European-inspired factory program called Designo. It is aimed at
solid Mercedes buyers who are ready to stretch their limits just a
bit and put together their own package of designer amenities _
those amenities coming in the forms of paint, leather, and wood.
</P>
<P>
   Special paint colors include black diamond, silver, green,
copper, and slate blue. The leather combinations for seats and
paneling include light brown, blue and charcoal, green and
charcoal, copper and charcoal, charcoal, shell, black and red, dark
blue and black. Wood trims are also optional in some models.
</P>
<P>
   Elegant in the right hands, customer choice can sometimes lead
to garish combos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like Elvis's bedroom,'' a friend said as he gazed upon
the red and black leather interior of my black diamond SL500. But
to each their own, though the possibilities for elegance or
gaudiness will be limited since Mercedes plans to produce only
250-500 of each (itals)Designo(unitals) model annually.
</P>
<P>
   So forget color and hop inside.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, soft leather seats. Firm sides from hips to shoulders.
Long, broad and firm base with myriad levels of adjustment behind
and below. Move the seat back and the seat belts adjust and the
headrests rise, assuming if you are moving back, you are likely
taller than the seat's last occupant.
</P>
<P>
   Grab the leather-wrapped wheel and look around.
</P>
<P>
   Light controls in a pod to the left. Straight ahead, a package
of gauges _ gas gauge alone, a grouping that includes oil and water
readouts and one for miles per gallon at current operation, then
the speedomoter and tachometer in separate rims, and, off to the
right, the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Simple controls at center dash: climate up top, audio below, and
just below that a hodgepodge including controls for the trunk lid,
towing protection, central locking, hazard lights, stability
control, adaptive dampening, and the roll bar.
</P>
<P>
   Controls for windows, mirror, heated seats, and the convertible
roof are clustered around the stick for the five-speed,
electronically-controlled, automatic (with driver-adaptive option)
transmission.
</P>
<P>
   You're surrounded by front and side airbags as you gaze out over
the long hood. On rainy days, a single, broad wiper blade cleans
the windshield with remarkable sweep.
</P>
<P>
   On a sunny day, drop the roof _ a remarkable mechanical event in
itself. Push a single button and hold it until all is done and the
windows go down. The rear quarter of the roof unlatches itself and
folds up against the main roof. Now the main roof unlatches with a
loud snap from the frame at the top of the windshield and lifts
itself. In the rear, a leather panel rises and the roof drops into
its storage compartment. The panel drops to cover the roof as the
roll bar, which had moved to get out of the way, comes back up, as
do the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Cool fall day, maybe too cool for a ragtop? No problem. Crank
the automatic climate control to 92 degrees and you are bathed in
warmth even as crisp fall air swirls about the car.
</P>
<P>
   You won't find much storage space inside _ narrow, covered slots
in the doors (deep and hard-to-reach bottom in them), and two small
storage areas between the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Fire up the engine and a restrained rumble bubbles from the
exhaust. Notice that the brake and gas pedal seem to have extra,
unnecessary travel in them.
</P>
<P>
   Notice just how long that hood is, and you'll understand why
this car ``drives long,'' unlike smaller sports cars. It is quiet
on the road, cruises at 75 at just over 2,000 rpms.
</P>
<P>
   It is not remarkable off the line and has a strange acceleration
lag (almost like a turbo lag). But punch it at speed, while turning
2,000-5,000 rpms, and it jumps to the job, sending the car surging
ahead (autobahn-like).
</P>
<P>
   The Electronic Stability Program helps avoid slides and spins by
correcting for over- and understeer. It uses torque and brake
controls to accomplish this.
</P>
<P>
   It stops fast and straight even from high speeds, ABS aided by a
brake assist system that boosts maximum power to the brakes when
the pedal is stomped, as in an emergency, and held there.
</P>
<P>
   A solid cruiser. Fast as you wanna be. Reliable. A Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The fabric covering at the lower-front portion of the doors
will get rubbed to tatters by the leading foot of emerging
occupants.
</P>
<P>
   --The lids on both between-the-seat storage bins jammed
repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The popouts in the rocker panels for attaching a jack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The numbers &QL; 
Base price: $81,100 &QL; 
Price as tested: $94,360 &QL; 
Horsepower 302 /Torque: 339 lb/ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 99 inches/ 177.1 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 71.3 inches/ 51.3 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 4,121 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 2 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1991 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-ART-BOS &LR;      09-30 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT RODS: ALL DONE WHEN YOU RUN OUT OF MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUDSON, Mass. _ Hot Rod. Slang. An automobile rebuilt or
remodeled for increased speed and acceleration. _ The American
Heritage Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Heirloom. Noun. A valued possession passed down in a family
through succeeding generations. _ The American Heritage Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Heirloom Hot Rod. Nascent slang. A lovingly cared for, souped-up
automobile, the result of thousands of hours of toil, which may get
passed down in a family through succeeding generations, or may be
fought over or found in pieces in a barn or garage, or may find its
way into the hands of a wealthy, private collector. _ Ford's Whacky
Auto Terms.
</P>
<P>
   I am crossing a field on as sparkling and clear and warm a late
summer Monday as you will ever get. The sounds of the fading '90s
echo to either side of me: teams of girls and boys playing soccer
behind the high school. Parents shouting. Whistles wailing. It is
wonderful and perfect and monochromatic. ``Pleasantville,'' the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of me, the sounds of the lingering '50s fill the air: Rock
'n' roll music blares from speakers mounted on poles and the rumble
of hot rods reverberates and stirs the smell of fried food _
burgers, fries, hot dogs. With each step I take, the world becomes
more colorful: candy apple reds, Bombays, pinks, blacks,
turquoises, inky deep blacks, gleaming metallics. The world is
filling in with color. ``Pleasantville,'' the movie.
</P>
<P>
   I am here to see hot rods and custom cars, all 1959 and earlier
vintage automobiles, and I am far from alone. Thousands join me to
view the 1,100 cars whose owners were lucky enough to sign up in
time to be admitted to the 27th Annual Ty-Rods Old Timers Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Monday and with so many people skipping work, you'd
think it was opening day for the Carmine Hose. But, no. These are
car people and they are playing Hot Rod Hooky.
</P>
<P>
   I am working. Tough job. Somebody's gotta do it.
</P>
<P>
   So I stroll amidst the paint jobs, the highboys and low cars,
the chrome, the carefully painted flames, the pleats and rolls, the
chops and channels.
</P>
<P>
   Cars rumble in through the day. Peter Raffi of Derry, N.H.,
owner of a classic 1955 Chevy pickup truck popularly known as a
Cameo, says that for car owners, ``driving in and driving out are
the best parts.'' That's because it's a parade of pride _ pride in
your car, its sound, its look.
</P>
<P>
   But something troubles me. Have these gems, these wonderfully
built and maintained autos become, maybe, too valuable? What is to
come of cars that may have been turned into hot rods 40 and 50
years ago for a few hundred or a few thousand dollars, which now
are worth $20,000 and $30,000, and in rare cases $100,000? Do they
become so valuable they end up in climate-controlled warehouses,
accessible to only the wealthiest of collectors? In museums?
</P>
<P>
   Some will, but here's hoping most get passed on, generation to
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Thank the Ty-Rods for this day. Founded in Concord in 1952,
they've been holding this show ever since they decided nearly three
decades ago that they needed a way to get old members back
together. First show, at the VFW in Littleton, drew 38 people and,
says Bob Parker, a Ty-Rod since 1956, 26 or 27 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the old image of hot rodders as rowdies, the Ty-Rods
have always been a relatively peaceful bunch (excepting, Parker
says, the night pizza ended up all over the walls at a veterans'
establishment and they were asked to move the whole show outdoors).
</P>
<P>
   The Ty-Rods club was formed by members who felt their original
group, the Piston Pushers, danced too close to the Hollywood
stereotype of hot rodders. The latter club appellation being an
explosive piece of equipment and the former being an implement of
control, you can see where the names came from.
</P>
<P>
   The Ty-Rods lived down the pizza-fling and their show just grew.
Lately, they've had to drop the high end on the vintage of cars
from 1967 to 1959, and even with that, the 1,100 slots handed out
first-come, first-served go rapidly. Many are turned away.
</P>
<P>
   It's so big that the hot rods (Parker says hot rods are cars up
to 1939 and everything after that is a custom) at this show
represent a triangle with its points at Maine, Florida, and the
Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a New England show and the New England contingent is
beautiful and strong: the 1950 Mercury sedan of Jack Carr of
Billerica; the mustard and white 1957 Ford Fairlane of Richard
Perkins of Nashua, N.H.; Richard Sabotka's pink and black 1956 Ford
Victoria, home port, Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hamel of North Hampton, N.H., is here in a 1956 Chevrolet
Cameo pickup, tropical turquoise and Bombay in color, with its
unique from-the-factory fiberglass bed and 2 1/2 years of
restoration in it.
</P>
<P>
   For many young car buffs today, turning their ride into a hot
rod means fancy wheels and a new computer chip to boost engine
performance; that and tinted windows. Not like the days when
Parker, the longtime Ty-Rod, built a '32 Ford coupe, added a big
Caddy motor, and didn't have what you'd spend on wheels, tires, and
computer chips today in the whole rig.
</P>
<P>
   That was back when airport runways were where you got to test
your efforts and the cars often reflected, in crude fashion, what
GIs had spotted in European sports cars and brought back from World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   But time is often warped.
</P>
<P>
   Walk up to Howard Poulin Jr., of Manchester, N.H., and ask him
if his brilliant yellow 1931 Ford five-window coupe is based on the
car in the movie ``American Graffiti'' and you get a rolling
belly-laugh. This car was built in 1959, way before the movie,
before, even, the movie's setting. A whole year before Poulin was
racing on the straights in Fremont, Calif. Way before high-tech,
expensive drag racing got to be more than he could afford and
brought him back to where he is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm right back to where I started,'' he says, sitting happily
beside the coupe that on any given day, in its time, could
challenge anything else out there that was street legal.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to schisms. You've got them among race fans:
Indy vs. NASCAR; among bikers: Harley vs. Asian-made bikes and old
Harley riders vs. new Harley riders (never mind that without new
Evo Harley guys and women, Harley would be dead as the Henry J),
and, in hot rod and custom: steel vs. technology.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Poulin can say he's not the owner of some
``Tupperware, yuppie, kit-car,'' and William Horn of East Freetown
can stand proudly beside his 1939 Chevy Master Deluxe gasser from
the '60s, straight axle, not lowered, big block Chevy 454 cranking
out 435 horsepower, and say proudly, ``It's all steel.''
</P>
<P>
   But like many hot rods, it's not finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all done when you run out of money,'' says Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes me wonder and worry.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when every aficiando pours every hard-won cent into
every car and then the car gets so valuable as Hot Rod Heirloom
that just maybe it's worth more to some collector than it is to
them?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
