<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1994 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BOSTON-ARTIFACTS-ART-     09-30 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-ARTIFACTS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUG-UP COLONIAL ARTIFACTS OFFER RARE INSIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ What one specialist called Boston's most important
collection of historical artifacts ever excavated from the depths
of the earth comprises 500 boxes of trash.
</P>
<P>
   There's a quarter of a million seeds, mostly cherry pits; 160
fragments of cloth, seven shoes, myriad broken chamber pots and
another quarter-million random items, from wig curlers to preserved
intestinal parasites and grain weevils.
</P>
<P>
   This up-close-and-personal snapshot of colonial Boston is
available for public inspection thanks to an entity usually
associated with the city's future rather than its past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archaeology of the Central Artery Project: Highway to the
Past,'' at the Massachusetts Historical Commission's Commonwealth
Museum, displays the treasures unearthed before the Big Dig began
to transform Boston's highway system.
</P>
<P>
   To comply with federal and state law, the Central Artery Project
commissioned a thorough archeological analysis of the areas the
road construction would disturb.
</P>
<P>
   From 1979 through 1994, excavators carefully explored a small
handful of important sites in Charlestown and the North End, and on
Spectacle Island in Boston Harbor. They found such treasures as the
oldest bowling ball known in the New World, which dates to about
1670.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it throws Boston into turmoil, The Big Dig has proven a
boon to archaeology, said Dr. Ann-Eliza Lewis, archaeological
collections manager for the Massachusetts Historical Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, she said, it is impossible for social scientists to
access artifacts hidden under a bustling city, locked beneath
asphalt, skyscrapers and other buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that this is the most significant excavation
Boston has ever seen,'' Lewis said. ``There are some other pockets
that could still be explored, but there aren't any more Big Digs,
and it's almost impossible for researchers to excavate in urban
situations because it's so disruptive to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The trash and ordinary household objects on display are
enlightening, archeologists say, because they provide tangible
evidence of everyday life in bygone times that are typically
documented only in dusty books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's spectacular, because you don't normally find this kind of
material,'' said Central Artery Project archaeologist Robert J.
Hasenstab. ``The garbage people discard normally disintegrates, and
it's so valuable because it can tell you what people are eating,
what their sanitation and health is like.''
</P>
<P>
   A North End privy _ or 17th-century outhouse _ provided much of
the Central Artery Project's most impressive finds. Because it was
sealed off with clay, it preserved biodegradable items such as
lace, food items and bugs.
</P>
<P>
   The privy was owned by Katherine Nanny Naylor, a wealthy woman
who died in 1716 at the age of 86.
</P>
<P>
   Naylor was one of four ``really strong colonial women,'' in
Lewis's words, whose lives are highlighted through their
belongings. Also featured are two colonial-era businesswomen and a
17th-century Native American political leader who used a
bow-and-arrow as her signature.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit includes artifacts from the Three Cranes Tavern in
Charlestown's City Square.
</P>
<P>
   The tavern _ which stood on the site of the former home of John
Winthrop, the first governor of the Massachusetts Bay Colony _ did
140 years of brisk business before it was burned to cinders in the
Battle of Bunker Hill in 1775, Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Among its hidden riches was a large, two-handled jug, circa
1750, meant to hold posset _ warm milk mixed with spiced rum _ and
to be passed around the room for communal drinking.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Historical Commission has designed a
curriculum for 5th and 6th graders around the collection, and
museum officials hope to welcome as many as 2,000 schoolchildren in
the next few months. The free exhibit is open until November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids can really interact with history on a very personal
level,'' with archaeology, Lewis said. ``They see a marble, and
it's different, but they recognize it. It allows them to think like
an archaeologist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
