<SLUG> BC-TUITION-BIDDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET TUITION SERVICE IRKS SOME COLLEGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: eCollegebid.org is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was bound to come to this.
</P>
<P>
   Just as thousands of people bid every day for cheaper airline
tickets on the Internet, now they can bid for cheaper college
tuition, too.
</P>
<P>
   A bidding service launched on the Web last week has college
admissions officers in a furor, saying it is preying on families'
anxiety about the cost of a college education, and is adding to
cynicism about colleges at a time when rising tuitions have public
suspicion at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   The service, eCollegebid.org, also exposes a little-known and
little-advertised fact about college pricing: At even the most
prestigious schools, less than half the students pay full ``sticker
price,'' which at many schools has surpassed $30,000 for tuition,
room, and board. And as on an airplane, hardly anyone pays the same
as the person in the next seat.
</P>
<P>
   What students do pay is determined not only by how much they can
afford, or how much their parents make, but also by how badly
colleges want them. So two students with equal incomes, similar SAT
scores and grades, and similar sports or outside interests will pay
different amounts if Student A can use an offer from another
college to bargain for more financial aid from one that really
wants him or her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the inevitable and logical and probably very useful
result of the chaos in college pricing,'' said Gordon Winston, a
professor of economics at Williams College and the director of the
Williams project on the economics of higher education. ``This will
clearly increase the customer's power to extract concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   The founders of eCollegebid.org say they have identified up to
800 private colleges and universities that could participate in the
tuition bidding experiment, and that they have signed up a few
institutions, which they would not identify. Whether or not the
service succeeds, education specialists say it is merely the first
sign of how radically the Web will change enrollment and tuition
procedures at colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It underscores a change in the public mindset, that higher
education is a commodity to be purchased, it doesn't have that
holiness,'' said Richard Chait, a professor at Harvard's Graduate
School of Education. ``The question is not whether it's good or
bad, but that it was inevitable. We've socialized people to believe
that commerce of all manner of purchases is possible over the Net.
This is a private good, privately purchased, and it's governed by
rules that govern other private goods that are privately purchased.
I bid on a hotel, why not a freshman year?''
</P>
<P>
   The service seemingly is attempting to exploit a frenzied
financial aid system, where savvy parents haggle with schools over
price, and where students make decisions about where to get an
education based on how much they can afford.
</P>
<P>
   The eCollegebid.org service asks would-be students to submit the
amount they are willing or able to pay to attend college, whether
they want to commute or live in a dorm, what sports or interests
they have, and to specify a region where they would like to attend
school, and an area of study. The bidding students would find the
identity of the school they might attend only if their bid is
accepted. The service is free and bidders would be under no
obligation to attend the university.
</P>
<P>
   The service is scheduled to begin as the next application cycle
begins in November. The founders promise to put the power of
pricing in the hands of the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   College admissions officers say the value of an education should
not be reduced to a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been accused of being gatekeepers, used car salesmen,
and with things like this, you can understand why,'' said Joyce
Smith, executive director of the National Association of College
Admissions Counselors. ``This is an educational experience for a
child, not a car, not an airline ticket. This is really
disconcerting.''
</P>
<P>
   But admissions officers concede that the potential appeal of the
service is a direct result of the confusion over the cost of
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's confusion, partly because of the way we have behaved,
and there's also cynicism,'' said Michael McPherson, president of
Macalester College and the coauthor of an acclaimed book on student
aid. ``The temptation of having something that looks simple and
straightforward is considerable. I compare it to the success of
Saturn with cars. They've said, `There's no screwing around, we're
just going to tell you what it is.' People would like some analogy
with colleges.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidding for tuition takes advantage of a fact often overlooked
in the arena of college applications: Whatever the anxiety over
increased competition, there are hundreds of less competitive
schools with empty seats at the end of the admissions cycle, and
they would love to fill them.
</P>
<P>
   Tedd Kelly, eCollegebid.org founder, says it will appeal
especially to families who make too much money to qualify for
financial aid, but not enough to pay tuition in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is saying to students, they've still got places in mind,
and I have them in mind,'' said Kelly, a longtime college
enrollment consultant. ``And colleges have the choice of saying,
`Do we want to pursue someone who can only pay $8,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly would not name the colleges in his consortium. And he has
fewer than a dozen schools signed up, although he says he will have
many more by Nov. 1. About 800 of about 2,000 four-year colleges
nationwide fit into the profile he is targeting _ the schools with
leftover seats. The schools, he says, are likely to be liberal arts
schools in the Midwest, and to take students who have SAT scores
between 800 and 1,000, and grade-point averages of 2.5 to 2.9.
</P>
<P>
   The college admissions counselors raised concerns about the new
service at their national convention last week, and asked the
organization to do what Smith called ``an ethical review'' of the
new company, even though the founder is a member.
</P>
<P>
   ``That there are colleges that are so desperate to get a body
with some money is the wrong message to send about education,'' she
said. ``One would hope that a college is recruiting a student to
come because they have a good match, and academic environment,
something that suggests a student should be there other than `I can
afford to pay.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Others agree that the bidding in its crudest form may be a bad
idea. But, they say, it is simply the first.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit College Board launched an online service last week
to help students identify colleges that match their interests, to
compete with other commercial groups doing the same thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1997 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CHEVRON-HNS &LR;      09-30 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEVRON PICKS INSIDER TO HEAD COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kenneth T. Derr will retire at the end of the
year as chairman of the board and chief executive of the Chevron
Corp., turning over power to a highly regarded lieutenant, David
O'Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   A seamless transition is forecast when Derr, 63, retires Dec. 31
and O'Reilly, a chemical engineer born and reared in Dublin,
Ireland, succeeds him.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron made the announcements on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave O'Reilly is the right person to lead Chevron in the
future,'' Derr told a news conference at the corporation's
headquarters in San Francisco. ``He combines broad company
experience with a record of achieving superior business results,
and he has strong leadership skills.''
</P>
<P>
   One analyst who tracks the oil industry said virtually the same
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevron's stock is up fivefold during the decade of the 1990s
and Ken Derr is largely responsible for the policies that allow the
company to perform that well,'' said Douglas Terreson of the
Houston office of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time a person has performed in that manner he will be
difficult to replace, but Dave O'Reilly is very well regarded on
Wall Street. He's very talented and he has had tremendous
successes,'' Terreson said.
</P>
<P>
   Derr joined Chevron in 1960 after his graduation with a master's
of business administration degree from Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   From 1985 to 1989, when he assumed the position of chief
executive officer, he served as one of the company's two vice
chairmen, responsible for Chevron's U.S. petroleum business,
chemicals, coal, land development, research and several other major
corporate divisions, such as human resources, public affairs and
environmental affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Derr was responsible for merging Gulf Corp. into
Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly, 52, began his career at Chevron in 1968. He later
became manager of Chevron's refinery in Salt Lake City, was
manufacturing manager for Chevron Chemical's Olefins Division and
was general manager of the refinery in El Segundo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, he has been responsible for worldwide
exploration and production operations. He was elected vice chairman
in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Derr said that he told board members several years ago that he
did not want to work after he was 65 years old and that 10 years
was a sufficient time to serve as chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife thought that maybe a little less than that would have
been OK, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, O'Reilly was made head of worldwide exploration
and production operations as a signal that he was the probable heir
apparent, Derr said.
</P>
<P>
   Derr said he had been diagnosed with prostate cancer in late
1987, had successful surgery in June 1998 and is in excellent
health. He said the diagnosis had no effect on his decision to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my 63rd birthday a couple months ago and I think it is
time to spend a little bit more time with my grandkids, whom I
hardly see, and even play a little bit more golf,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly said that during Derr's tenure, Chevron's market
capitalization grew from $15 billion to $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pay dividends in this business, unlike some of the
`dot-com' companies, but $100 invested in Chevron in 1989 (when
Derr took charge) would be worth $700 today, and I think we owe Ken
a debt of gratitude for his leadership during the past decade,''
O'Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly described himself as ``focused on the business'' and
able to get results. He allowed, ``I tend to be impatient at times.
I get that feedback also.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his priority at the helm of the corporation would be to
achieve top shareholder return and to do that there would have to
be growth in earnings ``at a faster rate, while maintaining
profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it requires an oil company merger for that to happen
``is questionable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Merger talks between Chevron and Texaco Inc. ended earlier this
year due to disputes over who would lead the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly said what Derr has long said, that Chevron would not
merge for the sake of size, but only if it made good business
sense. ``I don't see that we have to do something on a macro scale
to be a top performer in this business,'' O'Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Chevron has been evaluating merger candidates,
said oil analyst Michael Young of Deutsche Bank Securities in
Boston. ``I would expect that the evaluation of merger and
acquisition opportunities by Chevron will continue under O'Reilly
as much as under Derr,'' Young said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
