<HEADLINE>
REVERSING THE ORDER OF THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems I'm forever mail-ordering stuff from catalogs only to
send it back.
</P>
<P>
   The return forms list categories under Reason For Return. Check
one: Too big. Too small. Wrong color. Wrong size. Quality. Design.
</P>
<P>
   I've never seen one that says, ``Changed my mind'' or ``No
longer in the mood'' or ``My self image has shifted.''
</P>
<P>
   I've thought about writing ``Changed my mind'' in the section
that's sometimes provided for ``Comments,'' but I've never done it.
I imagine somebody in the Return department looking at my form and
saying, ``Changed her mind? Who does she think she is? Return
denied!''
</P>
<P>
   So usually I end up lying on the return forms. I feel guilty
about lying, but it seems to work. One of the many advantages of
buying things from mail order companies is that they'll take the
stuff back, no questions asked, within certain limits anyway. I'm
sure there are returners who try to put one over on the catalog
companies, just as they try to put one over on stores.
</P>
<P>
   In Filene's the other day I overheard a woman say, ``They don't
fit. You have to take them back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But they've been altered,'' the saleswoman protested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if I altered them, they'd fit. But they don't. You
have to take them back.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how this little drama resolved itself. I went on my
way wondering: Where do people get the nerve?
</P>
<P>
   But who am I, a woman who lies about her Reason For Return, to
criticize? I wish I didn't have to lie. I think mail order
companies should expand the list of categories.
</P>
<P>
   _ Foolishly imagined it would change my life.
</P>
<P>
   _ Felt bloated when I ordered it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Felt especially thin when I ordered it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Just had an urge to buy something.
</P>
<P>
   _ My kids laughed when I tried it on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ordered right after breaking up with boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hoped it would cheer me up. It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ordered after one drink too many.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't remember why I wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't remember ordering it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't remember, period.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fell off diet waiting for it to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fluctuating hormones influenced order.
</P>
<P>
   _ Needed to hear a kind voice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wanted to check if credit card over limit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Temporarily insane at time of order.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ordered when Mercury in retrograde.
</P>
<P>
   _ It's not A Good Thing.
</P>
<P>
   _ My cat doesn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Too revealing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not revealing enough.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ordered after too much coffee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ordered after not enough coffee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Full moon coincided with ordering.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hoped it would satisfy obscure longing. It didn't.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have crush on UPS man.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ordered after I forgot to take anti-depressant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Recovering shopping addict.
</P>
<P>
   _ Order influenced by space aliens.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kathie Lee has one just like it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bad feng shui.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hallucinating when ordering.
</P>
<P>
   _ The devil made me do it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ordered while on horns of moral dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
