<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2001 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BACH-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     09-30 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BACH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... his bags.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Americans reached Kiev in June. For two days there was more
frustration. The archives were closed for renovation, the visitors
were told. The manuscripts themselves had not been processed and
therefore could not be examined. The archives director, a former
KGB agent, was about to retire and could not accommodate their
requests. Finally, Wolff and company were granted special
permission to visit the upstairs stacks. A single box was pulled
down, and the rest, as they say, was history.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff's team celebrated that night by quaffing shots of
Ukrainian vodka on a riverboat restaurant. In the time they had
left, they examined only about 50 items, photographing what they
could. Ukrainian officials still did not realize what they were
sitting on, Wolff guesses. Despite warnings, they seemed startled
when news of the discovery brought German television crews
scampering to their doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I can tell, there's nothing else out there like this
in terms of a closed collection,'' says Wolff. ``There are
individual items missing from libraries, even groups of
manuscripts. But at least in the field of music, a collection of
this size does not exist'' outside the scope of scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a dollar value on the collection is hard to do, adds
Wolff, who is often asked by auction houses and private collectors
to appraise the authenticity _ but not the monetary value _ of
music memorabilia coming on the market. A JS Bach cantata has sold
for as much as $1 million, he says, but the CPE Bach collection
contains nothing of similar value. Not that Ukrainian officials
might be tempted to put the collection on the auction block anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would create major legal problems,'' avers Wolff. ``But
there's no question it's of immense value.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, which hopes to acquire a microfilm facsimile of the
Bach collection, will not bid for the original items either, say
Wolff. Most likely the manuscripts will remain in Kiev for
documentation, says Wolff, then be permanently housed in Berlin. A
bill passed by the Ukrainian Parliament just last week should help
codify an existing agreement between Germany and Ukraine on the
return of such treasures, according to Grimsted. She and Wolff were
to meet this week in Cambridge with Rulan Pyrih, chief of the
Ukrainian archival administration. Their discussions will focus on
the future cataloging and microfilming of the Sing-Akademie
collection. Wolff heads back to Kiev next month to resume work on
site.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Kiev discovery thrusts Wolff into a spotlight he has been in
before. In 1984, Wolf ``discovered'' 33 chorale preludes by JS Bach
_ in Yale University's music library, no less, where they were not
so much missing as unattributed. That finding, announced not long
before Bach's 300th birthday, prompted a series of ``world
premiere'' concerts. (It also stirred up controversy when West
German organist Wilhelm Krumbach claimed that he had performed the
Bach chorales first.) Travelling to Lodz, Poland, in 1989, Wolff
authenticated what was basically the entire missing collection of
Philipp Spitta, a 19th-century musicologist who wrote the first
major Bach biography. The Spitta archives too had disappeared from
scholarly sight during the war years. In 1975, Wolff played a
significant role in verifying a set of 14 Bach canons belonging to
a Strasbourg Conservatory professor. The manuscript turned out to
be Bach's personal copy of the Goldberg Variations.
</P>
<P>
   International politics aside, Wolff says this latest find will
almost certainly shed new light on JS Bach's development as a
composer. Bach was a meticulous archivist, says Wolff, who not only
drew upon the work of his ancestors but also worked closely with
his sons, inspiring them as Bach in turn was inspired by them. His
notations on the Sing-Akademie manuscripts are thus potentially as
important to musicologists as the hieroglyphs in the tombs of the
pharoahs are to Egyptologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of his early compositions were questioned by earlier
generations of scholars because it didn't sound like Bach,'' says
Wolff. ``But Bach was essentially self-taught, and he exposed
himself to a broad range of music circa 1700. Relating his early
works to his eclectic study habits gives us insight into the mind
one of the great composers of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   In her forthcoming book ``Trophies of War and Empire,'' Grimsted
compares the manuscripts to liberated prisoners of war. At last,
she writes, the scores can be ``described, studied, performed, and
appreciated _ and at last be restored to their rightful place as a
major component of the common European cultural heritage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
