<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING GOOD AT GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest computer at my house isn't the homemade box I
usually work on, or the old Pentium 90 Linux server, or even the
blazing Athlon tower I borrowed from Advanced Micro Devices Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Instead it's this little beige box, roughly the size of a
package of software, that sits on the floor next to my TV set. It's
the new Sega Dreamcast _ a limited and in some ways rather crude
machine, which nevertheless could teach any PC a thing or two about
serving up realistic, razor-sharp electronic entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamcast illustrates our inevitable march toward a post-PC
world. Of course, some of us will always want all-purpose computers
that do many things reasonably well. But as processors get cheaper
and more powerful, it makes sense to build specialized devices that
do one or two things very well.
</P>
<P>
   This became obvious years ago to the makers of ``console
games,'' the electronic games that connect to your home TV.
Nintendo, Sony, and Sega have built this sub-species of computer
into a multibillion-dollar market. Along the way they've spawned an
arms race every bit as exciting as the Pentium III-PowerPC-Athlon
wars being waged on the desktop. Each firm keeps rolling out ever
more advanced game machines, based on ever more muscular
processors. Sony says its Playstation 2, due next year, will make
Dreamcast look like a pocket calculator. But for now, Sega holds
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamcast employs a processor made by the Japanese electronics
firm Hitachi using a technique called RISC _ Reduced Instruction
Set Computing. RISC chips use a stripped-down design that let them
run much faster than non-RISC designs like the Pentium. The G4 chip
that drives Apple Computer's ferocious new workstations is a RISC
chip; so is the Dreamcast processor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Dreamcast chip is designed to do one thing
especially well _ multiplying numbers with decimal points in them.
This kind of ``floating-point math'' is what computers use to draw
graphics. John Byrd, Sega's senior manager of developer technical
support, said the Dreamcast processor bangs out 1.4 billion
floating-point calculations per second.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a stream of wire-frame images, like a skyscraper
with the skin removed. This data is sent at 100 million cycles per
second _ much faster than in standard PCs _ to another chip that
draws the skin on each object, adds color, texture, and lighting
effects, and then flings it all onto your TV screen.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Dreamcast games that Sega sent me were rather
disappointing. There's little to recommend Blue Stinger, a
par-for-the-course first-person action saga: Kill bad guy, turn
left, walk down corridor, kill bad guy.
</P>
<P>
   Sonic the Hedgehog, Sega's hallmark animated character, is back
with Sonic Adventure, a lively game with excellent
three-dimensional animations. Still, Sonic is a cartoon character
in a cartoon world. To me, the most impressive computer effects are
the ones that succeed in emulating the real world.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the game that should send Dreamcasts flying off
store shelves is Sega Sports' NFL 2K. Here you have a game that
simulates football, a sport millions of us watch on TV every week.
And if you stand about 10 feet away from a TV running the new
Dreamcast game, you'll think it's Sunday afternoon. It's not just
the astonishing detail _ the snowflakes drifting across the
gridiron at Mile High Stadium, the gusts of mist from gasping
players. What really amazes is the reproduction of the way athletes
move. Linebackers cheat up to the line of scrimmage, leaning and
lurching, as they threaten a blitz. Receivers stagger forward with
safeties draped around their ankles. The illusion isn't perfect,
but closer than any computer game has managed up to now.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamcast experience comes crashing back to earth when you
hook up the built-in modem and optional keyboard and log onto the
Internet. The Dreamcast browser is primitive by PC standards, and
Web pages generally look awful on a TV set. But an Internet
capability is vital _ it'll let users play against each other on
line.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing costs $200. That's the cost of a high-end PC
graphics processor card, and the PC images still won't look as good
as the ones produced by a Dreamcast. The Dreamcast is no substitute
for a ``real'' computer. But if you're chiefly interested in games,
it's as real as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
