<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-MYSTERY-BOS &LR;      09-30 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MYSTERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SECOND SIGHT' IS NEARLY FIRST RATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SECOND SIGHT 
Produced by: David Lascelles 
Directed by: Charles Beeson 
Screeplay by: Paul Milne 
Date: Thursdays at 9 p.m., PBS 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ``Second Sight,'' the crime thriller initiating the 20th
season of PBS's ``Mystery,'' isn't the best production the British
series has produced, it's still superior to most of what you see on
televison. Falling short of ``Mystery'' masterpieces such as
``Inspector Morse'' or ``Prime Suspect'' simply means, like all
merely good things, to miss perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of the two-part, three-hour British cop drama (airing
Thursday, Sept. 30 and the following Thursday at 9 p.m.) involves
the brutal killing of a university boy at his family's comfy
suburban home. A prominent subplot, or more accurately, the coplot,
concerns the descent toward blindness of Detective Chief Inspector
Ross Tanner (Clive Owen). Just as he begins leading the murder
investigation, a rare virus begins stealing his eyesight,
intermittently splintering and clouding his vision.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that the pretty blonde detective assisting him,
Catherine Tully (Claire Skinner), volunteers to furtively guide
Tanner about without giving away his disability. Unsurprisingly,
the distance between them is eventually reduced to nothing _ as in
warm skin-to-skin.
</P>
<P>
   If Paula Milne's teleplay sounds somewhat contrived, well, it
is. It's too literarily conscious of its double suspense vehicles:
the manhunt for the elusive killer, and the eye disease threatening
the chief investigator's sight as well as his career. But she
writes crisp, smart dialogue, and fills her murder story,
especially when it ripens in Episode 2, full of cleverly nasty
twists and turns, and an array of credible suspects. Suspicion is
cast on a devious nanny jilted by the murder victim. Inspector
Tully even intuits the dark possibility of incest between the boy
and his mother. And the murdered youth's stepfather turns out to
have a long-lost, jealous, and possibly evil, twin brother who may
have a hand in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The fine production has both luster and, again especially in
Part 2, a dynamic, riveting pace. The camera's shifting point of
view pumps up the tension. Some of ``Second Sight'' is filmed from
Tanner's perspective, revealing his blurred, fragmented vision
while also suggesting, more dramatically than Milne's script does,
a connection between dimming eyesight and heightened insight. At
other times, the camera is a long-distance voyeur, intensifying the
creepiness of events. It also moves in close on faces, mercilessly
plumbing the character of heroes and (potential) villains alike,
while showing off the excellent cast.
</P>
<P>
   This, like so many quality English TV productions, features
nearly flawless performances from stars to minor character players,
the result, probably, of a culture where actors tend to move so
easily and often between screen and stage work. Owen overdoes
Tanner's sullenless a bit, but he brings an intense duality to the
character, a hard, brooding exterior armoring his fears and
cloaking his tenderness. Like Owen, Skinner is too actorishly good
looking to be easily believed as a thick-skinned homicide
investigator, but she evokes a rough edge that gives her cop a
nice, tough reality. The romance between her character and Owen's
unfolds with a refreshing tartness that testifies to the cool
control of both these fine performers.
</P>
<P>
   The other distinction of ``Second Sight'' is the overall sense
it conveys of a real, full-blooded, lived-in world, with its
ambient sounds of traffic and chit chat and rain and busy,
eye-filling interiors and rich cityscapes. This is something
American television (and Hollywood) isn't good at and one reason
why a series like ``Homicide'' felt so different and special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second Sight'' may not be perfect, but you won't get up the
morning after feeling guilty about spending part of the night with
it _ and that's a good test for good television.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
