<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2018 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BLIND-PAINTER-ART-BOS     09-30 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLIND-PAINTER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTIST WORKS ON THROUGH BLINDNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRANSTON, R.I. _ When Vicente Paratore, a successful artist for
many years, was blinded by a stroke, he plunged into an emotional
and spiritual darkness blacker than anything he had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Five times, Paratore tried drown himself in his hot tub. But
each time, something pulled him up, he says. Was it an angel? the
ghost of his mother trying to save him? Or perhaps, he says with a
touch of black humor, ``it was my own blind ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   In a saga as compelling as it is improbable, the blind artist,
who lives in Cranston, R.I., found a way to paint again even though
he could no longer see his canvas.
</P>
<P>
   A show of his work is in progress through October 21 at The
Learning Center of the Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an amazing artist, absolutely amazing,'' said Sonia
Javier-Obinger manager of community benefits for Beth-Israel
Deaconess and the exhibit's organizer. ``It's the fact that he has
this perspective, despite his limitations. His intense, vibrant
colors speak to his passion. You can see that he loves what he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a lunch he cooked at his apartment in Cranston, Paratore
described his life in broad, inspiring strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Now 67, he was born in a town near the Andes in central
Argentina, he said. When he was 11, his father, a construction
worker, died. Vicente dropped out of school to help earn money for
his family, doing an array of department store jobs.
</P>
<P>
   He immigrated to the U.S. in 1959 when he was 27, working first
as a shoemaker and then as a window-dresser in downtown Boston. In
1969, he launched forth on his own as a self-employed artist.
</P>
<P>
   In what he calls his ``gypsy go-round,'' he made paintings and
sculptures and travelled around the country exhibiting them. He
also made clowns and masks from burlap sacks, which he sold from a
booth at Quincy Market.
</P>
<P>
   He felt successful and satisfied. He moved his wife and five
children into a dream home in North Scituate.
</P>
<P>
   But stresses were mounting. He was trying to expand commercial
operations by building a production factory in Argentina. His wife
became seriously ill, which worried him deeply.
</P>
<P>
   One warm evening in May, 1986, after mowing his lawn, ``I was
surprised to find my eyes full of water. When I woke up the next
morning and tried to read a newspaper, the letters were all
blurry,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said he had a stroke, which damaged his optical nerves.
He was hospitalized for two weeks. To his horror, his eyesight
deteriorated day after day until he had no sight at all in one eye
and just four percent vision in the other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Going from light to dark like that, it was the most terrible
thing you can imagine,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   As his family watched anxiously, he sat in a chair in his
kitchen for eight months, utterly depressed, afraid to move. ``I
thought, I can't paint, I can't see the colors I love, I can't
drive, I couldn't do anything,'' he said. ``If I left the chair, I
was afraid I'd stumble.''
</P>
<P>
   In complete dispair, he tried to commit suicide. But something
wouldn't let him slip away. He fervently prayed for some sort of
answer.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, he asked a phone operator for the closest
center for the blind. She put him in touch with IN-SIGHT, a
rehabilitation agency for the blind in Warwick, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a black hole, really desperate,'' recalled Judy
Smith, IN-SIGHT's president. ``But he was tremendously motivated to
pursue his artistic career.''
</P>
<P>
   He met other blind people with similar struggles. IN-SIGHT staff
taught him basic skills, such as how to read braille, walk with a
cane, cook, shave, arrange his clothes, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, he began to regain his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest breakthrough came on Easter Sunday, 1989. His
grandchildren, playing with clay, urged him to make some big, funny
glasses for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started working with the clay, something clicked in my
mind,'' he said. That was when he invented the ``paint by touch''
technique that brought him back to life again.
</P>
<P>
   He explained how he molds the clay into thin strands which he
applies to poster board, forming the outlines of the main subjects
for his composition. Then, using a razor, he cuts around the clay,
making a stencil.
</P>
<P>
   After applying background colors to his canvas, he paints within
each stencil window, using paint from tubes marked with raised clay
letters to identify the hues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see with my inside mind,'' he said. ``It's fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Executed primarily in oils, watercolors and acrylics, his
paintings feature simple images _ A-frame homes in a deserted
landscape, boats in a harbor, sea waves breaking over rocks, as
well as abstracts.
</P>
<P>
   If his work appears less detailed now, it also has a raw power
lacking in his earlier art.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you paint with your eyes, you get critical, you go back
and change a lot of things, you destroy your first impressions,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I paint with my heart and my mind, and I don't go back and
fix my paintings because I don't really see them. I think my colors
are more clear, more vibrant, and more exciting than when I had my
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm more proud of myself,'' he added. ``I feel happy,
really happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2019 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BACH-2TAKES-ART     09-30 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BACH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCIDENT AND ADVENTURE UNCOVER BACH LONG THOUGHT LOST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gray cardboard box offered few clues to its actual contents.
Plucked at random from a shelf at the Ukrainian Central Archives in
Kiev last June, where it had sat, conceivably untouched, since
1973, the box was opened to make a point. Not to make news around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is precisely what happened. When Harvard
musicologist Christoph Wolff opened the lid, he saw several bound
volumes of old music scores. The director of the archives had
expected to hear murmurs of approval from his American visitors at
the fine condition of the materials. Instead, Wolff's movements
were greeted with awestruck silence.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Kennedy Grimsted, an associate with Harvard's Ukrainian
Research Institute in Cambridge, Mass., spotted a red
``Sing-Akademie Zu Berlin'' stamp on one of the manuscripts. None
of the Americans had seen such a stamp before, yet its import was
unmistakable. Grimsted turned to Wolff, a renowned Bach scholar.
``OK, Christoph, this is it,'' she said excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Wolff, a Harvard music librarian, pinched her husband.
Wolff's eyes were locked on the name written on one of the
manuscripts: ``Rungenhagen,'' a k a Carl Friedrich Rungenhagen, a
German composer and former director of the Sing-Akademie.
</P>
<P>
   There was little doubt in Wolff's mind that he was staring at
the Holy Grail that had eluded him for more than 30 years: the
``lost'' musical estate of Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach (1714-1788),
second son of Johann Sebastian Bach and in his own lifetime the
best-known member of the musical Bach family.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a treasure trove of 17th- and 18th-century music,
especially German music, the collection was known to include some
500 scores composed by the multibranched Bachs _ along with CPE
Bach's own compositions (including 20 Passions and 50 keyboard
concertos), letters from Johann Goethe to former Akademie director
Carl Friedrich Zelter, and unpublished works by Carl Henrich,
Johann Gottleib Graun, Georg Philipp Telemann, Johann Adolph Hasse,
and other important composers of the time, which have never been
available for performance.
</P>
<P>
   All of it, more than 5,100 items, presumed missing and lost to
posterity in the rubble of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was overwhelmed,'' recalls Wolff, whose verification of the
Bach collection caused a worldwide sensation this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back upon the moment from his office in University Hall,
Wolff continues, ``A collection of mainstream music of this
significance has not surfaced in quite some time. I was not
prepared for seeing the whole thing there, intact. It was truly an
enormous surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The saga of the Kiev discovery _ set against a backdrop of
Allied bombs, fleeing Nazis, Soviet raiding parties, and KGB
stonewalling _ reads like an Indiana Jones filmscript penned by
John le Carre after hours at the Royal Berlin Conservatory library.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the tale are three figures: Wolff, the Bach
expert who was convinced the collection could be found despite
repeated denials from German and Russian authorities; Grimsted,
whose expertise in Ukrainian ``trophy'' art led her to pick up the
trail of the collection in Kiev; and a Ukrainian official named
Hennadii Boriak, who supported American efforts to solve a riddle
that had frustrated scholars since 1943.
</P>
<P>
   Among the saga's juicy plot elements are the breakup of the
former Soviet Union and the global campaign to return thousands of
cultural artifacts stolen or seized during World War II. While not
as startling as unearthing a missing cache of Rembrandts, say,
discovery of the CPE Bach collection has excited music scholars
worldwide _ and rekindled hope that other ``missing'' wartime
spoils will be found, documented, and returned to their rightful
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the old Soviet Union was about to open those
archives,'' says Grimsted, noting that for decades the KGB
controlled the Soviet archival system and that its influence is
still being felt, both by researchers like herself and by
bureaucrats who outlasted the Soviet regime. Russia has made it
illegal to return trophy materials to Germany. Ukrainian officials
have taken a softer stance, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``The official line now is that the archives were never a
secret,'' she says. ``I think local officials are embarrassed that
it took a foreign scholar like Wolff to come in and tell them what
they had.'' Grimsted calls the discovery ``the tip of the iceberg''
in terms of the number of trophy materials that may yet be located
within Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story behind the headlines begins more than 200 years ago,
with the founding of the Sing-Akademie in Berlin, in 1791. While
primarly dedicated to musical performance _ in 1829, Felix
Mendelssohn directed Bach's ``St. Matthew's Passion'' at the
Akademie _ the choral society also became a major repository of
18th-century German music, largely due to its acquisition of the
CPE Bach estate under Zelter's aegis. Even so, according to Wolff,
the collection was poorly cataloged and inaccessible to most
scholars long before its disappearance behind Soviet lines.
</P>
<P>
   In 1943, as Allied bombs rained down upon Berlin, German
authorities shipped thousands of cultural treasures out of the
capital. They were taken to the countryside, remote hiding places
such as to salt mines and monasteries and castles like the one in
Silesia (now part of Poland) where the Sing-Akademie collection was
secreted.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the collection after the Nazis' defeat is still
being pieced together by Grimsted and others. Sing-Akademie
headquarters, located in what later became East Berlin, were
destroyed in the bombing. Soviet troops subsequently captured many
of the strongholds where the Nazis stashed their artifacts. Some
were taken home as war booty. Others were burned as a fuel during
the brutal winter of 1945. Grimsted's research revealed that the
Ukrainians had their own cultural trophy brigades ``in the field''
in 1945 and 1946, competing against other Soviet factions.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed to care much about the Sing-Akademie collection
until the 1960s, when Wolff was doing graduate work in Berlin. For
his dissertation, Wolff hoped to reconstruct the music library of
JS Bach. One primary source was the printed estate catalog of CPE
Bach, published in 1790. In the shadow of the Berlin Wall, however,
scholarly exchanges between East and West were virtually
impossibly. Wolff was told that in all likelihood the Sing-Akademie
archives had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   It was over a decade later that Wolff, the author of an
acclaimed Bach biography, heard a rumor that part of the archives
had ended up in Ukraine. He tried to verify the rumor through
musicians he knew in Kiev and Odessa, but no hard evidence turned
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept asking, though, which was a good thing,'' says Wolff,
who since 1992 has also served as dean of Harvard's Graduate School
of Arts and Sciences. As recently as 1998, inquiries on his part
yielded nothing more hopeful. Then Grimsted told Wolff earlier this
year that while researching her forthcoming book on Ukrainian
trophy art, she had located a document _ translated from a 1957
Soviet Ministry of Culture report and published in a book by a
German library committee _ alluding to the Sing-Akademie archives
being in Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   The initial response from Ukrainian officials was that the
document was probably a forgery. But at this point, the trail had
heated up again.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Boriak, whose chance encounter with a retired Kiev
librarian supplied a key piece to the puzzle. The librarian told
Boriak she had seen a report of a large collection of foreign music
being transferred from a Kiev conservatory to the more spacious
Ukrainian Central State Archive-Museum of Literature and Art, in
1973. The collection was not described further in the report, nor
was its existence confirmed by any archival records available to
Grimsted or other foreign researchers.
</P>
<P>
   However, it did not take a great leap of imagination, or faith,
to suppose this could be the Bach archives. Boriak all but
confirmed their existence through his own contacts at the state
archives. It remained for someone of Wolff's stature to examine the
collection and state whether he believed it was the real thing or
not.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsted e-mailed Wolff to pack his bags.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
