<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2021 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-30 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTS OF CATEGORY KILLERS TAKING IT ON THE CHIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Category killers were one of the great success stories of the
1980s. Almost overnight, they changed the retail landscape with a
simple concept _ that you could sell one thing in a great big store
and make a lot of money at it. Toys, office supplies, hardware,
electronics: If you picked the right one you could vanquish the
competition and dominate your field.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, some of the category killers have been bleeding
themselves. Toys ``R'' US just lost its chief executive and its
stock is down 65 percent from its all-time high. The office
superstores _ Staples, Office Depot, and OfficeMax _ have lost
anywhere from 40 percent to 50 percent of their market value since
the spring. The two big pet supply chains, Petsmart and Petco, have
been in Wall Street's doghouse for months.
</P>
<P>
   While there are different forces at work in each industry, there
is one unifying theme: intense competition. Like gunslingers in the
Old West, the category killers are being challenged by rivals who
want to prove they are faster, or cheaper, or better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is survival of the fittest,'' says Walter Salmon, an
emeritus professor of retailing at Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us may be the most troubled store of the bunch. For
years it was the largest seller of toys in America. More recently
it has lost that title to Wal-Mart, who along with Target has
demonstrated that you don't have to be a toy specialist to sell
toys.
</P>
<P>
   Retail analysts and money managers say Toys ``R'' Us's decline
is as much an example of corporate suicide as it case of being
mugged by rivals. The company's sins are many, says Steve Paspal, a
money manager with Sovereign Asset Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their service has fallen apart, the merchandising has been
horrible, the stores are too cluttered. Why would you want to go?''
asks Paspal. On top of all that, Toys ``R'' Us has been slow to
respond to Internet challengers like eToys.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Wal-Mart offers the same toys for less money and
the shopping experience is better.
</P>
<P>
   In the office-supply business, the competition comes mainly from
within.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become clear that three strong players in this market
is at least one too many,'' wrote a pair of analysts from Donaldson
Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette in an August report that depressed the stock
prices of all three office superstores.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts said the three big players were building too many
stores in a bid to win market share. The result has been weak
same-store sales at Office Depot and OfficeMax and a fear _ so far
unrealized _ that Staples will suffer the same fate. Wal-Mart has
been a minor factor in this market as well, because of its strong
back-to-school business.
</P>
<P>
   In the pet market, the news is no better. Petsmart's stock has
tumbled from 19 to less than 4 since April; rival Petco's stock is
trading at around 12, down from 18 in July. Both companies have had
trouble digesting acquisitions, both are expanding rapidly and, you
guessed it, both have had to contend with Wal-Mart, which sells $2
billion a year worth of pet supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart's success cuts to the heart of the very concept of a
category killer. Do people want to go to a different store for each
specialty or would they prefer to go to one place and buy
everything on their shopping list?
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the superstores are hurting. Home Depot, the
home-improvement specialist, continues to do well and remains a
favorite among investors. Home Depot has eliminated all of its
regional competitors and only Lowe's remains as a serious national
rival.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Home Depot like the fact that the chain hasn't been
content to rest on its laurels. It regularly comes up with new
concepts _ stores that offer decorative goods to upscale shoppers,
smaller stores for urban locations _ that contribute to rapid
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are continually reinventing the business,'' says Margaret
Buescher, a portfolio manager with Vaughn Nelson in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In electronics, both Circuit City and Best Buy have managed to
prosper, in part because they are the only two big players still
standing.
</P>
<P>
   No one is predicting the demise of category killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retailing most formats survive,'' says Harvard's Walter
Salmon. But if there is a lesson in the woes of some of the
industry's best-known names it is this: Retailing is a brutally
competitive business. It's a place where you kill or you get
killed, even if you once were a category killer yourself.
</P>
<P>
   In consumer-driven America, we wouldn't have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
