<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TIMOR-OBSTACLES-BOS &LR;      09-30 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-OBSTACLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEDING EAST TIMOR REFUGEES A DAUNTING TASK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REMEXIO, East Timor _ This week, relief workers in the United
States and Taiwan are battling floodwaters and searching collapsed
buildings to get help to the victims of Hurricane Floyd and the
Taipei earthquake. The destruction is terrible and the need
tremendous, but at least aid workers there don't need troops with
submachine guns to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Here in East Timor, the violence and devastation of the last
month were inflicted by men and sponsored by authorities. Some of
the perpetrators are still here and most of the homeless have been
pushed over the border to West Timor. Fires set by foes of
independence still rage daily, and killers claimed nine more
victims just a few days ago, despite the presence in the territory
of more than 4,000 foreign peacekeepers. The rainy season, which
makes many roads impassable, is just a month away.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it's hardly the ideal environment for providing
relief to the needy. The UN mission appealed Tuesday for $135
million over the next six months for humanitarian work.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days into the peacekeeping effort in East Timor, at a stage
when aid workers would like to be well along in the mission to
provide food, water, sanitation, medicine and shelter for tens of
thousands of people displaced within East Timor and 200,000 more
who fled or were forced over the western border, two basic
obstacles still stand between victims of the crisis and the relief
they need: a dangerous environment and a lack of transportation.
(Most vehicles were destroyed in the fires and looting).
</P>
<P>
   Other problems stem from those. Wednesday, air drops of food
were halted after a 3-year-old boy was hit by a falling box and had
to have his leg amputated. Indonesian troops are accused of
commandeering relief trucks and blocking a baby food delivery Both
troops and the desperate refugees have looted aid warehouses for
``a spontaneous distribution,'' in the euphemistic parlance of aid
workers. Practically the only hindrance that doesn't exist here is
a plague of locusts, one UN official said.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying practical and political barriers are so numerous,
it is hard to count them. Those carrying on the revenge campaign
that followed a landslide vote for independence on Aug. 30 flushed
people out of their homes, and now want to starve them in the
hills. Indonesia, which has ruled East Timor since it annexed the
former Portuguese colony in 1976, at first put up barriers to
airdrops of aid, perhaps because allowing them would be a tacit
acknowledgement of Jakarta's inability or unwillingness to stop the
post-election violence that sparked a humanitarian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers say they will help anyone in need, on either side of
the dispute. But since most of the victims back independence and
their attackers included Indonesian military and police, providing
relief to survivors or helping them move back from West Timor is
almost a political act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the interesting position of having to deal with
aggressors to get food to the victims of the crisis,'' said Charles
Robin, commodities officer for World Vision, an organization that
is coordinating distributions for the United Nations' World Food
Program.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the bigger job will be the long-term political and
economic reconstruction of East Timor. But for now, the effort to
build a humanitarian operation from ground zero that can distribute
emergency relief quickly and efficiently to hundreds of thousands
of survivors appears daunting.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Robin said, ``we don't know how many people there
are, where they are and what condition they're in.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding out means driving up into the mountains where people
have fled and counting heads, or relying on estimates from
independence leaders who are running a government-in-exile in the
hills. But without trucks or gasoline to haul loads, or enough
peacekeepers to protect aid convoys, even basic reconnaisance
missions are not an easy feat. And when aid workers can't
distribute food in faraway locations themselves, there is always
the concern that a community leader designated to coordinate will
take a cut for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most mundane problems can delay or foul up a delivery.
After losing trucks one day to the Indonesian military and being
delayed the next because there were no peacekeepers available to
protect an aid convoy, Robin finally was on his way to deliver aid
in the hills above Dili. But halfway up the mountain, the driver of
the aid truck pulled over and refused to budge.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, it turned out, had fled the violence to Dare, a hill
station at the turnoff in the road, and he thought the rice and
medical supplies were going there, to families including his own.
As a multivehicle military escort waited impatiently, the driver
angrily kicked his tires and claimed he didn't have enough gas to
get to Remexio, the place where leaders of the resistance had said
the humanitarian needs were greatest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget about what the leaders say. We are the regular people,
and we are hungry,'' the driver said furiously.
</P>
<P>
   It took Gregorius Fernandez, UNICEF director for East Timor, 10
minutes to persuade the driver to push onwards. ``Yes, we are all
hungry, but we brought some rice to Dare Wednesday. What about our
brothers and sisters in Remexio?''
</P>
<P>
   Past miles of scrubby trees, dry soil and wild red poinsettias,
the convoy finally arrived in Remexio, where dozens of people who
had walked days barefoot from Dili to escape pumped their fists and
cheered in welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no food; for one week, we are just eating leaves,''
Maria Teresa Gusmao, a 30-year-old mother who trudged here over
nine days with her seven small children.
</P>
<P>
   Even as refugees began to flow back into Dili by the thousands
in the last few days, severe food shortages in the city remain and
hungry people have scuffled over food at distribution centers.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Mountain, the UN humanitarian coordinator for East Timor,
has handled emergency relief in Sudan, Angola and Turkey. By no
means is Timor the most difficult operation he he has participated
in, he said, but it would certainly be easier if it were safe to
traverse the territory, something that most observers said cannot
happen until peacekeepers fan out to protect vast areas of deserted
wasteland and flush out militias _ or until the last Indonesian
troops leave.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that may take a while. Until then, people remain hungry and
need shelter, Mountain said. ``We can't sit still til all this is
sorted out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
