<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2039 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-McNASTY-HNS &LR;      09-30 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-McNASTY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 UPN SHOW IS `McNASTY' TO THE CORE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unless you're male, 21 or younger, wearing a baseball cap,
listening to hip-hop while simultaneously playing Sega Dreamcast
and _ here's the key _ fully, ragingly, perpetually aroused, then
there's no need for you to read any further.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you may get some joy out of an attempt to dissect
``Shasta McNasty,'' the new UPN offering that was the critical
odds-on favorite for worst show of the season and possibly ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shasta McNasty'' (Thursdays, 9:30 p.m. Eastern) is a neutron
bomb of immense proportions. You're stunned into stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps it's too easy to just trounce ``Shasta McNasty.'' To
say that this is no ``ER'' is to master the obvious (though ``ER''
in its own way is formulaic and tedious and probably bores young
males witless). UPN couldn't dumb down ``Shasta McNasty'' to any
greater degree.
</P>
<P>
   UPN is going after young males. While The WB is going after
young women and has, successfully, used that strategy to gain a
niche in the competitive world of network television, UPN only this
season has attempted to get the guys. The network put two hours of
wrestling on Thursday night, has loaded up with a bunch of
action-adventure shows and some sci-fi material, and now enters the
comedy arena with a show so dumb, so low-brow that, if you compare
it to just about anything else, is shocking in its lameness.
</P>
<P>
   That's really the point of ``Shasta McNasty.'' It's a comedy for
young guys, the people who loved ``Dumb and Dumber'' and others
like it. Dean Valentine, the president and chief executive of UPN,
believes that there's a market for the kind of humor that runs
through ``There's Something About Mary'' _ and he's right. (But
this show has nowhere near the, uh, sophistication of that movie _
which was able to attract all kinds of viewers.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Shasta McNasty'' centers on three slackers _ two of them white
_ who are in a fledgling hip-hop group. They are Scott (Carmine
Giovinazzo), who at least tries to have a conscience; Dennis (Jake
Busey, son of Gary Busey); and Randy (Dale Godboldo).
</P>
<P>
   The premise is that these guys pal around, do dumb guy things
all the time, refuse to mature even an inch, and scramble to get
money so they can continue their lifestyle, which apparently
involves drinking, cruising for chicks and playing music (the dream
scenario for the target demographic, naturally).
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, called ``Little Dude,'' featured Verne Troyer, best
known as ``Mini-Me'' in the ``Austin Powers'' movie sequel. As you
might well guess, the midget jokes go off like fireworks _ up to
and including an actual dwarf-bowling scene.
</P>
<P>
   Troyer seems more than game to be made fun of, but also embraced
by the goofy guys (after much slapstick comedy, some swearing and
an instance where he bites Scott's girlfriend on the butt).
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Gary Coleman make a cameo, to continue the short
jokes, but Heather Kozar, a former Playmate of the Year, also has a
few lines, right after the close-up of her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   You know where ``Shasta McNasty'' is setting the bar, right? But
the fact that it shows no embarrassment, no shame in this approach
(after dwarf-bashing, plus some racist and sexist jokes, the show
has a kind of fearless we'll-do-anything moxie), is oddly
refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's network is becoming the best untold story of the new
season, as it rebounds from disastrous ratings and is beginning to
punch the shoulder of its rival, The WB, really hard. ``Dawson's
Creek'' and ``Felicity'' may have snagged the magazine covers and
hype not long ago, but wrestling, cheap action and stupidity may
ultimately be just as profitable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
