 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, Oct. 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE (Tokyo) _ Developing: A leak at a nuclear plant in
Tokaimura, 75 miles northeast of Tokyo, has put three workers in
the hospital, and required the evacuation of hundreds of people
living nearby. An emergency Cabinet meeting was called. By Howard
W. French.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA ANNIVERSARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ANNIVERSARY (Beijing) _ The PRC celebrates its 50th
anniversary. By Seth Faison. (The ceremonies in Beijing start at 10
p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ASSESS (Beijing) _ A news analysis on 50 years of
communism in China. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-REVOLUTION (Undated) _ Recalling the Communists' entry
into Nanjing in 1949. By Seymour Topping.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-GUERRILLAS (Dili, East Timor) _ After 24 years in the
hills, some pro-independence Timorese guerrillas come down and
visit the capital. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA (Jakarta) _ Developments: U.S. Defense Secretary Cohen
visits, rioters attack the Australian Embassy, the Indonesian
parliament will open on Friday. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MASSACRE (Washington) _ Folo on the story of a massacre of
Korean civilians by U.S. soldiers at the beginning of the Korean
War. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CAUCASUS (Moscow) _ Caucasus developments: Russian troop
incursions into Chechnya are reported.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS (Belgrade) _ A day after police forcibly
prevented opposition groups from marching on President Milosevic's
house, they plan to try again. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIAN-FACTION (Jericho, West Bank) _ Mustafa Zibri, a
leader of what has been a radical anti-peace Palestinian group
returns to the West Bank for first time in 30 years. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NOBEL-GRASS (Undated) _ Gunter Grass wins the Nobel Prize for
Literature. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebars as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on the spending
bills, as the fiscal sands run out. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BUDGET (Washington) _ President Clinton talks about
budget matters at noon. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-INCOME (Washington) _ The Census Bureau releases its
annual estimate of Americans' income and how many people live in
poverty. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-ISRAEL (Undated) _ Dozens of Jewish leaders view and
react to the Disney exhibit on Israel in Florida. By Gustav Nebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FUNDRAISING-REPORT (Washington) _ Wrapping up the third quarter
fund-raising figures for the presidential candidates. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Datelne to kum, N.Y.) _ With Al Gore on the first
day of his new campaign. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BEATTY-SCENE (Los Angeles) _ Imagine a political convention
merging with a celebrity roast. That pretty much describes the
scene as Warren Beatty discussed politics before a star-studded
crowd in Hollywood. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
