<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2079 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-HAITI-COFFEE-ART-$ADV     09-30 1480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-COFFEE-ART-$ADV3-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING COFFEE TO U.S. MAY GIVE HAITIAN FARMERS A CHANCE TO EASE
THEIR PLIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 3.) 
(Eds.: Graphic available onNYT database) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAP ROUGE, Haiti _ As some foreign-aid officials tell it, people
like Orguste Boniface may hold the key to solving Haiti's perpetual
poverty puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   A small-boned man with calloused hands and a deferential manner,
Boniface grows coffee and a few food crops on a couple of lush
acres atop the low mountains of southern Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Haitians, the fiftyish Boniface has been farming his
whole life. And, like most, he's never earned more than not nearly
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to work hard and produce the coffee, but it's not
really a good business,'' Boniface says. ``There are more workers
than land. Nobody has a chance to get ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, aid planners bankrolled by the U.S. government are betting
that helping Boniface and his neighbors sell their best coffee
directly to American buyers will put more cash in the farmers'
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   The extra money, the foreign planners say, will allow Haitian
farmers to hold on to their land. In doing so, the cash may give
this stricken country its best, perhaps last, shot at staying
afloat in an increasingly market-driven world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do nothing but charity, you aren't going to achieve
anything,'' says Zach Lea, an Auburn University agricultural
economist who is helping to develop the direct-selling program for
Haitian coffee. ``There has got to be some blending between pure
economic profit and some sort of charitable work.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems worth a try. Few other schemes in the past half-century
have pulled Haiti's countryside from its deep morass.
</P>
<P>
   Rural Haitians, appallingly poor, struggle with a shrinking
amount of available land, with severe erosion and with a government
that always has taken far more than it has given back.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of people have fled to the cities,
overwhelming urban planners and swamping labor markets. Rural
Haiti's torment has fed its urban ruin.
</P>
<P>
   The peasants who stay clear the steep mountainsides and plant
beans, corn and other crops. Most of the food is eaten by the
farmers' families, the rest sold to Haiti's hungry cities.
</P>
<P>
   But the thin soil wears out. Crops start failing. And with much
of their natural brush scraped away, there's nothing left to brace
the slopes against the seasonal rains.
</P>
<P>
   Gravity pulls at Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, foreign-aid agencies have tried to stop the erosion
by paying local farmers to plant millions of trees. But before the
trees grew very tall, cash-starved peasants cut them down,
rendering the timber into charcoal for sale in Port-au-Prince and
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   The more trees that were planted, the more that were chopped
away.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, foreign-funded agencies contracted local people to
dig irrigation canals, to terrace mountainsides and to plant
hedge-rows to stop the decay. But, unconvinced of the projects'
purposes, farmers worked only as long as they were paid. Things
fell apart when funding stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lea and other planners say markets can succeed where aid
long has failed.
</P>
<P>
   Better prices will encourage peasants to plant and maintain
coffee bushes and cacao trees, they say. More trees and bushes will
keep the topsoil on the mountains. Increasing income will allow
rural families to better educate their children. An educated
population can generate prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm betting is that if I change the price of coffee,
people will go out and try to produce more,'' Lea says. ``If we
change the price 20 or 30 percent, people start becoming more
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   There are problems, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The local leaders of the peasant coffee associations that market
the product have sometimes simply replaced the Port-au-Prince
businessmen who brokered coffee exports, keeping the lion's share
of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee is a commodity, subject to wild swings in price.
International coffee prices have been sinking for years, and
profitable markets for even the best quality coffee can be
difficult to find.
</P>
<P>
   There is still too little technical advice to farmers about how
to treat diseases that attack the coffee shrubs and how to improve
the quality of the coffee beans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lea and other proponents say, direct selling already has
significantly boosted the incomes of mango and cacao growers
elsewhere in Haiti. They say the model can work for the coffee
farmers as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmers have to change the way they harvest, and cooperatives
have to be set up differently,'' Lea says. ``Haitian coffee will be
a much larger success story in the future, a true success story.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics say that focusing on export markets, instead of
trying to provide enough food for Haiti to be self-sufficient, has
created more problems than it has solved.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Development GAP, a Washington think tank that studies
the negative effects of the global economy on developing countries,
found that dropping tariffs and other barriers has increased
Haiti's dependency on imported food.
</P>
<P>
   In only a decade, for example, Haiti has gone from growing
nearly all the rice it consumed to importing half of its needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Development aid has been too focused on an export-led model of
development and that has never been appropriate for Haiti,'' says
Lisa McGowan, a Washington, D.C., economist who has worked on
Haitian economic development issues since 1983 and who wrote the
Development GAP report.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't depend upon someone else to feed you,'' McGowan
says. ``It is a recipe for disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Orguste Boniface and his neighbors in the village of Cap Rouge
were among the first Haitian farmers to participate in direct
export of coffee, and they acknowledge that the plan has brought
them a little extra income. Families have a little more food, the
farmers say. And a few more local children have been able to go to
high school in nearby towns. But the farmers say the extra money,
so far, has been far from their salvation.
</P>
<P>
   A miles-long string of small houses, well tended fields and
family graveyards, Cap Rouge hangs like a necklace on the ridgeline
above Jacmel, a picturesque town on Haiti's Caribbean coast.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with much of blighted Haiti, Cap Rouge seems blessed.
Rain-fed fields boast dark loam and verdant crops. Most houses are
well-kept and gaily painted. Residents travel part of the year to
jobs in Jacmel and elsewhere to boost their families' incomes.
</P>
<P>
   But Cap Rouge is crowded, with every house seemingly bursting
with children. Almost every piece of available land, even the
rockiest and steepest hillsides, has been planted with something,
attesting to the lack of fields.
</P>
<P>
   Like those across Haiti, many people from Cap Rouge still slip
illegally into the Dominican Republic to find work in the fields
and construction sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the Dominican Republic we would be dead,'' says Lundi
Morila, 61, who served as the senior government authority in Cap
Rouge under past dictatorships.
</P>
<P>
   Other farmers have moved away to Jacmel or Port-au-Prince, where
work is scarce and finding food is a daunting expense.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers remain as suspicious of direct-selling schemes as
they are of most everything else. Long decades of being cheated _
or thinking they were cheated _ by better-educated and wealthier
people from the cities have made the farmers look askance at anyone
offering to improve their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say all the money goes to the poor, but the poor never
see it,'' says Jean Baptist Lesciant, a member of one of the Cap
Rouge coffee growers associations. ``When they send money, the
people in the city keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cap Rouge so far has been spared the erosion that has destroyed
much of the Haitian countryside. But nearby valleys along the
highway that cuts north from Jacmel to Port-au-Prince already have
been denuded. Some Cap Rouge farmers say those valleys foretell
their village's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years from now this will be all desert,'' Morila says as
he glances at the fruit trees and bean plants that lick the edges
of Cap Rouge. ``To make Haiti better you have to make work for
people. We need some kind of industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Orguste Boniface shares three small houses in Cap Rouge with his
wife, many of their 10 children and several grandchildren _ 20
people in all. The family survives on what it can grow on the few
hilly acres surrounding their houses. And things get tighter with
each new mouth to feed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no clinics, no stores, no help,'' says Boniface's
wife, Civilizae, as she surveys the reddish-brown sprinkle of
coffee beans drying on the concrete patio in front of her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``This life is miserable,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
