<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2098 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-HAITI-AID-ART-2TAKES-     09-30 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITI-AID-ART-2TAKES-$ADV3-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE DECADES OF AID, HAITI STILL DESPERATELY POOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 3) 
(Eds.: Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti _ The crowd forms early each morning in
front of a small hospital along the road that climbs from the
simmering squalor of Haiti's capital to the cool heights where its
wealthy few live.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people come for free medicines they could never
afford, to treat the stomach ailments and lung diseases that plague
the poor everywhere. Others bring emaciated toddlers for emergency
care, the clinic's paid Haitian staff and foreign volunteers all
that stand between the babies and the grave.
</P>
<P>
   Run by the Roman Catholic Church, the hospital was founded more
than a dozen years ago to care for severely malnourished children
brought to an orphanage farther up the mountain. Soon, ragged
people from across Port-au-Prince were coming for free medical
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since the hospital opened, Haiti has ricocheted
between heavy-handed dictatorship and half-hearted democracy.
Foreigners have spent enormous sums to relieve the country's raw
poverty. Roads have been built, free meals handed out, development
schemes launched.
</P>
<P>
   None of it has mattered to the hospital or to the people who
depend upon it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really hasn't been much of a difference at all in terms
of malnourishment and other health problems,'' says Rick Frechette,
a 46-year-old priest and physician from Connecticut who has worked
at the hospital since it opened. ``How do you have development when
most people don't work? People need jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, foreign governments, aid agencies and lenders like
the World Bank have poured billions of dollars into this country,
trying to fix what they think is broken. And for decades, those
efforts have come up pitifully short. Now, five years after a U.S.
invasion reinstalled elected civilian rule, Haiti still struggles
for its footing.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than push this nation of 8 million toward prosperity,
many say, the aid has served merely to soothe foreign consciences.
While softening the social and political impact of Haiti's
destitution, it has converted many people into charity cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``International aid for the past 40 years has failed,'' says
economist Kesner Pharel, a former Haitian central bank official who
now owns a private consulting firm. ``People are living the same
way they always have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having someone in the hospital,'' Pharel says. ``You
try to make them comfortable until they die, but they will never
leave the ward.''
</P>
<P>
   Ragged and rancorous, Haiti points to the failure of
international aid to better the lives of the Earth's poorest in an
age driven by free trade and market capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   With its economic policies engineered by foreign technocrats,
Haiti finds itself unable to compete in the global economy,
incapable of feeding and caring for itself. Aid, some critics say,
merely softens the blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Development schemes in Haiti have never responded to the needs
of the Haitian people,'' says Lisa McGowan, a Washington, D.C.,
labor economist and consultant who has 17 years' experience with
Haitian poverty. ``It's not that they are putting money into a
hopeless situation. It's that they are the ones calling the shots,
and the shots they are calling are not working.''
</P>
<P>
   International aid's failure in Haiti comes as budgets for
development and relief are being slashed in Washington and other
world capitals and as liberals and conservatives grow increasingly
critical of the aid industry.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 1,000 foreign and Haitian aid agencies and
development groups work in the country, supported by foreign
governments, private foundations or Christian churches.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government has been spending about $100 million a year
in Haiti since 1994. Canada, France and other countries also send
tens of millions of dollars in help. The bulk of the U.S. aid comes
in the form of free food distributed as meals at schools or sold in
Haitian markets to fund other development projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're spending a lot of money, but things are getting
worse,'' says Michelle Carter, an official in Port-au-Prince with
CARE, the big U.S-funded aid agency that has been working in Haiti
since 1959. ``It seems like the needs have increased and people's
expectations have increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unstable situation,'' she says. ``To expect aid
agencies to generate a better standard of living is unfair. It goes
beyond aid agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, things would be even more dire without the foreign
help. Aid has helped rebuild some of the country's roads and
utilities. It has financed government administration and children's
educations, and it has helped keep the poorest Haitians alive.
</P>
<P>
   But it also has spawned corruption, enabled inept rulers to
maintain power and prevented Haitians from taking control of their
own destinies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of all the aid in Haiti, there is such a dependency
culture that efforts in development are thwarted by attitudes,''
says Leanne Geisterfer, who works in Haiti for the development
agency of the Christian Reformed Church, based in Grand Rapids,
Mich. ``There are little pockets of hope, but the overwhelming
attitude is, `What are you going to do for us?'
</P>
<P>
   ``From a development perspective,'' she says, ``that is a
killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Haiti remains the poorest country in the hemisphere. Destitute
Honduras appears decidedly well off in comparison. Mexico, with its
millions of people in bitter need and its yawning gaps between rich
and poor, seems wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 80 percent of rural Haitians live in poverty,
defined by aid experts as having to spend more than three-fourths
of their income to eat each day.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, unemployment hovers near 70 percent, although many
Haitians make livings as street vendors or doing other such
``informal'' labor. A good job pays about $2 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Per capita income here stands at about $250, far below 30 years
ago, less than a tenth of that of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy is 55 years, about 20 years less than in the
United States and many Latin American countries. More than half of
Haiti's people cannot read or write.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti already ranks among the world's most crowded countries.
Its population is expected to double to 16 million in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at our worst. We cannot go lower than where we are,''
says Jean Claude Cerin, the 42-year-old Haitian director of the
Mennonite Economic Development Agency, a U.S. organization that
provides small loans to Haitian farmers and merchants. ``We have to
do something as a nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We either will get our act together, or the country ends up
being a protectorate of the international community,'' says Cerin,
who earned a master's degree in the United States in developmental
economics.
</P>
<P>
   Like other experts here, Cerin blames Haiti's perpetual crisis
on the country's failed politics, on an economic system that favors
a minuscule elite and on ill-conceived foreign schemes that he says
have tended to create dependency rather than promote
self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are shortcomings on both sides,'' Cerin says. ``They
come together and really create quite a chaotic situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaos rules Port-au-Prince, the once charming port city that has
become a teeming warren of the dispossessed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traffic chokes the crumbling streets. The luxury cars and sport
utility vehicles of foreign-aid workers and Haiti's rich navigate a
sea of jalopies.
</P>
<P>
   Electricity blacks out frequently, staying off for hours. Phone
service is a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Most people in the capital spend their days buying and selling
whatever they can. Vendors line every thoroughfare, offering
everything from fruit to engine oil, from clothes and art work to
electronic gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   Beggars throng intersections and the entryways of office
buildings. Armed assailants sometime attack motorists snared by the
traffic. Shootings are common.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the poor dress in second-hand clothes donated to U.S.
charities, then sold to brokers and shipped here for resale.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone suffers. Haiti's old-money families thrive. And the
burgeoning narcotics trade pumps new wealth into the country, which
has become a way station on the cocaine trail. Haitians living in
the United States and elsewhere send as much as $800 million home,
economists say. Some of that money has financed new houses and
small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Mansions rise in the wealthy mountainside neighborhoods above
the Haitian capital. Other new luxury homes go up near the airport
on the northern fringe of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked behind high walls, the offices of the more prominent
private-aid agencies pepper the well-to-do neighborhoods of the
capital. Suspicious guards keep out the uninvited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they send a lot of help to Haiti, but it stays in the
city,'' says Jean Bonnet, a coffee farmer near the Caribbean coast
south of Port-au-Prince. ``People just put it in Swiss banks.''
</P>
<P>
   With few large successes to brag about, foreign-aid officials
point to projects like a recently improved two-lane highway that
runs along the shore west of Port-au-Prince and over the mountains
to the Caribbean coast town of Jacmel, which planners hope will
become a tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
   But good roads have been built here before. Most have
deteriorated because of the region's torrential rains and a lack of
repair well before the loans to build them have been repaid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem in Haiti is not a question of building roads but
of maintaining them,'' Pharel says.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti's biggest hurdle remains political. The country grapples
with the legacy of the 28-year, U.S.-backed dictatorship of the
Duvalier family, which ended in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   A series of inept and short-lived military rulers replaced the
Duvaliers. The generals yielded briefly in 1991 to the popularly
elected government of Jean Bertrand Aristide, a Roman Catholic
priest, and then reclaimed power in a coup seven months later.
</P>
<P>
   Aristide had been elected president on the promise of bringing
sweeping change that would benefit Haiti's poor. Although restored
to office by the U.S. invasion, he never regained the political
momentum he needed to carry out his plans. The grass-roots movement
that supported Aristide disintegrated over the past five years.
Former allies became fierce rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his waning popularity and fractured political movement,
Aristide is expected to retake the presidency in elections late
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the funding promised by the World Bank and other lenders
following Aristide's return in October 1994 has been held up by
lack of approval from the Haitian Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Long too combative to agree on the projects or much of anything
else, the Parliament was disbanded last January by President Rene
Preval, who succeeded Aristide in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
   New parliamentary elections, in which some 60 political parties
may field candidates, are scheduled for late November. But only 5
percent of those eligible cast ballots in the April 1997 vote. A
high-level Haitian commission later found those elections to be
riddled with fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many humanitarian aid organizations, both government
and private, devoted money to short-term projects and giveaways.
The various aid groups have not coordinated many projects,
according to a recent U.N. report, and have done little to plan
strategy with Haitian officials.
</P>
<P>
   Aid groups, critics say, often have focused more on meeting the
requirements set by donors than on worrying about the long-term
effects of their own projects.
</P>
<P>
   Haitians have been paid to make improvements in their own
communities without being convinced of the need for them. Some aid
workers say that when a project's funding runs out, villagers allow
the improvements to decay. This process, they say, has been
repeated year after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing here is providing emergency assistance even
though the emergency is no longer on CNN,'' says Chris Hennemeyer,
the country's representative of Catholic Relief Services, whose aid
program in Haiti mostly consists of distributing U.S. government
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of foreign aid coming in here now is not going to
change things,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists say Haiti's future depends on urban industry
aimed at exporting goods. Low-wage labor is about all this country
has to offer, they say.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a buyer's market in cheap labor these days. And
Haiti competes with countries throughout Latin America and Asia
where phones work, electricity stays turned on and politics remain
relatively stable.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti needs nearly 2 million jobs, economists say. But the
country's assembly industry, which at its height employed just
60,000, was gutted by the U.S.-engineered economic embargo aimed at
ousting the military junta in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti's factories, many of which assemble clothing and other
goods for sale in the United States, have recovered slightly in
recent years. Still, industrial employment remains barely half what
it was before the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   An industrial future for Haiti, if it happens at all, will be a
long time coming.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, something must be done about the rural poor,
aid workers say.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger, overcrowding and a badly deteriorating environment
continue to drive many thousands from the land.
</P>
<P>
   Some have taken to open boats, trying to sail to better lives in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Others have slipped across the border into the Dominican
Republic in search of low-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Still others have poured into Port-au-Prince and smaller cities,
scratching for work where little is to be had.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Port-au-Prince, many find surviving from day to day as
difficult as raising a crop in the depleted soil.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most desperate of them eventually show up at the
front door of the small hospital that the Rev. Rick Frechette runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the root of the problem is that Haiti has never
been cut into the world economy,'' the priest says. ``People need
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
