<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CHRONO-1001-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILEPOSTS IN 50 YEARS OF DIZZYING CHANGE IN CHINA
 &HT;    With CHINA-CELEBRATE-1001.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Here is a capsule of Communist China's last 50 years:
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 1, 1949 _ Communist guerrilla leader Mao Tse-tung declares
the founding of the People's Republic of China after driving Chiang
Kai-shek's Nationalist armies to exile on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   1950-53 _ Chinese troops fight to a bloody stalemate against
U.S.-led United Nations forces in the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Late 1953 _ Mao launches China's first Five-Year Plan, aiming to
yank China into the industrial age using Stalin's model.
</P>
<P>
   May-July 1957 _ Mao signals a reform period, saying, ``Let 100
flowers bloom.'' Chinese intellectuals respond with a burst of
grievances, but Mao soon reverses direction and tens of thousands
are sent to labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   1958 _ Mao launches the ``Great Leap Forward,'' aiming to
multiply China's strength by spreading small-scale mines, mills and
factories throughout the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   March 1959 _ Chinese troops smash a rebellion in Tibet, forcing
Tibetan spiritual leader the Dalai Lama to flee to exile in India.
</P>
<P>
   1959-60 _ Caught up in ``Great Leap'' hysteria, peasants fail to
harvest crops. Food production falls disastrously, leading to a
famine that killed an estimated 30 million Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   1960 _ Moscow orders thousands of Soviet technicians out of
China, as China and the USSR break apart over Soviet criticisms of
the ``Great Leap.''
</P>
<P>
   October 16, 1964 _ China explodes its first atomic bomb in the
Lop Nor desert of western China.
</P>
<P>
   1966 _ Mao unleashes the ``Great Proletarian Cultural
Revolution,'' a chaotic decade when some 10 million radical teenage
``Red Guards'' destroy cultural relics, burn books and accuse their
elders of treason. Millions of intellectuals are ``sent down'' to
the countryside for ``re-education.''
</P>
<P>
   February 1972 _ President Richard Nixon visits China and agrees
to ``normalization'' of relations between the U.S. and China. The
two countries agree that ``Taiwan is a part of China.''
</P>
<P>
   July 28, 1976 _ The world's worst earthquake in modern times
devastates Tangshan in northern China, killing 240,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 9, 1976 _ Mao dies at the age of 83, and the Cultural
Revolution soon ends.
</P>
<P>
   1978 _ New Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping launches China's
two-decade spurt of economic growth by loosening communist-style
controls and encouraging Western investment.
</P>
<P>
   September 1980 _ China adopts ``one-child policy.''
</P>
<P>
   June 4, 1989 _ About 500 to 1,000 pro-democracy supporters are
killed in Beijing when student protests in and near Tiananmen
Square are crushed by Chinese tanks.
</P>
<P>
   1995-1996 _ China raises war fears by firing missiles into the
sea off Taiwan during war games before Taiwan's first presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   July 1, 1997 _ After a century and a half of British colonial
rule, Hong Kong returns to Chinese sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   May 7, 1999 _ NATO jets bomb the Chinese embassy in Belgrade,
touching off huge anti-American protests in China.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
