<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2127 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN     09-30 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTY PYTHON BROKE ALL THE RULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Thirty years ago, the Beatles _ who helped turn
Western culture inside out _ were breaking up, but another bunch of
British naughty boys were just getting a forum to thumb their
collective noses at, well, just about everyone.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 5, 1969, ``Monty Python's Flying Circus'' debuted on the
British Broadcasting Corp., and the world of comedy hasn't been the
same. Irreverent, innovative and intelligent, Monty Python's humor
was as surreal as it was broad. Sketches were often an unlikely
combination of ``Alice in Wonderland'' meets British music-hall
bawdiness, with the line ``and now for something completely
different'' meaning the lads repeating the same sketch over again.
</P>
<P>
   The series ran until 1973, and while it's been available on
video, A&AMP;E is beginning to release it on DVD, with some bonuses.
(Columbia recently put out ``Monty Python and the Holy Grail'' on
DVD for $24.99). The series comes in a two-disc packet ($24.99)
with three episodes on each disc, which have added material like
clips from their 1982 Hollywood Bowl appearance and bios of the
boys. There are four sets from the first season.
</P>
<P>
   Consisting of John Cleese, Eric Idle, Michael Palin, Terry
Jones, Terry Gilliam and the late Graham Chapman, the boys didn't
even have a name when they were conceiving the show, but their
zaniness resulted in a BBC executive referring to them as a
``flying circus.'' No one seems to remember who came up with Monty
Python, but Palin had suggested Gwen Dibley's Flying Circus from a
name he found in the paper. Luckily it didn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   Once on the air, Monty Python quickly established, as one writer
put it, ``a state of mind.'' The absurd was normal, normal was
absurd. In a famous early sketch called ``The Funniest Joke in the
World,'' a comedy writer conceives the world's funniest joke and
dies laughing. The scene quickly segues to a breathless reporter
covering the action as a policeman tries to remove the deadly joke
from the writer's house as if it were a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The scene quickly shifts again as the joke somehow becomes part
of the Allied effort to defeat the Germans. Hitler is shown telling
a joke (not really, of course) as the Germans try to develop their
own deadly joke. Soon, Allied troops are running through woods,
shouting out the joke in German (so they are unaffected), as Nazi
troops fall like flies. All this in about four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If the Pythons were afraid to poke fun at sacred cows, they
weren't afraid to put their Oxford educations (not all of them) to
use, either. Who else would have Cardinal Richelieu, chief adviser
to France's Louis XIII, as a character in a skit. Well, actually it
isn't the cardinal but a Richelieu impersonator, but you get the
idea of silliness. Then again they had Mozart hosting a program on
famous death scenes and Picasso painting during a bicycle race.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Holy Grail,'' the lads skewer _ or is it lance? _ the
Arthurian legend as the knights pretend to ride through the kingdom
while their servants follow behind smacking two coconuts together
to simulate hoofbeats.
</P>
<P>
   If their lunacy wasn't always brilliant, it was always inspired,
and their influence on comedy is incalculable. What the Pythons did
was help rewrite the rules _ jokes didn't need punch lines,
sketches didn't need endings, and if the confines of traditional
humor boxed them in, they just destroyed the box.
</P>
<P>
   There is a blurb on the series cover that probably wasn't
written by one of the Pythons: ``Now in glorious digital DVD format
so that you, the digital aficionado, can enjoy the original
scratches, pops and hisses with crystal clarity.'' It's a bit of
irony that the boys would appreciate. Nevertheless, in another
irony, they do look great on DVD. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2132 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-BLUEMOUNDS03-C     09-30 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BLUEMOUNDS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protected area of Minnesota, Blue Mounds a beautiful reminder of
what used to be
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday Oct. 3.
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUVERNE, Minn. _ As the last bit of sunlight faded behind the
wooded hillock that hid our Blue Mounds State Park campsite, my
husband and I floated up to our necks in a little lake on the edge
of the prairie.
</P>
<P>
   The whir of the insects, the breeze rustling through the tall
grasses, even the roaring of bullfrogs, sounded only slightly
exotic to our Georgia ears. But the sudden howling and yipping of
nearby coyotes, followed by the bellow of a startled bison _ a
member of the park's herd _ left us with no doubt that we were a
long way from home.
</P>
<P>
   Sod busters who passed this way more than a hundred years ago
must have heard many of the same sounds. But at that time a sea of
grass stretched unbroken from Canada to Texas, sustaining vast
herds of bison and other wildlife. Today, pieces of the prairie
remain only in parks and preserves _ protected areas, like Blue
Mounds, in the extreme southwestern corner of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Mounds' 1,500 acres offer visitors a pioneer vision of
natural beauty _ wildflowers, cliff swallows and dickcissels,
bison, head-high teasel and big bluestem. The park itself is well
above the level of the adjacent farmland. Open year-round for
camping, the property boasts miles of trails, lakes for swimming
and fishing, and quiet places for repose and daydreaming.
</P>
<P>
   The morning after our swim, we rose at dawn and hiked the Upper
Mound Trail, which leads out onto a gently rising tall-grass
prairie. All around us the grass and wildflowers were high, almost
impassable, undulating in the wind. The views of the surrounding
farmland were distant and wide.
</P>
<P>
   At one point an entire flock of larkspurs shot up from the
brush, right beside the path. A couple of miles from the trail
head, the path approached the sheer cliffs on the park's eastern
side. Standing atop them, with our backs to the scenery of a time
gone by, we gazed out across the beautiful geometry of a vast,
cultivated plain.
</P>
<P>
   The cliffs are composed of glossy pink Sioux quartzite and are a
popular destination for rock climbers. Viewed through the haze of
distance by early settlers, the 80-foot-high outcrops looked blue
on the horizon. Thus, pink cliffs were dubbed ``Blue Mounds,''
despite a glaring chromatic discrepancy.
</P>
<P>
   This beautiful planar quartzite crops out, not only in the
vicinity of the cliffs, but also at unexpected places all over the
park. Metamorphosed from sandstone, it is ancient, about 1.5
billion years old. The presence of iron oxide tints the rocks pink
and purple.
</P>
<P>
   Farther along the trail we came to the Rock Alignment, a
mysterious, 1,250-foot-long line of rocks at the southern end of
the park. It was built by prehistoric peoples; its purpose remains
unknown. Observers have noticed, however, that on the first days of
spring and autumn, sunrise and sunset line up precisely with this
cryptic strip of stone.
</P>
<P>
   After our hike we packed up our camping equipment, hopped in the
car and drove to nearby downtown Luverne. There we sought out the
Koffee Haus on Main Street, a local hangout we heartily recommend
(507-283-8676). It has delicious pastries, breads and other light
fare, plus a variety of beverages in addition to coffee. The prices
are cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street is the Brandenburg Gallery (507-283-1884), which
features the work of National Geographic photographer Jim
Brandenburg, a Luverne native. Wander in for a look at his nature
photos, many of them featuring the Great Plains. You can buy
prints, framed or not, right off the wall.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Blue Mounds State Park has 73 tent and RV sites, 40 with
electrical hookups, near bathrooms and showers. The 14 walk-in
campsites _ carts are provided for transporting your gear _ are
private and primitive, with no water or electricity nearby, and no
shower in the bathroom (showers are a long walk or a short drive
away). The park also has a swimming beach, a lake, a playground for
children, and 13 miles of hiking trails. Near the south end of the
park is an interpretive center; the entrance is farther north.
</P>
<P>
   Take I-90 to Luverne, Minn. Blue Mounds State Park is a few
miles north of town on U.S. 75.
</P>
<P>
   The park is open year-round for primitive camping, but park
staff turn off the showers when the temperature begins to drop. One
year, the shower cutoff date was in January; another year, it was
in October. The park entrance fee is $4 per car. It's $8 per day to
camp in a primitive site, while the developed ones cost $12 per
day, plus $2.50 for electricity. For more information: 508-283-1307
or www.dnr.state.mn.us/parksandrecreation/stateparks/.
</P>
<P>
   With 4,700 residents, the nearby town of Luverne offers some
pleasant amenities. The town has five motels, including the locally
owned Cozy Rest (1-800-839-1375) and the Comfort Inn
(1-800-228-5150). The Magnolia Steakhouse, near I-90 and U.S. 75,
offers steaks and seafood (507-283-9161), and the Blue Mound Inn
(507-283-2718), on U.S. 75 on the way to the park, features a
hearty smorgasbord. For more information, contact the Luverne
Chamber of Commerce: 1-888-283-4061 or www.luvernemn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca McCarthy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1500EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2133 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-LEAFSPOTS03-CO     09-30 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LEAFSPOTS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tool around the South for a blazingly good fix of gorgeous fall
color
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The temperatures are dipping. The days are shortening. And the
trees are getting ready for their closeup.
</P>
<P>
   Every fall, the leaves put on their colorful pageant, and
Atlantans flock to sites where the show is the most dramatic. Sure,
we can all watch the colors change in our own back yards, through a
film of local smog. But _ call us crazy _ many of us would rather
take in this annual spectacle at some place like North Carolina's
Grandfather Mountain, bundled up against a chilly October breeze,
surveying the brilliant, multihued patchwork for miles around.
</P>
<P>
   Because of an unusually dry summer, the trees in some Southern
states may experience earlier-than-normal color change, according
to the U.S. Forest Service. Last week, the poplars, sourwoods and
sumacs were just beginning to turn in North Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   At least one leaf expert says the drought will cause greater
vividness in some areas. Western Carolina University biology
professor J. Dan Pittillo, who has observed color patterns in North
Carolina for years, predicts brilliant hues in the state's central
Piedmont area and good color in the mountains. (Last year, the leaf
season in western North Carolina peaked around Oct. 20.)
</P>
<P>
   Below are some places around the South where you can get your
fall color fix. For regular fall color updates, call the U.S.
Forest Service at 1-800-354-4595 or visit
www.fs.fed.us/news/fall.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE RIDGE PARKWAY
</P>
<P>
   This 469-mile mountain thoroughfare, stretching from
Waynesville, N.C., to Waynesboro, Va., offers some of the best fall
foliage views in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf peepers will want to stop at the Cumberland Knob Recreation
Area, 18 miles south of Sparta, N.C. Pack a picnic lunch and head
for the 2,885-foot summit of Cumberland Knob, with open areas that
offer impressive vistas. Motor a few miles north to Doughton Park,
where, at the Wildcat Rocks overlook, you can gaze 1,500 feet
straight down to Basin Cove.
</P>
<P>
   Another hot fall color spot is Grandfather Mountain, one mile
off the parkway on U.S. 221 near Linville, N.C. Take the mile-high
swinging bridge that leads to the summit (5,964 feet above sea
level) or hike along 12 miles of trails shrouded in clouds. Be on
the lookout for bears, panthers, deer and eagles amid the dazzling
quilt of reds, yellows and oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Ridge Parkway information: 828-298-0398 or www.nps
</P>
<P>
   .gov/blri.
</P>
<P>
   If you're making the drive in late October, be sure to drop by
the Craft Fair of the Southern Highlands, Oct. 21-24 in Asheville.
The semiannual event features fine crafts for sale, demonstrations
and entertainment including traditional mountain music and
storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   CHEROHALA SKYWAY
</P>
<P>
   This 51-mile roadway winds through the Unicoi Mountains from
Tellico Plains, Tenn., to Robbinsville, N.C. Great views can be
found at Turkey Creek Overlook, 15 miles east of Tellico Plains,
and Unicoi Crest Overlook near the Tennessee-North Carolina line.
</P>
<P>
   On the North Carolina side, the road begins a steep descent into
the Santeetlah Creek Valley, revealing a breathtaking view of the
heavily wooded Santeetlah Creek Gorge, with the Smoky Mountains
looming in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-800-245-5428 in Tennessee; 1-800-470-3790 in
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   CHEROKEE FOOTHILLS
</P>
<P>
   SCENIC HIGHWAY
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeous vistas and historic sites dot this 130-mile route
through the foothills of the Blue Ridge Mountains in the
northwestern corner of South Carolina. Avid hikers should schedule
a stop at Table Rock State Park north of Pickens. It's a difficult
five-mile trek to the summit of Table Rock Mountain, but the view
from atop the mountain's sheer cliffs always draws raves.
</P>
<P>
   Also visit Caesars Head State Park, where you can pick up the 4
1/2-mile trail to Raven Cliff Falls, the Southeast's second-highest
waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 1-800-849-4766.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHEAST ALABAMA
</P>
<P>
   A drive along the Lookout Mountain Parkway north of Gadsden
should give leaf lovers plenty to gawk at. Make your way to DeSoto
State Park, set on 5,067 wooded acres along Little River Canyon.
Forty miles of scenic roadway wind through the park; stop at DeSoto
Falls and drink in the majestic rush of a 100-foot waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   From the parkway, take the 22-mile scenic route along Canyon
River Drive. The road follows the edge of the Little River Canyon,
the deepest canyon east of the Mississippi, and offers views of
Little River Falls and stunning rock formations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 205-845-3957.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHEAST GEORGIA
</P>
<P>
   Why go out of state? We have some excellent leaf-watching right
here in Georgia. Here are two routes that take you past some of the
state's most awe-inspiring natural wonders.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Travel north of Helen on Ga. 75, turn right on Ga. 365 to Anna
Ruby Falls and Unicoi State Park. (The trail to Anna Ruby Falls is
closed for repaving until next week. Call 1-800-532-2521 for
updates.)
</P>
<P>
   Backtrack to Ga. 75, then head north to Ga. 180, which leads to
the turnoff to Brasstown Bald, Georgia's highest peak at 4,784
feet. Return to Ga. 180 and proceed west to U.S. 129, then travel
south to Vogel State Park. Backtrack again: Go north on U.S. 129,
east on Ga. 180, then south on Ga. 348, which will take you past
Helton Creek Falls and connects with Ga. 75 Alternate via Richard
Russell Scenic Highway.
</P>
<P>
   While you're in the area, check out Oktoberfest in Helen,
continuing through Nov. 6. Northeast Georgia's alpine village
celebrates with German music and authentic food and beer in the
Festhalle. 706-878-2181.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  From Atlanta take I-85 to I-985 to Gainesville, then follow
Ga. 60 to Dahlonega. Then go east on Ga. 52, which will take you
past Amicalola Falls State Park _ a great place to stop for a
picnic and a hike to the falls. Continue east on Ga. 52 to Ellijay,
where you'll head north on U.S. 76/Ga. 515 through Blue Ridge and
on to Blairsville.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Paula Crouch Thrasher contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
