<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2134 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-YURTS03-COX     09-30 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-YURTS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experience the great outdoors doesn't have to mean roughing it
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTAHALA GORGE, N.C. _ What was that?
</P>
<P>
   The brief, inhuman bellow seems to have come from a sodden copse
of pine trees standing between me and the Falling Waters Adventure
Resort's bathhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Hurriedly deciding to forgo my usual bedtime ablutions, I creep
slowly backward on the footpath. I cock an ear to catch the next
unholy yelp, but there is only the plop of plump raindrops soaking
the campground from the leafy bows above.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was _ Bigfoot? Eric Robert Rudolph? The Blair Witch?
_ has apparently gone. But I swear I could make out definite
consonant and vowel sounds in that monstrous moan. I think my
hellish tormentor was crying ``yurt!''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was envious of my lodgings. And rightly so. Modern
yurts _ canvas huts modeled after the living quarters of ancient
nomadic Mongolian tribes _ are to tents what the Ritz-Carlton is to
Motel 6. Each of the eight fat, round, rust-colored dwellings at
Falling Waters' yurt village boasts amenities that would make your
average flannel-clad woodsman spit in disgust: a polished Douglas
fir floor. A comfy canopy bed flanked by Pottery Barn-style side
tables and lamps. A refrigerator, coffee maker, ceiling fan, space
heater, chest of drawers _ and don't forget the basket of fresh
towels in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   If one must be camped in the woodsy recesses of Western North
Carolina, fending off demons during a rare summer rainstorm as I
did or watching the leaves change as fall sets in, one could do far
worse.
</P>
<P>
   As Falling Waters owner Jim Greiner notes, the yurts are for
people ``who like the idea of camping'' but not necessarily the
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of our renters are big-city professionals,'' says
Greiner, who built the village in 1998 across the highway from his
11-year-old Wildwater Nantahala Rafting Center, five minutes from
the northern end of the Nantahala River. ``They want the option of
being outdoors in a beautiful area, but with some of the perks that
you don't get in a tent.'' Chief among them, heavy insulation and
airtight, double glass doors that keep out bugs, snakes and worse.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the staples of camping remain _ the communal bathhouse,
for instance. True, its private restrooms and showers are
uncommonly clean, and there's usually hot water, but you still have
to shuffle across the campground in your flip-flops to get to it.
There are also several built-in outdoor grills, which look as if
they've cooked up some real tasty burgers ... on nicer days.
</P>
<P>
   But for the past 48 hours, the rain has made it difficult to
enjoy the outdoor pleasures that draw thousands of rafters, hikers
and mountain bikers to the area every year. The yurts stand vacant
(save mine), the muddy hiking trails that wind through the woods
around the village remain unmarked by boot prints. A few die-hard
rafters took to the churning river earlier in the day, but most
folks, like me, stayed indoors.
</P>
<P>
   And oh, what scintillating rainy-day diversions a yurt offers!
After scrapping a planned morning hike, I spent a half-hour or so
watching the spectacle ``When Rivulets Collide'' on the outside of
the glass doors. After that, I ate four Pop-Tarts. Then I tried to
guess which breed of lapdog the squeaking ceiling fan sounded most
like. (Pomeranian, I decided.) Finally, I settled in on the bed and
read, oh, about three pages of Bill Bryson's ``Notes From a Small
Island'' before curling up for a long nap.
</P>
<P>
   But even cabin fever can't take away from the resplendence of
the surrounding landscape. My yurt (8, ask for it) overlooks the
vast Nantahala Gorge; mist rises from the placid waters of Fontana
Lake at the bottom. Hemlock branches envelop the picnic areas like
the arms of evergreen mothers. A frisky waterfall splashes down the
side of the gorge through clumps of hardwoods sure to be wrapped in
multihued muumuus when autumn dresses this mountain idyll.
</P>
<P>
   One can stroll onto the yurt's deck and gaze for hours at the
lake, listen to the fecund hum of the forest and pontificate
Thoreau-like on the poetic beauty of nature. Just watch your back _
who knows when the Blair Witch might return?
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Falling Waters Adventure Resort/Wildwater
Nantahala Rafting Center, 1-800-451-9972 or www.fallingwatersresort
</P>
<P>
   .com. Yurts are $59 a night for two; there is a $5 a night
charge for each additional guest. Open March through November.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From Atlanta take I-75 north to I-575, continue
north on I-575 until it turns into Ga. 515, going to Blue Ridge.
Stay on bypass around Blue Ridge, go four miles past the turnoff
for Ga. 5. Turn left onto Ga. 60/Spur 60. Turn right on Spur 60 at
Mineral Bluff. Turn right on U.S. 64/74 and travel past Murphy and
Andrews, N.C. Enter the Nantahala Gorge, traveling past the turnoff
for U.S. 129 and Wesser, N.C. Go about seven miles. Yurt check-in
is at Wildwater Nantahala Rafting Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What to bring: Clothing suitable for hiking, rafting and
horseback riding. You might want to bring food and drinks for a
cookout and to stock the refrigerator in your yurt _ the nearest
full-size grocery store is 10 miles away in Bryson City.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eating out: The Fryemont Inn, an upscale rustic lodge in
Bryson City, serves up a dinner menu that ranges from Southern
comfort (country ham with red-eye gravy) to fine dining (roast
lamb, fillet of trout sauteed in mushrooms and white wine).
1-800-845-4879 or www.fryemontinn.com. The Mountain Steak House
offers a casual atmosphere, fine rib-eyes, strips and T-bones and a
stocked-to-overflowing salad bar. 828-488-4399.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What to do: The Wildwater Nantahala Rafting Center offers
daily guide-assisted rafting trips on the Nantahala River for $32
per person and raft rentals for $18-$27. The center's Raft &AMP; Rail
Excursion includes a two-hour trip on the Smoky Mountain Railway up
the Nantahala Gorge, followed by an eight-mile guided raft trip
downriver. $55 adults, $43 children. 1-800-451-9972 or www
</P>
<P>
   .wildwaterrafting.com.
</P>
<P>
   Get a lesson in Native American culture in Cherokee, N.C., about
20 miles northeast of Falling Waters. Attractions on this
56,000-acre reservation include the Oconaluftee Indian Village, the
Museum of the Cherokee Indian and Harrah's Cherokee Casino. For a
brochure, call 1-800-825-8352.
</P>
<P>
   English Mountain Llama Treks pairs hikers with llamas for guided
excursions through the Pisgah and Nantahala national forests. A
five-hour trek is $60; an overnight trek is $200; and a two-night
trek is $300. 1-800-653-9984 or www.hikinginthesmokies.com.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
