<HEADER>
A2137 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-TERENCE-STAMP-IN     09-30 1349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-TERENCE-STAMP-IN-THE-LIMEY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LIMEY SIDE OF TERENCE STAMP 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Terence Stamp
in ``The Limey.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's been almost 40 years since Terence Stamp, then a
20-year-old neophyte actor, was nominated for a
best-supporting-actor Oscar for ``Billy Budd'' (l962).
 &HT;    Stamp didn't win, but almost four decades later he's a contender
for the award again with a powerful performance in the title role
of a very different kind of movie _ ``The Limey,'' which opens on
Oct. 8.
 &HT;    Stamp was born in East London, which makes him a genuine limey _
referring to an Englishman, the label was first attached to British
sailors because of the lime juice served aboard ships of the Royal
Navy to prevent scurvy. He plays another limey, Dave Wilson, a
lean, mean, silver-haired senior citizen just released from a
British prison ... and bent on vengeance.
 &HT;    Wilson's daughter has died in a mysterious car crash in
California, it seems, and the ex-convict and renegade dad flies to
Los Angeles to discover the truth about her untimely demise. There
he encounters her lover (Peter Fonda), a sleazy, rich rock
entrepreneur, one of those languid, lounge-lizard leftovers from
the 1960s who are instantly recognizable to anyone familiar with
the culture of the Sunset Strip.
 &HT;    The movie is violent and intense _ director Steven Soderbergh
calls it ``a mystery thriller that has been put through a
Cuisinart.''
 &HT;    An intriguing footnote is that Dave Wilson is the same low-rent
criminal Stamp played in director Ken Loach's British film ``Poor
Cow'' (1967). In fact, Soderbergh even spliced scenes from that
movie into the new film as flashbacks, with the young, fresh-faced
Stamp helping to flesh out the history of his aging limey.
 &HT;    In a separate interview, Soderbergh says he never considered
anyone else for the role.
 &HT;    ``The last time I saw Terry in a lead role he had a dress on,''
he says, referring to Stamp's star turn as a drag queen decked out
in a glitzy wardrobe of evening clothes, trekking around the
Australian outback, in ``The Adventures of Priscilla, Queen of the
Desert'' (1994).
 &HT;    ``But he has such a great cinema face,'' Soderbergh says, ``and
this film is about you staring at this guy for 90 minutes. If you
don't do that, the movie doesn't work. He's very idiosyncratic,
with lots of baggage.''
 &HT;    Buoyed by the enthusiastic early response to the picture from
the Toronto Film Festival, Stamp has been working hard to plug
``The Limey.'' At 59 he's still handsome, and enviably trim in a
lilac, double-breasted suit, a flower-painted tie and brown shoes,
with the dark hair of his youth now a distinguished silver.
 &HT;    He admits that his success in ``Billy Budd'' came to him while
he was still immature. He was only in his early 20s when he found
himself an icon of Britain's ``Swinging '60s.''
 &HT;    ``I remember the '60s fondly,'' he says. ``I had time for
everything in those days, because I became famous in l960. I
thought it was just happening to me _ I didn't realize it was
happening to everybody.
 &HT;    ``I can't think of a better time to be a young man than London
at the beginning of the '60s.''
 &HT;    By his own admission, Stamp cut a wide swath in those days.
 &HT;    ``Of course that era coincided with the pill, and girls suddenly
realized they enjoyed sex as much as guys,'' he says, and laughs.
``Before that, it had been very difficult to get laid.''
 &HT;    Stamp was suddenly hot stuff. He roomed with another
up-and-coming young actor, someone named Michael Caine. His
girlfriend was supermodel Jean Shrimpton, the Cindy Crawford of her
era. Life could not have been sweeter.
 &HT;    ``I know it's fashionable to put the '60s down,'' Stamp says,
``but you won't hear me do it. It was heaven on earth for a few
minutes.''
 &HT;    The success of ``Billy Budd'' brought him to Hollywood to work
with the legendary director William Wyler in ``The Collector''
(l965). At the time, however, the young Brit was more than a little
arrogant and, despite having only a single film under his belt,
spent much of his time battling the director.
 &HT;    ``If I have any regrets at all about that period, it was because
I really wasn't mature enough to appreciate Wyler,'' Stamp says in
retrospect. ``He was a director I would have liked to have worked
with later on. I loved him.
 &HT;    ``But I got on wonderfully well with him,'' he adds. ``Whenever
I came back to Hollywood I would go to Wyler's house and play pool
and chat him up.''
 &HT;    The actor says that the most highly charged experiences in his
long career onscreen have involved the top directors he's worked
for _ Wyler, Peter Ustinov, who directed ``Billy Budd,'' and
Italian film legend Federico Fellini, for whom Stamp starred in
``Spirits of the Dead'' (1968).
 &HT;    More recently, he popped up as Kryptonian supervillain General
Zod in ``Superman'' (l978) and ``Superman II'' (l981), as well as
appearing in ``Legal Eagles'' (l986) and Oliver Stone's ``Wall
Street'' (l987). He began his fourth decade as an actor by donning
those dazzling dresses in ``Priscilla.''
 &HT;    So far this year he has been seen in George Lucas' ``Star Wars:
The Phantom Menace'' and in Frank Oz's ``Bowfinger,'' playing the
leader of a California cult.
 &HT;    The ``Star Wars'' experience, he says, was disappointing.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't a very interesting job,'' Stamp recalls. ``On my
first day I was looking forward to doing a scene with the beautiful
Natalie Portman. When I arrived, George Lucas told me he'd given
her the day off.
 &HT;    ```There's this post here with this bit of paper on it _ that's
Natalie,' he told me.''
 &HT;    Besides letting him revisit his Wilson character, the actor
says, part of the joy of making ``The Limey'' was getting to work
with Fonda for the first time.
 &HT;    ``Thirty years ago Peter and I had one riotous night on the town
after attending a film festival in Sicily,'' Stamp says, chuckling.
``We vowed to work together. Well, it's taken all this time to make
it happen.''
 &HT;    In October Stamp returns to the Australian outback to star
opposite Val Kilmer in ``Red Planet.'' This time, he insists, he's
not playing a villain.
 &HT;    ``I'm the voice of reason,'' he says, ``a Nobel Prize-winning
physicist who has turned to philosophy because science doesn't
answer any of the really interesting questions in life.''
 &HT;    After living in Italy for seven years, Stamp now calls New York
home _ ``London is my spiritual home,'' he adds _ and says that at
this point in his career he chooses pictures carefully.
 &HT;    ``My life is passing,'' he says, ``and it's not as if I were
Ewan McGregor and had another 50 films ahead of me. I'm not going
to be able to do this forever, so I'm wanting to have the most fun
I can.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Limey,'' consult the
official Website at www.limey-themovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
