<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-GARDENING-HNS &LR;      09-30 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GARDENING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBECCA'S GREEN THUMB MAKES GARDENING EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DIANA RATHBONE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Rebecca Kolls is a guru for the garden set.
She's fun, energetic and especially practical. That combination is
like honey to fans of ``Rebecca's Garden,'' her show on the Home &AMP;
Garden cable television network.
</P>
<P>
   Though some might say the two look a bit alike, Rebecca Kolls is
no Martha Stewart; her advice is decidedly more user-friendly. Her
stated goal is to make viewers feel they can do it too.
</P>
<P>
   That was evident on the set of ``Rebecca's Garden'' last week,
when Kolls was in San Francisco to shoot several episodes at the
Filoli Gardens in Woodside. Her guest on the show was Don Dillon,
the 78-year-old former mayor of Fremont, whose family has owned
Four Winds Growers for nearly half a century. His subject? How to
grow dwarf citrus indoors, which is the only way it can be done
outside of California and Florida. (The show will air sometime in
the chilly middle of February.)
</P>
<P>
   Kolls didn't let Dillon get away with offering vague advice.
</P>
<P>
   When he answered a question about watering by saying, ``Let the
plant talk to you,'' she pressed him to be more specific until he
recommended twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   They stood behind an old wooden table at the side of the pool.
He was in a black shirt and magnificent straw hat, she in a white
tank top and pink blouse. According to the makeup and wardrobe
person, Denice Lacher, guests and hosts must be color-coordinated
in advance of a shoot: ``You can't have them both turning up in
red, or they look like bookends.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon was an excellent guest, completely natural. Either he was
so accustomed to being on television that he no longer notices the
camera, or else, absorbed in his plants, he really did forget he
was being filmed. In this he was not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Kolls appeared much more interested in finding out whether she
could safely push a stake through the roots of a Eureka lemon (yes
_ just ram it on through) than whether her nose was powdered just
so. When the producer, Darren Howelton, suggested skipping a
segment on foliage, Kolls demurred.
</P>
<P>
   Thus she and future viewers learned from Dillon that pale green
leaves with yellow veins indicate a lack of nitrogen, while yellow
leaves with green veins mean a lack of one of the trace elements.
</P>
<P>
   The show is designed for non-experts, and Howelton himself said
he started his first garden using tips from the program. ``It's
like always being in school,'' he said, his head emerging from the
blue rucksack where it had been stuck for most of the morning as he
monitored the action on a tiny screen.
</P>
<P>
   He and Kolls carefully avoid anything too technical, emphasizing
the useful. For example, most dwarf citrus are grafted (which means
the bottom of the plant is not a Valencia orange at all but only
the orange's foster parent), but grafting was mentioned only for
practical purposes: Because branches below the graft are suckers,
they must be removed.
</P>
<P>
   The same philosophy informs both her spin-off magazine
(Rebecca's Garden is published by Hearst Communications Inc., a
unit of the Hearst Corp.) and Rebeccasgarden.com., where the how-to
articles look like a recipe in ``The Joy of Cooking,'' even down to
a list of materials.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the plants shown were popular favorites, like the Dancy
tangerine (a hit at Chinese New Year) or Kaffir lime (the leaves
are used in Thai food), but the urge to impress the neighbors was
not ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon and Kolls discussed something called Buddha's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Totally inedible, all peel and no flesh, it looks like a yellow
fist with curly, gnarled claws _ a sure-fire conversation starter.
</P>
<P>
   Kolls got her start as a weather reporter. She majored in
atmospheric science at the University of Kansas because ``after
taking one course, I couldn't stand not to go on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was aiming for NASA until her professor found her a job as a
weather reporter for a small TV station, where she improvised by
including gardening tips. This led to a $200,000 rooftop garden at
a CBS affiliate in Salt Lake City, constructed specifically for her
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   After one of her segments appeared on ``Oprah,'' she was offered
her current program. In the end, she said, she chose gardening over
weather. ``It's what I love to do anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To explain her success, Kolls conjured an image of shingling
roofs. ``One tile, by itself, is useless,'' she said. ``But get
enough of them, and not only is the house protected, but if one
shingle wears out, there are enough left to carry you through.
Build on what you have.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to wonder, however, if just anyone could have
turned a love of petunias and tornadoes into such a solid
structure.
</P>
<P>
   Until her children were born, Kolls was terrified of going
on-camera. ``I spent five years shaking in my boots, trying to be
someone I wasn't,'' she said. ``After the kids, I didn't care
anymore. I could finally be myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the set of her program had to be the least stressful in
history. When the table got messy with spilled earth and pruned
leaves, Kolls and Dillon scooped them up as casually as if they
were both at home.
</P>
<P>
   Just off set, an editor from the magazine was conducting an
informal dwarf-citrus tasting. The winner: Nazami kumquats. Tart,
small and delicious, they beg to be made into tea.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on, each retake got tighter, the information a
little more concise. The makeup artist kept an eagle eye out for
fading lipstick and shiny foreheads, while the sound person stopped
the shooting each time a plane flew overhead. It took 2 1/2 hours
before Howelton was satisfied with his four minutes of program.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was time for the closing segment. Kolls smiled
encouragingly into the camera and, rather like Jane Fonda pushing
aerobics fans to go for the burn, she urged her viewers to ``Go out
there and do it, too. Just get your hands dirty!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
