<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2162 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DISC-REVIEWS-LADN     09-30 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISC-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  NINE INCH NAILS/``THE FRAGILE'' (Nothing/Interscope)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dig out the torn fishnets and black eye makeup. Ten years after
``Pretty Hate Machine'' took industrialized Goth mainstream, Trent
Reznor, rock's own little Nietzsche, has released Nine Inch Nails'
first album in five years. The dreadful two-disc result has all the
excitement and musical value of a faucet leaking in a moldy room at
the end of the hall. Actually, Reznor would probably get a kick out
of that image. It's just the thing to spark his next
one-dimensional concept album. With its uninspired one-note musical
interludes resembling machinery spinning out of control or anemic
pianos tinkling their last, ``The Fragile'' is relentlessly empty.
Lyrically, the continually overrated Reznor spouts senior-year Goth
platitudes of the ``life is bleak'' variety so cliche-ridden
they're too embarrassing to repeat here. Of mild interest is the
standout track ``We're in This Together,'' which boasts a spark of
energy and almost comes close to a genuine tune. 1 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QR; 
JOSHUA BELL AND EDGAR MEYER/``SHORT TRIP HOME'' (Sony Classical)
</P>
<P>
   Violin virtuoso Bell and bassist Meyer are joined by progressive
bluegrass instrumentalists Sam Bush and Mike Marshall on this
inspired melding of the classical world and traditional Americana.
Composed by Meyer, the music never veers far from its roots in
country, bluegrass and folk so that even at it most complicated or
experimental, it's eminently listenable. With enjoyable melodies
and wonderful interplay among these four superb musicians, this is
the type of project that helps keep the movement between genres
fluid while providing some terrific sounds. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Rob Lowman &QR; 
KATHRYN STOTT/``LA HABANERA: THE PIANO MUSIC OF ERNESTO LECUONA''
(EMI Classics)
</P>
<P>
   The composer and keyboard artist Ernesto Lecuona (1896-1963)
lives up to his epithet as ``the Cuban Gershwin'' with this lovely
and varied collection of short piano works. Performed by Stott with
great playfulness and ardency, these miniaturist pieces give
evidence of Lecuona's technical proficiency as well as his
unusually diverse (particularly for his time) musical parlance, a
fusion of Cuban, African, classical, Spanish and African-American
traditions. The yearning romanticism and powerful climax of
``Preludio en la Noche'' at first seems an ocean and perhaps 50
years removed from the jaunty ``...Y la Negra Bailaba!'' and the
vaguely ragtime-y ``Danza Negra.'' But Lecuona's synthesis of the
sentimental and the cosmopolitan, lush glissandos and capricious
dance rhythms, invests these 23 pieces with a vitality that spans
the decades as surely as it spans the northern and southern
hemispheres. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Reed Johnson &QR; 
BILLY BRAGG/``REACHING TO THE CONVERTED'' (Rhino)
</P>
<P>
   British singer-songwriter Bragg made his biggest splash in the
States last year with ``Mermaid Avenue,'' an outstanding tribute to
Woody Guthrie cut with alt-country rockers Wilco. This interesting
batch of rarities and British A- and B-sides is likely to further
broaden his appeal both to the converted and new initiates. The
best songs among the 17 offerings combine Bragg's lethal wit with
his passion for social causes. Also included is a cover of the
Beatles' ``She's Leaving Home'' and a hilariously revamped reading
of the Four Tops' ``Walk Away Renee'' with former Smiths great
Johnny Marr on guitar. For an assemblage of bits and pieces, this
works surprisingly well as a cohesive effort. 3 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QR; 
IRISH TENORS/``THE IRISH TENORS'' (Master Dance Tones)
</P>
<P>
   When Irish tenor Joe Feeney on ``The Lawrence Welk Show''
reached for high notes, he sounded as if someone had just
overtightened a screw in his back. That unpleasant memory makes
``The Irish Tenors,'' recorded live at the Royal Dublin Society
Main Hall, a delightful surprise. John McDermott, Anthony Kearns
and Ronan Tynan make the music of their homeland appealing to any
listener. Each of the 20 tunes is a story, relating Ireland's
tormented history, lifelong love, impetuous courtship, sweet
memories and more. McDermott, a North American for most of his
life, has the most Irish sound. A self-trained Celtic tenor, he
sings with a lilt, hanging on consonants rather than vowels, which
would make an opera purist cringe but is perfectly suited to this
material. McDermott's ``Danny Boy'' and ``Believe Me'' are eloquent
in their simplicity, and ``The Old Man'' is very poignant. Kearns
is a lyric tenor whose expertise with both oratorio and Gilbert &AMP;
Sullivan is evident. He brings sweetness to ``Grace'' and high
spirits to ``Eileen Og'' and ``Boolavogue.'' Ronan Tynan,
discovered at a talent contest five years ago, displays a natural
gift and heartfelt intensity in ``I'll Take You Home Again
Kathleen'' and ``The Town I Loved So Well.'' His range and style
are a good bridge between McDermott and Kearns. Their trio efforts
also are charming, particularly the flirtatious ``Will Ye Go,
Lassie, Go?'' The Royal Symphony Orchestra, with conductor-arranger
Frank McNamara's light touch, uplifts the vocals rather than
smothering them. 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Valerie Kuklenski &QR; 
MARC ANTHONY/``MARC ANTHONY'' (Columbia)
</P>
<P>
   His namesake was a Roman general who loved Cleopatra and died
tragically. Salsa superstar Anthony loved Jennifer Lopez and faces
down a batch of tragically overproduced schlock. By turning his
back on the salsa genre that made him famous, Anthony misplaces
much of his bite in favor of sappy love ballads. Sometimes, the
mush can be mildly diverting, but too much syrup set to throbbing
strings can leave even the most ardent romantic fool cold. Although
one or two tunes, including ``That's Okay'' and ``I Need to Know,''
act as a good foil for Anthony's internationally popular voice, we
were reaching for the hemlock by the end of this treacly ordeal. 1
1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Shuster &QR; 
STEFON HARRIS/``BLACK ACTION FIGURE'' (Blue Note)
</P>
<P>
   Harris, at a mere 26 years of age, has been touted as one of
jazz music's brightest stars and this impressive release confirms
the designation. Building on the solid foundation of ``A Cloud of
Red Dust'' (Harris' debut last year as a leader), ``Black Action
Figure'' finds the vibraphonist playing with more confidence,
versatility and artistry, delivering a varied program of masterful
music. Harris is ably supported by the Blue Note stable, including,
most notably, Greg Osby and Gary Thomas on sax and pianist Jason
Moran. The selections swing from the Ornette Coleman-like
complexities of ``There Is No Greater Love'' to delicate ballads
like the closing ``Faded Beauty.'' Believe the hype _ Harris is the
real deal. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   _ Glenn Whipp &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
