<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT DEALS BLOW TO GUN MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Advocates of gun control are applauding the
nation's first appellate-level court ruling declaring that gun
manufacturers can be held accountable in criminal shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, issued Wednesday by the First District Court of
Appeal, allows the families of eight victims in the 1993 shooting
at a San Francisco office building to proceed with their lawsuit
against the maker of the guns used in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1 ruling, the state court said Navegar Inc., the
Miami-based company that makes the TEC-DC9 and TEC-9, marketed the
semiautomatic weapons to appeal to people attracted to violence and
should have foreseen the injuries. The court said the weapons
appeared to have no legitimate civilian use.
</P>
<P>
   The mentally disturbed gunman, Gian Luigi Ferri, entered the
downtown high-rise with two TEC-DC9 pistols in July 1993 and opened
fire in a law office. Ferri shot dead eight people and wounded six
others before killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We conclude there are triable issues as to whether Ferri would
have engaged in the conduct at 101 California Street, and could
have killed and injured as many people as he did, if the TEC-DC9
had not been promoted by Navegar as it was and made available to
persons like him,'' Justice J. Anthony Kline wrote in the majority
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Jetto, the lawyer representing the gun manufacturer, said
he would probably appeal the decision to the California Supreme
Court. He said he would challenge the new standard established in
Wednesday's decision that gun manufacturers have a duty not to
engage in ``negligent marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is brand new,'' Jetto said. ``I think it introduces great
uncertainty in marketing practices in any number of different ways.
What marketing practices will cross the line under this test? I
think that will be one of the primary issues on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Horwitz, executive director of the Educational Fund to
End Handgun Violence in Washington, D.C., hailed the court's
decision as a major step forward in the push to hold manufacturers
responsible for gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, manufacturers would say, `We don't really care
who gets the gun. Once it goes out of our shop, we don't have any
responsibility,''' he said. ``Courts are saying, `Yes you do.'''
</P>
<P>
   The TEC-DC9 is a weapon designed for mass killing, said Dennis
Henigan, legal director of the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence
in Washington and lead lawyer for the families of the victims in
the San Francisco case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a gun Navegar was promoting for home self-defense
or hunting or target shooting. Clearly Navegar understood that a
good part of its market was the criminal market,'' he said. ``It
was a gun designed for war, to be spray- fired from the hip, and
that's exactly how Mr. Ferri used it.''
</P>
<P>
   A TEC-DC9 was also carried by one of the two students who killed
13 people at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., in April.
The two teen-ager gunmen then killed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting Justice Paul Haerle expressed distaste for weapons
such as TEC-DC9 but said Ferri was solely responsible for his
actions. He said the majority opinion made ``legal and analytical
errors'' and committed ``an egregious exercise in judicial
legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco is one of about two dozen cities in the country
suing gun manufacturers for damages.
</P>
<P>
   The new judicial standard established in the ruling would
bolster San Francisco's claim, said Deputy City Attorney Cam Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our case, we're alleging some manufacturers are engaging in
wrongful distribution that would enhance the risks to the public,''
he said. ``If you're distributing in a way that it will increase
the risk it will fall in the hands of criminals and felons ...
you're violating this duty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
