<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2168 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TREK-ON-THE-SET-OF-ST     09-30 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-ON-THE-SET-OF-STAR-TREK-VOYAGER-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALICE' IN OUTER SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., OCT. 11, 1999) 
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Claire
Rankin and Robert McNeill Duncan in a scene from the ``Star Trek:
Voyager'' episode ``Alice.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Scene 44 is a long, long trek.
 &HT;    It's early in the morning on Stage 9 at Paramount Pictures,
where veteran director David Livingston is preparing the day's
first shot on ``Alice,'' the ``Star Trek: Voyager'' episode that
will air on Oct. 20.
 &HT;    Livingston has gathered everyone _ sound, lighting and camera
crews, as well as guest star Claire Rankin and series regulars
Robert Duncan McNeill and Roxann Dawson _ on a Voyager corridor set
to describe his vision of the scene at hand.
 &HT;    ``Alice'' involves an alien ship so desperate to get home that
its id, in the form of a beautiful woman named Alice (Rankin),
takes possession of Tom Paris (McNeill) and forces him to pilot the
ship back to its own world. No one but Paris can actually see
Alice, making his increasingly combative conversations with her
seem like the ramblings of a madman to those around him,
particularly Torres (Dawson).
 &HT;    ``This episode has a lot of scary stuff in it that's been fun to
play,'' McNeill says during a break. ``You know what it reminds me
of? Do you remember the John Carpenter film, `Christine'? Instead
of someone dealing with a possessed car, we've got a possessed
shuttle that I have to deal with.''
 &HT;    Livingston has made it clear how he wants to handle the scene,
which involves Paris confronting Torres and then storming away,
only to run into Alice and exchange harsh words with her, too. A
hand-held Steadicam will capture the action in a single lengthy,
fluid shot, cutting back and forth between two-shots _ in which two
people share a frame _ and closeups.
 &HT;    ``It's all about the mystery and the weirdness of the
consciousness existing only in Paris' perception and no one
else's,'' Livingston explains during a brief break. ``The challenge
is getting that on the screen, and we're trying to do it with cool
camera moves that reveal Alice's presence.
 &HT;    ``We're doing a lot of rotation shots, where we start in one
place and pan over,'' he adds. ``We start the episode that way,
without showing Alice, and people will probably say, `Why is the
director doing this?' Then we start to show Alice, and we're still
doing the rotation shots.
 &HT;    ``It's a stylistic conceit that we're trying to do on the
episode,'' Livingston concludes. ``As a director, you just try to
come up with some kind of hook that keeps you interested in the
episode and, hopefully, it will keep the audience interested,
too.''
 &HT;    Rehearsal begins an hour later, after everyone has donned their
costumes and had makeup applied, and after the sound crew has
figured out how to work around McNeill and Rankin's loud-crinkling
spacesuits. Livingston watches the first moments of rehearsal
anxiously _ something's not working, and the clock is ticking.
 &HT;    McNeill leans against a wall as his tirade at Alice builds to a
crescendo, and the actor's positioning leaves no room for the
cameraman to maneuver.
 &HT;    ``That's the part that's ugly,'' Livingston says, creating a box
with his fingers and peering through it as if it were a camera
lens. ``It's just going to be the backs of heads when we put it on
film.''
 &HT;    The director makes several suggestions, and the scene is
rehearsed again. McNeill, himself a director of several
well-received episodes, puts in his two cents' worth, and the
cameraman offers his thoughts. Subsequent runthroughs satisfy
Livingston, and he orders the camera to roll.
 &HT;    On take one, McNeill blows his line.
 &HT;    ``You're really out of breath,'' he ad-libs to Dawson, ``and
your hair looks great.''
 &HT;    Everyone cracks up, even Livingston.
 &HT;    Dawson, McNeill and Rankin tinker with their line delivery in
takes two, three and four, none of which thrill Livingston.
 &HT;    On take five, however, everything clicks.
 &HT;    ``Perfect,'' Livingston announces. ``Print that.''
 &HT;    A stickler, Livingston wants more. Take six elicits another
``Perfect, print that.'' So does take seven. The actors and crew
are ready to move on to the next scene, but Livingston wants yet
one more.
 &HT;    For take eight, the actors play the hell out of the scene.
 &HT;    ``Fabulous! Great!'' Livingston says. ``Print that.''
 &HT;    Scene 44 is in the can. Three-plus hours have passed. The scene
will run less than two minutes on screen.
 &HT;    Welcome to the 24th century. 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
