<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2191 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-REDS-PLAYOFFS01-C     09-30 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-PLAYOFFS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cincinnati Reds control their own destiny, seek first title
since 1995
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The Cincinnati Reds are in the state of Wisconsin
and they also are in the state of confusion. And it has nothing to
do with choosing bratwurst or knockwurst or what kind of crackers
to have with the cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Their confusion surrounds whether they should be concerned about
the Milwaukee Brewers, the Houston Astros, the New York Mets or
whether some moronic fan might leap from the County Stadium stands
tonight and assault first baseman Sean Casey.
</P>
<P>
   Reds manager Jack McKeon offers solid advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not against any wall and we decide our own fate,''
McKeon said before leaving Houston, where the Reds and the Astros
split a two-game series Tuesday and Wednesday. ``That means if we
win our last three games, no convoluted playoff system can rob us
of anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are so close to their first National League Central
championship since 1995 that they can sniff the champagne with the
corks still tucked in the bottles. They and the Astros are tied for
first place and each has three to play.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati takes step one of its three-step program tonight in
County Stadium against the Brewers and they certainly are putting
their best arm forward. Left-hander Denny Neagle, 6-0 with a 2.30
earned run average in his last six starts and 9-3 with a 3.23 ERA
in 12 games since coming off the disabled list, gets the baseball.
</P>
<P>
   If he can't get it done, it's midseason acquisition Juan Guzman
on Saturday. If he can't get it done, it's veteran Pete Harnisch on
Sunday. If they can't get it done, the Reds are done.
</P>
<P>
   While the Reds finish with the Brewers, Houston has three in the
Astrodome against the Los Angeles Dodgers. If both the Reds and
Astros win all three and finish in a tie, the Reds are division
champions on the strength of their 9-4 mastery over Houston in
head-to-head games.
</P>
<P>
   As the sign painted on a wall outside the Houston clubhouse
says, ``It can Happen!''
</P>
<P>
   Can the Cincinnati Reds become Cin-derella? They think so as
after five months and 159 games the season comes down to three
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously would have liked to gone to Houston and won two
games to put Houston two games behind us with three to play,''
Casey said. ``But we were on the road, 55,000 screaming fans _ so
we're glad we got a split in that situation. We're glad to be where
we are (in the standings) going into this last series of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it is all about,'' Casey added. ``You can't ask
for anything more. These last three games mean something . . . mean
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Milwaukee is a National League bottom-feeder, the
Reds haven't whomped them. They are 5-4 this season against the
Brewers, 3-3 at home and 2-1 in County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the final game in the Astrodome _ 4-1, on Wednesday to
drop into a tie after beating the Astros, 4-1, on Tuesday to take a
24-hour one-game lead _ isn't causing McKeon to sweat around the
collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win six in a row, you're going to lose once in a
while,'' he said. ``We'll try to start another streak. We're tough.
We bounce back after losses.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a third party in the scenario. The New York
Mets still can make it a three-way tie or they can snatch the
wild-card sweepstakes from the Reds or Astros if one deflates
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Houston outfielder Carl Everett isn't afraid to show his disdain
for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't care less about the Mets,'' he said. ``I hate the
Mets. I hope they lose every game.'' And tomorrow Everett will
reveal how he really feels.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon admits that while his team argues with Milwaukee this
weekend, he'll keep one eye on the scoreboard to see how
Houston-Los Angeles is progressing and the other eye on the same
scoreboard to see how New York-Pittsburgh is unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't much else to do between innings in the dugout,''
McKeon said. ``I don't have a book to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't there a book entitled, ``How to Win Games and Influence
Pennant Races''?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
