<HEADER>
A2193 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX     09-30 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAILING LISTS SOLD AT A RAPID CLIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITOR'S NOTE: Rogers Cadenhead is taking some time off. He
left us a few of his favorite items from yesteryear. His column
will resume with sparkling fresh material when he returns.)
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Is it true that if you buy nose-hair clippers from a
magazine ad, your name will be sold to direct-mail marketers? _
J.T., Dallas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ Apparently, yes. Author William Poundstone investigated
this bit of urban lore, which holds that people who buy mail-order
Klipette nose grooming products are a highly prized demographic
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason, that mentality is just right for some
direct mail-order pitches,'' Poundstone writes in ``Big Secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Clippers distributors can make more money selling the name of
purchasers than they do on the product, he writes. The author
ordered clippers under a fake name, and 10 months later, that name
started getting pitches for virility products and other unusual
wares.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ What exactly is the Curse of Barilko? _ J.S.,
Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ The curse is a bit of hockey lore involving the Toronto
Maple Leafs, the Stanley Cup, a star player and a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, Bill Barilko won the Cup for the Maple Leafs by scoring
an overtime goal to beat the Montreal Canadiens, 3-2. It was the
fourth NHL title the Leafs had won since Barilko joined the team.
</P>
<P>
   After the Cup finals, Barilko disappeared on a plane flight
during a Hudson Bay fishing trip, and his remains were not found
until 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs did not win a Cup during the decade that Barilko was
missing, and they won immediately after his body was found. Leafs
fans, used to winning titles, concluded that a curse was to blame
for all those Cup-impaired years.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Can you confirm that the word ``rhubarb'' was used to
describe a baseball fight in the '50s? _ U.C., Fort Worth, texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ The term ``rhubarb'' was popularized in 1939, when
Brooklyn Dodgers broadcaster Red Barber used it to describe heated
arguments and brawls on the field.
</P>
<P>
   According to Stuart Berg Flexner in ``Listening to America,''
the term dates back to 1915, when it was used in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Actors in a crowd scene, needing to appear angry, confused and
moblike, would yell ``rhubarb!'' over and over. The term has fallen
into disuse today among baseball commentators.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
