<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRIENDS-FILM-REVIEW-N     09-30 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UNCOMMON FRIENDS': A MAN WHO KNEW THE ELITE BUT WASN'T KNOWN
HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Narrated by Walter Cronkite, a peculiar documentary titled
``Uncommon Friends of the 20th Century'' is built on the
relationships of a Zelig-like Floridian named Jim Newton with some
of the foremost figures of this time.
</P>
<P>
   A weak broth of biography, spiritual uplift and environmental
concerns, this film is strongest in its use of personal photographs
and archival film to recall people like Thomas A. Edison, Henry
Ford, Harvey Firestone and Charles A. Lindbergh.
</P>
<P>
   But its generally uncritical and sometimes apologetic posture
(Lindbergh's acceptance of a Nazi medal) and its failure to
distinguish between its authentic film images and its re-enactments
of events, like an incident during the invention of the electric
light, undermine the value as documentary history of its already
sketchy biographical materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uncommon Friends,'' directed by John Biffar, is based on the
1994 autobiography of Newton, who was 20 in 1924 when he met Edison
while developing Edison Park, a residential community in Fort
Myers, Fla., where Edison was a winter resident.
</P>
<P>
   Edison took a liking to the young man, and the friendship
between the two led to Newton's friendships with Ford, Firestone,
Lindbergh and members of their families.
</P>
<P>
   The generous helping of Edison films, accompanied by
reminiscences by Newton and his wife, Ellie, are the highlights of
``Uncommon Friends.'' Edison proves to have a winning sense of
humor, particularly when the great inventor responds to a question
about Einstein's theory of relativity by saying, ``I don't think
anything of Einstein's theory, because I don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, ``Uncommon Friends'' amounts to no more than a
brief, small footnote to history.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `UNCOMMON FRIENDS OF THE 20th CENTURY'
</P>
<P>
   Produced and directed by John Biffar. Running time: 63 minutes.
This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Walter Cronkite (Narrator) and James D. and Ellie Newton.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
