<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DRIVE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     09-30 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DRIVE ME CRAZY': BOY NEXT DOOR IS THE NEXT BEST THING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As teen-age romantic comedies go, ``Drive Me Crazy'' ranks among
the easy to take.
</P>
<P>
   The principals are Adrian Grenier and Melissa Joan Hart, the
star of television's ``Sabrina, the Teen-Age Witch,'' whose looks
are attractive without being extraordinary. The supporting cast,
led by Susan May Pratt, Mark Webber, Ali Larter and Gabriel
Carpenter, among others, is well chosen. And best of all, ``Drive
Me Crazy,'' directed by John Schultz from a Rob Thomas screenplay
based on Todd Strasser's novel ``How I Created the Perfect Prom
Date,'' treats its teen-agers as characters, not caricatures.
</P>
<P>
   Chase Hammond, portrayed by Grenier, even knows how to use
``who'' and ``whom,'' and in one of several signs that it is witty
as well as wise, ``Drive Me Crazy'' doesn't shy from letting him do
so.
</P>
<P>
   When Chase was a little boy, he and Nicole Maris, the girl next
door, were good friends. But as they grew up, they grew apart; and
at the outset of ``Drive Me Crazy,'' while still occupying adjacent
houses, they also occupy opposite ends of the high school social
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   The long-haired, dark, scruffy Chase is part of the bright rebel
crowd. Nicole, blond and effervescent, represents the
establishment, busy planning the school's centennial celebration
and waiting eagerly for its basketball star, the handsome but not
too intelligent Brad ( Carpenter) to pop the important question:
will she be his date for the big dance.
</P>
<P>
   But when Chase is dropped by his cause-loving girlfriend, Dulcie
(Ms. Larter), and when Brad literally falls for a cheerleader from
a rival school, Nicole enlists Chase in a scheme to win them back
by pretending to be romantically involved and making them jealous.
</P>
<P>
   So Chase endures a makeover and starts going to basketball
games, and he and Nicole get to know each other again.
</P>
<P>
   On the sidelines, making much mischief, is Nicole's devious and
cynical best friend, Alicia (Ms. Pratt), who has an agenda of her
own, while Chase's decent but uncharismatic pal Dave (Mark Webber)
pursues a cyber-romance with a mysterious woman.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay furnishes its protagonists with some
psychological underpinning as the children of single parents:
Nicole a product of divorce and an unreliable father, and Chase
scarred at an early age by the death of his mother.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to an ending, ``Drive Me Crazy'' offers no
surprises, but it arrives there in amiable, sensible style.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DRIVE ME CRAZY'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Drive Me Crazy'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes some importunate back-seat groping, some
excessive drinking and its consequences, and schoolyard language
that seems intended to spare the film the dreaded G rating that
might have alienated the teen-agers who are its most likely
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Schultz; written by Rob Thomas, based on the
novel ``How I Created My Perfect Prom Date'' by Todd Strasser;
director of photography, Kees Van Oostrum; edited by John Pace;
music by Greg Kendall; production designer, Aaron Osborne; produced
by Amy Robinson; released by 20th Century Fox. Running time: 93
minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Melissa Joan Hart (Nicole Maris), Adrian Grenier (Chase
Hammond), Stephen Collins ( Maris), Mark Metcalf ( Rope), William
Converse-Roberts ( Hammond), Faye Grant (Mrs. Maris), Susan May
Pratt (Alicia), Mark Webber (Dave), Ali Lartner (Dulcie) and
Gabriel Carpenter (Brad).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
