<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2222 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r a BC-CHARLES-SAATCHI-ART-C     09-30 2447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLES-SAATCHI-ART-CONTROVERSY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES SAATCHI: THE COLLECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By DEBORAH SOLOMON  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    Charles Saatchi had promised to meet me at a restaurant on
Savile Row. Arriving in central London a few minutes early, I gazed
into the shop windows, with their stylish suits of twill and tweed.
They reminded me of something Gertrude Stein once said.
 &HT;    Asked why she had such an impressive art collection, she
replied, ``Because I don't buy any clothes.''
 &HT;    I wondered how Saatchi would answer the same question, but
mostly I wondered whether he would even materialize for our
meeting. Famously reclusive, he is Britain's leading patron of
contemporary art, and he had already warned me not to expect too
much of him.
 &HT;    A few days earlier, I had picked up my phone and heard a British
voice blurt: ``You can't possibly be serious about this interview.
It's just ridiculous that you would cross the Atlantic to meet a
man who speaks in monosyllables and has nothing of interest to
say.''
 &HT;    Saatchi, of course, is an advertising wizard, the founder with
his younger brother Maurice of the huge firm of Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi.
But these days his most inspired campaign is surely the one that
has turned him into the Maecenas of new British art.
 &HT;    The London art scene had its '80s in the '90s _ it suddenly rose
up as a happening place _ and this is largely Saatchi's doing. For
about a decade, he has been buying the latest art in large
quantities and exhibiting it at the Saatchi Gallery, his palatial
if hard-to-find museum in residential north London.
 &HT;    In the process, he has brought international recognition to a
generation of hypercaffeinated artists led by Damien Hirst of
pickled-shark fame, and reinvented drizzly London as a shining
capital of contemporary art.
 &HT;    Saatchi is vastly controversial in London, which is not
surprising. The British, forever hemming and hawing, have never
been comfortable with either vanguard art or undiluted ambition.
 &HT;    They speak of Saatchi as a ``human Hoover'' who buys art in bulk
and manipulates the market for personal gain. His traveling show,
``Sensation: Young British Artists From the Saatchi Collection,''
is scheduled to open Sat., Oct. 2, at the Brooklyn Museum of Art.
 &HT;    New York 's Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, after viewing the exhibition
catalog, said the work was ``sick stuff'' and threatened to cut off
all subsidies to the museum unless it cancelled the show.
 &HT;    On Sept. 28, the museum filed a lawsuit in federal court
accusing Giuliani of violating the First Amendment by threatening
to cut off its funding. City officials announced that they too are
preparing for legal action.
 &HT;    When ``Sensation'' was unveiled two years ago at the Royal
Academy of Arts in London, visitors to the exhibition, who had
never quite thought of elephant dung or an erect cucumber as the
stuff from which masterpieces are made, were appalled that the
Royal Academy had chosen to lend its imperial imprimatur to
Saatchi's sexy collectibles.
 &HT;    Academicians resigned in disgust, protesters hurled eggs and
radio broadcasters led off their hourly news bulletins with
dispatches from ``the Royal Academy of Porn,'' as The Daily Mail
rechristened the museum. In other words, ``Sensation'' went exactly
as planned.
 &HT;    In Brooklyn, before Giuliani's expressions of personal outrage,
the show actually was expected to be less controversial than it was
in London, in part because many of the 43 artists in it have
already won a loyal following in the New York art world.
 &HT;    There is, for starters, Damien Hirst, Brit Art's charismatic
forerunner, who remains best known for suspending a shark in an
enormous tank of formaldehyde, a symbol of the coming art invasion.
There is Rachel Whiteread, a sculptor whose plaster casts of whole
rooms, or of old bathroom sinks and tubs, have a ghostly, nearly
classical presence.
 &HT;    The show has lots of serious painting _ from the good-taste
abstractions of Fiona Rae, Jason Martin and Gary Hume to the
figurative sublimities of Jenny Saville, whose obese female nudes
make cellulite seem almost appealing.
 &HT;    To be sure, some of the work in the show goes for cheap thrills
(like the Chapman brothers' penis-headed mannequins) and some of it
is merely flaky (like Tracey Emin's ``Everyone I Have Ever Slept
With 1963-1995,'' a tent appliqued with the names of her many bed
mates).
 &HT;    Skeptics see the exhibition as Saatchi's latest effort to
inflate the value of his holdings, the sly move of a man for whom
art is mainly a speculator's game.
 &HT;    Yet it seems more likely that Saatchi is a genuine original, the
latest in a line of historic collectors to be acquisition-addicted
and prone to eccentric ways. He gives parties he does not attend,
has never been to a board meeting and is so camera shy I didn't
know what he looked like before we met.
 &HT;    In fact, when a handsome man ambled over to my table in the
restaurant, I assumed he was the maitre d'hotel and started to ask
for fizzy water, only to hear him say, in a voice just above a
whisper: ``Charles Saatchi. Sorry I'm late.''
 &HT;    Saatchi is an animated, striking man of 56 with a tangle of
black hair and large, watchful eyes. He was dressed casually in a
white, short-sleeve shirt and loose black pants. Sitting down to
lunch, he lighted up a Silk Cut cigarette (``I'll never quit,'' he
said with cheerful defiance) and mentioned he was leaving for Italy
the next morning to binge on Renaissance art.
 &HT;    Piero della Francesca is one of his passions. Racing go-carts is
another. He offered me a cigarette and when (why not?) I accepted,
he smiled and said, ``Oh, good, we can be weaklings together.''
 &HT;    I had expected him to be someone else, a
skulking-around-in-the-shadows type, the diffident spook of legend.
But now I saw that he can be extremely charming. Taking out a small
note pad, he pretended to interview me (``Tell me, how did you
become an art critic?'') and in general displayed a disarming mix
of attentiveness, modesty and wit.
 &HT;    Two hours into our lunch, I opened my own note pad. That's when
he shut down. He appeared pained and fidgeted nervously with the
sugar packets on the table.
 &HT;    ``There's nothing complicated about me,'' he insisted with comic
futility. ``There are no hidden depths. As Frank Stella used to say
about Minimalism, What you see is what you see.''
 &HT;    From an art perspective, England has always been
ultraconservative and, frankly, a bit of a snore. England is a
literary country, as opposed to a visual one _ a place that accepts
the most radical innovations in fiction, drama and even high-end
television, but not in the visual arts.
 &HT;    But, regardless of one's picks and pans, the main point is that
Saatchi has managed to assemble the defining contemporary art
collection of a nation.
 &HT;    Not since the '60s, when David Hockney bleached his hair, donned
a gold lame jacket and became a painter-celebrity, has the London
art scene generated so much interest.
 &HT;    His critics insist that Saatchi is not a bona fide collector but
a glorified art dealer interested only in stimulating markets and
making a killing. They say that artists have been hurt by his
divestments and like to tell the tale of Sandro Chia, the Italian
figurative painter. His prices plummeted, his gallery dropped him
and he talked of ``emigrating to Alaska'' after Saatchi bought and
sold his work en bloc.
 &HT;    The abstract painter Sean Scully, some of whose canvases were
once owned by Saatchi, says: ``He's really a commodities broker who
has been let loose on the art world. He claims to love art, but his
is the love that the wolf has for the lamb.''
 &HT;    Faced with such charges, Saatchi says heatedly: ``If I were
interested in art as investment, I would just show Picasso and
Matisse. But that's not what I do. I buy new art, and 90 percent of
the art I buy will probably be worthless in 10 years' time to
anyone except me. I don't know how much of the art I like is
significant; I hope some of it is. Who knows what will last?
History is very cruel, isn't it?
 &HT;    ``At any rate,'' he continued, ``I try to keep my collection
fresh. I don't want to end up like William Randolph Hearst in
Xanadu, who just hoarded art and squirreled it away. Why do I buy
art? I often ask myself the same question. I do it for the pleasure
of putting on shows. The whole thing is purely selfish. It's for my
personal gratification.''
 &HT;    His friends insist that the criticism surrounding him is just
sour grapes. As Hirst says: ``You can't imagine how much people in
England resent success. If you leave a really big tip in a
restaurant, the waiter looks at you like, Who the hell do you think
you are to try to impress me and patronize me like that?''
 &HT;    More to the point, Saatchi is not just another British success
story, but a defiant outsider. Born in Baghdad, the son of a
textile-mill operator, Saatchi grew up in a Jewish family in north
London.
 &HT;    An indifferent student and college dropout, he was 27 when he
and his kid brother started Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi. That was in 1970.
Maurice oversaw the business side and Charles took care of the
creative side. By 1986, the firm had become the biggest ad agency
in the world, but Charles was already off on a second career.
 &HT;    If he brought an American-style brashness to British
advertising, he would soon do the same thing to the British art
scene.
 &HT;    ``I grew up on Chuck Berry and Elvis Presley,'' Saatchi says.
``I grew up in the cinema. I was completely in love with anything
American. When I was 19, I came to New York for the first time and
saw a Pollock painting at the Museum of Modern Art and it was
life-changing. Looking at pictures, going to a movie and seeing a
girl was my ideal day when I was young.''
 &HT;    He started collecting early _ jukeboxes, initially _ and
purchased his first work of art (a Sol LeWitt drawing) when he was
still in his 20s. Soon he and his first wife, Doris, an
American-born art writer, were flying to New York once a month to
shop for major art.
 &HT;    In 1985, they opened the Saatchi Gallery, 30,000 square feet of
dazzling whiteness tucked behind imposing gray gates on Boundary
Road. They put on shows that established them as the collectors
with more _ more Julian Schnabels (27 paintings), more Anselm
Kiefers (23 in all), more Cy Twomblys, more Joel Shapiros and, in
particular, more gleaming grids and tilting trapezoids by the
Minimalists.
 &HT;    But then their romance with the American art world seemed to
evaporate almost overnight. In 1990, Saatchi and Doris were
divorced, and like a man who longs to divest himself of his past
and his possessions, he sold off most of the artwork they had
purchased together.
 &HT;    ``I loved Minimalism very passionately,'' Saatchi says, ``but
when you realize there are other things in life besides Carl Andre
and Robert Ryman, it's difficult to look at them and have the same
love affair.''
 &HT;    He became consumed by a circle of British artists who were in
their early 20s and had befriended one another at Goldsmiths
College. They were clearly aware of New York art and its theories,
but their work appeared to be as much about the issues of youth _
sex, death, cigarettes, looking back in anger, etc. _ as the issues
of art.
 &HT;    By now, it would be hard to find a collector who is more
temperamentally allied to the art of the '90s, more in sync with
the pop thrust of contemporary art, than Saatchi, he of the
Elvis-embracing heart.
 &HT;    Last December, Saatchi _ who lives in a townhouse in Chelsea
with his second wife, Kay Hartenstein, and their 4-year-old
daughter _ donated 130 artworks for a Christie's auction that
raised $2.6 million to create scholarship bursaries at four London
art schools. And then, in February, he gave an additional 100
pieces from his collection to the Arts Council of Great Britain.
 &HT;    Moreover, he and his brother not long ago financed the
construction of a London synagogue and named it after their
(still-living) parents. The new Saatchi Synagogue is highly
unusual, not least because it is looking to generate buzz.
 &HT;    When the temple opened, a poster for it was plastered throughout
the London Underground _ a spoof of a Damien Hirst dead-animal
sculpture featuring a chicken floating in a tank of chicken soup.
``My parents think I'm nuts,'' Saatchi tells me.
 &HT;    His art, it seems, leaves him with little time for the
advertising business. ``I'm too old for advertising,'' he says with
typical self-mockery. ``It's a business for young minds. I show my
stuff to people and they laugh at me.''
 &HT;    We were still in the restaurant, and it was getting late. I
asked him why a man with abundant social poise might choose to lead
a reclusive life. It was one of many questions he dodged with
humor, saying only, ``I think it's time to put you into a taxi.''
 &HT;    The other day, I was sent a 90-minute documentary about the
Saatchi brothers that was recently broadcast on Britain's Channel
4. It's called ``The Real Saatchis: Masters of Illusion,'' and it
is grossly unflattering.
 &HT;    Saatchi is characterized as arrogant and reckless, a
``megalomaniac'' with 17 cars and not one firmly held conviction,
other than an adman's belief that image is everything.
 &HT;    As I watched the documentary, I wondered to myself: Who is
Charles Saatchi? A man I had lunch with one Tuesday on Savile Row,
a man who had charmed me to the bone. I admit he won over my
critical heart. Was I naive, taken in by a brilliant image maker?
 &HT;    Actually, I believe he is genuine. I can still see him now,
standing on the street corner where we parted, awaiting the taxi,
hands in his pockets. He said to me then: ``Do I have a good eye? I
have a good eye for me. I don't know that my collection will ever
satisfy anyone. But it satisfies me.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Deborah Solomon  
