<HEADER>
A2228 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ELMO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-30 0554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELMO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ELMO IN GROUCHLAND': THAT SPECIAL BLUE B-L-A-N-K-E-T 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end.) 
(jt) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elmo the Muppet's first movie gets off to an enchanting start.
Bert and Ernie welcome everybody; Elmo wakes up in polka dot
pajamas in his own adorable little-child's bedroom and sings a
tribute to his comforting blue blanket; Elmo spills orange juice on
his blanket; Elmo goes to the laundromat to wash it, and a lot of
people and Muppets from ``Sesame Street'' are there. The Henson
magic is at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland'' stays great right
through the scene in which Elmo chases his blanket, accidentally
whisked away by a passing Muppet Rollerblader, down the street and
tells the gathered crowd to move on. ``Nothing to see here,'' he
tells the onlookers. ``Just a little monster trying to get his
blanket back.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Elmo descends into Oscar the Grouch's trashcan home
and, through a colorful, spiraling magic tunnel, into Grouchland,
and much too much of the warm fuzziness disappears. Sure, his line
upon arrival, ``Elmo doesn't think he's in `Sesame Street'
anymore,'' is nice for the adults (there are ``Titanic'' and ``Gone
With the Wind'' references too), but after that most of the jokes
are about the joys of grossness (there's a car mess instead of a
car wash and the most popular ice cream flavor is anchovy swirl).
Yes, small children love dirt, but this magical land just looks
depressing. And yes, Oscar is a ``Sesame Street'' favorite, but one
grouch goes a long way; here we have an alternative universe of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Elmo's quest is the faraway hilltop castle of Huxley (Mandy
Patinkin), who has come into possession of the blanket and won't
give it back. Huxley's problem, of course, is that he hasn't yet
learned to share. Patinkin, wearing extra eyebrows, is just right
as the villain, enjoying playtime as much as any child. ``Which one
of you dares to question my evil ways?'' he says to his terrified
underlings at one point. Vanessa Williams, as the Queen of Trash,
looks beautiful but doesn't fare as well comically.
</P>
<P>
   The film offers lessons about cooperation, perseverance and
transformation, including but not restricted to growing up (``I've
got what it takes,'' says a caterpillar, explaining that he's a
butterfly-to-be, ``right here inside''), and they're well handled.
But the somewhat complicated plot may disappoint or confuse some
tiny Elmo fans. It's a good thing that Bert and Ernie turn up on
screen periodically to explain, reiterate and reassure.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE ADVENTURES OF ELMO IN GROUCHLAND'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Gary Halvorson; written by Joseph Mazzarino and
Mitchell Kriegman; director of photography, Alan Caso; edited by
Alan Baumgarten; production designer, Alan Cassie; produced by Alex
Rockwell and Marjorie Kalins; released by Columbia Pictures.
Running time: 90 minutes. This film is rated G.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Vanessa Williams (Queen of Trash) and Mandy Patinkin
(Huxley). Voices of Kevin Clash (Elmo), Carroll Spinney (Big
Bird/Oscar the Grouch), Martin P. Robinson (Telly Monster), Frank
Oz (Bert/Grover/Cookie Monster), Fran Brill (Zoe), Steve Whitmire
(Ernie), Jerry Nelson (Count von Count) and Stephanie D'Abruzzo
(Grizzy).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
