<HEADLINE>
`LOVE REINVENTED': GLIMPSES OF THE WORLD AIDS HAS WROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gay men have sexual encounters in a car parked on a Paris
street, in a young stranger's apartment, in a New York subway
station, beside a perfect beach and in a hospital room. Lesbians
talk about HIV while strolling near dawn by the Seine. Condoms are
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   When watching ``Love Reinvented,'' it helps to know what most of
these 12 short films were originally meant for. In 1995 the
Association of Lesbian and Gay Pride Films in France held a
screenplay competition, seeking material for AIDS-related
public-service shorts.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting films were shown on French television, then in
theaters. Alone, any number of these would be powerful, poignant or
both. Together, for the purposes of a theatrical release, they
almost cancel one another out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burn Rubber'' looks most like a commercial for safe sex. In it
two gay men who have been seeing each other drive off in a
convertible for a romantic weekend and show that they didn't forget
to pack lots of condoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cherish,'' one of two non-French films added to the package,
is particularly touching. An AIDS widower mourns his dead lover in
flashbacks of happy days, as he goes about ordinary daily tasks
like washing the dishes. Grief may be the most prevalent AIDS
experience now, remembering our friends, relatives and lovers who
got sick and died too soon for protease inhibitor cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Ordinary Night,'' in which a seemingly joyous young man
sings as he rides his bicycle to his date, is also effective. The
date turns out to be a night at the hospital with his dying
boyfriend. ``Inside'' is an affecting monologue by a young man with
AIDS, alone and perpetually indoors, telling his video camera all
the things he wishes he had been able to do (``I'd have liked to
meet a guy.'' ``I'd have liked to grow old.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Reinvented'' is a reminder that despite education and
near-miracles in treatment, the AIDS crisis isn't really over. All
over the world some men and women, young and old, straight and gay,
still say, like the unseen narrator of ``A Moment,'' ``He's too
young to have it'' and act accordingly. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LOVE REINVENTED'
</P>
<P>
   A compilation of 12 short films: ``Close To'' directed by David
Ottenhouse, ``Cherish'' directed by Stephen Jones, ``So What?''
directed by Francois Dupeyron, ``One Moment'' directed by Pierre
Salvadori, ``All Is Not Black'' directed by Philippe Faucon,
``Night Hustler'' directed by Anne Fountaine, ``Pregnant or
Lesbian?'' directed by Francoise Decaux-Thomlet, ``Inside''
directed by Marion Vernoux, ``Tears of AIDS'' directed by Paul
Vecchiali, ``Burn Rubber'' directed by Merzak Allouache, ``The
Seagull'' directed by Nils Tavernier and ``An Ordinary Night''
directed by Jean-Claude Guiguet; in French, with English subtitles.
Compilation released by Jour de Fete Films. Now playing in New York
City. Running time: 72 minutes. This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
