A2234 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     09-30 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORS EXPECT DOW TO TRIPLE ITS CURRENT LEVEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where's the bear?
</P>
<P>
   With half the adult population in the United States invested in
the stock market, that question must be almost always gnawing at
the back of most investors' minds.
</P>
<P>
   It seems impossible that the market could continue with such
strength. In 1982, the Dow Jones industrial average was a mere 777
points.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan pointed
out the possibility of ``irrational exuberance'' in stock values,
the Dow had climbed to more than 6,400.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it is over 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Where's the bear?
</P>
<P>
   If you believe a financial journalist and an economist, nowhere
in sight. James Glassman and Kevin Hassett suggest that you think
big _ really big. They see the Dow more than tripling the current
level, and that's in the next three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   They published those opinions in an article in The Wall Street
Journal in 1998, headlined ``Are Stocks Overvalued? Not a Chance.''
The article discussed a new way of looking at stock values,
ditching the price/earnings ratios that are historically used to
gauge whether stocks prices are overheated.
</P>
<P>
   The article infuriated academics and rallied investors. Glassman
and Hassett decided they were onto something.
</P>
<P>
   Now their opinions are spelled out in a new book, ``Dow 36,000:
The New Strategy for Profiting from the Coming Rise in the Stock
Market'' (Times Books, 294 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Glassman, a seasoned business journalist, was a columnist for
The Washington Post and now writes a financial column for Reader's
Digest. He's a frequent commentator on National Public Radio's
``Morning Edition'' and public television's ``Nightly Business
Report.''
</P>
<P>
   Hassett, who has a doctorate in economics, is a former senior
economist for the Federal Reserve Board and is a resident scholar
at the American Enterprise Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they have thrown out convention, which hasn't been
accurately explaining the phenomenal bull market, and come up with
a new idea. Their timing may be just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``No area of inquiry is more ripe for a paradigm shift than
modern finance,'' they write. ``The old model, which focuses on
historical valuations, does not seem to work any longer. Everyday
investors, spurred on by the efforts of creative thinkers like Tom
and David Gardner, the brothers who launched the Motley Fool Web
site and books, are learning to ignore the experts.''
</P>
<P>
   Glassman and Hassett's concept on valuing stocks is based on a
term they call the ``perfectly reasonable price'' of a stock. To
get to that price, the authors suggest looking at two fundamentals
of a company, dividends and growth.
</P>
<P>
   Their research found that since 1946, dividends have risen on
average more than 6 percent annually, while after-tax earnings have
risen more than 7 percent. With compounding, that means those rates
double about every 10 years, the authors write.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those growth rates are at the heart of our theory about rising
stock prices,'' Glassman and Hassett write. ``They have largely
been ignored by analysts, who prefer to judge stocks by
backward-looking valuation techniques that, much of the time, have
argued against investing in stocks at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Their theory holds even with companies that don't pay dividends,
the authors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dividend is not just the quarterly check you get from a
company,'' they write. ``Microsoft has value now even if we expect
that it will never pay regular dividends as traditionally defined
because, ultimately, someone will take cash out of the firm _
either after a liquidation or after a buyout by another company.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be 100 years before that cash flows into a shareholder's
pocket, but the value of the stock could still reflect that cash
flow today, Glassman and Hassett write.
</P>
<P>
   The book provides interesting fodder on why this stock market
does not appear to be heading towards the bear side anytime soon.
And it shows individual investors how simple math can help them
ride the market as high as it goes.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Got Money? Financial Advice for Your Twenties &AMP; Thirties''
</P>
<P>
   By Jeff Wuorio
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $15
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that more and more universities and colleges
are offering personal finance courses, and students are flocking to
them. The bad news is that the cost of higher education is
exploding, so graduates still often end up with a mountain of debt,
even if they've managed their money wisely. This financial primer
includes Web sites and information on cyberinvesting to bring
</P>
<P>
   basic principles up to date. Wuorio is a financial journalist.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Good enough isn't enough ... Nine Challenges for Companies
that Choose to Be Great''
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Weiss
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $25
</P>
<P>
   Consultant Alan Weiss spends his life going into companies and
telling them commonsense solutions to problems. Now you can buy his
book and avoid his fees. Weiss insists that there is a mediocrity
in American business that has most workers shrugging their
shoulders and saying, ``It's good enough.'' In his book, Weiss
takes shots at corporate boards, executive compensation, legal
eagles and even consultants who come to study a problem and then
stay on to become part of it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lost Art of the Great Speech: How to Write One, How to
Deliver It''
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Dowis
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   Veteran speechwriter Richard Dowis provides a how-to look at
writing and delivering a speech, including anecdotes from a long
career in communications.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
