<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIEGFRIED-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIEGFRIED AND ROY: THE MAGIC BOX': THAT OLD 3D MAGIC, WITH SMOKE
AND TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Movies are not a hospitable medium for magic, at least not the
kind of magic practiced in Las Vegas by Siegfried and Roy.
</P>
<P>
   So the new 3-D Imax film, ``Siegfried and Roy: The Magic Box,''
must be classified a disappointment, even if it did not prove also
to be an overblown compound of windy narration, repetitive
illusions, undernourished biography, swollen music and ludicrous
performance.
</P>
<P>
   After all, moviegoers routinely exposed to the filmmaking magic
that transports them to alien worlds, among imaginary creatures,
into intergalactic explosions and ancient societies, among other
illusions, can hardly be expected to sit jaws agape while a couple
of caped vaudevillians drape cages and make elephants and tigers
and themselves disappear and reappear amid puffs of stage smoke,
belching flames and legions of marching, dancing showgirls.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, thanks to 3-D, a tiger or lion appears to vault
overhead or move close enough to invite a pat on the nose, but
otherwise little seems wondrous about ``Siegfried and Roy,'' which
was directed by Brett Leonard, whose credits include the superior
and more imaginative ``T-Rex: Back to the Cretaceous.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Hopkins, the narrator of ``Siegfried and Roy,'' must
have had all he could do to keep a straight face while intoning its
repetitive words about realizing dreams, the awesome power of
magic, the harmony of man and animal and especially the line about
the character who grew up in ``pre-post-World War II Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is at its most charming in its re-creation of the time
when Siegfried Fischbacher and Roy Uwe Ludwig Horn met as young men
while working as stewards aboard an ocean liner, where they first
joined forces in a magic act (involving Roy's pet cheetah) for its
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Siegfried and Roy'' is at its most cloying at its outset, when
two little boys overdo their awe while wandering backstage into a
meeting with the two magicians that leads to the interwoven,
fanciful depiction of their early life in Germany and their act in
Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Given the popularity of Siegfried and Roy, the reality of their
performance is probably more entertaining than this 3-D cinematic
illusion. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SIEGFRIED AND ROY: THE MAGIC BOX'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brett Leonard; director of photography/visual
effects supervisor, Sean MacLeod Phillips; edited by Jonathan P.
Shaw; music by Alan Silvestri; visual effects production designer,
Michael Hartog; produced by Michael V. Lewis; released by Imax Ltd.
Running time: 50 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Siegfried Fischbacher and Roy Uwe Ludwig Horn
(themselves), Anthony Hopkins (Narrator), John Summers (Teen-Age
Siegfried), Andrew Dunlap (Teen-Age Roy), Dillon McEwin (Young
Siegfried) and Cameron Alexander (Young Roy). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
