<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLUNKETT-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PLUNKETT AND MACLEANE': TAKING FROM THE RICH AND GIVING TO
THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody beats the British when it comes to concocting cinematic
visions of society as a fetid swamp of debauchery and sadism. And
``Plunkett and Macleane,'' the film debut of Jake Scott, a British
director from the world of music video, fits right in to a nasty
tradition that embraces everything from Ken Russell's portraits of
the artist as sacred monster to the kitchen-sink nihilism of
``Trainspotting.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the true adventures of two ``gentlemen'' highwaymen in
the mid-18th century, this frenziedly overdirected hybrid of a
buddy movie and a costume drama could be described as a Hogarthian
panorama of depravity and treachery set to a late-'90s disco beat.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally recalling the gleefully scatological spirit of
``Trainspotting,'' ``Plunkett and Macleane'' reunites two of that
movie's stars, Robert Carlyle and Jonny Lee Miller, as scoundrels
who play a Robin Hood game of stealing from the rich and giving to
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The aristocrats on whom these larcenous antiheroes prey are as
loathsome a bunch of gargoyles as you're likely to encounter in any
film this year. Consumed by greed, lust and vanity, they are
extreme caricatures of corruption and depravity. Leading the list
is Lord Rochester, played by Alan Cumming with an electrical dash,
a smirking, slithering effeminate proto-dandy whose favorite
pastime is ``corrupting the young.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly out of sexual desire and partly out of his innate impulse
toward mischief, Rochester becomes Macleane's tour guide in an
upper-crust social jungle that the movie portrays as a garish
18th-century prototype of the Studio 54 culture rife with drugs,
prostitution and venereal disease.
</P>
<P>
   The movie savagely ridicules 18th-century foppishness in a scene
at a wig maker's where some of the headdresses trotted out are
laugh-out-loud ludicrous. A ballroom dance is depicted as a rowdy
beat-driven free-for-all at which many of the men are flouncing gay
blades and the women voracious leering harpies.
</P>
<P>
   These people are so unattractive that when the pair hold up
their carriages or break into their fancy parties and make off with
their jewels, you practically want to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Will Plunkett (Carlyle), the brains behind the
operation, and his partner, James Macleane (Miller), a thief and
priapic gigolo, are morally superior to the people they rip off.
They're just better looking. Macleane, especially, is as wild and
insatiable as his victims. No sooner has the pair amassed a fresh
trove of stolen treasure than he squanders it at the gaming table
and the tailor's.
</P>
<P>
   The two team up in prison, where Plunkett recognizes Macleane as
a man who, when properly attired and coached, could pass himself
off as a gentleman of leisure. Observing the young man's sexual
stamina with the female prisoners, he also realizes that Macleane's
charms, properly deployed, could help smooth his way into some of
England's grandest houses to glean useful information about the
transportation of money and jewels.
</P>
<P>
   Bribing their way out of prison with a stolen ruby, the two go
into business and soon become 18th-century tabloid stars. Their
first mark is the Lord Chief Justice Gibson, with whose beautiful
daughter, Rebecca (Liv Tyler), Macleane becomes instantly besotted.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson's sadistic second-in-command, Chance (Ken Stott), also
covets Rebecca. And as Plunkett and Macleane pull one daring
robbery after another, Gibson's reputation as a supercop plummets,
while Chance's soars. It all builds up to a daring rescue and chase
in which Plunkett, Macleane and Rebecca flee Chance and an army of
policemen through a network of sewers.
</P>
<P>
   None of it adds up to terribly much beyond a rip-roaring
adventure that shows off Carlyle and Miller as cynical British city
cousins of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PLUNKETT AND MACLEANE'
</P>
<P>
   `Plunkett and Macleane' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has sexual situations
and a lot of bawdy humor.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Jake Scott; written by Robert Wade, Neal Purvis and
Charles McKeown, based on an original screenplay by Selwyn Roberts;
director of photography, John Mathieson; edited by Oral Norrie
Ottey; music by Craig Armstrong; production designer, Norris
Spencer; produced by Tim Bevan, Eric Fellner and Rupert Harvey;
released by USA Films/Gramercy Pictures. Running time: 102 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jonny Lee Miller (James Macleane), Robert Carlyle (Will
Plunkett), Ken Stott (Chance), Alan Cumming (Lord Rochester),
Michael Gambon (Lord Chief Justice Gibson), Liv Tyler (Lady Rebecca
Gibson) and Claire Rushbrook (Lady Estelle). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
