<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUPITER'SBONES-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOPPY EDITING KILLS THIS MURDER MYSTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETSY FRIAUF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Jupiter's Bones''
</P>
<P>
   by Faye Kellerman
</P>
<P>
   Fiction
</P>
<P>
   William Morrow, $25
</P>
<P>
   This could have been a good book.
</P>
<P>
   The elements are there. 1. Corpse of eccentric person found in
mysterious circumstances. 2. Several suspects with motives. 3.
Harried detective with a wife and children who want him home rather
than out chasing hunches on his own time.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Jupiter's Bones'' lacks three things: an editor, another
editor and a proofreader.
</P>
<P>
   Descriptive passages go on too long. The action bogs down. Far
too many words are devoted to developing the wackiness of the cult
that the deceased person led. One imagines the editors of this book
_ if there were any _ sitting around thinking up stupid character
names when they should have been doing the sweaty work of pruning
words and sentences while leaving the pith. ... Uh, let's see, was
it Pluto or Nova who signed the death certificate?
</P>
<P>
   There's far too much telling rather than showing. An editor
could have explained to Faye Kellerman that verbs speak louder than
adjectives or even adverbs. And for heaven's sake, let's please not
have any ``noxious habits.'' Let's just smoke and hide the butts.
</P>
<P>
   Far too many strain-your-credibility scenes are included to
accentuate the good-guyness of Detective Pete Decker. He keeps
peace among his subordinates. He mollifies his wife even though
she's trapped all day with a 5-year-old and he breaks yet another
date. He talks his teen son into giving up dope, porn films and sex
with his true love, all in one conversation (interrupted, of
course, by a call from the office).
</P>
<P>
   Less than halfway through the book, the reader begins to hope
the detective is really the perpetrator. It'd take a murder to tip
his scales away from saintliness.
</P>
<P>
   One hesitates to bring up typographical errors when one's own
newspaper recenty, for lack of an ``r,'' turned a pantry into an
article of feminine clothing. But let's do it anyway. Worse than
the abundance of typos in ``Jupiter's Bones'' is the omission of
crucial words. The reader can usually decipher what is meant. But
one doesn't expect the price of a book to include Mad Libs, the old
parlor game of fill-in-the-blank.
</P>
<P>
   It's too long, the writing is stilted and the editing and
proofreading are shoddy. But it has a plot, all right, albeit a
formulaic one. If the Heaven's Gate tragedy interested you, this
book may be worth a look. But one is reluctant to endorse a work in
which the publisher seemed to have so little faith.
</P>
<P>
   (Betsy Friauf works on the ``Star-Telegram's'' features copy
desk. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
