<SLUG> BC-ROSE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW ROSE HOTEL': CORPORATE INTRIGUE, STEAMY SEDUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end.) 
(jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Abel Ferrara began making a directorial name for himself in
the early 1980s, it was as a bad-boy filmmaker with tastes for
lurid sex, gritty violence and gripping, stylish stories of life in
the fast lane going wrong. It's a sign of the times that Ferrara,
whose cinematic obsessions have barely changed, has come to seem
positively tame. But even though the threshold for onscreen
exploitativeness has been raised ever higher, this filmmaker's work
still retains its peculiar innocence. Nobody could have made ``Bad
Lieutenant'' without taking it to heart.
</P>
<P>
   Sleaze notwithstanding, Ferrara's work hews firmly to its own
ideas of purity. He continues to encourage stony leading men toward
remarkable feats of self-flagellation, and to have faith in the
ability of kinky eroticism to settle most situations.
</P>
<P>
   After ``The Blackout,'' which surfaced at Cannes in 1997 and
confirmed that his tastes had not remotely changed, Ferrara is back
with ``New Rose Hotel.'' As written by the director with Christ
Zois, it is adapted from a story by William Gibson and affirms that
soft-core porn is alive and well in cyberpunk.
</P>
<P>
   Willem Dafoe and Christopher Walken are Exhibits A and B this
time, allowing themselves to be drawn into the steamy turmoil of
Ferrara's world. In a story that involves corporate intrigue, they
play spies trying to seduce a Japanese geneticist with the help of
one of those compliant, dreamy prostitutes (Asia Argento) who loom
so large in the filmmaker's imagination. As ever in Ferrara's
films, the steam is on, the ridiculous only is at arm's length and
the credits are intriguing. The musicians Ryuichi Sakamoto (who won
an Oscar for ``The Last Emperor'') and John Lurie turn up in the
cast, as does Annabella Sciorra. The geneticist in this
international tale is played by Yoshitaka Amano, a big man in the
world of designing video games.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NEW ROSE HOTEL'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``New Rose Hotel'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity,
nudity, sex, violence and decadent situations. It couldn't exist
without them.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Abel Ferrara; written by Ferrara and Christ Zois,
based on the short story by William Gibson; director of
photography, Ken Kelsch; edited by Anthony Redman; music by
Schoolly D; produced by Edward R. Pressman; released by Avalanche
Releasing. Running time: 93 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Willem Dafoe (X), Christopher Walken (Fox), Asia Argento
(Sandi), Yoshitaka Amano (Hiroshi), Annabella Sciorra (Madame
Rosa), John Lurie (Distinguished Man) and Ryuichi Sakamoto
(Hiroshi's Executive).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
