<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2294 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-WEB03     09-30 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WEB03 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A wardrobe off the web off the web
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3
 &HT;    By Goutami Hyma Mikkilineni
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As each day passes, virtual shopping becomes more of a virtual
necessity. In sprawling metropolises such as Atlanta, the time it
takes to drive to a mall or boutique can exceed the time one has to
shop.
</P>
<P>
   E-tailing for clothes can save you time and money.
</P>
<P>
   And, thanks to the horizon-broadening nature of the World Wide
Web, shopping online could spare you the embarrassment of arriving
at an event wearing something that somebody else has on.
</P>
<P>
   After extensive Net surfing, we've honed homed in on a handful
of e-tail sites that stand out.
</P>
<P>
   THE SITES
</P>
<P>
   www.bluefly.com
</P>
<P>
   Overview: Bluefly buys designer goods at a discount and claims
to charge its e-customers 35 percent to 40 percent less than
department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Rear view: Calvin Klein cotton briefs that cost $6.50 or more at
department stores are only $4 per pair from Bluefly.
</P>
<P>
   Obstructed view: All e-tailing entails delayed gratification.
Bluefly offers three delivery options: Standard (three to five
business days for $3.95), two-day delivery ($9.95) or overnight
($14.95). There's a 90-day grace period for returns, which might
come in handy, because Bluefly doesn't offer ``virtual modeling''
of its merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   www.gap.com
</P>
<P>
   Bridging the divide: This site is eerily similar to Gap stores
themselves. Everything even costs the same. The e-tail advantage is
the wider range of colors and sizes available online. Filling the
void: Given that there's no chain with more outlets and no easier
store to shop at than the Gap, a Web site seems like overkill. If
there were a price advantage to shopping the Gap online, this site
would be more useful. As it is, it acts as one huge advertising
vehicle. Gap fanatics, delve right in.
</P>
<P>
   Perk up: This site makes gift-giving easy. Once you enter loved
ones' birth dates, for example, the site reminds you to place an
order on time. Shipping is fast and the delivery cost is nominal.
</P>
<P>
   www.clinique.com
</P>
<P>
   Bonus time: Can't find your favorite shade of Clinique makeup at
the nearest mall? Log on to this site for the full complement of
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Face time: The site offers tips, demonstrations and previews of
the company's upcoming free gift offers. It also advises online
shoppers to visit a Clinique counter instead of the site if they're
not sure what they want. Good advice, because if the tint on your
computer screen is off, you could wind up purchasing a very wrong
shade of eyeliner. But if you're looking for new supplies of old
favorites, have at it.
</P>
<P>
   Prime time: Unless you pay extra shipping costs, it's going to
take a week to get your makeup.
</P>
<P>
   www.lancome.com
</P>
<P>
   More than skin deep: This site is gorgeous, with arguably the
Web's best tips on applying makeup and directions easy enough for
any cosmetics novice to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Pore choices: The dizzying breadth and depth of Lancome's
cosmetics are showcased with exceptional visuals. And the site
offers good advice about coordinating colors.
</P>
<P>
   Lip service: The only letdown is that you can't actually make
purchases from this site. It merely whets your
</P>
<P>
   appetite for the products and lists stores where they're
available. No word on whether they'll be e-tailing in the future.
</P>
<P>
   www.ashford.com
</P>
<P>
   Dollar figures: This site is a must-see for those who like to
dress as if they do all their shopping out of town. Besides items
such as Cartier watches and Louis Vuitton bags, there's also a
``shop'' for vintage apparel. If price is no object, point your
mouse here.
</P>
<P>
   Greener pastures: This 6-month-old site's ``boutique'' section
is still under construction. When it's finished, Ashford promises
to offer the most glamorous clothes from the world's fashion
capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Handling charges: Ashford doesn't charge for shipping. And why
should it, when it's already charging top dollar for the
merchandise?
</P>
<P>
   www.eoffprice.com
</P>
<P>
   A penny saved: This site rivals Bluefly in the level of savings
offered. Eoffprice claims that its designer clothes are discounted
from 25 percent to 75 percent off manufacturers' suggested retail
prices.The best deal: women's Calvin Klein jeans for $29.50.
</P>
<P>
   Slow credit: The merchandise selection appears limited. And
shipping can be confusing, because this site caters to customers
worldwide. Also, delivery takes from one to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Small change: Eoffprice, which offers children's wear as well,
might appeal to parents who dread trotting their offspring to malls
for clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Goutami Hyma Mikkilineni writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
