<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern festivals
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Suches, Ga. _ The 22nd Annual Indian Summer Festival Saturday
and Sunday features exhibits of pottery, folk art, antiques,
leather craft, quilts, pine furniture and baskets. Also, food,
entertainment, quilt show, auction and Saturday night dance.
706-747-5434.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clarkesville, Ga. _ The Third Annual Harvest of Habersham
Saturday and Sunday features an art show and sale, antiques,
entertainment, antique car show, children's activities, a farmer's
market and down-home cooking. Gary Puckett performs at 5 p.m.
Saturday; the Tams, 3 p.m. Sunday. 706-778-4654.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Andersonville, Ga. _ The Andersonville Historic Fair Saturday
and Sunday features historic characters plus 600 re-enactors in
Civil War garb. Also, Civil War collectibles, antiques, arts,
crafts and two battle re-enactments. The Sumter Players will
present ``The Andersonville Trial.'' 912-924-2558.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tifton, Ga. _ Saturday's Fourth Annual La Fiesta del Pueblo
celebrates Hispanic culture with a parade, folkloric dance, pinata
breaking, arts and crafts exhibits, Mariachi music and authentic
foods. 912-382-8878 (Luz Marti) or 912-386-3558 (Arts Station).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Savannah, Ga. _ Oktoberfest on the River Festival Friday
through Sunday features German food and beverages, oompah bands and
the Swingin' Medallions. 912-920-3209 or www.savriverstreet.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jonesborough, Tenn. _ The National Storytelling Festival
Friday through Sunday showcases storytellers, stories and
traditions from across America and around the world. 423-753-2171.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ The Fourth Annual Celebration of Fine Craft on
the city's revitalized riverfront next to the Tennessee Aquarium is
Saturday and Sunday. The craft fair sponsored by the Tennessee
Association of Craft Artists features contemporary work for sale by
nearly 100 regional artists. 423-697-1335 or 615-665-0502.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans _ Audubon Zoo's 15th Anniversary Louisiana Swamp
Fest, Saturday and Sunday and Oct. 9-10, includes Cajun and zydeco
music, Louisiana food and crafts, and Cajun lifestyle presentations
including boat builders, weavers and wood carvers. 1-800-774-7394
or www.auduboninstitute.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston _ ``The Charleston Barbados Connection'' is the
theme of the Charleston Garden Festival opening Thursday and
continuing through Sunday. The event includes a Southern Garden
Symposium, guided tours of private plantations, walking tours of
gardens, lectures and how-to demonstrations, a plant swap,
Plantation Dinner and rare plant auction and Caribbean Garden Gala.
843-762-1855.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mobile, Ala. _ The Fifth Annual BayFest, an outdoor music
festival showcasing more than 100 national and local acts on seven
stages, is Friday through Sunday. Acts include John Michael
Montgomery, the Robert Cray Band, B.B. King, Chaka Khan and Hank
Williams Jr. 334-470-7730.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Athens, Ala. _ The Tennessee Valley Old Time Fiddlers
Convention is Friday and Saturday at the Athens State University
campus. An arts and crafts fair will be held in conjunction with
the event. 256-233-8100 or www.athens.edu/fiddlers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The 10th Annual Thomas Wolfe Festival is
Friday through Sunday at the Thomas Wolfe Memorial. The festival
includes lectures, walking tours and special performances honoring
the life and work of the author, a native son. 828-253-8304.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ Michaelmas: An English Harvest Fair
continues weekends through Oct. 24 at Biltmore Estate, which is
reviving the traditional feast day celebration dating to
sixth-century England. The event includes music and theatrical
performances in the Italian garden, crafts demonstrations and jazz
concerts at the Winery. 828-255-1174 or www.biltmore.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brevard, N.C. _ Forest Festival Day on Saturday celebrates the
forest heritage with mountain music, crafts and a lumberjack
competition at the Cradle of Forestry. 828-877-3130.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
