<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2296 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-GETAWAY01-COX     09-30 1867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tobacco town rises from the ashes
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA, Fla. _ When the shade tobacco business went belly up and
the canning company closed in the 1960s, this little
wide-spot-in-the-road town near Tallahassee just about rolled up
its sidewalks. Nothing much happened for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1984, a renaissance began when Lee Hotchkiss and Keith
Henderson moved their Tallahassee antiques shop to an ivy-covered
brick building at Main Street and Seventh Avenue in the heart of
Havana.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;H Antiques became the cornerstone of what is now one of the
Southeast's largest arts and antiques centers. Earlier this month,
Tallahassee Magazine bestowed its Best Antiques Shop award
collectively on all of Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Although businesses have come and gone in the past 15 years,
there are nearly 40 antiques shops, galleries, boutiques and cafes,
enough to keep a visitor busy for a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend the town will be abuzz with the 4th Annual Havana
Bead and Jewelry Festival. And looking even further ahead, Havana
MusicFest 2000 is set for March 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   The town, with a population of 1,500, chugs ahead like the
Little Engine That Could, despite the deaths this year of two of
its biggest boosters: watercolorist Lee Mainella, who founded the
Florida Art Center and Gallery, and Paul Nicholson, founder of the
popular Nicholson Farmhouse Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost two pillars of the community,'' says Sandi Beare,
co-owner of Mirror Image Antiques and self-appointed one-woman
visitors bureau. ``They are the type of people who inspire you to
carry on. We would be remiss if we did not continue'' what they
pioneered.
</P>
<P>
   Mirror Image specializes in antiques, fishing collectibles and
baseball and sports memorabilia. The space also includes the Vault
Art Gallery, inside a 1906 bank vault.
</P>
<P>
   Beare's father, Richard Beare, runs Lord Beare's Gourmet
Specialties in a small pantry in the back of the shop. Among the
dozens of items offered there are English teas, McVitie's Original
Digestion Biscuits, Scott's Porage Oats, clotted cream and frozen
entrees such as Cornish pasties and Scottish beef bridies.
</P>
<P>
   While Havana made its reputation as an art and antiques mecca,
``We are becoming an international design marketplace,'' Beare
says.
</P>
<P>
   Home furnishings abound _ from international finds hand-picked
by Terri Paul in Africa, the Philippines, Indonesia, South America,
Mexico and China at Wanderings to plain Amish designs from Amish
Country Oak Furniture and Tarahumana Gardens. There's antique
wicker and old wrought iron patio furniture at Specialty Designs,
child-size wooden furniture made by Davey Edwards at Carole's Doll
Shoppe, and just about anything you might want, new or old, spread
through two buildings and a veranda at the massive Antiques Center.
</P>
<P>
   Little River General Store feels as homey as its name.
Proprietor Rita Love stocks kitchen gadgets, country gourmet foods,
wooden and metal toys (no plastic!), gardening tools, household
cleaning agents, natural health and beauty aids, Woolrich clothing
and much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a froufrou gift shop,'' says Love. ``Everything I
sell is useful and has a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   At H&AMP;H Antiques, where it all started, Hotchkiss and Henderson
help clients select furniture and upholstery from their Norwalk
line. They've expanded from antiques and now offer custom-made
heart pine and cherry reproductions made by local craftsmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturday and Sunday, the town is packed,'' says Hotchkiss,
who lives above the store with her business partner. ``People like
it that you're usually dealing directly with the owner of the
store. You get better service.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the H&AMP;H team, Christy Parks-Witt and her family live in the
100-year-old house where she runs her business, the Berry Patch.
The shop not only offers quality antiques, Heirloom lace and a line
of bath and home aromatherapy products, but it welcomes guests to
the Tea Room on Wednesdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a great summer,'' says Parks-Witt. ``We're seeing a
lot of tourists, but the local folks are getting smart and keeping
their money in our county. Tons of people are moving in. Young
couples are buying homes in the historic district. You can raise
your family here. It's more like Mayberry RFD.''
</P>
<P>
   Artist Jay ``Animal'' Williams thrives in the laid-back
atmosphere. ``It's quiet here, and I need that. This really is the
place for an artist to be.''
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Florida State University in Tallahassee, Williams
works at his Laffing Bird Gallery, creating whimsical works of art
_ mirrors, brooches and kaleidoscopes _ from stained glass and
broken china, as well as abstract sculptures in brass, copper,
steel, glass and found objects. He is working on an intricate
stained glass ``painting'' of an undersea scene that involves
fitting together hundreds of pieces of glass like a jigaw puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love people,'' says Williams, who'll chat with visitors no
matter how busy he is. ``A lot of my work has to do with humanity.
I feel alientated by modern culture _ computers, answering
machines. I want some human response in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of blocks away at Havana's Cannery, ownerTrey Morgan
is turning out small batches of his private-label sauces, which
include honey mustard, barbecue and citrus ketchup. The Cannery is
a 31,000-square-foot antiques mall with more than 100 antiques
dealers, plus Rafters Interior Market, Shade restaurant and the
bottling operation. Constructed in 1934, the two-story building was
home to Havana Canning Co. for nearly three decades, followed by
Cal's Tupelo Honey until 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a spark here,'' says Morgan, a Tallahassean who
purchased the building in 1994. ``It's been here awhile. It's not
an easy business we've picked, but I'm sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan predicts that Havana's best days are yet to come. ``It
takes time. Lee Mainella knew how to do it. He taught me. It's
coming to fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Getting there
</P>
<P>
   Take I-85 south to I-185; continue until I-185 ends in south
Columbus, then pick up U.S. 27 south. Follow the highway; watch
signs for turns, but stay on U.S. 27 through Bainbridge and
directly into Havana, which is 12 miles north of Tallahassee. It's
250 miles from Atlanta, about a five-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   Hours
</P>
<P>
   Most shops are open Wednesdays through Sundays. Hours are
generally 10 a.m. until 5 or 6 p.m., except noon-5 p.m. Sundays.
The Cannery is open until 10 p.m. Fridays and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 850-539-4852.
</P>
<P>
   Events/attractions
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 4th Annual Havana Bead and Jewelry Festival: More than 100
bead makers, distributors and jewelry artists are expected to
gather this weekend at Havana's Cannery, 115 E. 8th Ave. 10 a.m.-6
p.m. Saturday and 11 a.m.-5 p.m. Sunday. $3. Information:
850-539-3800.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Qunicy Music Theatre: The restored Leaf Theatre (yes,
we're talking tobacco leaf) in downtown Quincy, 10 miles west of
Havana on Fla. 12, opens its four-musical season with ``Nunsense,''
with performances Oct. 7-9 and Oct. 15-17. $9; $8 seniors and $6
students. Tickets: 850-875-9444. Web site: qmt.homepage.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The North Florida Art Trail: Pick up a copy of the brochure
with map at the Gadsden County Chamber of Commerce in Quincy. (Or
call ahead for a copy at 850-627-9231.) Designated by the Florida
Legislature in 1997, the trail begins in Havana and travels along
Fla. 12 through the communities of Quincy, Greensboro and
Chattahoochee, inviting travelers on a self-guided tour of the
arts, antiques, agriculture, history and natural amenities of the
region. Along the trail are art galleries, historic tobacco barns,
Victorian homes (including Havana's 150-year-old McLauchlin House,
which now houses six antiques shops), bed-and-breakfast inns,
working artists' studios and murals.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nicholson Farmhouse: This complex of rustic farmhouses is on a
50-acre tract of woods and pasture on Fla. 12, 3 1/2 miles west of
Havana. The main dining room is in the 140-year-old Nicholson
House, where ``wet-aged'' steaks ($12.95-$25.95), lamb chops
($17.95) and shrimp ``farmhouse-style'' ($18.95) are among the
offerings. Boiled peanuts are brought to the table with the water.
4-10 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays. Reservations advised. 850-539-5931.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shade: As in shade tobacco. This diner, inside the Cannery,
features a tobacco-leaf decor and New Southern cuisine. Lunch
specialties include a fried green tomato sandwich with goat cheese
crumbles and a fried catfish sandwich with jalapeno tartar sauce
(both $6, served with choice of hot stir-fried slaw, sweet potato
haystack or cheese grits cake); grilled country sausage with beans
and rice topped with the Cannery's own mustard sauce ($7); and
black-eyed pea cakes with herb-roasted sour cream on a bed of
Southern succotash ($5). Save room for homemade desserts. Lunch,
11:30 a.m.-3:30 p.m. Wednesdays-Sundays; supper, 5-9:30 p.m.
Fridays-Saturdays. 115 E. Eighth Ave. 850-539-3800.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dolly's Expresso Cafe: Lunch specials include a half Cuban
sandwich with a side of black beans and yellow rice ($5.40) and a
chicken salad plate ($6.50). Also, specialty coffee drinks, ice
cream and desserts, such as Key lime pie, tiramisu and cannoli. 11
a.m.-4:30 p.m. Tuesdays-Thursdays (until 5:30 Fridays-Saturdays)
and noon-5 p.m. Sunday. 206 First St. N.W. 850-539-6716.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Berry Patch: The Tea Room is open on Wednesdays and by
appointment. You'll be served tea sandwiches (chicken, ham salad
and cucumber), scones with clotted cream and jam, apricot tarts,
lemon-butter cups and the signature strawberry bread and choice of
tea. $14 per person. 117 E. Sixth Ave. By reservation only:
850-539-6988.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Historic Havana House Bed &AMP; Breakfast: Bunking at this 1907
home in a residential area two blocks from the shopping district is
like staying with relatives. Your hosts will be innkeepers Bruce
and Shirley Gaver. There are two guest rooms with private bathrooms
in this renovated dwelling, which was built by the first mayor of
Havana. The entrance is at the back door, where you're likely to be
greeted by Whiskers the tabby cat. There's a small garden and a
screened porch with a swing. Art and stained glass, much of it
created by the Gavers, along with antiques and collectibles
brighten the interior. Rates are $80 and $90, including a full
country breakfast. 301 E. Sixth Ave. Reservations: 850-539-5611 or
visit www.electro-net.com/(tilde)sgaver.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Allison House: Built in 1843 by former Florida Gov. A.K.
Allison, this English-style bed-and-breakfast in nearby Quincy is
one of the oldest residences in the area. The inn, with five
comfortably appointed rooms filled with English antiques, is
operated by Stuart and Eileen Johnson, who'll be happy to supply
you with a copy of the walking tour brochure that will guide you
through the town's 36-block historic district. Rates are $75 to
$90. 215 N. Madison St. 1-888-904-2511.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
