<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2306 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-RONSTADT01-COX     09-30 1369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RONSTADT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With her rock star days long gone, singer Ronstadt prefers
keeping things simple
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You won't see Linda Ronstadt's story on VH1's ``Behind the
Music'' anytime soon. No boxed set of her four-decade career or
graying reunion tour with her former backup band, the Eagles. As
shocking as it may seem to the millions of fans who made her the
queen of California country-rock in the 1970s, when she warbled
such honey-powered hits as ``Blue Bayou'' and ``You're No Good,''
Ronstadt says she gladly _ no, ecstatically _ dropped out of the
pop mainstream. And she has no desire to go back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rock 'n' roll is the least authentic thing I ever did,'' she
says bluntly, calling from her publicist's office in New York. ``It
was unbearable. I was unhappy onstage and unhappy performing. I
never felt happy. I never felt like a basic part of me was being
expressed. It's just a tiny part of my personality. I didn't love
it like other people did. It seemed a little junky even when I was
a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa. This is Linda Ronstadt talking? With her darkly beautiful
looks and rich alto voice, the singer probably got more young women
to listen to pop radio in the Me Decade than just about any other
female artist. She sold millions of records, took home a passel of
Grammy Awards and had a who's who of guitar-slinging rocker
boyfriends along the way. Country diva Trisha Yearwood says the
only reason she's in the business is that Ronstadt's big sound
compelled her to sing into a hairbrush as a kid. There's hardly a
young country female vocalist, from gutsy Terri Clark to tiny
Martina McBride, who doesn't credit Ronstadt's early, hippie-tinged
forays into twang for making the genre alluring and hip to an
entire generation of women who didn't favor beehive hairdos.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling the plugs
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very, very successful blending the pop-rock and the
country stuff,'' observes Bob Bailey of Atlanta oldies station Fox
97. ``She sort of took her career in a lot of different directions:
the Broadway thing, the Spanish-language album. But I think it is
that '70s success that people remember most.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the 53-year-old vocalist, who makes a rare live
appearance Sunday at Symphony Hall with duet partner Emmylou Harris
to promote their new ``Western Wall: The Tucson Sessions'' album,
considers herself retired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't perform very much and don't tour very much,'' Ronstadt
says unapologetically. ``I made a real concerted effort to stop it
since I turned 40. First, I stopped singing in English. Then I
stopped touring, then I stopped recording in English. I did come
back and make two more (English-language albums), but all during
that I wanted a life and a home.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what she got in the early 1990s. Fed up with the
superficial demands of the entertainment business, Ronstadt moved
home to Tucson, Ariz., where she adopted two children and focused
her energies on getting back to basics. First she threw out her
vinyl album collection, including even the Rolling Stones records
(off which she had one of the most popular cover hits of her
career, the raunchy ``Tumbling Dice''). Then she pulled the plug on
the television, the VCR, the CD player, the dishwasher and even the
touch-tone telephone. She hangs clothes out on the line and listens
only to National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took out everything in my house that blinked except for the
children,'' she says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Critics who have seen the Ronstadt-Harris show in other cities
say that Ronstadt indeed seems to approach the stage with the
casualness of someone who's just come in from the garden. In
Phoenix, she wore rolled-up bluejeans, a denim shirt and clogs.
She's heavier than the days when she posed in Daisy Duke
short-shorts for album covers, but she seems much happier.
</P>
<P>
   Memories for a generation
</P>
<P>
   ``TV is so unkind to music,'' she says. ``My whole life I've
tried to stay off of it. It's too narrow a sound band, and the
image with the little square box just defeats everything. TV became
so influential in trying to dispense our music, but it's like
dipping a gourd into a vat of kerosene. The music had to be altered
to go through the medium, and it was the undoing of pop music in
this culture. It destroyed regionalism, subtlety, anything that
wasn't mass-produced.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album with Harris, with whom Ronstadt has collaborated
since they made ``I Can't Help It (If I'm Still in Love With You)''
in 1975, is a low-key exploration in which the pair weave their
harmonies around many sounds and styles. Recorded at the Arizona
Inn in Tucson, the album is much less country than the duo's work
with Dolly Parton. It drifts toward the more experimental,
featuring material from writers such as Patty Griffin, Sinead
O'Connor and Leonard Cohen. The title track was penned by Rosanne
Cash.
</P>
<P>
   Ronstadt usually tosses in one or two gems during the live show.
Sometimes it's ``Heart Like a Wheel''; sometimes it's ``It Doesn't
Matter Anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Steve Harris, who is bringing the duo to Symphony Hall,
says he feels that Ronstadt has ``gotten back to music that is her
calling,'' and that's the attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (people in the audience) are there to hear the kind of
songs they grew up with,'' Harris says. ``These were superstars in
the old days, seen minimally at the Fox or Chastain. To see them in
a 2,000-seat room is a treat. When we announced the show, my
attorney called me four times wanting tickets. The fans have got
the enthusiasm back.''
</P>
<P>
   It's certainly memories of sweet, granola rock that sent
49-year-old Bert Kelley of Buckhead to stand in line at Symphony
Hall the morning tickets went on sale. The show sold out within
hours, with many seats going to middle-aged fans who abandoned live
music years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been to a concert in 20 or 25 years,'' Kelley says.
``I remember swearing them off in my 20s because of the crowds and,
unless you had tremendous seats, you couldn't see anything. But
when I opened up the paper and saw that picture of Linda and
Emmylou together at Symphony Hall, it just did something to me. I
played these two women's albums over and over again. ``Silver
Threads and Golden Needles,'' ``Don't Cry Now.'' As a young, single
woman, their music spoke to me. I don't even have any of the albums
anymore, and it's made me want to go out and get all their CDs.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MUSIC OF LINDA RONSTADT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1966: ``Different Drum,'' with the Stone Poneys, introduces
Ronstadt as a miniskirted member of the Southern California
country-rock mafia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1970: ``Long, Long Time,'' from ``Silk Purse,'' scores a hit.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1972: Becomes first pop star to record Dolly Parton's ``I Will
Always Love You.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1973: ``Love Has No Pride,'' from ``Don't Cry Now,'' is
released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1974: Top-selling album ``Heart Like a Wheel,'' featuring ``It
Doesn't Matter Anymore,'' ``You're No Good'' and ``When Will I Be
Loved,'' is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1975: Becomes queen of cover songs with the hits ``Heat
Wave,'' ``Love Is a Rose'' and ``Tracks of My Tears.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1977: ``Blue Bayou,'' ``It's So Easy,'' ``Poor Pitiful Me''
and ``Tumbling Dice,'' from ``Simple Dreams,'' are released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1978: Becomes one of the first mainstream American artists to
cover an Elvis Costello song, ``Alison,'' on the ``Back in the
USA'' album.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1981: Ditches rock to perform in ``The Pirates of Penzance''
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1984: Dabbles in torch songs on ``Lush Life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1986: Does it again on ``For Sentimental Reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1987: Wins Grammy Award for the country-flavored ``Trio''
album with Dolly Parton and Emmylou Harris. Records
Spanish-language album ``Canciones de me Padre'' and resurfaces on
adult-contemporary charts with ``Somewhere Out There,'' the theme
song from the animated movie ``An American Tail.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1989: Teams up with New Orleans soul man Aaron Neville on
``Don't Know Much.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1999: ``Trio II,'' with Harris and Parton, and ``Western Wall:
The Tucson Sessions,'' with Harris, are released.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Miriam Longino
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
