<HEADER>
A2309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MCCAIN-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     09-30 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 `FAITH OF MY FATHERS': STANDING HUMBLY BEFORE A McCAIN FAMILY(EDS: Publication notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The appearance of Sen. John McCain's ``Faith of My Fathers''
seems to have been timed to the unfolding presidential campaign in
which McCain, an Arizona Republican, is a candidate. But this book
is not your typical campaign autobiography, and this is because
McCain has not had the experience of your typical candidate.
</P>
<P>
   His book, which centers on his seven years as a prisoner of war
in Vietnam, is a testament to the martial values of honor and
patriotism. It is also a record of McCain's struggle to live up to
the expectations passed down from generation to generation in a
family that has served in the armed forces since before the
Revolutionary War.
</P>
<P>
   McCain provides admiring portraits of his grandfather, John
McCain Sr., and his father, John McCain Jr., both of whom were
four-star admirals in the U.S. Navy. He tells of his own early
introduction to the martial tradition of his family as well as his
rebellious bottom-of-the-class performance at the Naval Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the centerpiece of this book is McCain's account of his
years of imprisonment, during which he and his fellow POWs fought
against the determined effort of the enemy to take away their
souls.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his straightforward recitation of those nightmare
years, McCain remains a model of modesty, giving credit for greater
bravery to others who, he says, endured more than he did and showed
greater powers of resistance.
</P>
<P>
   But if he never presents himself as a hero _ and he does not
conceal what he regards as his one terrible moment of capitulation
to his captors _ it is impossible to read this book without
realizing that a hero is what he is.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a review of a book, not a man, and thus the question
remains: Has McCain written a good book? Certainly ``Faith of My
Fathers,'' which McCain wrote with his legislative assistant, Mark
Salter, is lively and readable. One learns a good deal about the
character and philosophy of this presidential candidate, although
one learns pretty much nothing about his current political program
or of his life, private or public, since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's book is in this sense a modest achievement of both the
autobiographical and the prison-writing genres. Almost everything
before the chapters on the POW experience seems like a sketchy
preface. The story of his imprisonment is vivid and concrete and
ought to be read, but McCain has written of it with terse
effectiveness before.
</P>
<P>
   He begins with a memorable family scene: his father and his
grandfather meeting on the bridge of a submarine tender in Tokyo
Bay right after the Japanese surrender. In his first several
chapters he summarizes their careers and provides affectionate
sketches of them, complete with testimonials from others. He cites,
for example, a radio commentator who declared his grandfather ``one
of the world's greatest carrier task force commanders, an
outstanding example of American manhood at sea.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain does not want only to express admiration of his father
and grandfather but to explicate what he sees as both a privilege
and a burden. ``The relationship of a sailor and his children is,
in large part, a metaphysical one,'' he writes. ``By your father's
calling, you are born into an exclusive, noble tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain says that noble tradition required him to live up to a
standard of courage set by the father and grandfather who went
before him. During one moment, after enduring savage beatings that
continued for days, McCain tape-records a phony confession that is
used in North Vietnamese propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   He recovers his self-esteem after that moment, which he sees as
a failure, a weakness; but nothing seems more important to him than
his father's laconic absolution of him for it. ``You did the best
you could, John,'' his father tells him after his release. ``That's
all that's expected of any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's father was the commander of all U.S. forces in the
Pacific for many of the years in which his son was a POW, and that
led to a special situation for McCain. When the Vietnamese wanted
to score a propaganda victory by offering to release him ahead of
his jailed comrades, McCain, despite being tortured and badly in
need of medical treatment, refused.
</P>
<P>
   Typically he does not give himself a great deal of credit for
this honorable and courageous stand. Instead he talks about the
inspiration provided by his father and grandfather and by the
amazing spirit of resistance demonstrated by the other Americans
held in Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered love and honor,'' he writes. ``If you valued
them, and held them strongly, love and honor would endure
undiminished by the passing of time and the most determined assault
on your dignity. And to hold on to love and honor, I needed to be
part of a fraternity. I was not as strong a man as I once believed
myself to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Here and there one wishes for greater specificity and more
openness. It seems coy of McCain, for example, to talk about two
American prisoners in Hanoi who openly sided with the enemy and
received privileges in return without giving their names. He talks
glowingly about the steadfastness of his wife, Carol, who raised
his three children alone while he was imprisoned, but he does not
even mention that the two were divorced after his return, and that
he remarried.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain's description of what he and his fellow prisoners
endured is gritty and moving. He shows admirable restraint here. He
tells us about being regularly beaten or of having his arms roped
and pulled behind him and left that way overnight, but he does not
ask us to share his pain.
</P>
<P>
   Early on he says that if you haven't been a POW yourself, it is
impossible fully to understand what it was like. That is certainly
true. Yet one can understand a pithy something about it thanks to
this restrained and honest account.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FAITH OF MY FATHERS'
</P>
<P>
   By John McCain with Mark Salter.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 349 pages. Random House. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
