<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GAME'S UP FOR A PITCHER, A THIEF AND A SUBURBAN DAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `BLUE STREAK' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martin Lawrence, Luke Wilson, Dave Chappelle, Peter Greene &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Les Mayfield &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 93 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What is it with you and heating ducts?'' a Los Angeles police
detective asks Malone (Lawrence), the newly appointed head of the
burglary division. Any time Malone spots a grating around the
precinct house, he wants to rip it open and crawl right in.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Malone really isn't Malone but Logan, a jewel
thief who, while fleeing a compromised robbery situation two years
earlier, taped an $18 million diamond to the ventilation system of
what was then a building under construction and is now the police
station.
</P>
<P>
   To retrieve the stone, he impersonates an officer. After
heroically disarming a suspect who happens to be an old criminal
buddy, he gets promoted and starts his diamond hunt in earnest.
With his past experience, he's highly qualified to lead the
burglary squad.
</P>
<P>
   For example, out at the airport he gives an impromptu primer on
how big thefts are faked to mask bigger drug deliveries. He can
also spot a prison tattoo at 30 paces.
</P>
<P>
   His fellow officers are so impressed that they are reduced to
straight men for Malone's jivey patter. But the diamond hunt is
sidetracked by a drug case. The FBI gets involved. So does a former
associate who wants the rock for himself.
</P>
<P>
   A multi-wreck car and truck chase pulls up at the Mexican
border, which works out well for Malone. By now he has been found
out and needs another lineage. Has he told anybody that he's part
Mexican? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE For all the clowning, shootings and beatings are
graphic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX No actual sex, only base (and funny) references. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Lots of obscenities and coarse talk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10 Obviously not the best idea, especially for the
younger ones. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13 As always, parental guidelines prevail. Sure, it's
crude, lewd and silly, but they will have fun and there's not a
whole lot of harm. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `FOR LOVE OF THE GAME' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Costner, Kelly Preston, John C. Reilly, Jena Malone, Brian
Cox &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sam Raimi &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 140 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen years as a major league pitcher have left Billy Chapel
(Costner) with a sore shoulder, a salary that enables him to stay
in hotel suites that resemble Chenonceaux and the chilly, slightly
patronizing manner of a paragon who will proceed from the Hall of
Fame into American folklore.
</P>
<P>
   Billy's life story unfolds on the day he takes the mound against
the Yankees for the last game of his last season. He's really a
decent fellow, but all the ideals he must uphold in this movie
leave him acting and talking like a wind-up exemplar.
</P>
<P>
   Told by the Detroit owner (Cox) that the game stinks these days,
he replies: ``The game doesn't stink, Wheeler. It's a great game.''
Spoken like a man whose entire life has been devoted to baseball
from the days he pitched to his tall, devoted dad (cut to home
movies), who loved the game as passionately as he loved Billy's
revered mother.
</P>
<P>
   As for Billy's own track record with women, there is his
five-year relationship with Jane (Ms. Preston), an attractive book
editor with a spirited young daughter (Ms. Malone).
</P>
<P>
   After meeting exceedingly cute when her car breaks down, the
pair begin a strange arm's-length affair that consists mainly of
very long periods apart followed by short, intense get togethers
during which there is much anguishing over whether Billy could ever
love her as much as he does the game.
</P>
<P>
   Answering that for herself, Jane takes a great job in London.
But the day she leaves happens to be the day Billy is on the mound
at Yankee stadium and (guess what?) pitching a perfect game. But
that 40-year-old rotator cuff is really hurting.
</P>
<P>
   On cue Billy breaks a sweat and even winces a little. As the
soundtrack rises to a celestial level, the whole country is
watching on the tube _ even Jane, who has put off her flight to
London. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None but Billy bleeds profusely after cutting his
pitching hand with a saw. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Billy and Jane grapple in an elevator and make love one
night, though far, far from the camera. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Locker-room talk is punctuated with some solid swear
words. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOOTNOTE Billy is a heavy enough drinker to suppose that he
either has a problem now or will have in future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10 It's baseball, but there's all the romance stuff
and at 140 minutes this is a major league sit for little ones (and
others). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13 The film falls through the cracks for children and
teen-agers. Either the sports will appeal but not the love story or
vice versa. And to some viewers, though not all, developments on
both fronts will seem both overdone and interminable (just throw
the ball, why doesn't he?). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN BEAUTY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Spacey, Annette Bening, Thora Birch, Wes Bentley, Mena
Suvari, Peter Gallagher, Chris Cooper &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sam Mendes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 115 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deep in weirdest suburbia, Lester Burnham (Spacey), who is dead,
relates how it all ended just when he had pulled the plug on his
whole miserable existence and started to make headway as a
liberated man, of all things, with an entirely revamped attitude.
</P>
<P>
   A victim of downsizing at work, he takes a philosophical
approach to the employment situation and gets a job at a fast-food
chain called Smiley. Leave the money-grubbing to his wife, Carolyn
(Ms. Bening), a frantically stressed-out real-estate woman whose
drive to succeed has her so tied in knots she can only sputter
slogans to herself as she barges around town in her sport utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Sulking at home is their neglected teen-age daughter, Jane (Ms.
Birch), who hates them both and even half-seriously discusses
killing her father with Ricky (Bentley), her boyfriend and
next-door neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The troubled Ricky, who is a drug dealer, shadows everybody and
everything with a video camera. He is also at a dead end with his
father (Cooper), a disturbed Marine colonel who collects Nazi
memorabilia and disciplines his son by beating him up.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lester lusts after Jane's teen-age friend Angela (Ms.
Suvari), works out rigorously in his garage, throws crockery around
the dining room and lays down the law. No longer will he be
dominated by his wife and daughter. Lester will just be Lester. But
now Lester is dead. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE The colonel punches his son, and there is a bloody
murder by gunshot. But the real violence is the anger coming from
every pore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Lester masturbates and his wife has sex with the local
real-estate king (Gallagher). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A lot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP Obviously the film isn't for children, but it is
a heady story with a strong point of view, involves teen-agers and
includes superb performances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
