<HEADER>
A2341 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-30 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT BANK IS LURING PARIS DEALERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One night two years ago, the Paris antiques dealer
Ariane Dandois recalled, she was at a dinner party, bored stiff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly I had a flash,'' she said. After owning a gallery for
25 years on the Rue des Saints-Peres, off the Boulevard
St.-Germain, she said she told herself: ``The Left Bank is over for
dealers. Sotheby's has opened on the Faubourg St.-Honore;
Christie's is moving near the Champs-Elysees. I have to move to the
Right Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   She left the party and drove to the Rue du Faubourg St.-Honore,
Paris' equivalent of Madison Avenue, lined with embassies, art
galleries, luxury hotels and fashion boutiques like Hermes and
Versace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the middle of the night,'' Ms. Dandois said. ``I drove
up and down, looking for a building for sale.'' She saw one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intuitively,'' she said, ``I realized it might be the last
available space on the street for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   That night she couldn't sleep. The next morning she told a real
estate agent she wanted to buy it. She had a strong premonition
that it would be sold that day.
</P>
<P>
   She was right. The sale was to close that very day, at noon.
Undeterred, she drove to the site at 11:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went up to the seller,'' she said, ``and offered $100,000
above the asking price. He said, `Done.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Dandois gallery opens this week at 92 Rue du Faubourg
St.-Honore. The building is one of three on the Place Beauvau, a
square alongside the Rue du Faubourg St.-Honore that was
established in 1770, when one of Louis XV's generals built a
mansion amid the district's vegetable gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Today it is a fashionable address, a block from Sotheby's and
across the street from the Elysee Palace, the official residence of
French presidents since 1873.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dandois is in excellent company. One neighbor, Jacques
Perrin, a specialist in fine 18th-century French antiques, is vice
president of France's National Union of Antiques Dealers. He has
spent the last 10 months redoing his own gallery with help from
Francois-Joseph Graf, a well-known Paris decorator who excels at
traditional luxe French interiors.
</P>
<P>
   With yards of brown damask and antique boiseries on the walls,
the new gallery, which reopens this week, looks like a very grand
but comfortable Paris apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor is Aveline, an antiques gallery founded in 1956
that has just moved to the Place Beauvau. It is owned by Jean-Marie
Rossi, an elder statesman of the Paris antiques world who
specializes in art and important continental antiques. Rossi also
hired Graf to design his gallery. The space will not officially
open until late October, although he is already receiving clients
there.
</P>
<P>
   Dandois, Perrin, Aveline _ together with Didier Aaron and
Maurice Segoura, two other respected Paris antiquaires _ cater to
an exclusive clientele. They routinely sell signed palace furniture
for millions of dollars to museums like Versailles and to the most
serious collectors, including the Americans Henry Kravis, Ronald
Perelman, Susan Gutfreund and Anne Bass.
</P>
<P>
   Didier Aaron, who also has a gallery in Manhattan, sells his
most expensive antiques at his Paris gallery, at 118 Rue du
Faubourg St.-Honore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to spend half a million dollars on a Louis
XIV chair made for Versailles,'' he said, ``you would just as soon
travel to Paris, stay at the Ritz and have a wonderful
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   These galleries are also destinations for successful American
designers like Peter Marino, Alan Wanzenberg, Jeffrey Bradfield and
Juan Pablo Molyneux. As Marino said: ``French dealers do their own
thing. Ariane supplies us with forgotten markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike her neighbors, Ms. Dandois designed her own space, which
is minimalist and spare. Instead of parquet, the floors are paved
in a pale gray marble from Greece. Instead of damask, the walls are
painted pale taupe with flecks of silver and gold to catch the
light.
</P>
<P>
   A famously stylish woman, Ms. Dandois deliberately chose a cool,
clean modern setting to showcase her Edo screens from Japan, and
her French, Russian, German and northern Italian furniture.
</P>
<P>
   She has an inventory of 1,500 pieces, and though she is known
for 18th- and 19th-century French, Russian, Swedish and Baltic
antiques, she does not specialize in any period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found how wonderful it was not to be limited,'' she said.
``The most amusing thing on earth is to shop. And there are lots of
things to discover. The best part is the research.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had spent days trying to identify two 18th-century
black commodes with simple bronze decorations she had bought. She
finally realized she had seen an identical one in a museum in
Prague.
</P>
<P>
   She is now showing an unusual Italian piece: a circular center
table whose base is carved in the form of a tree trunk, covered by
gilded vines festooned with grapes. The base also has carved paw
feet.
</P>
<P>
   The table is circa 1830 and is similar, she said, to one in the
Getty Museum that Christie's sold in New York in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French think a table like this belongs in a kitchen,
because they don't know about it,'' she said. ``I bought it from a
private house in Turin where it sat in the front hall. It has
grandeur and fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   The price is $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to be original,'' she said. ``I just have
unusual taste.''
</P>
<P>
   She attributes this to her being half Russian.
</P>
<P>
   In her gallery she is showing a pair of overscale carved gray
oak settees, circa 1735, in the manner of the architect William
Kent. They are from Rushbrooke Hall, the seat of the Jermyn family
in Suffolk, England.
</P>
<P>
   She also has a pair of gilt bronze Louis XVI candelabra by
Francois Remond, a Paris bronzier; a pair of consoles attributed to
Thomire and Duterme; a few sparkling crystal Russian chandeliers;
an important Irish chimneypiece in the style of Thomas Hope, and an
Edo screen depicting a chariot filled with flowers. The prices
range from about $20,000 to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``A third of my antiques cost less than $30,000,'' she said. ``A
third go for between $30,000 and $60,000, and the rest go for
more.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't get to Paris, Perrin and Ms. Dandois will be
in New York at the Seventh Regiment Armory at the International
Fine Art and Antique Dealers Show from Oct. 15 through Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Similar works will be available at a Sotheby's sale of European
furniture, works of art, tapestries and carpets on Oct. 13 and at a
Christie's sale of French and Continental furniture on Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   The openings of Dandois and Perrin in Paris coincide with the
second International Ceramics Show at the Hotel Dassault on the
Champs-Elysees, through Sunday, with 34 dealers selling fine
antique faience, porcelain, earthenware, majolica and glass. There
are also seminars each day.
</P>
<P>
   Information on the ceramics fair is available on the Web at
www.franceantiq.fr/siccaf/
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dandois may be right. This week, at least, the Right Bank
rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
