<HEADLINE>
WATCHING FOR A BREAKOUT  
 POLLACK GETS AGE-CONSCIOUS  
 SODERBERGH'S DEVELOPMENT  
 SUNDANCE FAVORITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; HOLLYWOOD _ A lot of eyes are watching the box-office numbers this
weekend. Of course, there are always a lot of eyes watching the
weekend box-office numbers in Hollywood. Sometimes it seems as if
that's all they're watching (that and one another). But this
weekend a lot of people are watching with breath held and something
resembling hope in their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' the acid-laced suburban comedy from Sam
Mendes, a first-time movie director, has been among the
best-reviewed films of the year. It opened on just 16 screens in
five cities on Sept. 15 and earned more than $53,000 a screen in
its opening weekend. Originally Dreamworks, the studio distributing
the film, planned to put the movie into wider release on Oct. 1.
Instead, studio officials decided to push it onto more than 400
additional screens on Sept. 22, when it still earned nearly $14,000
a screen.
</P>
<P>
   These are impressive numbers, especially for a film as dark and
hard-to-define as ``American Beauty.'' This weekend it will expand
into more than 200 additional screens. At that point ``American
Beauty'' will have moved beyond the big-city theaters into smaller
cities and outlying suburbs. If it continues to do well, even more
screens will be added into mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the film is working with big-city audiences,'' said
one marketing executive from a rival studio. ``But the question is
whether it will do well in the South and small towns in Ohio and
everywhere, because to be a real breakout hit, you have to do well
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Another studio marketing executive said: ``I hope it does make
it. But it's a little early to be handing out gold medals. There
are plenty of cases of movies that started out strong and then
expanded onto more screens and died. This could turn out to be a
$35 million movie, or it could be a $75 million movie. It's too
early to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Also this weekend another offbeat, independent-minded studio
production _ David Russell's Gulf War film, ``Three Kings,''
starring George Clooney _ will be released by Warner Brothers. It
is unusual for major studios like Warners and Dreamworks to release
films like ``American Beauty'' and ``Three Kings,'' both of which
have more of the feel of an independent movie. And that's why so
many people in Hollywood are interested in seeing how they do,
along with another forthcoming studio film with an independent
sensibility, David Fincher's ``Fight Club,'' coming out of 20th
Century Fox on Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very interested in seeing if these movies do well,
especially `American Beauty,''' said one director who was busy with
the release of his own fall movie. ``If it does well and makes a
lot of money, it's going to be a very good thing for all
filmmakers, especially those interested in making sophisticated
films for sophisticated audiences, instead of the latest
high-concept or teen-gimmick thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Youth
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Pollack, who has been making movies since ``The Slender
Thread'' in 1965, is also interested in what older, more
sophisticated moviegoers are going to see this fall. His newest
film, ``Random Hearts,'' with Harrison Ford and Kristen
Scott-Thomas playing a cop and a congresswoman thrown together when
they discover their spouses had an affair, is opening on Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never gotten truly excited about something and had them
say, `Sydney, my boy, no, we can't make this movie because it
doesn't appeal to the youth market,''' Pollack said. ``That hasn't
happened to me. Yet. I still believe there are exceptions to that
youth rule, at least I hope there are. I think 35- or 40-year-old
people are hungry for mature entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the things that have changed in the 34 years he has been
making movies, Pollack said, is how ``economics have started to
color everything.'' Several of his films _ he named ``Jeremiah
Johnson'' and ``They Shoot Horses, Don't They?'' _ probably
couldn't be made today, he said, ``largely because it's just a
different marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Young moviegoers, who have always been important to the film
business but are even more important today, seem to want to see
movies with young people in them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first knee-jerk reaction for a 23-year-old couple on a
date is to go see a movie about 25-year-olds,'' he said. ``But I
still believe there are exceptions. At least, I hope there are.''
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A Matter of Structure
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while to figure out what you're good at, because at
the beginning you think you can do anything,'' Steven Soderbergh
said.
</P>
<P>
   This director was slowly working his way through a sandwich
during a break in the marketing mania of the recent Toronto
International Film Festival. Soderbergh was at the festival, as he
had been at Cannes earlier in the year, with his film noir ``The
Limey,'' about a British thug who comes to Los Angeles to find out
who killed his daughter and makes rather nasty work of a bunch of
Hollywood types. The star of the film, Terence Stamp, was seated at
a nearby table. (``During the filming, Steven evoked feelings in me
that hadn't been evoked since I worked with William Wyler,'' Stamp
had said earlier. ``You could just tell, with both of them, that
they absolutely knew what they were doing.'')
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh, who began his career as a film-festival darling with
``Sex, Lies and Videotape,'' and whose last film, ``Out of Sight,''
was chosen by several critics' groups as the best of 1998, has been
able to bounce back and forth between the studio and the
independent worlds. While ``The Limey'' is an independent effort,
to be distributed by Artisan Entertainment, his next movie, ``Erin
Brockovich,'' will be made for Universal with Julia Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh said that only now, after eight films, did he feel he
understood his strengths and limitations as a director. This has
led him to take more of an interest in the structure of his films,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I finished `Out of Sight,' I wanted to do something right
away,'' he said. ``I had a buzz. I was energized. I wanted to work
again immediately. And I wanted to make a movie set in Los Angeles,
but one without the usual visual cliches of L.A. movies. I was
having all of these ideas about structure. I had this idea about
playing around with how the meaning of an image can shift through
repetition, how it begins to have a different meaning as the film
goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   What ``The Limey'' had, he said, was a simple story line with
well-defined, easy-to-understand characters that allowed him to
take chances with time shifts and nonlinear storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the simplicity of the through line that makes it work,''
he said. ``Otherwise you'd have people saying, `Huh, what's going
on?' It could get ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
