<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2352 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE     09-30 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOLLYWOOD: get ugly.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For ``The Limey,'' Soderbergh adopted a new way of shooting his
scenes, which he retained on ``Erin Brockovich.'' He watches
through the camera while the scene is being shot. Many people think
that's how all directors work, but they don't. There has been a
growing distance between the director and the set, often with the
director parked in a tent many yards away, watching the proceedings
on video monitors. Soderbergh said he tried that approach and
thought it was counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to look through the camera because it is bringing me as
close to the movie as is humanly possible,'' he said. ``It's
literally like seeing the film while you are shooting. And I truly
believe that the energy of the set needs to be directed to where
the camera is pointing, not diffused between the set and some tent
nearby.''
</P>
<P>
   Stamp said the technique had an extraordinary effect on his
performance. ``Steven could sometimes whisper directions to me
while we were in the middle of a scene, while I was still in the
moment,'' he said. ``It was so intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy Indeed
</P>
<P>
   Steve Zahn, who appeared in Soderbergh's ``Out of Sight,'' was
also at the Toronto festival, as he had been at the Sundance
festival earlier in the year, promoting his latest comedy, Mark
Illsley's ``Happy, Texas,'' in which he plays a supremely dimwitted
convict who is forced to pose as a beauty pageant coordinator in a
small Texas town.
</P>
<P>
   The film emerged as one of the favorites at Sundance in January,
but there was some grumbling about how Zahn and his co-star, Jeremy
Northam, were cast as straight guys pretending to be gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how it is when you're meeting a new director,
sometimes you try to test each other,'' Zahn said. ``But in this
case we hit it off immediately, and we agreed that we should not
play these characters as over-the-top or flamboyant when they're
pretending to be gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes have been trimmed from the film and some extra
looping of dialogue added since Sundance, Zahn said, but it was
mostly little bits and pieces lost and additions for clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Zahn said he was drawn to ``Happy, Texas'' by the richness of
the comedy, even down to the smallest roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people are doing movies just to do movies,'' he said.
``But here was a case where people were doing it because they
really thought it was a good movie. You know, it's become a pastime
for Americans to make fun of people, to laugh at people. A lot of
the comedy now is about making fun of someone. I loved this because
it wasn't like that. It was laughing at something that's a real
story. You'd be surprised how rarely you see scripts like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
