<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHTING A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By BEN RATLIFF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROYAL TRUX: ``Veterans of Disorder'' (Drag City).
</P>
<P>
   Rock may be losing its sense of confusion. Easily sorted into
camps and sounds these days, and into both the mainstream and the
substreams, the music is more calculated than ever to make you feel
a certain way, happy or sad, or angry or obnoxious. So it's nice to
hear the eighth Royal Trux album and think one more time, What on
earth are these people up to?
</P>
<P>
   This duo, Jennifer Herrema and Neil Hagerty, started out making
murky collage records in the late '80s; they made the listener work
hard to get close to them. Slowly they began to favor
straightforward rock songcraft with unusual details, made a couple
of major-label records and more recently circled back to some of
their old, opaque ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veterans of Disorder'' combines these approaches in a record
that's alternately beautiful and awful, but at least it's trying
desperately for something ... something ... well, something.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Herrema, who just wheezes and snarls when she travels
outside a narrow pitch range, sounds like Janis Joplin with a
throat condition. Hagerty, a versatile instrumentalist, sings, too,
playing guitar riffs that you might have heard out of the window of
a hand-me-down gas guzzler in a suburban parking lot in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Recorded with various accomplices, the album's a mixed message:
bored and cantankerous like the Rolling Stones but also full of
old-fashioned electronic sounds that woof up out of the mix and
abrupt snip-offs at the end of each song that undermine a sense of
grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Trux's production sound is so jarring and alien _ with so
much bleeding of sound, layering of tracks, hill-and-dale dynamics
and deliberate gunk _ that its skill at making records is quite
naturally underrated. Whoever hears the band feels queasy at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veterans of Disorder'' starts with ``Waterpark,'' a great riff
tune; you think you're going to hear an album of Detroit-style hard
rock.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the rest of the record brings droning stomps; chants
like ``Shake off that second skin'' and ``Yo se!''; an
unlistenable, out-of-tune song with a habanera rhythm called
``Lunch Money''; an intriguing tape-edit work with chimes, tea
kettles and Ms. Herrema yelling the numbers 1 through 30, and a
fairly beautiful, serene nine-minute song at the end called ``Blue
Is the Frequency,'' a song for driving into a California sunset,
with a long guitar solo.
</P>
<P>
   It's a short record, and there's much to pay attention to. Royal
Trux performs Friday night at the Cooler, in Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-ART-NYT &LR;      09-30 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME POWER-HUNGRY PIGS AND OTHER POLITICAL ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at the end of the review. Also, a
brief item on `The Secret Life of Geisha' follows the main item.
Times, channels are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(th) 
 By CARYN JAMES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Collectivizing the farm turned out to be a rotten idea, Jessie
the dog lets us know at the start of ``Animal Farm,'' TNT's
stylish, shrewd but oddly unengaging version of Orwell's classic.
Barely mentioned in the book, here Jessie is its melodious-voiced
narrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a storm of judgment,'' she says as the camera roams
over the lush, rain-ravaged countryside and she recalls how the
rebellious animals took control of the farm, only to have their
socialist dreams destroyed by a megalomaniac leader, a pig named
Napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   Enhancing Jessie's role and making the story her flashback were
among the film's wisest ideas. Julia Ormond gives her a voice that
is affecting and maternal. It could be called human except humans
are among the villains here.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years we had been hiding from oppression, hiding from
Napoleon's spies,'' Jessie says. Her tone of sad retrospection
makes sense, for she is telling us what history already has.
Orwell's fable, after all, lost its political urgency long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Published in 1945 as a warning against Stalin's repressive
control of the Soviet Union, ``Animal Farm'' had a hard time seeing
print in the post-World War II atmosphere of sympathy for the
Soviet Allies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the post-Cold War era, it is a cautionary tale whose
battles have all been fought, however much historians continue to
wrangle over their meaning. (Orwell's ``1984,'' by contrast, is
more ominous than ever. Big Brother, the Thought Police and
full-time video surveillance are just a few of its nightmarish
legacies.)
</P>
<P>
   The film tries, with shaky results, to capture what is most
brilliant about ``Animal Farm,'' which Orwell subtitled ``a fairy
story'': the double layer that allows it to work as a children's
animal tale and a political allegory. But Hallmark Entertainment
(the producers of extravaganzas like NBC's ``Merlin'') has created
a work that could also have been called ``Animatronic Puppets
Farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the movie includes real animals and computer-generated
effects, the charming puppets from Jim Henson's Creature Shop give
them their most vivid and humane qualities, and the stunt of their
lifelike presence threatens to overwhelm the drama itself. The
puppets' mouths do not always move in perfect synch to the words,
but the animals have been given amazingly expressive eyes that make
them convincing as thinking, speaking creatures.
</P>
<P>
   It is still easy to see in these characters the historical
models for Orwell's animals, models so specifically Soviet that the
novel doesn't translate easily to any other regime.
</P>
<P>
   The actors' voices are all superbly chosen. The blustery Peter
Ustinov is Old Major, the Marxist-Leninist pig who creates the
theory of animalism. ``Man is our enemy,'' he says, standing on
high bales of hay in the barn and preaching to the masses below.
``Remove man and we will be free and equal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Free and equal,'' the sheep bleat in unison.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Stewart brings his great authority to Napoleon, Josef
Stalin's stand-in, who amends Old Major's rule ``All animals are
equal'' to ``But some animals are more equal than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey Grammer is Napoleon's rival pig, Snowball, who is exiled,
like his real-life model, Leon Trotsky. Napoleon's attack dogs are
sent after him; in this case they are Jessie's puppies whom
Napoleon has taken from her at birth and trained to be his fiendish
security force, a doggy KGB.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Holm is especially sinister as Squealer, Napoleon's
propaganda minister. As the pigs grow closer to vile humans in
their lust for riches and power, Squealer takes to wearing a
monocle on a green ribbon. It is one of the film's many sharp small
touches. Paul Scofield is Boxer, the exploited workhorse who
believes the lies of the pigs in charge.
</P>
<P>
   As the overthrown capitalist, Farmer Jones, Pete Postlethwaite
is among the few human actors on screen. Scenes added to the book
give Jones a nasty personality and the animals reasons to revolt,
but they add a bluntness to the tale. Jones accidentally shoots Old
Major, who in the book dies of old age.
</P>
<P>
   And while the animals are singing an anthem, ``Beasts of the
world/We shall unite,'' which evokes the marching rhythm of the
``Internationale,'' the song is intercut with a scene of a drunken
Jones having adulterous sex in the farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Some changes are even more heavy-handed. Though the story is
still set in the 1930s and '40s, television is the opiate of the
barnyard. Napoleon and Squealer see the other animals watching
Jones' television, mesmerized by the Keystone Kops. ``Keeps them
quiet,'' Napoleon observes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could be useful,'' says Squealer. It is an irresistible idea
handled with none of Orwell's deftness.
</P>
<P>
   The propaganda films that Napoleon and Squealer create are
delicious, though: black-and-white movies that owe a debt to Leni
Riefenstahl, showing geese marching in step.
</P>
<P>
   The largest change is also the worst. Cautionary tales do not
have happy endings, yet this ``Animal Farm'' invents a conclusion
that is hopeful and far too abrupt.
</P>
<P>
   For all its thoughtfulness, the uneven film is too tough to be
entirely childlike, too soft to be politically powerful, too
lacking in dramatic pull to keep viewers' attention. In the end it
misses that tenuous balance that made Orwell's work so enduring.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANIMAL FARM'
</P>
<P>
   TNT, Sunday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by Alan Janes and Martyn Burke, based on the novel by
George Orwell; John Stephenson, director; Greg Smith, producer;
Mike Brewster, director of photography, music by Richard Harvey;
creature effects by Jim Henson's Creature Shop; Robert Halmi Sr.,
executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   With: Pete Postlethwaite (Farmer Jones), Alan Stanford (Mr.
Pilkington); Caroline Gray (Mrs. Jones), Gail Fitzpatrick (Mrs.
Pilkington), Joe Taylor (Mr. Frederick), Jimmy Keogh (Dennis) and
Noel O'Donovan (Eric). Voices of Kelsey Grammer (Snowball), Ian
Holm (Squealer), Julia Louis-Dreyfus (Mollie), Julia Ormond
(Jessie), Paul Scofield (Boxer), Patrick Stewart (Napoleon) and
Peter Ustinov (Old Major).
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   `THE SECRET LIFE OF GEISHA'
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Sunday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   Readers of Arthur Golden's best-selling novel, ``Memoirs of a
Geisha,'' will revel in this colorful glimpse behind the veiled
life of Japan's mystery women. The two-hour documentary, narrated
by Susan Sarandon, takes the camera into today's geisha houses and
interviews members of its archaic profession.
</P>
<P>
   Golden, one of the on-screen experts, explains a traditional way
to tell geishas, who do not sleep with their clients, apart from
prostitutes. Geishas wore their boxlike sashes, called obi, tied in
back. Prostitutes tied theirs in front for ease of removal. This is
not an artfully made documentary, but its detailed subject is
thoroughly fascinating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EPIC-THEATER-REVIEW-A     09-30 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPIC-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EPIC PROPORTIONS ' : PARTING THE SEA WITH SLAPSTICK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds: production notes at end of review) 
(bl) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sprawling biblical narrative of the sort that
Cecil B. De Mille used to whip up is the cinematic genre being
spoofed in ``Epic Proportions,'' the flailing attempt at a comedy
that opened Thursday night at the Helen Hayes Theater. But it's
understandable if you find yourself thinking of another type of
popular melodrama from a bygone era, the kind in which the winsome
heroine is cruelly held captive and tortured while she strains to
stay plucky and hopeful as she prays for deliverance. For there
before you, smiling as though her life depended upon it, is Kristin
Chenoweth, the undersize actress with the outsize presence who
walked away with last season's revival of ``You're a Good Man,
Charlie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chenoweth, bless her heart, is imprisoned in a relentlessly
unfunny cartoon, and all the charm and luminosity in the world
aren't going to raise the dampening clouds that hang over her.
</P>
<P>
   This actress, whose performance as an angst-ridden preschooler
in ``Charlie Brown'' netted a clutch of theater awards last spring,
became the personification of a cherished Broadway fairy tale, in
which the determined kid from corn country is transformed overnight
into a big-time star.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway, however, is no longer the enchanted kingdom of success
fables like ``42nd Street'' and ``Morning Glory.'' Gone are the
days when a relative unknown like Mary Martin could dazzle
Manhattan in a novelty number in Cole Porter's ``Leave It to Me''
and proceed into a glittering succession of tailor-made vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the recent careers of Faith Prince, Melissa Errico and
Rebecca Luker, who have yet to find a show to match their
breakthrough performances in, respectively, ``Guys and Dolls,''
``One Touch of Venus'' and ``The Boys From Syracuse.'' (Audra
McDonald and Donna Murphy are the rare contemporary exceptions, and
their appeal is of a moodier, more cerebral variety.) Little wonder
that for such gifted performers, the prospect of a television
series starts to look like the Promised Land.
</P>
<P>
   If I seem to be putting off any detailed description of ``Epic
Proportions,'' which was written by Larry Coen and David Crane and
has been directed (after a fashion) by Jerry Zaks, it's because
there isn't much to say about it except, ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   This shaggy dog story about shooting a ``Ten
Commandments''-style movie on an Arizona desert in the early 1930s
was warmly received in an earlier off-Broadway incarnation in 1986,
before Crane went on to glory as a co-creator of the hit sitcom
``Friends.'' It is possible that in a more relaxed, intimate
environment the show's galumphing blend of slapstick gags and hoary
jokes might have worked better.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is hard to imagine this material successfully
stretching to much more than a five-minute television sketch or a
fleeting segment in a Mel Brooks movie. (With the well-advised
deletion of its intermission during previews last week, the show
now runs a long 85 minutes.) The eight-member ensemble, which Zaks
appears to have left mostly to its own devices, must deliver lines
as old as vaudeville, supplemented with grimaces and stiff, stagy
postures that seem less to have been thought out through rehearsal
than improvised in desperation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chenoweth is Louise, an assistant director in charge of
extras and the focus of a romantic triangle in which two brothers,
local farmboys who have signed on as spear carriers, vie for her
affections.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Bennet (Alan Tudyk) is the one who wants to be an actor,
but it is the hunkier Phil (Jeremy Davidson) who first captures
Louise's attention with his knack for manipulating crowds, a talent
acquired during his time in a high school marching band. Before
Phil arrived, says Louise in a joke that represents the high point
of the evening's humor, they had planned to part the Red Sea on the
side.
</P>
<P>
   Richard B. Shull portrays D.W. DeWitt, the nutty old director
who soon disappears into the sanctuary of a newly erected pyramid,
and Tom Beckett, Ross Lehman, Ruth Williamson and Richard Ziman
play everybody else, from a swishy leading man ( Beckett) to an
aging, predatory movie queen (Ms. Williamson).
</P>
<P>
   Many of the scenes seem to keep coming back at you, as though
they had been staged on a treadmill, including antic moments
involving the pulling of chest hair and the repeated bludgeoning of
performers during takes of the same scene. And here is a typical
sample of the dialogue: ``It's the greatest story ever told.''
``It's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   All the performances need reining in; on the other hand, without
the mugging, there would be nothing to command the attention,
except for William Ivey Long's costumes and David Gallo's sets,
which bring to mind a minimalist version of Tony Walton's
comic-strip designs for ``A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the
Forum.''
</P>
<P>
   With marcelled hair, Ms. Chenoweth looks the very model of a
1930s ingenue, a dewier version of the young Joan Blondell, and she
again demonstrates a solid instinct for comic timing. But there is
so little character for her to work with that she overcompensates
in self-sabotaging ways. She wrings the cuteness in her Betty Boop
voice, and she bizarrely underscores her punchlines by licking her
lower lip in the manner of Ernestine, the telephone operator of
Lily Tomlin routines.
</P>
<P>
   To say that she deserves better is an understatement. Shaw's
Joan of Arc complained that the world was unable to accept its
saints; the Broadway of today seems similarly incapable of
nurturing its natural stars.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EPIC PROPORTIONS'
</P>
<P>
   By Larry Coen and David Crane; directed by Jerry Zaks; sets by
David Gallo; costumes by William Ivey Long; lighting by Paul Gallo;
sound by Aural Fixation; fight director, Rick Sordelet; technical
director, Peter Fulbright; production stage manager, Rick Steiger;
associate director, BT McNicholl; general management, Brent Peek
Productions; associate producer, William K. Ehrenfeld. Presented by
Bob Cuillo, Brent Peek, Robert Barandes, Matthew Farrell and Mark
Schwartz, with Philip and Patricia Barry Productions and Robert
Dragotta. At the Helen Hayes Theater, 240 W. 44th St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Tom Beckett (Octavium and Cochette's Assistant), Kristin
Chenoweth (Louise Goldman), Alan Tudyk (Benny Bennet), Jeremy
Davidson (Phil Bennet), Richard Ziman (Jack, First General and
Brady), Ross Lehman (Shel and Executioner), Richard B. Shull (D.W.
DeWitt) and Ruth Williamson (Cochette). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
