   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-SUMMIT _ PALISADES, N.Y. _ President Clinton's
appearance is expect ed to be the highlight Thursday at the third
of the influential education summits held in the last decade by
governors and corporate CEOs. Among the six Cox-state governors,
five plan to attend and the sixth, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, is
listed as ``probable.'' (Mollison, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   COALITION _ WASHINGTON _ The Christian Coaltion's ``Road to
Victory'' conference opens today in Washington and a new force is
at work here: Steve Forbes. Jerry Keen is one of a growing
contingent of former Christian Coalition officials who have been
drawn to the Forbes campaign. Keen, the former Georgia chairman,
says: ``Bush has Ralph and Pat,'' referring to Ralph Reed and Pat
Roberston. ``We have everyone else.'' (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS-MONEY _ It's the final bell for the third quarter of
campaign fund raising and Texas Gov. George W. Bush remains the
all-time heavyweight champion. The governor collected $16 million
in the past three months, bringing his total to about $53 million.
On the Democratic side, Bill Bradley offers a report that serves as
another reminder that he is a serious challenger to Al Gore.
(Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
