   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-ROUNDUP _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Receding water reveal some
of first homes to be flooded. Inspections should be finished today.
Latest on damage totals, FEMA trailers and Martin Luther King III
visits. (Greenville Daily Reflector).
</P>
<P>
   w/FLOODS-PETS _ RALEIGH _ More than 1,000 dogs and cats were
rescued from floodwaters last week. Those sick and whose owners
could not be located were sent to NC State University's veterinary
school. While the vets are nursing them back to health in a field
hospital behind the NC Museum of Art, the Humane Society has taken
digital photos of every animal admitted to the hopsital and posted
them on a website this week for owners to look for their pets.
(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLOODS-SHELTER _ GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Shelter residents leave
schools for Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs, another upheaval. Some have been
home and found they have nowhere else to go. The home's of others
still are underwater. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Jounal-Constitution),
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   UGA-RACE _ UGA President Michael Adams is expected to tell the
University Council if he will keep or drop race as a factor in
admissions for borderline students. (McCarthy/Rankin/Brice, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   w/UGA-TEXAS _ Legal sidebar accompanying main UGA story,
explaining U.S. Supreme Court precedents and that Texas case called
Hopweood, which has no controlling authority here in Georgia but is
very influential. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPACE _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt came to Atlanta on
Thursday to praise Gov. Roy Barnes for protecting Georgia's green
space. Babbitt also pushed for support of a bill pending in
Congress that would provice millions of federal dollars for Georgia
and other states to open new parks and acquire environmentally
sensitive land. (Seabrook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-MISSING _ A muddy 1989 Chevrolet Caprice containing six
bodies was pulled from Pea River in southern Alabama Wednesday. The
vehicle's tags matched the missing car belonging to Lamar Junior
Stackhouse, 25, of Enterprise, signaling an apparent end to the
mystery of what happened to a group of six friends who disappeared
after a night of partying May 9. The car, with the remains still
inside, was taken to the Alabama Department of Forensic Science in
Montgomery for autopsies, said Alabama Bureau of Investigation
agent Simon Benson. Because of the decomposed state of the bodies,
authorities could not positively identify the remains Wednesday
night. State police are treating the deaths as an accident but
planned to search the area today. Early in the search there were
worries that the six friends were victims of a hate crime. (Manuel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
