<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON WHAT'S NEW IN HOME VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Trove of Titles At the Library &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 the MacArthur Foundation Library Video Project set out
to alert the public that libraries were good places to find many
titles one didn't find lying around the average video store.
Librarians needed to be reminded, too.
</P>
<P>
   By helping them set up consortiums to buy large amounts of
titles like ``Best Boy,'' Ira Wohl's acclaimed documentary about
his retarded cousin, and ``Hearts and Minds,'' Peter Davis' Vietnam
documentary, the project built awareness among a list of
participants that has grown to 12,000 libraries.
</P>
<P>
   That message delivered, the focus narrowed to groups of videos
in single-subject areas. In 1994 it was Latino issues and in 1996,
health. This year the topic is aging. Libraries can choose from
among 47 titles _ most of them feature documentaries _ dealing with
family biography, the aging process, discrimination and
intergenerational stress, sexuality, health and care-giving and
like matters. The organization, now called the Library Media
Project, helps them buy a selection at favorable prices.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes are available for lending, of course, but there is
another purpose. ``The idea is to foster public discourse,'' said
Mary Kirby, the project's executive director. Libraries organize
discussion groups around documentaries like Wohl's follow-up film
``Best Man: `Best Boy' and All of Us 20 Years Later''; Frederick
Wiseman's award-winning ``Near Death''; ``Sonny and Cornblatt,'' a
kind of nonfiction ``Grumpy Old Men'' about two elderly people who
gradually grow to like each other, or Skip Sweeney's ``My Mother
Married Wilbur Stump,'' about a family's consternation when a
parent marries an alcoholic, seven-times divorced piano player 13
years her senior.
</P>
<P>
   Librarians or interested individuals who would like their own
libraries to take part may get in touch with the project at (800)
847-3671 or fax (773) 878-8404. The e-mail address is
info(AT)librarymedia.org and the Web site is
http://librarymedia.org. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eccentric Duo
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone will immediately warm to what they see in the
Brothers Quay Collection, recently released by Kino, but given a
chance, films by the eccentric pair, Tim and Stephen, tend to grow
mesmerizing.
</P>
<P>
   One cassette includes 10 of the brothers' animated shorts, six
of them for the first time on video. On another tape is ``Institute
Benjamenta'' (1996), the Quays' first live-action film.
</P>
<P>
   Their animated work is caught in a dreamworld of tiny objects.
``Street of Crocodiles,'' a 21-minute short and their best-known
film, is based on a story of the Holocaust by the Polish Jewish
writer Bruno Schulz. ``Institute Benjamenta'' interprets Robert
Walser's Kafkaesque novella about a disruptive influence loose in a
school for servants. ``Later in life we will be something very
small and subordinate,'' a student says. Information: (800)
562-3330. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pushing Tin
</P>
<P>
   A film about air traffic controllers telegraphs its climax, but
an exceptionally strong cast carries the story well beyond the
inevitable crises aloft. John Cusack is Nick, hotshot of the
control tower, and Cate Blanchett is his wife, Connie, an Elizabeth
I who talks about tuna casseroles with a Long Island accent.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton is Russell, the daredevil newcomer to the tower.
Angelina Jolie is his wife Mary, a former biker chick who shakes up
the controllers' wives, not to mention Nick, who makes his play one
boozy night.
</P>
<P>
   As directed by Mike Newell, ``Pushing Tin,'' Janet Maslin wrote
in The New York Times, ``gets past its initial `M-A-S-H'-style
comic chaos and becomes a four-character story with four characters
worth watching.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Fox. $104.16. 99 minutes. 115 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Oct. 5. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This Is My Father
</P>
<P>
   A glum Irish-American schoolteacher named Kieran (James Caan)
returns to the old sod in search of his roots. Flashing back to
1939, Paul Quinn's film centers on the romance between Kieran's
mother, the pretty, impetuous 17-year-old Fiona Flynn (Moya
Farrelly) and his father, a shy orphaned farmer also named Kieran
(Aidan Quinn).
</P>
<P>
   An aged fortuneteller (Moira Deady) helps uncover the tale of
Fiona's malevolent mother (Gina Moxley) and her efforts to keep the
couple apart. Some stellar actors, including Colm Meany and John
Cusack, add verve in cameo parts, while its principal players
``move through this story in quietly impassioned style'' (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 120 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Oct. 5. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lost and Found &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What a beautiful French cellist named Lila (Sophie Marceau) sees
in a chicken-breasted twerp of a restaurant owner named Dylan
(David Spade) is hard to imagine. In Jeff Pollack's film it is
posited that Dylan's concern for her lost dog, Jack, somehow
transforms into romance down the line, but that's a reach to say
the least.
</P>
<P>
   In point of fact, Dylan has hidden the pooch in his apartment,
where it swallows a diamond and necessitates a probe through doggy
doo. Perhaps therein also lies a metaphor for ``a rancid little
nothing of a movie'' (Stephen Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Warner. $104.16. 99 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Oct. 5. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doug's First Movie &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an animated film based on the television series ``Disney's
Doug,'' the sweet, geeky Doug Funnie spots a weird creature
swimming around polluted Bluff Lake. Grounded by the toxic waters,
the ``monster'' turns out to be a cuddly blue thing Doug names
Herman Melville and hides from hordes of crazed reporters.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, Doug is trying to gain the attention of pretty
Patti Mayonnaise, who is also being courted by Guy Graham, the
obnoxious editor of the school paper. Put all of this together and
Maurice Joyce's film ``isn't inspired children's entertainment, but
it has a certain charm'' (Anita Gates). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Disney. $22.99. 83 minutes. Closed captioned. G. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIZZY'S DREAM BAND. For a concert recorded in 1981 at Avery
Fisher Hall, the trumpeter Dizzy Gillespie handpicked 25
colleagues, including the baritone saxophonist Gerry Mulligan, the
drummer Max Roach, the vibraphonist Milt Jackson, the pianist John
Lewis and the vocalist Jon Hendricks. Backstage interviews are
included, as well as clips of Gillespie playing with Charlie
Parker. 1999. Fox Lorber. $19.98; DVD, $24.98. 89 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   SOMETHING WICKED THIS WAY COMES. Adapted from Ray Bradbury's
story, Jack Clayton's film is set in Green Town, Ill., where Dark
(Jonathan Price) brings his mysterious Dark's Pandemonium Carnival.
There to save the people from ensuing havoc is the librarian
Charles Holloway (Jason Robards). A Disney production, the tale
might have had more bite, but it is enjoyable nevertheless. 1983.
Anchor Bay. $14.98. 95 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   BERNADETTE PETERS IN CONCERT. The Broadway diva performs hits by
Stephen Sondheim, Jerome Kern and others. Additional songs have
been stirred into the show broadcast on PBS this summer. 1999.
Acorn. $19.95. 91 minutes. Information: (800) 999-0212.
</P>
<P>
   BARRIERS. Bullied at his mostly white school, an affluent black
teen-ager named Tori (Jamaul Roots) takes up with Snake (Geoff
Garcy), a streetwise, tough-talking boy from Harlem. Trying to keep
Snake out of their son's life, Tori's parents hire a white female
(Annie Golden) to escort him home from school, but an eventual
showdown will test everybody's notions of race and class. 1998.
Water Bearer. $29.95. 90 minutes. No rating. Information: (800)
551-8304.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
