<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2383 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-ANIMALFARM-REVIEW-     09-30 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANIMALFARM-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ANIMALS RULE IN TNT'S TURN ON ORWELL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All right, so the new movie version of ``Animal Farm'' backs
down a little at the end to brighten George Orwell's bleak
allegory. It's not as if ``Animal Farm'' (Sunday on TNT) is about
to be confused with the glad-girl joy of ``Pollyanna.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the makers of this splendid cable movie keep faith with
the spirit of Orwell's amazing barnyard blast at totalitarianism.
They also keep up with the latest advances in animatronics and
computer wizardry to make ``Animal Farm'' a visual wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Stewart (Napoleon), Kelsey Grammer (Snowball), Julia
Ormond (Jessie), Ian Holm (Squealer), Paul Scofield (Boxer) and
Peter Ustinov (Old Major) lead the film's credits for their voice
work, but the true star here is Jim Henson's Creature Shop.
</P>
<P>
   The London workshop is the sole component of the late Henson's
legacy that hasn't declined since Henson died nine years ago. It
just keeps getting better.
</P>
<P>
   Henson's artificial creatures stood in for live animals in much
of the endearing theatrical hit ``Babe,'' and some of those same
replicates, the sheep especially, seem to be on display here.
</P>
<P>
   But the porcine creations reach new heights, or maybe grand new
wallows. (Too bad, though, that Kevin Bacon couldn't have been a
voice talent.)
</P>
<P>
   Old Major, the prize boar of Manor Farm and the story's version
of Karl Marx, is an imposing hunk of authority and porky decency.
Snowball, representing Leon Trotsky, is your basic white pig. But
Napoleon is sublimely Josef Stalin.
</P>
<P>
   The animatronic pig is symbolically Stalin in its crudity; its
mouth and snout are full of drool, snorts and foul, wet mysteries.
But it's Stalin as well in its heft, its carriage and in those sly,
suspicious eyes.
</P>
<P>
   This is the pig that helps drive off the drunken farmer Jones
(Pete Postlethwaite) and establish a utopia of animal equality,
only to become a dictator who begins his tyranny by hogging, as it
were, the milk and apples.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Napoleon is sleeping in a farmhouse bed, slurping
whiskey, selling the steadfast horse Boxer to the glue factory, and
striking deals with his human collaborator, Mr. Pilkington (Alan
Stanford). He's also the beneficiary of a cult campaign managed by
his propaganda minister, Squealer.
</P>
<P>
   By then, in Orwell's enduring phrase, the denizens of Animal
Farm are taught that all animals are equal, but some animals are
more equal than others.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the hope-filled tag-on at the end of the movie,
screenwriters Alan Janes and Martyn Burke have altered Orwell's
1945 novel to fatten the role of the kindly sheepdog, Jessie. The
purpose is to give viewers a narrator, and a sort of easy onscreen
entry into the story.
</P>
<P>
   But first-time director John Stephenson, who heads the Creature
Shop in London, doesn't veer unreasonably from the source material.
And he brings to the film a sure sense of pacing and a keen, mature
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Little propaganda movies within the movie, paeans to Napoleon,
are dead-on parodies of grim, Soviet-style propaganda films.
Stephenson, with the help of skillful film editing, also winningly
creates a pitched barnyard battle between the animals and their
human antagonists.
</P>
<P>
   (He manages to slip in a dig at television, too. Noticing that
farmer Jones' TV set has a strangely calming effect on the other
animals, Napoleon murmurs, ``Hmmmm, keeps them quiet. Could be
useful.'')
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Robert Halmi, television's most prolific impresario
for literary classics, ``Animal Farm'' is sure to remind viewers of
``Babe.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all those creatures, of course, but also the bucolic
fairy-tale look of the piece. Where is this, and when? Someplace
with a British thumbprint, it seems. (In fact, gulp, it was filmed
in Ireland.)
</P>
<P>
   But ``Babe'' was the antic fable of the little pig that could.
``Animal Farm'' is a darkly corrosive story of human vice, told
whole-hog.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
