<HEADER>
A2392 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-GRANDILLUSION-TE     09-30 0244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GRANDILLUSION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALLY, REALLY GRAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Grand Illusion'' is simply among the finest films ever made, a
delicately etched look at an era that was ending even as the movie
was being filmed.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Renoir's reverie on the struggles of French soldiers
suffering at a German prison camp during World War I isn't filled
with the kind of atrocity that we've come to expect from such
films. But that's because it's a movie about the spiritual horror
of what was thought to be the last World War _ ``Grand Illusion''
was initially released in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   As the French prisoners put together their escape plans, Renoir
offers a window on the imperiled and dying European nobility, a
class of people more closely aligned with the 19th century _ in
which time their training and ideals were born _ than the 20th,
which was as new and strange to them as Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Although Renoir is impatient with this class, he notes its death
with a touch of regret, perhaps because no filmmaker's work is more
suffused with craft and empathy. The scene of noblesse oblige as
Jean Gabin is dying, and Erich von Stroheim's attempt to minister
to him as his station merits, will stay with you forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand Illusion'' is unrated, with adult subject matter. In
French, with subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2393 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-GROUCHLAND-TEX     09-30 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GROUCHLAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLEAR CASE OF BLANKIE-PANKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Henson's Muppets have always been decidedly more hip than
other characters in children's programming. They're funnier and
more savvy, even a little grittier _ if the imagination allows a
connection between ``Muppets'' and ``gritty.'' In short, they're as
cool as multi-hued cloth puppets can be, and their human
personalities make them far more fun than all those other creatures
on kids' television.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland,'' the latest Sesame
Street spinoff to hit theaters, Elmo and the gang capitalize on
that coolness quotient as much as they can in a movie aimed at
4-year-olds. And it's that smartness _ a way of being funny without
talking down to kids _ that makes the movie worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins with Elmo and his blanket doing a musical number
in a laundromat, with fellow customers _ and pieces of laundry _
joining in. But Elmo won't share his blanket, and when it gets away
from him, he goes into full panic mode.
</P>
<P>
   In search of his fabric friend, Elmo trespasses in Oscar the
Grouch's trash can. A secret door falls open and whisks him away to
Grouchland, Oscar's hometown, a land of garbage and grossness. But
just as Elmo is adjusting to ``grouch culture,'' the evil menace
arrives on the scene in a helicopter. It's Huxley (Mandy Patinkin),
who lives in a castle in Grouchland and wants to take everything
from everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Huxley takes Elmo's blanket, prompting Elmo to make a long,
lonely journey to the castle to get it back. Along the way, Elmo
becomes discouraged and then inspired by a bug and a talking plant.
Finally, he decides he does have the strength to stand up to the
selfish Huxley. Personal growth ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Bert and Ernie stop the action occasionally to explain things to
the audience _ a plus for small children.
</P>
<P>
   Patinkin is convincingly evil _ as convincing, that is, as a
grown man who covets blankets and toys and lollipops can be.
Vanessa Williams is the Queen of Trash, who convinces Elmo to
persevere.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Elmo's friends arrive to help him (from Maria to Big
Bird, they all slip through Oscar's magic door), he has figured out
the big lesson: ``Nobody wants to be friends with a greedy, selfish
villain.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids will probably like the interaction that develops between
characters and the audience. And _ no surprise _ the film
encourages teamwork and sharing.
</P>
<P>
   But who else would bring you singing socks with such finesse?
Who else would throw in a talking plant that wonders, ``How come
nobody ever thinks their shrubbery got somethin' to say?'' In a
movie that's essentially about losing, finding and then sharing a
security blanket, ``Elmo'' proves Sesame Street is a pretty cool
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland'' is rated G and is
suitable for all audiences.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2394 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-DRIVEMECRAZY-TEX     09-30 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DRIVEMECRAZY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S ALL THAT, AND IT'S NOT ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Drive Me Crazy'' is one of those movies that deserve two
reviews: One for its target audience, and one for people who can
drink legally. This isn't meant to be as condescending as it might
sound. But it seems unlikely that people who have put any distance
between themselves and high school would be interested in this
slight comedy-drama, while teens can probably relate to its
characters' problems.
</P>
<P>
   Teens will probably have a moment of clarity, though, when
Barenaked Ladies' ``It's All Been Done'' plays on the soundtrack.
It's all been done, all right, again and again. It's so been done
that ``Drive Me Crazy'' is like holding up some gender-switching
mirror to ``She's All That.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a shallow, popular guy, there's a shallow, popular
girl (Melissa Joan Hart of TV's ``Sabrina, the Teenage Witch'').
Instead of a nonconformist girl getting a makeover, it's a
nonconformist boy (Adrian Grenier). Instead of a bet, it's
teen-romance politics that creates their liaison: He wants to make
an ex-girlfriend want him back, she wants to attract the attentions
of a hunky basketball player. Instead of a prom, there's a school
centennial dance _ but a prom scene, by any other name, still
smells like a prom scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drive Me Crazy'' could have used some of the high spirits and
pop-cultural self-consciousness of ``She's All That,'' which used
those ingredients to steamroller many of its flaws. ``Crazy'' is
actually pretty sane, and its diagrammed structure and slack pacing
give you too much time to think about things that are wrong with
it.
</P>
<P>
   Things like the way Grenier's character makes the transition to
the ``in'' crowd so fast, it looks as if he's been brainwashed by
the Gap's ``everybody in khakis'' commercials. Things like the way
the movie tries to equate high-school pep rallies with Nazi
rallies, a callow joke that overstates the evil of the former and
trivializes the evil of the latter. Things like the way the movie
can't quite decide whether conformity or nonconformity is better,
then tips its hand by linking itself to the latest Britney Spears
single.
</P>
<P>
   Hart and Grenier are likable enough, although Grenier was much
better in the recent ``Adventures of Sebastian Cole,'' in which he
played a character who would have dismissed ``Drive Me Crazy'' as
soon as he saw its poster. The most likable characters, though, are
a not-that-geeky geek (Mark Webber of the upcoming ``Whiteboys'')
who tries to keep Grenier in line, and a beauty queen (Keri Lynn
Pratt) who has a strong, compassionate side. If the movie had been
about them, it could have been something interesting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drive Me Crazy'' is rated PG-13 for infrequent strong language
and scenes of teens drinking.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film ritic for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
