<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2397 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-PLUNKETT-TEX     09-30 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PLUNKETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME-WARP BANDITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the 18th-century highwaymen Plunkett and Macleane were as
proficient as director Jake Scott, they might have had a more
successful career. Scott tries a fresh spin on this tale of two
freebooters, the up-from-the streets Plunkett (Robert Carlyle) and
the well-born but broke Macleane (Jonny Lee Miller), who throw
together their lots. Plunkett's goal is to use Macleane's
background and access to fellow noblemen to scope out their homes
as likely robbery targets. Macleane's ambition is to squander his
life in the tradition of spoiled gentry, by gambling and
womanizing. Scott's application of a less formal and more playful
directing style to the stodgy costume drama results in a few
elements stolen ... er, pilfered ... um, inspired by about 900
other movies, including ``Les Miserables.'' He must think half his
job is done when he uses two stars of the tricked-out
``Trainspotting.'' Scott is lucky that one of those stars is
Carlyle, one of the most intense and charismatic actors around.
Plunkett is a conceit _ an apothecary/explosives expert who is,
ironically, more noble than Macleane. But Carlyle, a performer with
a fiery love of acting in his eyes, elevates Plunkett into a full
character. The wastrels he plans to rob are totally unreal to
Plunkett: To him, they're garbage wrapped in skin.
</P>
<P>
   A bond grows between Plunkett and Macleane only because of
Carlyle's emotional investment. Both parts are underwritten,
although Scott dances through the material by using anachronisms so
relentlessly, including a banging techno score, that you might as
well be watching a Janet Jackson video.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plunkett &AMP; Macleane'' is rated R for violence, profanity and
adult sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBR/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
