<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The game of the week was musical chairs _ director's
chairs.
</P>
<P>
   On the set of ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' a musical adaptation
of Joyce's short story, a formal announcement was released on
Tuesday that Richard Nelson would be sharing the directing credit
with Jack Hofsiss, originally announced as the show's sole
director. The show's first preview is Friday night at Playwrights
Horizons.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Sanford, the artistic director of Playwrights Horizons, said
Nelson, who adapted Joyce's story, had been handling most of the
directing chores since last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rehearsals weren't where we wanted when we made the switch,''
Sanford said. ``We talked to Jack, and Jack addressed the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors had been circulating that Hofsiss, a veteran Broadway
director, had been dismissed or pushed out. Sanford denied those
rumors and said that Hofsiss was still attending rehearsals and
that much of his work was still evident in the piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``This took a year and half to mount,'' he said. ``And Jack was
driving for most of that time.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift would have no effect on the show's schedule, Sanford
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to pretend that this wasn't dramatic,'' he said.
``But there have been much more dramatic things happen in
rehearsals.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Public Theater, another directorial change was made,
under very different circumstances. Marcus Stern, the planned
director of ``In the Blood,'' by Suzan-Lori Parks, was forced to
drop out of the production after seriously injuring his knee.
</P>
<P>
   David Esbjornson, director of the recently opened ``Mud'' and
``Drowning'' at the Signature Theater Company, has taken over, but
the first preview has been pushed back a week, to Nov. 2. Charlayne
Woodard heads a six-person ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, however, talk of directorial changes seemed to be
just that, talk. The rumor du jour on Broadway was that Sam Mendes,
the director of ``Wise Guys,'' the new Sondheim musical, and of the
film ``American Beauty,'' was close to leaving the developmental
production at the New York Theater Workshop. Gossips also posited
that the show, scheduled to begin on Oct. 29, might be delayed
because rehearsals began a week later than scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   But John Barlow, a spokesman, said that while rehearsals for
principal performers were delayed by a week, the show's stars,
Nathan Lane and Victor Garber, are now in the second week of music
rehearsals at the workshop and the full company rehearsals with
Mendes would begin on Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim and John Weidman, the book writer, are working on the
script and score, and on Monday, a letter went out to renewing
subscribers of the workshops inviting them to the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's on schedule,'' Barlow said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Gershwin Theater, Broadway's biggest theater,
seems to be becoming its biggest dance hall.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next spring, the 1,933-seat Gershwin will be home to
``Riverdance,'' the Irish dance spectacle. But coming up first is
the return of ``Tango Argentino,'' a surprise critical and popular
hit in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the show, a two-hour revue performed by 30 dancers,
sparked a minirevival of the tango in the city, replete with tango
lessons, tango togs and tango parties. It ran six months. This
fall's version will be an eight-week run, beginning on Nov. 11 with
much of the original cast, including Hector and Elsa Maria Mayoral,
who are described in press materials as ``President Clinton's
personal tango instructors while he was in Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being another all-dance entry on Broadway,
``Argentino'' seems to be the latest to try to capitalize on the
throngs of people expected in the city for the millennial
celebration. Other limited-run entertainments include planned gigs
by the comedian Jackie Mason, the singer Liza Minnelli and by the
daytime-television actress Susan Lucci in ``Annie Get Your Gun.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all of the regional summer theater festivals, New York Stage
and Film, in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., has kept a lower profile, inviting
fewer big-name movie stars and little critical appraisal than
festivals like the Williamstown Theater Festival.
</P>
<P>
   But as the 1999-2000 season develops, it looks as though as many
as five plays that had their debuts in Poughkeepsie will appear on
New York stages.
</P>
<P>
   The first up is ``Chesapeake,'' by Lee Blessing, a one-man show
that features Mark Linn-Baker as both its actor and one of its
producers.
</P>
<P>
   The play, about a performance artist who kidnaps a conservative
senator's dog, had its debut at the Stage and Film this summer and
begins previews at Second Stage Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read it, I knew it was something I wanted to do,'' said
Linn-Baker, of the play. ``I was just praying I wasn't the only one
that thought that.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't. For ``Chesapeake,'' Linn-Baker teamed with Max Mayer,
the director and the man with whom he and Leslie Urdang founded
Stage and Film in 1984. The program, on the campus of Vassar
College, now runs eight weeks and presents nearly two dozen new
works. The whole idea, then and now, was to develop work ``outside
the scrutiny of critical and commercial eyes,'' Linn-Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   But that ethos has not prevented some intrepid producers from
sampling the fare and importing it to New York. This season,
transfers from Stage and Film will include ``The Clearing,'' now
playing at the Blue Light Theater Company; ``Hurricane,'' by Erin
Cressida Wilson, opening at Classic Stage Company in December and
``Bomb-itty of Errors,'' a hip-hop Shakespearean adaptation, which
has been optioned by the producer Daryl Roth.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, Manhattan Theater Club confirmed that the play
``Current Events,'' by David Marshall Grant, will open on its
second stage in June 2000. David Petrarca will direct. The play had
its premiere at Stage and Film in July.
</P>
<P>
   Considering all this, might Linn-Baker have a future as a
big-time producer? ``I'm an actor and a director,'' he said. ``I
like to get my hands dirty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
