<HEADER>
A2399 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FERMAN-POPMUSIC-TEX     09-30 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERMAN-POPMUSIC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE GUYS FROM TEXAS MARK THREE DECADES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the CD title implies, that little ol' band from Texas marks
its 30th anniversary this year of pumping out superamped
boogie-blues. That's brawny beats from Frank Beard, rumbling bass
and the occasional lead vocal from Dusty Hill, and salacious
singing and swaggering guitar solos from Billy Gibbons.
</P>
<P>
   And by now, it ought to be all over: There's only so much you
can do with three guys and a bunch of Lightnin' Hopkins and Freddie
King guitar riffs on 11, and it would figure that by now it's all
been said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the '90s have been a relatively lean decade for da
Top: They released their worst CD ever, ``Antenna,'' in 1994. And
they are not the concert draw they were in the '80s, when a
combination of smart tunes and fun videos for ``Legs, Gimme All
Your Lovin''' and others made them one of the most popular live
acts in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But lo and behold, the new ``XXX'' is a darned good record. Due
to some by-the-numbers, been-there-done-that boogie, this isn't one
of their greatest efforts by any means, but it does sound as though
the band is energized and still willing to tinker with the formula.
It is, at times, downright strange _ and that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   There is, first of all, the rap _ yes, rap _ touches of
``Crucifixx-A-Flatt.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the slow blues _ every Top CD has to have one, you
know _ of ``Made Into a Movie,'' which has a slightly psychedelic
expansiveness that compares with Neil Young's ``Cortez the
Killer.''
</P>
<P>
   It gets odder, though. ``Dreadmonboogaloo'' is a quirky, quick
little slice of organ-spiced ZZ-goes-lounge (er, kind of) that sets
up four live songs _ the first time that the band has mixed live
and studio cuts since 1975's ``Fandango!,'' the LP that gave the
band the huge hit single ``Tush.''
</P>
<P>
   The introduction to these songs is by one Ross Mitchell, who
basically takes the intro James Brown got on his 1963 ``Live at the
Apollo'' and makes it sound real stiff and white-bread, going so
far as to call them ``the ZZ Tops.'' Then the band comes on in what
sounds like a packed bar and does ``Sinpusher,'' an obvious remake
of 1994's ``Pincushion.'' And if that's not strange enough, the
next song is Elvis' ``Let Me Be Your (Teddy Bear),'' slowed down
considerably and featuring Dusty on lead vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Huh? The final two songs, ``Hey Mr. Millionaire'' and ``Belt
Buckle,'' are only fair, but by this time the left turns, the fat,
thick sound and the small handful of stellar tunes _ ``Movie'' and
the opening ``Poke Chop Sandwich'' among them _ has made this, if
nothing else, an interesting CD. It doesn't have the consistency of
1973's ``Tres Hombres, Fandango!'' or 1983's ``Eliminator,'' but it
shows that the three wise men of rock 'n' roll are still good for
some aural barbecue and the occasional pleasantly twisted detour
from the norm.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
