<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Oct. 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   With moisture having been swept east over the Atlantic by
Thursday's cold front and with moisture over the Gulf of Mexico
corralled by steering winds from the west, most of the East will be
dry Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One small exception will be southern and central Florida, where
isolated showers and thunderstorms develop mainly during the
afternoon in response to warm air converging and rising near a
stalled front lying across the middle of the peninsula. Also, a few
showers will skirt upstate New York and northwest New England as a
moisture-starved disturbance pivots east across southern Ontario
and southern Quebec. But spotty showers from variable clouds will
be confined mainly to the St. Lawrence River Valley, including the
island of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Broken areas of rain will spread from South Dakota toward Iowa,
southern Wisconsin and northwest Illinois Friday and Friday night.
Some snow may fall during the first half of the day in a narrow
swath on the northern fringe of the rain shield. Thus, only limited
parts of South Dakota will likely be affected by snow. As
temperatures rise from their morning nadir, all of the
precipitation that develops across parts of the Middle West will
fall as rain. Meanwhile, the leading edge of the coldest air mass
of the season will brush North Dakota and northern Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Pockets of snow will develop east of the Front Range of the
Rockies from the Black Hills of South Dakota to parts of northeast
Wyoming and southern Montana as moist, chilly winds from the east
ascend the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Santa Ana Heat
</P>
<P>
   The temperature soared to 102 degrees at Los Angeles Thursday,
marking one of several records that were set in California. Heat
mounted as winds from the east, which were orchestrated by a
sprawling high pressure system over the Rockies, warmed on descent
from the San Gabriel and San Bernardino Mountains. Moreover, these
winds kept the layer of cool Pacific air confined to the beaches.
Offshore winds that bring heat to California are called Santa Anas,
which derive their name from the canyon through which they course
on their westward journey toward the coast.
</P>
