<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE SPORTS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These sports stories for release Friday, October 1, 1999, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-METS _ NEW YORK _ Braves at Mets game coverage.
(Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: First pitch is at 7:10 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-REDS-PLAYOFFS _ A look at the National League pennant race
in the final weekend of the baseball season. The Reds, for their
part, believe they are in control of their own destiny. ( McCoy,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-TENN-ESPN _ Are the officials at ESPN upset with the
Tennessee football program? That's what fans and players in
Knoxville are thinking after a recent story by the cable network
alledging academic fraud among the university's football players.
Tennessee offensive lineman Spencer Riley has recently gone on the
record with comments about ESPN and fans believe the cable network
had a role in promoting Michigan's Charles Woodson to win the
Heisman over Vols quarterback Peyton Manning in 1997. Fans in
Knoxville are not happy with the cable giant. (Barnhart, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-UGA-SANKS _ Georgia coach Jim Donnan and running back Jasper
Sanks think unrealistic expectations from fans and media
contributed to Sanks'disappointing debut last season. Despite
entering as one of the Bulldogs' most heralded freshmen since
Herschel Walker, Sanks had weight problems and injuries and
finished with 65 yards on 10 carries. But a rededicated Sanks
reported 18 pounds lighter this season (216) and stronger from a
year in theweight room. After an injury-free preseason, he gained a
starting job. And after three games, he has consecutive 130-plus
rushing games. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-BUCKEYES _ Heading into a big matchup with Wisconsin, we
analyze OSU's first three games. The Bucks have gotten out of the
blocks very slowly going into halftime tied and struggling even
when they played back to back games against opponents that were 30
points plus underdogs. The Bucks may be in trouble when they lineup
against the Badgers explosive offense. (Vinella, Dayton Daily
News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-TECH-TERPS _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech vs. Maryland lead, 8
p.m. (Clemons, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL/PROS
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS _The Falcons offense, among the league leaders in
most categories last season, has started out kind of slow, then
fizzled out all together. The problems began with the release of
Tony Martin and mushroomed with the injuries to Jamal Anderson and
Chris Chandler. (Winkeljohn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   RACING
</P>
<P>
   CAR-NASCAR-FEATURE _ When Ray Evernham left Hendrick Motorsports
on Wednesday, it left a void on arguably the best racing team in
Winston Cup history. And that's how the Evernham-Jeff Gordon
pairing will go down in history. (Carvell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET NASCAR PAGE
</P>
<P>
   The budget for this week's CoxNet NASCAR page has been revised
following developments in the Hendrick Motorsports' team. Here is a
budget for the page, which will be available Thursday before 3 p.m.
EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET NASCAR 1001 _ When Ray Evernham left Hendrick Motorsports
on Wednesday, it left a void on arguably the best racing team in
Winston Cup history. And that's how the Evernham-Jeff Gordon
pairing will go down in history. (Carvell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP NOTES _ Odds and ends column from the world of
Winston Cup. (Carvell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH SERIES NOTES _ Odds and ends column from the world of
Busch series. (Carvell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH GRAND NATIONAL STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   NEXT RACE _ A preview of Sunday's NAPA Auto Care 500 from
Martinsville Speedway featuring a 2-column color illustration of
Martinsville Speedway, Martinsville, Va.
</P>
<P>
   HOCKEY
</P>
<P>
   NHL-OPENERS _ The NHL _ without Wayne Gretzky for the first time
in 20 seasons _ opens the season Friday with two games, several new
rules and a new team _ Atlanta. The first games are Pittsburgh at
Dallas and N.Y. Rangers at Edmonton. Gretzky will be honored in
Edmonton. (Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-THRASHERS _ ATLANTA _ GM Don Waddell and coach Curt Fraser
say that the Thrashers will play an aggressive style while still
concentrating on defense. What does that mean? A look at the kind
of games Thrasher fans can expect this season. The opener is
Saturday night against New Jersey at Philips Arena. (Schultz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BUICK-DAY1 _ PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ First round of Buick
Challenge golf tournament at Callaway Gardens. (Sheeley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 13.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS-IOC _ ATHENS, Greece _ The International Olympic
Committee executive board meets in the host city for the 2004 Games
amid fresh allegations that Atlanta Olympic bidding officials may
have been less pure than they claimed in their campaign for the
1996 Games. Ironically, Athens, one of Atlanta's rivals, has been
assumed over the years to have been the dirtiest contestant for the
1996 Games. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
