<HEADER>
A2410 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT &LR;      09-30 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE PICASSOS FROM ESTATE AUCTION; VERTICAL POLLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another Estate, More Picassos
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last week Christie's announced that it was selling a
group of paintings, drawings and sculptures belonging to Madeleine
Haas Russell, one of San Francisco's most important collectors, who
died in April. This week, it's Sotheby's turn to crow about being
chosen to sell artwork from a major estate.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Nov. 10, it will auction a collection of
20th-century art belonging to Eleanore and Daniel Saidenberg, the
Manhattan gallery owners who represented Picasso in the United
States from 1955 until the artist's death in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The Saidenbergs' estate is far bigger than Mrs. Russell's, so
big that Sotheby's is selling the works in a special evening
auction by itself. Included in the sale are 46 works of
20th-century art from the couple's personal collection. Sotheby's
estimates that the auction could total $55 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Saidenbergs were not typical art dealers. Mrs. Saidenberg,
who died in August, was a founder of the Art Dealers Association of
America. She was also a modern dancer. Saidenberg was also a
well-known cellist and conductor.
</P>
<P>
   The couple first opened their gallery, which was on the Upper
East Side, in 1950. In addition to Picasso they showed such
20th-century masters as Braque, Leger and Kandinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Saidenbergs were dealers first,'' said Charles Moffett,
co-chairman of Sotheby's Impressionist and modern art department
worldwide. ``They didn't create an enormous collection but a
special one. Clearly the things they held back for themselves were
works that spoke to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting that will get the most attention at the sale is
Picasso's ``Seated Woman in a Garden.'' Made on Dec. 8, 1938, it is
one of the grandest depictions of Dora Maar, a mistress of Picasso
whom the artist frequently painted. Maar is regally seated on a
thronelike chair surrounded by naively rendered flowers in this
densely painted work, adorned by a variety of stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's estimates that the painting, which measures 51 by 38
inches, could bring $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another prized Picasso belonging to the Saidenbergs will be
offered in November. It is ``The Statuary,'' a 1925 neo-classical
work in which a female figure poses formally beside a modeling
stand on which rests a bust of an elderly man. The painting was
shown at the artist's request in an exhibition of his work at the
Galerie Georges Petit in Paris in 1932. It is estimated to bring
$12 million to $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't the only Picassos on offer in November. Christie's
will auction one from the Haas estate that depicts another of
Picasso's mistresses, Marie-Therese Walter. Painted in 1932, it
measures 65 inches by 53 inches and shows Walter reclining with one
arm over her head. Christie's believes it could bring around $35
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Saidenberg sale also includes paintings, drawings, sculpture
and ceramics by a variety of artists, among them Braque and Leger.
</P>
<P>
   A Sideways Pollock?
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Whitney Museum of American Art say they haven't
made a mistake. Jackson Pollock's ``No. 27, 1950,'' displayed in
the opening gallery of the second part of ``The American Century:
Art and Culture 1900-2000,'' has been hung vertically on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow drip painting is signed on the horizontal side and
has always been exhibited that way, except at its first public
appearance in Pollock's 1950 show at the Betty Parsons Gallery on
West 57th Street in Manhattan, when it was oriented vertically.
Next to the elevators on the Whitney's fifth floor, where the
painting now hangs, the museum is displaying several photographs of
that first show as supporting evidence. Also on display are eight
small square drip paintings that were in the Parsons show and are
visible in the photographs. They hang in stacks of four not unlike
a Donald Judd wall sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had only ever seen it hung horizontally,'' said Lisa
Phillips, the show's curator, who is now director of the New Museum
for Contemporary Art in Soho. ``But when I went to a lecture given
by T.J. Clarke at the Museum of Modern Art around the time of its
Pollock retrospective, he showed the painting hanging vertically.
It was a revelation. We wouldn't have done this if Pollock himself
hadn't approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell Anderson, director of the Whitney, said that ``No. 27''
was hung vertically ``in part out of a desire to provide a sense of
the original character of the works in the show.'' Still, many
visitors who notice the signature going up the painting's left-hand
side are perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Varnedoe, chief curator of paintings and sculpture at the
Modern, noted that when Hans Namuth filmed Pollock working outside
his Long Island studio in East Hampton, ``Pollock is moving around
the painting's sides, so there's no telling if he had any
particular orientation in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Varnedoe, who organized the Modern's giant 1998 Pollock
retrospective, said he hung the painting horizontally in that show
because of the orientation of its signature. But he added that ``if
it had been sufficiently important to Pollock, it wouldn't have
been hung vertically at Betty Parsons.''
</P>
<P>
   Harlem Losing Director
</P>
<P>
   Kinshasha Holman Conwill is stepping down after 11 years as
director of the Studio Museum in Harlem. The museum's collection
grew significantly during Ms. Conwill's tenure, and she helped
organize more than 40 exhibitions. Recently she announced that the
institution, on West 125th Street, would undergo a major expansion
and renovation to install the first galleries devoted to its
permanent collection. The museum will expand to 72,000 square feet
from 60,000.
</P>
<P>
   George Knox, chairman of the museum's board of trustees, said
the museum had formed a search committee to find a new director.
Although Ms. Conwill is leaving Oct. 31, the board has not yet
named an interim director.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
