<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-ART-2TAK     09-30 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEK 4 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK:
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville (2-1) vs. Pittsburgh (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Buckle down for a fierce battle, a tingling fight, a
knock-'em-down-and-out affair between the American Football
Conference's top-ranked defensive teams. Points will be a premium.
So will rushing yards. There is bad blood here but also an intense
rivalry and respect between divisional foes who have won four
apiece in their last eight meetings. And the winning team in each
of those games has been the home team. Jacksonville last season
ended Pittsburgh's hold on the AFC Central. That will fuel the
Steelers. So will quarterback Kordell Stewart handling the ball,
back Jerome Bettis running with it and linebacker Jason Gilden
pursuing it. Steelers, 17-13.
</P>
<P>
   1 P.M. GAMES:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (1-2) vs. Dallas (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Dallas has won 16 of its past 17 meetings versus
Arizona but the last game was the loss, a wild-card playoff game
last year where Arizona shocked Dallas and quarterback Jake Plummer
riddled them. In fact, Plummer in his last two games against Dallas
has completed 50 of 92 passes for 678 yards with five touchdowns
and three interceptions. Last year in a regular-season game against
Dallas he threw the ball 56 times and gained 465 passing yards. No
doubt, the Cowboys have him targeted and gained an extra week
through the bye to find solutions. Arizona panicked in its Monday
night loss at home against San Francisco and Dallas will blitz
Plummer heavily to force more errors. Cowboys, 23-14.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore (1-2) vs. Atlanta (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: It has gotten ugly quick for Atlanta with injuries and
spotty play and turnovers. The Falcons have won five of six against
the AFC and 10 of 11 at home. It did that with a sure running game
and with surer hands _ few turnovers. Error-free ball will be
Atlanta's chief goal in this game. Stopping Ravens back Errict
Rhett will be another. Expect an Atlanta rebound with Chris
Chandler to receiver Terance Mathis paving the way. Linebacker
Jessie Tuggle and the Atlanta defense will play in inspiring,
aggressive style, and, for the moment, right Atlanta. Falcons,
23-13
</P>
<P>
   New England (3-0) vs. Cleveland (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: New England has won close games with late, exacting
offensive drives for scores and with a fourth-quarter defense that
has excelled. Now they travel to the new Dawg Pound and are in
jeopardy of being bitten. This is a dangerous game for New England
because quarterback Tim Couch will be improved and so will the
Browns defense. Too, Cleveland has the fewest penalties (8) and
penalty yards (50) in the league. The Browns are hungry for that
first victory. New England will need another fourth-quarter surge.
Patriots, 24-21.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans (1-1) vs. Chicago (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Mike Ditka remains legend in Chicago and the city is
excited, once again, to welcome him back. Ditka will find a better
Bears team, though. Their three games have each been decided 7 or
fewer points. The Bears defense leads the league in fumble
recoveries and it leads the NFC with nine total turnovers forced.
Bears quarterback Shane Matthews has not not forced his passes and
back Curtis Enis has gained 193 rushing yards and 135 receiving
yards. End Clyde Simmons has four sacks. Look for the Bears to play
in their old style with robust defense and a solid running game.
Ditka would be proud. Problem is, this time, he is on the receiving
end of a Bears throwback victory. Bears, 28-7.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia (0-3) vs. Giants (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: The Eagles were shut out by Buffalo last week and show
little signs of life. They enter against a team struggling on
offense, particularly in the running game. Joe Montgomery gets a
crack at running back for the Giants and expect him to surprise. He
has excellent quickness and shows determination at the end of his
runs. The Giants, like many NFL teams, are slow to put the ball in
the hands of rookies but Montgomery will show why this is often an
ill-advised philosophy and why if a player can, indeed, play,
experience matters little. The Giants offense will emerge and the
Eagles as a team will continue to sink. Giants, 33-17.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis (2-0) vs. Cincinnati (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Willie Jackson of the Bengals leads the AFC in kickoff
return average. That's about it for Cincinnati. It is off to
another woeful start and meets a team that is excited about its
play. The Rams are averaging nearly 400 yards of offense and their
quarterback, Kurt Warner, is one of only two in the league in the
last 50 years with three touchdown passes in his first two starts
(Dan Marino in 1983 is the other). Warner wasn't even supposed to
be playing: the Rams invested big free agent dollars in Trent Green
during the offseason to be their quarterback. But Warner and a team
full of optimism for the first time in a long time continue their
winning ways. The Bengals? There's always Willie Jackson. Rams,
23-20.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay (2-1) vs. Minnesota (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Mitch Berger punts for the Vikings and his average
leads the league. He will get plenty of practice against Tampa Bay
because the Bucs own the league's No.-1 ranked defense. Tampa Bay
is averaging only 143.3 passing yards and 55 rushing yards allowed.
But they may play without end Warren Sapp, injured and likely
slowed even if he plays. That gives Minnesota a slight edge in a
rugged game where turnovers late are decisive. Vikings, 16-10.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   4 P.M. GAMES:
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City (2-1) vs. San Diego (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Not only are the Chargers the best in the league at
allowing the fewest average yards per carry, they also have not
allowed a 100-yard rusher in 21 consecutive games. The Chargers
have turned the ball over only once. They could be 2-0 but wilted
against the Colts last week at home. Kansas City has won two
straight and has beaten San Diego in three of its last four. But
watch quarterback Jim Harbaugh outplay the Chiefs' Elvis Grbac and
for back Natrone Means to help the Chargers win with tough
fourth-quarter running. Chargers, 19-14.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (1-2) vs. Washington (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: George Seifert has not lost to Washington and Norv
Turner has not lost to Carolina. Something between these head
coaches must give. It will be Seifert. He used to handle the
Panthers while 49ers head coach but his Panthers do not have
similar talent. They whipped the Bengals last week and back Tim
Biakabutuka gained 132 rushing yards. He added
franchise-record-long touchdown runs of 62 and 67 yards. On one of
them, he reversed field and sped away. Against the Redsksins, he
will reverse, spin _ and run into more defenders. His counterpart,
the Redskins Stephen Davis, has eight rushing touchdowns and he
will reach the end zone again. So will his team, often, in another
display of why they figure to battle prominently for the NFC East
divisional crown. Redskins, 30-17.
</P>
<P>
   Jets (0-3) vs. Denver (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: A rematch of last season's AFC championship game (won
by Denver, 23-10) has fizzled into a fight for survival. Both
teams, winless, are reeling. Steve Atwater, the Jets safety, played
10 seasons for Denver before joining the Jets. He will give them an
inside track, particularly on the Broncos defense. It is a big game
for Broncos kicker Jason Elam; with 2 points he passes Jim Turner
and become's Denver's all-time leading scorer. Terrell Davis rushed
for 167 yards the last time these teams played. He won't get that
many this time, but enough to give Denver the victory. Broncos,
21-17.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (3-0) vs. San Francisco (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Tennessee is turning heads. It is in sole possession of
first place for the first time in six years. It has never been 4-0.
It won't be this time, either. The Titans showed wonderful resolve
on the road at Jacksonville in winning a critical divisional game
against a strong team. Asking for that two weeks in a row, even
without the 49ers Steve Young in the lineup, is too much. Young is
out nursing a concussion and his backup, Jeff Garcia, will find
receiver Terrell Owens open for big plays. The 49ers defense is led
by veteran end Charles Haley, an inspiration to his teammates and
one of the game's most knowledgeable players. 49ers, 17-12.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT:
</P>
<P>
   Oakland (2-1) vs. Seattle (2-1) COMMENT: Oakland and Seattle
battle for first place in the AFC West under bright lights and
scrutiny. Are the Raiders for real? Can coach Mike Holmgren work
similar magic with Seattle as he did in Green Bay? Oakland trails
only Indianapolis in AFC offensive yards gained. The Raiders have
gained a boost in back Tyrone Wheatley's power running. But Seattle
is a team full of stars that have underachieved. Playing in prime
time often brings out the best in underachievers. Look for Seattle
to click. Seahawks, 28-20.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT:
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo (2-1) vs. Miami (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENT: Another divisional battle for the top spot. Miami leads
the AFC East. Buffalo wants an early share of the top spot. Watch
how Miami defends Doug Flutie. Expect the Dolphins to rush him wide
and make his scramble up the middle where linebacker Zach Thomas
will be waiting. Scrambling against this defense could be scary for
Flutie. The Dolphins gang tackle and punish ballcarriers. This is a
game Miami wins with defense. Dolphins, 21-9.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
