<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUINEVERE-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S NO KING ARTHUR, BUT SHE'S NO GUINEVERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's apparent that a romance movie has issues when a
smooch between the Guy and the Girl makes one squirm in one's seat,
when every domestic quarrel warrants silent celebration, when all
one can really hope for the characters is terminal disease.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Guinevere,'' an artsy film about a 20-something girl who
``comes of age'' by shacking up with a man at least twice her age,
this issue is not about blushing at on-screen lip-lock or the
conventional conflicts and slightly ``ageist'' criticism of
May-December romances. After Clinton and Monica, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   The issue at hand, or should we say lip, is failure on the part
of writer-director Audrey Wells, and likely on the part of the
actors, to convince us that there is anything behind that kiss
other than stage direction.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, best known for writing ``The Truth About Cats and Dogs,''
has penned the love into the script, doing plenty of telling about
why a 21-year-old girl would need a 50-year-old man, but she fails
to capture on camera any of the magic that is falling and being in
love.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Polley (Go) is Harper Sloane, a lost little rich girl
raised in San Francisco by a family of lawyers. On the eve of
entering Harvard Law School under pressure by her family, she meets
Connie Fitzpatrick, played by Stephen Rea (Michael Collins''), who
decides she has it in her to be a photographer like him, even
though she's never taken a picture, painted a painting, etc.
</P>
<P>
   He calls her his Guinevere, as in the ``aging King Arthur falls
in love with young Guinevere'' tale, and invites her to move in
with him if she promises to devote herself to kissing and becoming
an artist. (There's other stuff along the lines of kissing that is
implied off-screen, thank goodness.)
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks into her study, Harper discovers she's the latest in
a long line of Connie's Guineveres and leaves in an angry huff,
eliciting much personal viewing joy. (Lan-ce-lot! Lan-ce-lot!)
</P>
<P>
   But she comes back, there's more lip-lock, and critics' disgust
ensues.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not all bad. The plot is cliched, but with the
simple inclusion of on-screen love, it could have been saved. The
cinematography is hearty and gentle, putting an artistic edge to
the lens that mirrors the plot beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the love issue, which is large, a normally outstanding
Polley gives a great performance, particularly as she giggles her
way through the very first kissing scene. She wears her insecurity
on the extra-long sleeves she stretches and clutches in moments of
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Rea does well as the playboy photographer past his prime,
avoiding the bottled performance that could have been brought so
easily to this role. Again, he just fails to show us his affection
for Polley in anything other than a fatherly, distant way.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Smart as the lawyerly, affection-hungry, sexy Mrs. Sloane
is a wonder to watch in a plot sadly underplayed by Wells. The
monologue in which Rea's character is taken from King Arthur status
to a quivering sliver of a man with a few of Smart's crafty eye
squints and her gutsy delivery is the sole reason to see this
movie. It is here that Wells shows her best talent and character
introspection.
</P>
<P>
   But all is lost once more at the ending, which we won't give
away, except to note that it involves fictionalized ascension to
heaven: white clouds, white clothes and all. Harper starts the
scene by saying ``OK, so I know this is cheesy, but . . . '' But
nothing. She's right.
</P>
<P>
   Where, oh where, is Lancelot when you need him? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jaimee Rose can be reached at (602) 444-7975 or at
Jaimee.Rose(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
