<HEADER>
A2421 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-AROUND-WORLD01     09-30 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AROUND-WORLD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Around the world on a budget
 &HT;    By Jason C. Nuttle
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The trip started with a phone call.
``Remember talking about traveling around the world?'' my best
friend Chad asked.
</P>
<P>
   And soon we were off.
</P>
<P>
   We spent four months and $7,000 each (including the $2,000 I had
to get wired to me) hauling our backpacks around the world.
</P>
<P>
   We traveled by plane, train, motorcycle, bike, felucca (an
Egyptian sailboat) _ you name it.
</P>
<P>
   We used a Eurail pass to explore England, France, Belgium, the
Netherlands, Germany, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary,
Austria, Italy, Spain, Switzerland and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   And onward by air _ to Cairo, Bangkok, and Hong Kong. Chad found
an online travel agency called Ticket Planet (www.ticketplanet.com)
that specializes in around-the-world air fares for budget
travelers. We stayed in hostels and lived cheap.
</P>
<P>
   What would I have done differently? That's easy. I would have
bought a more comfortable pair of shoes, saved more money and asked
for more time off work.
</P>
<P>
   And I would have made sure my ATM card didn't expire halfway
into the trip.
</P>
<P>
   THE ROUTE: We traveled by train throughout Europe, then flew to
Cairo, Bangkok and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   VIEWING THE ELEPHANTS IS A WASH: On the second day of a
motorcycle trip in northern Thailand we came across an elephant
camp. Three elephants walked along the roadside and about a dozen
more splashed in the river. We parked the 150cc dirt bikes we had
rented and spent an hour watching the guides feed and bathe the
elephants. While scrubbing the elephant's back, one guide slipped
and fell in the river. He stripped off his shirt and washed up,
too.
</P>
<P>
   OH CAMEL, ALL YE FAITHFUL: In Cairo, I was determined to ride a
camel around the Great Pyramids in Giza. Horses were available,
too, but who wants to ride a horse to the pyramids? I shopped
around, and we finally found the right camels for the right price
($13 for an hour and a half). It was upsetting to see how much
garbage was around the pyramids and how poorly maintained they
were.
</P>
<P>
   DECK THE (FORMER) WALL: The two days we spent in Berlin should
have been two weeks. We took in umpteen museums and a three-hour
walking tour. We walked through Tiergarten park, and the city's old
zoo, saw the Reichstag, the city's Brandenburg Gate, remnants of
the Berlin Wall, and ended at Checkpoint Charlie, the gateway for
foreigners between the two Berlins during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   GIRLS AND DOLLS: A young girl with two Teletubbies peered out a
train window in an Antwerp, Belgium, train station, which was more
elaborate than a cathedral a few blocks away. The train station
stood about three stories and spanned two city blocks.
</P>
<P>
   SOARING OVER PRAGUE: One of the most majestic places in Europe
has to be Prague. I fell in love with it the first day. The locals
were all concerned about how prices have doubled and sometimes
tripled over the past few years due to the tourist dollar. We
thought everything was cheap.
</P>
<P>
   COWBOY JOE: A Barcelona street performer took time off from
working as a live statue of a cowboy for a hot cup of coffee on the
pedestrian street Las Ramblas. Passers-by would throw money into
his bucket and he would give a slight bend of the elbow and a
thumbs up. Other performers dressed as clowns, trees and silver
Roman figures. There also were artists and musicians on the street.
We spent Christmas at a nearby hostel called the Kabul, and instead
of the turkey dinner served in the hostel's kitchen, a group of us
opted for a little Pakistan/Mid-Eastern restaurant called El Gallo
Kirko. Chevy Chase's ``National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation,''
dubbed in Spanish, was on the TV.
</P>
<P>
   PAINTING THE TOWN: A portrait artist waited in a courtyard in
Florence, Italy, for a client to paint. The city has terrific art
galleries, ancient buildings mixed with modern complexes, and
millions of mopeds. We stayed in a hostel that used to be a
convent.
</P>
<P>
   THE LIGHTS OF VENICE: After an all-night train ride from
Budapest, we were in Venice. A gondolier tied his gondola to a dock
off one of Venice's many canals. The first thing I noticed when we
emerged from the train station was the sound of water everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   LEAPING OVER TO ATHENS: On a trail leading up to the Parthenon
is a rock where people congregate to take in the city and relax. We
spent the day milling around the ancient ruins and the museum until
we were kicked out.
</P>
<P>
   WINDMILLS IN OUR MINDS: You'd think it would be easy to find a
windmill in Holland. We were told they were north of Amsterdam and
could be reached by bike. Finding them was difficult. We finally
just stumbled upon one. It had a sign in the front yard telling
tourists not to walk in, that it was a private residence.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNEY ON THE NILE: We sailed in a felucca (a sailboat) on the
Nile River from Aswan to Luxor, Egypt, and spent three days
stopping by temples and sleeping underneath the stars. I woke
before sunrise and saw a family pulling up to shore near our boat.
They were there to buy food and clothes in the market. The boy was
standing with two women dressed in traditional black waiting for
the men to tie the boat.
</P>
<P>
   BUDAPEST FEST: One night on the way back to our hostel, The
Yellow Submarine, we came across a group of about 200 Hassidic Jews
dancing and singing near the train station. We spent the next day
soaking in hot baths, getting massages and relaxing, all for about
$15. The city is famous for its mineral waters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
