u s BC-NASCAR-MARTIN-NYTR &LR;      09-30 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-MARTIN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK MARTIN IS ONE TOUGH DRIVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is a gutty little guy. Plays with pain, as they say in
football.
</P>
<P>
   When he gets out of bed, Mark Martin hurts, yet he puts the pain
aside. It is mind over matter, and when he wants to, Martin can be
very focused.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his adult life, what Martin has focused most on is
driving a race car.
</P>
<P>
   In itself, given the level he competes at, that is enough. If
there is a driver in Winston Cup who can actually will himself to
win, that driver is Martin. A few others can match Martin's
intensity and concentration, but only a few.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, though, it has gotten tougher and tougher for
Martin to maintain his intensity. Drive a race car hard enough long
enough and you are almost certain to pay a price.
</P>
<P>
   A shredded tire sends you into the wall. A bump from behind
turns you sideways in front of oncoming traffic, which slams into
your car.
</P>
<P>
   Martin ran his first Winston Cup race in 1981 and the years have
taken their toll.
</P>
<P>
   Now 40, Martin is a physical fitness fanatic and that has no
doubt helped him. But there is still a bad back that bothers him.
</P>
<P>
   And there are the wrecks. For example, Martin crashed during the
final practice in Daytona before this year's Pepsi 400. He broke
his left wrist, a bone in his left knee and a rib. Still, he was in
his car the next day, his crew helping pull him out the driver's
window after he finished 17th.
</P>
<P>
   The next week at New Hampshire, he was sixth despite going into
a spin after Kenny Irwin got into him.
</P>
<P>
   Such things are not recommended as part of the healing process,
but must be accepted if you continue to compete, and in Martin's
mind, there was never a thought of not competing.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise that he continued to race, and last
Sunday, on the return trip to New Hampshire, his perseverance paid
off with a win, his second of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The wrist is better and the ribs are better and the knee is OK,
but the back is another story. Drivers have to decide for
themselves when not to race, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Elliott told me I was crazy,'' Martin said. ``He saw me
sitting sideways in the middle of the backstretch at New Hampshire.
He said I was crazy and should have been taking care of myself
instead of doing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taking care of myself,'' Martin declared. ``I'm not done
driving, yet. When I am done, I'll be done. I'll be finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not finished yet, so that means if I'm physically and
mentally capable of driving that race car, I'm going to drive it
every race until I decide that I've had enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the nature of this sport,'' Martin said. ``I have a
race team that has dedicated their lives to the effort, sponsors
who have dedicated their budgets, and I have more people riding on
what that 6-car does and what I do than the average person
realizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to drive the car and I'm going to do a good job. I
don't care if I've got broken bones or not,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   If there is to be a day of reckoning, it will come immediately
after the season ends, when Martin is scheduled to have an
operation on his troublesome back.
</P>
<P>
   After last year, he was to have surgery to correct a bulging
disc. But when an MRI disclosed that the bulge had disappeared,
Martin elected to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Well, what about my pain?' And they said, `Well, your
pain is a deteriorating disc and the only alternative we have is
fusion.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `That's it, I'm outta here. We ain't been talking
about fusion. I've heard bad things about fusion.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I didn't have it done, but now I'm up for the fusion as
long as somebody will not guarantee me, but really convince me,
that I'm gonna be better after I have it,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he will simply keep on keeping on. And if he
does not have too many brushes with the wall, if he is not sent
spinning too many times, he will put the pain aside and go for the
win.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because it is what Mark Martin does, that's why.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
