<HEADER>
A2423 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-NOTES30-COX     09-30 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Medical thrillers pay off for former doctor
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like Michael Crichton, Tess Gerritsen discovered that the pen is
mightier than the scalpel. Or at least more lucrative. A former
doctor who gave up medicine to raise her children, Gerritsen has
found a new career as the author of best-selling medical thrillers
such as ``Harvest'' and ``Life Support.''
</P>
<P>
   Her latest novel, ``Gravity'' (Pocket, $24.95), has been sold to
New Line Cinema for $1 million and is scheduled to be a movie next
summer. ``Contact'' screenwriter Michael Goldenberg is developing
the novel for the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gravity'' is a kind of ``Outbreak'' in space, she says.
``Anything that can go wrong, does go wrong.'' Set aboard a space
station, the story follows the efforts of Dr. Emma Watson to
control the outbreak of exotic DNA-mutating microbes called
Archaeons that could destroy humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Gerritsen, who lives in Maine with her physician husband, got
the idea for ``Harvest,'' her first blockbuster, while having
dinner with a police officer who had been traveling in the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``He heard from a Moscow cop that there were orphans vanishing
from the streets of Moscow, and the Russian police felt these kids
were being sent to the Middle East as organ donors. After trying to
convince people to look into it legally, with no response, I
decided to write a book. I like doing these kinds of novels because
suspense puts characters through the greatest crises they can
possibly face.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerritsen will sign her novel at 7 p.m. Wednesday at Chapter 11
Discount Books in Alpharetta. 10945 State Bridge Road,
770-667-0023.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literary gathering: More than 175 authors are expected at the
11th annual Southern Festival of Books Oct. 8-10 on the Legislative
Plaza in downtown Nashville. Headlining the event are Peter
Matthiessen (``Bone by Bone''), Scott Turow (``Presumed Innocent,''
``Personal Injuries''), Bobbie Ann Mason (``Clear Springs''),
Reynolds Price (``Letters to a Man in the Fire,'' ``Roxanna
Slade'') and Peter Guralnick (``Careless Love: The Unmaking of
Elvis Presley''). For a complete schedule, call 615-242-4400 or go
to www.tn-humanities.org on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Historical perspective: What a difference a century makes. In
his new book, ``London 1900: The Imperial Metropolis'' (Yale
University Press, $29.95), Georgia Tech history professor Jonathan
Schneer examines the capital city of the British empire at its peak
and follows the struggles of those who opposed racism and
imperialism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism pervaded every aspect of life, from advertisements on
down,'' Schneer says. ``Everything conspired to romanticize the
British empire.'' Even the London zoo, with its collection of
animals from British-controlled territories, reminded Londoners of
the vastness of the empire.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was a racist imperialist at the time, Schneer
notes. Some, such as African explorer Mary Kingsley, argued that
blacks were different, not inferior. And, in 1900, a group of black
Londoners organized a Pan-African Conference that was attended by
W.E.B. DuBois of Atlanta. It was a bold gesture at a time when Jim
Crow laws were at their height in America, Schneer says.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one lesson to be learned, Schneer concludes, it is
that empires come and empires go. ``The British thought they would
rule the world forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneer will talk about his book at 3:30 p.m. Wednesday in Room
177 of the Student Services Building, behind the Georgia Tech
Student Center. 225 North Ave., 404-894-3196.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
