</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-PERABO03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Emotions ring false in story collection
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The blurb on the book jacket tells us that Susan Perabo was the
first woman to play NCAA baseball, and that she has a place in the
Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y., to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   In the author's acknowledgments, she thanks the University of
Arkansas faculty ``for turning me from some pretty shaky raw
material into a writer, a teacher, and a reader of great books.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who can't sit in on one of Perabo's classes at
Dickinson College in Pennsylvania, where she teaches creative
writing, or check out her bedside reading, there's this, her debut
collection of stories. And while the verdict is still out on
whether the professors in Fayetteville can live up to their lofty
accolade, there are a couple of very nice reads in this promising,
albeit uneven, little volume.
</P>
<P>
   Perabo's modus operandi is to give ordinary life some cute
little quirk. But unlike a Guy de Maupassant or an O. Henry, who
saved their one-two punches until the end, she tells you what's
going on right up front, then asks you to tag along for the rest of
the ride. There's the Hollywood actor whose father turns out to be
a late-blooming kleptomaniac (``Thick as Thieves''). The woman who
splurges her inheritance on one of Princess Di's gowns (``Counting
the Ways''). The widow who pawns her silver and her car to buy
$35,000 worth of lottery tickets in nine months (``The Greater
Grace of Carlisle'').
</P>
<P>
   Only three stories into the book, a pattern emerges _ and it's
not that interesting as a literary device or a mirror of our times.
That we are more addicted to ephemeral pleasures than the ennobling
pursuits of the heart; that we trade in the currency of cash, not
love; that falling apart is easier than getting a life: Perabo has
fun pointing out what a sad, pill-popping, cigarette-smoking,
angst-ridden mass of humanity we are.
</P>
<P>
   But most of these stories are emotional duds with off-key humor.
Perhaps this collection wasn't a part of Perabo's master's thesis
at Arkansas, but at times it reads like it. This could be material
for a time capsule, but it doesn't serve the literature. As for the
comedy, one sometimes senses that Perabo needs you to write in the
margins: ``How clever!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It rained the morning of the day we killed Dennis Zeller,''
says the first sentence of ``Gravity,'' about two schoolgirls who
accidentally push their nemesis-bully over a precipice. Not only is
this story all cliff and no hanger, but it ultimately fails because
the characters feel so made up.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ... there's something awfully poignant about the man who
fakes amnesia to try to win back his wife (``Reconstruction'') or
the pyromaniac teenage girl whose cloudy, Xanax vision begins to
lift, thanks to the affection of her stepfather (``Some Say the
World''). If Perabo can get beyond the creative-writing mentality
and into the psychological resonance of the real world, she may end
up in the short-story writer's hall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   For now, we recommend Laurie Colwin and Lorrie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Who I Was Supposed to Be. By Susan Perabo. Simon &AMP; Schuster.
$20. 191 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Hasn't quite found her voice.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock is an arts writer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
