<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2425 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-REVIEW-TIMES03-COX     09-30 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-TIMES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tasty details make `Times' tale a lively read
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a switch: an American royal family of high achievement
and glamour that isn't dogged by decline, scandal or tragedy.
Imagine that!
</P>
<P>
   The Ochs-Sulzberger clan, which founded and still runs The New
York Times, may not make juicy tabloid copy the way the Barrymores
and Kennedys have done, but theirs is a fascinating 100-year saga
of high ideals and power plays on the world stage. And oh yes,
there's enough family warfare and Machiavellian office politics to
keep the narrative lively. Susan E. Tifft and Alex S. Jones tell
the story well.
</P>
<P>
   Too well, perhaps. Gassy at 780 pages, ``The Trust: The Private
and Powerful Family Behind The New York Times'' would make twice
the impact at half the length. It cries out for the ruthless blue
pencil of a Times editor.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``The Trust'' is good, though, it's very good. The first
200 pages have the built-in drama of the Times' unlikely rise from
a faltering daily in the 1890s to a great international organ by
the 1920s. The reason: Adolph Ochs. The ultimate Gotham outsider, a
newly arrived Jew from Chattanooga, where he owned another
struggling Times, Ochs was an inexhaustible entrepreneur. In the
early years the owner-publisher was always one step ahead of the
creditors, one inch from financial disaster, bluffing his way to
new loans with the illusion that everything was under control.
</P>
<P>
   Everything wasn't. Ochs was in constant crisis. Rival publisher
William Randolph Hearst (the model for ``Citizen Kane'') described
the Tennessean in his Journal-American as ``an oily little
commercial gentleman'' _ clear anti-Semitic code. The best revenge
for Ochs was the way he steamed past Hearst and other press lords,
achieving financial success with a journalistic quality and
integrity unmatched on the American scene.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Ochs' and his descendants' well-founded fear of
appearing ``too Jewish'' became paranoia: The Times' article on the
liberation of Dachau never mentioned the word ``Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama droops when the publisher's mantle passes to Arthur
Hays Sulzberger, husband of Adolph's daughter Iphigene. Though more
than the steward of Adolph's vision, the suave, cocktail-swirling
Sulzberger had a comfortable enough tenure that he could spend a
lot of time with chorus girl mistresses. This slack center of the
book dwells on the Ochs-Sulzbergers' wealth and social whirl (``at
each place was a finger bowl, a hand-rolled ball of butter ...''),
as if targeted toward the crowd that devours books on the late
Princess Diana. You don't have to be a socialist to get testy with
the cushy lives of all the Sulzberger cousins and in-laws that we
don't need to hear about.
</P>
<P>
   One of Arthur and Iphigene's pampered kids was Arthur Ochs
Sulzberger, who can never quite shake his childhood nickname of
Punch _ a clue to why he was barely taken seriously until his 50s.
But Punch comes into his own, and the book regains its excitement,
in the late 1960s (page 480). He braves the threat of a government
lawsuit in deciding to publish the secret Vietnam documents known
as the Pentagon Papers. He pressures two of his distinguished
newsroom relatives into early retirement, causing a family uproar
but allowing new blood to rush in. Since the late '70s Punch, and
his brash son Arthur Jr., have in turn boldly remade the Times from
the Great Gray Lady of yore into a more colorful, surprising
chronicle of the age.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget Iphigene, the Times' perennial ``gyroscope'' of
stability, its offstage ombudsman, with her cantankerous letters to
the editor published under a variety of assumed names.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of tasty detail pops up often in Tifft and Jones'
narrative, so you can forgive the breathless accounts of butter
balls. ``The Trust'' is thoroughly researched, entertainingly
written, and pulls no punches on the failings of the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   The Ochs-Sulzbergers: a clan that didn't squander its gifts. Now
there's a man-bites-dog story.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NONFICTION
</P>
<P>
   The Trust: The Private and Powerful Family Behind The New York
Times. By Susan E. Tifft and Alex S. Jones. Little, Brown &AMP; Co.
$29.95. 780 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Pulls no punches.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert, who's taking a year off from theater coverage to
write general features, worked as a New York Times newsroom clerk
in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
