<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NASCAR-SCHRADER-NYTR &LR;      09-30 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-SCHRADER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEN SCHRADER GETS A NEW RIDE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't so long ago when Andy Petree was walking around the
garage with a very upbeat attitude.
</P>
<P>
   He had just gotten a new sponsor, Oakwood Homes, for his Chevy.
He and Ken Schrader, his driver, had agreed to an extension of
Schrader's contract, although nothing was signed. And Sammy Johns
was working out well as crew chief.
</P>
<P>
   All of sudden, though, Petree is scrambling.
</P>
<P>
   First, Schrader shocked him by announcing he was leaving to take
Ernie Irvan's place in Read Morton's Pontiac. That immediately put
the deal with Oakwood Homes in jeopardy because it was Schrader who
brought Oakwood Homes to Petree.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Oakwood Homes is having financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Johns is leaving to go with Schrader.
</P>
<P>
   So suddenly, Petree has no driver, no crew chief and maybe no
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see what happens with Schrader and
Johns. Morton's car has close ties to Hendrick Motorsports, which
supplies Morton's engines. And Hendrick's engines are among the
best in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly, one of the reasons Schrader left Petree was because
he felt Petree's engines were underpowered.
</P>
<P>
   This is a critical move for Schrader. He will be 45 next year,
and this is probably his last chance to resurrect his career.
Schrader's last win came when he drove for Hendrick in 1991. It's
been a downhill slide since then.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his third year with Petree, his best finish with the team
is fourth, and he has not been in the top five in any race this
season.
</P>
<P>
   For Johns, this represents another potential step up. In his
first year as Schrader's crew chief, Johns hit it off with the
veteran driver, which is why Schrader is taking him along.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan's ride is regarded as nearly as good as the one in Robert
Yates' Ford, which was taken by Ricky Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   Morton's team is only in its third year of operation.
</P>
<P>
   If Schrader and Johns can take advantage of the situation, it
will have a major impact on their careers.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2448 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-FOODAID-1001-C     09-30 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-FOODAID-1001-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. FOOD AID PROGRAM FED RUSSIAN CORRUPTION, SENATE TOLD
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just days after Moscow asked for 5 million tons of
new U.S. food aid, a congressional panel was told Thursday that
previous food programs have nourished Russian official corruption
more than the Russian people.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. food program in Russia is ``a major scandal,'' said
Peter Reddaway, a political science professor at George Washington
University and a leading scholar on Russia. He was describing more
than $1 billion in agricultural products sent to Russia during the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pushed by our government because we wanted to help U.S.
farmers,'' he told a Senate Foreign Relations Committee hearing.
``And it was pushed by corrupt elements in the Russian government
who wanted to benefit directly from it themselves'' and then sent
too late to be of help, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the current U.S. program, American farmers
are paid for their products, which are shipped to Russia to be sold
at market value. The proceeds are supposed to go to the Russian
government's pension fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually nothing has gone into the Russian pension fund,''
Reddaway charged, in contradiction to the official U.S. government
position.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks appeared to surprise Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., who
told the hearing that he had helped push through last year's food
aid for Russia after hearing ``bleak'' predictions of empty shelves
and hunger.
</P>
<P>
   But he told Reddaway, ``If you are correct, we should not be
going ahead with such a program.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange came as Moscow this week asked for close to double
the amount of aid it received under an agreement reached last year.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said this week that the
Clinton administration was studying the new request and would make
a decision based in part on ``our experiences with the current
program.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the money that was supposed to be deposited in the
Russian pension fund, the U.S. State Department and Glickman
separately issued the same tersely worded statement that
``Currently, these deposits are being made on the agreed
schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to Reddaway's panning of the program, Agriculture
Department spokesman Andy Solomon said, ``Russia requested the
assistance, so they must believe it to be of some help to their
people.''
</P>
<P>
   American farmers are urging the extra assistance, which would
include at least 1 million tons of wheat. ``That's a good place to
start,'' said Dawn Forsythe, spokeswoman for U.S. Wheat Associates,
the export marketing arm of the wheat industry. ``Their bins are
empty and their harvest was poor.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that her association saw ``no evidence of diversions''
of U.S. wheat shipped during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   However, she acknowledged other problems, including the fact
that the aid, which had been sought to help Russia make it through
the winter, did not begin arriving until March.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0274 </DOCNO>
