<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-CELEBRATE-1001-     09-30 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CELEBRATE-1001-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: updates 2nd-3rd grafs to say that dawn has broken . . .
 &HT;    COMMUNIST CHINA STARTS 50TH BIRTHDAY CELEBRATION WITH SECURITY
LOCKDOWN
 &HT;    (EDs: Contains optional trim.)
 &HT;    With CHINA-CHRONO-1001.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Communist China began saluting 50 years of phenomenal
change Friday with an ironhanded security lockdown.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic in central Beijing was immobilized one minute after
midnight. By dawn, four columns of tanks, mobile artillery guns and
other armored vehicles had lined up in a camouflage-green phalanx
on the Avenue of Perpetual Peace, awaiting the order to start the
first military parade through Tiananmen Square in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chanting soldiers were gathered to step smartly in the company
of 25 groups of weapons, from tanks to radars to the new ``East
Wind 31'' intercontinental ballistic missile. And the air force was
about to unveil its new ``Flying Leopard'' fighter plane in a
screaming flyover of Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Civilian groups and 91 floats from all over China were primed to
round out the parade, evening extravaganza and colossal fireworks
scheduled to keep central Beijing paralyzed for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of police isolated the heart of the capital
before dawn Friday in a form of martial law aimed at guaranteeing
that no disruption _ or any speck of spontaneity _ would sully the
$36 million festivities.
</P>
<P>
   The 500,000 marchers and entertainers were as carefully picked
and placed as the 500,000 potted flowers stuck all over the city in
metal frames, shaped into huge boats, shooting stars or
gaily-colored columns.
</P>
<P>
   To assure none strayed from key nationalistic themes,
participants had a list of 50 approved slogans to shout, such as
the less-than-trenchant: ``Stress theoretical study, political
awareness and good conduct!''
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour parade hailed China's progress, with floats
including replicas of a space rocket launch and a snowy peak in
Tibet, where mountaineers surrounded by rainbows planted China's
red flag with five yellow stars.
</P>
<P>
   The troops, Communist Party cadres, bouncy youth groups and
ethnic minorities in multi-colored costumes would march down the
Avenue of Perpetual Peace, the capital's biggest east-west
boulevard, to be reviewed by President Jiang Zemin near the
entrance to the Forbidden City.
</P>
<P>
   The parade was shaping up as an eccentric combination of the
dour Stalinesque might of Moscow's Cold War processions in Red
Square and the pastel pageantry of Psdadena's New Year's Day Rose
Bowl parades.
</P>
<P>
   Central Beijing started shutting down at noon Thursday, when two
lines of troops carrying bull-horns swept across Tiananmen Square
to evict thousands of strolling Chinese and foreign tourists.
Bomb-sniffing German shepherd dogs followed.
</P>
<P>
   Then offices and shops along the parade route were searched,
locked and sealed by police.
</P>
<P>
   Before the sidewalks closed around the Forbidden City Thursday,
gray-haired Du Zhiying, 70, was having his picture taken before the
ever-present portrait of Chairman Mao Tse-tung.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our motherland has prospered,'' said Du, who was in Tiananmen
Square the day 50 years ago when the late Great Helmsman Mao
declared the People's Republic of China into existence.
</P>
<P>
   Du came from Shanxi Province for the celebration, but the
lifelong party bureaucrat said he was afraid he wouldn't get within
sight of Friday's events. They were open only to officials and
invited guests, and he was neither.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also tried to guarantee control by turning down
pollution, turning out itinerant workers and tuning off beepers and
mobile telephones that might interfere with military
communications.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's pollution is so foul that it obscured the last display
of military air power in 1984 during New China's 35th anniversary,
so factories this year got orders to shut down smoke-belching
furnaces 10 days before the event.
</P>
<P>
   No military parade was held for the 40th anniversary, a bleak
celebration in 1989 that came just months after tanks and soldiers
had made an unscheduled, blood-filled appearance, driving down the
same parade route and into Tiananmen Square to quell weeks of
student-led protests.
</P>
<P>
   Then, no one wanted a reminder of the efficiency of China's
military.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the mood is brighter.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Chinese live enormously better than they did 50, 20 or even 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Life was genuinely grim in 1949 when Mao Tse-tung stood atop the
Gate of Heavenly Peace to announce the meaning of his army's
victory in a vicious civil war. Hearts lifted with his proclamation
of a new era: ``We, the 475 million people of China, have now stood
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then a peasant family may have shared a single pair of
pants among 10 people who took turns going outside. Life expectancy
was 35 years, and education an extravagance for a small elite.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't change quickly. After a modest start into
industrialization, expanded education and agricultural renewal,
Mao's bizarre notions of continuing revolution sent China into one
chaotic frenzy after another.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Leap Forward. The Anti-Rightist Campaign. The Cultural
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the stilted titles lay famine, smeared reputations and
tens of millions of deaths. Mao and his minions nearly wasted a
generation of youth sent not to school but to pound stones or dig
potatoes into the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the relative calm and bloom of prosperity
brought by subsequent leaders _ initiated with the reforms of the
late Deng Xiaoping _ the Chinese people have been forced to do
without free expression and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Economic gains have been remarkable since Deng's reform began in
1978. China has become the world's 11th largest trading power,
churning out a gross domestic product, or GDP, of $96 billion last
year after a decade of average growth rates surpassing 10 percent a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy now is 71 years. Illiteracy is less than 15
percent, mostly among elderly and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet stirrings of protest, targeting both political restrictions
and uneven economic distribution, have the communist leadership on
edge.
</P>
<P>
   To head off public dissent, especially in the anniversary
run-up, authorities have taken drastic steps.
</P>
<P>
   At least 16,000 migrant workers were expelled from Beijing, and
thousands more Chinese without proper papers were dumped in
detention centers. Beggars, peddlers and prostitutes were driven
from streets. Even Chinese tour groups were forbidden to enter the
capital for the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide manhunt called ``operation strike hard'' produced
the arrests since summer of nearly 70,000 people officially
described as ``escaped'' or ``wanted'' criminals. Human rights
groups said democracy activists and religious leaders also have
been detained.
</P>
<P>
   The most sweeping control directive was the July outlawing of
the Falun Gong, a quasi-religious exercise and meditation group
claiming to have 100 million followers. After thousands of
adherents ringed the center of government in a silent protest in
April, authorities made mass arrests and banned public practice of
Falun Gong.
</P>
<P>
   The group's vibrant popularity among all classes and types of
Chinese was attributed to one factor the Communist Party has not
been able to control: the void in values so many Chinese want to
fill.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
