<HEADLINE>
U.N. TO INVESTIGATE RIGHTS ABUSES IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also INDONESIA) 
(th) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Overriding Indonesian objections to an
international investigation into human rights violations in East
Timor, Secretary-General Kofi Annan called Thursday for a report on
abuses in the territory to be conducted by an international panel
of experts.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Human Rights Commission voted on Monday to establish an
outside investigation, in which Asians would be involved. But the
panel rejected Asian requests to let Indonesia's rights commission
do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Annan asked for a report by Dec. 31. It will cover all of 1999,
because violence began soon after President B.J. Habibie of
Indonesia announced in January that he would offer East Timor
autonomy or independence.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Robinson, the high commissioner for human rights who will
organize the investigation, said she would be cooperating with the
Indonesian human rights commission, which has asked her for help in
starting its own inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, she said that the Indonesians
would have more ready access to West Timor and other places where
international investigators could not automatically go.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Robinson said West Timor was a high priority because of
continuing reports of intimidation of East Timorese forced into
camps there. West Timor, which shares an island with East Timor, is
undisputed Indonesian territory.
</P>
<P>
   An American diplomat said Thursday that the United States was
considering sending a high-level envoy to West Timor to try to
determine the extent of dangers to refugees there. Julia Taft, the
assistant secretary of state for refugees, visited West Timor last
week and sent back a report that American officials called
``chilling.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Robinson said she was concerned about many reports of
abuses against women in West Timor that reached her when she
visited Darwin, Australia, recently to talk with refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard very alarming allegations that even in the boats
taking them that women were raped constantly, frequently, and that
in three camps this continued to be a pattern of rape and sexual
assault,'' she said. She added that she was given similar accounts
in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Robinson said she was confident that cases against rights
violators could be built relatively quickly in the case of East
Timor, where pro-Indonesian militias backed by the military were on
a rampage for more than a week after the voting results showed that
the people of the territory had chosen independence by a wide
margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a very large number of witnesses of violations, and
they know who the perpetrators were,'' Mrs. Robinson said. ``They
know the names.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
