<HEADLINE>
COHEN ADMONISHES INDONESIA FOR `ABETTING' VIOLENCE IN EAST TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also INDONESIA-U.N.-RIGHTS) 
(th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Defense Secretary William Cohen met with
Indonesia's president and its top general Thursday and admonished
the military for ``aiding and abetting'' a terror campaign by
militias in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with President B.J. Habibie and the armed forces
chief, Gen. Wiranto, Cohen issued a written statement that called
on Indonesia's military to punish those responsible for the
violence and to disarm militias that have taken refuge in West
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Bangkok, Cohen said he believed that
Indonesia's leaders were committed to the success of the
Australian-led U.N. peacekeeping effort in the province.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Australian Embassy here, hundreds of protesters
massed, burning debris and an Australian flag, throwing stones and
home-made gasoline bombs. Other protests erupted elsewhere in the
capital and around the country, including the provinces of Aceh and
Irian Jaya, both home to their own independence movements.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of a new security law last week by the outgoing
legislature giving the military new powers to quell unrest has
sparked violent student protests. ``The situation in East Timor has
weakened Habibie in a way that has strengthened the military,''
said Bruce Gale, regional manager of the Political and Economic
Risk Consultancy.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, foreign intervention in East Timor has
unleashed a torrent anti-Western sentiment that has unnerved some
foreign executives, jeopardizing trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   Wiranto denied rumors Thursday that the military might respond
to growing civil unrest by taking political control. Nonetheless,
he has been cast as a political kingmaker.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Wiranto summoned the leaders of the country's six
major parties to discuss how the new legislature would be run.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't put tanks in the street, but behind the scenes they
are sending a clear message that they want to control the
situation,'' a European banker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
