<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MYSTERY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-TO-FAMILIAR THEMES LEAVE `ALASKA' BEREFT OF MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have sledded through ``Cool Runnings,'' skated past sequels
to ``The Mighty Ducks'' and now we're being snowballed by another
winter sports movie, ``Mystery, Alaska.''
</P>
<P>
   Has anyone noticed all these films come from the same
distributor and they all tell the same feel-good,
triumph-over-adversity story?
</P>
<P>
   Disney seems intent upon overdosing audiences with the little
guy proving himself against a seemingly superior force _ in this
case the New York Rangers hockey team. But no matter how warmly you
dress ``Mystery, Alaska'' with a top-notch cast that includes
Russell Crowe (``L.A. Confidential''), Hank Azaria and Burt
Reynolds, the film never achieves anything new or more enlightening
than Disney's earlier efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Team Mystery members play an ice hockey match every Saturday
morning. They're more devoted to the sport than they are to church
or their families. Hockey is the passion of the town of Mystery and
each of its 633 residents joins in to root for the oddball team
which includes solid Sheriff John Biebe (Crowe), sweet playboy
Skank Marden (Ron Eldard) and speed-skating teen-wonder Stevie
Weeks (Ryan Northcott).
</P>
<P>
   But when Charles Danner (Hank Azaria) returns home for one of
his infrequent visits, Team Mystery is about to become big news.
Danner left years before, chafing from small-town life, to pursue a
career as a journalist in the big city. He recently has written an
article for Sports Illustrated about the team and he's also the
ex-boyfriend of Biebe's wife, Donna (Mary McCormack).
</P>
<P>
   Danner devises a plan to pit Team Mystery against the
professional New York Rangers. Soon nerves will fray,
</P>
<P>
   relationships frazzle, dark secrets emerge and Mystery's
residents will wake up and find out what they're really made of.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jay Roach (the two ``Austin Powers'' movies) meanders
through rambling, heart-tugging, try-too-hard material that holds
few surprises. To his credit, he makes Mystery a place of somber,
icy beauty that is, unfortunately, thawed by the predictable
actions of its inhabitants. Try as he may, he can't transcend the
fact that ``Mystery, Alaska'' never sheds a TV-movie sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   That makes sense when you look at the writing credits and notice
that Emmy-winning boy wonder, David E. Kelley _ who has created
everything from ``Ally McBeal'' to ``Chicago Hope,'' ``Picket
Fences'' and ``The Practice'' on the small screen _ co-wrote the
film with Sean O'Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mystery, Alaska'' resembles Kelley's award-winning series with
its strong women, frenetic pacing, eccentricities and survival of
the underdog under adverse conditions. Kelley knows what audiences
emotionally respond to, but by stretching his trademark themes past
the running time of a TV program, he produces too little, too late
and for too long.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery, Alaska. Directed by Jay Roach. Written by David E.
Kelley, Sean O'Byrne. Cast: Russell Crowe, Hank Azaria, Mary
McCormack, Burt Reynolds, Ron Eldard. Hollywood Pictures. 118
minutes. Rated R for language, nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
