<HEADLINE>
IT'S HARD TO LIVE WITHOUT TELEVISION
</HEADLINE>
  (For release October 7)  
(rk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our family intended to go TV-free this summer.
</P>
<P>
   All summer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of watching reruns, I decided, we'd visit the
neighborhood pool, play whiffle ball in the back yard, go on
minivacations and camping trips, and visit friends.
</P>
<P>
   We started off with a bang, by sending the 21-inch Magnavox in
our living room home with my newly retired father-in-law. When the
kids hit the couch after school, staring at the spot where the TV
used to be, I saw how entrenched our viewing habits had become.
</P>
<P>
   The next to go was the RCA in the basement rec room, which we
were going to simply unplug for three months.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, however, presented a new excuse for leaving the tube
tethered just a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   First, my 8-year-old had his tonsils out and had to stay inside
and quiet for several days. ``I understand and applaud your
intentions,'' said his doctor. ``But now would really not be the
time to take away TV.'' And then, catching himself, he added:
``Heaven forbid he should actually have to read books for the whole
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, forcing a TV-free zone on a hurting kid was more than I
could justify, so we positioned our son on the basement couch with
pillows, Popsicles and the remote.
</P>
<P>
   After Adam healed, a family of eight came to visit. Great, I
thought _ backyard kickball games, cookouts, tours of local parks.
Then it rained the whole weekend. The crew camped out in the
basement, eating pizza, playing Nerf tag and watching every video
on the shelf, from the ``Star Wars'' trilogy to ``Toy Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the summer, excuse followed excuse: my parents came
to visit (my dad's a news junkie; my mom loves to follow her team
sports) national events broke, a special work project HAD to get
done on a Saturday, the kids were having meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   At times, allowing an hour of ``Winnie-the-Pooh'' or
``Wishbone'' was, I believe, what saved my delicate sanity.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not opposed to TV per se _ I enjoy vegging out in front of
``Ally McBeal'' or ``Profiler'' after the kids are in bed. My
husband will watch if I have the set on but is indifferent to most
TV viewing, preferring to build a bookshelf or get that elusive
eight hours of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   And the kids were getting just a little too comfortable with
marathon cartoon sessions when mom and dad weren't paying strict
attention. A half-hour would slip into an hour and a half of
``Scooby Doo'' without even trying.
</P>
<P>
   At best, we probably managed just a few weeks without any TV at
all.
</P>
<P>
   During one of those, Adam and Sarah were playing on the plastic
gym in the yard, staring through a square-shaped hole in the side.
``Hey, this is just like watching TV,'' Adam said, captivated by
the framed view of sky, pine tree and squirrels.
</P>
<P>
   Now that fall is here, school has resumed, and schedules are
back to normal, the kids get their regular half-hour on school
nights/hour on weekends of screen time (computer or TV.)
</P>
<P>
   But we're still down to being a one-TV household. And aiming to
stay that way.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
