<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ELMO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ELMO IN GROUCHLAND' RETURNS TO THE MUPPETS' WINNING WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For parents who have been holding their breath in anticipation
of a film geared specifically to toddlers and younger kids, it's
time to exhale. ``The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland'' will
entertain youngsters and reassure parents worried about scary or
inappropriate content.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this episode of Muppet mayhem veers away from the
glitzy format that made ``Muppets From Space'' so mediocre and
derivative of adult movies. Instead it remains faithful to the
essence of ``Sesame Street.''
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma in the film is simple: Elmo learns about sharing
after his beloved, fuzzy, blue blanket falls into Oscar's trash can
house. In his anxiousness to get it back, he mistakenly opens a
Pandora's Box of a door that transports him into Grouchland, a
place where it's against the law to ask for help, the daily paper
is
</P>
<P>
   The New York Slimes, residents get their hair done at the ``ugly
parlor'' and movie idol Sharon Groan is starring in ``Basically It
Stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Elmo, followed by some loyal Muppet (and human) friends, must
leave Sesame Street and make a quest to get his best blue friend
back from the greedy, selfish cad Huxley (Mandy Patinkin), a bad
guy with eyebrows that ``need a weed-whacking'' who rules over
Grouchland by taking everything from its inhabitants and then
hoarding it in his castle.
</P>
<P>
   On his journey, Elmo meets the Queen of Trash (Vanessa Williams)
and must face a ritual in self-esteem. Ultimately, he both teaches
and learns some other lessons in friendship and selfishness and how
the two just don't mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland'' also invites kids to
help Elmo on his Oz-like journey. There is an interactive,
shout-it-out ease to the film that is playful and pulls from the
same education-based format as the TV show.
</P>
<P>
   While adults may feel out of their league, there are a few jokes
that will appeal to them. And if the kids and toddlers who attended
a screening of the film last week are any indication, Elmo and his
pals just might have made a successful transition from ``Sesame
Street'' in this elemental adventure about manners.
</P>
<P>
   The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland. Directed by Gary
Halvorson. Written by Mitchell Kriegman, Joseph Mazzarino. Cast:
Mandy Patinkin, Vanessa Williams. Columbia Pictures. 77 minutes.
Rated G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2467 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-VIRTUAL-SURGERY-TEX     09-30 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-SURGERY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV AND BLACK-EYED PEAS TEACH NEOPHYTE SURGEONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If you want to be a surgeon, pickin' black-eyed peas
may be a good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   Pickin' 'em up and puttin' 'em in your ``pocket'' _ a small
container with a hole in the top _ is not as easy as it sounds.
Especially when you are picking them up with a blunt-nosed pincers
with a 24-inch handle under a foam table while watching what you
are doing only indirectly, on a TV monitor.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds confusing, but practicing laparoscopic surgical
technique is much safer this way. If a pea gets smashed or goes
squirting out of the grasper's clutch, you can always grab another.
That's not so with a slippery, diseased gallbladder.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the ``slam dunk,'' the drill is designed to help train
the surgeon to use the nondominant hand and develop better hand and
eye coordination.
</P>
<P>
   I'm at the State Fair of Texas in Dallas, testing a
virtual-reality surgical simulator that is part of HealthExpo, the
exhibit that fills the Hall of State. My surgical assistant is Nick
Gabriel, a general surgeon and postdoctoral fellow with the Yale
University School of Medicine's Endoscopic and Laparoscopic Center.
</P>
<P>
   He and his boss, Dr. James ``Butch'' Rosser Jr., also at Yale
(and who joins us from there on a monitor via cyberspace), say the
virtual reality simulator can dramatically change the way surgeons
are trained. The two conduct two-day laparacopic ``boot camps,'' in
which they have trained more than 500 surgical residents. They say
they can train anybody to do minimally invasive laparoscopic
surgery in two days. (Anyone who has a dominant hand, maybe, I
think.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to deliver the highest quality care to
everyone on the planet, no matter where they are,'' Gabriel says.
</P>
<P>
   Rosser developed the training kit for the simulator and many of
the instruments as well as the book, CD-ROM and video that go with
it and uses them to ``telementor'' surgeons in small hospitals in
remote areas all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make the equipment,'' Rosser explains. ``I work with
manufacturers to integrate the equipment and the technology to work
in ways they didn't plan. We can now teach people to use the
equipment and guide them while they do their first few surgeries _
from thousands of miles away. I can go everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   And he virtually does. For example, from the familiar
surroundings of his own surgical suite in New Haven, Conn., Rosser
recently directed a surgeon in Hawaii through his first complicated
laparoscopic procedure to cure a patient of chronic heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   But do these people from Yale think they can really teach
``anyone'' to do laparoscopic surgery in two days? Drills to help
master ``the terrible triangle'' convinced me that I have no
dominant hand. All these years I've thought I was right-handed, but
I'm really no better at maneuvering surgical instruments that I
can't see with my right hand than I am with my left.
</P>
<P>
   The terrible triangle is that formed by three trocars (sharp
hollow tubes) stuck through three tiny incisions that give access
to the inside of the abdomen without cutting open the patient. The
portals are for two long-handled graspers that can hold scissors,
scalpel, needle or other surgical necessities, and the tiny camera
that shows you what you are doing _ if it's at the proper depth and
angle.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel holds the camera steady and talks me through a more
difficult exercise, known as the ``Cobra Rope Drill,'' where one
examines the loops of the small bowel by running a coiled rope from
end to end, handing it off from one grasper to the next, every four
inches or so.
</P>
<P>
   I lost the bowel twice and had to start over.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I just need to work on picking some more of those peas.
</P>
<P>
   FYI &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the State Fair of Texas in Dallas can practice
laparoscopic surgery at the HealthExpo in the Hall of State, 10
a.m. to 10 p.m. daily through Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   These visitors can also enter a ``Jedi Knight'' contest, testing
their dexterity at laparoscopic skills. The winner will be invited
to participate in a skills shootout at the American College of
Surgeons meeting in San Francisco on Oct. 11-14.
</P>
<P>
   Planners say about 250,000 of the State Fair's total 3.4 million
visitors are expected to participate in HealthExpo, which also
includes 35 computer terminals where visitors can log on to all the
best health Web sites and a celebrity kitchen where they can learn
gourmet-style healthful cooking.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
