<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PLUNKETT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLASHY `PLUNKETT' HAS TOO MUCH MTV, TOO LITTLE SUBSTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's not an original idea rattling around in the empty-headed
but gorgeous-to-behold period film, ``Plunkett &AMP; Macleane.''
</P>
<P>
   Its story is a borrowed mish-mash of plot points from ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' ``Tom Jones,'' ``Robin Hood'' and
even ``The Duellists,'' which was directed by Ridley Scott.
</P>
<P>
   And that's an important note because ``Plunkett &AMP; Macleane'' is
the debut film from Jake Scott, son of Ridley (``Bladerunner,''
``Thelma and Louise'') and nephew of Tony (``The Hunger,'' ``Top
Gun''). A young Jake even had a small role in ``The Duellists,''
his dad's 1978 classic about honor set during the Napoleonic Wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plunkett &AMP; Macleane'' is as achingly atmospheric as Ridley and
Tony Scott's movies but Jake hasn't yet learned to overcome his MTV
and television commercials background and mentality. The film will
most likely please those with a short attention span because it's
illogically plotted, jam-packed with a bizarre, out-of-place rock
music soundtrack and contains lots of holes and silliness. But its
glittery, lavish sets and costumes almost convince us we're viewing
a guilty pleasure in the making.
</P>
<P>
   It also wastes a talented cast. Jonny Lee Miller and Robert
Carlyle, who starred together in ``Trainspotting,'' at least have
screen time, but actress Liv Tyler and especially Alan Cumming, the
scene-stealing, lascivious actor who won a Tony for his portrayal
of the emcee in the Broadway production of ``Cabaret,'' are given
little to do but pose and pout.
</P>
<P>
   In this ``buddy movie'' based on real-life characters, the
low-class Plunkett (Carlyle) and Captain James Macleane (Miller), a
gentleman who lives for pleasure, meet in debtors prison. The pair
buy their way to freedom after they cut a ruby out of a corpse.
They begin a new life in 1748 London with Plunkett planning their
criminal undertakings while Macleane handles the carnal pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   That changes after Macleane spies the niece of the Lord Chief
Justice Gibson (Michael Gambon), the spirited Lady Rebecca (Tyler).
Macleane falls in love and Lady Rebecca struggles to thwart the
advances of the odious and nefarious Thief Taker General Chance
(Ken Stott), her uncle's ambitious second-in-command. She, too, is
smitten.
</P>
<P>
   Before long Plunkett and Macleane have become infamous as
highwaymen, robbing coaches crammed full of drippingly decadent
nobles that pass along the road at night. Chance desperately wants
to bring down the thieves in order to advance his career. But the
duo have already become folk heroes to the poor, who applaud their
every move.
</P>
<P>
   If this story line sounds familiar, it's because it has been a
staple in films for decades. ``Plunkett &AMP; Macleane'' almost
convinces us it's a little different because of its breathtaking
production design and costuming. But don't be fooled. Beneath its
extraordinary exterior coat of paint is a less-than-ordinary film.
Jake Scott has clearly inherited the family's artistic eye but
he'll need to brush up on his continuity and story skills if he's
to surpass his dad's already legendary status.
</P>
<P>
   Plunkett &AMP; Macleane. Directed by Jake Scott. Written by Robert
Wade, Neal Purvis, Charles McKeown. Cast: Jonny Lee Miller, Robert
Carlyle, Liv Tyler, Alan Cumming. USA Films. 102 minutes. Rated R
for violence, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
