<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMP REMOVES NEWSPAPER COLUMNIST FROM BOOK PROJECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By WENDY BENJAMINSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush
has removed a newspaper columnist as the ghostwriter of his
autobiography in a dispute over how many policy details the book
should contain.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign Communications Director Karen Hughes will complete
the book and her name will appear as the ghostwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Herskowitz, a Houston Chronicle sports columnist, said
his initial deal with the Texas governor was that the book would be
``30 percent biography, 70 percent issues and (campaign)
platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes disagreed, saying that it was to be a ``broad-strokes
book on the governor's themes and philosophies and how he arrived
at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Herskowitz said, however, that when he finished the biographical
portion of the book last summer, working under a July deadline, he
sought detailed policy positions from the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In response, he said, the Bush campaign delivered to his house a
carton containing 1,000 speeches from which, he believed, he was to
glean Bush's stands on issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually five speeches the governor has given 200
times,'' Herskowitz said. ``There was no way I could write 70
percent of a book off that material.''
</P>
<P>
   Herskowitz said the candidate's staff told him that Bush's
positions on issues were ``still evolving.'' He added that Hughes
did not want the book to contain specific positions on certain
issues, ``nothing that could be criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting among Hughes, Herskowitz and Bush, they decided
that Hughes would complete the policy portion of the book and take
the ghostwriting credit. Herskowitz, Hughes said, would receive an
acknowledgment for ``getting the project started.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said she and Bush never wanted the book to be the
``typical guide to the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The book was supposed to be biographical and philosophical,
giving insight into the themes he is using in the campaign and how
he arrived at them,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   After reading Herskowitz's initial chapters, Hughes said, ``We
decided to get a book done that was insightful about the
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire Wachtel, an executive editor at William Morrow &AMP; Co.
Inc., which is publishing the book, said she was not satisfied with
Herskowitz's contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't seen the manuscript,'' she said. ``None of his
material is in the book. We got some chapters from him we found
unacceptable. We went to the Bush campaign and now we have a book
we're very happy with.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
