<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-QUAKE-1001-COX     09-30 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-QUAKE-1001-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO QUAKE KILLS AT LEAST 10, SHATTERS STRUCTURES AND NERVES
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A powerful 7.5 earthquake rumbled through southern
Mexico Thursday morning, shattering hundreds of buildings and
reportedly killing at least 10 people.
</P>
<P>
   The quake struck at 11:30 a.m. (CDT) (12:30 p.m. EDT) and was
centered about 280 miles southeast of Mexico City along the
sparsely populated Pacific coast of Oaxaca state. The epicenter was
offshore and in between the tourist resorts of Huatulco and Puerto
Escondido.
</P>
<P>
   One person was killed in Puerto Escondido and some hotels and
other buildings were damaged in the city of 18,000. In the state
capital of Oaxaca, two people were killed when they tried to take
refuge in a doorway and it collapsed on them, according to Oaxaca
Gov. Jose Murat. Two others died in Oaxaca after falling debris
struck them as they tried to flee into the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Four people were killed when buildings collapsed in rural
villages in Oaxaca state and one Mexican news service reported that
a 12-year-old girl suffered a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's quake, which hit in a series of rumbles lasting
several minutes, also jolted Mexico City, Veracruz, Michoacan and
Tabasco states. The quake was slightly stronger than the 7.4
temblor that killed more than 15,000 people in Turkey on Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, terrified residents poured into the streets,
some fainting or sobbing out of fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scared the hell out of me. I was so afraid because I live
on the fourth floor of a five-story building. It was horrible to
see everything moving, and hear my neighbors screaming and
running,'' said Laura Urzua, an 18-year-old student in this city.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred houses in Oaxaca state and about 100 businesses _
many of them in Oaxaca city's historic colonial center _ were
reportedly damaged and 20 people were hospitalized, according to
Murat's office.
</P>
<P>
   People said they were especially terrified because of the recent
earthquakes in Turkey and Taiwan, and the memory of Mexico City's
1985 temblor of 8.1 on the Richter scale. That quake killed more
than 10,000 people and destroyed many buildings in Mexico's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so strange that one quake after another has struck
recently,'' said Gabriela Duran, a 23-year-old Mexico City hardware
store employee.
</P>
<P>
   Unconfirmed news reports here said that in addition to at least
10 fatalities in Oaxaca, a woman in Veracruz state died after she
fell and hit her head trying to flee the quake.
</P>
<P>
   A man in Mexico City, some reports said, may have also died of a
heart attack suffered after the quake.
</P>
<P>
   News reports also claimed that most of Oaxaca state's water and
sewage treatment plants were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very worried about Oaxaca,'' Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo said in a televised interview Thursday. Mexican military
helicopters were surveying the state, which includes some very
isolated communities.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City office workers who streamed into streets remained
there long after the shaking subsided, hugging and crying. Some had
to be carried out of buildings because they had fainted or were
dizzy.
</P>
<P>
   At Mexico City's police headquarters _ a building that had been
shored up after the 1985 quake _ six people fainted, according to
television reports.
</P>
<P>
   On one street here, the brick facade of a large building slid
off during the quake, tumbling onto about a dozen cars parked next
to the structure.
</P>
<P>
   On June 15, Mexicans were jarred by a 6.7 quake that struck 165
miles southwest of Mexico City, killing at least 17 people and
injuring nearly 200. More than 7,700 homes and buildings were
damaged, many in the colonial city of Puebla east of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
