<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2503 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-GUERRILLAS-ART-     09-30 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-GUERRILLAS-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMOR'S GUERRILLA FIGHTERS VISIT THE CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor _ There was a new presence in the streets of
Dili On Thursday: hard, no-nonsense men with berets, flowing hair
and tiny two-way radios, the victors in a 24-year war of
independence for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting from their mountain strongholds for a first-hand look
at the capital, they were the first elements of the
pro-independence guerrilla army known as Falintil to make a public
showing here.
</P>
<P>
   In a convoy of two tiny, crowded vans, a truck and a half-dozen
motorcycles, the 30 fighters slowly toured the burned-out city,
looking but saying little.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoy!'' they shouted when they spotted friends on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, hey!'' their friends shouted back.
</P>
<P>
   As they passed the Santa Cruz Cemetery, the scene of a massacre
by the military in 1991 that severely discredited the Indonesian
presence here, an onlooker raised his fist in a salute and did a
small jig.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas stopped twice to meet with officers from the
international peacekeeping force whose presence here for the last
11 days has made the fighters' emergence from the mountains
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just having a bit of a yak,'' said an Australian soldier,
refusing to describe what happened in one meeting at the back of a
small house in Becora, a strongly pro-independence neighborhood
that had often been attacked and burned before the peacekeepers
arrived. It was here that Sander Thoenes, a Dutch journalist, was
killed last week by withdrawing Indonesian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, as the guerrillas and the soldiers sat under the trees
in white plastic chairs to talk, a thin stream of residents walked
by them, returning home from the hills. They had fled there when
the violence began after the announcement that East Timor had voted
overwhelmingly for independence from Indonesia in an Aug. 30
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   At the small house, the guerrillas handed over a cache of
weapons and ammunition they said they had captured from militia
groups armed and supported by the Indonesian military.
</P>
<P>
   But the leader of Thursday's expedition, Cornelio Gama, 54, the
deputy commander of Third Regional Command, said the members of
Falintil _ who were unarmed on their visit to the city Thursday _
would not lay down their own weapons, in defiance of a demand for
disarmament by the international peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the national liberation army of East Timor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gama, a small man with a nimbus of frizzy hair around his thin,
lined face and a clutch of Roman Catholic medallions around his
neck, has dedicated most of his life to the war for independence.
</P>
<P>
   A former soldier in the army of Portugal, the colonial power
here until 1974, he said he became a resistance fighter on the day
the Indonesian troops invaded in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   He has lived as a fighter in the mountains ever since, he said.
This was his first visit to Dili.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fought for 24 years without any international
support,'' Gama said. ``Now Falintil trusts the multinational
force. We respect that they are now the ruling power.''
</P>
<P>
   Just outside Becora, the tiny convoy stopped in the shade. Gama
waved his hand, and a lieutenant pulled a can of warm Bali Hai beer
from inside his shirt _ an almost impossibly rare commodity in this
devastated city.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting inside one of the vans, three young guerrillas _
including a teen-aged girl _ played a tape of a popular song in the
local language, Tetun.
</P>
<P>
   Beer in hand, Gama spoke in a loud voice over the sound of the
music. ``If you capture any militias, hand them over to Interfet,''
he said, using the acronym for the international peacekeeping
force. ``Do not beat them. Respect the international forces.''
</P>
<P>
   A young guerrilla with a purple beret and bright green shirt
said this was not his first visit to Dili since the militias'
campaign of terror began this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``When everything was burning, there were 15 of us in the city,
operating independently,'' he said. ``We had information that they
were going to carry out their campaign, so we came to observe.''
</P>
<P>
   But the guerrilla, who refused to give his name, said he and his
comrades had orders not to take any action, part of a Falintil
policy to operate within the law and maintain the moral high
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Was it difficult, as a guerrilla fighter, to look on passively
as his city burned and his people were terrorized and killed?
</P>
<P>
   The young man's lips began to tremble, and he turned his head
away slightly. ``It was terrible,'' he said. ``It made my heart
sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The convoy stopped at a seminary where international aid groups
have just begun providing medical care and other assistance.
</P>
<P>
   With Gama still sitting inside his tiny van with a microphone,
obscured by an assistant who sat on the hood with the tape recorder
as an amplifier,'' his disembodied voice addressed the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more vengeance,'' he said. ``We must work for national
unity. We must end our hatreds. We must unite in our thoughts and
deeds to rebuild the country.''
</P>
<P>
   A small patter of applause greeted his speech. The people here
seemed uncertain who had just addressed them or why.
</P>
<P>
   Then three military liaison officers from the United Nations
appeared, from Uruguay, Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have information,'' the Uruguayan officer said to
Gama. ``We need to have a clearer picture of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   An aide handed Gama a red plastic lighter, and he lit a sweet
clove cigarette. ``Yes, we can share information with you,'' he
said. The two men agreed on a later meeting.
</P>
<P>
   With the militia fading away and the Indonesian army gone except
for a token presence, power has shifted in Dili. But the city lies
in ruins, most of its houses burned and none of its shops reopened.
</P>
<P>
   The central marketplace has been burned to the ground. As the
Falintil convoy passed, a few people with brooms were starting to
sweep away the ashes.
</P>
<P>
   As the convoy moved down the pretty sea front, with its fresh
salt breeze, it passed graffiti marking the changing times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eat Hot Lead,'' read an angry message to the Timorese, sprayed
in black paint by the departing Indonesian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Under it was a new rejoinder: ``The most important thing is
freedom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
