r a BC-FLOOD-PETS-COX     09-30 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-PETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volunteers and vets work to save animals of N.C. flood
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ So weak it requires feeding by intravenous
needle, the beagle in cage No. 55 is one of the lucky ones.
</P>
<P>
   It survived Hurricane Floyd's devastating flooding and managed
to get rescued from the contaminated waters of eastern North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Now, along with another140 cats and dogs, the skinny beagle is
on the mend at an emergency field hospital for the feline and
canine victims of North Carolina's worst natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   While millions of dollars of aid for flood-ravaged people have
poured in from across America, a band of North Carolina State
University veterinarians and volunteers are doling out care on a
far more modest scale.
</P>
<P>
   They hope in coming months to reunite the misplaced pets with
their owners, presumably some who lost their homes and possessions
to floods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can return healthy pets to people who lost everything,
it will be a bright spot for them,'' said Dr. Kelli Ferris, an N.C.
State veterinarian who is in charge of the yapping, barking,
doggy-smelling hospital on Raleigh's outskirts.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening last week in the midst of the flooding, the
emergency hospital has treated more than 550 cats and dogs. They're
a mix of yard dogs without collars, valuable hunting dogs and house
cats accustomed to pampering.
</P>
<P>
   None has died, but many are sick from swimming in the swirling
black cesspool spawned by Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   A brew of livestock and human waste, petroleum and chemicals,
the toxic mess threatens public health and the environment across
wide stretches of eastern North Carolina farmland and all the way
to its beaches. State health officials warn that people who venture
into the surf should avoid getting water in their eyes, mouths or
cuts because of pollution from coastal rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The beagle in Cage No. 55, for one, has a severe case of the
mange, a skin disease that vets believe has been aggravated by
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   As listless as a brown-and-white rag, the dog is certainly one
of the saddest-looking patients in the Raleigh hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have named it Hope,''' Knightdale, N.C., veterinarian Phil
DeBrito said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hope was among 30 dogs that arrived Wedneday night from Tarboro,
one of the most flood-ravaged areas. Officials declared the animals
to be ``hazardous material'' because of pollution, DeBrito said.
</P>
<P>
   Before examining the dogs, vets put on full-body, zip-up suits,
sterile operating gowns, gloves and face shields. They also cut arm
and neck holes in thick-plastic cadaver bags and wear them as an
added precaution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know what they could be carrying out of those
areas,'' DeBrito said.
</P>
<P>
   After they were bathed, the dogs were put in cages in the
hospital. It's a 'round-the-clock swirl of activity as vets examine
the animals and keep track of their recovery on clipboards.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers take dogs for walks, feed them, clean their cages and
tote supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency hospital is a half mile from the N.C. State vet
school's teaching hospital, a precaution to minimize the chance of
disease being spread between the two facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-drawn yellow signs point down a muddy dirt road to the
makeshift hospital and an open shed where some of the animals are
being kept in cages.
</P>
<P>
   In a cracked parking lot, donations of dog and cat food are
piling up, alongside tables brimming with flea and tick powder,
medicine and rawhide chewies.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, a red Chevy pickup truck arrived loaded with
Ol' Roy dog food, Special Kitty cat food and several bags of cedar
shavings.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers rushed over to unload the truck. ``I just want to
help take care of these animals,'' said Raleigh cat owner Martha
Joyce, volunteering with her husband, Samuel.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina State's College of Veterinary Medicine opened the
hospital, after rescuers with the Humane Society of the United
States and other groups began snatching animals from flood waters.
The number rescued now tops 1,000, in some cases overrunning
eastern North Carolina shelters.
</P>
<P>
   So far, none of the animals at the Raleigh hospital has been
retrieved by their owners. However, officials say they know the
identities of about 40 owners whom they plan to contact.
</P>
<P>
   Humane Society volunteers are taking digital photographs of the
animals admitted to the hospital. The images are being posted on
the Humane Society of the United States Web site provided through
the Petshelter Network.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the vet school also plan to put the animals'
pictures in scrapbooks for owners who don't have Internet access.
If the animals aren't claimed within 30 days, volunteers will keep
them in their homes for a year in hopes of placing them in
permanent homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is one of our top priorities to reunite owners with their
pets,'' said Dr. Sally Vivrette, an N.C. State vet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
