A2507 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-PRISON-VIDEO-HNS &LR;      09-30 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-VIDEO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI CONVICT TESTIFIES IN TEXAS JAIL ATTACK CAUGHT ON
VIDEOTAPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ A Missouri murder convict testified Thursday
he did nothing to deserve being kicked and hit by officers and
bitten by a dog during a 1996 shakedown at the Brazoria County
Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just laying there,'' inmate Toby Hawthorne told jurors
hearing evidence in the case of two Brazoria County sheriff's
deputies and a private prison employee accused of using excessive
force on him during the videotaped jail search. ``I wasn't doing
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne referred to a sequence in the videotape in which he
lay on a cell floor as a dog handled by former Brazoria County
deputy David Cisneros twice bit him on the calf.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Cisneros, 39, of Angleton, Texas, former jailer
Robert Percival, 37, and former private prison employee Wilton
David Wallace, 52, of Angleton, are on trial in U.S. District Judge
Kenneth Hoyt's court on charges of violating Hawthorne's civil
rights. Each faces up to 10 years in prison and a $250,000 fine if
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace worked for Capital Correctional Resources Inc., which
housed 415 Missouri convicts in a portion of the Brazoria County
Jail the firm leased. The shakedown occurred Sept. 18, 1996, the
second day after the inmates arrived at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth man, former sheriff's Lt. Lester Eugene Arnold, 50, of
Vanderpool, pleaded guilty Tuesday to a misdemeanor count of
violating Hawthorne's rights by shocking him with a stun gun.
Arnold, originally indicted on three felony civil rights charges,
has agreed to testify against his former co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne spent more than three hours on the witness stand
Thursday, answering simply ``Yes'' or ``No'' to most of the dozens
of question prosecutors and defense attorneys asked as they
reviewed portions of the jail search video for 14 jurors, including
two alternates.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys suggested during cross-examination that
Hawthorne refused to follow officers' orders and was bitten by
Cisneros's dog because he thrashed around on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne, however, denied doing anything to provoke jailers or
members of a six-man emergency response team the sheriff's
department sent to the jail to control prisoners during a search
for weapons and other contraband.
</P>
<P>
   Response team commander Lt. Robert Christopher testified
Wednesday that Hawthorne and other prisoners complied with orders
during the shakedown. On Thursday, he testified that a response
team member grabbed Hawthorne's arm when Hawthorne failed to get on
his cell floor quickly.
</P>
<P>
   During the videotape review, Hawthorne pointed out that a table
and the location of Cisneros's dog prevented him from quickly lying
flat on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, Percival and Wallace are expected to take the stand in
coming days and tell jurors their own versions of what happened in
the shakedown, portions of which were shown worldwide on television
after the videotape surfaced nearly a year after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Their attorneys have told jurors that Percival and Wallace deny
hitting or kicking Hawthorne. Through his attorney, Cisneros has
maintained he never ordered his dog to bite Hawthorne and pulled
the animal back after bites occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne testified, however, that Wallace kicked him in the
head during the shakedown. Prosecutors maintain the videotape shows
Percival struck Hawthorne without reason and Cisneros caused his
dog to bite the inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros attorney Donald ``Tex'' Tonroy downplayed the severity
of three tooth marks evident in a Polaroid photograph taken of
Hawthorne's calf after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   But former jail nurse Sharon Sewell testified Thursday that the
bite marks were ``very deep'' and required periodic treatments and
dressings until Oct. 10, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne was brought to Galveston from a Missouri prison for
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne and the other Missouri inmates were at a prison in
Crystal City, Texas _ not Crystal City, Mo., as earlier reported _
immediately before arriving in Brazoria County.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne, 22, pleaded guilty in 1995 to second-degree murder
and armed criminal action, or use of a gun in a crime. A St. Louis
judge sentenced him to concurrent 20-year terms on each charge.
</P>
<P>
   An East St. Louis, Ill., resident until he was arrested for
murder on Oct. 8, 1994, Hawthorne is now being held at the Missouri
Eastern Correctional Center in Pacific, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Hawthorne's murder case were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
