<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2513 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-POLITICS-MONEY-COX     09-30 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-MONEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley edges Gore in campaign dollars
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley, who may be
moving toward a major upset or merely enjoying his 15 minutes of
political fame, now has more campaign cash in the bank than Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Reports to be filed later this mnth will show that Bradley
collected $6.7 million in the quarter that ended Thursday, compared
to Gore's $6.5 million, according to the campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to massive spending by Gore, who has raised about $26
million overall, the upcoming reports will show that Bradley's
estimated $10 million in the bank could be several hundred thousand
dollars more than Gore has. Bradley has raised $18.4 million since
beginning his long-shot attempt to defeat Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Official finance reports for the period are not due until Oct.
15. The money amassed by Gore and Bradley will multiply when
federal matching funds are made available. The same will happen for
all the Republican contenders other than George W. Bush and Steve
Forbes, who are declining the federal money and the spending limits
it brings.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to cash, Bush continues to be in a league of his
own. His campaign reported raising $19 million in the
July-September period, putting his total at more than $56 million
and leaving him with almost $37 million on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's expenditures, about $12 million in the recent quarter,
will be detailed in the Oct. 15 report. Bush, who began campaigning
months later than other candidates, has maintained a busy,
expensive travel schedule that, according to campaign sources,
costs an average of $40,000 per day.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has now raised about three times the amounts raised by
eventual nominees Bill Clinton and Bob Dole at a similar point in
the 1996 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers on the Democratic side were released as Bradley
enjoys a surge in polls and publicity. Gore, despite spending about
$16 million so far, is unhappy with the way his campaign is going.
On Wednesday, acknowledging he is in a ``hard, tough fight'' with
Bradley, Gore announced he is moving his headquarters and staff
from Washington to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, his campaign said the money side of the effort is
in good shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has all the resources he needs to be able to take his
message to the people of Iowa, New Hampshire, New York, California
and beyond,'' said Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman. ``We're right on
target at where we should be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign, consistent with its candidate's
understated style, declined to gloat about the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased with the steady growth in support the
campaign has enjoyed,'' said Douglas Berman, the campaign chairman.
``There are many people who want to support a candidate who is
running his campaign in a different way and leading on issues such
as health care reform, strong handgun control, child poverty and
campaign finance reform.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in California on Thursday, Bush sounded a
now-familiar refrain about his campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am humbled and honored that so many Americans are helping me
spread my message of improving schools to leave no child behind,
strengthening our military to keep the peace and ushering in an era
of responsibility in America,'' said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Democratic National Committee Chairman Joe Andrew
said Bush still does not have enough money to win the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money can't buy George W. Bush the leadership, the vision or
the policies to be president,'' said Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted Thursday that his money has come from 135,000
supporters and from every state. Under federal election law,
individual contributions are capped at $1,000 and political action
committee donations cannot top $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Thursday also released a list of 41 additional campaign
``pioneers,'' supporters who have collected at least $100,000 for
his campaign. Earlier this year, Bush listed 115 other pioneers.
The new additions include former Dallas Cowboy quarterback Roger
Staubach, Indianapolis mayor and Bush campaign adviser Steve
Goldsmith and a variety of people with ties to the Bush family.
</P>
<P>
   In South Florida, auto dealer and Bush pioneer Paul Anderson
said his ties to the Bush family began about 15 years ago through a
friendship Jeb Bush, now governor of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they represent the important qualities of the American
family that I believe in,'' Anderson said of his admiration for
members of the Bush clan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
