A2516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FASHION-EDITORS01-COX     09-30 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-EDITORS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Editors' top 3 picks for a fashionable fall
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fashion editors live in a sort of perpetual
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   When everyone else is talking fall _ football rivalries, new
classes, possible Halloween costumes _ they're thinking spring.
</P>
<P>
   Ask them to discuss the present, and they look a little
confused. (When pressed, can you recall details of what occupied
your thoughts six months ago?)
</P>
<P>
   In between Fashion Week shows earlier this month, when designers
were trotting out skimpy swimsuits and strappy sandals and
barely-there dresses for next spring, we asked editors to name
their top 3 picks for this fall. As in right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean fall? Not spring?'' they said. Blank stares. Then
furrowed eyebrows. ``Wait a minute, wait a minute,'' said one. ``I
have to think back.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they thought. And then they spoke:
</P>
<P>
   Polly Mellen, formerly with Allure:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``First of all, you've got to have a boot.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Second of all, I love Marc Jacobs jackets that are sort of
turn of the century. They have a Victorian feel to them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Comme des Garcons sequined dress. It has a certain
simplicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Are you sensing a theme here? That's right: Boots!
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Weber Cleary, In Style magazine:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Something sparkly, with beading or sparkle details. For the
holidays, that's how designers have interpreted the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``An animal print. A bag would be a good buy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Black-and-white combinations are very chic. Black and white
is a great thing because it goes from day to night very easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Quickest update: The animal-print bag. You can buy a cute one at
Target for around $15, and it's sure to last as long as this trend
is hot. And right now, it's sizzling.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Betts, Harper's Bazaar:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Calvin Klein black leather trench coat.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Donna Karan modern ballgown.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Marc Jacobs chunky sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Short cut: The idea of a black trench coat may be a little
off-putting to some, but a black jacket in leather or
animal-friendly pleather is a classic piece. And more appropriate
for our balmy winters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2518 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FASHION-TREND01-COX     09-30 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-TREND01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fashion Week trends strap on all the extras
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   PACK A BAG ...
</P>
<P>
   Anna Sui accessorized her romantic collection with embroidered
bags in feminine colors. There's no single identifiable bag trend
for spring. Ralph Lauren's models toted oversized gingham bags down
the runway, while Badgley Mischka's and BCBG's mannequins carried
smaller beaded and beribboned purses in feminine colors. Chado
showed purses that resembled mailing tubes outfitted with straps.
</P>
<P>
   PULL ON SHOES MADE FOR WALKING
</P>
<P>
   Strappy sandals with little heels, like those at Rebecca
Taylor's show, ultimately have a leg up on the cowboy
boot/pseudo-galoshes that came prancing down spring's runways.
DKNY's fast-stepping models sported space-age lucite wedges (''for
a look that walks on air''), and Anna Sui relied on embroidered
ballet slippers. But what you'll see most often in Spring 2000?
Colorful sandals with skinny straps.
</P>
<P>
   AND TAKE OFF FOR ... AN AFRICAN SAFARI
</P>
<P>
   Good news for animal-print lovers: They just won't go away.
Leopard prints were used for shirts, such as a magenta halter top
by Nicole Miller, and zebra prints showed up on dresses by Bill
Blass and Michael Kors. Diane Von Furstenberg's show was a
veritable Noah's Ark of prints: giraffe-print skirts,
chameleon-print dresses and embroidered flamingo tops.
</P>
<P>
   A VISIT TO THE OLD WEST
</P>
<P>
   Designers loved the Western look for spring, but they weren't
satisfied with plain 'ol bluejeans. Tommy Hilfiger spangled his
with fields of stars and flames rising from the hems. Jill Stuart
added heart stitching on a demin jacket, and Ralph Lauren dressed
up a pair of black leather pants with swingy fringe from hip to
toe.
</P>
<P>
   A TOUR OF EAST ASIA
</P>
<P>
   ``Memoirs of a Geisha.'' While several designers bowed to
Japanese traditions of dress, Donna Karan based most of her
collection on the kimono, wrapping and re-wrapping her models'
wasp-thin waists in black, white and dark shades of blue. Alexander
McQueen and Cynthia Rowley based shirts on what looked like Asian
designs, and Han Feng shaped her soft, silk styles with colorful
kimono-like belts.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE ON THE EDGE
</P>
<P>
   Anything that can be stitched to a hem will be stitched to a hem
next spring. You won't be able to miss oversized sequins, strands
of tiny beads, ostrich feathers, and fringe long and short. Even
comparatively simple dresses, such as a Calvin Klein number and a
breezy slip from BCBG, don't stop at one hem. ``People are back to
romantic decoration and embellishment of clothes,'' explains Vogue
editor-at-large Andre Leon Talley.
</P>
<P>
   A TROPICAL GETAWAY
</P>
<P>
   Salsa dresses and sarongs and flirty little skirts _ not to
mention a field of florals _ called to mind the tropics on several
runways. Even more designers, from Bill Blass to BCBG, used sunny
island colors. Michael Kors paid kooky tribute to the '70s
glamorous life with a caftan, and Oscar de la Renta strung together
huge shells to create necklaces with as much coverage as some
Versace halter tops.
</P>
<P>
   BON VOYAGE!
</P>
<P>
   Even when seen from behind, shirts and dresses are busy with
extra details such as buttons meant for decoration only and
corset-like laces. This sheer DKNY top borders on the obscene from
the front, and its wraparound snakeskin print and uneven hem clamor
for your attention out back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
