<HEADER>
A2520 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-EDUCATION-SUMMIT-1001     09-30 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-SUMMIT-1001-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNORS WORRY ABOUT BACKLASH TO SCHOOL REFORMS
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALISADES, N.Y. _ Governors opened the third national Education
Summit Thursday by trading tips on how to squash a pending backlash
against tougher academic standards in the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're all going to face the predictable sniping,'' summit
co-chair Louis Gerstner, chief executive officer of IBM, told about
100 reform-minded participants, including educators, business
leaders and the governors of 24 states.
</P>
<P>
   He said attacks on the standardized tests used to measure
academic achievement typically include ``charges of discrimination,
and allegations that we're hurting people because they can't earn
passing grades based on the new standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerstner's response to the critics: ``People are getting hurt
right now, every day. They're being sentenced to enter the
workforce with diplomas that have all the value of a Russian
ruble.''
</P>
<P>
   Others made the same point in more circumspect language.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons that goals set at the 1989 summit weren't met
despite the later emphasis on high standards that emerged from the
1996 summit, is that the ``goals were too high and the standards
had no teeth,'' said Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, the only
governor to attend all three of the gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Setting high standards was enjoyable. Enforcing them ``is the
bad part,'' said President Clinton, who went to the first summit as
governor of Arkansas and the last two as president. He said he
thinks that is why more states have set high standards than have
moved to tie rewards and punishments to those standards.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1996 summit, 14 states had adopted measurable standards,
and 11 used test scores to make decisions on whether to intervene
in a failing schools, or to let children graduate or move up to the
next grade. Today, 49 states have academic standards, but only 16
base high-stakes decisions for schools or students on test results.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina and Texas, which have had high-stakes tests the
longest, have had the greatest gains in national comparisons of the
performance of fourth-, eighth- and 12th-graders in several
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has worked and the consequences are good,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some states have had revolts by parents and business
leaders,'' said Washington Gov. Gary Locke. ``Parents have to
understand that the standards have to be tough in order to get
children ready for the modern world.''
</P>
<P>
   Several participants said that parents of children in strong
school districts are often the most vocal opponents of
state-mandated tests, which create a risk of marring their
college-bound children's high school transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the winners in the system as it now stands,'' said
Joseph Cirasuolo of the American Association of School
Administrators. ``I think some of the folks with kids in better
schools see more kids coming into competition with their kids for
the best (colleges) and best jobs if standards bring up the
performance of the schools that lag behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Using lots of experts and providing enough time and money to
develop valid tests helps undercut the contention that tests are
biased, Thompson said. But he warned his fellow governors to expect
battles with legislators over high-stakes tests.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Gov. Bob Taft said that Ohio avoided a lot of objections by
concentrating its first pass-fail test for promotion on whether
fourth graders could read well enough to move up to fifth grade.
``All the public would agree that kids could read,'' Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Frank O'Bannon of Indiana said public outcries dimmed in
his state after state officials, educators and business leaders
``came together'' and developed a campaign to travel around the
state explaining why today's high school graduates need to know
more than those of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Financial and other rewards to schools that show improvement in
their scores, even if they haven't reached the top yet, are being
tried in California, said Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have standards that are not variable, but we try to reward
progress toward meeting those standards,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
