<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; OUTTAKES FROM BEATTY'S NEWEST GIG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A Personals spy who was at  &UR; Warren Beatty &LR; 's maybe-I-am
maybe-I'm-not announcement Wednesday night whispers:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lara Flynn Boyle &LR; , 29, and  &UR; Jack Nicholson &LR; , 52, were looking
``very affectionate'' at the table right in front of podium.
 &UR; Courtney Love &LR; , dressed in her trademark ``appropriately smutty''
fashion, kept stepping outside to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its political nature, the event began like a Hollywood
gala, with taped clips of celebrities wishing Beatty well. The
cheerleaders included  &UR; Barbra Streisand &LR; ,  &UR; Dustin Hoffman &LR; ,  &UR; John &LR; 
 &UR; Burton  &LR; and  &UR; Willie Brown &LR; , whose segment was booed.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the evening Beatty ``seemed like a character'' in
one of his movies, overwhelmed and a bit befuddled.
</P>
<P>
   When his wife,  &UR; Annette Bening &LR; , was asked whether taking part
in politics was anything like appearing in a political movie, such
as ``The American President,'' she gave a definite ``No. This is
real life.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Real life?  &UR; Arnold Schwarzenegger  &LR; says in an interview in
the November issue of Talk that he's thinking about running for
governor of California in 2002. ``The possibility is there,'' he
said, ``because I feel it inside. I feel there are a lot of people
standing still and not doing enough. And there's a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   As to his past life, Schwarzenegger said he would come clean.
``What it is is what it is. I inhaled, exhaled. Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Upon reading in New York magazine that  &UR; Kevin Costner &LR; 's
frontal nude scenes in ``For Love of the Game'' were cut, said one
Universal official, partly because a test screening audience
``giggled at Kevin's penis,'' reader  &UR; Tom Costner &LR;  comments:
``Clearly Kev comes from the other branch of the Costner family
tree, the phallically challenged one.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Matt Damon &LR;  and  &UR; Ben Affleck &LR;  are turning  &UR; Howard Zinn &LR; 's
book ``A People's History of the United States'' into a movie. Zinn
is a counterculture intellectual famous in the '60s and '70s, and
was mentor to Damon (who quoted him in ``Good Will Hunting''). He
was also mentor to  &UR; Alice Walker &LR;  and  &UR; Marion Wright Edelman &LR; ,
early friend of the Clintons and founder of the Children's Defense
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Zinn will speak about his book at the San Francisco Book
Festival at Fort Mason on October 16; he'll be introduced by
Edelman, who's speaking just before him on her memoir, `Lanterns: A
Memoir of Mentors.''
</P>
<P>
   - The license plate on a car seen in Berkeley by  &UR; E. Doyle &LR; : ``2
MANY US''; its bumper sticker was ``Make love not more.''
</P>
<P>
   - MSNBC says that socialite/fashion designer/flower arranger
 &UR; Carolyne Roehm &LR;  (who used to be married to tycoon &UR; Henry Kravis &LR; ) is
romantically entangled with  &UR; Ed Rollins &LR; , Republican political
consultant who managed  &UR; Michael Huffington &LR; 's campaign (and whose
wife,  &UR; Sherrie Rollins &LR; , dumped him for  &UR; David Westin &LR; , the
president of ABC News).
</P>
<P>
   - The San Francisco Opera having announced that its new general
director is  &UR; Pamela Rosenberg &LR; ,  &UR; Roberto-Juan Gonzalez &LR;  was
reminded of the 1982 movie ``Yes Giorgio,'' in which  &UR; Luciano &LR; 
 &UR; Pavarotti &LR;  fell in love with a woman named Pamela, whereupon he
proclaimed, ``Pamela, you are a thirsty plant and I, Giorgio Fini,
will water you!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMERCIALS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - A new TV ad for Dannon yogurt features celebrity volleyball
player  &UR; Gabrielle Reece &LR; , and includes a picture of Reece as a
girl, sitting next to a table on which is a carton of Dannon
yogurt. The ad's line: ``You grew up eating Dannon.''
</P>
<P>
   But the picture is fake. Its original version, without yogurt,
appears in Reece's book, ``Big Girl in the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   An ad executive told Advertising Age that the ad wasn't intended
to fool anyone; it was intended to be ironic, ``underscoring the
sardonic tone of the campaign,'' says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   - New York cabdrivers are unhappy about a new campaign for the
clothing company French Connection U.K., which features the
company's initials in ads atop the taxis. ``It's clearly
denigrating to the industry,'' said New York Taxi Commissioner
 &UR; Allan Fromberg &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``London is a little more scruffy than New York. But you also
have a lot better showers here, so maybe it's just that people look
a lot cleaner.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  -  &LR; Actor  &UR; Rupert Graves &LR;  on fashion in London and New York, in
the menswear daily DNR.
</P>
</TEXT>
