<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-FEDERER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES A. FEDERER JR., ONCE EDITED SKY &AMP; TELESCOPE MAGAZINE; 90 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Anthony Federer Jr., a self-taught astronomer who
parlayed his avocation into a long career as editor-in-chief of Sky
&AMP; Telescope magazine, died Tuesday in a nursing home in Mystic,
Conn. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Federer was born in St. Louis. He was raised in Connecticut,
where, as a young man he ``studied the stars though an oak tree in
front of our home in Redding, Conn.,'' according to a reminiscence
published in the November 1986 issue of Sky &AMP; Telescope.
</P>
<P>
   After becoming a marine insurance underwriter in New York City,
he continued to pursue his interest in astronomy as a night student
at City College of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In 1927, he became a founding member the Amateur Astronomers
Association and began conducting classes under the auspices of the
group. In 1934, a year before the Hayden Planetarium was slated to
open in New York City, Mr. Federer quit his insurance job and began
studying full time at City College, where he earned a bachelor's
degree in physics.
</P>
<P>
   When the planetarium opened of Oct. 3, 1935, he was a guest
lecturer in the premiere program at the state-of-the art facility.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Federer soon became editor of the Hayden planetarium
publication, Sky. In 1941, he was invited to merge the magazine
with Telescope, a journal published at the Harvard Observatory. He
moved his operation to Cambridge, Mass. and the first issue of the
merged Sky &AMP; Telescope magazine sold 5,000 copies. The magazine for
amateur and professional astronomers now has a circulation of about
125,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Federer retired in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 his contributions to the study of the stars were
recognized when the International Astronomical Union named Asteroid
4726 in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Marion Wilcox Korab Federer of Stonington,
Conn.; a son, C. Anthony of Durham, N.H.; a daughter, Barbara
Meredith of London; four grandchildren and three
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2526 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-ASSESS-810(2TAK     09-30 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ASSESS-810(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: IN A DIFFERENT CHINA, FEELINGS OF BOTH PRIDE AND REGRET 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHINA-ANNIVERSARY, CHINA-REVOLUTION) 
(bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Wang Ruoshui was on Tiananmen Square that electric day
exactly half a century ago Friday when Mao Tse-tung announced,
``The People's Republic of China is founded! From this time on, the
Chinese people have stood up!''
</P>
<P>
   Wang, who was an underground Communist as a student and would
become a leading journalist and party theoretician, remembers how
proud he felt. ``We thought we were creating a new history,'' he
said. ``We believed we were creating a new, free, strong,
democratic and prosperous China.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic it is not, but when Chinese people weigh the
revolution that began 50 years ago, they express pride that the
nation is united and finally, as Mao promised, standing up in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   If asked about events they would rather forget, Chinese say that
Mao's unbridled political campaigns _ the economic fantasies that
caused millions of famine deaths, the vicious purges that scarred
generations and brought the nation to a standstill _ were a
terrible mistake. They go on, though, to heap praise on Deng
Xiaoping's economic opening two decades ago that brought prosperity
and more control over their personal lives, if not their political
choices.
</P>
<P>
   But among many in the older generation of Communists, there is
also a sense of loss. Though not all of them have come to share
Wang's belated conviction that democracy is the only answer, many
old revolutionaries wistfully recall a time of idealism, when the
young revolutionaries were uncorrupted and respected. While they
may marvel at today's wealth, these elders lament the widespread
corruption of officials today, and the growing disparities in
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, now 73, rose to be deputy chief editor of the Communist
Party's newspaper, People's Daily, before he was fired in 1983 for
his liberal leanings. Today he rails against corruption like
everyone else. But more than that, he decries the lack of
restraints on party power that facilitates it; and he decries the
lack of political choices and press freedom.
</P>
<P>
   That he is one of the rare Chinese who dares to question the
political order in public is revealing in itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current leaders say stability takes precedence over
everything, but what they really mean is the survival of their
regime,'' Wang said. ``China does need stability, but not the kind
that protects corruption. Political reform is the best way to
prevent instability.''
</P>
<P>
   After the savage chaos of the Mao era, which followed decades of
invasions and civil war, a yearning for stability was
understandable. In the late 1970s, after Mao's death, stability was
Deng's prime concern as he laid out a simple strategy for
modernizing the insular and dispirited country: on the political
side, preserve Communist Party dictatorship; on the economic side,
start opening to the world and tapping the power of market
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look to the future!,'' Deng exhorted the nation, steering them
away from recriminations that could destroy the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Deng's approach was remarkably successful, yielding two decades
of startling economic growth and social change. And the country,
making a pun on the Chinese word for ``future,'' enthusiastically
transformed his slogan into ``Look to the money!''
</P>
<P>
   Farmers resurfaced their dirt floors with concrete, bought
televisions and often refrigerators. Urban professionals bought
stylish clothes and started saving to buy cars and take foreign
vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of memorizing Mao's sayings, students now delve into the
Internet. Once-cowed workers take to the streets when their wages
go unpaid and aggrieved farmers, instead of ``eating bitterness,''
in the Chinese phrase for suffering, are apt to try suing local
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the leaders under President Jiang Zemin are still
following Deng's basic prescription _ pursuing deeper changes in
the economy while zealously guarding the party monopoly and holding
``stability'' as gospel.
</P>
<P>
   But the society is vastly more complex and demanding than
before. It is increasingly wired to the unforgiving global market,
and there are signs that the era of easy 10 percent-plus growth
rates has ended.
</P>
<P>
   The central question facing China today, many scholars here and
abroad believe, is whether Deng's aging formula has run its course.
Do Jiang and his colleagues, they ask, need a new political vision
if China is to flourish in the emerging world?
</P>
<P>
   ``Deng's approach turned out to be workable for two decades, and
China made enormous progress,'' said Minxin Pei, a Chinese-born
political scientist with the Carnegie Endowment for International
Peace in Washington. ``But now they've got to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a political loosening and far stronger legal checks and
balances, Pei and other critics say, China cannot conquer the
widespread official corruption that even party leaders admit is
corroding their authority.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In China, practical arguments for democracy are nothing new. But
so far, the country has continued jailing or exiling dissidents who
push too hard. And there are still those, even outside government
circles, who think that the current approach may be the only
realistic one for now.
</P>
<P>
   Xiao Gongqin, a historian at Shanghai Normal University, said he
agreed that as society grows more complex and social interests
diversify, democratic channels must emerge to deal with their
demands. ``But I feel China is not yet at that stage,'' he said.
``It's at the most trying stage of modernization.''
</P>
<P>
   Dali Yang, a Chinese-born political scientist at the University
of Chicago, thinks the leadership deserves more credit than it
gets.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the government is already in the midst of an
ambitious ``rebuilding of the institutional sinews of the state,''
including revamping of the tax, banking, legal and regulatory
systems in addition to the painful pruning of state industries.
Progress with these, Yang argued, ``will eventually allow the
Chinese leadership greater room for political liberalization,''
which he is certain will come.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1948EDT &QL; 
