<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORNO-FASHION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORN IN THE U.S.A.: TEENS' T-SHIRTS REFLECT THE TIMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blake Perez and his friends are pimps and porn stars in
training, and some attend a bastion of higher learning called
Pimptown University, or are breaking into the world of gainful
employment as members of the National Pimp Association.
</P>
<P>
   If, that is, one believes their T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for proof of the decline of the current generation
of high-schoolers need look no further than the local Gadzooks
stores. There, one can find shirts with slogans such as ``Porn Star
in Training,'' ``Pimp,'' and ``National Pimp Association,'' the
last of which features a silhouette of a stereotyped '70s pimp, a
guy with platform boots and a wide-brimmed hat, complete with
feather. At local Wherehouse Music locations, kids can buy stickers
that say ``Porn Star in Training,'' ``Pimp Daddy,'' ``Stripper''
and more.
</P>
<P>
   And all those shirts and stickers, according to store employees,
are wildly popular with guys and girls between ages 14 and 17.
Wherehouse employees say they literally cannot keep enough of a
sticker that says ``Skinny Little B-----.''
</P>
<P>
   What the heck is going on here? you ask.
</P>
<P>
   To Perez, an articulate, friendly, home-schooled 16-year-old,
it's part of the game of shock-the-parents-and-impress-your-friends
that's repeated with each new generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a fad; it's real in right now,'' he says, pausing in
a Fort Worth mall on a recent Saturday afternoon and adjusting the
safety pins on his bucket hat, which features a Marilyn Manson
American flag. ``Ninety percent of my friends wear these shirts.
It's shock; it's to see what other people will say. We want to be
us. We want to be different, and we'll do anything possible.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. David Welsh, a Fort Worth psychologist who
works extensively with adolescents, teens proclaim themselves pimps
and porn stars for a variety of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One is that they simply want to shock Mom and Dad and their
third-period biology teacher; in that sense, he says, ``It's
business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh says the mainstreaming of pornography and hip-hop lyrics
are also playing a part.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really bothers me; the themes of adolescence have been
ratcheted up to such a degree, in terms of content and images,''
Welsh says. ``Kids will be kids, but it's being taken to a more
disturbing and dangerous level than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   James Scott, the 18-year-old manager of the Gadzooks store at
Hulen Mall in Fort Worth, says the shirts have been around at least
a year and sell as well as shirts without sexual innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, a lot of guys want to say, `Yeah, I can get any
girl I want _ I'm a pimp,' '' Scott says. ``It's to show off, to
brag. When it was time to go back to school, we sold a lot of the
`Porn Star' shirts. About sixty percent of the people that buy the
`Porn Star' T-shirts are guys. A lot of times we get groups of guys
and they all buy the same shirt _ `Pimptown University' or
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough; after all, as Perez points out, his parents wore
shirts that espoused more scatological philosophies akin to ``Stuff
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   But is something else going on here?
</P>
<P>
   According to a Wherehouse employee who doesn't want to be
identified, the popularity of the shirts and stickers is proof that
``Our culture has gone completely downhill, and kids think it's
cool to be a porn star.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kid Rock's whole philosophy is, `Get as many girls backstage
as you can' and these kids have to process that somehow,'' she
adds, referring to a popular rock-rap star who celebrates a
hedonistic lifestyle. ``Kids today feel no shame about being a porn
star or a stripper.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the vast majority of the teens who wear the shirts
will not end up working in the sex industry. But porn is right
there, all the time, via cable TV and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent article in the Los Angeles Times,
adult-film production has increased by 25 percent this year and is
a $4 billion industry, with between 175 and 200 films produced
weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Hip-hop is also affecting how teens see male-female
relationships, Welsh says. Top male stars often refer to themselves
as ``pimps'' and ``playas'' and mention a past as a dope dealer to
further their street credibility. The genre also has several female
stars, such as Foxy Brown and Lil' Kim, who refer to themselves as
b------.
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up, Welsh says, and ``the content of a lot of the
media is more mean-spirited and misogynistic, and kids are
absorbing that. The mainstream acceptance of porn is a new
phenomenon. Kids have more access to porn than ever before, and
guys like Howard Stern have porn stars on as guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are starting to believe porn is legitimate entertainment.
And if you're an insecure adolescent male you start looking at the
portrayal of (the pimp) lifestyle and think, `Yeah, I could do
that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The decline of American culture? Evidence that we're sliding
down the slippery slopes to pure decadence?
</P>
<P>
   Blake Perez has to smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about society falling apart; we're just trying to
be different,'' he says. ``We want to be remembered and leave our
mark. Girls think it's cute. They want to leave their mark, too. We
all want to believe in our own thing. I just know we're all the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDRV/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
