<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2533 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-VONNEGUT-ANTHOLOGY-RE     09-30 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VONNEGUT-ANTHOLOGY-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VOICE OF A GENERATION AGES WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CATHY FRISINGER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Bagombo Snuff Box''
</P>
<P>
   By Kurt Vonnegut
</P>
<P>
   Short stories
</P>
<P>
   G.P. Putnam's Sons, $23.95
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Vonnegut has come unstuck in time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, it was practically a law that college students read
Vonnegut. That was the year ``Slaughterhouse-Five'' was published,
and its message about war, delivered in a
comic/tragic/satiric/pseudo-scientific manner, jibed perfectly with
the anti-Vietnam temperament of the time. Hooked on the wit of that
twisted tale, a youthful audience hungry for more ``discovered''
Vonnegut's earlier writings.
</P>
<P>
   It is 30 years later. Ask a college student today who Vonnegut
is, and you might get a response like, ``He's that dude who wrote
that graduation speech about wearing sunscreen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, and wrong again.
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, not Vonnegut but a Chicago newspaper
columnist who made the pitch for Bain de Soleil. More important,
Vonnegut's writing still has a remarkably contemporary feel, and
Gen X-ers who ignore him are missing out on a great source of
pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Now Vonnegut leaps backward five decades to his first days as a
writer.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time before television stole the minds of America.
During the late '40s and the '50s, there was great demand for short
stories as entertainment. Vonnegut discovered that he could do
better than be a flack for General Electric; he could write amusing
stories for magazines such as ``Cosmopolitan, The Saturday Evening
Post, Ladies' Home Journal'' and ``Colliers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bagombo Snuff Box'' is a collection of 23 of those early
stories. His other short stories have previously been collected in
``Welcome to the Monkey House.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories in ``Bagombo'' range from silly to serious, although
most have at least some element of comedy. A couple are downright
romantic _ most likely written with a particular magazine's
audience in mind _ but all the others cover topics familiar to fans
of Vonnegut novels. ``Souvenir'' and ``Der Arme Dolmetscher''
reflect the author's World War II experiences. The title story and
``Custom-Made Bride'' deal with people being something other than
what they appear to be. ``The Package'' and ``2BR02B'' look at the
foibles of technology.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Thanosphere'' (written before the first manned space
flight), an astronaut aboard a secretly launched rocket ship
discovers ``others'' out there.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the more lighthearted tales concern high school band
leader George M. Helmholtz, whose dream is as high as, but no
higher than, having the finest marching band on Earth. Vonnegut
could have made this character a buffoon, but he treats him with a
certain respect that lets the reader smile and cheer him on at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was perfectly swell,'' is the opening line of
``2BR02B,'' a chilling tale about one way that society's march
toward conquering disease, aging and other perils might go awry.
</P>
<P>
   An introduction by Vonnegut illuminates his history and is a
welcome addition to the stories. He also offers some advice on
writing:
</P>
<P>
   ``1. Use the time of a total stranger in such a way that he or
she will not feel the time was wasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``2. Give the reader at least one character he or she can root
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``3. Every character should want something, even if it is only a
glass of water.''
</P>
<P>
   And so on.
</P>
<P>
   No mention of sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bagombo'' might have been slightly improved by the inclusion
of the magazine and date of original publication for each story.
</P>
<P>
   In a postscript, Vonnegut admits that, while editing stories for
the collection, he felt compelled to rewrite the denouement of
three _ ``The Powder Blue Dragon,'' ``Hal Irwin's Magic Lamp'' and
``The Boy Who Hated Girls.'' As they appear in ``Bagombo,'' these
three stories come to abrupt, harsh endings. It would be nice to
compare them with the original endings, which probably were more
sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   But these are small quibbles about a very welcome collection of
clever tales.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers who last read Vonnegut before their hairlines began
to recede should come unstuck in time and take a dip from ``Bagombo
Snuff Box.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those uninitiated Gen X-ers _ Vonnegut would never waste
the time of a total stranger. ( Baby boomer Cathy Frisinger works
on the ``Star-Telegram'' features copy desk. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
