<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS END DISAPPOINTING QUARTER ON UPBEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks closed out a largely negative quarter on a
positive note Thursday, as a rally in the bond market helped to
push major market indexes higher.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks also benefited from quarter-end ``window-dressing'' by
mutual fund managers Thursday. In order to shore up their
portfolios, some managers buy shares of companies that have done
well to make end-of-quarter reports look better to their investors.
</P>
<P>
   Led by gains in Hewlett-Packard, General Electric and Minnesota
Mining and Manufacturing, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
123.47, or 1.2 percent at the close, to 10,336.95.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a good performance by drug stocks and big
money-center banks helped to push up the Standard &AMP; Poors 500 index
by 14.34, or 1.13 percent, to 1282.71.
</P>
<P>
   Gains of two points or more in stocks like Nextel and Comcast
led the NASDAQ composite index up by 15.89 points, or 0.6 percent,
to 2746.16. And the Russell 2000 index of small-company stocks
jumped 5.79, or 1.4 percent, to 427.31.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a broader context, Thursday's gains failed to mask
what was a disappointing quarter for most investors.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer quarter, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell
each month, and ended up down 6.6 percent from where it stood at
the end of June. It is the first time the index has fallen for
three straight months since the period of August through October
1990, following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which set a new high of 11,326 on Aug. 25, was down 5.8
percent for the quarter. Helped by semiconductor companies, the
NASDAQ was up for the period, but not much: a 2.2 percent advance.
And the Russell 2000 index slumped by 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``During this period we had profit-taking from the tremendous up
move that took place from last October until April, as well as on
concerns about inflation and the dollar,'' said Peter Canelo, a
U.S.investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. ``But
in terms of the S&AMP;P, we have really gone nowhere for quite some
time.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of March, the S&AMP;P index stood at 1286.40, Canelo
noted, less than four points above its closing level Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The last three months have been a good time to own
semiconductor, biotechnology, computer software and oil stocks. And
gold mining stocks had a great quarter in a week.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a decidedly different story for investment bank and
brokerage stocks, for apparel retailers, airlines and life
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   And those industries were not alone. As many analysts have
noted, most stocks have been struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through Wednesday, a dozen of the 63 groups we cover showed
positive performance'' during the quarter, said Douglas Cliggott,
U.S. equity strategist at J.P. Morgan Securities Inc. ``One other
group was flat. That means 50 sectors were negative. Stock
leadership during the quarter was diverse, but quite narrow.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the breadth of the market's advance Thursday was
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, winners outnumbered losers by a
margin of just under 2-1. The ratio of winners to losers on the
NASDAQ market was much narrower, but still positive.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was heavy. More than 1 billion shares changed hands on
the Big Board. Volume on the NASDAQ market was 1.16 billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   Among Dow stocks, Hewlett-Packard rose 1 1/2, to 90 3/4. General
Electric was up 2 1/8, to 118 9/16. And 3M gained 2, to 96 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in interest rates helped big bank stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup gained 1 3/8, to 44. Chase Manhattan was up 2 3/8, to
75 3/8. And BankBoston gained 2 1/16, to 43 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks also had a good day.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer was up 1 7/8, to 35 15/16. Bristol-Myers Squibb gained 2,
to 67 1/2. And Schering-Plough gained 2 1/16, to 43 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   But investors were not kind to insurance companies after reports
surfaced that trial lawyers were preparing class-action lawsuits on
behalf of managed-care patients.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna fell 10 9/16, to 49 1/8. Cigna was down 9 1/4, to 77 3/4.
And United Healthcare slid 11 13/16, to 48 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is the next quarter will start out pretty much the way
this one finished, with a lot of volatility and a lack of
conviction,'' Canelo said. ``But by the end of the year I think the
market will be doing well. Interest rate worries will be behind us.
Y2K concerns will be over with and I think the dollar will get the
usual strong bid that we have seen at the end of the last four
years. Things look cloudy now, but there will be a Christmas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
