   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPENDING (Washington) _ President Clinton signs a
stopgap spending measure to keep the government operating and
blasts the Republicans for using ``gimmicks'' to avoid tapping
surplus Social Security funds. Clinton warns congressional
Republicans that if they resort to delayed Earned Income Tax Credit
payments to the poor, as now planned, he will veto the measure. By
NANCY MATHIS and GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-WELFARE (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush, in a move
that has upset some legislators, is taking steps to cut parents and
children off welfare permanently and sooner than state law
requires. In a document prepared for federal officials, Bush is
opting in favor of a provision in the 1996 federal welfare law to
cap welfare benefits. Under the Bush plan, an estimated 10,000
children will be cut off the rolls a year earlier than necessary
and 5,500 adults would be permanently severed from benefits one to
three years earlier than necessary. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-VIDEO (Galveston, Texas) _ A Missouri murder convict
testifies that he did nothing to deserve being kicked and hit by
officers and bitten by a police dog during a 1996 shakedown at the
Brazoria County Jail. The man was testifying in the case of two
deputies and a private prison employee accused of using excessive
force during the search. By KEVIN MORAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-MARIJUANA (Houston) _ In what may be the first ruling of
its kind, the 1st Court of Appeals says a police officer cannot
enter a residence without a search warrant simply because the
officer smells marijuana inside. In its ruling, the court threw out
the conviction of a Houston man for marijuana possession. By RON
NISSIMOV. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MARS-PROBE (Undated) _ NASA's investigation into last week's
loss of the Mars Climate Orbiter indicates the catastrophic
navigational error occurred because a contractor, Lockheed Martin
Astronautics in Colorado, and the Jet Propulsion laboratory in
Pasadena, Calif., miscommunicated. One team used English units of
measurement, while the other used metrics in a key calculation. By
MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-PIZZA (Undated) _ Pizza Hut makes a deal to slap a big
advertisement on the side of a Russian rocket set to carry
components of the international space station into orbit. By MARK
CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
