<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIAN-FACTION-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HARD-LINE PALESTINIAN RETURNS TO THE WEST BANK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERICHO, West Bank _ A leading Palestinian radical, one of the
few renegades who had remained committed to armed struggle against
Israel, returned home from Damascus Thursday after 32 years in
exile.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian, Mustafa Zubari, known as Abu Ali Mustafa, also
ended years of estrangement from Yasser Arafat, and entered the
West Bank to a minor hero's welcome from senior officials of the
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   After greeting him at the Jordanian border, the officials
accompanied Zubari to a small ceremony, complete with beeping horns
and ululation, at a dusty bus depot in this desert town.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through a crackling loudspeaker, Zubari neither
renounced violence nor embraced peace. The officials who greeted
him, however, made it clear that they saw his return as a victory:
the collapse of a stubborn pocket of resistance both to the peace
process and to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not ask him to sign anything, but there is a consensus
that everybody who returns will denounce violence,'' said Tayeb
Abdel Rahmin, secretary general of the Palestinian Authority. ``His
blessed return represents an important turn and a necessary step
for national unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Zubari, 61, is the deputy chief of a Damascus-based radical
faction of the Palestine Liberation Organization. His group, the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, is best known for
plane hijackings in the 1960s and '70s. Its leader, George Habash,
a 72-year-old Marxist, is expected to retire soon and pass the
reins to Zubari.
</P>
<P>
   Through private meetings in Cairo and Amman, Arafat negotiated
the return directly with Zubari. It is part of an aggressive
campaign to bring home key rejectionist leaders and consolidate
Arafat's already formidable control over the Palestinian people at
the beginning of final peace talks with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat also recently reconciled with Nayef Hawatmeh, the leader
of another Syrian-based Palestinian faction, the Democratic Front
for the Liberation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   In his quest, Arafat has had some unlikely help from President
Hafez al-Assad of Syria, a longtime personal rival. Over the summer
Syria, partly in the interest of renewing its peace talks with
Israel, instructed Palestinian dissident groups in Damascus to give
up the armed struggle and remake themselves as political groups.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat also secured help from Israel, which granted permission
for Zubari to enter the West Bank. And he is seeking an entry
permit for Hawatmeh, too. Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Thursday
that Israel is considering the Palestinian request because Hawatmeh
has been portrayed as ``joining the camp of supporters of the peace
deals.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel endorses Arafat's drive to tuck the secular radicals back
under his wing, believing it will strengthen the peace effort. The
radicals split from the Palestine Liberation Organization after
Arafat signed the Oslo peace agreement with Israel in 1993; they
saw it as a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear whether this drive will have more than a
symbolic importance: With their leaders abroad, the radical secular
movements of both Zubari and Hawatmeh were long ago marginalized in
the West Bank and Gaza. The radical Islamic movements have
overtaken them as the chief opposition to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secular opposition doesn't have any teeth,'' said Mahdi
Abdul Hadi, the director of the Palestinian Academic Society for
the Study of International Affairs. ``As long as you're in the
diaspora, you have no constituency.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Joshua Teitelbaum, an expert on Palestinian politics at the Tel
Aviv University Dayan Center, said Arafat would use the returns as
``a fig leaf to talk about national reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll give him a bit more legitimacy: that's he taking in
all the Palestinians, that he's all-encompassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, say the return of the dissidents will help
Arafat face down Hamas and Islamic Holy War, the two religious
fundamentalist opposition groups _ especially if the secular
dissidents are allowed some local authority in towns and refugee
camps where they still have support.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials Thursday said that Zubari's group would
not join the Palestinian Authority, but as PLO members would have a
say in the peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   On the symbolic level, both the Palestinian officials and Zubari
made it clear Thursday that his return would be placed in the
context of a major issue on the table in the talks: the right of
return for millions of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome Abu Ali and his return to exercise his legitimate
right to live in his homeland,'' said Saeb Erekat, a senior
Palestinian official.
</P>
<P>
   Zubari, his voice echoing through a large bus station that held
only about 100 supporters, said: ``I am telling you that there are
four million Palestinians who look at Palestine with the desire to
come back. No one or no force can prevent them from dreaming to
return to their land.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanking Arafat for persuading the Israelis to let him enter,
Zubari acknowledged, ``Yes, we are together.''
</P>
<P>
   But his oratory still bore fire. ``We are together to carry the
flag of the Palestinian resistance as far as they resist our hope
for sovereignty in our land. We have the right to exert all
legitimate struggle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
