<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2543 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FLOODS-SHELTERS01-COX     09-30 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-SHELTERS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stability eludes flood's shelter dwellers
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Grief visits in the quiet of the evening,
when the children are asleep and adults grow weary of talking.
</P>
<P>
   While silence is a relief when you're living cheek to jowl with
hundreds of strangers, it also frees the mind to think about
terrible things.
</P>
<P>
   Like having no home, no car, no clothes, and no idea what the
future holds.
</P>
<P>
   Each night, as Rita Tripp tries to find a comfortable position
on her army cot, she feels the grief pushing on her. A victim of
Hurricane Floyd, she has been living in shelters for two weeks. Her
trailer near Pinecrest Mobile Home Park is probably destroyed,
along with all of her possessions and her car.
</P>
<P>
   Losing belongings and living in a shelter is devastating enough:
Add to that feeling like a vagabond. Tripp and most other residents
left homeless by Floyd have had to pack their suddenly-meager stash
of possessions and move three or four times in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp moved for the fourth time Thursday, from Bethel Elementary
School to the Boys &AMP; Girls Club on Fire Tower Road. She was one of
about 440 people the Red Cross transferred from area schools to
three Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs. Classes are set to begin on Monday, so
officials need to ready the schools for the students' return.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, flood victims were moved around because their shelters
were leaky or without power or water. Now, 150 live in the Ayden
club, 65 in Farmville and 225 in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a struggle, getting tossed around so much,''
Tripp said as she waited outside the gymnasium that would be her
new, temporary home. ``We pack and unpack, pack and unpack. We want
to go somewhere permanent.''
</P>
<P>
   National Guardsmen pulled cargo trucks up to the gym and
unloaded possessions and cots. Bedding and clothing and stuffed
animals and coloring books were bundled in black garbage bags with
family names taped to the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's fellow shelter dwellers straggled off school buses and
walked into the 8,000-square-foot gym. They looked long-faced and
tired, and they shuffled like people who have had to get used to
being told where to go. They lined up their cots along the yellow
cinder block walls and sat down heavily, gearing up to unpack _
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer this goes on, the more this is hitting them,'' said
Michael Raper, a Red Cross volunteer who has been living in the
shelters with flood victims. ``They thought, 'Oh, I'll take shelter
from the storm and then go home.' Now, it has been two weeks, and
they're finding out their houses are gone. And they're worried:
They don't understand that the Red Cross is not going to leave
anyone with nowhere to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Harry Grubbs, a National Guard chaplain, was on hand
Thursday at the Fire Tower shelter in case anyone needed to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was a good place to be _ where people are being
uprooted one more time,'' he said. ``Tempers are growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis and Catalina Cruz stood in the sun outside the gym,
watching as their 3-year-old son, Ippolito, darted between their
legs. They're uncomfortable with the lack of privacy in the
shelters, so they've been sleeping in the back of their Taurus
station wagon. Luis, unable to return to his farming job, is
concerned about money. The family's mobile home in Eastwood Country
Estates is ruined, and they are wondering when help will arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have promised us mobile homes, but we have not heard
anything,'' he said, referring to the 300 campers the Federal
Emergency Management Agency plans to set up. ``I don't know why it
is taking so long.''
</P>
<P>
   FEMA has said it will be at least the weekend before the first
batch of campers on County Home Road are ready to live in.
</P>
<P>
   Several flood victims said Thursday they are pinning their hopes
on being assigned a camper. Some are simply looking for some sense
of permanence, although they are not sure what form that permanence
will take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready for FEMA to do what they got to do,'' said Chris
Barfield. ``I'm ready to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   But he has no home. His trailer on Old River Road by the airport
has been under water for two weeks. He doubts anything has
survived, but he hasn't been back to check.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want us going back because there's a lot of
snakes,'' he said. ``And the power's out, so it's dark, and I'm
scared of snakes. I don't mess with snakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Barfield and his wife and 3-year-old son have moved three times
since the storm hit, each time loading and unloading their gray
pickup with garbage bags of donated clothes, blankets and pillows.
Tied to the truck by a chain is Corn Bread, the family puppy.
</P>
<P>
   Spot Dog, another family pet, was too big to bring along when
they evacuated in rising flood waters two weeks ago. Barfield
doesn't know if the dog is dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
   Reatha Phillips, Barfield's wife, tried to focus on the positive
as she sang Gospel songs along with the truck's radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have met a lot of nice people, and I hope one day I will
get to repay them,'' she said. ``One woman gave me clothes, and a
man told me when I get back in a home to go see his son at his
electronics store and he will give me a new TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what she does all day, she said she tries to stay busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make phone calls, I wash clothes, I read to my son and take
him out to play,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp said she enjoys talking with her new friends during the
day, and she even finds herself laughing at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty good during the day,'' she said. ``But it's when
you lay down at night that things start to come to you.''
</P>
<P>
   She grew quiet as her eyes filled with tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk about this anymore,'' she said. ``We've held it
in a long time, trying to hold up. It's like you wish you could
find a room to go in and just be alone and let it all out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
