<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-GUINEVERE-SPI &LR;      09-30 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-GUINEVERE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROMANCE IN `GUINEVERE' IS BAFFLING, NOT RACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First-time director Audrey Wells (who wrote ``The Truth About
Cats and Dogs'') has written and crafted an enigmatic but gorgeous
film that purports to delve into the forbidden bond between an
older man and a very young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``Guinevere'' won raves at the Sundance Film Festival for
what some viewed as a ``racy'' theme, the film is hardly
provocative. It's a surprisingly tame look at how an older artist,
a photographer named Connie (Stephen Rea), who isn't much of a
Lancelot, seduces a Guinevere every few years, uses her as an
assistant in his work and romantically exploits or initiates her
into his life.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, and especially in its ending, the film is reminiscent
of Bob Fosse's autobiographical 1979 effort, ``All That Jazz,'' in
which a self-destructive choreographer faithlessly uses the women
around him to fuel his art _ even though he makes each of them a
better dancer in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guinevere'' isn't nearly as interesting. It lacks the
fundamental ruthlessness and brutal truth that made ``All That
Jazz'' so unapologetically original. Instead, it soft soaps and
romanticizes its tale of an older man who easily convinces a young
woman to become little more than his gofer while he undercuts her
substantial power as a muse. The film provides only a glimpse into
why a man twice the age of his young lover is so willing to be with
a person who is, for the most part, unformed.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem is Rea's character, who is a lost-puppy-dog,
drunken reveler who makes no apologies for his lifestyle. There's
little reason for his latest conquest, Harper (Sarah Polley), to
take a shine to him outside of her own inexperience and perhaps
rebellion against her rich family and the plans they've forged for
her future.
</P>
<P>
   Harper's jaded mother, played by Jean Smart, is the smartest
thing in the film. A confrontational scene between Smart and Rea is
right on in its brittle accusation, but there are far too few of
these moments in the film. Every Guinevere that Connie has ever
seduced still likes the guy no matter how he mistreated her, and
their lives seem to have fallen ridiculously by the wayside after
they leave him. That's a conceit that barely rings true, even to
those of us who may have weathered a mentor relationship early on.
</P>
<P>
   Wells eventually turns Connie into the tragic figure, a noble
fool, despite his behavior, and the focus shifts from Harper to
Connie, who becomes the victim in the end.
</P>
<P>
   We never learn who Wells is siding with, if she's mocking a
lifestyle that seems demeaning or if she's glorifying the fact that
such relationships still exist. That lack of focus ultimately
undoes the film and undercuts, for the first time, the potency of a
performance bu Canadian actress Sarah Polley (``The Sweet
Hereafter'').
</P>
<P>
   Still, you've got to give Wells credit for giving us a
panoramic, visually lustrous and romantic view of San Francisco. If
this screenwriter ever decides to stop writing, she definitely has
a career in directing and in capturing a world full of bohemian,
Edward Hopper-esque flavor that is potentially awe-inducing and
grandly romantic to aspiring artists everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Guinevere. Directed and written by Audrey Wells. Cast: Sarah
Polley, Stephen Rea, Jean Smart, Gina Gershon. Miramax Films. 105
minutes. Rated R for sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
