<HEADLINE>
TRITE THEME OF `DRIVE ME CRAZY' WOULD SEND ANYONE OVER THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How much longer will Hollywood insist upon driving us crazy with
insipid romantic comedies about two polar-opposite high school kids
who, after sparring and trying to get each other to change, find
they're perfect together on the eve of the big dance?
</P>
<P>
   ``She's All That,'' ``Can't Buy Me Love,'' ``10 Things I Hate
About You'' _ you name it, the formula is pretty similar no matter
who's starring in the film. In this case, it's a vehicle to thrust
Melissa Joan Hart, who stars in the TV series ``Sabrina, the
Teenage Witch,'' onto the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Drive Me Crazy,'' she plays Nicole, a popular high school
senior who has a crush on Brad (Gabriel Carpenter), a basketball
star. But Brad finds Nicole's snake of a friend, Alicia (Susan May
Pratt), far more thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Her next-door neighbor is Chase (Adrien Grenier), an activist
and coffeehouse denizen who dates the equally bohemian Dulcie (Ali
Carter). But Dulcie's ditched him.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole and Chase scheme to make their partners jealous: they'll
pretend to be dating. The usual pitfalls ensue and by the night of
the dance, they discover they like each other.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, ``Drive Me Crazy'' is so badly plotted and
written that it rarely makes much sense, even with the elementary
story line.
</P>
<P>
   Drive Me Crazy. Directed by John Schultz. Written by Rob Thomas.
Cast: Melissa Joan Hart, Adrien Grenier. 20th Century Fox. 91
minutes. Rated PG-13 for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-NIEMAN-KOVACH-BOS &LR;      09-30 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIEMAN-KOVACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIMAN CHIEF KOVACH TO STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Recommending an ``upgrade'' to a leader who
could help navigate technological and economic changes in the media
business, Bill Kovach announced Thursday that he would step down as
curator of the Nieman Foundation for Journalism at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard spokeswoman said President Neil Rudenstine will choose
a successor to Kovach with the advice of a search committee, to be
named immediately. The foundation, which runs the nation's most
prestigious journalism fellowships and serves as a sort of
journalism think tank, hopes to have a new director by April, in
time to choose the new class of Nieman fellows.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the foundation's advisory board, Kovach cited
``personal and practical reasons'' for stepping down. The changes
in communications technology and the economic hierarchy of
journalism have altered the work of the business, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have struggled to keep abreast of this change . . . but I
grow distant from direct experience,'' he wrote. ``It makes me less
able to anticipate or appreciate their practical needs. The
university and future fellows are, as we say these days, ready for
an upgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   A former New York Times reporter and editor, Kovach arrived as a
Nieman fellow 11 years ago after resigning as head of the Atlanta
Journal and Constitution in a dispute over editorial independence
from its ownership. He became ``emergency'' curator after the death
of Howard Simons in 1988, and was named to the post officially the
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to move on and step back a little bit,'' Kovach said
Thursday. ``I came here planning on staying six months at most. . .
. This is my tenth Nieman class. And that is a nice round number.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard has lost two media heavyweights this year, with Marvin
Kalb already having stepped down as director of the Joan
Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics, and Public Policy at the
Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine is considering a long list of people to replace
Kovach, one source said, but there are no firm or final contenders.
The Shorenstein Center has been searching for a leader for several
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the person who takes over at Nieman and at the
Shorenstein Center are mindful of these tremendous changes (in
journalism) and therefore more determined than ever to stick to
some of the fundamental values, and not to let the marketplace
determine how news is covered,'' said Kalb, now executive director
of the Shorenstein Center, from a new satellite office in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Kovach has been the very model of a curator for the
Nieman Foundation,'' Rudenstine said. ``He commands instant respect
in this country and abroad, and has constantly enhanced the quality
and the reach of the Nieman Fellows program. We will feel his loss
in many, many ways, and it will be far from easy to find a worthy
successor.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovach and his wife, Lynne, plan to move to Washington where he
plans to write several books, including a memoir. He will stay
active with the group he founded, The Committee of Concerned
Journalists. He will complete a two-year term as ombudsman with
Brill's Content in summer 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Media reporter Mark Jurkowitz of the Globe Staff contributed to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
