<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2573 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-BEAUTY01-COX     09-30 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BEAUTY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suburban angst delivered in superb fashion
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Like a microscope focusing on a toxic
specimen, the camera of ``American Beauty'' swoops down through the
neatly lined trees of a benign suburban street and into the home of
the Burnhams. The gentle motion begins a fasten-your-seat-belts
journey through the armored defenses of a prototypical family, an
organism pulsing with pain and unexpected humor.
</P>
<P>
   With sour sarcasm, Lester Burnham (a bone-weary Kevin Spacey)
narrates the ride, introducing himself, his maniacally driven real
estate agent wife Carolyn (an aptly shrill Annette Bening) and his
acutely insecure teen-age daughter Jane (Thora Birch). Trapped in a
dead-end editorial job and a comatose marriage, 42-year-old Lester
tells us that he will be dead within a year, in a voice at peace
with his imminent demise.
</P>
<P>
   He might as well be dead. Carolyn and Jane both think he is a
loser, and he hasn't the gumption to disagree. But Lester's life is
about to be transformed by the sight of Jane's cheerleader friend
Angela (``American Pie'''s Mena Suvari), a calculating Lolita that
he imagines surrounded by blood red rose petals in one of
first-time director Sam Mendes' several bold fantasy touches.
Lester's life suddenly has meaning, so he quits his job, buys a
sports car and begins pumping iron in anticipation of his conquest
of Angela.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lester's changes are the most obvious, everyone in
``American Beauty'' longs to break out of their unfulfilling
existence. And thanks to Alan Ball's cleverly schematic and
deliciously surprising screenplay _ his first, after toiling in the
formulaic fields of TV's ``Cybill'' _ they each reach out for what
has been missing in their lives. Carolyn, for instance, not only
attains motel intimacy with her Realtor rival (Peter Gallagher),
but finds intermittent inner peace on a pistol range.
</P>
<P>
   If the Burnhams seem normal at a distance, there is no hiding
the aberrance of their new neighbors _ a rigid retired Marine
colonel (Chris Cooper), his catatonic wife (Alison Janney) and
their misfit son, Ricky (Wes Bentley), who sees the world through
the lens of a video camera when he is not selling drugs. Yet there
is a sweetness to Ricky's quickly developed fixation on Jane, a
kindred spirit amid her own parental war zone.
</P>
<P>
   Ball's script, captured with such assurance by Mendes, begins
with an agile balance between the dramatic, the comic and the
horrific. Gradually, it accelerates into bitter melodrama, but even
that feels premeditated and coolly controlled. In its transcendent
final moments, as we reach the burst of violence we've been
promised from the start, ``American Beauty'' brings to mind the
mordancy of another suburban elegy, ``The Ice Storm,'' while still
remaining wholly original.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by cinematographer Conrad L. Hall, Mendes delivers a
vivid, dreamlike visual style. As his theater background
(``Cabaret,'' ``The Blue Room'') suggests, his real strength is
drawing performances from actors. Spacey is commanding, even in his
lethargy, as Everyman Lester, and his climactic encounter with
Angela will make you stop breathing. Birch goes beyond the usual
teen angst and newcomer Bentley projects an understated
self-confidence that is mesmerizing. Only Bening seems to be
working too hard, pushing Carolyn a little closer to caricature
than necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But the flaws are minor compared with the insidious achievements
of this Hollywood studio release that feels, looks and satisfies
like a maverick independent film. With ``American Beauty,'' Mendes
and Ball combine for the most unsettling and impressive double
debut in memory.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
