<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-KINGS01-COX     09-30 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-KINGS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gulf War gets anti-war treatment
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Every major conflict deserves its own
chaotic, surreal anti-war movie, and now Desert Storm has one. In
case your television was in the shop that month, David O. Russell's
gritty, grungy ``Three Kings'' takes us back to early 1991 to
re-create the bedlam of that media war's final days. It is a
stunning film that scratches its head over what that effort to
repel Iraqi aggression was really about.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is one constant in war, it is greed, so Russell
grafts his political cynicism onto a caper tale, as four soldiers
wander off in search of riches once a tenuous cease-fire is
negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie opens, Saddam Hussein's forces have been routed
from Kuwait, and American troops are celebrating the victory, but
there is also a pent-up frustration of never having engaged in
ground combat. With the truce conditions unclear, a soldier
casually asks his pals, ``Are we shooting?'' just before taking aim
and picking off an Iraqi atop a nearby sand mound. If you think
that war is hell, you should see the ravages of peace.
</P>
<P>
   While processing the surrendering enemy _ variously referred to
as ``towel heads'' and ``camel jockeys'' _ a map is found on one of
them. When maverick Special Forces Capt. Archie Gates (a jut-jawed,
gruff George Clooney) recognizes that it indicates the location of
Iraqi-confiscated Kuwaiti gold ingots, he soon commandeers a Humvee
and leads a trio of military misfits on a mercenary mission.
</P>
<P>
   Call it ``Kelly's Heroes'' for the '90s. Their AWOL odyssey for
riches turns into an eye-opening expedition of incongruous sights
and encounters, which brings them no closer to understanding the
war. Assisted by Newton Thomas Sigel's stunning, bleached-out
photography, director Russell creates a sandscape of surreal
visions and actions. From a mine-strewn desert to skeet-shooting
with football bomb targets to underground caches of such Kuwaiti
treasures as luxury cars, cell phones and plastic forks, it rivals
``Catch-22'' or ``Apocalypse Now'' in absurdist imagery.
</P>
<P>
   As Gates and his makeshift squad bully their way through the
locals en route to the gold, it is hard to tell the Iraqis from the
Kuwaitis, and that just might be the point. Certainly, when the
American soldiers start manhandling the people they have just
liberated, the Kuwaitis have difficulty distinguishing between us
and the oppressive Iraqis. Also left twisting in the arid Middle
Eastern wind are the Iraqi rebels who helped rout Hussein, stymied
by our policy of indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the subject matter, ``Three Kings'' has relatively
little overt violence, though that will not be much consolation to
the cow that gets exploded as target practice. And squeamish
moviegoers are not going to care for Russell's two ventures inside
the human body, one to see the organ damage of a bullet and the
other to view an impromptu lung operation.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney inches closer to movie stardom as Gates, but he seems
content to fit into the ensemble next to Ice Cube as a devoutly
religious Detroit baggage handler and Mark Wahlberg as a family man
who gets captured and tortured by the Iraqis. Spike Jonze will
probably get on your nerves as a dense redneck in way over his
head, but Nora Dunn has some amusing screaming fits as a TV
reporter purposely diverted from the final scraps of the news.
</P>
<P>
   Russell has come a long way from the shaggy dog-story farce of
``Flirting With Disaster,'' adding some gravity to his palette
without abandoning the dark humor. There undoubtedly were some
tales of valor from the Gulf War, but you'd never know it from
``Three Kings.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
