<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2580 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-PIANIST-FLANAGAN01-CO     09-30 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANIST-FLANAGAN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flanagan has the key to soul-stirring jazz
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ Tommy Flanagan has been playing at the Village
Vanguard, the steadfast Greenwich Village basement club that still
clings hard to its status as a jazz mecca, since 1956. Year in,
year out. Here in Manhattan, where the Detroit native lives,
Flanagan arrives for his periodic engagements as if signaling the
change in the seasons.
</P>
<P>
   His picture, framed and hung on the wall just behind the piano
bench, occupies the club's own hall of fame, a gallery of jazz
giants that includes Miles and Mingus and John Coltrane. That's
something most mortals will never accomplish, let alone mortals as
low-key as Flanagan.
</P>
<P>
   So the pianist is part of the room's storied past. But on a
recent evening he very much commands its present. There's something
at once avuncular and wonderfully droll about Flanagan, 69, who
will perform Saturday with his trio at Spivey Hall in metro
Atlanta. He's widely, enthusiastically acknowledged as one of the
senior statesmen of the piano _ the consummate sideman who was
essential to Ella Fitzgerald and Sonny Rollins, the man with a
string of sublime trio recordings. But he's also, it turns out,
something of a comedian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just a pianist,'' he begins, in a long aside that
precedes the first tune of the set. ``I'm a jazz poet ... but I'll
let that hang.'' Dressed in a black blazer, black mock turtleneck
and gray slacks that drape generously off the knees, he cuts a
distinguished figure, his silvery goatee and thick-lensed glasses
conspiring with a bald scalp to give him an intellectual cast that
fits well with his deadpan delivery and the elliptical pauses in
his speech. ``I'm not going to say another word tonight,'' he
continues, ``except to tell you what I play if I can remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan is such an alchemist that the joy of his performances
isn't what he plays but the way that he plays it. He's the kind of
bandleader who enjoys musical in-jokes, seemingly trivial
commentaries that begin as a tangent and circle back toward a
clever punch line. Introducing a movie theme as his second number
in a set that touches on Monk, Ellington, Bud Powell, Thad Jones
and George Gershwin, Flanagan can't quite recall its composer.
``Maybe it was one of the Newmans,'' he suggests. ``Lionel or
Albert ... well, we know it's not Randy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sweet in this off-handed way,'' says Karen Bernstein, a
film producer who was introduced to the pianist when he became the
musical consultant on her current project, a documentary on Ella
Fitzgerald. ``He's very soft-spoken. He chooses his words
carefully, beautiful, compact and elegant _ like his piano playing.
He's purposeful.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan squeezed in a few of those words before his show,
huddled in the narrow hallway behind the bar in the compact club.
Here's what he had to say.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've been playing piano for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, I have been playing a long time. Since I've been 5 years
old I've been playing. Come the millennium, I'll be 70, so that's
65 years of playing. So I know my way around a little bit. But you
never know it all. I mean, just ask one of those big boys, you
know, like Horowitz or Rubenstein. They were practicing all their
lives, just trying to get better, and I'm doing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you like in the standards that you decide to play?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, they're the ones that I like and the ones that I think
people like. I make a compromise between them and myself. If I play
my stuff that I like well enough, they'll like it, too. That's what
I hope for.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has your approach to piano evolved over the years?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Oh, well, hardly at all. I still have the quest for being
better. I still like the way a few of my heroes play. Like, you
know, I think Hank Jones and Bud Powell and Teddy Wilson and Nat
Cole and Art Tatum are just the greatest pianists of all time to
me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did you take from the experience of playing with John
Coltrane?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not just John Coltrane. My greatest times were with
Coleman Hawkins and Sonny Rollins. I loved playing with John
Coltrane. He was a big challenge. I caught him right in the middle,
when he was changing his style of playing. I was right in the midst
of that. I enjoyed watching him go through it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've been with your current trio (bassist Kenny Washington
and drummer Lewis Nash) for 10 years. What's the key to their
staying power?
</P>
<P>
   A: All you have to do is listen to the trio. They're very
sympathetic
</P>
<P>
   Tommy
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan Trio
</P>
<P>
   8:15 p.m. Saturday. $25, $35. Spivey Hall, Clayton College &AMP;
State University, 5900 N. Lee St., Morrow. 770-961-3683.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
