<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2581 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-Q7A-GILL-MESSINA01-CO     09-30 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Q7A-GILL-MESSINA01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A conversation with ... Vince Gill and Jo Dee Messina
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What goes around does indeed come around.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth country singer and picker Vince Gill holds an Atlanta
distinction. He was the last musical act to perform at the Omni, in
March 1997, before the wrecking ball arrived. Tonight, he's the
first country act to play the tony venue that took its place,
Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   We caught up with Gill, who last week won a Country Music
Association award for best vocal event of the year (with Patty
Loveless), and opening act Jo Dee Messina, who grabbed the Horizon
Award for best new artist, on the road in Allegan, Mich. They
shared their thoughts about their careers, country music and the
changing concert landscape in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Gill
</P>
<P>
   Q:You closed down the Omni; now you're one of the first acts in
the new Philips Arena. Your thoughts?
</P>
<P>
   A:I really don't know anything about the new place. I loved the
Omni. We played there for years. It was always a great-sounding
arena. I'm kind of sad to see it go. When they built the new arena
in Nashville, I was on the committee to pick the design. And they
built a great arena.
</P>
<P>
   Q:I've read that you are going to take a break after this year.
Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   A:Yeah, I'm kind of wrapping things up. I want to get off the
bus for a while. I haven't ever taken the time to stop in 25 years,
and I feel like it's time to take a little bit of a break. I feel
that personally and professionally, it's the right thing to do.
I've been out there all the time for 10 years. Here's another
single and another single. I think maybe the people could use as
much of a break as I could (laughs). I really don't have a plan.
I'm not the type of individual that has to have a deal. I don't
want to have an alter ego and make an aerobic polka record or
something.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I wonder who you're referring to? Garth Brooks?
</P>
<P>
   A:I don't fault him for doing any of it (the Chris Gaines
project). But it's so foreign to me because I don't possess any of
that thought process.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Your latest album, ``The Key,'' was inspired by the death of
your father. It's very traditional, with a lot of songs that sound
like 1960s Nashville. How did you put it together?
</P>
<P>
   A:What a lot of it was, was me seeing country music walking away
from all those traditional values and feel of those songs. Today,
we basically try to country-up pop songs. We put fiddles and steel
over a Rolling Stones groove and say it's country. At some point,
we've got to look in the mirror and say, ``This is what we are and
what we're doing.'' The bottom line is, we're the ones doing it.
</P>
<P>
   I just missed them, songs that felt like ``The Grand Tour,'' Bob
Wills, Conway Twitty. It's my perception of country music, which is
not necessarily what it is today.
</P>
<P>
   I knew going in I was making a record that went way against the
grain. I thought I was going to do something to get people to
reinvest in the traditional movement, kind of like Randy Travis did
in the '80s. But it did just the opposite. I think it surprised
everybody it was so country from the start to the finish. But I
think it's the best record I ever made.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You recently went through a very public divorce and became the
center of a lot of tabloid gossip linking you with various people.
This is tough to bring up, but on the Internet, there are 53 chat
sites that come up when you type in ``Vince Gill/Amy Grant.''
</P>
<P>
   A:Is that all? (Laughs.) What I think happens with all this is,
people tend to think the worst of people. If anything is offensive
to me, that is. They take the lowest common denominator and go to
that. The ins and outs of friendship are mine. They are not for the
whole world to try to figure out. Whether it's Amy or whoever, I
have a right to be friends with anybody I want to, and I don't have
to defend or deny that. That's been my M.O. all along. I've never
acknowledged the tabloid stuff. None of it. That's the neat thing
about doing an interview. I can either answer the questions or not.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The other big talk on the Internet is about this duet you have
with Barbra Streisand on her new CD.
</P>
<P>
   A:We did a video of it. It's a Richard Marx song, so it's very
adult-contemporary. It was a blast getting to sing with her. She
was nice to me. The biggest fear I had when we did the video was I
was afraid I was going to have to be an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How's life in your 40s?
</P>
<P>
   A:I'm the happiest I've ever been.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Dee Messina
</P>
<P>
   Q:You've had quite a year, with four No. 1 records. How does it
feel to be opening for Vince Gill?
</P>
<P>
   A:He is truly someone that I respect. When he asked me to be
part of the tour, it floored me. The fact that I'm here is very
fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You nearly went bankrupt between ``Heads Carolina, Tails
California'' and the second album.
</P>
<P>
   A:I was really scared and nervous about it. There are no sure
bets in the music business. No one dreamed it would take so long to
find the right material. We basically vanished for a year. It
wasn't intentional, but the entire team felt we didn't have the
material. We had ``Bye Bye'' cut. We had ``I'm Alright'' cut. The
first album was experimental _ country, rock, blues. This one just
flows from the beginning to the end.
</P>
<P>
   Q:To me, ``Stand Beside Me'' really defines your sound and image
_ kind of the tough, independent working gal.
</P>
<P>
   A:There's a great story about that song. Faith Hill was going to
record it, but when she came down to do it, she said, ``This song
is a Jo Dee tune. Why don't you see if she wants this?'' I knew I
loved that song the first time I heard it _ the simplicity of the
intro, the verse, how it builds up and gets huge. The song ended up
doing well, and I owe that to Faith Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Faith's husband, Tim McGraw, is your producer. How has he
helped shape your sound?
</P>
<P>
   A:He's very, very influential. What I owe Tim I couldn't
possibly put into words, his compassion, his understanding. There
was a song for this album that I wasn't excited about. He said,
``If she's not excited, then don't let her cut it. She has to sing
it every single night for the rest of her life.'' He goes to bat
for me that way. It's a great chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Were you shocked to find yourself nominated for both best
female vocalist and the Horizon Award at this year's Country Music
Association Awards?
</P>
<P>
   A:It was very much a shock. I never dreamed I'd be in the female
vocalist category.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What did you think when you saw yourself on the fashion pages
of People magazine?
</P>
<P>
   A:It floored me. I ran to Wal-Mart and bought a copy
immediately. It's wild. At the time, I didn't know anything about
fashion. I had to read up on it, study to find out who is Donna
Karan, Anna Sui, Ralph Lauren. You sit around with a bunch of
stylists who say, ``We have a Richard Tyler-type dress.'' And I was
like, ``What does that mean?'' That's a world I don't live in. I
hate to shop. I order out of catalogs or go to Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You were raised in Boston, but you sound so very country. How
come?
</P>
<P>
   A:I was raised outside Boston in a very small town. We had to
drive 40 minutes to the closest McDonald's. I loved that. My dad
had all of Tammy Wynette's records, and I listened to them. What
really got me, though, was when I saw ``Coal Miner's Daughter.'' I
saw it over and over again. I can recite the whole movie for you
word by word. I loved the image, the realism of the songs, the
wholesome family roots down home.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Are you getting recognized on the street more now?
</P>
<P>
   A:Yeah, but it's still surprising. I didn't know people even
knew I existed. To think that people like you is a nice thing, a
very warm feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Gill,
</P>
<P>
   Jo Dee
</P>
<P>
   Messina
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight. $28 and $38. Philips Arena, 1 Philips Drive N.W.
404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
