<HEADER>
A2582 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN-COALITION-BO     09-30 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-COALITION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAKENED CHRISTIAN COALITION STILL DRAWS POLITICAL HOPEFULS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Christian Coalition opens its ``Road to
Victory'' convention with presidential candidates Friday, the
organization will once again put forward its message that a
Republican can't win the White House without focusing on
conservative issues such as opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign so far is hardly what the coalition intended.
Some candidates who adhere closely to the coalition line have
dropped out of the race, while several of the remaining top
candidates have assiduously played down abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition is striving to emerge from a near-death experience
during the past year. The organization is in debt, claims only 15
to 20 active state operations, and saw a number of top officials
leave the group. The coalition is run by founder Pat Robertson, who
recently donated $1 million to keep it afloat financially. A widely
discussed plan to create a political action committee that can
donate money to candidates is on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are in deep trouble,'' said Larry Sabato, a University of
Virginia professor who has watched the coalition for years. ``They
have gone from being at the peak of Mount Everest to being at about
the level of the Dead Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the religious conservatives who make up the bulk of the
coalition say they have the political power to have an impact on
the GOP race, especially in early states such as Iowa, South
Carolina, Virginia, and Michigan. Seven of the eight Republican
candidates are coming to court votes. Senator John McCain of
Arizona declined the invitation to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the coalition returns to financial and political health
in the coming months, its members appear deeply divided over the
candidates. Unless the coalition rallies around one candidate, its
influence might be too diffused during the primaries, although the
organization is likely to be a factor in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for the social conservative movement is to
become a little bit more politically astute and rally behind one
candidate,'' coalition spokesman Mike Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what appears to be a groundswell for George W. Bush
among Republicans, the Texas governor is still viewed suspiciously
by many social conservatives, as was his father in the 1988 and
1992 campaigns. While the younger Bush opposes abortion, he rarely
brings up the subject in speeches and has made clear it isn't a top
priority.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has focused recently on courting social conservatives,
suggesting that faith-based groups be allowed to run government
social programs. In addition, Bush has suggested that failing
schools could lose federal funds, which then could be used at
private institutions in states that allow such a transfer. And Bush
has met privately with Robertson and hired the former Christian
Coalition executive director, Ralph Reed, as a top adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Governor Bush has got a real strong affinity with the
conservative grass roots of the party,'' Reed said in an interview.
``He is a person who has a profound faith testimony himself. He
talks about how his faith in God changed his life, and that is a
message that resonates very powerfully with this constituency.''
</P>
<P>
   While there has been no obvious sign of a rush by coalition
members to the Bush camp, the Texas governor has been helped by the
fact that coalition members haven't rallied around his opponents,
either.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican candidates most closely associated with the
coalition have stumbled. On Monday, for example, former Vice
President Dan Quayle, who was counting on strong support from
coalition members, dropped out of the race due to a lack of funds.
Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire has dropped out of the GOP field
to launch an independent bid. And another coalition favorite,
Patrick J. Buchanan, is on the verge of leaving the Republican
Party to seek the nomination of the Reform Party, whose
economic-centered platform purposely excludes any mention of
abortion or other social issues.
</P>
<P>
   All the Republican candidates oppose abortion. But a number of
the leading prospects have played down the significance of the
issue. In addition to Bush's rare mention of the issue, former
American Red Cross president Elizabeth Dole has said she doesn't
want to be drawn into the ``dead-end debate'' on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is unpopular with the coalition because his original
campaign finance bill would have required the disclosure of donors
who contribute to political ads that run in the late stages of a
campaign. Although that provision has been stripped from the latest
version of McCain's bill, many coalition members believe the
senator intends to restrict their voice in politics.
</P>
<P>
   That has left four other Republican candidates who strongly
oppose abortion to fight for coalition support: former Reagan aide
Gary Bauer, publisher Steve Forbes, Senator Orrin Hatch of Utah,
and talk show host Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest fight is between Bauer and Forbes, who have become
bitter enemies this year in their effort to become the favorite of
social conservatives. On Wednesday, Bauer held an extraordinary
news conference to deny rumors he was having an affair with a
campaign aide and implied the stories were being spread by Forbes'
campaign. Forbes denied that his staff had anything to do with the
rumors.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Forbes has gone to great lengths to portray himself
as a champion of the coalition's causes _ a turnabout from his 1996
campaign. Forbes once called Robertson a ``toothy flake'' and said
in 1996 that he would work mostly to stop late-term abortions. But
after losing that campaign, Forbes has switched strategies, calling
himself ``pro-life'' and hiring many former Christian Coalition
officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2583 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS01-COX     09-30 2062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Biographer' breathes life into Reagan
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 3.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a book a dozen years ago, Garry Wills traced the stamp of
American character on the lives of six presidents, from Washington,
Jefferson and Madison to Kennedy, Nixon and Ronald Reagan. For
Wills, that character had evolved by a kind of natural selection,
our presidents arising as embodiments of the myth and mettle that
sustain us. Evolution had taken us, somehow, from the founders to
Nixon and Reagan, and along the way made a monkey out of Charles
Darwin.
</P>
<P>
   We never quite know what to make of a sitting president. Harry
Truman was something of an embarrassment, a Kansas City rube who
had never been to college, and Dwight Eisenhower an inarticulate
mumbler for whom a press conference was a more formidable
undertaking than the invasion of Normandy. And not even President
Clinton has been lampooned like Lincoln. ``The baboon,'' the
newspapers called him, and sophisticated folk chortled heartily.
</P>
<P>
   They were all sly as foxes, knowing more than they had need to
reveal and happy to play dumb for their inquisitors. The modern
master of the art form was Ronald Reagan, who may really have been
dumb but whose stature posthumously is not shrinking in the way
Jack Kennedy's is.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan no sooner left office than he lost his mind, sealing off
the world and questions with it.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Morris spent 15 years in Reagan's periodic company, and
there are people who wonder if his own faculties aren't a few
marbles short. The book for which Morris signed a $3 million
contract in 1985 has appeared at last, handsomely swaddled in its
dust jacket. But the birthing room, rather than being aglow with
joy, is edgy with concern.
</P>
<P>
   What was to have been a court biography penned by a much-admired
Pulitzer Prize winner suddenly is the subject of debate about
Morris' honesty and forthrightness. The protagonist of ``Dutch: A
Memoir of Ronald Reagan'' is alternately the 40th president and a
fictional Edmund Morris, one who was not alive when he appears in
large portions of the book. Hence the word ``memoir,'' not
``biography,'' in the subtitle.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is fooled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is the authorized biography of Ronald Reagan,'' Leon
Wieseltier, literary editor of The New Republic told The New York
Times, ``I think I'll wait for the unauthorized biography.''
</P>
<P>
   Times columnist Maureen Dowd _ happy, you'd think, to find
something to write about other than the Clintons and their various
dysfunctions _ leaped on it like a hound thrown a sirloin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Morris' batty book is surely destined for commercial
success,'' she writes. ``There's a lot of nostalgia for Reagan and
Reaganism. And we have become a culture of morphing. Entertainment
has overwhelmed truth, and the universities are riddled with
professors who deny that objectivity is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right about some of that, of course. The aesthetic of
postmodernism reduces factuality to the perception of the observer,
with consequences that have made sophistry respectable and nihilism
fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   But the literary device of an author's inserting himself into
the story is not original with Morris. The first modern biography,
Boswell's ``Life of Johnson,'' is in fact a highly personal account
of a worshipful young Scot's brief time with the literary dictator
of the age. Samuel Johnson was already in his 50s by the time
Boswell met him, and Boswell knew little of the childhood
insecurities that marked Johnson for life. Yet Boswell caught
vividly the essential truth about the man _ not simply his
omnivorous curiosity but an outsize character and unforgettable
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of fact and fiction braided (faction?) spring
readily to mind: Truman Capote's ``In Cold Blood''; Gore Vidal's
``Lincoln''; John Berendt's ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and
Evil''; Norman Mailer's ``The Executioner's Song.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is always the sterling example of Bob Woodward,
confidant to dying spymasters, eavesdropper in the chambers of
Supreme Court justices, recorder of pillow talk between a president
and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence is one thing and assertion another, and the argument
for veracity need hardly be made. But it's surprising, even so, to
read that Professor Alan Brinkley of Columbia University had never
heard of fictional devices in biography. ``This is a very
particular genre,'' he told the Times, ``and it has a long
tradition and a very narrow and restricted set of conventions.''
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, biography is the one genre where the
unconventional is now and then granted a certain license. What
Morris has done, says Hayden White, a professor of comparative
literature at Stanford University, ``is no different from the
practice of those biographers who purport to see the world from the
perspective of their subjects: from inside the mind, spirit or body
of the historical personages whose `lives' they purport to
understand better than those personages themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The biographer's first obligation _ implicit in the word
``biography'' _ is to create a life. Not to invent a life the
subject did not live, but to convey convincingly what T.S. Eliot
called skull beneath the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Research might yield footnotes, piled into the back of the book
in a great slag heap. But the spirit of the life being re-created _
its aspirations and insecurities, its quirks and lasting obsessions
_ too easily slips away. And many a subject has preferred it so,
burning letters and private papers and enjoining family and friends
from cooperating with prospective biographers.
</P>
<P>
   The biographer's art, therefore, is an imaginative and intuitive
one. Ideally, as Marc Pachter, former historian of the National
Portrait Gallery, wrote in ``Telling Lives,'' the biographer
``vanishes into the shadow of his creative achievement.'' But not
always. If the biographer is there, ``he is only there in a certain
way, which is difficult to define. The greater his skill, the finer
his intuition of personality, the less aware we are of him in our
experience of the narrated life.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, exceptions exist, and Morris' book is one.
</P>
<P>
   When Morris signed on to write Reagan's biography, Random House
projected publishing the book in 1992. Seven years passed, and
Morris was nowhere close to presenting a manuscript. He had had
frequent access to the president while Reagan was in office, was
allowed to attend White House meetings, had the opportunity to
visit the places Reagan had been, from his Illinois hometown to
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Theodore Roosevelt _ Morris' previous subject _
Reagan ``was a man of benign remoteness,'' unfailingly, unflappably
cordial yet without a sense of his own past. He could joke more
than he could reflect.
</P>
<P>
   Morris at different points in the book wonders if the man is an
amiable simpleton or someone whose hidden depths he cannot plumb.
His ambivalence is resolved in an interview to be published in the
November-December issue of American Enterprise magazine, where he
claims that Reagan was a man ``of considerably more deliberation
and philosophical seriousness than he's ever been given credit
for.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is little hint of this in ``Dutch.'' The Reagan whom
Morris knew was not given to introspection and had no capacity for
self-analysis, and now he was sinking into senescence. Ever more
desperate as deadline after deadline passed, Morris came to a
realization: He must create dramatis personae for himself and
others, and they _ but mainly he _ would inhabit the world the
Dutch lived but not could not recollect.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the charge of deception. But the Ronald Reagan who
bestrides these pages is believably the Dutch Reagan who had been a
lifeguard while growing up in Illinois, who began his radio career
the year Franklin Roosevelt made his final fireside chat, who
squired starlets at the behest of studio moguls and who saw his own
star power fade in middle age.
</P>
<P>
   The narrative risks that Morris undertook are large, and some
would say foolhardy. But the panache with which he has brought
``Dutch'' off is breathtaking. No one reading the book can doubt he
is in Reagan's benignly remote company. Morris has a gift for acute
observation, and nails Reagan's every mannerism _ the husk of the
voice (``breathing around words''), the tilt of the head, the lie
of the hair (``thick and shining as an otter's'') _ and every
reflexive response.
</P>
<P>
   With word pictures he also captures the mood of White House
courtiers who found themselves in trouble. One day in early 1993,
Reagan returned to the White House, ``at the reluctant invitation
of President Bush,'' to receive the Medal of Freedom. Morris
attended, along with 500 others. ``Even (former Treasury Secretary)
Don Regan and (military adviser) John Poindexter showed up,'' he
writes. ``The latter had the gray transparency of someone sucked
dry by legal process, as did (former Defense Secretary) Cap
Weinberger.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1994, a month after Reagan disclosed to the American
people that doctors had told him he was suffering from degenerative
cognitive dementia, Morris visited him in his office in California:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I entered his office, he was sitting in the same quiet
pose he always assumed during `personal time' at the White House:
glossy head tilted forward, jacket sleeves half on his desk, white
cuffs protruding exactly one inch, his black Parker lying ready on
its own polished leather reflection. He rose with his usual air of
gentle surprise, but I got the feeling that if I had come in
through the window he would have reacted no differently.''
</P>
<P>
   They made small talk, and Reagan wanted to show Morris a
painting someone had given him. Morris thought it would be a
portrait of the five living presidents together, something he knew
Reagan was proud of. Instead it was a watercolor of a scene at the
banks of the Rush River near Tampico, Ill., where he had pulled so
many bobbing heads from the water long ago. Morris had been there:
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognized every curve of the oak trees and the long grassy
slope of the meadow.
</P>
<P>
   ```This,' Dutch breathed, ``is where I was a lifeguard ... I
saved 77 lives. And you know, none of 'em ever thanked me!'
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his only unhesitant speech during our short interview,
a confidence exchanged between strangers. He had long since stopped
recognizing me; now I no longer recognized him. For all the
intimate familiarity of that face and body, and the soft husk of
his voice, I did not feel his presence beside me, only his
absence.''
</P>
<P>
   But what, finally, had been behind that enigmatic presence? A
man practiced at responding on cue, yet not always recognizing a
face in front of him (even, one time, his own son's). A man with no
particular interest in other people, but also without malice. A
responsible, if disengaged, father. A man whose only loves seemed
to have been his wife, Nancy, and his country.
</P>
<P>
   None of his four children would graduate from college and none,
apparently, would provide him with descendants. (Adopted son
Michael has two children, and daughter Maureen has adopted a
child.) ``Whether these derelictions caused him the slightest
regret,'' Morris writes, ``is one of the imponderables buried in
the alabaster depths of Ronald Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   And now those depths are beyond mortal reach. Was he impaired
while in office? Morris, reading eight years of graceful,
grammatically correct but unrevelatory diaries, is certain he was
not.
</P>
<P>
   Did he know _ contrary to his protestations _ about the
Iran-Contra affair? Morris thinks it likely that Reagan approved
the diversion of funds. Whether he understood their use is another
imponderable, like the man himself.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier biographer, the journalist Lou Cannon, called Reagan
``a mirror of the American people.'' For eight years a sizable
majority of Americans, younger ones included, identified with him.
There is something incalculable in this that neither opinion polls
nor daily journalism can measure. Neither, for that matter, can
biography. It tries only to bring into focus the figure in the
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan
</P>
<P>
   By Edmund Morris. Random House. $35. 864 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
