<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2584 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TURNER-SOUTH01-COX     09-30 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-SOUTH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner's latest TV a bow to the South
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ted Turner is going to be a daddy again.
</P>
<P>
   When Turner South flickers to life at 2 p.m. today, the newest
Turner-Time Warner venture will offer cable subscribers in six
states a mix of original series, movies, ``classic'' wrestling,
regional news reports and the Braves, the Hawks and the Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   The quirky, white-haired billionaire will formally introduce his
18th network, the fourth bearing his name, this afternoon in a
five-minute, pre-taped message also featuring country singer Marty
Stuart and horror novelist Anne Rice, to air in Georgia, Alabama,
Mississippi, South Carolina, Tennessee and parts of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling 24-hour network initially will be available to
roughly a million households in its coverage area _ over half of
which will be in metro Atlanta, through MediaOne, Prestige and Time
Warner Cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're offering viewers and advertisers is something
that's never really been done before; television with a Southern
flair,'' said Bill Burke, president of Turner South, who will be
leaving to head Time Warner's Internet and digital ventures just
days after the launch. TNT and TCM President Brad Siegel will
succeed Burke at the helm of Turner South and TBS. ``We see this as
an opportunity to celebrate everything about the South's unique
culture, and the people who live here,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course not everyone is as impressed by the bouncing baby
network's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Ginsberg, a media analyst for BBDO South, has been keeping
tabs on the rollout. He views this latest gambit as a
characteristically shrewd move that will likely lure smaller
advertisers who can't afford to buy time on higher-priced national
networks.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``the viewers don't really get anything out of
this. From watching it you probably wouldn't know if it was
regional or local, and I don't know if anybody will really care.
What you have to remember about Turner and Time Warner is that they
have deep pockets and, most importantly, staying power.''
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Turner South is the first-ever truly regional
entertainment network in the country, but it's following in the
well-worn footsteps of other successful Turner upstarts such as
Turner Classic Movies and the Cartoon Network.
</P>
<P>
   Freshening up in the vault
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to build a network around a full slate of
original shows, the bulk of Turner South's programs will be culled
from the company's massive library of film and video properties
that are being repackaged and freshened up for a younger viewers
and insatiably nostalgic baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   It will also include a certain amount of synergy between other
Turner/Time Warner owned ventures such as WCW and Southern Living.
</P>
<P>
   ``World Championship Wrestling Classics,'' for instance, will
feature bouts dating back 20 years, long before Jesse ``The Body''
Ventura was running the state of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wrestling before wrestling was cool without all the
glitz and glamour you have today,'' said David Rudolph, Turner
South's director of business development. ``Of course, we're not
going to air this on the same nights as our other live wrestling
shows. We'll put it on nights when people who love wrestling want
to supplement their viewing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Southern Living Presents'' will take the contents of the
glossy lifestyle magazine and spin them off on the air. Just like
its big sister TBS which was created 25 years ago as a vehicle for
the once-hapless Atlanta Braves, sports will also be a staple for
Turner South. And yes, at least one of the teams in every game will
be on the Turner payroll.
</P>
<P>
   After gestating for more than a year in Turner Broadcasting
headquarters on Techwood Drive, the delivery of Turner South wasn't
without some bumps.
</P>
<P>
   New kid on sports block
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports South _ a regional sports-only network which had a
``no compete'' agreement with Turner _ lost a court battle that
otherwise might have have kept Turner South from launching on
schedule, if at all. A district court judge ruled that because
Turner South's programming is more entertainment-oriented, it did
not pose a direct threat to the Fox network. The ruling is being
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Turner South will telecast 46 Atlanta Thrashers
hockey games this season, 15 Hawks matchups starting Nov. 6 and 35
Braves games next season which otherwise would have aired on WUPA.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South's wrestling and sports programs will likely
convince men to tune in, but Rudolph says women are not being
forsaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our stated demographic is adults 25-to-54-year-olds across the
board,'' he said. ``But there are other programs like `Southern
Living' that will focus on food, travel, home decorating and
gardening that we think will have a very strong female skew.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other niche cable networks vying for attention, one of
Turner South's biggest challenges is establishing itself as a
distinctive brand that entices viewers to put away their clickers
and set a spell.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put: What the heck is a Southern network and who wants to
watch one anyway?
</P>
<P>
   In a ``Tonight Show'' monologue after Turner South was announced
in February, host Jay Leno answered that question by trading on
some unflattering Southern stereotypes. Leno jokingly suggested the
network's lineup might include shows such as ``Everybody Loves
Raymond, Including His Sister,'' and ``Sabrina, the Teenage
Mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Few were laughing at Turner South, at least not for long.
However Leno's off-color jibes underscored the task of overcoming
built-in perceptions that the new network would be little more than
a second-rate, cable backwater _ Bubbavision.
</P>
<P>
   What programmers and marketers have devised in some ways are
refreshingly clever. Others are downright corny.
</P>
<P>
   Themes with a twang
</P>
<P>
   The network will feature regular movie franchises with evocative
themes such as ``True Grits'' and ``Kudzu Theater'' (the tagline:
``Movies That Grow on You'').
</P>
<P>
   But only a handful of the second- and third-run movies appearing
in those time slots will have any discernible Southern connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wrong to imply that Southerners will only watch a
movie if the guy in the lead has a Southern accent,'' Burke said.
``What we're doing is packaging these movies in a way that feels
appropriate for the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner South hopes to convey that down-homey feeling for viewers
in other ways as well.
</P>
<P>
   During interstitials _ breezy informational segments between
scheduled programs _ the network's catchy black-and-Granny-Smith
green logo will alert viewers to festivals, fairs and community
happenings.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South will also feature bluesy banjo riffs and moody
vocals instead of jarring, whiz-bang sound effects that have became
standard issue on other networks.
</P>
<P>
   If the bulk of Turner South's programming invites viewers to
slow down a bit, Burke said other network offerings aim to capture
the quickened pace of life in Sun Belt capitals such as Atlanta and
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Whole World Theater Comedy Improv'' features an
unpredictable Atlanta-based troupe of comics, and the
still-evolving ``College Show'' will give a generation of TV-savvy
coeds at Southern campuses a chance to create their own programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only regret is that I won't be around to see Turner South
through after flipping the switch,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
