<HEADER>
A2585 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MILAN-SHOWS01-COX     09-30 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-SHOWS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jil Sander a breath of fresh air for buyers
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN _ Sometimes the best critics of a designer's collection
are the people who buy from it at wholesale, and then try selling
the clothes to us at twice that price.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Kalinsky, who owns the Jil Sander boutique at Phipps
Plaza, and Kal Ruttenstein, the venerable buyer for Bloomingdale's,
had different agendas entering Sander's spring/summer 2000 runway
preview Thursday, and different reasons for praising it afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Kalinsky was there to select clothes for his ``ladies,'' who
shell out thousands of dollars per Sander outfit. Ruttenstein's job
was to pick out those pieces that would sell well among the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ethereal, simple and beautiful,'' Kalinsky said of the
collection, which was bursting with bright white skirts, dresses
and tops that were at once boxy and form-flattering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was lovely,'' Ruttenstein said. ``I especially
liked the washed-out Hawaiian prints.''
</P>
<P>
   Sander's fabrics were just on the modest side of sheer; for sex
appeal's sake she laid bare the back and the rib cage. She hemmed
skirts and dresses at the knee and offered a slinky new beltless
shorts silhouette that stopped at mid-thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved the new shorts,'' Kalinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 35 outfits shown were solid-colored: white, black or
butterscotch. But a handful featured blue, pink and yellow floral
fabrics turned inside-out for a sun-bleached effect.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike virtually every other designer here, who have gone
overboard with ruffles and beadwork, Sander's main decorative
features were wide, flat pleats (both vertical and horizontal) and
three-ply folds of fabric that encircled the torso.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the eveningwear idea of nail heads on chiffon,''
Ruttenstein said. ``It looked very young and fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jil's clothes never look like what you see at other shows,''
Kalinsky said. ``That's what I like about her; she marches to her
own drumbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bare Market: Just how much sass, sex, glitz and garishness
will the market bear come spring? That's the question Dolce &AMP;
Gabbana pondered when they turned their showroom into an old
Italian street market setting _ replete with fishmongers, gypsies
and greengrocers _ and dressed their models in the most outlandish
and outstandingly creative ensembles seen so far during Milan's
Fashion Week. The combinations of materials, colorations, styles
and embellishments are (truly) too numerous to list. But highlights
of this raucously received collection include: the season's most
intriguing suits (mannish, three-piece numbers in black, gray or
sequins with skinny lapels and high-collared shirts and wallets on
chains); eight-inch skirts rendered in everything from patent
leather to stars-and-stripes sequins; bugle-beaded boots that
actress Salma Hayek said ``looked liked wearing Christmas on your
feet''; and beaded bras worn underneath silk chiffon blouses _ or
nothing but matching chokers _ during the show's grand finale. The
designers foisted mad combinations of styles out onto the runway
like braggarts flaunting their craftsmanship. And no one could
blame them. ``I'd put some of the outfits together a little
differently,'' Hayek confided, ``but otherwise I loved it all.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
