<HEADER>
A2587 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-JAPAN-URANIUM-EXPLAIN     09-30 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-URANIUM-EXPLAIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST URANIUM DISASTER MAY BE WORSE THAN THREE MILE ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The deadly accident at a Japanese uranium processing plant
Thursday can't compare with the disastrous explosion at the
Chernobyl nuclear reactor in 1986, but it's probably more serious
than the 1979 meltdown at Three Mile Island that crippled the US
nuclear industry.
</P>
<P>
   And a similar accident once happened in this country.
</P>
<P>
   That's the early consensus among authorities on nuclear power as
Japanese emergency officials struggled to contain the country's
worst nuclear power accident ever, and President Clinton offered to
do ``whatever we possibly can'' to help the people affected by the
accident 70 miles northeast of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious nuclear accident,'' said US Energy Secretary
William Richardson, who was touring nuclear facilities in Russia.
``The good news is that it's not a widely contaminated area. It's a
limited area.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident, which exposed at least two workers to potentially
lethal radiation and forced people within six miles to remain
indoors, happened when workers at the JCO Company in Tokaimura
inadvertently set off a powerful nuclear reaction while making fuel
for commercial nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   A nuclear reaction, the key ingredient for generating nuclear
power, occurs when a high concentration of radioactive elements is
brought together, causing atoms to begin splitting spontaneously,
releasing vast amounts of heat. But, unlike a nuclear reactor that
is sheathed in steel and concrete to contain the reaction when it
``goes critical,'' a nuclear processing plant has no similar
protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuclear reactors are designed to go critical. Fuel processing
facilities are never intended to go critical,'' said Dr. John
Bernard, acting director of the nuclear lab at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology in Cambridge, Mass. ``There was a human
error where they miscalculated the amount of uranium.''
</P>
<P>
   The three most seriously injured workers at JCO were purifying
the uranium fuel in a bath of nitric acid when they suddenly saw a
blue flash, company officials said, and they were instantly exposed
to radiation levels high enough to induce vomiting and diarrhea.
Plant officials believe they accidentally put up to 35 pounds of
uranium into the tank, far more than the normal limit of eight
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday, radiation levels in the densely populated
surrounding areas were thousands of times the normal level and the
Japanese government had called on 310,000 people living within six
miles to remain indoors until emergency workers can stop the
continuing nuclear reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities planned to smother the accident in sodium borate, a
chemical used to stop nuclear reactions in nuclear plants by
absorbing the colliding neutrons that keep the chain reaction
going. But they were trying to figure out how to get close enough
to dump the powder onto the radioactive tank, company official
Kohgo Usami said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the accident is still unfolding, both MIT's Bernard and
nuclear engineer David Lochbaum of the Union of Concerned
Scientists said the Tokaimura accident isn't nearly as big as the
Chernobyl accident in the former Soviet Union, where 31 people were
killed immediately and thousands more may have died from radiation
exposure in the years since.
</P>
<P>
   At Chernobyl, they point out, the 190-ton nuclear core exploded,
spewing detectable radiation for thousands of miles. At Tokaimura,
by contrast, the effects are likely to be less farflung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that it will be a long-term problem,'' said
Lochbaum. ``This appears to be a local disaster and not a global
one.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bernard of MIT said the Tokaimura accident
has already done more harm than the partial meltdown at the Three
Mile Island nuclear plant in Pennsylvania. There, he said, ``people
were scared, but no one was harmed physically'' in what is still
regarded as the worst US commercial nuclear accident.
</P>
<P>
   Some, such as Lochbaum, believe that people died from long term
exposure at Three Mile Island. But Lochbaum agrees that no one at
Three Mile Island got such high immediate radiation doses as the
three workers who are in critical condition in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the US Nuclear Regulatory Commission were quick to
point out that the seven nuclear fuel processing plants in the
United States follow strict safety procedures to prevent nuclear
reactions by limiting the volume and concentration of uranium
workers handle, and requiring other safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We routinely inspect these plants for criticality control,''
said NRC spokesman Beth Hayden.
</P>
<P>
   However, a ``criticality incident'' quite similar to the
Tokaimura accident has happened at one US commercial processing
facility, the long-closed United Nuclear Corporation plant in
Charlestown, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1964 employee Robert Peabody accidentally set off a
nuclear chain reaction when he poured liquid uranium into a tank.
He died after being exposed to 1,000 times the lethal dose of
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   ``These incidents were very similar,'' said Felix Killar,
director of material licensee and insurance issues for the Nuclear
Energy Institute, a US industry trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Early reports on the Japanese accident suggested that the
Tokaimura plant did not have the safety features of American
plants, and that the nuclear facilities in Tokaimura have had
safety problems in recent years, including a fire that exposed 37
workers to low-level radiation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lochbaum of the Union of Concerned Scientists said it
is too soon to say whether the Japanese accident is relevant to the
US fabrication plants located in Virginia, Missouri, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the keystone cops over there. those are highly
dedicated people,'' said Lochbaum. ``For us to say it can't happen
here so quickly without even understanding what happened, to me is
an irresponsible attitude.''
</P>
</TEXT>
