<HEADER>
A2588 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-EYMAN-COLUMN01-     09-30 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EYMAN-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Who will take the place of our older readers?
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Booksellers and publishers struggling to
stay alive have a new study that explains why they're struggling to
stay alive. The study informs us that people ages 55 to 64 read for
53 minutes a day compared to those in the 25 to 29 bracket, who
read for only 24 minutes a day.
</P>
<P>
   While it might be logical to focus on that portion of the market
that reads more, that would also mean having to constantly
replenish the said market, which is in the process of dying off.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom has always suggested that younger people who
don't read will read more as they age. I don't buy it. Reading is a
habit, not something that comes to you as a Pauline conversion as
you sit in the doctor's office waiting for your cholesterol
results.
</P>
<P>
   UPCOMING ...
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Berg, who has a way of writing biographies that render
other books on his subject irrelevant, has chosen his next subject:
Woodrow Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   It's a puzzlement, although it continues Berg's affinity for
furtive, essentially hidden personalities. Wilson's is a great
story, but one that has been written a dozen times. Barring a cache
of new papers, one wonders what Berg can bring to such a well-known
story beyond his own penetrating lucidity.
</P>
<P>
   As with his Pulitzer Prize-winning ``Lindbergh,'' Putnam will
publish, many years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Amis, who writes good books that get good reviews but
that nobody ever seems to buy, has signed with Talk Miramax, the
Tina Brown/Weinstein brothers/Disney imprint. Amis' deal
encompasses three books, a screenplay and contributions to Talk
magazine. One of the books will be a memoir involving Amis' late
father, Kingsley.
</P>
<P>
   SOCCER MAMAS ...
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins will be publishing ``The Girls of Summer,'' a
serious book by New York Times sportswriter Jere Longman about the
U.S. women's soccer team. The book will be out next summer, in time
for the Olympics, where the team will be competing.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS I DON'T EVEN WANT
</P>
<P>
   TO THINK ABOUT, LET ALONE READ ...
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Carol Oates is writing ``Blonde,'' a novel about Marilyn
Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE ...
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three reasons for becoming a writer. The first is
that you need the money; the second, that you have something to say
that you think the world should know; the third is that you can't
think of what to do with the long winter evenings.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
