<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2594 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ARMS-TREATY-775&AMP;ADD-N     09-30 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMS-TREATY-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT OFFERS TO HOLD HEARINGS ON NUCLEAR TEST BAN TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an abrupt but calculated reversal, Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott offered Thursday to schedule a quick
vote on a treaty banning nuclear testing, expressing confidence
that Republicans have the votes to defeat one of President
Clinton's top foreign policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   For months, Senate Democrats and the administration have
demanded that Lott and his top lieutenants drop their opposition to
the treaty and allow hearings and a floor vote this year. Democrats
threatened this month to tie the Senate in procedural knots if
Republicans refused to relent.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Lott called the Democrats' bluff, offering 10 hours of
debate and a vote on the pact as early as next Wednesday. It takes
the approval of two-thirds of the Senate, or 67 votes if all 100
senators are present, to ratify a treaty. All 45 Democrats are
likely to back the accord, aides said, but only two Republicans
publicly support it, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and James
Jeffords of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   In a spirited exchange on the Senate floor Thursday, Sen. Tom
Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader, objected to Lott's
offer, saying it gave short shrift to a landmark pact. Daschle
requested more time for debate and a later date for the vote. Aides
to both leaders met late Thursday to discuss a compromise, which
Lott said was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Given the alternative of having the Republican-controlled Senate
keep the pact bottled up indefinitely, treaty supporters said they
were willing to take their chances with a vote this fall, even
though they face steep odds of winning ratification.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the best way to deal with this, but it's better
than nothing,'' Sen. Joe Biden of Delaware, the ranking Democrat on
the Foreign Relations Committee, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Biden urged the White House to ``pull out all the stops'' to
lobby for the accord, including having Clinton hold a news
conference and a nationally televised address. A spokesman for the
National Security Council, David C. Leavy, said, ``The president is
fully committed to the treaty. We hope there can be adequate time
for debate and analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, the White House chief of staff, and Sandy Berger,
Clinton's national security adviser, were discussing strategy
Thursday with Senate Democrats, and Leavy said the White House
would hold several public events to rally support.
</P>
<P>
   Treaty proponents argue that it would lock in American nuclear
superiority achieved in more than 1,000 nuclear tests between 1945
and 1992, when the United States agreed to halt testing. Failure to
ratify, supporters say, could open the door for emerging nuclear
states like India and Pakistan, to conduct more tests, and may also
weaken support for other arms pacts, like the treaty to prevent the
spread of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The current and four former chairmen of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff support the test ban, which would prohibit underground
nuclear tests. Atmospheric testing is already banned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This country has a moral responsibility in the world to lead
on the question of the nonproliferation of nuclear weapons,''
Dorgan said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the pact say that a test ban would eliminate the
country's ability to test the safety and reliability of its nuclear
arsenal. Moreover, opponents say, the pact is unlikely to take
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Only 23 of the 44 nations whose approval is required for the
treaty to take effect have ratified the pact. Even one holdout
among the 44 so-called nuclear-capable countries, like North Korea,
could prevent the treaty's enactment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This treaty is bad, bad for the country and dangerous, but if
there is demand that we go forward with it, as I have been hearing
for two years, we are ready to go,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed the treaty in 1996, making the United States the
first signatory, and sent it to the Senate for approval a year
later. Since then, the treaty had been stalled in the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, whose chairman, Sen. Jesse Helms of
North Carolina, is locked in a fight with the administration over
two other treaties Helms wanted to kill before addressing the test
ban pact.
</P>
<P>
   Since Helms has refused to hold hearings on the treaty, the
Senate is poised to vote for the first time on a major treaty
without a hearing in its committee of jurisdiction, aides said.
However, the treaty has been discussed in Foreign Relations
Committee hearings on other subjects and in the hearings of other
panels.
</P>
<P>
   With an international conference in Vienna on Oct. 6 set to
discuss ways to bring the treaty into force, Senate Democrats like
Biden and Dorgan stepped up their threats of guerrilla tactics if
the treaty did not move. Lott's offer is pegged to that date.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, Senate critics quietly lined up a stable
of national security experts who opposed the treaty to advise
Senate Republicans. The experts included former Defense secretaries
Dick Cheney and Donald Rumsfeld; former national security adviser
Brent Scowcroft; and two former CIA directors under Clinton, R.
James Woolsey Jr. and John Deutch.
</P>
<P>
   Treaty supporters had little reason to expect Republican
backing. Sen. John Warner of Virginia, the chairman of the Armed
Services Committee, declared his opposition to the pact, based
largely on classified information.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republican foreign policy moderates _ like Sen. Chuck
Hagel of Nebraska, Sen. Richard Lugar of Indiana, and Sens. Olympia
Snowe and Susan Collins of Maine _ were either undecided or leaning
against the pact, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never discount the charm or ability of the president
to seduce and flatter members, but there really hasn't been a lot
of work done by the administration or Democrats on this,'' said one
senior Senate Republican aide. ``The field has been fallow. We're
ready to rumble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
