</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAD01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mead buy of AT-A-GLANCE planned to expand product line
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Mead Corp. is buying AT-A-GLANCE Group of Cullman
Ventures Inc., a family-owned calendar and appointment book maker
based near Albany, N.Y., for $550 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, announced Thursday, is expected to close by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   AT-A-GLANCE makes diaries, calendars, appointment books,
planners and accessories. The company has a 700,000-square-foot
facility in Sidney, N.Y., and is the area's largest employer with
1,800 jobs. Sales, which are about $325 million, have doubled over
the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Mead officials declined to disclose how much AT-A-GLANCE might
add to the company's bottom line and said exactly how many jobs may
be lost in the deal is under review.
</P>
<P>
   AT-A-GLANCE will bring two important things to Mead's struggling
School and Office Products Division: an expanded product portfolio
and a way to sell directly to business consumers, company officials
said. AT-A-GLANCE distributes its wares to office product dealers
who sell to offices. Mead sells its notebooks and other products
through retailers such as Kmart and Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Mead also announced this week that it bought a license to make
and sell school and office products with the Nike name and swoosh
design for the back-to-school season in 2000. Mead had a Nike
license from 1994 to 1996, but then the sports and fitness apparel
giant backed away from licensing for a short time.
</P>
<P>
   Mead School and Office Products Division President Neil
McLachlan said the Nike license and the AT-A-GLANCE deals are
growth engines for his division. Mead's high-profile school and
office products division has seen earnings drop 17.3 percent
between 1997 and 1998 and 38 percent for the first half of 1999.
McLachlan said the division needs new products that consumers will
find useful and retailers see as exciting. Acquisitions are a key
growth strategy for the division, he said.
</P>
<P>
   AT-A-GLANCE owner Lewis Cullman's interest in philanthropy was
beginning to conflict with the business, so he hired Goldman Sachs
to market the company to a buyer, said AT-A-GLANCE President Doug
Willies. Goldman Sachs approached Mead, which had been eyeing the
time management product line for more than two years, McLachlan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
