A2599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-DISNEY-ISRAEL-NYT &LR;      09-30 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON EVE OF JERUSALEM EXHIBITION, DEBATE FLARES
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also filed in ``a'' category) 
(rk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walt Disney Co.'s exhibition on Jerusalem continued to draw
controversy Thursday, the day before it was to open to the public,
as prominent Jewish and Arab-American organizations complained that
it portrayed a Jerusalem shorn of what they said was crucial
political context.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League
of B'nai B'rith, said he ``was disappointed, saddened, a little bit
offended and at times angry'' at the absence of any mention in the
exhibition that Israel considers Jerusalem its capital. Foxman
toured the exhibition at Disney World on Wednesday, among several
hundred guests on a long-planned visit arranged by Israel's Foreign
Affairs Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem exhibition, partly paid for with $1.8 million from
the Israeli government, lies within the Millennium Village, which
includes exhibitions of other nations, at the Orlando, Fla., theme
park. Although that area opens Friday, the question of what the
Jerusalem exhibition says, or does not say, about Jerusalem's
political status has proved a headache for Disney for weeks. The
entertainment giant has had to deal with controversy among Jewish
and Arab organizations in this country and also among governments
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, the United Arab Emirates, which like other Arab
nations insists that Israel has occupied East Jerusalem illegally,
threatened to call for a boycott of Disney products if the
exhibition portrayed an undivided Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has not said whether the exhibition ever identified
Jerusalem as such or whether the company altered the exhibition at
some point. On Sept. 17, Disney released a statement simply saying
that the exhibition contained ``no reference to Jerusalem as
capital of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Foxman said what he saw ``was a sanitized Jerusalem, a Jerusalem
unconnected to anywhere.'' He added: ``I guess if Disney would
permit me and I had the funds, I would love to do an exit poll,
asking kids, `Where is Jerusalem?' I'm not sure what kind of an
answer we would get.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition also continues to be controversial among
Arab-American organizations. Hanna Maksoud, president of the
Arab-American Anti-Discrimination Committee, who toured the
exhibition on Sept. 15, said Thursday that the exhibition was
unsatisfactory because it did not distinguish East Jerusalem from
the larger metropolis. As a result, she said, the exhibition
implicitly portrays all of Jerusalem as Israeli.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maksoud said an Arab-American delegation would visit the
exhibition Friday and hold a news conference afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Warren, a Disney spokesman, declined to comment on the
exhibition's history, saying information about ``the development
process'' was ``proprietary, out of courtesy to the clients we work
with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was always intended to be an exhibit that celebrates the
culture and people of Israel,'' Warren said. ``Certainly, everyone
that sees it will form their own opinion, and we respect that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2015EDT &QL; 
