<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2601 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-BRADLEY-DEBATE-N     09-30 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BRADLEY-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BRADLEY ARE SET TO BEGIN EARLY SERIES OF DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley are poised to begin an unusually early and intense series
of debates in the run-up to the primary season next year. As a
start, their campaigns said Thursday they have agreed to take part
in a nationally televised town meeting four weeks from now in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Gore's advisers said, they had been reluctant to
agree to early debates because they feared it would elevate the
stature of Bradley and give him millions of dollars worth of free
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   But now that Bradley has emerged as a threat for the Democratic
presidential nomination, the vice president's advisers said they
were willing to risk giving heightened exposure to a rival who Gore
had virtually ignored for months. Instead, their hope now is to
capitalize on what they consider to be Gore's adroit debating
skills. .
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the campaign released a letter from Tony Coelho,
Gore's campaign chairman, to Douglas Berman, his counterpart in the
Bradley campaign, calling for a series of debates beginning as soon
as next weekend. ``Al Gore sincerely believes that the American
people deserve to know and understand both the similarities and
differences between himself and Senator Bill Bradley,'' Coelho
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bradley campaign has not responded specifically to the
letter, Anita Dunn, Bradley's communications director, said her
candidate has long been eager to engage the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's willingness to debate Bradley is yet another indication
of how competitive the race for the Democratic presidential
nomination has become in recent weeks. On Wednesday, Gore announced
he was paring down his campaign organization and moving his
headquarters from Washington to Nashville in his home state of
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday, new financial reports indicated that Bradley
had raised more money in the past three months than the vice
president and had more cash on hand as the primary season
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two Democratic presidential contenders seem to be
rushing toward head-to-head confrontations, the Republican
frontrunner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, has declined to debate
his rivals until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Gore, Bush is so far ahead in the polls that his advisers
said there was nothing for him to gain by participating. And,
unlike Gore, Bush has had far less experience in debates and, by
his own admission, is still being schooled by his advisers about
many national and international issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers conceded that Bradley knows the issues but noted
that the vice president was far more experienced in national
debates. ``I'm going to present my own vision for what this nation
needs to do in the future,'' Gore said Wednesday night in an
interview on CNN. ``And I can't think of a better way to do that
than have a good, spirited debate about the future of America with
somebody who I know well, Bill Bradley. And I hope that he will
accept my challenge to a series of debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Gore's debate challenge, Bradley, campaigning in San
Diego on Wednesday, said, ``That's an abrupt strategy shift _ this
time yesterday they were ignoring me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore won much praise in debates in 1996 for his
dispatching of Ross Perot, the Reform Party presidential candidate,
and Jack F. Kemp, the Republican vice presidential contender, he
did not draw such reviews for how he handled a debate in 1992 with
Vice President Dan Quayle. Gore was criticized then for not
defending his running mate, Bill Clinton, from Quayle's attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gore and Bradley have agreed to appear at a Democratic
dinner in Des Moines on Oct. 9, where both are scheduled to speak
but not debate. Some news organizations have scheduled debates in
New Hampshire in January and in California in early March, but so
far the only actual forum that both sides have agreed to is an
hour-long session sponsored jointly by CNN and WMUR, a local
television station in Manchester, N.H., on Oct. 27.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsors described the format as more a town meeting at
Dartmouth College than a debate because the candidates, while
appearing side-by-side on stage, will take questions from ordinary
citizens and not spar directly with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not billing this as a debate,'' said Tom Hannon, CNN's
political director. ``It may be a semantic difference, but there
will be no panel of journalist questioners, there will be no point,
counter-point or rebuttal except if one candidate personally
attacks another the moderator will give them a chance to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN, WMUR, which is an an affiliate of ABC, and the Fox network
, are sponsoring a similar event the next day _ this one 90 minutes
_ among six confirmed Republican contenders, but Bush has said he
will not participate. Mindy Tucker, a spokesman for Bush, said the
only such event he has thus far agreed to is a debate in Iowa on
Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking forward to debating next year when people are
paying attention,'' Ms. Tucker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
