u f BC-DOW-QUARTER01-COX     09-30 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-QUARTER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stocks' dismal quarter ends on positive note
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Investors gladly put a dismal third-quarter
performance behind them and started looking forward to the next
round of profit reports they hope will rally the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The fact stocks ended the quarter Thursday with surprisingly
strong, broad-based gains was small consolation to investors whose
portfolios had followed the market's indexes down as much as 10
percent from recent highs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been in a correction since late April,'' said Alfred
Goldman, strategist for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons. ``In April it was up
46 percent from last October's lows. The market obviously went too
far, too fast, and a correction was inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman compared conditions to torture that ``wears everybody
down and out'' but added that the sell-off is probably coming to an
end due to its length.
</P>
<P>
   At Prudential Securities, technical analyst Ralph Acampora said
he adjusted his Dow forecast downward after the blue chip index
dropped below a key support level last week but also said he is
``bullish long term.''
</P>
<P>
   He now looks for the Dow to hit 12,000 next year instead of in
1999, which was his earlier forecast. The Dow's record is
11,326.04, set Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Acampora called the current correction ``a great opportunity to
buy, once we experience a selling climax such as the one we
experienced in (October) 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   From here on, analysts said, the market will be driven by the
outlook for interest rates and the strength of third-quarter
profits. Rising rates could put a damper on trading, while upbeat
profit growth could propel the market to new highs, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's policy-makers meet Tuesday to act on short-term
interest rates. An increase would be the third since June. Analysts
are divided on prospects of a rate change. Some think an increase
is unlikely now because of fresh news of slower economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in stock prices due to the correction also makes a rate
boost unlikely, some analysts contend. They cite Fed Chairman Alan
Greenspan's concern about the role of stock market wealth in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   The government said Thursday that gross domestic product, the
broadest measure of the economy, grew at an annual rate of 1.6
percent in the second quarter, revised from the earlier 1.8 percent
estimate. First-quarter GDP growth was an annualized 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market took heart with the GDP news despite a strong
August housing report. The result was that the yield on the 30-year
Treasury moved lower.
</P>
<P>
   According to Goldman, a Fed rate increase would not necessarily
harm the market, since Wall Street already anticipates another one.
The absence of a rate rise Tuesday would probably boost buying, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for third-quarter profits, analysts look for year-over-year
gains of about 16 percent, slightly better than the second-quarter
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
