a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV07-     09-30 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV07-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PLANNING FOR AND COMMUNICATING ABOUT DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Oct. 7) 
(bl) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was her wish that her ashes be scattered and she meant that
in a global way, so a woman named Woody is landing in many places.
She is in a public garden. She is next to a Buddha statue in a
friend's back yard. Her cousin delivered his portion to a special
tree that grows out of a rock in the Sierra. She is by her home in
the apple orchard.
</P>
<P>
   Her son says, ``My mom wanted to be part of everything and go
everywhere.'' And so Woody is getting her wish.
</P>
<P>
   She was taken to Campobello, FDR's vacation home. She is in a
flower pot on the third floor balcony of an apartment in Los
Angeles. She is scheduled to go to Tonga. And there will be more.
Close to 100 containers of Woody's ashes were given out at her
memorial picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Woody's way may not be everybody's choice, but it's part of a
trend that's changing the American way of formula funerals and
starting new family traditions. People are planning their exit
ahead of time, not leaving things to chance or to a grieving and
overwhelmed relative to second guess their wishes.
</P>
<P>
   A Connecticut writer, Lynn McPhelimy, came up with a way to
encourage people to discuss and write down all the pertinent
details ahead of time just as she did with her own parents. Her
workbook, called ``In the Checklist of Life: A Working Book to Help
You Live &AMP; Leave This Life,'' has pages for writing down special
memories _ what time was supper every night? _ to personal requests
_ what music do you want at your funeral?
</P>
<P>
   Lynn wrote it after her parents died within months of each other
from cancer and after talking frankly and intimately to her about
their deaths. Her mother wanted to wear her yellow suit and be in a
closed casket with a single rose on top. Her father wanted to wear
his gardening clothes.
</P>
<P>
   There were also practical things that had to be shared. Lynn's
father drew her a map to the septic tank so the next time it needed
pumping she wouldn't have to dig up the yard.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about it all, says Lynn. What is the special meaning of
certain books, old Christmas ornaments. Who do we call to get the
garbage stopped? How often do you feed the roses?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to do any of that you have to get past the giant
taboo subject. Children don't want to talk about the fact that
their parents will not always be around, and parents aren't too
wild about the inevitability either.
</P>
<P>
   But, talking about death doesn't hasten it any more than hiding
from the subject keeps it away. While ``How do you feel about
dying?'' isn't a popular conversation starter, once broached, the
subject has endless possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Who do you not want speaking about your life at your funeral? Do
you want to be cremated or buried? Can I have the tea pot with the
red handle?
</P>
<P>
   A friend, who promises not to die for a long time, and I
recently got on the subject of multiple scattering. She would like
to have half of her ashes delivered back east to be buried next to
her husband, but she wants the other half sprinkled into the
Pacific. I said I was thinking about the Atlantic, the Pacific and
maybe some place in France.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn McPhelimy published her book herself after 15 publishing
houses wrinkled their noises. She's sold over 100,000 copies, has
been on Oprah and The Today Show and is impressed by how
enthusiastic people get once the subject is out.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it turns them back on to living. There's a section in
the book that asks what you wished you had done in life. A
74-year-old woman wrote down white-water rafting, then decided she
still had time and scheduled six days on the Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Swartz writes for The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.
</P>
</TEXT>
