<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-ZENGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZENGA OUT A REVOLUTION COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY _ Walter Zenga is leaving the Revolution as abruptly
as he was hired. Zenga, who was named coach of the team after
arriving for a tribute game Aug. 22, 1998, was fired Thursday with
the Revolution in a desperate fight to qualify for the Major League
Soccer playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Nicol, a former star defender with Liverpool and
Scotland's national team, will coach the Revolution in Saturday's
game against the MetroStars at Foxboro Stadium and the
regular-season finale at D.C. United Oct. 9. Nicol, who was
player-assistant coach with the Boston Bulldogs this season, has
been scouting in El Salvador and will join the Revolution at
practice Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga, 39, conducted a training session at Babson College
Thursday morning, then met with general manager Brian O'Donovan.
During a meeting that lasted about five minutes, Zenga asked
O'Donovan to confirm him for next season, according to sources.
O'Donovan refused and instead fired Zenga, who as goalie also was
one of the team's most important players. Zenga's hand-picked
assistant, Giuseppe Galderisi, also was let go.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Zenga publicly campaigned to remain in charge of the
Revolution. O'Donovan stated at the time that no decision would be
made until after the regular season. The Revolution then lost, 1-0,
to Dallas, assuring that the team will have its worst record in
four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution are only a point behind fourth-place Miami
and have a significant lead in the goal-differential tiebreaker in
the Eastern Conference. The fourth-place team will meet D.C. United
in the playoffs starting Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting in the coaches' locker room, Zenga said: ``I
have nothing to say now, but I will talk (Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donovan said a press release would be issued, but did not
reveal the subject.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden dismissal of their coach astonished Revolution
players, most of whom had departed from the locker room unaware of
the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am surprised by the timing of the change,'' defender Dan
Calichman said. ``We assumed the season would be finished and,
hopefully, we would make the playoffs, then everyone would be
evaluated.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga led the Revolution to their only playoff berth as a
goalkeeper in 1997 but retired after the season. He returned last
year as a replacement for coach Thomas Rongen and guided the
Revolution to three victories in the final six games by emphasizing
defense-first tactics. The Revolution seemed comfortable with this
identity, and Zenga brought in Calichman to reinforce the defense,
plus John Harkes to provide leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution struggled during preseason training and some
players seemed dissatisfied with the team's extended stay in Italy
during training camp. Yet, the Revolution earned 18 points and
climbed as high as third place in the first half of the season. But
the team since has collapsed and has a 1-12-1 record in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Questions were raised about the team's tactics after it switched
to a 3-5-2 alignment, and doubts were raised in July when the
Revolution added striker Ariel Graziani instead of Ghanaian
defender Joseph Addo, who had been preferred by Zenga and
Galderisi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly understand that Walter and Beppe must have options
out there, certainly in Italy, and they want to know where they
stand,'' Calichman said. ``I respect that, but I understand both
sides here. If someone doesn't like the way I play, I get traded.
I'm sorry to see it happen. People being fired is always the
hardest part about this business. On a personal level, I'm sad to
see them go.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicol, 37, started his professional career with Ayr United in
Scotland and was part of some of the most glorious and tragic times
in Liverpool history, playing for the 1984 European Champions Cup
winners in Rome and the runners-up in the 1985 violence-plagued
final at Heysel Stadium in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what he's done as a player but I don't know him,''
captain Mike Burns said of Nicol. ``He's in a no-lose situation, an
interim situation in which, hopefully, we'll make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit unusual for a coach to be fired with two games left
in the season. We were caught off guard. We expected the entire
organization to be evaluated at the end of the season. There is
always tension, and we've had it for four years in this situation.
They have tension in D.C., but it's a different kind. When you lose
a number of consecutive games, everything is magnified. But to use
Walter as a scapegoat, I don't think that is fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
