<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SIGNS TEMPORARY SPENDING MEASURE, BLASTS GOP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
and GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton signed a temporary spending
measure Thursday to keep the government operating and accused
Republicans of using ``gimmicks and gamesmanship'' to conceal
dipping into the Social Security surplus to fund the federal
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned Republicans that he would vetotheir plan to
delay Earned Income Tax Credit refund payments to the poor, one of
their gimmicks, he said, to come up with a spending plan that does
not break legislated spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   He urged them to get to work on a realistic fiscal 2000 budget
before the temporary spending measure expires.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 fiscal year began Friday with no budget agreement in
sight, and the White House and GOP majority in Congress found
themselves in a familiar position _ a stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid shutting down the government, Congress passed and the
president signed the continuing resolution extending funding for
all government agencies until Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats, trying to keep the heat on the GOP,
suggested there would be little support for another lengthy stopgap
spending resolution and raised the prospect of another budgetary
train wreck this year.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders countered that it was Clinton who has yet to get
serious about the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't done anything all year on it,'' said House Majority
Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. ``Now he comes along and says, `Look,
if you guys don't finish this thing in three weeks I'm going to
shut down the government.' I mean I don't understand that kind of
presidential behavior,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that months ago the administration submitted its
budget proposal that would have raised taxes on tobacco companies,
corporate polluters and closed corporate tax loopholes while also
spending more on education, setting aside the surplus for Social
Security and beginning to pay off the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of making difficult choices to finish their work and
crafting a responsible budget, they've resorted to gimmicks and
gamesmanship like using two sets of books and designating the fully
predictable census, for example, as emergency spending,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said most troubling to him was the Republican effort to
``disguise the fact that they are spending the Social Security
surplus'' by delaying Earned Income Tax Credit payments to nearly
20 million poor families.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, under consideration by the House Appropriations
Committee, would save more than $8 billion for fiscal year 2000 by
making monthly EITC payments to families in the $20,000-$30,000
income range instead of paying in a lump sum. The savings would
come from pushing some of the payments, based on 1999 earnings,
into fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dismissed that plan as ``an effective tax increase on
the most hard-pressed working Americans'' at a time when they are
trying to lift themselves out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``So let me be clear. I will not sign a bill that turns its back
on these hardworking families. I don't think we ought to be putting
more roadblocks in their way,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The EITC ensures a cash refund from the Internal Revenue Service
to the lowest income taxpayers, even those who might owe no taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, citing a new Census Bureau report on income, contends
the EITC has helped double the number of people coming out of
poverty in the past five years. The annual Census report showed
dropping poverty rates, especially in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans denied they were making the change to hide use of
Social Security surplus money in their spending plans.
</P>
<P>
   Army said the Republican attempt to alter the EITC payment is
``good policy'' and a ``good management tool.'' He equated the tax
credit to a welfare program and suggested it should conform to
other welfare programs by being paid out on a monthly basis.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said the program needed
reform because ``the working poor don't need help with their annual
budget, what they need help with is their monthly budget.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush distanced
himself from the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they ought to balance the budget on the backs of
the poor,'' Bush said in California.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has completed work on five of 13 spending measures to
fund the government. Clinton has signed two of them into law,
vetoed one and has threatened to veto four others still pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have urged from the very beginning that we sit down and
negotiate these things together to be able to avoid completely any
prospect of shutting down the government,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., the Senate minority leader.``They're on the road to doing
so if they aren't careful. We don't want that to happen. They say
they don't want that to happen, but they're actions speak a lot
louder than their words,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Lew, the president's budget chief, also said there would be
little appetite for another lengthy resolution after Oct. 21.
``They (Republicans) shouldn't have any illusions about lots of
long extensions,'' Lew said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also blasted Republicans for launching a new political
advertising campaign Wednesday that blames Democrats for wanting to
spend Social Security money. The Republicans' own Congressional
Budget Office reported the GOP would be spending $18 billion from
the surplus, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help noting that these are the same people who told us
they could spend all this money and cut taxes $792 billion and
never touch the Social Security surplus,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vetoed the GOP's 10-year $792 billion tax cut last week.
Republicans, in turn, said they would not agree to Clinton's
spending increases or tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole budget position we're taking now...is we're going to
stop this raid on Social Security money,'' Armey said, disputing
the CBO report as a ``misrepresentation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
