<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKBOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET-BANKBOSTON MERGER CLEARS FINAL HURDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ State officials gave a final nod Thursday to Fleet
Financial Group Inc.'s proposed acquisition of BankBoston Corp.,
eliminating the last regulatory hurdle to a deal that creates New
England's dominant bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Board of Bank Incorporation unanimously
endorsed the $16 billion transaction, which the two banks expect to
formally close Friday. The agency's sign-off is the final green
light for the two Boston-based companies to forge ahead in the
arduous task of melding two different cultures into the nation's
eighth-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at both companies declined to comment on what two
industry sources said Thursday was new consideration in recent days
by Fleet chief executive Terrence Murray to call the holding
company of the new bank Fleet Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's current ticker symbol on the New York Stock Exchange,
FLT, would remain for the new company, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe reported earlier this week that Murray has insisted
that the main retail bank _ the core of the new company _ bear the
Fleet name only. The Globe, citing sources familiar with the
matter, also reported that certain BankBoston portions of the new
company _ the Latin American franchise and San-Francisco investment
bank Robertson Stephens _ would retain their current names, though
the latter would drop its BankBoston prefix.
</P>
<P>
   The banks expect to announce a new, 22-person board next week,
Fleet spokesman James Mahoney said. The board is scheduled to hold
its first meeting in the third week of October.
</P>
<P>
   Since New England's largest bank deal was announced in March,
industry analysts on Wall Street and elsewhere have wondered how
two companies widely viewed as different would work together to
meld their operations.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, in a brief telephone interview Thursday, said his
relationship with his BankBoston counterpart, Charles K. Gifford,
was ``professional, collaborative, and in the spirit of getting the
job done.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he and Gifford made decisions, Murray replied:
``We go one way (on one matter), then next time we try to yield to
the other person.'' Murray is chairman and chief executive of the
new company, with Gifford in the number two position of president
and chief operating officer. Gifford is scheduled to take the top
post at the end of 2001, when Murray will retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a merger of equals,'' Murray said, repeating a
phrase often pronounced by Gifford. Some industry analysts have
said that so-called mergers of equals end up as transactions in
which the culture and ethos of the acquiring company dominates.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Fleet-BankBoston merger won support Thursday
from Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal, who had
opposed the deal. While Blumenthal has no regulatory power over the
transaction, his office could have filed lawsuits designed to delay
or block the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad, stark fact is that an antitrust lawsuit was
critically undercut by two key federal agency approvals,''
Blumenthal said in a statement, referring to recent approvals by
the Justice Department and Federal Reserve for the merger.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint press release with the Connecticut treasurer,
Blumenthal said Fleet had agreed to divest an additional seven
Connecticut branches and invest an additional $700 million, or
total $2.9 billion, in state community projects. Fleet also agreed
to set aside two branches previously sold to Wyomissing, Pa.-based
Sovereign Bancorp for purchase by a minority-owned bank.
</P>
<P>
   A local banking source said Thursday that Boston Bank of
Commerce, a leading minority-owned bank, planned to bid on the two
Connecticut branches. BBOC is also trying to buy five Boston-based
branches, but negotiations with Fleet have stalled over price
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, under a major divestiture of assets, Sovereign
bought more than 270 Fleet and BankBoston branches, with nearly $13
billion in deposits. Murray said Sovereign would employ 900 people
more than expected, and that job cuts from the merger would be less
than 2,500. An equal number of positions will be eliminated through
attrition.
</P>
</TEXT>
