<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAB HAS ROOM FOR THE WHOLE CREW  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, OCT. 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Nissan Frontier Crew Cab is not a graceful
vehicle, but it's a useful one. Combining the benefits of a
sport-utility vehicle with an open-bed pickup truck, it becomes
something else altogether.
</P>
<P>
   It's a compromise, to be sure. The back seat is not really where
you'd want to be for a cross-country journey, and the pickup bed is
at least a foot shorter than those on most pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Crew Cab answers the need of many families who want the
convenience of a small pickup and still have enough room for junior
and the twins. It can haul, it can tow and it can boondock, and it
can take everybody along.
</P>
<P>
   There have been full-size crew-cab trucks for decades, usually
for commercial or construction applications but increasingly for
personal use. The compact Crew Cab is a new development, at least
for the United States, although in such places as Africa and
Australia, the design is old hat.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan is the first to come to market, although Ford is
developing one off the Explorer, and other automakers are readying
their own. Ford has coined a nickname for its version that is sure
to stick as a generic term: Sport Truck.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew Cab benefits from Nissan's well-engineered Frontier
chassis, which also can be had in standard-issue pickup form or
King Cab. Nissan also has used the Frontier as the basis for the
new Xterra sport-utility vehicle, which has been a huge hit,
especially among younger drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew Cab is considerably roomier than the King Cab, with a
full-width back seat. It also has the advantage of real,
full-functioning rear doors instead of the clamshell doors on King
Cab or other makers' stretch-cab pickups.
</P>
<P>
   The Frontier is a good driving truck with a rugged feel and,
with the V-6 engine, enough power and torque to perform most truck
duties. Both the two- and four-wheel-drive versions of the crew cab
are built on the sturdy four-wheeler chassis.
</P>
<P>
   The test truck was an upgraded four-wheel-drive SE model with a
nicely equipped interior and a decent stereo system. It came with
automatic transmission, and a five-speed manual is available. With
the automatic, towing capacity is 5,000 pounds; 3,500 pounds with
stick.
</P>
<P>
   On the outside, the SE includes aluminum alloy 16-inch wheels,
step rails and mud flaps, chrome bumpers and fog lamps. The only
option was a power package for windows, locks and mirrors, remote
door locks and security system, and cruise control, all for $1,080
extra.
</P>
<P>
   Crew Cab also can be had with a flexible roof rack that can be
equipped to tote bikes, skis, kayaks or luggage. A sunroof also is
available.
</P>
<P>
   For those who find the 54-inch-long cargo bed too small for
practical purposes, Nissan offers an interesting tubular bed
extender that mounts on the lowered tailgate, effectively
increasing the length by 16.5 inches. When the tailgate is up, the
extender can be moved forward in the bed to create a storage area
for smaller items. The bed extender can be used on any of the
Frontier pickups.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that short bed will be a sticking point for many pickup
users, especially those who use the trucks for business.
</P>
<P>
   Although the four-door configuration makes the Crew Cab more
flexible, it's still no substitute for a passenger car. The front
bucket seats are comfortable enough, but the back on the rear seat
is nearly upright, and legroom is marginal. Few full-size adults
would be happy back there for very long.
</P>
<P>
   The rear doors, although preferable to the clamshells on
stretch-cab pickups, are a lot narrower than the doors on a
four-door car or sport-utility vehicle. For an extra-tall guy like
me, getting in and out is a strenuous piece of contortionism, and I
think it would be the same story for anybody even approaching 6
feet in height.
</P>
<P>
   For those more accustomed to the cushy rides of today's luxury
SUVs, the Crew Cab may feel harsh. Handling is improved, however,
because of the stiff suspension and reduced body sway.
</P>
<P>
   The look of the Crew Cab appears clunky to some eyes, oddly cut
off behind the rear doors, with a boxy cabin and disproportionately
short bed. To others, however, it's strikingly macho and
purposeful, helped no doubt by the aggressive stance, beefy tires
and broad fender flares.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's California design studio penned the look, and the Crew
Cab is built in the Japanese automaker's Smyrna, Tenn., factory.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew Cab gets a love-it or hate-it reaction wherever it
goes, but Nissan should be able to sell as many of these as it can
pump out. The four-door is available in the same sort of funky
colors available for the Xterra, included bright yellow. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vehicle type: Five passenger, four-door pickup, rear/four-wheel
drive. &QL; 
Base price: $22,240. &QL; 
Price as tested: $23,840. &QL; 
Engine: 3.3-liter V-6, 170 hp at 4,800 rpm, 200 lb-ft of torque at
2,800 rpm. &QL; 
Transmission: 4-speed automatic. &QL; 
Curb weight: 4,141 pounds. &QL; 
Wheelbase: 116.1 inches. &QL; 
EPA mileage: &QL; 
15 city, 19 highway. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pluses &QL; 
Versatility. &QL; 
Unique image. &QL; 
Driveability. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Minuses &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tight back seat. &QL; 
Small pickup bed. &QL; 
Controversial styling. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at (602) 444-8106, or at
bob.golfen(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
