<HEADLINE>
BELL MANAGERS QUESTION MOVE TO CASH-BALANCE PENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following an earlier change of heart at International Business
Machines Corp. about converting longtime employees' traditional
pensions to cash-balance accounts, Bell Atlantic Corp. managers
have petitioned a US Senate panel to investigate whether a similar
move by their employer was discriminatory.
</P>
<P>
   The petition, filed on behalf of 250 managers from
Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Rhode Island, and New York, was
delivered last week to Massachusetts Senator Edward M. Kennedy for
consideration as his Senate committee, where Kennedy is the ranking
Democrat, considers hearings on cash-balance accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic stood by its plan Thursday and denied any bias. It
said it went out of its way to ensure that older managers with
significant years of service would receive more money in their cash
balance accounts, thereby reducing the impact of the conversion
from a traditional defined benefits pension plan.
</P>
<P>
   Rosel &UR;  &LR; Patton, 47, a manager in the company's engineering design
center in Marlborough, Mass. who delivered the petition last week,
called the Bell Atlantic move ``very disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   Patton said the conversion of her pension in 1997 will lead to a
33 1/4 percent reduction in benefits from her previous, traditional
pension plan, when she reaches 30 years of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this had been done properly I would have had an opening
balance of about $210,000, but I only had $129,000 in the
account,'' Patton, a telephone employee for 28 years, said.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic managers Arthur Callahan and Arthur Huse, who work
in Burlington, Mass., believe their pensions will be reduced 29 and
21 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   A Bell Atlantic spokesman in New York, Steven Marcus, said the
conversion took employees' experience and age into account. ``When
we established an opening balance in their accounts, we put in
extra money using a formula based on age and length of service,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under most cash balance accounts, a company contributes 2
percent. Our contribution ranges from 4 percent to 7 percent,
depending on age. The contribution for older employers is 7
percent. So, our plan does not discriminate based on age,'' Marcus
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for allegations that early retirement penalties were charged,
Marcus said he was unaware of such assessments.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic implemented its cash balance pension program in
two stages, beginning in December 1995 at sites in New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Maryland, Delaware, Virginia, West Virginia and the
District of Columbia. In 1997, the pensions of former Nynex Corp.
managers were converted from conventional defined benefits plans to
cash balance accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The Bell Atlantic managers' petition was filed less than a week
after IBM, under political pressure, agreed to allow employees 40
and older with at least 10 years on the job to choose between the
new cash balance account and a traditional defined benefits pension
plan. Under the latter, long-term employees accrue more benefits
during the last decade of work. Under cash balance accounts, by
contrast, benefits accrue at the same rate yearly, giving younger
workers the chance to earn more earlier in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, two Bell Atlantic managers from Massachusetts have
filed complaints with the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission
alleging age discrimination. In interviews Thursday, they claimed
the company added early retirement penalties to the formula it used
to calculate the managers' cash balance accounts, even though they
have not yet retired.
</P>
<P>
   To support their position in the cash-balance pension fund
fight, other Bell Atlantic employees meanwhile launched a Bell
Atlantic employee pension site on the World Wide Web, similar to
pension club sites created earlier by employees at IBM and other
companies where conversions have become controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Huse, a former Nynex employee, had 29 years of service with the
New England Telephone Co. and Nynex Corp. before Nynex merged with
Bell Atlantic in 1997. He has been with Bell Atlantic two years.
``As more people become aware, the furor is beginning to foment.''
</P>
<P>
   Patton last July filed a complaint about the Bell Atlantic
conversion with the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission,
alleging age discrimination. The EEOC has since said it plans to
investigate the legality of cash balance accounts.
</P>
</TEXT>
