<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED SEEN LEAVING INTEREST RATES UNCHANGED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The economy is still growing at a rapid clip.
Commodity prices are rising. With unemployment low, workers are
demanding and getting higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   But for every signal suggesting that inflation might be lurking
just over the horizon, there are others indicating that price
increases are well under control and that whatever inflationary
pressures might be building will dissipate in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Federal Reserve is likely to leave interest
rates unchanged when its policy committee meets on Tuesday,
analysts and economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Fed officials have hinted as much in their public statements
over the last few weeks, saying that they see prices as stable and
the economy's ability to grow without inflation benefiting from
huge investments in productivity-enhancing technology.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, typically gives financial
markets a clear warning when he is seriously considering a rate
increase, but in a speech Thursday night in Minnesota, he did not
mention current economic conditions or monetary policy. Instead, he
warned about the dangers of trade protectionism.
</P>
<P>
   Less clear is whether the Fed will feel compelled to nudge rates
up at its subsequent meeting, in mid-November. If the economy does
not show clear signs of cooling off somewhat over the next six
weeks, analysts said, there is a good chance that the central bank
will nudge its benchmark rate up by a quarter of a percentage point
by the end of the year. The clearest clue to the Fed's intentions
will be whether it adopts a formal tilt toward higher rates at its
meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given their rhetoric of late, the Fed is going to stay on hold
at the Oct. 5 meeting,'' said Paul Kasriel, an economist at
Northern Trust Co. in Chicago. ``There is a distinct possibility
that they could issue a directive biased toward tightening, which
would put us on a rate-hike watch for the Nov. 16 meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates twice this year in quarter-point
increments, most recently on Aug. 24 when it increased its federal
funds target rate to 5.25 percent. At the same time, the central
bank said inflation risks had been markedly diminished, a sign of
its confidence that growth would slow to a non-inflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that the economy grew at a
revised annual rate of 1.6 percent in the second quarter, down from
4.3 percent in the first quarter. The government had previously
estimated growth at 1.8 percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Growth has subsequently rebounded considerably, however, and
most economists are now forecasting that the economy expanded about
4 percent in the quarter that ended Thursday and will maintain
something close to that pace for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's maybe a little more rapid than the Fed wants, but there
are some indications that things are slowing down a bit,'' said
Stephen Slifer, an economist at Lehman Brothers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new homes rose 2.9 percent in August, the Commerce
Department said Thursday. But other interest-rate-sensitive
activity suggests that the general upward trend in interest rates
over the last several months is beginning to work its way through
the economy. Mortgage refinancing, for example, which has put
additional cash in the pockets of many consumers, has slowed
substantially.
</P>
<P>
   The downturn in the stock market is also likely to diminish any
fears among Fed officials that the economy is overheating.
</P>
<P>
   But the strongest case for holding rates steady may be that
there are almost no signs of consumer price inflation. Core
inflation _ excluding volatile energy and food prices _ rose just
1.9 percent over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that isn't price stability, I don't know what is,'' William
McDonough, the president of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York,
told reporters last week.
</P>
<P>
   With inflation so well behaved, Fed officials are talking more
openly about the possibility that their traditional models for
predicting inflation are no longer worth much. As a result, they
seem less inclined to raise rates before they are sure that
inflation is threatening the long expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose, like now, we're uncertain about the underlying model
of the economy,'' Robert Parry, president of the Federal Reserve
Bank of San Francisco, said in a speech on Monday. ``In that case,
pre-emptive policy can lead to the wrong action. When there's a
high degree of uncertainty about forecasts, it could be best for
policy to be more cautious _ in the extreme, to wait until
inflation actually starts to rise before acting to tighten.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are enough signs of persistently strong demand and
inflation-warning signals that the Fed is sure to remain vigilant
in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Orders for durable goods unexpectedly rose again in August after
a big surge in July. Consumer confidence, while dipping, remains
high, and job creation remains strong even as the supply of
available workers is shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for oil and other commodities are rising. Demand for
American goods from abroad is picking up, and the dollar's long
rally appears to be coming to an end, creating the risk of higher
import prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a strong economic performance, probably stronger
than most at the Fed think is sustainable,'' said Kenneth Mayland,
an economist at KeyCorp in Cleveland. ``More and more evidence is
coming in that there has been a change in the inflation
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of this year, economists speculated that the Fed would
be unlikely to raise interest rates during the last two months of
1999 because of fears that the computer problems associated with
the end of the century might wreak havoc with the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But as government officials and corporate executives have grown
more confident that the United States will escape any serious
problems, analysts have changed their minds and now think the Fed
would be willing to tighten policy in November if economic data
justify higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Y2K situation is going so smoothly now that it's much less
of a constraint on Nov. 16 policy action if deemed necessary,''
Mayland said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
