u f BC-CMGI-FLYCAST-BOS &LR;      09-30 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-FLYCAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CMGI ACQUIRES ANOTHER ON-LINE FIRM, THIS TIME IN ADVERTISING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CMGI Inc., the Andover, Mass. Internet venture company,
announced Thursday its third major acquisition of an on-line
advertising firm in the last two weeks, agreeing to buy a San
Francisco marketer for about $741 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI said it plans to exchange 7.2 million shares for control of
Flycast Communications Corp., an aggregator of ads that are
distributed over the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives CMGI what it calls a full lineup of
infrastructure to target ads at individual consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're amassing as much reach as we can, and the plan is to
derive as much revenue from those page views better than anyone
else,'' said Bill White, CMGI executive vice president for
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, CMGI said it plans to issue stock worth about $500
million to buy AdForce Inc., an advertising broker; also last week,
CMGI-controlled research firm Engage Technologies Inc. said it will
use $193 million in stock to buy AdKnowledge Inc., a
marketing-management service.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI's efforts come at a time of high expectations that the
Internet will develop into a major marketing channel, and have set
up CMGI to compete head-to-head with traditional market leader
DoubleClick Inc. of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies aim to develop sophisticated programs that show
consumers only those on-line ads likely to interest them, based on
their demographics and past surfing habits.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, such ads should also command higher fees.
</P>
<P>
   The total market for such on-line material is variously
estimated to reach around $7 billion by 2002, from around $1.5
billion last year, according to survey firm NUA of Dublin. In the
first quarter of this year $693 million was spent on such content,
according to the Internet Advertising Bureau in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the expected boom, the effectiveness of on-line
marketing so far is a still an open question, particularly in the
area of what are called ``banner ads,'' or small boxed messages
that often appear on Web sites hosted by other companies.
</P>
<P>
   For most banners, a click-through rate of less than one-half of
1 percent is considered strong, compared to a response rate several
times that for ads in magazine or newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the Web goes, we're still in the game of trying to
figure out what works,'' said Jay Kim, of the Paul Kagan Associates
consulting firm in Carmel, Calif. Flycast chief executive George
Carrick concurred. For many advertising buyers, he said, ``The cost
equation versus the benefit equation still has to sort itself
out.''
</P>
<P>
   CMGI wouldn't discuss how the Flycast deal will impact its
operating results, or describe how its new push into advertising
relates to its plans for the AltaVista search engine, most of which
CMGI bought from Compaq Computer Corp. earlier this year and plans
to take public.
</P>
<P>
   But financial analysts said the Flycast agreement puts CMGI in a
position to link its various ad-related technologies. For example,
banner ads gathered by Flycast and AdSmart could be sorted through
servers hosted by Engage, then targeted to specific consumers using
AdForce-built programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more or less done, in terms of enabling themselves to
target the ads closely,'' said First Albany Corp. analyst Ullas
Naik. ``In theory, sophisticated targeting can drive the
click-through rates pretty high.''
</P>
<P>
   CMGI's acquisition spree is made possible by its strong share
price, which closed at 102 1/2 Thursday, more than 10 times its
value of a year ago. Like other technology stocks, however, CMGI
shares have fallen lately: the company reached a high of 165 in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1996, Flycast lost $9.3 million in 1998 on sales of
$8 million; some analysts had expected the company to become
profitable by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Flycast is known for its partnerships with about 1,200
small-to-midsize Web site companies, complementing CMGI's AdSmart
service, aimed at providing content from larger companies.
</P>
<P>
   Flycast's roughly 140 employees will remain in San Francisco
under chief executive George Carrick.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for CMGI to exchange 0.4728 of its shares for
each of Flycast's 15.26 million shares outstanding, giving the deal
a total value of $741 million based on CMGI's closing price
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Flycast shares rose 7 1/2 to 45 1/2 apiece after the agreement
was announced Thursday; the purchase represents a premium of 27
percent over company's market value Wednesday, before the agreement
was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is scheduled to be completed in January, pending
approvals from regulators and Flycast shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Flycast's Carrick said he held talks with two other companies
before settling on the deal with CMGI, but he declined to name them
or discuss whether a breakup fee would be paid to investment
bankers should the a rival suitor emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Should a counterbid succeed, the agreement gives CMGI the option
of buying up to 19.9 percent of Flycast. Major Flycast investors
include venture-capital firms Bessemer Venture Partners of Menlo
Park, Calif.; Charles River Ventures of Waltham; and St. Paul
Ventures of St. Paul, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Other major holders of Flycast stock include BellSouth Corp., US
West Inc., and SBC Communications Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
