   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, Oct. 1,
and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Bob Schenet
at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   WTO-SECURITY (Seattle) _ Fire trucks will be strategically
placed downtown. Ambulances will be ready. Dogs will sniff for
bombs. And in buildings near the convention center, officers in
riot gear will be waiting, watching and hoping they are not called.
If they are, something has gone wrong. Seattle is gearing up for
the World Trade Organization conference.
</P>
<P>
   By Judd Slivka. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WTO-ENVIRONMENT (Washington) _ The heads of five major
environmental organizations blast the Clinton administration for
allegedly abandoning environmental concerns as it prepares for this
fall's meeting of the World Trade Organization in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   POLTIX-MCCAIN (Seattle) _ GOP Sen. John McCain, the latest
plainspoken presidential candidate from Arizona, visits Seattle and
promises to again make Republicans the party of reform. He also
says a conservative can stand for environmental conservation.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``p'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-BIAS (Seattle) _ A federal judge closes the chapter on
the biggest settlement of racial bias charges in history of The
Boeing Co. by approving a $15 million settlement.
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Nyhan. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-KINGS (Undated) _ Every so often a film comes along that's
as entertaining as it is a viable, political message destined to
make viewers rethink their stance about war. The '70s films
``MASH'' and ``Catch 22'' are prime examples of satires that had an
impact because of their conscience and comedic irreverence. ``Three
Kings'' is certainly a welcome addition to the genre.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SUGARTOWN (Undated) _ ``Sugar Town'' is a surprisingly
innocuous, rather shapeless comedy that is enjoyable to watch and
often quite clever with its barbs. But we don't get to know any of
the characters _ there are too many to focus upon intently in a
90-minute running time _ and by the final frames it doesn't resolve
itself or its issues and, in truth, doesn't have much to say.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MYSTERY (Undated) _ This feel-good sports story, set in
snowy Mystery, Alaska, boasts a terrific cast. But as directed by
``Austin Powers'' helmer, Jay Roach, and co-written by TV boy
wonder David E. Kelley, the film never reaches much more than a TV
movie of the week mentality.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ELMO (Undated) _ ``The Adventures of Elmo in Grouchland''
is certainly an improvement on the last installment of Muppet
mayhem, ``Muppets From Space.'' And better, the film is geared
specifically to toddlers and small kids and retains the essence of
the TV show, ``Sesame Street.''
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PLUNKETT (Undated) _ ``Plunkett &AMP; Macleane'' almost
convinces us it's a little different because of its breathtaking
production design and costuming. But don't be fooled. Beneath its
extraordinary exterior coat of paint is a less-than-ordinary film.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-GUINEVERE (Undated) _ ``Guinevere'' is a gorgeous film that
purports to delve into the forbidden bond between an older man and
a very young woman.Though it won raves at the Sundance Film
Festival for what some viewed as a ``racy'' theme, the film is
hardly provocative. It's a surprisingly tame look at how an older
artist, who isn't much of a Lancelot, seduces a Guinevere every few
years, uses her as an assistant in his work and romantically
exploits or initiates her into his life.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-CRAZY (Undated) _ ``Drive Me Crazy'' is so badly plotted
and written that it rarely makes much sense, even with the
elementary story line. And just how much longer will Hollywood
insist upon driving us crazy with insipid romantic comedies about
two polar-opposite high school kids who, after sparring and trying
to get each other to change, find they're perfect together on the
eve of the big dance?
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-ANIMALFARM (Undated) _ Delivering the message is where TNT's
``Animal Farm'' falters. With astonishing animatronics and
computer-generated imagery, the film is a technological triumph on
the order of ``Babe.'' But even with ``Babe'' director John
