<SLUG> BC-INCOME-REPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS' INCOME UP 3.5 PERCENT IN 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Household incomes rose for a fourth consecutive year in 1998,
but disparities between the top- and lowest-paid Americans widened
at a time the nation is enjoying its longest peacetime economic
expansion, according to a US Census Bureau report released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The median income of Americans rose 3.5 percent last year,
reaching a record high of $38,885, up from $37,581 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's income level was one dollar higher than the previous
record of $37,884 _ in inflation-adjusted dollars _ reached in 1989
before the nation went into a deep slump in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' median income, however, has not yet returned to
the levels hit during the late-1980s boom, Census data show. Median
income is not the average income but the income level at which half
of all Americans earn more and half earn less.
</P>
<P>
   While incomes nationwide rose, the number of Americans living in
poverty fell last year by 1.1 million, to 34.5 million poor in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   That brings the nation's poverty rate back to about the same
level, statistically speaking, as the 13.1 percent low of 1989.
Declining poverty levels were led by the South, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best news is that these gains finally are being shared
with all groups, from the wealthiest to the poorest,'' President
Clinton said at a White House news conference after the bureau
released its annual income and poverty report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Census Bureau's report wasn't all rosy.
</P>
<P>
   The data show that US income inequality was little changed from
1997 and has steadily widened since 1980, providing yet more
evidence of what some economists contend is a growing economy of
haves and have-nots that has developed during the nation's long
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-paid 5 percent of Americans earned $132,199 or more;
the bottom 20 percent earned $16,116 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, Americans with incomes in the top 5 percent
earn at least 8.20 times more than Americans in the bottom 20
percent _ an insignificant change from 8.22 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's income disparity is far bigger than that which
existed in 1980, when the top-paid group earned 6.8 percent more
than the bottom group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how much income inequality has grown over the last
two decades,'' said Jim St. George, executive director of the Tax
Equity Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   St. George noted the data does not include capital gains earned
from real estate or stock market portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the alliance said the median income of the
state's residents was $42,344 in 1998, slightly below the 1997
income of $42,678.
</P>
<P>
   And although national incomes have caught up with income levels
reached a decade ago, Massachusetts' incomes have not:
Massachusetts' median income last year was 10.8 percent below the
1989 level of $47,436, inflation adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   Also dramatic was the drop in the number of poor Americans under
18 years of age. Their numbers fell to 13.5 million, or 18.9
percent, down from 19.9 percent in 1997. It was the first time the
poverty rate for children had been below 20 percent by a
statistically significant margin since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty rate among Hispanic Americans fell to 25.6 percent
from 27.1 percent, and for whites fell to 8.2 percent from 8.6
percent. The poverty rate for blacks stayed about the same in 1998,
holding at a record low of 26.1 percent reached last year.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty rate in the South fell to a record low of 13.7
percent in 1998 from 14.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between men's and women's earnings did not change
much either, with women earning 73 cents for every dollar earned by
men, compared to 74 cents in 1997. Women with a professional degree
faced the biggest pay gap, earning only 61 cents on the dollar
compared to men with a similar education.
</P>
<P>
   Median income rose in all four regions of the country. The
biggest increase was in the Midwest, where incomes climbed 4.4
percent to $40,600. Incomes increased 3 percent to $41,000 in the
West; 2.8 percent, to $40,600, in the Northeast; and 2.6 percent,
to $35,800, in the South.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
