<SLUG> BC-WTO-ENVIRONMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS BLAST CLINTON ADMINISTRATION TRADE
STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The heads of five major environmental organizations
Thursday blasted the Clinton administration for allegedly
abandoning environmental concerns as it prepares for this fall's
meeting of the World Trade Organization in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental groups that spoke out yesterday, including the
Sierra Club, the National Wildlife Federation and Friends of the
Earth, all claim to support global trade. But they warned that in
the interests of opening markets to American companies, the Clinton
administration is sacrificing core American values of environmental
protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are outraged about the behavior of the Clinton
administration in pushing trade at all costs,'' said Brent
Blackwelder, president of Friends of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the groups alleged that the United States has been
forced to weaken its protection for endangered sea turtles as a
result of WTO membership and that the United States is now
preparing to support changes to the WTO that could lead to
unfettered logging of third-world countries. They alleged that the
United States has changed clean air and endangered species laws to
comply with the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until trade rules incorporate core democratic values like
environmental stewardship, new trade agreements do not deserve and
will not garner public support, and right now the Administration is
doing little to change that,'' said Mark Van Putten, president of
the National Wildlife Federation. ``The environmental agenda that
has been set forth so far for the upcoming ministerial is
inadequate, and unless it is improved and improved soon, public
skepticism will deepen.''
</P>
<P>
   The criticism, coming from mainstream environmental groups that
work closely with the Clinton administration on many issues, gave a
boost to the credibility of some of the more radical groups
threatening to disrupt Seattle during the WTO meeting starting Nov.
30. The environmental leaders yesterday declined an opportunity to
distance themselves from any of the organizations or any of the
disruptive tactics being threatened by groups considering the use
of civil disobedience to hinder the WTO meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forthcoming WTO summit is shaping up to be probably the
most tense confrontation between the American government and its
people perhaps since the '70s,'' said Carl Pope, executive director
of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental groups, who also included Defenders of
Wildlife and the Center for International Law, want the Clinton
administration to fight against WTO oversight of forestry and
fisheries, to call for an assessment of the environmental impact of
previous WTO agreements, and to alter trade rules so there is more
deference to national environmental and health standards.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky's office, which
increasingly is garnering criticism for failing to respond to
concerns about the WTO, did not return several calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   However, on the U.S. Trade Representative's web site, Barshefsky
denies that the WTO is harmful to environmental protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each WTO member remains free to set its own appropriate levels
of environment, health and safety protections, and the United
States is committed to maintaining high levels of such
protection,'' says a document called ``America and the World Trade
Organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO Agreements simply provide that the environment,
health, and safety standards chosen by governments be fair and
transparent, and not be used as disguised barriers to trade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
