u a BC-HAZING-LAW-HNS &LR;      09-30 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAZING-LAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPELLATE COURT RULES STUDENTS MAY NOT BE COMPELLED TO REPORT
HAZING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In what is called the first ruling of its kind, a
Houston appellate court said Thursday that students who may have
participated in a hazing incident may not be compelled to report it
to school authorities.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the 14th Court of Appeals upheld a Brazos
County court at law that dismissed criminal charges against two
Texas A&AMP;M University students for not reporting hazing in a
precision rifle drill team.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion said forcing students to report hazing incidents in
which they may have participated violates their right against
self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate opinion did not say anything about the specific
hazing incident or the alleged role of the two students, Dusty Hugh
Boyd and Javier Chapa.
</P>
<P>
   Brazos County Attorney James Kuboviak said he could not comment
because he considers the case ongoing. He declined to elaborate,
saying only that the incident was connected to the Fish Drill Team
disbanded in 1997 after a member complained that upperclassmen beat
him and forced him to cut his shoulder with a knife.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sinder, a legal assistant to Chapa's father, Jose, who
represented his son in the appeal, said he did ``not remember'' the
specific allegations against the two students. Jose Chapa practices
in McAllen.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the boys were charged with is failure to report
themselves; in essence they are charged with a failure to
confess,'' Sinder said.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was the first time an appellate court examined the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   A state law designed to stop hazing says it is a misdemeanor for
anyone who has ``firsthand knowledge'' of the planning or
occurrence of a hazing incident at an educational institution to
not alert authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd and Chapa were initially indicted on charges of
participating in the alleged hazing and assault and not reporting
the incident. Prosecutors only pursued the not reporting charge.
</P>
<P>
   Eight students were charged, but information was not available
Thursday on disposition of these cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court is unable to reasonably construe (the reporting
requirement) in a manner that is not repugnant to the
constitutional protections regarding self-incrimination,'' said the
appellate opinion authored by Justice J. Harvey Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   The state law has a provision that could grant immunity to those
reporting hazings, but the appellate court said this would not
provide adequate protection, since it would be up to a judge
whether to grant the immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Sinder said students should be required to report hazing if they
have no fear of being charged with participating in crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the law itself was drawn up for good purposes,'' he
said. ``If you're in a fraternity and you're a pledge, and you see
several people get injured, you ought to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinder said he is not familiar with the history of the
anti-hazing law.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M officials said they did not have time Thursday to look
up the incident, but that confidentiality laws would likely prevent
their discussing the roles of particular students.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Paul Murphy and John Anderson concurred in the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
