u i BC-CHINA-REVOLUTION-NYT &LR;      09-30 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-REVOLUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS RECALLS CHINA'S OLD GUARD FALLING TO THE NEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mo.) (See also CHINA-ASSESS, CHINA-ANNIVERSARY) 
 Seymour Topping, former managing editor of The New York Times, was
a reporter for The Associated Press in China in 1949.  
(bl) 
 By SEYMOUR TOPPING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On April 22, 1949, Chiang Kai-shek's Nationalist capital,
Nanjing, lay prostrate before Communist troops swarming across the
Yangtze River in their climactic offensive of the Chinese civil
war.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in the preceding months, the former imperial capital of
Beiping (today known as Beijing) had surrendered to the Communists.
Chiang had retreated to Taiwan, taking with him the government
reserve of gold and silver bullion, national art treasures, his
elite army divisions and air force units.
</P>
<P>
   As the Communist troops approached Nanjing, where I was a
reporter for The Associated Press, it was in pandemonium. At the
airfield, frenzied Nationalist officials and the wealthy fought to
get aboard the last planes out.
</P>
<P>
   I watched in disbelief as a Nationalist general shouted orders
to soldiers to load his piano and other furniture abroad a military
plane. Mayor Teng Chieh, trying to escape with a car loaded with
300 million yuan from the city's treasury, was beaten by his
chauffeur and bodyguards, and his legs broken.
</P>
<P>
   As looters ravaged the city and time bombs left behind by the
Nationalists exploded at key installations, apprehensive diplomats
huddled in their barricaded embassies. A Peace Preservation
Committee of leading citizens and Communist underground workers
sought unsuccessfully to restrain the mobs as shooting broke out
and dead lay on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The palatial residences of Nationalist officials were the main
targets of thousands of poor who had swarmed up from the city's
slums. An old woman, her gray hair pulled back into a bun, wearing
a ragged black tunic and hobbling on tiny feet bound in the old
custom, happily carried off four elaborately embroidered cushions.
A grinning soldier, throwing away his rifle, gingerly made off with
a lamp in each hand.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hours of April 23, the massive gates of the walled
city of 1.2 million were ajar, looters continued to roam the
streets and flames reddened the skies.
</P>
<P>
   The city had been abandoned by its army garrison. The municipal
police had fled. At the dingy Cairo Hotel, the Peace Preservation
Committee headquarters, I learned that the Communists were expected
to enter through the Northwest Gate.
</P>
<P>
   About 3 a.m., accompanied by Bill Kuan, a Chinese reporter for
Agence France-Presse, I drove my jeep north along the Zhongshan Lu
thoroughfare toward the gate. Suddenly there was a shout of
``Stop!'' and two Communist soldiers with rifles converged on us
from the sides of the road. They were the advance patrol of the
column that was to enter Nanjing. They led us back to the gate, and
there I watched as the first Communist troops entered the capital.
</P>
<P>
   A Communist officer, who was urging his exhausted troops
forward, impatiently ordered me and Kuan to drive back into the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Gratefully I drove to the telegraph office, where, moments
before the cables were cut off, I was able to file a 60-word
bulletin to The Associated Press on the Communist troops' arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Calm was not restored until Communist troops, welcomed by
banner-waving university students, completed their takeover of the
city and planted their flag atop Chiang Kai-shek's Taiping Palace.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, thousands of Communist troops in their yellow-brown
uniforms and flat peaked caps sat in orderly lines along the
sidewalks, listening to talks by political commissars and singing
revolutionary songs. People from nearby houses brought hot water
and tea for them to drink.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon three Nationalist bombers, in the first of many
raids over the next months, strafed the airfield, trying
unsuccessfully to detonate fuel and ammunition dumps.
</P>
<P>
   My second encounter with the Communist troops that day went less
well. Soldiers entered the Associated Press compound and became
excited at finding me at a typewriter beside a shortwave radio. For
the next two days, I was confined to the compound, with soldiers
posted at the gate. But then they disappeared and I, like the few
other Western reporters remaining in Nanjing, was free to move
about and file articles.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the prices of daily necessities stabilized. Most
shops reopened, as did dance halls. Beggars disappeared from the
streets. Censorship was imposed on the local newspapers and radio.
</P>
<P>
   University students, enthusiastic about the new government,
gathered in public assemblies to sing songs that commissars had
taught them, with lines like, ``Reactionaries who exploit the
people deserve to be cut into thousands of pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 2, the U.S. ambassador, J. Leighton Stuart, left Nanjing
after the State Department rebuffed Mao Tse-tung's overtures for
diplomatic recognition, declaring that the United States would
retain ties with the Nationalist government on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   And it was also in August that people began grumbling about the
new Communist administration. Taxes had risen sharply even as the
city's commercial life withered. The local press reported of
sabotage and assassination of Communist officials in the
surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Ideological strictures on the universities and other spheres of
intellectual life tightened. In schools, factories and municipal
offices, study groups were formed to discuss Maoist theory and
participants were required to confess ideological sins. As the
``re-education'' campaign intensified, there was a decided change
in the private attitudes of many liberal intellectuals who had at
first welcomed the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   This change was visible in the attitude of J.C. Jao, my Chinese
assistant in the AP office. Jao, a graduate of the University of
Missouri journalism school in his late 40s, had taught at
universities and been editor of The Tsingtao Herald. Like many of
his liberal friends, he was impressed by the good conduct of the
victorious Communist troops and caught up in the talk of China's
``liberation.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time I left Nanjing for Shanghai in September,
leaving him in charge of the office, he had become distrustful of
the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Beiping, now renamed Beijing (or northern
capital), was restored as China's capital, and it was there that
Mao, on Oct. 1, proclaimed the establishment of a People's
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Some months later, Jao said that he had been interrogated and
sent on an indoctrination course. He said that he was resisting
taking a job with the Communists writing anti-American propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1951 the Communists mounted a campaign for ``the
punishment of counterrevolutionary offenses.'' It led to the
executions over the next two years of an estimated 1 million to 3
million people. Jao was among the first to be shot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
