u a BC-ALA-MISSING01-COX     09-30 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-MISSING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    6 bodies pulled from Ala. river
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lamar Junior Stackhouse paid $3,000 for his burgundy,
1986 Chevrolet Caprice with chrome custom rims. He bought it on a
Friday, his father recalls. The seller drove nearly 150 miles from
Tallahassee, Fla., to Stackhouse's home in Enterprise, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Stackhouse picked up five friends. They drove 25
miles west, mostly on Ala. 134, across Ballard's Bridge, and into
the town of Opp for an evening at the Hideaway nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   They left the Hideaway in the wee hours Sunday morning _ then
vanished into the pre-dawn darkness of rural south Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   That was in May. There was no trace. Stackhouse was still
missing on his birthday, Sept. 3, when he would have turned 26.
Some residents speculated that the six black men and women had been
abducted as part of a hate crime.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the NAACP urged a more aggressive search. On the
group's national hotline, a spokeswoman read a statement attributed
to NAACP President Kweisi Mfume that said, ``An investigation by
the FBI is certainly warranted because of the circumstances
surrounding this case, and Alabama's history of civil rights
violations.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, investigators found the four-door Caprice
submerged in 9 feet of water in the Pea River near Ballard's
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Myron Williams, chief sheriff's deputy for Coffee
County, Ala., said, ``The evidence looks to be just an accident.
Just went off the road and into the river.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Alabama Bureau of Investigation said
Thursday that initial forensic tests show no evidence of foul play
and that the wrecked car displays signs ``consistent with an
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   None of that is of comfort to Woodrow Stackhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after his son disappeared, he rode up and down Ala.
134 searching for an accident site.
</P>
<P>
   He found tire tracks under Ballard's Bridge, four feet from the
river. No skid marks. Just tracks. Stackhouse said he went to
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine how I feel, knowing it was there for four
months?'' Stackhouse said Thursday. ``It was hard. It was real
hard. I feel bad that I was there three days after the accident.''
The driver failed to handle a turn just before the bridge and
rolled down a steep embankment, killing everyone, Sheriff Ben
Moates said.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow Ballard's Bridge, which does not meet current
standards, will be replaced, Gov. Don Siegelman announced last week
at the Pea River. Four people died last year on a crash on the
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   On June 3, divers and cadaver-searching dogs searched the same
area but found nothing. The water was 10 feet higher and moving
more swiftly at the time. At least three other times, divers
searched nearby rivers while other officials flew overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went back over the bridge hundreds of times,'' Williams
said. ``We were just starting over.''
</P>
<P>
   Divers went back into the Pea River on Wednesday and spotted a
Chevy with wide tires. A wrecker was called. It took more than
three hours to pull the car up a 20-foot embankment. Four bodies
were found in the car. Groans and prayers filled the air as the car
creeped up the river bank.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, divers found two more bodies in the river.
Investigators are analyzing dental records.
</P>
<P>
   Family and friends anguished for months over the missing:
Stackhouse, Eula Jossett Lee, 27, and Angela Roberts Young, 26, all
of Enterprise; Valerie Jones McCoy, 27, of Level Plains; James
Anthony Reynolds, 28, of Webb; and Tamara Monique Ward, 22, of
Ozark.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's closure but it's heartbreaking,'' said Cliff
Johnson, whose wife is the aunt of one of the missing. ``It's been
a mental strain the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Christina Johnson was a cousin of two of the missing women.
``The girls taught us to make peanut butter cookies,'' she said.
Despite signs of an accident, Woodrow Stackhouse wonders if
something worse happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think someone did something to him,'' Stackhouse said. ``My
son just bought that car. Maybe someone was after who had owned the
car'' before.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Mobile Register, which cited legal records,
Lamar Junior Stackhouse was unemployed and had an extensive
criminal history and had been convicted of dealing cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   But Stackhouse said he didn't think his son's past had anything
to with his death. In recent weeks, Lamar Stackhouse talked about
returning to junior college to learn about computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a nice, fun-loving person,'' Stackhouse said.
``And now, a part of me is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
