<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-SECURITY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE GEARS UP TO DEAL WITH ANTICIPATED WTO PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Fire trucks will be strategically placed downtown.
Ambulances will be ready. Dogs will sniff for bombs.
</P>
<P>
   And in buildings near the convention center, officers in riot
gear will be waiting, watching and hoping they are not called.
</P>
<P>
   If they are, something has gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The security plan for the World Trade Organization meeting in
Seattle is still a work in progress, and officials, of course, are
reluctant to release specifics.
</P>
<P>
   But this much is known: The city will spend $6 million on
security during the WTO conference. Eighty percent of Seattle's
police force _ virtually any officer who might come in contact with
protesters _ will go through nine hours of training. And several
downtown streets will be blocked off during some of the busiest
shopping days of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The city's police and fire departments, the State Patrol and a
dozen federal agencies _ from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms to the State Department's Diplomatic Security Division _
have been working on the security plan for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that time has been spent looking at what happened at
other WTO conferences. During a 1998 meeting in Geneva, for
example, the Jamaican ambassador's car was overturned and several
blocks of the city were damaged during a riot.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, organized labor, angry over WTO treaties it says has
taken away union jobs, has rented the Kingdome for a Nov. 30
protest. Environmentalists, decrying the organization's
environmental policies, plan rallies, too.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO conference runs from Nov. 29 to Dec. 3 and will be the
largest trade conference held on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   So there is a plan, exquisitely detailed with pages of ``What
ifs?'' and ``What thens?'' It deals with riots and chemical or
biological attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been sitting in on some of the meetings,'' said Greg
Petersen, with the city's budget office. ``And with some of the
contingencies they're planning on, I don't know how these guys
sleep at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters are inevitable, so police are trying to reach them
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to talk to them beforehand,'' said Seattle Police
Capt. Brent Wingstrand, who is helping coordinate the department's
WTO plans. ``We'd like to see if we can accommodate them _ do they
want a photo opportunity? _ in a way that no one goes to jail and
everyday citizens' lives aren't disrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the crowds, Seattle will shift officers in its
patrol division to 12-hour days. And patrol will ``borrow'' from
other units, such as burglary and vice. Detectives will be put back
in uniform for the duration of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Other agencies will see their resources stretched by the
conference, too.
</P>
<P>
   For example, each dignitary requires a motorcycle escort. That
means all of Seattle's motorcycle officers, all of King County's
motorcycle officers and all of the State Patrol's local motorcycle
officers will be busy. And they have contingency agreements with
other municipalities to provide more motorcycles and officers.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Police and State Patrol drivers have undergone Secret
Service and FBI training learning how to defend a motorcade from
attack. And there will be more State Patrol officers on area
highways.
</P>
<P>
   But no one can compete with Tukwila, which has to provide
security for a Nov. 30 dinner at the Museum of Flight at Boeing
Field.
</P>
<P>
   The county sheriff's department, which is responsible for
security at Boeing Field, will lend a hand, but Tukwila will be
taking the brunt of the museum's security.
</P>
<P>
   Like Seattle, Tukwila's 75-officer department will convert its
follow-up units to uniform patrol to augment security at the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to use everybody,'' Tukwila Police Capt.
Doug Patrlow said. ``We're still in the planning stages, but I
think you'll find us looking for support from the other cities.''
</P>
<P>
   The security for the Museum of Flight gala underscores the
workings between federal and local law enforcement agencies, and it
provides a glimpse of the potential threats each side must deal
with.
</P>
<P>
   Local police will primarily face protesters. The federal
agencies are concerned about terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   In all probability, a federal explosives team will sweep the
venue before the gala. After they pronounce the area secure, the
local police _ King County and Tukwila _ will then try to make sure
nothing happens at the event.
</P>
<P>
   If the gala's attendees are heads of state _ perhaps President
Clinton or Cuban President Fidel Castro, as has been rumored _ the
Secret Service will have protective details working.
</P>
<P>
   If the attendees are lower than heads of state but still
sufficiently high-ranking, agents from the State Department's
Diplomatic Security division will provide security.
</P>
<P>
   And some delegations, such as South Korea and Japan, will
probably bring their own security forces with them.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around during the conference won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, where many of the
delegates are coming in, will be especially busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to encourage delegates not to engage in media
opportunities on the premises,'' Port of Seattle spokesman Bob
Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get everyone involved through the airport as fast
possible to make as few problems as we can for our regular airport
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Securing the convention center means snarling Seattle's
endemically bad traffic. It means blocking off streets and manning
the tunnel beneath the convention center to make sure no one parks
an explosive-filled truck there.
</P>
<P>
   The event will stretch the city's emergency services, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at downtown as a `city-within-a-city,''' said
Assistant Fire Chief A.D. Vickery. ``So we added more fire and EMS
staff there.''
</P>
<P>
   The additional fire and rescue equipment will be stationed
within a set radius _ the exact distance is yet to be determined _
of the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   The units, staffed by otherwise off-duty personnel, will be
mobile, and they form the heart of the fire department's part of
the security plan: The Incident Response Team.
</P>
<P>
   The fire department will set up a 24-hour command center near
the conference, in part to monitor fire alarm boards at the hotels
where dignitaries are staying.
</P>
<P>
   Scaled-down versions of the department's hazardous-material and
technical-rescue teams will in the area, too, and the department
will keep two trailers full of specialized rescue and firefighting
equipment close at hand.
</P>
<P>
   How much will all of this cost?
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $6 million the city will spend, the county
sheriff's department will have to ask the King County Council for
between $600,000 and $1 million to cover expenses, said John
Urquhart, a sheriff's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There is hope the federal government might reimburse the city
and county for some of the expenses. The Seattle Host Committee _
which brought the conference here in the first place _ has already
committed $1.5 million to reimburse various agencies their public
safety costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't hope to get everything back,'' said Roger
Ramsey, the fire department's assistant chief for special
operations. ``It's like when you throw a party and invite the
neighbors, you have to pay for some punch and chips to serve
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
