<HEADER>
A2643 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-'TIS-REVIEW-TEX     09-30 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-'TIS-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCOURT'S IRISH VOICE SPEAKS WITH THE RING OF REALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM FUQUAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   'Tis: A Memoir
</P>
<P>
   by Frank McCourt
</P>
<P>
   Personal history
</P>
<P>
   Scribner, $26
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, a young Irish immigrant earned his degree from New York
University and landed a teaching job at McKee Vocational and
Technical High School on Staten Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   His students were not scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teacher, ain'tcha gonna take the attendance?'' was Frank
McCourt's welcome to his first class. He inherited his charges
midterm, after their instructor, one Miss Mudd, abruptly resigned
the instant she glimpsed freedom in the person of her successor and
offered her parting advice:
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a good view of New York Harbor from here, and Monday
morning if these kids aren't driving you crazy you'll see a big
ship sailing by and that'll be me on the deck, waving and smiling,
because there's two things I never want to see again in my life,
with God's help, Staten Island and kids. Monsters, monsters. Look
at 'em. You'd be better off working with chimpanzees in the Bronx
Zoo. What's this? Nineteen and fifty-eight. How did I ever last?
You'd need to be Joe Louis. So, good luck, son. You're gonna need
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The luck is his students'. Before he is promoted to the city's
elite public high school, he has thrown out the official curriculum
and the kids are reading Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   But luck is hardly for McCourt. Anyone familiar with ``Angela's
Ashes,'' McCourt's 1996 memoir, could tell you that. His first
volume, which won the Pulitzer Prize, recounted his birth in
Brooklyn to Irish immigrants and his hardscrabble childhood back
amid the streets of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   It's not necessary to have read McCourt's previous volume to
enjoy `` 'Tis'' _ only to enjoy a life recited in rhythm, employing
language from both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   As if building one of the stone walls found on his rocky Irish
native land, McCourt piles word after word, end on end, one atop
another. In the end, the structure is so honest and tangible, so
finely crafted, that you feel every rough edge and smooth, rounded
surface and know that they are real.
</P>
<P>
   This telling commences in 1949, aboard the HMS Irish Oak out of
Cork.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were to be 14 passengers on the ship but one canceled
and we had to sail with an unlucky number. The first night out the
captain stood up at dinner and welcomed us. He laughed and said he
wasn't superstitious over the number of passengers but since there
was a priest among us wouldn't it be lovely if His Reverence would
say a prayer to come between us and all harm. The priest was a
plump little man, born in Ireland, but so long in his Los Angeles
parish he had no trace of an Irish accent. When he got up to say a
prayer and blessed himself four passengers kept their hands in
their laps and that told me they were Protestants. My mother used
to say you could spot Protestants a mile away by their reserved
manner. The priest asked Our Lord to look down on us with pity and
love, that whatever happened on these stormy seas we were ready to
be enfolded forever in His Divine Bosom.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon disembarking, McCourt seeks work. A worldly priest steers
him to the local Democratic Party headquarters _ (''another vote
for the party if the kid here ever votes,'' his benefactor
explains), where he receives a reference to the Palm Court Hotel.
With his Irish brogue, his appalling, inflamed eyes and cursory
schooling, his prospects are limited to a notch above the kitchen
jobs destined for Puerto Ricans. But his boss, Mr. Carey, tells
McCourt that his future is unlimited.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells me keep my eye on the ball, don't forget to take a
shower every day, this is America, stay sober, stick with your own
kind of people, you can't go wrong with the Irish, go easy with the
drink, and in a year I might rise to the rank of porter or busboy
and make tips and, who knows, rise up to be a waiter and wouldn't
that be the end of all my worries. He says anything is possible in
America. Look at me, I have four suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Carey is pretty much right.
</P>
<P>
   After a stint in the Army, McCourt decides to enroll at New York
University. Despite never attending high school, he promotes
himself as college material because he has read ``Crime and
Punishment'' and ``Moby-Dick.'' He is approved for two courses, a
light load that allows him to keep working in meat warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in heaven, and the first thing to do is buy the required
textbooks, cover them with the purple and white NYU book jackets so
that people in the subway will look at me admiringly.''
</P>
<P>
   College is more like purgatory. It's easy to forget that McCourt
wasn't far removed from that time and place when signs declared
``No Irish Need Apply.'' A literature professor spots his
so-obvious Irish name and humiliates him for confessing a love for
the writing of Jonathan Swift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he tells the class that my essay is a perfect example of a
simplistic approach to literature, that while `Gulliver's Travels'
may be enjoyed as a children's story it is important in English
literature, not Irish, ladies and gentlemen, for its satiric
brilliance.'' As class ends we slink with McCourt down six flights
of stairs ``so I don't have to be in the elevator with students who
might despise me for enjoying `Gulliver's Travels' for the wrong
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   We revel with him when later he earns praise for the same
undisguised appreciation of great storytelling. And again when, at
their first chance meeting, his future wife (an Episcopalian)
``passes and gives me a little smile that I wonder why God is so
kind to me that He lets me have a smile from the loveliest girl in
all of NYU.'' And we want to throttle him when his irresponsible
drinking threatens to wreck the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   McCourt provokes that range of emotions the only way a writer
can: with stories that carry the ring of truth. The pealing seems
likely to call as many readers to this volume as responded to his
first installment.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
