<SLUG> BC-GREENSPACE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Babbitt praises Ga. governor on environment
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Standing on the bank of the Chattahoochee River in
Atlanta on Thursday, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt called Gov.
Roy Barnes' efforts to protect Georgia's green space a ``model for
all over this land.''
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt also urged support for federal legislation that would
provide millions of dollars to build new parks and protect more
land in Georgia and other states.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes is calling for counties to protect at least 20 percent of
their land from development and is pushing for a 180-mile-long
greenway on each side of the Chattahoochee from Helen to Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with Barnes on Thursday on the river's edge, Babbitt
said he expects green space protection will be a major issue in
next year's presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   He said securing full funding of the so-called Land and Water
Conservation Fund by Congress this year is one of his top
priorities. The fund, created in 1965, includes money from the sale
of federal offshore oil and gas leases. Most of the fund was
intended for preserving the nation's natural landscape.
</P>
<P>
   If the fund were fully operational, Georgia would receive almost
$10.3 million a year. Since 1965, Georgia has received $66.5
million from the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``The promise of the Land and Water Conservation Fund has never
been fully kept,'' Babbitt said. ``It was to provide almost $1
billion a year through direct federal purchase and through grants
to states that could then be used to protect land and open space.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Congress has usually approved less than one-third of
the money available. One reason is that some legislators,
particularly those from Western states, have objected to the
government's acquiring more land.
</P>
<P>
   Full funding of the fund is a major component of the ``Lands
Legacy'' initiative proposed in January by President Clinton. His
initiative would provide almost $1 billion a year in federal money
to protect a variety of sites, historic spaces and open lands
across the nation. It also would make available more funds for
parks and for wildlife conservation and restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Several bills now pending in Congress would increase funds for
preservation and conservation. One bill, the so-called Conservation
and Reinvestment Act of 1999, would provide about $22 million a
year to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Federal legislators will hammer out a final version from the
various bills.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
