<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Oct. 3,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-JAZZ-MUSICIANS (New York) _ In the last few years, the New
York downtown music scene has undergone a startling mutation,
albeit one not immediately audible to the innocent ear. Clubs like
the Knitting Factory and Tonic stillfeature many of the usual
musicians, some of them now approaching 50. The music has largely
retained its brash, collage-driven spirit. But beneath the
appearance of continuity, a paradigm shift has emerged. Once known
for their rootless cosmopolitanism, downtown musicians are now
passionately searching for roots _ not necessarily their own. By
Adam Shatz. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TERENCE-STAMP-FILMS (subslug) (London) _ At the age of 60,
white-haired and soft-spoken, Terence Stamp has evidently come to
terms with that other Terence Stamp who became an overnight star in
Peter Ustinov's 1962 movie version of ``Billy Budd,'' that
high-living younger self who was a fixture in English tabloids as
an icon of the Swinging '60s. But he still can't help wondering
why, when the 1970s arrived, he vanished from the screen. Now, in
Steven Soderbergh's new movie, ``The Limey,'' which opens in New
York on Friday, the young and the old Terence Stamps have been
brought together in a novel way. ``The Limey,'' which is slang for
a Briton, has Stamp playing Dave Wilson, a tough Cockney ex-con who
travels to Los Angeles to avenge what he believes is the covered-up
murder of his daughter, Jennifer. By Alan Riding. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BOYS-DON'T-CRY-FILM (Undated) _ Most actresses know that their
careers are largely dependent on their looks. But last year, Hilary
Swank had to worry about her appearance both as actress and actor.
``Its absolutely amazing what happens when a woman chops her hair
off,'' said Ms. Swank, who cut hers to play a woman passing as a
young man in the film ``Boys Don't Cry.'' The movie, opening on
Friday, tells the tale of Teena Brandon, a young woman from
Nebraska who abandoned her identty to embark on a new life as
Branda Teena. A true story that ended in 1993 when she was murdered
by two male friends enraged by the deception. By Ted Loos.
(Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   DREAM-OF-LIFE-VIDEO (subslug) (Undated) _ ``Sergei, you are a
true Bolshevik,'' Joseph Stalin is said to have exclaimed to Sergei
Eisenstein, clapping him on the back, after viewing ``Alexander
Nevsky.'' In the late 1930s one appreciated that kind of reaction
from Stalin, and it certainly was opportune for a director whose
prior lack of enthusiasm for the state and the Communist revolution
had stalled his career for almost 10 years. With ``Alexander
Nevsky,'' his first film with sound, Eisenstein climbed back into
official favor. By Peter M. Nichols. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DAME-EDNA-THEATER (New York) _ In previews at the Booth Theater,
where it opens on Oct. 17, ``Dame Edna'': The Royal Tour,'' is the
Broadway debut of a cross-dressing character whose ``natural
wisteria'' hair color, and penchant for gladioli and calling her
audience possums are more famous in Britain and her homeland of
Australia than the drag queen Ru Paul is here. Although less
well-known in America than in any other English-speaking part of
the world, Dame Edna Everage has had no trouble so far drawing a
celebrated audience. By Frank DeCaro. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSICALS-DANCING (New York) _ In the last couple of seasons, the
musical theater, both in New York (``Fosse,'' ``Footloose'') and in
London (``Oklahoma!,'' ``Swan Lake'') seems to have rediscovered
dancing _ not as an ornament or a practical interlude to entertain
the audience while the actors or singers change costume, but as a
resource in itself that can help advance the themes or story of a
show, or, in the cases of ``Fosse'' and ``Swan Lake,'' embody them
fully. By Mindy Aloff. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   LIMON-DANCE (New York) _ As a dance student at the Juilliard
School in the 1960s, Carla Maxwell studied with both Jose Limon and
Antony Tudor, two of the century's seminal choreographers. Aside
from their Juilliard connection, the two _ the first a pillar of
midcentury American modern dance, the other a master of subtle,
psychologically astute classical ballets _ were not likely to find
their paths crossing. But they will now. Works by these
choreographers will share a program when the Limon Dance Company,
of which Ms. Maxwell is the artistic director, comes to the Joyce
Theater starting Tuesday for a two-week season. The troupe will
perform Tudor's 1937 masterwork ``Dark Elegies'' alongside Limon's
``There Is a Time,'' from 1956. By Susan Reiter. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KERNIS-MUSIC-AWARD (Undated) _ The track record of some of the
Pulitzer Prize awards for music in recent years seems destined to
guarantee even greater bafflement for future auditors. Even now,
who can fail to be stumped by the 1990 prize awarded to Mel
Powell's ``Duplicates: A Concerto for Two Pianos and Orchestra''
over John Corigliano's greatly esteemed (and widely performed)
Symphony No. 1? Notwithstanding the occasional inscrutable
decisions, few could disagree with the 1998 Pulitzer Prize awarded
to Aaron Jay Kernis for his String Quartet No. 2 ``musica
instrumentalis''. As performed by the Lark Quartet on a recent
Arabesque disc (Z6727) coupling the award-winning work with its
predecessor, Kernis's String Quartet No. 2 is revealed as one of
the finest American string quartets written in the last two
decades, and, perhaps, much longer than that. By Lawrence A.
Johnson. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAMMESES-PHOTOGS (Paris) _ After a series of gifts and sales of
their treasures to the Bibliotheque Nationale and the Musee d'Orsay
in Paris as well as to the J. Paul Getty Museum in Santa Monica,
Calif. (now in Los Angeles), and the Metropolitan Museum of Art in
New York, Andre Jammes and his wife, Marie-Therese have sent to
auction much of what is left of their ``magnificent obsession,''
said Philippe Garner, the director of the photography department at
Sotheby's in London. Thirty of the most important photographs and
albums are on exhibit through Tuesday at Sotheby's in New York. The
sale of the collection, 2,000 images in 280 lots, will take place
on Oct. 27 in London. By Rita Reif. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MORIYAMA-PHOTOGS (Undated) _ One of the pleasures of the
relatively young field of photographic history is that discoveries
are still possible and neglected areas can be filled in. Right now
New York is playing host to three shows of the photography of Daido
Moriyama, born in 1938 and one of Japan's most respected and
influential contemporary photographers. By Vicki Goldberg. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-ARISTOCRATS (Undated) _ The ``Mobil Masterpiece Theater''
version of ``Aristocrats'' is (a three-part production beginning
next Sunday night on PBS). An era of powdered wigs, corsets,
bustles and towering plumed headdresses may seem an unlikely place
to discover strong, intelligent women taking charge of their lives,
but the second half of the 18th century was a time of great social
change in Britain. By Anita Gates. (Moved).
</P>
