<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, OCTOBER 1
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-INDIAN-MUSEUM-NYT (moved on Tuesday, Sept. 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, Sept. 28,
about the groundbreaking for the National Museum of the American
Indian misstated the previous occupation of Kevin Gover, who now
heads the Bureau of Indian Affairs. He was previously a lawyer in
private practice. He is not a law professor at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INFANT-SLEEP-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Sept. 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Sept.
29, about the Consumer Product Safety Commission's warning against
having children under 2 sleep in adult beds misstated the given
name of a woman in Fremont, Calif., who says she and her husband
sleep with their infant daughter. She is Valerie Wright, not
Jennifer.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-COCHRAN-NYT (moved on Wednesday, Sept. 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, Sept.
29, about Johnnie L. Cochran Jr.'s new post at a New York personal
injury law firm misstated the location of a fatal crash last year
that led to a case on which he worked. It was in Brooklyn, not
Queens.
</P>
