<SLUG> BC-MARS-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA BLAMES DESTRUCTION OF MARS PROBE ON MEASUREMENT MIX-UP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An embarrassing mix-up with its aerospace contractor over the
use of English and metric units of measurement led to the
navigational errors that caused last week's loss of the $125
million Mars Climate Orbiter, NASA said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials believe the probe broke apart or overheated in
the atmosphere Sept. 23 as it was maneuvering into orbit around
Mars after a near 10-month journey from Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Errors that crept into maneuvering commands, based on
discrepancies from the two systems of measurement, allowed the
spacecraft to sweep within 37 miles of the Martian surface rather
the intended 93 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The errors were repeated throughout four major maneuvers and
other smaller steerings during the Climate Orbiter's journey, which
began with a Dec. 11, 1998, liftoff from Cape Canaveral, Fla.
Previously, NASA had believed a one-time error in the last of the
major maneuvers, Sept. 15, was responsible for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday's disclosure, the space agency embraced
responsibility for the mistake, rather than haggle over sharing
blame with Lockheed Martin Astronautics, the Denver-based aerospace
company that builds its Mars probes and furnishes mission support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have caught this,'' said Carl Pilcher, NASA's
Washington-based chief scientist for solar system exploration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our inability to recognize and correct this simple error has
had major implications,'' said Edward Stone, director of NASA's Jet
Propulsion Laboratory, the Pasadena, Calif.-based facility that
developed the spacecraft and served as its mission control.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the Mars Polar Lander, a companion spacecraft
similarly launched Jan. 3, depends on a close working relationship.
Polar Lander is in the home stretch of a voyage to soft land at the
planet's South Pole and dig for signs of frozen water in the
subsoil.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the space agency could not rule out the prospect of
a similar failure to convert the English metric units provided by
Lockheed Martin Astronautics  &UR;  &LR; into the metric units used by JPL to
communicate with the probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our highest priority. We are checking it out as
aggressively as humanly possible,'' Pilcher said. ``You can correct
a navigational error almost at any time until you arrive at your
target. So if there has been any error made in the Mars Polar
Lander, we have plenty of time between now and arrival at Mars to
correct it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin did not respond to requests for comment, but
acknowledged a role in the loss late Thursday in comments to The
Associated Press. ``We should have had them in metric units,'' said
Noel Hinners, the company's vice president for flight systems.
</P>
<P>
   According to the space agency, the mix-up was over Lockheed
Martin's use of pounds of force, an English unit used in the U.S.
corporate aerospace community, to calculate steering commands for
the Climate Orbiter, and JPL's use of Newtons of force, a metric
measurement.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the two facilities managed to work successfully to
steer the Mars Global Surveyor successfully into orbit around the
Red Planet in 1997. Global Surveyor's cameras are currently
photographing the rugged Martian terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Two investigative panels at JPL and a third independent review
panel, which NASA administrator Dan Goldin will soon name, will
determine to uncover the breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same people, the same contractor,'' said Pilcher.
``It worked flawlessly. So why didn't it work here.? We don't
know.``
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We have a good track record for success, and the
reason is not because people don't make mistakes. It's because we
have all the systems, processing and software for checks and
balances. All of that stuff is designed to detect human error, to
correct it before it does any harm. What happened in this case is
that all of those checks and balances and systems failed us. We
didn't recognize the error, and we didn't correct it.''
</P>
<P>
   The space agency has invested $356 million in the Climate
Orbiter and Polar Lander missions as part of a longer term,
multiprobe effort to determine whether the cold, arid climate of
Mars was once warm and wet enough to host even primitive life.
</P>
<P>
   The Climate Orbiter was to function as a weather satellite
measuring cloud, dust, temperature and wind speed changes in the
atmosphere throughout a full Martian year. It was also to serve as
the primary communications relay between the Polar Lander and the
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The Polar Lander, however, is equipped to communicate directly
with the Earth or through the already orbiting Global Surveyor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
