<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UGA-TEXAS01-COX     09-30 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-TEXAS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courts' rulings influence admissions policies across nation
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ University of Georgia President Michael Adams plunged
UGA into the unfriendly waters of the federal court system with his
decision Thursday to continue using race in the school's admissions
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the U.S. Supreme Court has consistently
struck down racial preference programs involving government
contracting and hiring. And the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
in an influential ruling in 1996, rejected racial preferences in
admissions at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court declined to consider the University of Texas'
appeal in the case filed by white plaintiff Cheryl Hopwood.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts have referred to the ``Hopwood effect'' as
universities across the country altered, or abandoned, race-based
admissions policies. Even though the 5th Circuit has no
jurisdiction over Georgia, former state Attorney General Michael
Bowers had asked the university system to treat the ruling as a
precedent.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 21 years since the Supreme Court directly addressed
a challenge to racial preferences in college admissions. In 1978, a
deeply divided court ruled as unlawful a racial quota system used
by the University of California-Davis medical school. The school
had reserved certain entrance slots for minorities, a program
challenged by rejected applicant Allan Bakke, who is white.
</P>
<P>
   But the late Justice Lewis Powell, writing for a 5-4 majority,
said that ``some'' consideration could be given to race to help
achieve a diverse campus.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, in his speech Thursday to the University Council, seized
on that precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``As was held by the U.S. Supreme Court in the Bakke case ... we
believe that using race as a factor in admissions, but not as a
sole determining factor, is a legitimate approach in Georgia,'' the
UGA president said.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Bolden of the NAACP Legal Defense Fund said he believes
UGA's admissions program would survive a Bakke legal test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is certainly a program that is fully consistent
with the law out there today,'' he said. ``This is an affirmative
action program which is carefully crafted and specifically drawn to
provide opportunities to have a diverse campus.''
</P>
<P>
   UGA's admissions program is not a quota, Bolden maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ensures that the school obtains highly qualified students
of all races,'' he said. ``And given the history of this
institution and given the significance of having an
African-American presence at this institution, the admissions
program is warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``history'' is the fact that UGA did not admit black
students until January 1961, when Hamilton Holmes and Charlayne
Hunter-Gault integrated the school, under court order.
</P>
<P>
   Curt Levey, director of legal and public affairs for the
Washington-based Center for Individual Rights, noted that the
philosophical composition of the Supreme Court has changed greatly
since the Bakke decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a decision like Bakke is the best the liberals can
hope for,'' he said. ``And I don't even think they would get
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Individual Rights represents white plaintiffs who
are suing the University of Michigan's race-based admissions
policies. A trial is not expected until next year. Lee Parks, the
Atlanta lawyer heading the case against UGA, said the university's
admission policies create racial set-asides that courts have
consistently rejected.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Avant Edenfield, who is presiding over the
case, already has strongly criticized UGA's racial preference
policy. Any appeals of Edenfield's eventual ruling would go to the
11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta and, possibly, to the
U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been to both of those places,'' said Parks, who has
successfully argued reverse discrimination voting rights cases
before both courts. ``These courts are not sympathetic to this
issue. They call it racial balancing, that's their buzzword. And if
UGA's plan can be reduced to a racial balancing approach, and I
believe it can, then it's out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
