u p BC-FUNDRAISING-REPORT-NY     09-30 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY RAISES MORE MONEY THAN GORE IN LATEST QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In another sign that his bid for the Democratic
presidential nomination is gaining strength, former Sen. Bill
Bradley has raised more money than Vice President Al Gore in the
last three months.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who on Thursday reported raising $6.7 million to Gore's
$6.5 million, has also spent substantially less than the vice
president and has more cash in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising juggernaut of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas,
meanwhile, continued to vacuum up donations at a record pace and
now has $37 million cash on hand. That is more than Gore, Bradley
and all of Bush's Republican rivals combined.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cemented his commanding financial position by raising $19
million in the period from July through September, bringing his
total for the first nine months of the year to more than $56
million. He has already announced that he will forgo federal
matching funds, freeing him to spend as much as he can raise
between now and the national nominating conventions next August.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, whose fund-raising prowess was once viewed as a critical
advantage over Bradley, had anticipated Thursday's bad news. On
Wednesday, the vice president announced that he was trimming his
staff and relocating his campaign headquarters from the K Street
lobbying corridor of Washington to Nashville in an effort to slow
spending and move his campaign closer to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Since the vice president will continue to live in Washington,
the move reflected the urgency of the campaign's need to conserve
money as much as a symbolic distancing of Gore from the Clinton
White House and the world of Washington insiders.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's campaign raised what aides said was a
disappointing $6.5 million in the third quarter and spent nearly
all of it. Gore has been forced to increase his fund-raising
targets for the rest of the year and has acknowledged that he will
have to continue to prospect for contributions early next year even
as he campaigns full time in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has raised $24.2 million this year and spent more than $14
million, leaving him currently with $9.7 million to $10 million in
the bank, Gore advisers said. Nearly half of his total spending has
been on fund-raising costs, including hiring professional
solicitors, direct-mail appeals and money-raising events like
dinners and receptions. The rest has gone to pay for a staff of
high-priced consultants, travel, overhead and organizations in
early primary states.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has raised $18.4 million since starting his exploratory
committee last December. In the past three months, he raised $6.7
million and spent slightly less than $4.2 million. His campaign
reported that he now has about $10 million cash on hand, enough to
remain competitive with the vice president deep into the primary
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on track to raise what we believed we needed to raise
for a competitive campaign,'' said Anita Dunn, Bradley's chief
campaign adviser. ``We're very encouraged by the fact that in this
third quarter we have seen a surge in the number of small
donations.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has kept his expenses down by traveling light and
keeping his campaign organization relatively small. Costs are now
rising, Ms. Dunn said, as the campaign opens offices in New
Hampshire and Iowa and builds a full-time staff.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's aides and advisers put a brave face on what appears to be
a grave situation for an incumbent who just a few months ago was
expected to have an easy path to the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has all the resources he needs to be able to take his
message to the people of Iowa, New Hampshire, New York, California
and beyond,'' said Chris Lehane, a Gore spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Gore adviser said the vice president would be
pressed for resources after the compressed primary season this
winter. He acknowledged that there would be little money left to
spend after April, and added, ``First we have to survive until
April.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Republican hopefuls, Sen. John McCain of Arizona
reported raising $3 million in the last three months, bringing his
total to $7 million for the year. Gary Bauer raised about $2
million, for a total this year of $5.4 million, most of it in small
donations that will qualify for federal matching money. Bauer has
$300,000 cash on hand, said Frank Cannon, his campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Elizabeth Dole, Kathleen Harrington, said Mrs. Dole's
campaign had raised about $1.5 million in the past three months and
$5 million this year. Ms. Harrington asserted, ``We're making
history'' by raising a majority of funds from women contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, who is now running as a Republican but flirting
with the idea of seeking the Reform Party's presidential
nomination, raised $1.6 million in the third quarter and has taken
in $4 million for the year. His campaign has about $250,000 in the
bank, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah has brought in $1.2 million since
announcing his long-shot bid for the White House this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, heir to a magazine publishing fortune, is
financing his own campaign and is therefore not dependent on
federal matching money or subject to federal election spending
rules. His campaign did not respond to a request for figures on his
spending to date.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's figures are unofficial estimates provided by the
campaigns. Final figures are due to be reported to the Federal
Election Commission on Oct. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
