<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOT POLICE CONFRONT ANTI-MILOSEVIC DEMONSTRATORS FOR SECOND
NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Riot police stopped a march of
anti-government demonstrators for the second consecutive night,
clubbing opposition leaders without provocation and stampeding
thousands of people back toward the center of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   After the clash Wednesday night, when demonstrators had tried
marching toward the suburb where President Slobodan Milosevic and
other leaders live, opposition leaders thought they had chosen a
noncontroversial destination, across the Sava River to New
Belgrade. But at least 300 police in riot gear moved quickly to
block the march on the Brankov bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The police action for the second night running made it clear
that Milosevic's government has decided to try to intimidate the
demonstrators and keep them hemmed in to central Belgrade, where
their nightly rallies have been authorized.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the financial police shut down the printing plant of
Glas Javnosti, an independent newspaper that has been printing the
daily bulletin of the opposition parties in the Alliance for
Change. Plainclothes policemen also surrounded the headquarters of
the opposition Alliance for Change, party officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of Milosevic's determination to use force, if
necessary, to prevent a popular uprising, leaders of the opposition
Alliance for Change faced their own stark choice: to push for
confrontation now, when the number of protesters remains relatively
small, or to try to avoid street battles and seek change through
larger demonstrations or early elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that Milosevic is prepared to use violence to
protect himself,'' Milan Protic, an opposition leader, said late
Thursday night. ``It's definite now that Milosevic is ready to do
anything, and we have to adapt our tactics. We don't want innocent
people to get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, when about 20,000 demonstrators tried to march
to Dedinje, where Milosevic lives, police stopped the march and
appeared to seek confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   That encouraged opposition leaders to call for more
demonstrators to come Thursday night, when they promised to try to
reach Dedinje again, and Democratic Party leader Zoran Djindjic
said he hoped as many as 100,000 would turn out.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, no more demonstrators came out to march Thursday
night, one reason Djindjic and the other Alliance leaders decided
to go instead to New Belgrade. Recent polls indicate that up to 70
percent of Serbs are afraid to participate in demonstrations,
fearing violence or the loss of their jobs, compared to only 40
percent in 1996, when Belgrade saw 88 days of pro-democracy
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Police were in no mood for negotiations Thursday night.
Djindjic, walking with other leaders at the head of the march,
stepped forward to talk with the policemen at the head of the
cordon blocking the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot go ahead,'' the police commander said to Djindjic.
``You are taking full responsibility if you go any farther.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Djindjic could say a word, policemen clubbed him on the
shoulder with a baton and also clubbed his aide, Cedomir Jankovic,
and then pressed forward, forcing the marchers to reverse course
off the bridge, whacking demonstrators with batons, arresting those
who taunted them and clubbing a woman who had fallen to the
pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at St. Sava Clinic said Thursday night that at least 15
people were brought to the hospital with light wounds and at least
one person was admitted with a severe concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Governing parties issued statements accusing the demonstrators
of instigating Wednesday night's violence _ which was untrue _ in
order to boost the poor turnout at the rallies. They also accused
the opposition of being in the pay of NATO and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday and Thursday night, police seemed particularly angered
by demonstrators' taunts that they should ``go to Kosovo,'' a
reprise of a taunt from the 1996-97 demonstrations. But Thursday
night, one policeman shouted back, ``And where were you?''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have painted Djindjic, who fled to Montenegro
during the bombing and spent much time in NATO countries then, as a
tool of NATO, trying to finish ``the aggression by other means'' by
overthrowing Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a speech to a few thousand protesters who gathered in
the Square of the Republic after the march was broken up, Djindjic
vowed to keep up his campaign against Milosevic, saying it was the
duty of his generation to bring ``the dictator down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only one life, but it must be worth living,'' he said.
``We must fight for that life, and if we must give victims for
that, then we must give them.'' He said that ``we are for
nonviolent methods.'' However, asked in an interview about the
pacifist Gandhi, he said that this was the Balkans, not India,
``and our enemy is not the British, but Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Alliance leaders asked demonstrators to return to Dedinje Friday
night, but in cars, busses and trucks, instead of on foot.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts began Thursday to bring all opposition parties together
on a common set of demands for free, early elections, as the main
opposition party, the Serbian Renewal Movement of Vuk Draskovic,
has been demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic has criticized these rallies as counterproductive and
repeated Thursday that the only effective method to produce
political change is by elections, not street protests.
</P>
<P>
   His party praised the negotiations as a step toward Draskovic's
platform, and Djindjic said the talks had begun well. But Alliance
officials said that street pressure would be vital to get Milosevic
to agree to any early elections, let alone to resign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2665 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-REHM-MEMOIR-TEX     09-30 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REHM-MEMOIR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOGRAPHY REVEALS SURPRISING TRUTHS ABOUT RADIO'S DIANE REHM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Finding My Voice''
</P>
<P>
   by Diane Rehm
</P>
<P>
   Memoir
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $24
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the ``Diane Rehm Show'' on National Public Radio is
a constant in the lives of many baby boomers. The same folks who
progressed from hard rock to rock, to oldies rock, have forgone all
rock to listen to Rehm's talk show. She's a morning delight. She is
well-informed. Her listeners, no matter how mighty, show her great
respect. She manages her call-in, no matter how contrary, with
great aplomb. She talks to both sides of controversial issues in a
soft, slow, quavery voice that echoes decades of living. Although
we never see her, we know she is old, she is wise, she is a
wrinkle-ravaged crone.
</P>
<P>
   Listener, hold the phone while we take this commercial break.
</P>
<P>
   Rehm's new book, ``Finding My Voice,'' is now on bookstore
shelves. There on the cover is Rehm, and Rehm is a babe _ a
blond-fluff bunny, with a big swirl of cotton candy hair, and a
pretty, hyperaccessorized, femmed-out personal style. She's not a
crone, not at all. And ... she's never been to college.
</P>
<P>
   No way, you say? Yes, way. She comes from an Arab family whose
members believed that college was unnecessary for girls. That's
another shock. We thought she was a Southern belle.
</P>
<P>
   That tremulous voice is not real either. Well, it's hers, but it
is not her natural voice. As her radio show went nationwide four
years ago, she began a battle with spasmodic dysphonia, a movement
disorder affecting the muscles that control speech. The cause is
unknown, there is no cure, but she is undergoing regular
treatments. Her voice is getting better.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Finding My Voice,'' Rehm details her odd childhood with a
mother who wielded psychological abuse as a disciplinary tool. To
escape, Rehm married young and divorced soon thereafter. She
married again; this union was rocky, as well. She dodged the
frustrations of home and family by running into the radio booth.
Then, just as she was finding her niche, accepting success and
managing her marriage, she began to lose her voice. At this exact
moment, Diane Rehm was introduced to America.
</P>
<P>
   Even as she struck a chord and began gathering a huge audience,
she was riddled with anxiety and constant self-criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Rehm is not the wise woman we believed her to be.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is her writing style as graceful as her interviewing
techniques. When the conversation becomes one-sided, with Rehm
alone on the page, she natters on much longer than she would ever
allow a guest to do. She tells us in excruciating, chronological
detail about all her jobs in radio. She wants us to meet every
doctor she met, and to share all the incorrect diagnoses. We must
turn page after page while she dithers about treatment. Rehm, it
seems, is the relative you don't want to sit next to at the
Thanksgiving dinner table. She has interviewed heads of state,
authors, activists and stars, and all she wants to write about is
how mean her mother was and her most recent doctor's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Within one chapter of the book is what the bottom-feeding minds
want to know: How do you handle the telephone jerks? She has a
lever she can use to fade out the long-winded, and a button to zap
hostile or abusive callers. What happens if a caller or guest uses
inappropriate words? Rehm is broadcast on a seven-second delay, so
she or her engineers can do a quick edit.
</P>
<P>
   Who were terrible guests? Tom Clancy, who mumbled
monosyllabically until listeners chastised him into good behavior.
Then there was septuagenarian actor Tony Randall, who, with a new
bride and new child, suggested that they should talk about the size
of his paternity equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Who are the perfect guests? Hillary Clinton and Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
   What we'd like from her book is more dish and less detail. But
that is not what Rehm is about. Mindless blather can be found on
any of a number of other stations; just push the button and listen
to the rock jocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding My Voice'' exposes Rehm as a fraud. She is not a
wonderful, revered crone. She is more human than ever imagined. She
is an insecure, hard-working woman with a troublesome husband, who
has the ear of thousands because she does her homework and she
listens well.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what Rehm has to say about what she does best:
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone asked me the other day whether talking with some of
the world's outstanding figures didn't leave me starstruck. I
acknowledge that my place behind the microphone affords me an
opportunity few people in this world enjoy, this is, to spend an
hour _ alone _ with people like these. I know how fortunate I've
been to have had that opportunity and to have had the vast majority
of guests, no matter how extraordinary, treat me with simple
kindness and respect. Which brings me to a point in which I believe
very strongly: You get what you give in this business. If you treat
guests, listeners and colleagues with respect, they will almost
without exception treat you in the same way. There have been many
times on the air when I could have responded angrily to the
comments of a guest or caller, and believe me, there have been many
times when I've wanted to. Perhaps that kind of outburst might have
been entertaining, and numerous talk-show hosts around the country
do use their guests as foils for their aggressive humor. I've
chosen to move in a different direction. I have a hard time
listening to that kind of harshness on the air, which is no doubt
why it's not part of my approach to broadcasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Rehm is not the woman we thought she was. In print, at
least, she's more interesting by far, at least when she focuses on
what readers really want to know. Now, welcome back to the show.
.MDBR/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
