<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATTY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President? Beatty won't try for part
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Although he hinted he won't be running
for president any time soon, actor Warren Beatty on Tuesday gave a
glimpse of what a Beatty campaign might look like: loads of
Tinseltown glamour, a strong measure of big government liberalism
and plenty of laugh lines.
</P>
<P>
   More than 160 members of the media from around the world, along
with 1,000 guests, crowded into the opulently decorated ballroom at
the Beverly Hilton _ the site of the annual Golden Globe Awards _
to hear what Beatty might or might not say about his political
ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Those ambitions became fodder for speculation six weeks ago when
political commentators began talking about a Beatty candidacy for
president, and some of Beatty's closest friends urged him to run.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty ridiculed the ``grand mentioners in the media'' who kept
fueling the speculation even after he had described a presidential
bid as ``highly improbable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on a listening tour of my house for the past six
weeks,'' he cracked.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that he was happily married to a woman ``half my age''
(actress Annette Bening), with three children and expecting a
fourth soon.
</P>
<P>
   And while he did not rule out a presidential bid, he did say,
``I like my day job, I like making movies, and I want to keep on
making them.''
</P>
<P>
   What Beatty really had on his mind, it turned out, was to chide
the Democratic Party for drifting to the right.
</P>
<P>
   He called both Vice President Gore and former New Jersey Sen.
Bill Bradley well-meaning centrists who had abandoned Democratic
principles. Beatty railed against the influence of money in
politics and called for universal health care coverage for all
Americans and an end to ``corporate welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the value of social programs,'' said Beatty, to
loud applause. ``I believe in the safety net, I believe in
regulation, I believe in activist government.''
</P>
<P>
   The dinner was sponsored by Americans for Democratic Action, a
liberal group that advocates steep defense cuts, campaign finance
reform and gun control. Beatty was honored with ADA's Eleanor
Roosevelt award. Vietnam activist Tom Hayden was in the audience,
along with pornography publisher Larry Flint, actress Courtney Love
and some of Beatty's closest Hollywood friends. Some guests sported
computer-made stickers that read ``Beatty 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of Hollywood celebrities also appeared on video to
praise Beatty or joke about his potential bid for president. ``I
want to be your running mate,'' said director Rob Reiner.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, actress Roseanne Barr said she wanted to run
against Beatty in 2000 on the platform of free plastic surgery for
everyone. The video reel also replayed some of Beatty's movies,
such as ``Reds,'' and, of course, the political satire
``Bullworth,'' which featured Beatty as a senator running for
president and speaking out about many of the same social themes he
mentioned Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd vote for him in a second,'' said Raoul O'Connell, 29, a
film director who conceded he knew about Beatty's politics only
through ``Bullworth.''
</P>
<P>
   In some places the idea of a movie star running for president
might seem far-fetched. But this is Hollywood, where a successful
acting career launched onetime actor Ronald Reagan into politics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even some of the celebrity guests marveled at the
prospect of a once notorious ladies' man occupying the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a single man a long time,'' said director Penny
Marshall, whose credits include ``A League of Their Own.'' ``The
girls would come out of the woodwork'' if he became president.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty's friends also hastened to describe him as a lifelong
political activist who was committed to liberal ideas, noting that
he once took a year off to work on George McGovern's failed
presidential bid in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has enormous intelligence and craggy, tough integrity,''
said actress Faye Dunaway, who starred with Beatty in ``Bonnie and
Clyde.'' ``Just don't underestimate him,'' she added emphat-
ically.
</P>
<P>
   Dustin Hoffman, who is supporting Bradley, described Beatty as a
passionate idealist who was ``frustrated that the system has a
hammerlock on the candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren represents us,'' said Hoffman. ``He can say anything he
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Hoffman couldn't resist a joke. Asked whom Beatty
should choose as a running mate if he should win the Democratic
nomination, Hoffman said, ``Now that's a good question. Who should
be his running mate? Susan Sarandon?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
