<SLUG> BC-KOREA-MASSACRE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 U.S. TO REVISIT ACCUSATIONS OF A MASSACRE BY GIs IN '50  
(js) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The secretary of defense ordered the Army on
Thursday to undertake a new and thorough review of reports that
U.S. soldiers killed Korean civilians at the beginning of the
Korean War nearly 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In an account published on Wednesday by The Associated Press, a
dozen American veterans confirmed accusations by Korean villagers
that in July 1950, hundreds of refugees were killed by U.S. gunfire
under a bridge near No Gun Ri in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen wrote to Louis Caldera, the
secretary of the Army, asking him to ``devote whatever resources
are appropriate to accomplish this review as thoroughly and as
quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   At a Pentagon briefing, Caldera said Thursday that the AP
investigation provided ``new information that demanded that it be
looked into.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These reports are of course very disturbing,'' Caldera said.
``Earlier this year our Army center for military history did a
search and found nothing in the official records that substantiates
the claims that U.S. Army soldiers perpetrated such massacres.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said he appreciated that Cohen had instructed
the Army to examine all the available information and evidence, and
``get to the bottom of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The government of South Korea announced Thursday that it would
start its own investigation, said Hebeom Kim, a spokesman at the
Korean Embassy here. He said South Korea might ask the United
States for declassified military documents.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera said that the new review would take at least one year
and would encompass all historical records, including those at the
National Archives, which were the source of much of the new
evidence uncovered by the AP, as well as interviews with U.S.
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it would not excuse the alleged acts, history records
that the early weeks of the Korean conflict were very chaotic,''
Caldera said. ``U.S. soldiers, although they fought with great
courage under very harsh conditions, were ill-trained and
ill-equipped to fight because of the large reduction in resources
available to the military for training and equipment following
World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 30 South Korean survivors and relatives of the victims
filed a suit asking for compensation for the incident, but the suit
was rejected on a technicality. The claimants had described a
three-day period of killing, saying that U.S. planes had strafed
hundreds of refugees who were fleeing from North Korean troops,
leaving about 100 people dead. The survivors fled under the bridge,
where they said they were pinned by U.S. troops who shot and killed
almost all the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews, some of the U.S. soldiers at No Gun Ri
said they had been ordered to fire on the refugees because their
commanders believed that North Korean troops, disguised as
peasants, had infiltrated the refugee column and were shooting at
the Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2103EDT &QL; 
