<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GA-AFFIRM-340&AMP;ADD-NYT     09-30 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-AFFIRM-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESISTING JUDGE, UNIVERSITY OF GEORGIA TO CONTINUE AFFIRMATIVE
ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Disregarding the strongly worded advice of a federal
judge, the University of Georgia announced Thursday that it would
continue to use race as a factor in admitting up to 20 percent of
its freshman class.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by university president Michael Adams on an
issue that has been the subject of intense debate for months puts
the school on a collision course with U.S. District Court Judge B.
Avant Edenfield, who has been hearing a series of challenges to the
university's admissions policy. In a non-binding opinion attached
to a related ruling in July, Edenfield said the university ``cannot
constitutionally justify'' the use of race in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Because at least one new court case challenging the policy has
already been assigned to Edenfield, it is likely that he will have
a fresh opportunity to issue a formal ruling against the school
soon. But Adams made it clear the university was reluctantly
willing to accept a prolonged legal fight and a series of appeals
in order to preserve the diversity of the student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that all of us have a responsibility to deal with
the legacy of segregation as an issue in both academe and
government,'' Adams said, in a speech that received a standing
ovation from the University Council, an advisory body of faculty,
administrators and students. ``My commitment to providing
opportunity to all is fundamental, and under my leadership the
University of Georgia will remain committed to this basic right.''
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly conservative legal climate, when other
schools have been backing away from their affirmative action
policies, Thursday's decision makes the University of Georgia one
of the most prominent schools to voice full-throated support for
racial preferences, particularly in the South. Hoping to banish the
memory of the school's all-white past, most of the state's
establishment has supported the admissions policy, including Gov.
Roy Barnes and even state Senate Republican Minority Leader Eric
Johnson.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Those who argue that the only fair method is a statistical
ranking of applicants' academic records miss an important point,''
Adams said. ``True fairness also includes a professional assessment
of unique family situations, the schools the student has attended,
the community he or she came from, and whether applicants had to
overcome economic hardships to build a record of academic
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Most students are admitted to the university without any
consideration of race. Between 80 and 90 percent of each incoming
class are admitted solely on the basis of their test scores and
high-school grades. The remaining 10 to 20 percent can have a
slightly lower academic record, but their chances are boosted if
they are non-white, or are the child of an alumnus, or the first in
a family to attend college, or if they have unusual talents and
civic accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the policy, only about 6 percent of this year's freshman
class of 4,200 students is African-American, compared with 30
percent of the state as a whole. About 15 percent of the class is
non-white. But even this modest use of race as a factor was enough
to prompt a lawsuit from A. Lee Parks Jr., an Atlanta attorney who
often represents clients trying to end affirmative action programs.
Parks on Thursday accused Adams of caving into pressure from
faculty members, and predicted extended new rounds of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a wonderful opportunity to base their admissions on
socio-economic factors that really demonstrated need, but instead
they've taken the same old road,'' said Parks. ``We'll be seeking
an immediate temporary injunction against this policy, and now the
litigation will come to a final head.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials, who clearly do not want black enrollment
to drop, are now taking a firm stand on the fairly shaky foundation
of the 1978 Bakke decision by the U.S. Supreme Court, which ruled
that race could be one factor used in admitting students, as long
as a quota system was not employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the legal landscape has become uncertain and
confusing since then,'' said Dan Coenen, a constitutional law
professor at the university's law school. ``But until the Supreme
Court speaks again, it's still the law of the land, and this
admissions policy is entirely acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams made it clear in an interview Thursday that a ruling by
the high court would be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unsettled legal area,'' he said, ``and we might all be
better served in the long term if it could be made more clear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
