<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COALITION01-COX     09-30 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COALITION01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christian Coalition blessings sought
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Though the Christian Coalition has been beset by
turmoil, most of the Republican presidential candidates will flock
to its Road to Victory '99 conference, which begins here today.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas will try to show that he can appeal
to socially conservative Republicans, even though his more centrist
campaign has downplayed abortion and other social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Only Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) is skipping the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The event is especially important to Steve Forbes, who once
belittled coalition founder Pat Robertson as a ``toothy flake'' and
asserted that the group did not speak for most Christians.
</P>
<P>
   But Forbes has become increasingly outspoken on social issues,
promoting what he calls ``the right to be born'' and criticizing
court decisions against school prayer and vouchers for private
schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Following his one-note 1996 campaign devoted to a proposed
single tax rate on income, Forbes has assiduously courted the
religious right, hoping to emerge as the choice of conservative
Republican primary voters who object to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said this week, for instance, that he would like his
first act as president to be signing into law a ban on
partial-birth abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes, now that he's been converted, has all the things the
social conservatives like to see in a candidate,'' said James Guth,
an expert on Christian conservatives who teaches at Furman
University in Greenville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' effort, as well as his considerable wealth, has
attracted about a dozen former state or regional officials of the
Christian Coalition and the Eagle Forum, another group of
conservative activists.
</P>
<P>
   That group includes Jerry Keen, former chairman of the Christian
Coalition in Georgia, and Christian activists in Iowa, New
Hampshire, South Carolina, Louisiana and Washington _ states with
early primaries or caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Forbes can turn this newfound support into a serious
challenge to Bush remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Keen warns that if Christian conservatives do
not rally around one candidate, ``it almost guarantees another
establishment candidate'' will be the GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Keen is serving as Forbes' coalitions director. Pleased with
Forbes' second-place finish in the Iowa straw poll, which Bush won,
Keen said the campaign showed its ability to turn out its
supporters. ``We've got grass-roots people and activists. They turn
out bodies,'' he said. ``Bush has Pat (Roberston) and Ralph (Reed,
the coalition's former executive director.)''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson has spoken highly of Bush, but has not endorsed him.
Reed is a paid adviser to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said that all the candidates, except for Bush, have the
same goal: ``Play the applause-meter game and emerge as the
proprietary candidate of grass-roots conservatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of most of the candidates in Washington indicates
that, despite the Christian Coalition's money troubles and staff
shake-up this year, ``evangelical Protestants represent a very
important constituency in the Republican party,'' Guth said.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, those voters make up a third of the
participants in the Iowa caucus, a quarter of the electorate in New
Hampshire and 40 percent in South Carolina. Those are the first
three significant Republican contests next year.
</P>
<P>
   When the campaign for the presidency began in earnest this year,
a half dozen candidates were vying for the votes of social
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But the field has narrowed considerably since then. Vice
President Dan Quayle withdrew from the race this week. Sen. Bob
Smith (R-N.H.) quit the Republican party to mull a third-party
candidacy, calling the GOP insufficently conservative. Pat
Buchanan, lagging in the polls, is considering taking his campaign
to the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Forbes and Gary Bauer, former president of the Family
Research Council, are the chief competitors in the Republicans'
race within a race. Radio commentator and former diplomat Alan
Keyes also is a candidate for the support of conservative voters.
</P>
<P>
   And events of recent days have seemed to benefit Forbes. Several
prominent Buchanan backers have moved to Forbes in protest of
Buchanan's flirtation with the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Jarvis, Bauer's national campaign chairman, also
defected to Forbes, saying he does not believe Bauer can win the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis also acknowledged this week that another factor in his
decision was his concern that Bauer was spending too much time with
a female campaign aide. Jarvis called the situation
``inappropriate.'' Bauer firmly denied having an affair.
</P>
<P>
   But Bauer and his campaign staff have accused Forbes' campaign
of spreading the rumors of an affair, a charge the Forbes camp
denies.
</P>
<P>
   Today's conference, which will include speeches by Bauer, Bush,
Elizabeth Dole and Republican congressional leaders, could mark a
new, contentious turn in the jockeying between Bauer and Forbes.
Forbes is scheduled to speak Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, a former domestic policy aide to Ronald Reagan, has a
strong claim on Christian conservatives, combining years of
opposition to abortion rights with his concern about religious
persecution in China, the Sudan and other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the contest between Bauer and Forbes will not matter
if Bush continues his march to the Republican nomination. Forbes is
a strong second to Bush in recent polls in Iowa, but in New
Hampshire and nationally, he and Bauer fare poorly in polls.
</P>
<P>
   And the Texas governor, while waging a centrist campaign that
plays down abortion and other social issues, has not simply
forfeited his claim to the votes of social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Texas, with Bush's assent, recently joined an
appeal to the Supreme Court in support of organized prayer at
public high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is going to be in a good position to make an appeal,'' Guth
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
