<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: PINOCHET RULING OCT. 8
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet will learn next week whether he will be
sent to Spain to stand trial on torture charges. Deputy Chief
Magistrate Ronald Bartle ended four days of hearings at Bow Street
magistrates court saying he would issue his decision on Oct. 8. The
former Chilean dictator, 83, is supposed to be present for the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: 2ND THOUGHTS ON FOX HUNTING
</P>
<P>
   Backing off of a pledge made by Prime Minister Tony Blair, the
government said it would no longer press for a law banning fox
hunting. The leader of the Commons, Margaret Beckett, said it would
be ``a complete waste of everybody's time'' to try to pass
legislation sure to be bottled up by the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: STUDENTS TAKE TO STREETS
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of students demonstrated across France in a second day
of anti-government protests. They want more teachers, better
equipment, less crowded classrooms and changes in study programs to
make them more suited to the job market. After large protests a
year ago, the minister of education promised reforms. But the
students said the government had done too little.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: 3 BASQUES SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   The French arrested three suspected members of the Basque
separatist movement ETA who were found with 2.5 tons of explosives
in a house near Pau, not far from the Spanish border. The police
said the cache may be part of the 8 tons of dynamite stolen when
gunmen broke into a warehouse in western France.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: POPE BLESSES ST. PETER'S
</P>
<P>
   At a gala ceremony punctuated with 17th-century-style fireworks
that matched the Baroque architecture, Pope John Paul II blessed
the newly restored facade of St. Peter's. ``We easily understand
our pleasure in this restored masterpiece,'' the pope said. ``But
it cannot only be esthetic; it must open itself to the inner appeal
of spiritual reality.''
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM: EUROPEAN REFORMS
</P>
<P>
   In the first of a series of promised reforms, the new executive
commission of the European Union has begun by curtailing tax
privileges for itself. Neil Kinnock of Britain, commissioner in
charge of reforms, said senior officials would no longer enjoy
tax-free alcohol, tobacco and gasoline for personal use. The
changes are a result of a crisis in March, when the last commission
resigned after reports of cronyism and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: VOLUNTEER ARMY
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori signed a law making military service
voluntary, replacing forced recruitment. He acted after growing
complaints that forced recruiting of Indian youths had caused a
wave of suicides. Fujimori said the virtual end of the terrorist
violence and peace with Ecuador led him to change the policy.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: SALINAS PAYS VISIT
</P>
<P>
   Former President Carlos Salinas de Gortari returned quietly to
Mexico from exile in Ireland for less than 24 hours, to attend to
what he called ``personal and family matters.'' Salinas, who fell
into disgrace after he left office, avoided public attention.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: FISHING DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   Interpreting a 1760 British treaty, the Supreme Court has ruled
that Atlantic-region Indians have the right to fish commercially
year round without licenses. But as Mi'kmaq fishermen set lobster
pots this week, during the normally closed fall season, non-Indian
lobstermen in Nova Scotia vowed to pull out the pots if they remain
by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: LEGISLATOR SHOT
</P>
<P>
   A legislator, Duma Nkosi, was shot and wounded by four gunmen in
Soweto, authorities said. Nkosi, who was visiting relatives, was
hit by six bullets but managed to fire back. He was listed in
stable condition.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: GENERAL STAYS
</P>
<P>
   Quieting rumors that the two men are on the outs, Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif has extended Gen. Pervez Musharraf's tenure as
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Committee for another two
years. The move was intended to end rumors about a change in
command.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: NEW TALIBAN GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Continuing their new offensive, Taliban militia, backed by air
power, have made additional gains into the northern territory
controlled by the nation's remaining opposition group, known as the
United Front. Thousands of refugees are fleeing the area
surrounding Taloqan, a vital support base for the anti-Taliban
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   SYRIA: AT ODDS WITH ISRAEL
</P>
<P>
   A Syrian demand in a United Nations speech by Foreign Minister
Farouk al-Shara that Israel has to return all of the Golan Heights
because Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin had promised to do so brought
a quick response from Israel's representative, Dore Gold. He said
no such promise was ever made.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: OIL BOOM
</P>
<P>
   With oil prices continuing to rise, Iraq may earn nearly $7.2
billion in sales in the six months ending Nov. 20. That is nearly
$2 billion more than authorized by the Security Council, but is
unlikely to be challenged by the Council, concerned about reports
of hardships in Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
