<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-NYT     09-30 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RETOOLED CAMPAIGN, BUT GORE MAKES THE USUAL STOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the first day of his retooled campaign, Vice
President Al Gore spent a day much like any other. He addressed
corporate officials in New York City, walked the streets of a
depressed, upstate town, and returned to the city to meet with
reporters and then financial contributors for his second
fund-raiser in as many days.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday marked Gore's first foray outside Washington after
announcing his plans on Wednesday to revitalize his presidential
campaign by moving his headquarters from Washington to Tennessee
and by holding smaller, more intimate events that would, as he put
it, get him closer to the people.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated that theme Thursday morning, saying he would take
his campaign ``from K Street in Washington to the aisles of K-Mart
in Nashville.'' Chris Lahane, his press secretary, said Gore did
not mean to imply he would be running a cut-rate campaign, only
that he would be spending more time with ``real'' people and less
time with Washington insiders.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of frugality was an important message to convey as it
became clear Thursday that Gore had raised less money in the last
three months and had less cash on hand than his sole Democratic
challenger, former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little Thursday to indicate that Gore had pared
down his campaign. He still traveled in a lengthy motorcade. And he
made his comment about K-Mart on the 56th floor of a Park Avenue
office tower to about 200 chief executives, a group that would
probably be more comfortable in the offices of lobbyists on
Washington's K Street than in K-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   And except for his stroll around a couple of blocks of
Amsterdam, N.Y., where he shook hands with unemployed residents in
the shadow of a closed toy factory, Gore stuck to traditional
venues and sounded his traditional themes of universal child care,
stronger public education and spreading economic prosperity to all
corners of the country..
</P>
<P>
   The formats that he chose generated little of the fanfare that
often accompanies presidential campaigns. That was especially true
of his visit to Amsterdam, a town of old rug mills that converted
to making toys and then went out of business, where he met with
residents and then led an hourlong forum on reviving depressed
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Walking along Grand Street and First Avenue in Amsterdam, he
stopped and chatted with residents who had come out on their front
stoops.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Choat, 26, a laid-off worker from a nearby plant, said of
Gore: ``I earned a lot of respect for him because he talked to
us.'' Dave Passafiume, 33, who is unemployed and finds Amsterdam
``dead,'' was less enthusiastic. ``I can't find a job,'' he said,
adding that he thought few politicians could really make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo accompanied
Gore and announced grants of $300,000 to help Amsterdam. Cuomo said
later that the purpose of their visit _ trying to spark economic
revitalization _ did not lend itself to typical campaign
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad-news topic, the upstate economy,'' Cuomo said.
``The basic message is, `We have a real problem to deal with.'''
</P>
<P>
   Those who met Gore were pleased nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came right to us, and that makes a significant
difference,'' said Elizabeth DeBella, 36, a nurse from nearby
Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the New Yorkers who met Gore had a good
impression of him as well. Leon Wagner, an investment banker, saw
him at the Sky Club on Park Avenue. ``He is so much better in
person,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason that myself and friends are going to get behind the
vice president now is _ I work on Wall Street _ it's a little like
getting behind a stock that's a little soft,'' Wagner said. ``The
perception is that Bradley is on an uptick, but the fact is the
vice president has experience. And frankly, I'm not willing to vote
against the prosperity that we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
