<HEADER>
A2700 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-MIRAGE-ART     09-30 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-MIRAGE-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITSUBISHI MIRAGE LS COUPE: THE JOYS OF BEING MIDDLING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By DAN NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those given to class envy, the current crop of megadollar
sport utilities and luxury sedans could easily cause a rise of the
proletarian gorge. But workers of the world, take heart.
</P>
<P>
   New cars and trucks are actually at their most affordable level
in 19 years, said David L. Littman, chief economist for Comerica
Bank in Detroit. Littman's affordability index compares the average
price of a new vehicle ($20,802 in the second quarter) with median
annual family income ($45,835). A new-vehicle purchase requires
23.6 weeks of income before taxes _ comparable with the 23.5-week
figure of 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The gains in affordability have come largely because family
income has risen more than 5 percent in the last year. But they
also reflect long-term price stability in the auto market, Littman
said, as well as downward price pressure from auto makers'
incentive programs, rebates and discount financing.
</P>
<P>
   And consumers are getting far more vehicle for each dollar
spent. After a period of de-contenting that followed the sharp rise
of the Japanese yen in the mid-'90s, manufacturers are engaged in a
game of content brinkmanship, loading even economy cars with
standard features that were once luxury options.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the much more advanced engineering and improved
reliability of budget cars, and it is clear that there has never
been a better time to be a driver of modest means. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to the Mitsubishi Mirage Coupe LS. If you went
looking for an average economy car, you could do a lot worse than
the Mirage. The compact coupe (the sedan, too) is in the middle of
its life span _ neither on the cutting edge like the new Ford
Focus, nor nearing extinction like the current Saturn S-Series. It
has average performance, average looks, average build quality.
</P>
<P>
   But average is by no means unappealing, particularly if you
judge by what cars offered for the money just a few years ago. The
test vehicle, priced at $16,062, was flush with standard amenities,
including air-conditioning, power windows and doors, a CD player
with respectable amplification, cruise control and a brace of
convenience lighting. The $1,030 sport package rolled in a spoiler,
fog lights, 14-inch alloy wheels and other sporting livery.
</P>
<P>
   Where once an economy car was a Savonarola-like exercise in
privation, the Mirage is a surprisingly comfortable and convenient
place to go about the business of commuting. The seat height is
easily adjustable with a side-mounted lever; the steering wheel
height adjusts, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Power exterior mirrors are standard on the LS model. White
gauges spruce up the function-first interior of muted grays and
black vinyl. The Focus may establish a new benchmark for flashy
small-car interiors, but the Mirage upholds the rationale for
simple, intuitive organization.
</P>
<P>
   Under the hood is Mitsubishi's 1.8-liter four-cylinder engine, a
113-horsepower stalwart that has seen service for several years.
Nowhere is technological creep more evident than in power plants.
And yet, this engine remains one of the thriftiest in the class,
turning in EPA ratings of 28 miles per gallon in town and 36 on the
highway. Only a few years ago, those kinds of numbers could be
achieved only by breathless three-cylinder vehicles. Now, that
level of economy is simply expected.
</P>
<P>
   The Mirage's driving dynamics benefit from the raised bar of
expectations across the economy car field. It rides on a four-wheel
independent suspension _ some front-wheel-drive competitors still
use a less sophisticated beam axle in the rear _ as well as
power-assisted rack-and-pinion steering and vented disc brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Mitsubishi does not offer anti-lock brakes on the
Mirage, a choice that seems like a clear vote of the efficacy of
such systems (and the backlash of the insurance industry against
ABS).
</P>
<P>
   The Mirage is a lively, competent car that can be thrashed with
its five-speed manual transmission to 60 mph in about 9 seconds and
happily hurled down country roads. Naturally, the car has a lot of
understeer dialed into the suspension, so it readily plows ahead
when cornering forces exceed the grip of the 185/65 14-inch radial
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one ought to bear in mind that this middling commuter
appliance would beat the tweed britches off a typical British
sports car of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Mirage comes with Mitsubishi's 60 month/60,000-mile
powertrain and 36/36,000 basic warranty (once almost unthinkable
except in the luxury class). Sales of the Mirage coupe were up 41
percent through August from a year earlier, to 10,614.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that improvement has come with an increase in browsers
in Mitsubishi showrooms; many buyers stopped in to look at the
sporty new Eclipse, the restyled Galant sedan and the Montero sport
utility.
</P>
<P>
   Few who buy the Mirage _ an Everyman of the cheap-car segment _
are likely to stop and appreciate just how far such cars have come.
It is easy to take the current level of indubitable reliability,
thorough engineering and plentiful equipment for granted. You need
only take a stroll through a used-car lot to cure your
ingratitude. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Gloriously average.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
