<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PFEIFFER-FOR </SLUG>
 WIRES  
 Compaq's Ousted CEO Eckhard Pfeiffer Resurfaces  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Eckhard Pfeiffer, the ousted chief executive of Compaq Computer
Corp., is resurfacing on Monday as chairman of the board of
Intershop, a San Francisco firm that helps clients build electronic
storefronts on the Web.
<P>
   The high-profile Pfeiffer had almost completely retreated from
public view since he departed Compaq about five months ago. He lead
the company for eight years before being forced to resign by
Compaq's board after a series of financial disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent the last five months determining my next steps,''
Pfeiffer said in an interview yesterday. ``I've fielded more than
100 proposals, from joining a board to becoming a CEO to taking on
a venture capital role.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer, who will officially join Intershop on Monday, will not
be committed full time to the company. ``I didn't want to lock
myself into a CEO position where you just keep going for 16 hours a
day.'' he said. He will continue to live in Houston, where Compaq
is based, and explore other opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The German-born executive serves on the boards of several major
companies, including General Motors and Bell Atlantic. Two months
ago, he also became chairman of Ricardo, a Internet auction firm
based in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer said he also is exploring some venture capital deals
and has given cursory thought to starting his own Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   So what attracted Pfeiffer to Intershop, a little-known company
that was founded in Germany seven years ago and last year lost
$17.3 million on sales of $20.4 million?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the challenge of growing small companies into big
global companies,'' he said. ``I think I can bring a lot to
Intershop in terms of industry contacts. I believe this is a truly
outstanding company in the e-commerce space.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer said he first became aware of the company last year,
when it went public on the German stock exchange and quickly soared
in value. Intershop, which is not listed in the United States, has
a market capitalization of about $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Though he refused to disclose how much he is being paid by
Intershop, Pfeiffer said he has made a large personal investment in
the company. ``It's important I make the company grow for all
shareholders as well as myself,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer is already a rich man. He received a $9.8 million
serverance check plus options for 13.5 million Compaq shares, now
valued at about $310 million, when he left the company.
</P>
<P>
   Intershop chief executive Stephan Schambach said Pfeiffer will
help open new doors for the company, especially as it transitions
away from its small and midmarket focus and begins to target
Fortune 1,000 companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a still a young company and don't have the authority to
deal with major accounts,'' he said. ``Eckhard gives us instant
credibility with potential customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer said his role with Intershop will be hands-on. ``This
is more than just running the board meetings,'' he said. ``I will
participate in the strategy process and engage to a large extend
with customers and partners.''
</P>
<P>
   David Truog, an analyst with Forrester Research, believes that
the seasoned Pfeiffer can help Intershop garner attention and
all-important buzz in its market. Right now, Intershop is not
mentioned in the same breath with competitors such as Broadvision
and Open Market, but Truog said that is likely to change.
``Intershop will make a splash with Pfeiffer, but the real impact
is yet to be seen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for his days at Compaq and his bitter ouster, Pfeiffer says
he does not hold a grudge against his old company, nor does he take
pleasure in watching its struggles of late. ``That is water under
the bridge,'' he said. ``I'm the largest individual shareholder in
Compaq, so I hope it grows and grows.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
