<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2704 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CAR-SMART-PRICE-ART-$     09-30 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-PRICE-ART-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARS THAT WERE STRIPPERS NOW COME FULLY CLOTHED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn., N.J.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MIKE COVELLO  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the average new car selling for more than $20,000, at a
time when even subcompacts flash gold badges and flaunt fancy CD
players, the thrifty consumer searching for bare-bones
transportation would seem forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it the penny-pinching customer who has disappeared _ gone
the way of the shade-tree mechanic, the front-door vent window and
spinner hubcaps? There no longer seems to be any demand for
Spartan, stripped-down cars.
</P>
<P>
   Such automobiles, known as price leaders, were once common at
dealerships. Even if few were sold, they could be advertised at
rock-bottom prices that brought shoppers onto the lot. Once there,
browsers might be talked into buying a ``loaded'' model.
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s and '60s, the plain-jane cars ultimately found
buyers, too, since they appealed to thrifty motorists who counted
their pennies and considered extra-cost add-ons _ like power
steering and radios, even heaters and electric clocks _ to be
unnecessary gadgets that would eventually break and have to be
repaired.
</P>
<P>
   All the lower-priced car lines offered budget models like the
Chevrolet Biscayne, and Studebaker even sold the plainer-than-plain
Scotsman _ the name played on a stereotype of thrift in the
politically incorrect '50s.
</P>
<P>
   The price leader has all but disappeared for several reasons.
The Depression-era mindset of pinching pennies and saving for a
rainy day, common among the parents and grandparents of baby
boomers, gave way to self-indulgence and conspicuous consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, our clients expect the base price of our cars to
represent a well-equipped vehicle,'' said Dave Schembri, general
manager of the New York region for Mercedes-Benz USA.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment once viewed as frivolous extras _ power steering,
stereo systems and air-conditioning _ is now seen as essential, and
comes on virtually every car sold in North America. Other items,
like air bags, are mandated by the government.
</P>
<P>
   But two of the biggest forces for change have come in the way
cars are built by manufacturers and acquired by the public.
</P>
<P>
   While car companies once offered buyers dozens of options and
hundreds of possible combinations of color, trim and equipment,
they now place a premium on standardization. By limiting the number
of combinations, a company streamlines the manufacturing process in
factories where, increasingly, vehicles are assembled from modules,
like finished dashboards, that were put together elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   It may be cheaper to include, say, power windows, than to build
the occasional car without them. So manufacturers are grouping
popular features into packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Option packages are not only a good deal for manufacturers and
consumers, but they help dealers to manage inventories,'' said Wade
Hoyt, a spokesman for Toyota. ``By ordering cars and trucks with
packages of popular options, the dealer is likely to have a vehicle
on the lot that the customer wants, avoiding delivery delays and
the chance the customer will shop elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Leasing is also changing the way cars are equipped. A high
residual value _ the amount the car is expected to be worth at the
end of the lease _ lowers the payments. So the options valued by
used-car shoppers _ leather seats or keyless entry systems _ may
increase the monthly payments by little or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Blitzer, co-owner of Devan Acura, of Norwalk, Conn., said
shoppers often came in to lease an Integra LS for $219 a month. But
when they see that for just $40 a month more they can move up to an
Integra GS, many agree to pay more. Or consider a standard 36-month
lease on a Chevrolet Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   The base model runs $266 a month, and the LS _ with a V6 engine,
power features, keyless entry, upgraded sound system and aluminum
wheels _ is $299.
</P>
<P>
   Martyn Schorr of PMPR Inc., a Closter, N.J., public relations
firm that works for clients including Buick, suggests that today's
strippers are pickup trucks. Although not many are sold, bare-bones
pickups still show up on dealer lots with rubber floor coverings
and roll-up windows. The two-wheel-drive Ford Ranger starts at
$12,295; a fully equipped Ranger tops $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Champagne Jr., of Champagne Chevrolet in Mansfield, Conn.,
says he has attracted little business by advertising price leaders.
He gets much better results, he says, by advertising cars with
popular equipment. Most consumers today are not looking for the
cheapest vehicle, but for the best value, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Schorr said that today's buyers were more sophisticated than
those taken in by bait-and-switch tactics once used by unscrupulous
dealers. Attracted by an advertisement promising rock-bottom
prices, the prospective customer would be told that ``we just sold
the last'' of the advertised car. For a few dollars more, though, a
better model could be had, and isn't that what you really want?
</P>
<P>
   Bait-and-switch selling suffered a blow from the disappearance
of stripped-down cars, but a bigger factor in its decline may have
been consumer protection laws. Now, many states require that an
advertised car be available in reasonable quantities to meet
reasonable demand. What is ``reasonable'' is determined on a
case-by-case basis, according to the Connecticut Consumer Agency. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
