<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION-UNION </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Lending Ploy Earns Interest as Bancorp-Union Bank Takeover Rumor  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A pressure tactic by a San Francisco community activist group has
touched off a wave of speculation, apparently unfounded, that Union
Bank of California could be sold to a Minnesota bank.
<P>
   Last week, the Greenlining Institute released a statement
raising the specter that Minneapolis's U.S. Bancorp, the nation's
13th-largest bank, might take over San Francisco's Union, the
second-largest bank based in California.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlining issued its broadside as part of a campaign to force
the Minnesota bank to increase the money it channels to
California's low-income and minority communities, an amount the
group charges falls short of what the bank should be doing.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bancorp will have more than $6 billion in assets and 125
branches in the Golden State when it completes two pending
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators are in the midst of examining U.S. Bancorp's
community lending record as part of the process of reviewing the
bank's application to buy Western Bank, a community bank based in
Newport Beach (Orange County). By playing the Union Bank card,
Greenlining sharply raised the stakes of the review, since Union is
10 ten  &LR; times bigger than Western.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlining is asking regulators to postpone action on the
application until a study of the lending records of U.S. Bancorp
and Western is completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a minor matter,'' said Robert Gnaizda,
Greenlining's policy director, in an interview. ``U.S. Bancorp
intends to be a major player. Within a year, they could be the
third-largest bank in California.``
</P>
<P>
   Gnaizda said his belief that U.S. Bancorp will try to buy Union
is based on a telephone conversation he had several months ago with
U.S. Bancorp chief executive Chief Executive  &LR; Jack Grundhofer, who
acknowledged an earlier bid.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that Union isn't interested in selling,
according to people close to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi, which owns just under
two-thirds of Union's stock, wants to keep a highly profitable
operation that turned out to be the crown jewel of its overseas
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Grundhofer told Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi executives that he was
interested in buying Union during a July 1998 trip to Japan. But
they never followed up, people familiar with the matter said.
Instead, U.S. Bancorp started buying up smaller California banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, U.S. Bancorp is interested in expanding its presence
in the state,'' said Joseph Morford, an analyst with the brokerage
Dain Rauscher Wessels. ``But Union's Japanese owners appear
committed to their investment in America.``
</P>
<P>
   Still, based on Greenlining's release, the San-Diego Union
Tribune reported yesterday that U.S. Bancorp might be eyeing
another bid for Union.
</P>
<P>
   The story was picked up by financial wire services, triggering a
brief surge in Union's stock. Union's shares ended up falling
$2.06, to $36.25, after an unidentified institutional stockholder
sold off a big stake.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Union and U.S. Bancorp declined to comment on
a possible takeover bid. U.S. Bancorp spokeswoman Marika
Cronin-Rose noted that the bank has pledged $2 billion for
California community lending programs and that federal regulators
have given the bank's community programs a satisfactory rating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
