<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0408 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2707 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-BUICK-DAY101-COX     09-30 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-DAY101-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leonard rides vibes to 67
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. _ By all reasonable logic, Justin Leonard
should have spent a numb post-Ryder Cup week, content to shake
hands as he returned to the PGA Tour but not likely to contend.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that might not be the case. Leonard trails leader Bob
Friend by two shots at the Buick Challenge, but a 5-under-par 67
Thursday has indicated something more than a ceremonial role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm surprised, but I'm very pleased,'' he
said. ``I think by playing a good round today, it will make it
easier for me to focus the rest of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Friend, who has reworked his swing this year and stands 164th on
the money list after a 1998 playoff loss to Billy Andrade in the
Canadian Open, had everything working Thursday. But it's a tough
week to steal attention away from a player on the cover of numerous
publications.
</P>
<P>
   Or his Ryder Cup teammates, for that matter. Steve Pate is a
stroke behind Leonard at 68. Davis Love III was at 70, with Jeff
Maggert at 73.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to individual goals again, Leonard almost has to
remind people that he's earned $1.7 million this year without
winning a PGA Tour event. Last week pushed him into golf history,
but not into next year's season-opening Mercedes Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't gotten any hardware and I'm not in Kapalua yet,''
Leonard said, ``but that's probably the only thing lacking. I'm
still trying to win a golf tournament. But if I don't win a
tournament . . . it's still been a wonderful year.''
</P>
<P>
   With perfect weather and the Mountain View course in typically
superb condition, the scoring went low for a lot of players. Tied
with Leonard at 67 were Trinidad's Stephen Ames, tour school rookie
Cameron Beckman, Harrison Frazar, Scott Gump, Frank Nobilo and
Frank Lickliter. Columbus' Larry Mize was in the group at 68.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the ropes, things were different for Leonard. Indeed,
nearly almost as many people had found the way on the 17th green at
Brookline on Sunday as were following him Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuesday pretty much prepared us for that,'' he said. ``There
were two people following us for four holes and we were all alone
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Friend had seven birdies and no bogeys. He is hoping that the
week might prevent a return trip to PGA Tour Qualifying School and
put an end to a ``pretty trying year''. At $159,149, he probably
needs another $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
