<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLYCAST-FLYCAST </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 CMGI Hooks Ad Firm Flycast  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
For the third time in two weeks, CMGI Inc. of Andover, Mass., has
snapped up a Bay Area business in its aggressive bid to dominate
the Internet advertising sector.
<P>
   Flycast Communications Corp., a San Francisco company that sells
advertising space on small and midsize Web sites, was yesterday's
target. CMGI is paying about $741 million in stock for Flycast.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, CMGI said it would buy AdForce, a Cupertino ad
server, and CMGI's Engage Technologies Inc. agreed to purchase
Adknowledge, a Palo Alto ad manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really shaping up as a battle of the titans _ CMGI
versus DoubleClick,'' said Marcia Kadanoff, chief marketing officer
for IQ.com, a Saratoga company.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick is a New York Web ad manager that serves 11 billion
impressions _ or ad views _ per month. With the addition of
Flycast, which serves 1.4 billion ad impressions per month, CMGI
will serve more than 20 billion monthly impressions.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleClick could not be reached for comment yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary rate of consolidation in the industry
``validates what we've always thought, which is that one year in
the Internet space is worth seven anywhere else,'' said Kadanoff, a
former Flycastexecutive.
</P>
<P>
   Flycast's unique technology measures the number of clicks
generated by specific ads on its network of 1,200 sites and
redirects ads according to where they receive the most attention
from surfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous amount of opportunity for synergy''
between Flycast and other CMGI properties, said Lyn Chitow Oakes,
Flycast's chief marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
   Flycast complements CMGI's AdSmart unit, which uses a different
model, serving ads to big, name-brand sites, executives said. CMGI
will also look for efficiencies between Flycast and AdForce; the
two use different technologies to serve ads. And Flycast is
expected to dip into Engage's database of anonymous surfer profiles
to target its ads.
</P>
<P>
   CMGI, which owns about 50 independently operated companies, will
issue .4738 of a share for each share of Flycast outstanding when
the deal closes, probably in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our 15th acquisition this year and the seventh in the
last three weeks,'' said David Wetherell, chief executive of CMGI,
in a conference call yesterday. ``Five of those have been in the
interactive marketing and advertising space. ... We have many more
acquisitions to come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The media business is about scale and media moguls,'' said one
person close to yesterday's deal who did not want to be identified.
``The bigger you are, the more money you make. The more sites you
have in your network, the more ads you can attract.''
</P>
<P>
   Also yesterday, Flycast announced its third-quarter revenues
will beat forecasts and its loss would be smaller than expected.
Shares of Flycast jumped $7.50, to $45.50. CMGI shares rose $2.19
yesterday to close at $102.50.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
