<SLUG> BC-LIESBOX-LIESBOX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS FOR CHECKING REFERENCES 
 &HT;     BY SAM MCMANIS 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Lyn Taylor, vice president at Robert Half International, a San
Francisco employment agency, says there are ways to get reluctant
supervisors and human resource workers to give information and
voice opinions about former employees. Among her recommendations:
<P>
   _Make reference calls yourself, rather than farm it out to
checking services. ``References are more willing to open up with
peers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _Make clear to the candidate that you will make a thorough
reference check and enlist his or her help in getting references to
be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   _If possible, get a candidate to sign a release protecting
former employers from liability.
</P>
<P>
   _Start at the bottom of a candidate's reference list and work
upward, because the candidate often lists the most flattering
reference first.
</P>
<P>
   _Start with basic questions when interviewing a candidate's
former employer, then gradually introduce subjective questions.
</P>
<P>
   _If a former employer is not forthcoming, read back to the
former employer that part of the candidate's resume that describes
the former job. ``If there's dishonesty or exaggeration, they may
feel compelled to set the record straight,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _If a reference seems receptive, ask for more names of persons
in the organization who know the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
