<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVE BY OLIVETTI BACKFIRES WITH STOCK TRADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The head of Olivetti SpA struggled Thursday to reverse
the most serious trouble he has faced since gaining control in May
of Telecom Italia. The chief executive, Roberto Colaninno, said he
would meet with institutional investors next Tuesday in Milan and
on Wednesday and Thursday in London in an effort to halt a flight
of investment capital from the Italian telecommunications giant.
</P>
<P>
   The market damage has been caused by the decision announced on
Tuesday to strip Telecom Italia of its most-valued asset, its
highly profitable cellular phone unit, Telecom Italia Mobile, and
transfer it to Tecnost, the Olivetti subsidiary used by Colaninno
to purchase control of Telecom Italia. The move was intended to
help Tecnost pay back the debt it took on to finance the $33
billion acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by what they apparently saw as a rude surprise, stock
investors punished the companies Thursday for the second
consecutive day, driving down the price of Olivetti shares 3.7
percent, after a 7 percent drop on Wednesday; Tecnost shares fell
4.4 percent, after an 11.4 percent loss Wednesday. The stock of
Telecom Italia gave up nearly 3 percent. The only market gainer was
the cellular phone unit in flux, Telecom Italia Mobile, whose
shares rose 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction to Colaninno's move put him in an awkward position,
one that contrasted sharply with the triumph he enjoyed in May,
when Olivetti, a former typewriter maker, succeeded in acquiring a
company more than five times its size.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the defection of key Telecom Italia shareholders to
Olivetti's side helped Colaninno overcome a rival bid for Telecom
Italia by Deutsche Telekom and win the biggest hostile-takeover
battle in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Colaninno has insisted that the move to strip Telecom Italia's
mobile phone unit _ transferring Telecom Italia's 60 percent stake
in that company to Tecnost and compensating Telecom Italia's
minority shareholders with Tecnost shares _ is part of an
industrial plan, and not purely a financial maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter published Thursday in The Financial Times, Colaninno
said the transfer would ``facilitate the efficient servicing of our
debt,'' but also give the companies the flexibility needed for
``value-enhancing alliances'' and tools to help overcome a legacy
of inefficiency at Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors apparently hoped that the Italian government,
which holds a 3.95 percent share in Telecom Italia, enabling it to
veto major changes, would intervene to block the plan. But Prime
Minister Massimo D'Alema said Thursday that the government could
only intervene if Telecom Italia asked it to do so.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, who spoke in a radio interview, is under pressure from
political opponents, who fear the dismemberment of the former state
telephone monopoly. But there is also concern that a loss of
investor confidence in the Italian capital markets will hurt the
planned sale of nearly $7.5 billion of shares in the Italian state
energy utility, Enel SpA.
</P>
<P>
   Colaninno's plan has also come under attack in Italy by groups
representing Telecom Italia employees and by consumer
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Giuliano Amato, the minister of the treasury, which
effectively controls the government's shares in Telecom Italia, is
expected to face questioning by the nation's Senate about the plan.
Amato has supported the position of nonintervention taken Thursday
by D'Alema.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2120EDT &QL; 
