<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WELFARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PUSHES TEXAS CLOSER TO FEDERAL WELFARE CAP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, in a move that sparked
protests from key state lawmakers, is taking steps to permanently
cut parents and children off of welfare sooner than state law
requires, his office confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a document heading to Washington on Friday, the Bush
administration is effectively opting for Texas to adopt the federal
welfare reform law's five-year, lifetime cap on cash welfare
benefits. Under the 1996 federal law, parents and children can be
permanently barred from Temporary Assistance for Needy Families
when a parent hits the five-year limit.
</P>
<P>
   The tough federal law was set to replace the state's more
generous welfare reform law in 2002, but Bush's move speeds up the
process by retroactively applying the five-year limit in most
cases. That means the clock would have begun ticking on benefits in
1996 instead of in 2002. From the governor's point of view, the
federal law doesn't contradict state law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because state law does not address maximum benefit limits, the
state falls under federal law that limits lifetime benefits to five
years,'' said Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrville Republican Rep. Harvey Hilderbran, the House sponsor
of the state's landmark 1995 welfare reforms, said he always
assumed the federal clock was ticking anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were silent on that. In my point of view there's not a
conflict,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo Democrat Sen. Judith Zaffirini, who carried the
legislation in the Texas Senate and chairs that chamber's Human
Services Committee, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am really shocked. I'm shocked at this move, shocked at this
action because it's inconsistent with legislative intent as I
perceive it,'' she said, adding that several measures to place
lifetime caps on welfare benefits have repeatedly been rejected by
state lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always worried about the children and made sure that
the children don't pay for the sins of the parents,'' she added.
``Our legislation does not impose lifetime benefit cuts and that
issue was debated. It was considered. We did not support it, and we
knowingly did not support it, willingly did not support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Elliott Naishtat, chairman of the House Human
Services Committee, complained that until this week the governor
had cut legislators ``out of the loop'' on the welfare plan. Bush's
action ``smells of politics,'' said Rep. Garnet Coleman, D-Houston,
and a co-sponsor of the state welfare reform bill.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon a Naishtat aide checked recorded tapes of
last-minute wrangling on the state welfare bill and reported that
lawmakers were not silent on the issue of lifetime benefit cuts in
1995. The House had agreed to them, but the Senate had rejected the
idea. When the bill was reconciled between the chambers, lawmakers
chose a five-year ``freeze out'' from benefits instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``To retroactively penalize children for the sins of their
parents would be unconscionable,'' said Coleman. ``We made a choice
in 1995 to exempt children from any time limits, and now the
governor wants to change the rules in the middle of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 10,000 children will be cut from welfare benefits
one year earlier and up to 300 more children two years earlier
under the governor's plan, Naishtat said. Roughly 5,500 adults
would be permanently severed from benefits one to three years
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Health and Human Services Commissioner Don Gilbert said
Thursday that the impact on children is not as great as some seem
to think. Under state law, a parent is forced off of welfare after
one to three years and then is ``frozen out'' from benefits for
another five years. If the parent is not working during that freeze
out, the child is still eligible for welfare benefits. It is not
until the parent returns to welfare and uses up the rest of the
five years, that the child falls permanently off the rolls as well.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the earliest a Texas child will first be forced
off the rolls will already be in their teens in the year 2006,
Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Coleman and Naishtat complain that the governor is
attempting to accomplish bureaucratically a major welfare policy
change that the state Legislature again failed to adopt last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Bush is taking advantage of a federal rule that
requires states operating under welfare waivers to list
inconsistencies between their state laws and the federal one.
Friday is the deadline for doing so. The U.S. Department of Health
and Human Services has some jurisdiction over the issue because the
vast majority of welfare money comes from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush points out no inconsistencies on the issue, the federal
government will automatically assume the federal provisions apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair. Our state law should stand. If the law is
supposed to be the law, then no one has the right to do something
differently than the law,'' Coleman said. ``The reality is on its
face, it's inconsistent. That's why in my opinion it's so egregious
to reinterpret something to meet your ends.''
</P>
<P>
   In a Sept. 21 memo to the Texas Health and Human Services
Commission, which must submit the document at Bush's behest, a
welfare official at the Texas Workforce Commission suggested
exactly that strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The federal certification process provides ``an unprecedented
opportunity'' for Bush, wrote Larry E. Temple, director of welfare
reform initiatives. He said the governor could now ensure that the
state's welfare reform effort ``remains on the philosophical track
that complements his vision for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple also noted that his own agency ``recognizes that an
inconsistency does exist with federal law'' in the sense that state
law only applies time limits to adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``TWC believes that the governor should not certify this
inconsistency,'' Temple wrote. ``The result of claiming this
inconsistency would prolong the time that families are on welfare
and be in conflict with the goals set forth in the governor's
five-point welfare reform plan.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Texas Department of Human Services, however, Commissioner
Eric Bost recommended against that policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients have been informed by DHS that the federal time limit
may apply, but they have not been informed that it does apply,'' he
said. ``As a matter of fairness, a reasonable notice to clients at
the beginning of the maximum lifetime federal time limit should be
provided.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
