<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-FEATURE01-     09-30 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-FEATURE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crew chief: Over and out
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The successful duo of Jeff Gordon and Ray Evernham is
history, but not the team's place in NASCAR's history books.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the driver, and Evernham, the crew chief, formed one of
the greatest combinations in the sport's modern era, winning three
Winston Cup championships. The twosome, which had the circuit's
longest-running working relationship, parted ways this week.
Evernham was given a provisional release, effective immediately,
from his duties as crew chief from Hendrick Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were probably the all-time best,'' Team Sabco
owner Felix Sabates said. ``Jeff and Ray seemed to have special
chemistry. They respected each other and worked together very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt and Kirk Shelmerdine teamed together to win four
Cup championships, one of the few crew-chief-driver combinations to
rival the success of Gordon and Evernham in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question about Jeff Gordon's talent,'' said H.A.
``Humpy'' Wheeler, president of Lowe's Motor Speedway in Charlotte.
``With Jeff and Ray Evernham together, though, they were virtually
unstoppable.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as Gordon has been in NASCAR, Evernham, who makes all
race-day calls, has been the voice in his ear during races. Gordon
was named Busch Series rookie of the year in 1991 and moved up to
the top circuit on a full-time basis two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Evernham was with Gordon every step of the way during the
meteoric rise of the No. 24 team. They won Cup championships in
three of the last four seasons and posted 47 career victories,
including five this year to tie Jeff Burton for the series lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is one of the most talented guys we've ever had in racing,
and he certainly has been an instrumental part in everything Jeff
Gordon has accomplished,'' Wheeler said. ``Evernham's real forte
has always been in the handling of the car. It's almost like a
black magic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Ray Evernham is one of the brightest, most ingenious
and skilled people who has been involved in Winston Cup racing,''
owner Jack Roush said.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was official, Cup points leader Dale Jarrett compared
the departure of Evernham with other heralded breakups in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's forever,'' Jarrett said, ``as good as things seem
that they may be. It's not just this sport; you see it everywhere.
You wonder why things get broken up, why everybody on the Chicago
Bulls wanted to go in a different direction when they had the world
beat. The Dallas Cowboys have everything going their way, and
everybody starts doing different things, and it creates problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have different goals and ideas, and whenever you reach
those goals sometimes you want to do something a little different.
Once that happens, though, it starts creating a problem within the
team, and it's hard to get that back, no matter how hard you try.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon admitted that the speculation surrounding Evernham was a
distraction for the team. The No. 24 car finished 17th last weekend
at Dover. Now, it will be interesting to see what effect it will
have. Hendrick mechanic Brian Whitesell will replace Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say Ray has done a great job, and as (the No. 24) team
goes forward, they will have trouble re-creating the same level of
communication, efficiency and end results,'' Roush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' Sabates said, ``the drivers are the
ones driving the race. I am a firm believer that you take Jeff
Gordon in my car, and he probably wins as many races for me as he
did for Hendrick. He may not win 10 one year, but he probably wins
eight. But if I put Evernham to be crew chief for one of my cars,
he may not win but one race. I think the driver makes 80 percent of
the race team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
