<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2715 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LIES-LIES_SFCHRON &LR;      09-30 2115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIES-LIES </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Resume Fairy Tales Have Companies on Guard  &HT;     By Sam McManis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Resume fibbing has been around since, well, resumes. After Adam was
expelled from the garden for biting into the apple, an old business
joke goes, he put down ``quality control supervisor, Eden Produce''
on his resume.
<P>
   Laughter abruptly stops, however, when seemingly innocuous
fibbing turns into gross exaggeration or out-and-out lying. Often,
the results are far from harmless for the employee, who loses his
job and reputation, and the company, which bears the cost of
replacing the employee and might lose prestige.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, several high-profile people have had lies,
omissions or excessive resume puffery come back to haunt their
careers in embarrassing public flaps:
</P>
<P>
   _In August, E. Michael Campbell, a renowed Lawrence Livermore
Laboratory physicist heading the $1.2 billion National Ignition
Facility project, resigned after it was revealed that he never
earned his doctorate from Princeton University, as he had stated.
</P>
<P>
   _Also in August, Buddy Tate Choy admitted that he lied about
earning a clinical social worker's license to get his job as social
services director for the San Francisco Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   _In 1996, it was revealed that San Francisco Police Chief Fred
Lau never finished his undergraduate degree at San Francisco State
University, despite saying so on his resume. Lau remains in office,
and Mayor Willie Brown told The Chronicle, ``I don't know anyone
who doesn't lie on their resume.''
</P>
<P>
   The incidence of resume fabrication in the public and private
sectors may not be as all-inclusive as Brown states, but it is
rampant.
</P>
<P>
   The American Psychological Association recently reported that 67
percent of all job seekers fabricate or embellish their managerial
or supervisory duties on resumes. A 1998 survey by the Society of
Human Resources Management showed that 90 percent of respondents
who checked candidates' past job titles, employment length and
salary histories reported some falsification. And Personnel Journal
reports that more than 500,000 people are claiming a bogus college
degree.
</P>
<P>
   Other polls don't show such a high degree of deception. Edward
C. Andler, who runs the Certified Reference Checking Company out of
St. Louis, says 36 percent of all resumes contain some form of
untruth, an increase of 24 percent since he first polled
corporations in 1979. Robert Half International, the San Francisco
employment agency, polled executives from Fortune 1,000 companies
and found that 30 percent of job candidates lie on resumes.
</P>
<P>
   But even if you stand by the aphorism, ``There are three types
of lies: Lies, damned lies and statistics,'' the numbers suggest
that there is as much fiction being pawned off by job applicants as
there is fact.
</P>
<P>
   Many large and midsize midsized  &LR; corporations do in-house
reference and criminal checking on applicants, and about 50
reference-checking firms &UR;  &LR; in the nation offer services ranging from
routine checking of college transcripts to verifying claims of
sales awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this business 20 years, and (resume lying) has
significantly increased the last 10 or so years,'' said P. Anthony
Price, managing director of Russell Reynolds Associates, a San
Francisco executive search firm. ``But there also is much more
diligence by many companies in reference checking.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you look at all the startups on the Peninsula and,
you know, many don't give a hoot what education credentials some
people have if they have the intellect and accomplishments. On the
executive level, though, I and my colleagues have interviewed at
least four or five alumni from Reebok, and each of those
individuals claimed singular responsibility for having invented the
`pump' shoe.''
</P>
<P>
   Many hiring directors can regale listeners with yarns of
fabulous fabrications from resumes that quickly were run through
the shredder.
</P>
<P>
   There's the tale of the applicant who claimed CFO experience in
the restaurant industry when he actually worked the cash register
at Taco Bell. There's the guy who covered a three-month stint in
the county jail as a ``sabbatical'' from his job.
</P>
<P>
   There's the now-infamous story of M. Larry Lawrence, former U.S.
ambassador to Switzerland who got the appointment partly because he
said he was a war hero who suffered a head injury when a German
torpedo struck his merchant marine ship in 1945. Truth was,
Lawrence was attending a junior college in Chicago at the time. In
1997, when that fact was revealed, Lawrence's body was exhumed from
Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   And in April, the Wall Street Journal reported that nearly
everything on the resume of Jeffrey Papows, president of IBM's
Lotus Development Corp., was fabricated, from his daring Marine
exploits as an aviator (he never flew) to his Ph.D. from Pepperdine
University (it actually was from an unaccredited correspondence
school), from his black belt in tae kwon do (he has a
less-impressive red belt) to his hardship as an orphan (his
parents, very much alive, live in Massachusetts).
</P>
<P>
   Whoppers like that aside, the best lies, the really plausible
and elaborately detailed ones, sometimes enable the cheater to
prosper and climb the corporate ladder _ at least until the truth
comes out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing more instances of lying exposed because
(companies) are checking more,'' said Andler, author of ``The
Complete Reference Checking Handbook.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started my business 12 years ago,'' he said, ``it was
just missionary work, trying to convince companies that they needed
to check. Now, it's become a full-fledged industry. But the job
seekers still are lying. I think people are either careless or
bold.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the boldness _ and bald-faced lying _ comes from
applicants conferring a college degree upon themselves, according
to Roger D. Sommer, a vice president with Interim Career Consulting
in Los Angeles and chairman of the employment committee for the
Society of Human Resources Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, a Ph.D. candidate will lie and say he's got a
doctorate, like the physicist in Livermore, but most of the time,
it's more blatant,'' Sommer said. ``I had a human resources friend
of mine who was going to just invent a degree from UCLA, and she'd
never been there. We talked her out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bridgeport, Conn., man made a living selling phony college
degrees and transcripts on the Internet, complete with
authentic-looking diplomas. The business, Prestigious Images, was
forced to close in 1998 after threats of trademark infringement
from top universities.
</P>
<P>
   Lying about education is most prevalent, experts say, because
many job announcements have specific degree qualifications. Many
applicants also know that many large corporations scan thousands of
resumes into a database and then type in keywords such as Ph.D. or
M.B.A. to weed out the underqualified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer screening is a problem for companies,'' Andler said.
``They waste a lot of time interviewing people with fabricated
credentials.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. of Palo Alto receives as many as 3,000
resumes a day, but it does not do complete reference checking until
late in the hiring process, said workforce planning manager Susan
Lovegren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't put our candidates through any of that until they've
been made an offer,'' Lovegren said. ``But we really don't rely
much on the resume. We have prospective employees fill out and sign
a pre-employment questionnaire that's seven pages long, verifying
education, criminal background, previous employment, personal
references. It's been very effective in catching those kind of
(lies).''
</P>
<P>
   Other common fabrications include inflating salary history,
puffing up job titles, plugging gaps in employment histories and
embellishing achievements on projects.
</P>
<P>
   To many hiring executives, an applicant who omits a brief,
unpleasant stint with companies also is perceived as deceptive. But
some believe otherwise, including Gerry Crispin, vice president of
staffing at Shaker Advertising Agency in East Brunswick, N.J., and
vice president of the Society of Human Resources Management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resume is an obsolete document that essentially is a
letter of introduction,'' Crispin said. ``From the job seeker's
point of view, it should be a marketing tool that tells the best
truths about that individual. That's it. Nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of a resume is to demonstrate that discussion
should continue. If you are a felon, do you put `I am a felon' on
your resume? Of course not. Now, does the signed job application
require that? In most cases, yes. So that's when the prison guy
should hand over his application and say, `There's something on the
application we need to talk about.' But on his resume, the things
that gets him in the door? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Sommer: ``Yes, it's a marketing document, but it
doesn't give you license to lie. You should put down all your
employment history that's relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaller companies often do not have the resources to do thorough
reference checking. Andler, whose reference-checking company
handles business of medium to large companies, says there are 48
reference-checking firms in the United States, most relatively new.
Cost for checking a resume runs from $12 to $100.
</P>
<P>
   One specializing in helping smaller businesses is Credentials
LLC, an Illinois firm that runs the Internet service
 &LR; www.degreechk.com/  &LR; which signs contracts with most major
universities to tap into the school's database to glean the basic
information about students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small businesses really need help,'' said Jack Weber,
executive vice president of Degreechk.com. ``I worked for a small
manufacturer for 15 years, employing 150 people, and we never once
verified a resume. In a small company, if you're interviewing a
person who looks presentable, can carry on a decent conversation
and knows basically what he's talking about, you're more than
likely going to hire him. Our basic, same-day degree checking costs
$12.50, and employers can find out right then if the person's
telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Half International released survey results last year
showing that only 63 percent of Fortune 1,000 executives polled are
honest in their assessments of former staff members when contacted
by reference checkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times, companies only give you name, rank and serial
number,'' said Taylor of Robert Half International, ``because if
you say something positive about someone and it doesn't pan out,
you could be sued. If it's negative, you can be sued. If it's no
comment, sometimes you can be sued. But if you get five references
from (an applicant) that can't give you anything but name, rank and
serial number, it could be a red flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry Mathiason, an employment law specialist with Littler
Mendelson in San Francisco, said that since 1938, cq &LR; California has
had criminal and civil laws prohibiting a prior employer from
giving false information about an ex-employee in a reference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond that, you've got general concern by companies that if
you give information about an employee, that the information will
be libelous or slanderous even though they believe it to be true,''
Mathiason said. ``There's a limited exception carved into
(California's) defamation statute where if giving information is
done in a business purpose and it is provided in good faith, it
would not qualify for slander or defamation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathiason said companies need to be vigilant in reference
checking to avoid negligent-hiring suits.
</P>
<P>
   There have been cases, experts say, in which longtime employees
caught in a resume lie have sued for wrongful termination even
though they admit to the fabrication. They point to their years of
service on the job and positive performance reviews.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of E. Michael Campbell, the Lawrence Livermore
physicist who withheld that he never finished his doctorate, many
hiring professionals say Campbell's track record as one of the
world's leading experts in high-energy lasers should hold more
weight than a lie told when he joined Lawrence Livermore in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell stepped down as head of the lab's laser project and is
on personal leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you don't fire somebody like that,'' said Pierre
Mornell, a Mill Valley hiring consultant and author of ``45
Effective Ways of Hiring Smart.'' ``They've proven themselves.
We're living in real life here. You talk to them about it. You tell
them they aren't going to be fired, based on their track record.
But you sure do ask them why they did it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
