<HEADER>
A2716 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FORD-AUTO-PARTS-345&AMP;A     09-30 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-AUTO-PARTS-345&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD WILL REPORTEDLY SHED PARTS UNIT AND GIVE GUARANTEES TO
WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Ford Motor Co. plans to spin off its giant auto parts
division directly to shareholders and give wage and job guarantees
to the division's factory workers in a contract under negotiation
with the United Automobile Workers union, said people familiar with
the company's plans.
</P>
<P>
   The parts division's future has been a major problem for Ford as
it tries to hammer out a new labor contract. The company had
considered selling the unit, called Visteon Automotive Systems, to
either Lear Corp. or to Delphi Automotive Systems Inc., which was
itself spun off in May from General Motors Corp. the people said.
</P>
<P>
   But labor issues along with tax considerations have instead
convinced Ford to spin off Visteon, which had $17.8 billion in
revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, GM reached tentative agreement with the UAW
union on a four-year contract that included annual raises of 3
percent a year on top of inflation adjustments, plus increased
pension benefits and a $1,350 signing bonus. Delphi, with $28.5
billion in revenue and 48,000 UAW workers, also reached an
agreement Tuesday with the union on a separate labor contract with
nearly identical terms.
</P>
<P>
   Those agreements included a promise to allow Delphi workers who
retire by the end of 1999 to be covered by GM's pension plan,
effectively a three-month extension of a promise given when Delphi
was spun off to GM shareholders. After that point, they would be
covered by a similar Delphi pension plan. The factory workers have
lobbied for coverage under the parent company because they worry
that the parts company may be less financially solid.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Delphi has reached a deal with the union on how its
workers will be treated, the union is expected to allow Ford to
follow the same pattern for Visteon's 23,500 workers, according to
a person close to the union, making a tax-free spinoff of Visteon
to shareholders more attractive. After the spinoff, Visteon would
agree to a four-year contract with the same wage, benefit and job
protections contained in the Ford pact.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Labor contracts for the 400,000 factory workers at GM, Ford and
DaimlerChrysler were to expire Sept. 14, but have been extended as
the union negotiates new contracts. DaimlerChrysler was the first
to reach agreement, and the union has demanded that the other
automakers accept the pattern of wages and benefits laid out in the
DaimlerChrysler contract.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at Visteon factories had opposed a sale or spinoff,
worrying that their wages and pensions would not be as stable at
Visteon as they would be at Ford. In recent weeks, some of
Visteon's salaried employees have sent e-mail messages to
management, protesting plans to sell the unit to another auto parts
maker, fearing that their jobs would be eliminated because of
overlap with the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Senior company officials exploring the sale of Visteon ran into
tax roadblocks. They could not devise favorable tax treatments for
selling Visteon to another auto parts maker, an executive close to
the planning said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had worried that an agreement attached to DaimlerChrysler's
labor contract that designed to limit asset sales would hinder
Ford's ability to sell Visteon. However, union and Ford officials
said that they expect the union to allow Ford to shed Visteon as
long as it follows the pattern set by Delphi earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Under those circumstances, a spinoff of Visteon seems
appealingly simple to Ford. Union and company officials anticipate
they will agree on a labor contract covering Ford's 101,033
unionized workers as soon as the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
   While the labor situation is fluid, and Ford could always change
its plans for Visteon if a buyer offered a higher price for it, a
person familiar with the company's plans said, Ford expected to
announce within a month its intention to spin off Visteon to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had been discussing a sale of Visteon to Lear for several
months, but the possibility of Delphi buying Visteon has not been
previously reported. In a surprising move, Richard Shoemaker, a
union vice president in charge of relations with GM, suggested in
closed-door meetings that Delphi consider buying Visteon, the
person said.
</P>
<P>
   A Delphi spokesman, Peter Rowe, said Thursday, ``we've evaluated
pieces of Visteon's business over the years, as we would any
supplier.'' But he denied that discussions had gone beyond that
point.
</P>
<P>
   A Ford spokesman, Jim Cain, declined to discuss the company's
plans for Visteon. But Ford has told Wall Street analysts in the
past that shedding Visteon would make sense only if the transaction
were tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said antitrust concerns would have
complicated, but probably not scuttled, the merger of any big auto
parts companies by forcing the divestiture of certain product
lines. Early last year, when Federal-Mogul Corp. bought T&AMP;N PLC, of
Britain, the Federal Trade Commission determined that the combined
company had too high a share in the thin-wall engine bearing
business, and forced Federal-Mogul to sell T&AMP;N's global
engine-bearing business to Dana Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
