<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2717 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CENSUS-INCOME-ART-875     09-30 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-INCOME-ART-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISING INCOMES LIFT 1.1. MILLION OUT OF POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lifted by the strong economy, American households
are climbing out of the income stagnation that has plagued them for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Rising incomes brought 1.1 million poor Americans out of poverty
last year and the percentage of people still below the official
poverty line fell to the lowest level since 1989, the Census Bureau
reported on Thursday. While blacks failed to increase their incomes
or lower their numbers living in poverty, as they had in 1997, they
held onto the gains that have come to them as a result of the boom
that began four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   An upbeat annual report on trends in American wages issued by
the Census Bureau suggested that the strong economy and the lowest
unemployment rate in 30 years have played big roles in improving
the lot of millions of American households.
</P>
<P>
   ``You raise wages in the short run by tightening the labor
market, but that has its limits,'' said Frank Levy, a labor
economist at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``You
cannot make the unemployment rate much lower than it already is,
and if wages are to continue to rise, that depends on the
productivity of workers and their bargaining clout with
management.''
</P>
<P>
   The most troubling aspect of the Census Bureau report concerned
income inequality. Although incomes rose last year for most
households, the spreads between the rich and the poor, and the rich
and middle-income Americans, have failed to narrow in the
prosperous late 1990s. And 1998 was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Incomes were another matter. The income of the median household,
meaning that half the nation's households earn more and half less,
recovered the ground that had been lost in the 1990s, and a bit
more. The median rose by 3.5 percent, the biggest jump in 13 years,
to $38,885, finally edging past the 1989 figure of $37,997,
adjusted for inflation. Households both above and below the median
also enjoyed roughly similar improvements.
</P>
<P>
   But income inequality has been resistant to the economic boom. A
high-end household, with an annual income of $133,000, for example,
still earns eight times more than a family at the poverty line of
$16,655 for a four-person household. That has been the ratio since
1993.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton saw a glass half full in the failure to
shrink income inequality. Noting that the gaps had widened during
the 1980s economic expansion, he argued that economic growth in the
1990s has been powerful enough to halt the process. ``Finally we
have stemmed the tide of rising inequality,'' he said, ``and this
new report documents the strong income growth among all groups of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are less sanguine. After six years of recession or weak
expansion, they note, a period of unusually strong economic growth
kicked in four years ago. Unemployment, at 4.5 percent last year,
was at its lowest level in decades. Wages have risen for tens of
millions of Americans, even after allowing for inflation. The
economy is indeed lifting many boats, but a rising economy, the
critics argue, has not yet been sufficient to reduce income
inequality.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the strongest economy in 30 years is unable to ameliorate
this serious economic and social problem, there is a strong
rationale for public policy that addresses these concerns,'' said
Jared Bernstein, a labor economist at the Economic Policy
Institute, which favors a higher minimum wage and laws that would
strengthen unions.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is now considering a proposal to raise the minimum wage
to $6.15 in two annual installments of 50 cents each.
Administration officials argued on Thursday that the earned income
tax credit, by rebating money to low-income households, has played
a role in reducing poverty and preventing the income gap from
widening. Citing this view, Clinton criticized Republicans on
Thursday for a proposal now before Congress to defer some of those
tax rebates.
</P>
<P>
   For the third year since 1994, more than a million Americans
rose above the official poverty line. The percentage of the
population still in poverty fell to 12.7 percent, or 34.5 million
people, from 13.3 percent, the lowest level since 1989. The rate
among blacks, 26.1 percent, is the lowest level on record, though
it is still a striking 2.5 times greater than the rate for whites.
But for the first time since 1993, there was no noticeable change
from the previous year. Hispanics, on the other hand, dropped their
poverty rate by nearly 1.5 percentage points, to 25.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, American workers accomplished this feat in part
by working longer hours, but in 1998 time spent on the job leveled
off at 3,149 hours a year _ roughly 60 a week _ barely changed from
the 3,139 hours in 1997, according to an analysis of the Census
data by the Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But other comparisons made the 1998 numbers seem less
impressive. The Center on Budget and Policy Priorities called
attention to the fact that the poverty rate, for all its decline in
recent years, is still above the rate for any year in the 1970s.
Similarly, poverty rates among children, which are higher in the
United States than in Canada or Western Europe, fell a full
percentage point, to 18.9 percent. But that level is well above the
rate in the 1970s.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Then, too, the decline in the poverty rate came almost entirely
as a result of a sharp drop in the South. Everywhere else, there
was no change to speak of, the Census Bureau said. The South, in
fact, has shrunk the percentage of people in poverty throughout the
decade _ partly because many companies have moved operations there,
generating millions of jobs, and partly because a big percentage of
the population earns the minimum wage and thus benefited from
increases in that minimum in 1997 and 1998. Poverty in the West, by
contrast, has risen during the decade, partly because of an
unusually large influx of immigrants, some economists say.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau, in its annual report, highlights household
income, because that includes virtually every American, including
unmarried young people living alone or with friends. Family income
is also calculated and that showed a similar improvement in 1998,
the median level rising to $46,737 in 1998 from $45,262.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
