<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2719 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-FRONTPAGE-1STLD-NYT &LR;      09-30 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-1STLD-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Eds.: adds new story, SCI-MARS-ORBITER; rearranges page) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Oct. 1. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-NUKE (Tokyo) _ In the worst accident in Japan's troubled
history with nuclear power, an out-of-control reaction at a fuel
fabrication plant near Tokyo spewed high levels of radiation into
the air. Thirty-five people were exposed, three of them seriously
injured, and 300,000 residents were ordered to stay indoors. By
Howard W. French. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,500
words.
</P>
<P>
   Story runs with 3-column photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Sidebar inside, JAPAN-NUKE-EXPLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead stories:
</P>
<P>
   NOBEL-GRASS (Berlin) _ Guenter Grass, whose epic first novel,
``The Tin Drum,'' first tackled the theme of Germany's agonized
identity, which he has examined from various angles throughout his
life, is awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature. By Roger Cohen.
(The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BRADLEY-DEBATE (Los Angeles) _ Vice President Al Gore and
former Sen. Bill Bradley are poised to begin an unusually early and
intense series of debates in the run-up to the primary season next
year. As a start, their campaigns say they have agreed to take part
in a nationally televised town meeting four weeks from now in New
Hampshire. By Richard L. Berke. (The story has moved in ``p'' news
file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to FUNDRAISING-REPORT, inside.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-INCOME (Washington) _ Lifted by the nation's strong
economy, 1.1 million poor Americans rose out of poverty in 1998,
and the number of people still below the official poverty line fell
to the lowest level since 1989. By Louis Uchitelle. (The story has
moved in ``w'' news file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ASSESS (Beijing) _ A news analysis on 50 years of
communism in China: In a different China, feelings of both pride
and regret. By Erik Eckholm. (The story has moved in ``i'' news
file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars inside: CHINA-ANNIVERSARY, CHINA-REVOLUTION.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   3-column photo reefer to: NY-MUSEUM-OPENING; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-ORBITER (Los Angeles) _ Simple confusion over whether
measurements were metric or not led to the crash last week of a
$125 million spacecraft as it approached Mars, NASA says. By Andrew
Pollack. (Scheduled to move by 10 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ARMS-TREATY (Washington) _ In an abrupt but calculated reversal,
the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, offers to schedule a quick
vote on a treaty banning nuclear testing, expressing confidence
that Republicans have the votes to defeat one of President
Clinton's top foreign policy goals. By Eric Schmitt. (The story has
moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-GUERRILLAS (Dili, East Timor) _ After 24 years in the
hills, some pro-independence Timorese guerrillas come down and
visit the capital. By Seth Mydans. (The story has moved in ``i''
news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Riot police stop a
march of anti-regime demonstrators for the second consecutive
night, clubbing opposition leaders without provocation and
stampeding thousands of people back toward the center of Belgrade.
By Steven Erlanger. (The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,200
words.
</P>
