<P>
   (NYT25) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- CHINA-FAMILIES, 09-24
-- ``Because I studied history I can communicate with my father's
generation,'' said Wang Dong, part of the third generation of the
family from Yuhuan village. ``But many young people can't.'' His is
pictured in his apartment near the campus of UCLA where he his a
graduate student. He is the first in his family to travel outside
China. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) EDISON, N.J. -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 3
-- BIZ-PRODUCTS-CHARITY, 09-30 -- A father and son examining a Tim
Allen craft kit in a Target store in Edison. Allen's vision was to
cash in on his fixated-with-tools comic persona by making
high-quality hammers, drills and other tools, and giving the
profits to the Tim Allen and Laura Diebel Foundation. But during
the first few years, the company has lost money. (Frank C.
Dougherty/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- SENSATION-REVIEW-2, 09-30
-- Gary Hume's ``Begging for It,'' on display as part of
``Sensation,'' the controversial new exhibit at the Brooklyn Museum
of Art. It would have been nearly impossible to anticipate that the
exhibit would provoke Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to go so far as to try
to evict the museum from its building. (Brooklyn Museum of Art/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- SENSATION-REVIEW-1, 09-30
-- Damien Hirst's ``Away From the Flock,'' on display as part of
``Sensation,'' the controversial new exhibit at the Brooklyn Museum
of Art. The survey of work by young British artists finally opens
to the public Saturday, two years after it was on view in London,
and despite Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's attempts to evict the museum
from its building. (Brooklyn Museum of Art/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) PHILADELPHIA, Pa. -- Sept. 30, 1999 --
BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN, 09-30 -- New York Mets pitcher Masato Yoshii
pitches against the Philadelphia Phillies last Friday. It was only
a few weeks ago that Yoshii was considered marginal in the Mets'
glut of starting pitchers. However Yoshii has been the Mets' most
dependable pitcher in September. While Hideki Irabu remains an
enigma with the Yankees, Yoshii has proved himself to be a steady
competitor with a good attitude. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) HUDSON, Mass. -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS,
09-30 -- Visitors take close looks at Hot Rods on display at the
27th Annual Ty-Rods Old Timers Reunion on Monday. Thousands came to
see the 1,100 cars whose owners were lucky enough to sign up in
time to be admitted. Founded in Concord in 1952, the Ty-Rods have
been holding this show ever since they decided nearly three decades
ago that they needed a way to get old members back together.
(Dominic Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- HYBRID-CARS-2, 09-30 -- The
Toyota Prius, already on sale in Japan and due here later in the
2000 model year, is a four-seater that will go more than 60 miles
on a gallon of gas, the manufacturer says. The car will sell in the
low $20,000 range - more than a Corolla, which is about the same
size, and less than a Camry. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- HYBRID-CARS-1, 09-30 --
Honda's Insight will be in showrooms by December, the first
mass-produced hybrids offered for sale in this country. They will
have an EPA fuel economy rating of more than 70 miles a gallon, the
company says, and will sell for less than $20,000. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- SPEND-CONGRESS-2, 09-30
-- Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle and Budget Director Jack Lew
check out their surroundings before the start of a news conference
about the federal budget on Thursday. At left is House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt. Disputes by the dozen left most congressional
spending bills unfinished as fiscal 1999 turned to 2000. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 09-30 --
Mark Linn-Baker performing in ``Chesapeake'' at the Second Stage.
The one-man show, about a performance artist who kidnaps a
conservative senator's dog, begins previews on Friday night. ``When
I read it, I knew it was something I wanted to do,'' says
Linn-Baker, who is also one of the play's producers. ``I was just
praying I wasn't the only one that thought that.'' (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 3 --
DAME-EDNA-THEATER-2, 09-30 -- Barry Humphries (aka Dame Edna)
outside the Booth Theater. Sylvia Miles, Monique Van Vooren,
Michael Feinstein and Isaac Mizrahi- celebrities of a certain
quirky ilk - have already been to see Dame Edna. ``I was determined
to find a rhyme for Mizrahi,'' says Humphries, 65. (Jeffery A.
Salter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 3 --
DAME-EDNA-THEATER-1, 09-30 -- Dame Edna Everage (aka Barry
Humphries) on stage at the Booth Theater. ``I'm a luxury item,''
she says of her stateside status. ``I'm caviar. A special interest
for the discerning few.'' Although less well-known in America than
in any other English-speaking part of the world, Dame Edna has had
no trouble so far drawing a celebrated audience. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- EPIC-THEATER-REVIEW, 09-30
-- Alan Tudyk and Kristin Chenoweth in ``Epic Proportions,'' which
opened Friday night at the Helen Hayes. The production spoofs the
sprawling biblical narrative screen gems of the sort that Cecil B.
De Mille used to whip up. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- ART-NOTES, 09-30 --
Picasso's 1938 ``Seated Woman in a Garden'' will be sold at
Sotheby's in November. The auction house estimates that the
painting, which measures about 51 by 38 inches, could bring $40
million. (Sotheby's/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- SPEND-CONGRESS, 09-30 --
House Republicans use a toy safe to lock up a mock Social Security
``charge'' card bearing President Clinton's name as a prop during
their news conference about budget negotiations with the White
House on Thursday. House members from left: House Majority Leader
Dick Armey and Rep. Paul Ryan. ``Mr. and Mrs. America, President
Clinton is using your Social Security card as his personal credit
card for more government spending,'' Armey told a news conference,
continuing the GOP drive to position itself as the defender of the
pension program. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- CLINTON-BUDGET, 09-30 --
President Clinton speaks to reporters about the federal budget at
the White House on Thursday. Clinton signed a spending measure to
keep the federal government open three more weeks, giving him and
Republicans more time to try to bridge a wide gulf on a 2000 budget
deal. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 3 --
BOYS-DON'T-CRY-FILM, 09-30 -- The actress Hilary Swank in Manhattan
in August. ``Its absolutely amazing what happens when a woman chops
her hair off,'' says Ms. Swank, who cut hers to play a woman
passing as a young man in the film ``Boys Don't Cry.'' The movie,
opening Friday, tells the tale of Teena Brandon, a young woman from
Nebraska who abandoned her identty to embark on a new life as
Branda Teena. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 3 --
MUSICALS-DANCING, 09-30 -- Deborah Yates and Boyd Gaines in
``Contact,'' choreographed and directed by Susan Stroman and
written by John Weidman. In the last couple of seasons, the musical
theater - both in New York and in London - seems to have
rediscovered dancing. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) AMSTERDAM, N.Y. -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- GORE-CAMPAIGN, 09-30
-- Vice President Al Gore greets Christopher Chioneck as his mother
Lisa Choat looks on during Gore's tour of the economically
depressed town in upstate New York on Thursday. At right is Housing
and Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo. Gore, who until a few
months ago appeared to have the nomination all locked up, if facing
a strong challenge from his only Democratic rival, former U.S.
Senator Bill Bradley. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CAMBRIIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- MUSIC-BACH-BOS,
09-30 -- From left, Christoph Wolff, Patricia Kennedy Grimsted, and
Barbara Mahrenholz Wolff, at the Music Library in Harvard
University's Paine Hall last week. The group found recently the
``lost'' musical estate of Carl Philipp Emanuel Bach (1714-1788),
second son of Johann Sebastian Bach and in his own lifetime the
best-known member of the musical Bach family. (Mark Wilson/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- Sept. 30, 1999 --
HAITI-AID-2-HNS, 09-30 -- Traffic chokes the crumbling streets of
the once-charming Haitian city of Port-au-Prince. ``International
aid for the past 40 years has failed,'' says economist Kesner
Pharel, a former Haitian central bank official who now owns a
private consulting firm. ``People are living the same way they
always have. It's like having someone in the hospital,'' Pharel
explains. ``You try to make them comfortable until they die, but
they will never leave the ward.'' (Andrew Innerarity/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti -- Sept. 30, 1999 --
HAITI-AID-1-HNS, 09-30 -- A Haitian youngster frolics in a
garbage-choked drainage gully that runs through the Port-au-Prince
neighborhood of Cite Absalon. The U.S. government has been spending
about $100 million a year in Haiti since 1994. ``They're spending a
lot of money, but things are getting worse,'' says Michelle Carter,
an official in Port-au-Prince with CARE, a U.S-funded aid agency
that has been working in Haiti since 1959. ``It seems like the
needs have increased and people's expectations have increased.''
(Andrew Innerarity/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) TAUNTON, Mass. -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- HOME-SILVER-BOS-2,
09-30 -- Table knives in a Chestnut Hill pattern, an order for a
hotel, await finishing touches at the Reed &AMP; Barton Silversmiths
factory earlier this month. Although it has reconfigured the Davis
Cup and made the medals for the 1996 summer Olympics, the 175-year
old silversmiths are reknowned for their table silverware. (Joanne
Rathe/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) TAUNTON, Mass. -- Sept. 30, 1999 -- HOME-SILVER-BOS-1,
09-30 -- Mario Moniz smooths edges on ice cream spoons at the Reed
&AMP; Barton Silversmiths factory earlier this month. Although it has
reconfigured the Davis Cup and made the medals for the 1996 summer
Olympics, the 175-year old silversmiths are reknowned for their
table silverware. (Joanne Rathe/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) JERICHO, West Bank -- Sept. 30, 1999 --
ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS, 09-30 -- Israeli soldiers look on as Mustafa
Zibri, right, second in command of the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, or PFLP, talks to reporters after
returning to the West Bank from Syria on Thursday. Zibri's return
signals an attempt by opponents of peace with Israel to reclaim
their dwindling power base in the Palestinian areas. Asked if the
PFLP will remain an opposition group, Zibri said, ``Yes,
definitely,'' but indicated that the group will not use violence
against Israel or Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
