<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2724 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-OPENING-ART     09-30 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-OPENING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: amendment rights. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The museum's lawyer, Floyd Abrams, was asking Judge Nina Gershon
to schedule a hearing when Michael Hess, the city's corporation
counsel, announced that the city had filed its own suit.
</P>
<P>
   Hess contended that since the city had brought suit in state
court, the federal suit filed by the museum should be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Gershon said she would consider the city's request, and
told both sides to submit papers by Oct. 4 on all the issues in the
case, including on whether she should dismiss it. The judge will
hold another hearing on Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's most widely discussed work, Chris Ofili's
``Holy Virgin Mary,'' was ensconced behind a Plexiglas shield in a
small alcove, with a guard posted nearby, in an apparent effort to
forestall any overt acts of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Four more of Ofili's works, all executed in his favored medium,
elephant dung, are also on view. All display his hallmark technique
of supporting the main body of work on two footlike pedestals of
dried pachyderm product, which is said by collectors to lose its
smell after it has aired out for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit also contains several pieces by Damien Hirst, who
works mostly in dead fish and animals. These include a shark, a
sliced-up cow, a lamb and a bisected pig in formaldehyde-filled
cases, and a Rube Goldberg-like device in which maggots feed on a
dead cow's head and give rise to flies, which are eventually zapped
by an electrical device called an ``insect-o-cutor.'' This last is
said to be a meditation on mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Basking in the publicity that the controversy has generated, the
museum played host to hundreds of reporters and photographers
Thursday morning for a first look at the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to see so many members of the press interested in
art,'' Arnold Lehman, the museum's director, said dryly, welcoming
the unaccustomed horde.
</P>
<P>
   But the embattled curator quickly turned serious, saying:
``Public funding of the arts is an investment in the values and the
ideals embodied in the First Amendment of the United States
Constitution. I hope that people will choose to see this
exhibition. I also hope they have the right to choose not to see
this exhibition. That is what democracy in America is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's something else I'd like to say,'' he added. ``The
Brooklyn Museum is more than just one work of art that incorporates
animal dung.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lehman staunchly defended Ofili's choice of artistic
material, saying that the use of animal dung is venerated in many
African cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they tell us is not a story of blasphemy, but of
reverence,'' he said. ``But it is in a language that is foreign to
many of us raised in the tradition of Western culture. Having these
sacred objects in our museums teach us lessons of tolerance,
understanding and diversity. If people do not make the effort to
understand, if people do not exercise tolerance and mutual respect,
then we all suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani continued to fulminate against the exhibition
Thursday from Bakersfield, Calif., where he was on a political
fund-raising jaunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the motivation is commercial
motivation. You'd have to be a fool not to see that,'' the mayor
said of the dispute that he himself stirred up. ``This is
essentially what you do to promote some kind of commercial
enterprise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
