<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2726 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-JOBS-$ADV03-NYT &LR;      09-30 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-JOBS-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUGGING THE DIKE AT WORK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.Y., Fla.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every once in a while, a worker's absence, for vacation or
whatever other reason, brings a request for a colleague to take on
new or unfamiliar duties. It's the old sink-or-swim situation.
Sometimes it's a near-drowning experience, but it can also offer
buoyant memories. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s, George Zucker of Haverford, Pa., was working
at a small radio station in Savannah, Ga., and pursuing his dream
of becoming a disk jockey. When the Sunday morning D.J. went on
vacation, Zucker was asked to work his shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I had to do was sign the station on and play
easy-listening music until the remote broadcast from the Taliaferro
Baptist Church,'' Zucker writes. ``As the church announcer, my job
was to introduce the pastor, then fade-in the chorus. Taliaferro
was pronounced `toliver,' and I learned it wasn't the only language
that needed watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I turned up the chorus that first Sunday morning, there was
only silence. Fearing the remote feed was lost, I uttered an
unchurchly expletive, a strong sibilant, which wafted into the
homes of all awaiting the holy word. The mike was open, which is
why I didn't hear the chorus in my earphones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the pastor and his flock heard me loud and clear,
blessedly no one complained to the station.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when Barbara S. Arion of Queens, N.Y., was a
teen-ager, she worked in the summer for the department store in a
small city.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two women who worked in the stationery
department,'' she writes. ``One was on vacation, and the other
became ill.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Arion and another teen-ager were assigned to fill their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was priced, as these two ladies had worked for the
store for years and knew every piece of their merchandise,'' she
says. ``We young people knew nothing of Crane and Eaton stationery,
as we could not afford these items.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, for the two weeks that we worked in the department, we
sold everything at the only pricing we knew _ Woolworth's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management never knew the difference. They thanked us for our
effort, as we had worked diligently and kept the stock neat and the
counter attractive. This type of problem would not exist today
because of the UPC code and computerization.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1986, and the place was Khartoum, the Sudan. Most
Americans had been evacuated after a terrorist incident in which a
United States embassy employee was shot.
</P>
<P>
   Louise M. Jones, now of Sebring, Fla., was the embassy's
procurement agent. A reduction in staff prompted by the incident
meant that everyone took on extra tasks, ready or not.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones soon found herself adding the duties of the personnel
officer, then the refugee affairs officer. At the same time, she
and her husband, Tim, an Army warrant officer attached to the
embassy, assumed unofficial but vital duties as hosts of occasional
gatherings in their home to help the morale of the remaining,
fearful staff.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Ms. Jones's services were volunteered to replace
the consular officer in charge of issuing visas. Then she found
herself dealing with the complaints of two Sudanese employees who
said they were overwhelmed by problems involving landlords,
contractors and suppliers, along with impatient visa applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I realized I was having equal difficulty in coping with
the sheer quantity of clients as well as with the confusion of
switching hats several times within an hour,'' Ms. Jones said. ``I
gave notice that I was going on strike and relinquishing
administrative duties within a week and would also be taking time
off to prepare for our scheduled departure from the Sudan in the
near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones continues: ``I don't claim to have done it all well,
but I did do it all, as did my colleagues. I realized how unique
was my situation when, one day, I found myself in the health unit,
as the only American woman available on site, to be present during
the gynecological exam of a patient by the male physician's
assistant.''
</P>
<P>
   During the exam, she said, ``I sat absorbing information in a
catalogue about specifications for septic tanks for the homes of
embassy personnel and had to be stirred from my reverie to be told
the exam was over and that I could leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
