<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2729 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ART-72     09-30 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-ART-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM FROM BUSH APPEARS TO DOOM REPUBLICAN BUDGET TACTIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT11, NYT17 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) (th) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Republican strategy to help finance the party's
spending plans by delaying federal tax breaks for working-class
families appeared doomed Thursday by opposition from the party's
senators and its leading presidential candidate, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush strongly criticized the Republican plan, which calls for
delaying payments of the earned-income tax credit, a tax break for
20 million working-class Americans. The proposal was the brainchild
of his fellow Texas Republican, House Majority Whip Tom DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they ought to balance their budget on the backs
of the poor,'' Bush said. It was the first major policy dispute
between Bush and Republicans in Congress, and it erupted despite
his pledge in June to refrain from criticizing them.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay responded by saying of Bush, ``He obviously doesn't
understand how Congress works.''
</P>
<P>
   As the fiscal year came to an end at midnight Thursday night
without a coherent budget from Congress, President Clinton signed a
measure keeping the government running for three weeks, while
warning Republicans to lay off ``gimmicks and gamesmanship'' in
their spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed that continuing spending bill not because I wanted
to,'' Clinton said, ``but because it was the only way to prevent
another government shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line at the end of the fiscal year was that
Republicans, having pledged repeatedly and passionately to write a
budget that would not use Social Security funds, now find
themselves billions of dollars shy of that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to do it,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois acknowledged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But to fail after making such fervent promises, many Republicans
believe, would be a political nightmare, unless they can
convincingly blame Clinton for the failure.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Republican leaders, including Hastert, brandished
copies of a letter from the Congressional Budget Office that they
said proved that they could complete the year's spending bills
without dipping into the Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   But the letter, one paragraph long and without supporting data,
was based on a plan to limit spending to $592 billion. The House
Republicans' own figures, circulated among members on Wednesday,
show them spending at least $600 billion, which would require a
$7.6 billion dip into Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans' plan was to cover that cost by delaying
payments of the earned-income tax credit. By breaking the payments
to the 20 million workers into monthly disbursements instead of
making them in annual lump sums as in the past, the Republicans
would push $8.7 billion of the payments into the fiscal year 2001.
</P>
<P>
   With a few other spending and savings adjustments, they would
bring their budget in $400 million shy of the need to spend Social
Security surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working people don't need help with their annual budget,''
DeLay argued Thursday. ``They need help with their monthly
budget.'' Hastert defended the idea as ``good policy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, DeLay single-handedly pushed an amendment
delaying the tax credit payments into the $85 billion spending bill
financing the Labor, Education and Health and Human Services
departments, winning a party-line vote in the House Appropriations
Committee. That means the idea is likely to come to a vote on the
House floor in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea, the heart and soul of the House Republicans' plan
to avoid spending Social Security funds, appeared to suffer fatal
political damage from Bush's opposition. Even if it survives a vote
in the full House, senior Republican senators strongly oppose it
and Clinton said Thursday he would never sign a spending bill
including the provision.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay learned of Bush's opposition while pushing the plan in the
Appropriations Committee hearing. Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, the
ranking Democrat on the committee, read Bush's comments aloud from
a news service article. The news left DeLay in stony silence.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said his amendment had been approved by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that vote, Congress made little visible progress in
completing its work on government appropriations for the fiscal
year 2000, which begins at 12:01 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 13 spending bills remain unfinished. Four have been
signed into law by Clinton, and one, financing the District of
Columbia, has been vetoed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The biggest works in progress _ bills financing the military,
labor programs, education, health and human services, agriculture
and transportation _ have been bogged down in bitter disputes over
political priorities and complicated by some of the most complex
accounting devices veteran members of Congress could recall.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest of all _ the Pentagon spending bill, nearly $270
billion _ has been held up by a dispute over financing for the
first models of the Air Force's F-22 jet, the most expensive
fighter aircraft in history. House and Senate negotiators have
agreed on the outlines of a deal that would block the Air Force
from building combat-ready aircraft in 2000, but allow production
of test models.
</P>
<P>
   As another example of the creative accounting devices the
Republican Congress is using, the Pentagon bill has also been
temporarily stripped of more than $8 billion, which will be
transferred to finance domestic programs, and then replaced by the
declaration of a spending ``emergency'' _ although no one is sure
exactly where the emergency money is supposed to come from.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring spending an emergency means that it technically does
not count against the spending limits, or caps, imposed by Congress
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate took $8 billion out of our bill,'' said Rep. John
Murtha of Pennsylvania, a veteran Democratic military appropriator.
``Where the hell are we going to get the $8 billion?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
