<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HEALTHCARE-CONGRESS-N     09-30 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SAY GOP MOVE UNDERCUTS HMO BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Supporters of a comprehensive House bill to
regulate managed care are accusing the Republican leadership of
trying to scuttle the legislation by tying it to a separate bill
that contains tax credits that Democrats strongly oppose.
</P>
<P>
   The House next week will debate several health-care bills
focusing on patients' rights under managed care. The bill most
likely to pass, sponsored by Reps. John Dingell, D-Mich., and
Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., enlarges the right to sue health
maintenance organizations and insures that people in HMOs have
access to emergency room care and to medical specialists.
</P>
<P>
   But Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois and other House
Republican leaders are trying to limit patients' ability to sue,
and have sought to mobilize their narrow majority behind another
bill that would siphon support away from the bipartisan
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Hastert and other House Republicans introduced a
bill that aims to broaden health-care coverage to 43 million
uninsured Americans. Some ideas in it, like expanding tax
deductions for self-employed people, enjoy broad bipartisan
support. But Democrats oppose other provisions, like tax-free
medical savings accounts, saying such accounts would draw the
healthiest and wealthiest people out of the insurance pool,
increasing premiums for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The rules for the floor debate next week will not be worked out
until Monday. But Hastert and Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the
majority leader, have said the House would vote separately on the
new insurance access bill, which is likely to pass, and then on the
Dingell-Norwood bill and other managed-care bills. The results
would be combined into one bill for purposes of negotiating with
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of this, supporters of the Dingell-Norwood bill said,
would be to drain Democratic votes away from their legislation
because even if it passed, it would be blended with a measure
riddled with what they called ``poison pills.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a serious attempt to address the problems of 43
million Americans with no health insurance,'' Norwood said in a
statement. ``It is an attempt to defeat managed-care reform through
parliamentary maneuvering.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were equally biting in their criticism. Dingell called
the bill ``a compendium of diversionary and obfuscatory mischief.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader, said it
was too costly and represented ``a cynical, desperate, last-minute
attempt to stave off a bipartisan managed-care bill on the verge of
passage, not a genuine effort to pass legislation to benefit
uninsured Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican aides say it is necessary to combine the
managed-care and access bills because the Senate's health-care
bill, approved in July, did not include any tax breaks. But Senate
Republican aides say their bill provides $13 billion in new tax
breaks, including medical savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill offered this week, sponsored by Reps. John
Shadegg of Arizona and James Talent of Missouri, both Republicans,
includes more than $40 billion in tax breaks over 10 years that
were part of the tax-cut bill that President Clinton vetoed
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have focused on these incentives because their
polling shows that Americans are more concerned about the uninsured
than regulating the managed-care industry. The bill would also
allow small businesses to use pooled bargaining power to negotiate
cheaper insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will allow the uninsured, especially families, greater
affordability when purchasing health care,'' Shadegg said.
</P>
<P>
   The health-care issue has been a political minefield for
Hastert. The original bill he promoted resembled the Senate
legislation, which sharply limited the ability of patients to sue
health-care providers.
</P>
<P>
   But several House Republicans, including many who are doctors or
dentists, like Norwood, a dentist, objected that the bill was not
helpful to patients, and they forged an alliance with the Democrats
backing the Dingell-Norwood bill. At least 40 of the 222 House
Republicans and almost all 211 House Democrats favor some form of
HMO liability proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert sought to broker a compromise, sponsored by Shadegg and
Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla. Their version, unlike the bipartisan plan,
does not include a right to sue in state court. Instead, it allows
the right to sue in federal district court only after a patient has
gone through a thorough appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   The Coburn-Shadegg bill, along with legislation sponsored by
Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, that limits liability even further, will
vie with the Dingell-Norwood bill next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
