<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-WILL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUNMAN'S HOUSE CLEARED FOR SALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB MAHLBURG 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Three weeks before Larry Gene Ashbrook went
on a murderous rampage at Wedgwood Baptist Church, a judge issued
an order upholding his father's will and clearing the way for the
sale of Ashbrook's home.
</P>
<P>
   Some friends and neighbors say Ashbrook may have been distraught
because he feared losing his home in Forest Hill, a Fort Worth
suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that Ashbrook's father, Jack Ashbrook, left the
house to all four children. That typically means that the house
will be sold, said Fort Worth attorney David Lobinger, who handled
the will of Larry Ashbrook's mother 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You end up selling the house and dividing the proceeds in
equal shares,'' Lobinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard R. Swarb, the attorney who handled Jack Ashbrook's will
in court, said he doesn't know what was planned for the house. But
he said that the judge had issued a final order and that steps to
dispose of property, such as selling a house are the job of the
executor of the estate, in this case Ashbrook's brother, Aaron
Ashbrook.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth police Lt. Mark Krey, who is leading the Wedgwood
investigation, called the idea that Ashbrook feared losing his home
``plausible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense,'' Krey said. But ``... the person who could
give us answers is not here to give us answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the Sept. 15 shooting, when seven people were
fatally shot and seven were wounded before Ashbrook killed himself,
the gunman trashed his modest single-story house. He smashed holes
in the walls, poured concrete in the toilets, overturned furniture
and used a shovel to hack large family portraits.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, Mary Thomason, knew the family since Larry Ashbrook
was a boy. She said Ashbrook feared that the house was being sold
out from under him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was what made him snap, because his income was
cut off when his dad died and he thought they were going to sell
the house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tax records show that the three-bedroom, two-bath home was
valued at $23,000. The family always had modest means but was
well-respected, Thomason said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were wonderful people, but their son went wrong,''
Thomason said. ``They were churchgoers, and they were just good
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Wilson, a spokeswoman for the Ashbrook family, said she
was unaware of legal moves involving the will.
</P>
<P>
   Lobinger, an assistant district attorney, said he only vaguely
remembers handling Ashbrook's mother's will 10 years ago. Like the
father's will, it was a standard document, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When their wills were drawn up in 1981, both parents listed
Larry Ashbrook as their last choice of the four children to handle
their affairs. Under the wills, Larry Ashbrook was to be executor
only if all three other children were ``unable or unwilling'' to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   The job of handling an estate is generally given to the child
perceived as the most responsible and with ``the best business
sense,'' Lobinger said. It is fair to assume that neither parent
viewed Larry Ashbrook in that role, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
