<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-CIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY TRIES TO TELL CIA TO STOP SPY OPERATIONS THERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JAMES RISEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A major ally has sent another signal to the United
States that the Cold War is over and that it is time to stop
playing spy games on NATO turf.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, German officials asked a CIA officer to leave the
country for the first time since the Cold War turned Germany into a
battleground for American and Soviet spies. Now, the CIA has been
forced to withdraw three additional officers from Germany,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Some U.S. officials played down the incident, saying it was a
result of friction between the chief of the German internal
security service and the CIA. Those officials stressed that the
move was not a result of a dramatic shift in policy toward the CIA
by Gerhard Schroeder's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the incident does seem to be part of a larger trend by
allied countries to tell Washington quietly that it is time to
scale back espionage operations. And it suggests that CIA efforts
to find new missions _ including economic espionage against trading
partners _ are meeting resistance.
</P>
<P>
   German television reported this week that German officials had
asked a married couple employed by the CIA, along with a superior
from Munich, to leave after the internal security service had
compromised their espionage operation. They were not listed as
official diplomats, but rather appear to be what the CIA calls
``nonofficial cover'' officers who pose as executives or use other
civilian covers to conduct espionage.
</P>
<P>
   The agency refused to comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Germans pressured the agency to withdraw an officer
from Bonn who was involved in economic espionage. That move
represented a significant shift in relations between the CIA and
the German security service.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the CIA had acted as if West Germany was its home
turf and had set up bases throughout the country. The agency has
long had a base in Munich, in part to conduct liaison activities
with the German foreign intelligence service, which is
headquartered there.
</P>
<P>
   But after the reunification in 1990 and the collapse of the
Soviet Union in 1991, German officials began to send quiet messages
to the United States that it was time to cut back. Disputes over
the issue were still not resolved by the time the German government
took action in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is hardly the lone allied country to show impatience
with the agency's post-Cold War presence. In 1995, France moved
against its station in Paris, forcing the withdrawal of several
officers after they had been caught conducting trade-related
espionage. The agency temporarily shut the station and froze
operations in the country until the furor died down.
</P>
<P>
   The agency had similar problems in India and Italy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
