<HEADER>
A2741 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-BUCKEYES01-COX     09-30 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BUCKEYES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio State aims to buck comeback trend
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Come-from-behind victories can be exciting and
inspirational, but they also can be a sign of a problem _
especially if they're coming against lesser opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the last three weeks, No. 12 Ohio State has had
to overcome early deficits to earn victories over relatively
nonthreatening, nonconference opponents.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Buckeyes kick off their Big Ten season against
Rose Bowl champion Wisconsin (2-2), and they realize another slow
start might not be so easy to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 3-1 and happy to be there, fortunate to be there,'' OSU
coach John Cooper said. ``I'm not over here singing the blues, but
we have to improve. I don't want to make (comebacks) a habit.''
</P>
<P>
   To get ahead early, Cooper said his team must eliminate the
``stupid mistakes'' they've been prone to recently: off-side and
illegal motion penalties; mismatched defenses; fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to come out smoking and get (Wisconsin) down and get
'em out of their game plan and out of their rhythm,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   OSU has shown it has the firepower to score early and often;
it's just that lately, it's taken a quarter or two to get the
offense going. Against UCLA three weeks ago, OSU fell behind 10-0
before quarterback Steve Bellisari sparked a comeback. Against Ohio
University, the Buckeyes trailed by 7 before their offense kicked
into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   And last week against Cincinnati, their deficit reached 14
before a couple of big plays bailed them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember last year we used to go down the field on the first
series and score 7 points,'' OSU co-captain and senior fullback
Matt Keller said. ``That's something we haven't done this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let teams get out in front of you with the teams we
have coming up (Wisconsin, Purdue, Penn State, Michigan). They'll
put you away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellisari said coaches have been encouraging him to run with the
ball when he has an opening, something he failed to do much against
Cincinnati. Instead, he relied on a couple of bombs to receiver
Ken-Yon Rambo, who caught three passes for 164 yards and a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big plays aren't always gonna be there. You want to try to
sustain a drive,'' Bellisari said.
</P>
<P>
   OSU had trouble doing that against the Bearcats. UC had the ball
for nearly 35 minutes while OSU had it for 24. UC also racked up 26
first downs; Ohio State had 19.
</P>
<P>
   The return of backup tailback Jonathan Wells and Keller, both of
whom missed the past two games because of ankle sprains, should
help OSU's running game. The Buckeyes already know Wisconsin, with
tailback Ron Dayne and a beefy offensive line, will be tough to
stop on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wisconsin is a big, physical football team that will run it
down our throats unless we stop them,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 Michigan was successful in defeating the Badgers, 21-16,
last week largely because the Wolverines shut down Dayne in the
second half (8 carries, 0 yards). He had 88 yards on 14 carries in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   With UM ahead 21-9 in the third quarter, Wisconsin was forced to
go to the air. Dayne didn't carry the ball in the last 10 minutes
of the game. Cooper knows Dayne will be forced out of the game
again if the Buckeyes can gain and maintain a comfortable lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we tackle Ron Dayne enough Saturday, we'll win,'' Cooper
said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting free safety and leading tackler Gary Berry is doubtful
to start Saturday against Wisconsin because of a neck injury he
sustained last week against Cincinnati, according to Cooper. Senior
Percy King will replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
