<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-ESPN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tennessee fans: ESPN's out to get us
 &HT;    By Leo Willingham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They call it The ESPN Conspiracy in Knoxville, Tenn.
In the hearts and minds of Tennessee football fans it's back _
bigger and stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   From the perspective of many Volunteers fans, it's not a
coincidence that ESPN's SportsCenter broke the story Sunday night
alleging possible academic fraud involving Tennessee football
players and their tutors. They see it as a cold, calculated attempt
by the network to ``get'' Tennessee, the defending national
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Fans have not been bashful about expressing that opinion on
radio talk shows and in other forms of communication. The Knoxville
News-Sentinel ran a cartoon Thursday morning that depicted an
unflattering portrayal of an ESPN reporter in a trench coat. And in
an Internet poll by the newspaper this week, 75 percent of those
responding said ESPN was trying to hurt Tennessee with its
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of fans are convinced that this is ESPN's way of getting
back at Tennessee,'' said Jimmy Hyams, a former reporter with the
News-Sentinel who hosts a daily sports talk show on WNOX radio. ``I
disagree with the idea that there is a conspiracy and have argued
with a lot of people about it. But these people will not be
swayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would ESPN be out to get Tennessee? From the perspective of
Volunteers fans, the fight goes back two years.
</P>
<P>
   _ It began on Dec. 13, 1997, at the Downtown Athletic Club in
New York. Quarterback Peyton Manning, perhaps the most revered
player in Tennessee history, finished second in the Heisman Trophy
voting to Michigan defensive back Charles Woodson. Tennessee fans
blamed ESPN and its parent company, ABC, citing excessive promotion
of Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN offices are hit with angry telephone calls, letters and
faxes. Chris Fowler, the host of ESPN's College Game Day show and
the most visible college football personality at the network,
receives a FedEx box filled with manure.
</P>
<P>
   _ A few days later, during a radio appearance with Nanci
Donnellan on her show ``The Fabulous Sports Babe,'' Fowler was
asked about the emotional reaction of the Tennessee fans and made a
reference to a ``trailer-park frenzy.'' Fowler has apologized
several times for the remark.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Jan. 2, 1998, ESPN took its ``College Game Day'' show to
Miami, where Tennessee faced Nebraska in the Orange Bowl. The
Tennessee crowd around the set became so unruly that extra security
had to be brought in. Fowler again apologized, but it fell on deaf
ears.
</P>
<P>
   _ At January's Fiesta Bowl, center Spencer Riley was asked about
the school's relationship with ESPN. Riley said, ``They've stuck it
to us ever since I've been here.''
</P>
<P>
   The story about alleged academic fraud, some Tennessee fans
thought this week, was ESPN's way of evening the score for the
Peyton Manning fallout. That was the opinion Thursday at the Old
College Inn, a popular hangout near the campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people up here still think they (ESPN) are the reason
Peyton didn't win the Heisman and they've never gotten over it,''
said Tom Clark, a former Tennessee student. ``And now this.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN officials deny any hidden agenda in their reporting of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could be further from the truth,'' said Barry Sacks,
the senior coordinator producer for ``College Game Day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're basically dealing with two issues. One is a bad comment
made by an announcer. The apologies have been made and the issues
have been dealt with,'' Sacks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other is a journalistic story _ a story that has also
occurred at Missouri, Notre Dame and other schools. Our people
received information, they followed up on it and reported it.
That's what news organizations do. These are not personal
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee story was written by Tom Farrey, a reporter who
works for ESPN.com, the organization's Web site, and was based on
copies of internal memos from athletic department memos. The story
was handled by the news division of ``SportsCenter,'' which is an
entirely separate division from ``College Game Day'' or the remote
operations that, ironically, will carry Saturday's game with Auburn
and the Oct. 9 game with Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
