<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-SANKS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sanks' promise shows
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's Jasper Sanks is second in the SEC in
rushing with 326 yards in three games. But the sophomore running
back knows all too well he should have at least one more yard.
</P>
<P>
   Sanks had the longest run from scrimmage of his career _ 54
yards _ against Central Florida last Saturday. But that's not what
people were talking about after the game. They were talking about
how Sanks got caught from behind at the 1 by a defensive back who
came from the other side of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Sanks was looking back at his pursuer rather than accelerating
to the end zone. But Georgia coach Jim Donnan didn't scold Sanks
for the error. He didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took plenty of grief from his teammates on that,'' Donnan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' Sanks said. ``I got phone calls, messages on my
answering machine. My roommmate (Tyrone Robertson) was the worst.
He'd act like he was on the radio: `Sanks could go all the _ oh, no
_ he's down at the 1-foot line!'''
</P>
<P>
   Sanks can joke about it now. Georgia needed three plays to do it
but got into the end zone, and the Bulldogs held on for a 24-23
win.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanks' solid work this season was not obscured by that
lapse. The 6-foot, 216-pound native of Columbus has answered
Georgia's call for a dependable running back. He has rushed for 130
and 147 yards in his last two games. With a 100-yard effort against
LSU on Saturday, he could become the first Georgia back since
Garrison Hearst in 1992 to get 100 in three consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with Jasper,'' Donnan said. ``Jasper's doing a good
job. He needs to keep working on his pass blocking and catching the
ball. Otherwise, he's doing fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Once considered Georgia's next great back, Sanks for a time last
year was considered its biggest bust of the 1990s. The Bulldogs
recruited Sanks over Tennessee's Jamal Lewis. But Sanks was at Fork
Union Military Academy trying to gain his eligibility while Lewis
was rushing for 1,364 yards and seven touchdowns as a freshman in
1997. Last year, Sanks struggled, finishing with 65 yards on 10
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Since last season, Sanks has recovered from hernia surgery and
lost 18 pounds. Now he's resembling the back recruiting analysts
gushed about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Told that he is ahead of Lewis in the latest SEC statistical
rankings, Sanks said with a grin, ``That's good to know. He's about
the only one I keep up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
