u s BC-FBN-FALCONS01-COX     09-30 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons desperate to discover playmaker
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jamal Anderson made his daily visit to Falcons
headquarters Thursday morning. He did his pre-surgical knee
rehabilitation and then, after busting the chops of some teammates,
went away.
</P>
<P>
   Was that the Falcons' security blanket walking out the door? It
depends.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is out for the season, and quarterback Chris Chandler
almost certainly will not play Sunday against Baltimore (1-2)
because of a strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Falcons (0-3) have the talent to win without
Anderson and Chandler, they have to convince themselves that they
can. Easier said than done. Anderson was second in the NFL last
season with 1,846 rushing yards. He and Chandler, the team's two
Pro Bowl offensive players, were the cornerstones of the league's
fourth-most prolific scoring offense last season.
</P>
<P>
   Their absences leave large voids, both physically and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson declined an interview Thursday before shopping for a
house, but he said that he believes in his teammates. He also said
he wasn't in St. Louis on Sunday because he didn't want to be a
distraction. He almost certainly will be at Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, center Robbie Tobeck joked about missing Anderson's
antics in the locker room. On the field, his absence is no joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing about missing Jamal and Chris,'' fullback
Bob Christian said, ``is we got to relying on Jamal to make a play
or Chris to make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian said, ``Now, we don't have those guys, and it's like
everybody is looking around for somebody else to make a play,
instead of each of us saying, `Hey, I'm going to make a play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons went through the same process last season.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 season, the team was 0-6 in games Chandler missed or
didn't finish because of injury and 7-3 otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, he missed the Oct. 25 game against the Jets, but
only after the game, a 28-3 loss on the road, did players and
coaches admit the degree of doubt with which they played.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, however, last season went so well that, after they won
a couple of games that Chandler left with an injury, the Falcons
gained confidence, went to St. Louis and won 21-10 on Nov. 29
without him. The Falcons were 4-1 in games Chandler missed or left
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was . . . a hurdle last year, but I think we're past
that,'' Tony Graziani said. ``Now, (Chandler) has been in there
twice and we haven't won. We know it's not him being gone that is
the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we've had so many bad things happen that our
confidence is shook,'' he said. ``We need to believe . . . in the
11 guys on the field. We need to make some big plays. If we put
together some drives, and create some excitement, I think our
confidence will be back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
