<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2745 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-OPENERS01-COX     09-30 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-OPENERS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Season of change: NHL drops the puck
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wayne Gretzky is gone, and Atlanta is back. It would
be hard to find a hockey fan outside of Georgia who would call that
a fair tradeoff, especially anyone in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL begins its 83rd season full of change and concerned
about who will be its big drawing card now that the Great One has
retired at age 38 after 20 glorious seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, hockey's all-time leading scorer, will be honored
tonight when his last NHL team _ the New York Rangers _ plays his
first _ the Oilers. The tribute, carried by ESPN at 7:30 p.m., will
be a final Edmonton sendoff for No. 99, who led the Oilers to four
Stanley Cup titles in five seasons during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically took the league and carried it on his back for 20
years,'' Vancouver's Mark Messier said of his former teammate in
Edmonton and New York. ``Obviously, the onus now goes on a lot of
the younger players, to learn from what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other game tonight has the Dallas Stars _ the first
Stanley Cup winner from the Sun Belt _ unfurling the championship
banner before hosting Pittsburgh on ESPN at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins, rescued out of bankruptcy court by former star
Mario Lemieux, are led by Jaromir Jagr _ Gretzky's most likely heir
apparent. Jagr, 27, led the NHL in scoring last season with 127
points. The right wing from the Czech Republic had 44 goals and 83
assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody dominates this league now,'' Jagr said. ``Guys like
Mario, Gretzky or Bobby Orr _ they were 20 years ahead of everyone
else when they played.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky played Year 2000 hockey in 1980.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas became the fourth consecutive Western Conference team to
win the Stanley Cup. The Stars beat Buffalo in six games when Brett
Hull scored a controversial goal in triple overtime. Hull had his
left skate in the crease before he put the puck past Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, the most dominant goalie in hockey for most of the 1990s,
announced during the summer that this season will be his last.
``I've played long enough,'' the 34-year-old Czech said. ``I want a
new life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek will be in goal Saturday when the Sabres open the season
at Detroit. The Red Wings won two Stanley Cups in a row before
losing to Colorado in the Western Conference semifinals last
season. Scotty Bowman will try again to win his record ninth Cup as
a coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers are the seventh expansion team to join the NHL in
the '90s, increasing the league total of teams to 28. Minnesota and
Columbus will join the league next season. The NHL had 21 teams in
1979-80, the Flames' last season in Atlanta before they moved to
Calgary. That was Gretzky's rookie year in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to replace Gretzky, the Rangers went on a spending spree
in the offseason, signing Theo Fleury and four other free agents.
But most teams tried to hold the line on skyrocketing salaries. The
average team payroll in 1988-89 was $5.3 million. Last season it
was $31 million per team. This season, the Rangers' payroll will be
about $67 million.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is still in a salary standoff with goalie Byron Dafoe,
who led the NHL with 10 shutouts last season, and the Bruins
dropped forward Dmitri Khristich when he won his arbitration
hearing. Other players who will not be on the ice when the season
starts due to contract squabbles include Keith Primeau, Joe Juneau,
Bill Guerin, Ulf Samuelsson, Mark Tinordi, Ray Sheppard and Joe
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's board of governors made several rule changes,
including going to four-on-four play in overtime. The use of video
replays has been limited, and the foot-in-the-crease rule was
revised. Two referees will be used in 50 games per team.
</P>
<P>
   Some defending Stanley Cup champs have adopted the attitude that
the seven-month regular season is only a tuneup for the playoffs.
But coach Ken Hitchcock thinks that Dallas must strive to have the
league's best record for a third consecutive season for a shot at a
second Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest mistake anyone can make is not worrying about your
daily performance,'' Hitchcock said. ``You can't think, 'Oh, well,
don't worry about it today. We'll get it tomorrow.' If you decide
you're going to drop your level of play in the regular season,
it'll drop in the playoffs. It's just natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
