<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-BIAS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE APPROVES $15 MILLION BOEING BIAS SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A federal judge approved a $15 million settlement of
charges of racial discimination at The Boeing Co. Thursday,
blessing the biggest resolution of racial bias in the history of
the aerospace giant.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge John Coughenour approved a plan that calls
on Boeing to pay $6.65 million to 3,600 employees and to alter its
promotion policies. He rejected the challenge of a group of African
American workers who charge it won't resolve the company's racial
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Cougenhour said both the payment and the internal changes
could help address complaints of discrimination at the world's
largest commercial airplane manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The distribution of information about promotion opportunities
will be improved, changes will be made in the procedure for
resolving discrimination related complaints, and free legal advice
will be available,'' Coughenour wrote in a 14-page decision.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision is an attempt to finally resolve two
class-action lawsuits that alleged a racially hostile environment
existed in the halls and on the manufacturing floors of Boeing. The
suits said blacks were subjected to slurs, crude drawings and
intimidations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Boeing promised to improve the way it hires
and promotes workers; adopt a new system for handling complaints of
discrimination, harassment or retaliation; and hire a consultant to
assess how well the changes work.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's efforts, and the judge's decision, however, aren't
enough, according to some African American employees. They
challenged the way the funds would be distributed and whether
Boeing would be held accountable if it didn't make the promised
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing these workers were mulling whether to take
the next step: to appeal the decision to the 9th Circuit U.S Court
of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's either appeal or nothing, there are no other options,''
said Martin Garfinkel, a partner at the law firm of Frank, Rosen,
Freed, Garfinkel &AMP; Roberts, who represented employees that objected
to the decree.
</P>
<P>
   They have 30 days to decide. Some workers, however, have already
made up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not through,'' said Dennis Harris, a 33-year Boeing
employee, who works in Long Beach, Calif. ``This is
heartbreaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge warned workers upset with the settlement that they
could face an uphill battle if they challenge Boeing in open court.
Boeing has faced a series of race discrimination charges in recent
years and it has won every time, according to Cougenhour.
</P>
<P>
   ``...Discrimination cases are notoriously difficult to prove,
particularly when they are based on failure to promote or other
discretionary practices,'' he wrote. ``There is also some risk that
the class certified by the court would not survive a challenge by
Boeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Cougenhour also dismissed charges that the lawyers who
negotiated the settlement, Oscar Desper III, Bruce Harrell and
others, failed their clients. For example, some workers complained
bitterly of being left in the dark as the settlement moved forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suggestion that this result displays anything less than
excellent legal ability or unwavering committment to the plaintiffs
is unsupportable,'' Cougenhour wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also won approval of their compensation _ $3.1
million to settle the charges and $750,000 to monitor its
implementation. In addition, lawyers representing workers in
Philadelphia are to receive $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 22, Boeing attempted to resolve the charges by
announcing a $15-million settlement, brokered with the help of
civil rights leader Jesse Jackson. Originally, 43 Boeing workers
sued Boeing. Workers for Boeing in Philadelphia and in Wichita,
Kan., joined in the suit. Eventually, a second suit also was
started.
</P>
<P>
   Cougenhour cited Jackson's involvement as proof of the
agreement's strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court considers his meeting with Boeing officials and
subsequent endorsement of the decree to be a very strong indication
that Boeing is sincere in its response,'' Cougenhour wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing offficials promised to honor the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boeing Co. is fully committed to implementating all the
changes as outlined in the consent decree,'' said Jim Dagnon, a
senior vice president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
