<SLUG> BC-SPACE-PIZZA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIZZA HUT TO PUT LOGO ON RUSSIAN ROCKET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pizza Hut Inc., the all-American fast-food purveyor, announced
Thursday that it will pay the Russians to place its new logo on the
rocket that launches the crew module for the international space
station.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-based company would not disclose the amount it will
pay for the fleeting advertisement nor whether it has contracted
with the Russian Space Agency or a private contractor for the
unusual display.
</P>
<P>
   However, company president Mike Rawlings estimated the cost at
half that of a 30-second television spot for January's NFL Super
Bowl. The Wall Street Journal reported the half-minute spot to be
between $1.9 million and $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement will span about 30 feet of the 200-foot tall
Proton rocket that will be launched from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in
Kazakhstan. The colorful rocket will carry the Russian service
module, which includes living quarters for three station residents.
</P>
<P>
   The module is 17 months late because of Russian financial
difficulties, and it is still undergoing ground tests. The National
Aeronatical and Space Administration and Russia, though, have said
it will lift off no sooner than Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, Pizza Hut saw an opportunity to make a statement to
consumers and competitors as the 41-year-old company undergoes a
$500 million makeover, including changes to its 10,000 restaurants
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do something that will capture the world's
attention,'' said Pizza Hut spokesman Jay Allison. The company
symbol will be visible for several minutes as NASA television and
news organizations train their cameras on the launch pad and the
rising rocket.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have flirted with commercial advertisers in space
before, including Pepsi, which produced an inflatable soft drink
can for cosmonauts to display.
</P>
<P>
   NASA, too, has begun to make overtures to prospective commercial
partners, including advertisers. Its current interest is a
corporate venture willing to help it build a large inflatable crew
module that could be launched to the new international station in
2004.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza Hut may be interested in additional space investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to be the first restaurant in space,'' said Allison.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
