<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2761 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-ROUNDUP01-COX     09-30 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-ROUNDUP01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More return home as roads open
 &HT;    By Nichole Monroe
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILE, N.C. _ No, Frances Jollie is not having a yard sale.
</P>
<P>
   The enormous piles of bookcases, appliances, books, clothing and
dressers in Jollie's front yard and garage are what is left of her
home. The house was inundated with about 5 feet of water from the
Tar River, which runs behind her residence.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, Jollie sat amid her belongings in a folding
chair, one of the remaining Greenville residents waiting for her
home to be inspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``A yard sale? Sure, take whatever you want, it's free,'' Jollie
quipped. ``I'm not worried about someone stealing anything because
they can have it. Everything is ruined. I try to put some fun in it
and joke about it to keep from going crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials expect to finish their inspections of flooded
homes by noon today, and will notify residents by phone when they
can pick up their house keys, said Katie Veilleux, public
information officer for the city.
</P>
<P>
   When residents pick up their keys, they can use the Greene
Street bridge because it's open after being closed more than a
week. The bridge was opened Wednesday because high water north of
the bridge subsided enough for cars to travel on the road, Veilleux
said. The bridge was the last artery leading north of the Tar River
to open.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk's office will be open Monday through Saturday 8 a.m.
to 5 p.m. Veilleux was unsure how many homes still need to be
inspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some spotty areas on the north side and random
areas that were inaccessible because of water,'' Veilleux said.
``It's hard to say how many there are.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts are still under way to shelter residents who don't have
homes they can return to. About 440 people moved from shelters at
area schools to Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs in Ayden, Greenville and
Farmville, according to the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Emergency Management Agency workers are still waiting
for the ground to dry enough to set up trailers on County Home Road
for shelter residents to move into, said Rudy Hernandez, FEMA
public affairs officer.
</P>
<P>
   The structures are about 8 feet by 30 feet and accommodate four
to six people. The County Home Road site will house more than 200
people. About 100 trailers will also be put in Grifton and more
will be placed north of the Tar River.
</P>
<P>
   County officials still must inspect about 2,000 homes, but have
been hampered by high water, said county spokesman Arlen Holt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the weather were to hold and the water were to recede
quickly enough, they might be able to get done by the beginning of
next week,'' Holt said. ``We're going back and trying to take care
of some of the things we couldn't get done right away. There are
still a number of areas we couldn't get into.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt said about three-quarters of the homes already inspected
require some kind of repair before the power can be turned on. He
said the damage estimates are not complete but remain at more than
$200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the county, two roads with restricted access have
opened. Pitt County Sheriff Mac Manning said a checkpoint at Clarks
Neck Road was removed Friday morning. A checkpoint at U.S. 264 and
Old Pactolus Road will be removed Saturday. Sunnyside Road and
River Road checkpoints will remain in place indefinitely, Manning
said.
</P>
<P>
   Areas will be re-evaluated every day and opened as flood waters
recede completely and residents can get back in and secure all
their belongings. Intense patrols including officers from other
counties and cities will continue countywide.
</P>
<P>
   With many roads damaged, under repair or closed, Department of
Transportation officials cautioned drivers to be careful while
driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limited access to many parts of the county is creating
bumper-to-bumper traffic congestion during different times of
day,'' a department news release said. ``Pitt County urges citizens
to remain cautious, be patient and drive defensively ... drivers
should anticipate traffic congestion and remain patient when
operating a vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bell Arthur, officials said it is not necessary for Bell
Arthur Water Corporation customers to boil their water.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King III, executive director of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, told about 50 people at Philippi
Church of Christ on Thursday that he would begin work to mobilize
national organizations to come down and help the people of
Greenville and eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is to continue to raise the issue of this
devastation,'' said King, son of slain civil rights leader Martin
Luther King Jr. ``There are still some people who are not being
appropriately provided for.''
</P>
<P>
   King said that upon his return to Atlanta, he will contact and
meet with, among others, leaders of the National Baptist Convention
and the National Conference of Mayors to create dialogue and come
up with ways to aid eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``This needs the nation's attention,'' said King, adding that he
will return in about a week with national leaders. ``People will
help as long as it is on the front pages of the newspapers, but
once it moves to the back, the nation does not respond as well. We
need to keep this out front.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Suggs and Anne Rochell Konigsmark of Cox News Service and
staff writers Judy Royal and Travis Fain contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
