<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2766 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-WRIGLEY-GUM-$ADV0     09-30 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WRIGLEY-GUM-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FOREIGN RIVALS, ONE HUNGRY MARKET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN VAROLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ Once a forbidden pleasure denounced by
Soviet officialdom, chewing gum has become entrenched in Russian
pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer demand for gum has led to a $180 million market _ and,
over the last two years, has brought investments of more than $170
million by international manufacturers in Russian operations.
</P>
<P>
   The William Wrigley Jr. Co. of Chicago, the world's largest
chewing-gum company with global sales of $1.8 billion last year,
has captured about 60 percent of the Russian market, according to
A.C. Nielsen, the market research company.
</P>
<P>
   But in the battle for shelf space in Russian stores, kiosks and
cafes, Wrigley has been dogged by an upstart from Denmark, a
family-owned company named Dandy, maker of the Stimorol and Dirol
brands, with $300 million in worldwide sales. Although its figure
does not jibe with the Nielsen number for Wrigley, Dandy claims 45
percent of the Russian market.
</P>
<P>
   While younger consumers can hardly remember life without gum,
those in their late 20s and older have a different story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a little girl, my swimming coach would tell us that
foreigners put needles in chewing gum to hurt Russian children,''
recalled Anastasia Vasilevskaya, 28, now deputy director of a
British-owned real estate company in St. Petersburg. ``This was
their way to keep us from chewing gum,'' she said, adding, ``I
often chew it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Voronkov, a sociologist in St. Petersburg, said, ``Thanks
to the efforts of Soviet propaganda, there existed a stereotype of
the uncultured American chomping on gum in the most disgusting
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why chewing gum?'' he added. ``Well, it was just an accidental
symbol of the American way of life, which was labeled antagonistic
to the Soviet life style.''
</P>
<P>
   With Russia embracing a market economy, many young people are
buying gum, even though the average monthly salary is only 1,000
rubles, or about $40.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confectionery is one of the first to rebound after any crisis
since prices are relatively low and affordable to the general
population,'' said Philip Wegh, director of the new Dandy factory.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Iskyam, a consumer goods analyst at Renaissance Capital, a
Moscow-based investment bank, said Wrigley and Dandy ``are
interested in Russia because it is a large market that is still in
its infancy, being relatively unsaturated.'' Renaissance Capital is
part of Sputnik Holdings, owned by the Russian-American financier
Boris Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Russian financial crisis of August 1998, the ruble has
fallen from around 6 to the dollar to a little over 25, sharply
raising the cost of most domestic goods as well as imports. Wrigley
and Dandy, because of their intense rivalry, have not raised prices
as much as most manufacturers, though a packet of chewing gum has
climbed to 6 or 7 rubles, from 3 before the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the battle can be seen on television, where Russians
are bombarded by advertising for Dandy's Dirol and Wrigley's
Doublemint, Juicy Fruit and Orbit, a brand popular in Europe though
virtually unknown in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Wrigley's testimonial ads, young Russians praise Wrigley's
``amazingly long-lasting flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, both companies are emphasizing what they call
``dental positioning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirol is functional chewing gum, and in our ads we try to
communicate the benefits of chewing it in the fight against tooth
decay,'' said Stanislav Cherkasov, Dandy's media and public
relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   An even stronger indication of the foreign companies' commitment
to the Russian market is the money spent building plants here. The
$70 million Wrigley plant in St. Petersburg began production in
late winter and will produce 15,000 tons of gum annually, not only
for Russia, which Wrigley says is one of its top 10 markets, but
also for export to Europe. Such exports would be important in case
of persistent economic difficulties in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Dandy built a $95 million plant in Veliky Novgorod, 112 miles
southwest of St. Petersburg, where it will make 7,000 tons of
Stimorol and Dirol a year. Lars Funder, general director of Dandy,
said it was ``100 percent committed to the Russian market.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrigley executives were also upbeat. ``Our sales last year in
Russia were around $100 million,'' said Stefan Pfander, Wrigley
vice president for Europe. ``Despite the economic difficulties''
last year, he added, ``we are here for the long haul.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
