<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2768 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV03-     09-30 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SAVINGS BONDS SPUTTER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 3) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Ill.)   (af)  
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last May, Richard P. Drury, 74, a retired civilian employee of
the Army who lives in Hilton Head, S.C., was reading a newspaper
article that led him to a startling discovery: 15 United States
savings bonds held by him and his wife, Carol _ worth a total of
$3,707.90 _ had not been earning any interest for at least three
years.
</P>
<P>
   He immediately cashed in these Series E bonds, which he had
acquired for $562.50 through a payroll deduction savings plan, and
stuck the money in a bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Before reading the article, Drury had no idea that the
government changed its rules about such bonds in 1965. Under that
revision, Series E bonds issued through November 1965 earn interest
for 40 years; those issued in December 1965 and later earn interest
for just 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew that,'' Drury said. ``All the information I had
been reading was printed prior to 1965 and it said 40 years. Can
you image the number of drawers or safety deposit boxes throughout
this country that are just salted up with bonds like these?''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel J. Pederson, a former supervisor of the Savings Bond
Division of the Federal Reserve Bank and the author of ``Savings
Bonds: When to Hold, When to Fold and Everything in Between'' (Sage
Creek Press, fourth edition, $19.95), has calculated that there are
more than $6.5 billion in savings bonds that have stopped earning
interest and never been cashed in. Some people tuck savings bonds
away and forget about them; other mistakenly think the bonds will
earn interest as long as they hold them.
</P>
<P>
   Savings bonds are popular, especially with older investors. Over
all, 55 million people hold a total of $180 billion of savings
bonds of all types.
</P>
<P>
   People like the bonds because they are easy to buy and, though
their various interest rates may be modest, their safety is rock
solid. And because you don't get the interest until you cash in the
bonds, taxes can be deferred until then, too.
</P>
<P>
   The popular Series EE bonds, the successors to Series E, can be
bought for as little as $25 each and have a face value of $50; the
most expensive are $5,000, with a face value of $10,000. Bonds
reach ``original maturity'' when they are worth their face value;
they continue to earn interest until they expire, but at differing
rates.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, figuring out when to cash in a bond can be tricky,
Pederson points out. It can make sense to redeem a bond that is
paying a particularly low rate, but the problem is identifying it _
not a simple task.
</P>
<P>
   Because banks make virtually no money from savings bonds they
sell and redeem, have little incentive to train employees in the
details of savings bond management. And because savings bonds are a
do-it-yourself investment, Uncle Sam, despite switching the rules
from time to time, will never send you a statement outlining your
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not sure of the status of a bond, look first at the
issue date in the upper right corner. Any bonds issued from 1941
through October 1959 have stopped paying interest, as have bonds
issued from December 1965 through October 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Series EE bonds, which were first issued in 1980, earn interest
30 years from the issue date. The same is true for the new Series I
bond, whose return is linked to the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates depend on when a bond was bought. Newly purchased
Series EE bonds earn a market-based rate equal to 90 percent of the
average of Treasury issues with five years left to maturity. The
rate, currently 4.31 percent, is reset every six months.
Inflation-protected Series I bonds now pay 5.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each bond needs to be looked at as an individual investment,''
Pederson said.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for most bond holders to even calculate how much
interest they have accumulated _ and how much their bonds are
therefore worth. Pederson's company, the Savings Bond Informer in
Detroit (800-927-1901), appraises savings bonds for clients based
on a sliding scale. For 1 to 10 bonds, for example, the fee is $15;
for 700 bonds, it is $119.
</P>
<P>
   A report analyzes each bond for a number of factors, including
the current rate it is earning, and offers advice on the best time
to sell it. The Savings Bond Informer also has a Web site
(www.bondhelp.com). The government offers a somewhat similar but
less extensive service free on the Web (www.savingsbonds.gov). It
requires downloading and installing a program called the Savings
Bond Wizard on your personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   After his discovery, Drury had some of his older bonds appraised
by Pederson's company. So did Walter H. Smorowski, 79, who lives in
Des Plaines, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Also alerted by a newspaper article, Smorowski realized that he
had about $6,000 of Series E bonds that were no longer paying
interest. Before cashing them in, he got a report from the Savings
Bond Informer that told him exactly how much they were worth. It
was a good thing, he said, because his bank at first wanted to give
him $1,000 less. The bank quickly corrected its error.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't gotten that report, I probably would have just
taken what they offered me,'' Smorowski said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
