<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AIDE TIED TO EFFORT TO UNDERCUT U.S. TOBACCO SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A top campaign consultant to Vice President Al Gore helped
Philip Morris Cos. develop television advertisements this spring to
undercut support for a planned federal lawsuit against the tobacco
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The consultant, Carter Eskew, said in an interview on Wednesday
that he was severing all ties with the concern that developed the
advertisements, which were tested before focus groups but have not
been produced. Eskew's resignation came after inquiries by The New
York Times this week to Philip Morris officials and Eskew about the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Eskew also helped to create a $40 million advertising blitz by
the cigarette industry last year that has been credited with
helping to defeat federal anti-tobacco legislation. He said that
his work on the latest Philip Morris project and other tobacco
industry assignments ended in July when he took a leave of absence
from Bozell/Eskew, the advertising and consulting concern that was
working on the advertisements, to join Gore's campaign as its top
media adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Roberts, a spokeswoman for Philip Morris, said the company
tested some advertisements several months ago in response to
President Clinton's announcement in his State of the Union message
in January that the government would sue cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department filed such an action last week, accusing
cigarette makers of racketeering and fraud and seeking to recover
up to $20 billion annually in health-care costs for what it
contends are illnesses linked to smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tested some ads because we are opposed to the lawsuit and
opposed to the funding of the lawsuit,'' Ms. Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the themes of the proposed advertisements was that any
government lawsuit represented ``taxation through litigation,''
said two consultants who had been briefed about the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the House and Senate have resisted an administration
effort to add $20 million to the appropriations bill for the
Justice Department to pay for the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's announcement in January, officials of Philip
Morris and the country's other big cigarette producers, including
R.J. Reynolds Tobacco and Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco, a unit of BAT
Industries PLC, met with their public relations advisers to develop
a response, said the people briefed about those meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The companies agreed on a strategy of contacting journalists,
editorial boards and politicians to promote their argument that any
government lawsuit against cigarette makers was unfounded because
the Justice Department did not have the legal basis to bring such
an action.
</P>
<P>
   But Philip Morris officials apparently wanted to take the
campaign a further step, by beginning an aggressive television
advertising campaign that might rally public and political support
against the filing of a federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roberts said the company decided not to produce the
commercials, but she declined to elaborate. The people briefed
about the campaign said officials of R.J. Reynolds and Brown &AMP;
Williamson either did not want to get involved in the campaign or
did not want to help finance it.
</P>
<P>
   An R.J. Reynolds spokeswoman said that the company did not have
any immediate comment. A spokesman for Brown &AMP; Williamson, Mark
Smith, said, ``If we did not agree to do the ads, it probably was
because of timing'' because the federal lawsuit had not been filed.
</P>
<P>
   An industry campaign designed last year by Eskew was credited
with helping cigarette makers to defeat a Senate bill to assess
hundreds of billions of dollars against the industry to sharply
drive up the price of cigarettes and reduce demand.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Salazar, a spokesman for the Gore campaign, said in a
recent interview that Eskew retained a relationship with his
concern while working for Gore but had to have all his projects
approved by the campaign and was prohibited from doing any tobacco
industry work or sharing in profits from such work.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Williams, a spokesman for BSMG Worldwide, which owns
Bozell/Eskew, said that Eskew had notified officials this week that
he had severed all ties with the company effective Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
