r s BC-FBN-NFL-COLUMN-LADN     09-30 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLTS' FIRST-ROUND PICKS IMPROVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAMIAN SECORE  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It didn't seem so long ago that the Indianapolis Colts wasted
one top-five draft pick after another, prompting self-appointed NFL
Draft expert Mel Kiper Jr. to initiate squabbles between him and
Colts management by making comments to the effect of, `and that's
why the Colts find themselves drafting in the same position every
year.'
</P>
<P>
   Like in 1990, when it drafted Jeff George No. 1 overall,
although George made it clear he never wanted to play there. Or in
1992, when they took Steve Emtman and Quentin Coryatt with the
first two picks of that draft. Or after selecting Trev Alberts
fifth overall in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four years, however, the Colts have made
outstanding first-round selections, all on offense, that has
provided the foundation for playoff hopes this year and well into
the future.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Colts selected Marvin Harrison, who leads all NFL
receivers with six touchdowns, 28 receptions and 422 yards.
</P>
<P>
   1997's first-round pick was tackle Tarik Glenn, who successfully
protects the blindside of quarterback Peyton Manning, the first
pick in the 1998 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Manning had the most prolific year of any NFL rookie quarterback
in 1998, setting rookie records in completions (326), attempts
(575), passing yards (3,739) and TD passes (26). This year, he
leads the AFC with 911 yards and 7 TD passes and his 404 yards
against San Diego Sunday broke Johnny Unitas' franchise record for
passing yards in a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts then filled its void in the backfield with Edgerrin
James, the fourth pick in this year's draft. James has two 100-yard
games and an AFC-leading 276 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short time we've played together, he's a threat on
every play and that's what you want in your running back, just like
Terrell Davis is for Denver and Jamal Anderson is for Atlanta,''
Manning said.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind Indy could have selected Ricky Williams ahead of
James at running back. Williams, with 120 yards and no TD's, has
picked up two injuries in two games. The Colts also turned out to
be the wiser in taking Manning instead of, gulp, Ryan Leaf. Enough
said there.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts have scored 86 points in three games and are one blown
second half lead against New England from being 3-0 in the NFL's
best division, the AFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were going to be a better team,'' Manning said.
``Our main goal in the offseason was to be an improved football
team and make the playoffs, which I think is a realistic goal.''
</P>
<P>
   GREEN'ER PASTURES: Although Rams coach Dick Vermeil vowed Trent
Green will still have his starting quarterback job next season when
he recovers from his preseason knee injury, what happens if Kurt
Warner continues to play like he's still lighting up the Arena
Football League? This is the dilemma Vermeil may face eventually,
but he's reaping the rewards of Warner's stellar start to the
season. Warner is a second-year Ram who began resurrecting his
football career with the Arena League's Iowa Barnstormers (1995-97)
and NFL Europe's Amsterdam Admirals in 1998. From the 8-on-8,
50-yard, indoor war to the ``big field,'' as Warner refers to it,
he's compiled 584 passing yards, six touchdowns and the second
highest QB rating in the NFC through three weeks (though the Rams
have played two games). ``I always believed that I had the ability
and I always hoped that I would get the opportunity, but I can't
say that I knew it would happen,'' Warner said. ``I had some
workouts that really went well but I think it was always that
skepticism that he had been successful, but it was in Arena
Football, it wasn't on the big field. Everybody always said that we
were always playing in a little cracker box.'' Warner, 28, recalls
his days of playing for crackers, comparatively speaking, in the
cracker box. He estimates his best Arena Football year made him
$65,000. ``I had a job in the offseason,'' he said. ``I would get a
couple of hundred dollars here and there for touchdown passes or
completion percentage or for wins and losses. It was real
incentive-based.'' Warner said his past prepared him for the NFL
much better than if he was drafted into the NFL straight away.
Particularly, he said the Arena League's offense-oriented, faster
paced game enhanced his ability to make quick reads and sound
judgments for the NFL game. ``It has given me a chance to play in a
lot of different football games, a lot of different situations and
how to react to a lot of different things,'' Warner said. ``I was
in a lot of big games in the Arena League and as offense is, you
have to score almost every time that you get the ball so you build
that mentality that no one can stop you.''
</P>
<P>
   TEAMMATES' TAKE ON GALLOWAY: Contract talks between Seattle
coach/GM Mike Holmgren and receiver Joey Galloway broke off again
last weekend, but its damage to the team and Galloway's alienation
from teammates are not as severed as they could be because Seattle
is off to a 2-1 start, which isn't quite the leverage Galloway is
looking for. ``I don't think it's affecting us,'' Seahawks
linebacker Darrin Smith said of the holdout. ``We're all just
trying to get better and win so it's hard to focus on issues we
don't have control of.'' It sure would be a shame to see Holmgren
turn this team into a winner, like he did in Green Bay, get the
Seahawks to the playoffs for the first time since 1988 and for
Galloway to miss out on it all.
</P>
<P>
   HERO OF WEEK 3: Brett Favre, Green Bay. He didn't cry like after
his comeback against the Raiders in Week 1, but his 15th
game-winning drive kept Minnesota weeping for yesteryear. Favre hit
Corey Bradford on a 23-yard, fourth-down, TD pass with 12 seconds
to lift the Packers to a 23-20 victory over the Vikings. By the
way, we're asking Oakland and Minnesota when the last time a
`prevent defense' actually lived up to its name.
</P>
<P>
   GOAT OF WEEK 3: Ki-Jana Carter, Cincinnati. Carter dislocated
his right knee cap against Carolina and was placed on injured
reserve, making it the third season-ending injury he's had in his
five NFL years. Having rushed for 747 yards in 32 career games,
compared to his 1,539 yards as a junior at Penn St., he should have
to return much of the money he's made that comes with being the No.
1 overall draft pick in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK: New York Jets (0-3) at Denver (0-3). In what
was supposed to be a high-profile game when the season started,
last year's AFC cream of the crop has been reduced to cream puffs
after losing their quarterbacks -- John Elway to retirement and
Vinny Testaverde to injury. A victory is vital for both teams for
two reasons: 1) To keep any sort of playoff hope alive. 2) To avoid
further embarrassment and get a victory before the Browns do.
Broncos 17, Jets 13
</P>
<P>
   UPSET OF THE WEEK: Oakland (plus 3 1/2) over Seattle. Nobody's
more upset over Joey Galloway's holdout than the Raiders' Charles
Woodson, who's quickly building his resume as one of the best
cover-corners in the game. Already boasting one of the better
defenses in the NFL, the Raiders' offense is holding up its end
with mistake-free quarterback play from Rich Gannon and a
revitalized Tyrone Wheatley. Raiders 24, Seahawks 16
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
