<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CHICAGO-COWS-ART-NYT &LR;      09-30 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-COWS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A CITY WITH CATTLE IN ITS PAST, THE COWS HAVE COME HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Now he had seen it all. The exasperated Chicago police
sergeant called to alert the authorities at city hall. Get this, he
told them: A fiberglass cow is standing in the middle of Michigan
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Relax, the sergeant was told, the cow is cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cows on Parade,'' a whimsical display of 300 painted and
decorated cows, has created an astonishing buzz. Sidewalk traffic
is jammed with people posing for pictures with the creatures.
Tourism has soared. Art careers have taken off.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Mayor Richard M. Daley's cultural affairs
department, the public art display is the latest example of how
artifice has replaced edifice as a tool of leaders of great urban
centers. In the days of the mayor's father, Richard J. Daley, when
federal money was plentiful for public works projects, Chicago
piled bricks and mortar to the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, the mayor promotes rose gardens and antique street
lamps and wrought-iron fences, esthetic touches that appeal in a
city where the lunch-bucket populace has largely given way to the
gourmet coffee set. But the stunning success of the objets de cow
also reveals the eagerness of ordinary people to appreciate art.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when New York taxpayers are debating whether to stop
financing a museum for a display that is, depending on the point of
view, provocative or disgusting _ it includes a portrait of the
Blessed Virgin stained with elephant dung _ Chicagoans, including
some who have not haunted a museum in a while, are being reminded
how art can make them smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``People seem alienated by the arts these days,'' said Donald
Stahlke, a Chicago artist whose tattooed cow, Taurus, stands in
front of the Wrigley Building here. ``If it is going to survive,
art is going to have to open up the market a little bit, get out of
the galleries, reach average people.''
</P>
<P>
   Stahlke said the cow exhibit has tickled the artistic
sensibilities of people like his parents, a retired factory worker
and a homemaker, who recently came to Chicago to view the painted
cattle and genuinely enjoyed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   High-brow art does pretty well here, too. The Art Institute
houses one of the nation's finest collections of French
Impressionist paintings, and people have flocked to shows of the
works of Monet, Renoir and Degas. But over the last few weeks,
Chicagoans have been hustling past these famous works to gaze, and
chuckle, at the cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fascinating to see how different artists started at the
same point, and did things so differently,'' said Lyda Haas, 68, a
retired medical assistant, as she admired some cows near the
Tribune Tower. ``They say there's one with high heels. That's the
one I want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Edfors, 52, a lawyer accustomed to taking a brisk,
no-nonsense walk to the office, has lately been stopping to spend a
moment with the painted cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I was skeptical,'' said Edfors on a glorious
September morning. ``I just thought this was silly and a waste of
money. But you know, Michigan Avenue has become livelier. People
are having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Cattle have a storied place in Chicago history. Mrs. O'Leary's
cow was blamed for the fire of 1871, although historians have since
vindicated her. The stockyards on the South Side, now defunct,
achieved literary fame, however unappetizing, when Upton Sinclair
wrote ``The Jungle'' in 1906. And for most of the '90s, the
basketball Bulls stampeded to a string of championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago art exhibition, which was modeled after one in
Zurich last year, features a herd bought by art benefactors and
corporations, who hired local artists to turn the bare, fiberglass
beasts into artwork.
</P>
<P>
   After the exhibition, they will be sold at a Sotheby's auction
at the Chicago Theater on Nov. 9. Tickets, priced at $25, are
expected to go fast.
</P>
<P>
   While the cows have generally been treated with respect _
indeed, sometimes with reverence _ there has been some vandalism.
In a few cases, people pulled off cow parts for souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were prepared,'' said Heidi Kooi, a spokeswoman for the
tourism office. ``We had ordered extra ears and horns.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials here estimate that the cow show, which runs
through Oct. 31, has brought an additional $100 million to $200
million in spending in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole phenomenon has some rural visitors to Chicago
scratching their heads in wonderment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can somebody tell me what's going on here with all these
cows?'' asked Larry Harris, 48, a tourist from Chatham, Va., who
works for a dairy farm in rural Virginia. He said he had come to
Chicago to see the bright lights and tall buildings, adding that at
home, he sees cows all day long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come all the way to downtown Chicago,'' he said with a groan
that turned into a belly laugh, ``and what do I see but cows.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
