<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAJOR STOCK GAUGES FINISH 3D QUARTER ON POSITIVE NOTE
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended the third quarter on a positive note, as a rally in
the bond market helped to push major market indexes higher. They
also benefited as mutual fund managers bought shares of companies
that have done well to make end-of-quarter reports look better to
their investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average finished the quarter at
10,336.95, after rising 123.47 points, or 1.21 percent. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index increased by 14.34 points, to
1,282.71, and the Nasdaq composite index jumped 15.89 points, to
2,746.16.
</P>
<P>
   Underwriting by investment banks slowed in the third quarter.
Securities firms and banks issued $473 billion of stocks and bonds,
a 3.5 percent increase from $456.8 billion in the third quarter of
1998, but a marked decline from the first two quarters of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL'S TAX INCREASES STRUCK DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's highest court invalidated two tax increases in surprise
rulings that could hurt the Government's efforts to narrow the
budget deficit. The rulings sent the stock market tumbling nearly 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH INSURERS' STOCKS FALL
</P>
<P>
   Shares of major health insurers, including Aetna, which was down
$10.4375, to $49.25, decline amid reports that trial lawyers were
preparing lawsuits on behalf of managed care patients. Lawyers who
gained high profiles in tobacco litigation and other cases are
preparing to sue managed-care companies and seek class-action
status after some large legal judgments against the insurers.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCETON ECONOMICS HEAD INDICTED
</P>
<P>
   Martin Armstrong, the investment adviser who was chairman of
Princeton Economics International, was indicted by a federal grand
jury on charges that he defrauded foreign investors in connection
with the sale of $3 billion in securities issued by Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS BUREAU UPBEAT ON WAGES
</P>
<P>
   Rising incomes, lifted by a strong economy, brought 1.1 million
poor Americans out of poverty last year. The Census Bureau said the
typical American household finally regained in 1998 the income it
had lost since 1989 to recession, wage freezes, downsizing and the
competition of foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI CHIEF DEFENDS REALIGNMENT
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Colaninno, the chief executive of Olivetti, will meet
with institutional investors next week in an effort to halt a
flight of investment capital from the Italian telecommunications
giant. The market damage has been caused by his decision to strip
Telecom Italia of its most-valued asset, its cellular phone unit,
Telecom Italia Mobile, and transfer it to Tecnost, the subsidiary
he used to win control of Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE BANK IN JAPANESE VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank teamed up with Sakura Bank of Japan in an effort
to take advantage of Japan's liberalized market for underwriting
bond and stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURE OF EXCITE(AT)HOME UNCLEAR
</P>
<P>
   The future of Excite(AT)Home is unclear after the company
canceled a meeting to vote on separating its cable modem venture
from its Internet portal service.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. MORGAN SETTLES KOREAN SUIT
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan agreed to take a 10 percent stake in SK Securities,
a South Korean brokerage house, settling a $380 million lawsuit and
ending a dispute with several Korean institutions over losses in
derivative securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
