<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAZIANO DESERVED THE AXE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The revelation that Bob Graziano was fired as president by the
Los Angeles Dodgers the other day wasn't nearly as surprising to me
as the revelation that Bob Graziano was hired as president by the
Dodgers in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Peter O'Malley is the culprit who committed that particular
felony, much to the distress of the more deserving Fred Claire, who
should have been given the job.
</P>
<P>
   I never rejoice in a person getting fired, but if ever a person
deserved such a fate, it was Mr. Graziano.
</P>
<P>
   The guy was a bean counter who somehow manipulated his way into
a position for which his only qualifications were a pleasing smile,
a friendly personality and a God-given ability to toady up to Peter
O'Malley and then to Fox executives Chase Carey and Peter Chernin.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano had no background in baseball, and originally was hired
by the Dodgers to oversee their financial affairs, quite befitting
a USC graduate with a degree in accounting who once worked for
Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   He was nothing more than a figurehead with the Dodgers, yet took
public responsibility for the trading of Mike Piazza and sacking of
Claire and Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodger franchise deteriorated into a chaotic, formless mess
under Graziano's watch, and his detachment is one of the few
positive moves Fox has made since buying the team from O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea what role, if any, Graziano played in hiring the
Dodgers' clownish general manager, Kevin Malone, or in all the
other moves that have turned a once proud franchise into one of the
laughingstocks of professional athletics.
</P>
<P>
   But I do know Graziano was quite willing to take credit for the
ceaseless stream of shenanigans, which the principled Claire
refused to do when the meddling Carey decided it would be a
brilliant idea to teach Mike Piazza a cruel lesson and dispatch him
to the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Claire would wind up getting fired for such insubordination, and
was widely applauded for it.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure Claire isn't shedding a tear over Graziano's
plight, and neither is anyone else with passionate feelings about
the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano was the quintessential example of the Peter Principle
an organization's employee advancing to his highest level of
incompetence and I'm sure he'll now go back doing what he does best
in the private sector, auditing accounts, upgrading computerized
ticket systems and catering shamelessly to those giving him orders.
...
</P>
<P>
   Taking into consideration the wacky way the Dodgers have
conducted business since Rupert Murdoch assumed control, I've come
up with two separate categories for Graziano's successor, SC
(serious candidate) and GC (goofy candidate).
</P>
<P>
   Here are my selections:
</P>
<P>
   (SC) Dennis Gilbert A former high-profile player agent (Barry
Bonds, Jose Canseco, Bret Saberhagen, Mike Piazza, etc.), Gilbert
understands the inner workings of baseball, having even played in
the minors himself. Well-respected by all factions of the sport.
Smart, shrewd and perceptive. Might have too many impressive
credentials for paranoid Fox execs.
</P>
<P>
   (GC) Marvin Davis Why not? The billionaire's name is linked to
every athletic business transaction in America, so why shouldn't he
be linked with a major athletic job opening?
</P>
<P>
   (SC) Fred Claire Who's more qualified than Claire, who spent 30
years with the Dodgers working in all aspects of the organization?
He has a keen awareness of hallowed Dodger traditions that have
been swept under the rug by Fox.
</P>
<P>
   (GC) Donald Sterling If the Dodgers are doing it for laughs and
all their moves in recent years indicate that they are then who
better to dispense histrionics than the zany owner of the Los
Angeles Clippers?
</P>
<P>
   (SC) Barry Kemp Unparalleled patience, as evidenced by the $10
million he's blown since 1996 during his ownership of the Long
Beach Ice Dogs and the fact that he agreed with the city to keep
his team here two more years so he can blow another $6 million. The
guy also knows how to field winning teams, as evidenced by the Ice
Dogs' success on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   (GC) Chris Rock Please, don't snicker. At least he's funnier
than Kevin Malone, whose comedic antics I believe are quite
unwitting.
</P>
<P>
   (SC) Beverly O'Neill Mayor Bev has played a vital role in the
revival of Long Beach. I'm sure she can perform similar managerial
magic with the Dodgers if only given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   (GC) Elgin Baylor One of the nicest guys I've known in sports,
and Fox would be doing a laudable public gesture by freeing him
from the oppressive shackles of Sterling. Doesn't know much about
baseball some claim he doesn't know much about basketball, either
but that should be irrelevant. I'm not sure that Bob Graziano even
knew the difference between a ball and strike. ...
</P>
<P>
   First, the Lakers sign A.C. Green, now Benoit Benjamin and John
Salley. Who next, Milton Berle?. ...
</P>
<P>
   So Billy Crystal pays more than $200,000 for a Mickey Mantle
mitt not worth more than $20,000. I never figured Crystal for being
as lousy a businessman as he is a comedian. ...
</P>
<P>
   It's been a sad week on the docks with the passing of one of the
most popular longshoreman, Dave Main, a San Pedro High graduate who
was a junior college All American lineman at Compton College in
1955. ``One of the toughest and nicest guys I've ever known,'' says
Ray Ortiz, who was a longtime friend and Downey neighbor of Main.
...
</P>
<P>
   Paul Tagliabue is doing everything within his power to hand over
an expansion franchise to L.A., but I'm still cynical about the
willingness of Michael Ovitz and his supermarket billionaire pal,
Ron Burkle, to put up their own money, which the NFL ultimately
will demand. ...
</P>
<P>
   The NFL officials assess too many unnecessary penalties, blow
too many calls and decide too many games. And this is a recording
that will be recited at least 15 more times in this column during
the fall and winter months. ...
</P>
<P>
   The more people I talk to, the more disgusted I get with Oscar
De La Hoya's performance against Felix Trinidad. There are a few
yokels not on Bob Arum's payroll who still are hopelessly blinded
by De La Hoya's well-marketed luster and worshipfully stick up for
their idol. But those whose brains actually have made it to their
heads and understand the nuances and subtleties of boxing are quite
unforgiving in their assessment of De La Hoya's $24 million public
fleecing. ...
</P>
<P>
   A fighter who does what he is paid to do in a ring he fights
Julio Cesar Chavez will be featured on Showtime Saturday night on
Showtime when he faces Willy (cq)
</P>
<P>
   Wise at the Las Vegas Hilton. Also on the card will be Richard
Lopez, who usually fights at 105 but has beefed all the way up to
108 for his match against Will Grigsby. Incidentally, I hear Chavez
has been savagely demeaning De La Hoya in Spanish television
interviews. ...
</P>
<P>
   Swimming great Susie Atwood reports that the second annual Long
Beach/C.A.R.E. Triathlon and Fitness Expo will be held on Oct. 16
between 10 a.m. and 5 p.m. at the JAX Bicycle Center in Long Beach.
A triathlon will be staged the next day, starting in front of the
Belmont Olympic Pool. Atwood's constant companion, the athletically
gifted, physically imposing, culturally enhancing Dave Butler, is
expected to participate in an event from which the proceeds will go
to the C.A.R.E. program. ...
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the perfect Dodger president would be my old radio
partner, Joe (The Big Nasty) McDonnell, consigned to eternal
obscurity these days doing afternoon quarterly hour updates on
KFWB, but still a feared journalist who broke a blockbuster this
week about two Dodger minor league coordinators allegedly becoming
``increasingly verbally abusive with young players.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers need a guy to clean house and make all the deft
moves, it would be ol' Joe, who always knows what's best for L.A.'s
sport teams that, at this desperate time, are badly in need of his
unique services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
