<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S EFFORTS ON BUDGET IMPERILED BY COURT RULINGS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  SAO PAULO, Brazil _ The country's highest court invalidated
two important tax increases Thursday in surprise rulings that could
hurt the government's efforts to narrow the budget deficit. The
rulings unnerved investors and stocks tumbled nearly 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The tax increases _ on the salaries and pensions of public
employees _ were challenged by civil servants, and the Supreme
Federal Tribunal sided with them in both cases.
</P>
<P>
   The court unanimously upheld a lower court's ruling that one
tax, which varies from 11 percent to 25 percent for Brazil's
694,000 retired civil servants depending on the size of their
pensions, was illegal. A second ruling found that increased taxes
on the salaries of 712,000 acting government workers were
unconstitutional. Many more civil servants on the state and
municipal levels are affected by the rulings.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions are a blow to President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso's efforts to exert more fiscal discipline in Latin
America's largest economy, which has struggled to recover from a
currency crisis in January that led to a rescue package by the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso's administration has been trying to narrow a gaping
budget deficit that corresponds to 12 percent of the nation's gross
domestic product. Pension spending, payroll outlays and interest
payments on government bonds are the main reasons for the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that one branch of the government is more concerned
with preserving the privileges of the civil service as it sees fit
rather than ensuring the long-term health of the economy,'' said
Marcelo Allain, the chief economist at Banco Inter American
Express.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimated the decision would cost the government 3.1
billion reais, or $1.6 billion, in lost taxes next year.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks here plunged after the rulings, with the Bovespa index
for the Sao Paulo stock exchange ending down 2.9 percent. The
Brazilian real weakened nearly 1 percent to a one-month low of
1.935 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me wonder about Brazil's ability to get serious,''
said Masaru Nakayasu, an economist here with Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
