<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FETAL-MURDER-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LED BY REPUBLICANS, HOUSE APPROVES BILL GIVING THE FETUS LEGAL
PROTECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite a veto threat from President Clinton, the
House of Representatives passed a bill Thursday that would grant a
measure of legal protection to the human fetus by establishing new
criminal penalties for anyone who injures or harms the fetus while
committing another federal offense.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill, mainly Republicans, said it would
protect ``unborn children'' against assaults and other acts of
violence. Opponents said it would undermine abortion rights by
granting legal status to the fetus at all stages of development.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was approved, 254-172, with support from 198
Republicans and 56 Democrats. The measure was opposed by 150
Democrats, 21 Republicans and 1 independent.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill passed Thursday night, a person who injures or
kills a fetus in the course of committing any of 68 enumerated
federal crimes could be convicted of a separate offense against the
fetus.
</P>
<P>
   The penalties would be the same as the punishment that could
have been imposed if the pregnant woman herself had suffered the
injury inflicted on her fetus.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a person who assaults a pregnant woman on a
military base could be prosecuted under the bill for murder or
manslaughter if the fetus died but the woman survived. By contrast
if the assault on the pregnant women occurred in a department
store, it would probably not be a federal crime, and the injury to
the fetus would not be covered by the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, federal homicide statutes reach only the killing of a
human being _ a person who has been born.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas D. Johnson, chief lobbyist for the National Right to
Life Committee, said the bill would establish an important
principle: ``when a criminal attacks a pregnant woman, injuring or
killing her and injuring or killing her unborn child, he has
claimed two victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats agreed that it might be appropriate to increase the
punishment for violence against pregnant women. But they said they
did not want to recognize the fetus as a separate person, a crime
victim with rights distinct from those of the pregnant woman.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers Jr. of Michigan, the senior Democrat on the
Judiciary Committee, said, ``The Supreme Court has never recognized
an unborn child as having legal status.''
</P>
<P>
   Conyers denounced the bill as ``a back-door attack on Roe vs.
Wade,'' the 1973 decision in which the court defined abortion
rights.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The bill evoked passions similar to those seen in prior
congressional debates over legislation to ban the medical procedure
that critics call a partial-birth abortion. The meaning of that
legislation was not immediately evident, but emerged only after
more than a year of analysis and debate by lawyers, doctors and
lobbyists for and against abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed by the House Thursday is known as the Unborn
Victims of Violence Act. It was drafted by Rep. Lindsey Graham of
South Carolina, Christopher Smith of New Jersey and Charles Canady
of Florida, all Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Mike DeWine of Ohio and Tim Hutchinson of
Arkansas, both Republicans, are pushing similar legislation.
``Unfortunately,'' Hutchinson said, ``there are instances where an
unborn child is intentionally assaulted or even murdered to prevent
its birth.''
</P>
<P>
   But the White House said that it strongly opposed the bill and
that the president's senior advisers would recommend a veto if the
measure reached his desk. To identify the fetus as a separate and
distinct victim of crime is ``unprecedented as a matter of federal
statute,'' the White House said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the House bill, an assailant could be prosecuted for
injuring or killing a fetus regardless of whether he knew that the
woman was pregnant. Prosecutors would not have to show that the
defendant intended to cause the death or injury of the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   The bill protects the ``unborn child,'' defined as ``a member of
the species Homo sapiens, at any stage of development, who is
carried in the womb.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the bill would not allow prosecution of doctors for
performing an abortion at the request of a pregnant woman. Nor
would it allow prosecution of ``any woman with respect to her
unborn child,'' or of any person providing medical treatment for
the woman or the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who leads the opposition to abortion,
said the bill ``fills a gap in our criminal law.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Armey of Texas, the House Republican floor leader, asked,
``How can you recognize the need for prenatal care and reject the
baby's right to protection from violence?''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., said the bill was just a back-door
way to ``establish the legal status of the fetus as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative to the Republican bill, Democrats offered a
proposal to increase the criminal penalties for certain acts of
violence against pregnant women. The Democratic bill focused on
harm to the woman, not the fetus. It was rejected by a vote of
224-201.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
