<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-F2201-COX     09-30 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-F2201-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    F-22's funding back in budget
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After weeks of contentious debate, a deal has been
reached between House and Senate negotiators over how much to spend
on the controversial F-22 fighter jet program.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal that could be unveiled as early as today,
Congress would spend an additional $1.3 billion on the stealth
fighter built by Lockheed Martin Corp. at its Marietta, Ga.,
facility.
</P>
<P>
   The funds would be in addition to $1.2 billion that has already
won approval, bringing the program's total funding to $2.6 billion.
That is about $400 million shy of what was originally requested by
the Air Force and approved by the Senate during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The F-22 won,'' said Sen. Paul Coverdell (R-Ga.). ``We've come
a long way from where we started.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell, Sen. Max Cleland (D-Ga.) and the entire Georgia
congressional delegation fought a battle to secure the additional
funding against Rep. Jerry Lewis (R-Calif.), chairman of the House
Defense Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis successfully waged a campaign to eliminate $1.85 billion
from the House version of the spending bill, saying the $70 billion
F-22 fighter program was too costly and untested. He urged a
``pause'' in the production of the plane to bring it in line with
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes a concession to Lewis that the funding used to
purchase the planes would not set in motion the production cycle.
Instead, the money would be pooled from research and development
funds for testing the plane.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives the Air Force $723 million in research and
development funds to buy up to six test planes. An additional $277
million would be set aside for advanced purchase orders to start
buying the first lot of 10 planes in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Another $300 million would be added to cover liability costs
associated with contract termination for subcontractors. Coverdell
said if that money is not used it can be used to purchase
additional aircraft. Members of the Georgia delegation were
relieved to find out the radar-evading fighter jet program had been
saved from the most serious threat in the program's 15-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like the Senate position basically prevailed,''
Cleland said. ``The bottom line: The Senate saved the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), whose district includes part of Marietta,
credited ``a massive team effort between the management and workers
at Lockheed, the Clinton administration and the Joint Chiefs of
Staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
