r s BC-FBC-AZUSA-LADN     09-30 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AZUSA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AZUSA PACIFIC'S JORDAN'S LATEST STOP IS A GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to forget last week's game has to be a little difficult
for Azusa Pacific's Deon Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   What is there to remember, you ask, about Jordan's performance
in a 59-52 marathon victory at the University of Redlands?
</P>
<P>
   How about a school-record 419 all-purpose yards, scoring
receptions of 94, 10 and 45 yards, an 80-yard punt return for a
touchdown and the game-winning 97-yard kickoff return for a score.
All of which added up to his selection as the NAIA Player of the
Week for his efforts in helping his team overcome deficits of 24-0,
31-7 and 38-13.
</P>
<P>
   But his first step in preparing for the team's next game which
is Saturday against visiting Western Oregon is forgetting about
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to start over,'' said the 23-year-old Jordan High
graduate. ``It was a good game and we got the victory. Now I want
to wipe the slate clean. It would be extremely difficult for me to
go out and duplicate that game.''
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, it would be equally difficult for the Panthers,
who are ranked No. 5 in the nation, to duplicate a game during
which they were in a 24-0 hole before 13 minutes were elapsed on
the clock. After the teams traded touchdowns, Jordan hooked up with
former Poly and LBCC quarterback Neo Aoga on a 94-yard scoring play
that was promptly answered by a Redlands touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan ended the first half with his 10-yard touchdown reception
and grabbed a scoring pass from 45 yards on the first drive of the
second half. His 80-yard punt return early in the fourth quarter
gave the Panthers their first lead of the evening and the kickoff
return lit up the scoreboard for the final time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extra conditioning after practice paid off,'' Jordan said.
``If this had been the first game of the season, I don't think I
would have been out there for those final two touchdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other NAIA players, Jordan didn't exactly take a
straight path to his school. After graduating from Jordan High in
1993, his stops have included Cerritos College, Compton College,
Long Beach City College, Hampton (Va.) University and Kutztown
(Pa.) State. But the only places he actually played in a game were
at Compton and Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   His journey and you may need a road map to follow began at
Cerritos College, where he enrolled as a full-time student and
joined the football team. After not seeing any game action, Jordan
decided to quit football. In 1996, he joined the team at Compton
College.
</P>
<P>
   ``It left a sour taste in my mouth when I was at Cerritos,''
Jordan said. ``I didn't want my football career to end like that.''
</P>
<P>
   His Compton College experience ended after one season when the
football program was shut down and it was back to the sidelines for
Jordan. He moved to LBCC in 1997 and helped the Vikings finish 9-2.
</P>
<P>
   The next stop was at Hampton, where Jordan quickly won a
starting position at receiver and kick returner. He traveled with
the team to its opener against Florida A&AMP;M and was sleeping snugly
in his hotel room on the eve of the game when the phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was (a Hampton coach) telling me that the NCAA was
questioning my eligibility,'' said Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that, according to NCAA regulations, a player
has five years to complete four seasons and Jordan's NCAA clock had
begun when he became a full-time student at Cerritos College in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I waited for four weeks to see if something would change and
then came home,'' said Jordan, who was eligible to play two more
seasons at a NAIA program.
</P>
<P>
   Once again he was out of football. A coach at Hampton helped him
hook on at Kutztown State so he packed his bags and headed for
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money situation wasn't right (at Kutztown),'' said Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   About the time he figured that out, Jordan received a phone call
from former LBCC teammate Jack Williams, who was the NAIA Player of
the Year while leading Azusa Pacific to the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked me if I was interested in coming home to play and I
jumped,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan showed up in Azusa three days into fall practice, but
quickly made an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just gave me a brief overlook at the playbook,'' Jordan
said. ``But most of the time I was just ad-libbing. I was worried
about getting on the field because they had set guys when I got
here.''
</P>
<P>
   None of them, however, have produced like Jordan. Despite having
trouble with conditioning in the first couple of weeks, Jordan is
leading the team in receptions (23 for 474 yards), all-purpose
yards (223.75 per game), scoring (10.5 per game), kickoff returns
(12 for 338) and punt returns (3 for 83).
</P>
<P>
   ``The (best) thing is I didn't want to be finished with
football,'' said Jordan. ``All I wanted was some place to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
