<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UGA-RACE01-COX     09-30 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-RACE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA affirms race in admissions
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Calling ``the twin goals of academic excellence
and a diverse student population ... absolutely compatible,''
University of Georgia President Michael Adams said Thursday that
race should remain a factor in evaluating some high school seniors
applying for admission to UGA.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement brought widespread expressions of support from
key state politicians, a dire prediction from the state attorney
general and a threat from the lawyer who challenged the standards
that he would seek an injunction to halt the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The University of Georgia wants to be fair, it wants to be
accessible, it wants to be representative of the total population
of the state,'' Adams told the University Council. UGA ``still must
achieve our goal to have an admissions system that is fair,
appropriate and legal. We believe that using race as a factor in
admissions, but not a sole determining factor, is a legitimate
approach in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   The university's admissions policy admits most students on the
basis of SAT scores and grade point average, and uses race among
numerous other factors in evaluating an estimated 10 percent to 20
percent of applicants not admitted strictly on the basis of their
scores and grades.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the policy for culling next fall's freshman class
will offer admission to the valedictorian and the salutatorian from
the 369 high school programs in Georgia accredited by the Southern
Association of Colleges and Schools. Such a provision has been
effective in increasing minority recruitment at other state
universities, said UGA Communications Director Tom Jackson, and
Adams felt it was appropriate for Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Although the policy will have to be ratified by the Faculty
Admissions Committee and the University Council, Adams, who has the
final say, effectively has committed the university to a costly,
perhaps protracted, legal battle. Some legal experts _ including
Attorney General Thurbert Baker _ predict the university has little
chance of winning that fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``While its chances of prevailing are slim, the university is
entitled to have its attorneys present its case in court,'' said
Baker, whose office would represent UGA.
</P>
<P>
   The school's admissions policies have been challenged in court
by several applicants who were denied admission on what they
contend are discriminatory grounds.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge B. Avant Edenfield chastised UGA in
July for using race as a factor in admissions, saying the
university couldn't constitutionally justify its use.
</P>
<P>
   For a relatively small percentage of applicants, admissions
officials employ the Total Student Index. The index is a list of
factors _ academic, demographic, leadership/activity, legacy and
family educational level.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning of Adams' decision on Thursday, Atlanta attorney
Lee Parks said in a letter to the attorney general's office that
the policy won't hold up in court. Parks said he has 16 white
females, all of whom were rejected by UGA, who want to join a suit
he filed in August against the admissions policies.
</P>
<P>
   Parks plans to file a motion next week seeking a temporary
injunction to halt UGA's employing its current admissions policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look back on this once promising window of opportunity
for settlement and compromise, and regret that it was slammed shut
without any effort at all to look for middle ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued after Adams made his announcement, he said
that, given the current legal trend regarding such matters, the
university's case will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gov. Roy Barnes and University System Chancellor Stephen
Portch declared support for Adams' decision, as did other political
leaders, including State Rep. Calvin Smyre (D-Columbus), chairman
of the University System of Georgia Committee, Senate Minority
Leader Eric Johnson (R-Savannah) and House Majority Leader Larry
Walker (D-Perry).
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over affirmative action and race-based policies
_ including the lawsuits against UGA and threats against the city
of Atlanta's affirmative action programs _ is likely to reignite
debate in the Legislature over such issues, Walker said. When Adams
finished his 20-minute talk, the audience in the law school
auditorium _ which had faculty, staff and students standing in the
back aisles _ burst into applause and rose to give him a standing
ovation, something rarely if ever seen in a University Council
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he came to the decision after months of talking to
faculty members, administrators, alumni and educational and
political leaders from across the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's best for the university,'' Adams said. ``This
is almost a matter of my wanting to treat others as I'd like to be
treated.''
</P>
<P>
   The reaction from some African-American students was that the
policy was good, but that more would be needed to increase
enrollment of minority members. This year, 597 black students were
accepted, but only 243 enrolled, a trend that began years ago.
Building a diverse student body is complicated and difficult,
students acknowledged. Sophomores Candice Bullett and Jamila
Tillman, graduates of Stone Mountain's Redan High, faulted UGA for
what they perceive as inadequate recruitment efforts. Bullett said
school officials came to DeKalb County to recruit black quarterback
Quincy Carter, but not black scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of kids recruited in my high school had parents
who were alums of UGA, and those kids heard the horror stories of
what it was like when their parents went here,'' said Tillman,
whose mother graduated from UGA in 1976. ``I heard a few stories,
but I came because of HOPE and because it is a great school,
especially for my major, public relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Kathey Pruitt, Bill Rankin and Plott Brice
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
