<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDLESTICK CLOSES WITH DODGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Eric Karros unzipped his backpack, ruffled
through some clothes and pulled out a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Karros doesn't get terribly sentimental about much, including
the closing of this Candlestick/3Com Park, but he understands
baseball history, so he held on to the last ball used here.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of day.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem sickening to Giants fans, but after 40 years of
baseball, Candlestick's finale was a Los Angeles Dodgers-dominated
9-4 win in front of a regular-season record 61,389 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And Karros, not the Giants, has the ball from the final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably (end up) in my closet somewhere, in a shoe
box,'' Karros said. ``There will be some ball out there that they
say, `Hey, this is the ball.' No. Wrong. That's the last put-out at
Candlestick. Not that it will change my career or anything, but I
was there when it closed.''
</P>
<P>
   It closed with the Dodgers pounding the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   With a rookie Aussie named Jeff Williams (2-0) striking out
Barry Bonds with the bases loaded en route to his second
major-league win.
</P>
<P>
   With Raul Mondesi hitting the last home run, a three-run shot
that was also the 1,000th hit of his career. Despite a splendid
three-day stretch of weather, with the wind finally stirring four
decades worth of ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind started kickin' up at the end and I said, `Now, this
is Candlestick,' '' said Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw, who threw the
last pitch. ``A lot of people think because they're moving to a new
ballpark it's going to change, but it's still going to be windy,
it's still going to be cold.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers and Giants waged some classic confrontations since
the park opened, but this wasn't one of them. The drama was created
by the knowledge this would be the last game played.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike past years when one team strived to ruin the other's
season, the excitement was generated from the soldout crowd who
understood the purpose this game will have in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was an awesome day,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said.
``A lot of people, a lot of excitement. We didn't end it like we
wanted to ... especially the way L.A. beat us, but it's over now.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgotten, at least for the day, was the cold, the wind and the
flying dust and trash that sometimes engulfed the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see some guys saving some dirt,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``Maybe the dirt will last longer than grass. There's
nothing I want here. I left my share of blood in this ballpark. I
remember standing at home plate and my eyes watering, so I kept
(blinking) so I could see the ball. And I know I didn't want to hit
it on the end of the bat, or get jammed.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Mondesi who broke the game open with his homer in the
sixth, a line drive over the left-field fence that gave the Dodgers
an 8-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was Williams' fifth-inning performance that provided the
moment of the day. The Giants already had a run in and the bases
were loaded with one out and Bonds batting. After getting behind on
a pair of called strikes, Bonds worked the count full before
Williams snapped off a breaking pitch for a called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans made it special, with the history that's gone on
here,'' Johnson said. ``It was a special day, and it was nice to
see a young pitcher come up and do something.''
</P>
<P>
   They said farewell to Candlestick Park with hoopla, trotting out
past greats who called this home. They celebrated the stadium's 40
years, and they celebrated for not having to play here again.
</P>
<P>
   But the indelible image of the last play will be Shaw getting
Marvin Benard to ground out to first base. And of Karros, scooping
the ball, stepping on first, and then riding out of town with the
most cherished souvenir of the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
