<SLUG> BC-NIEMAN-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 3RD JOURNALISM PROGRAM LOSES ITS DIRECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Kovach, the curator of the Nieman Foundation for Journalism
at Harvard University, submitted his resignation to the
foundation's advisory board this week, becoming the third head of a
major university-based program for journalists to resign in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations of Kovach, of James V. Risser, the director of
the John S. Knight Fellowships at Stanford University, and of
Marvin Kalb, the head of the Shorenstein Center for Press, Politics
and Public Policy at the Kennedy School of government at Harvard,
leave vacant three of the most prominent pulpits in the profession
at a time of growing concern about the future of journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Kovach, who is 67, said Thursday that he thought it was time for
the program to be led by someone who was closer to the
technological revolution sweeping the profession because of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new technology, the impact of the new technology and the
changes it's making both in journalism and the economic
organization of the business of news,'' Kovach said, is of such
significance that ``I think that someone in closer touch, or with a
better sense of the impact inside a news organization, might be
better equipped for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Risser, who is 61 and who, like Kovach, will leave next summer
at the end of the academic year, said that the changes in the
profession must be emphasized in programs like his and Kovach's.
Both programs bring in journalists in midcareer for a year's
intensive study of a subject of the journalist's choosing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
