<HEADER>
A2806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY-N     09-30 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD PAYOUT IN BRUTALITY CASES AGAINST NEW YORK CITY POLICE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City paid out a record $40 million in the
last fiscal year to resolve legal claims and lawsuits that accused
its police officers of brutality, up 40 percent from the prior
year, according to an analysis by the comptroller's office.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said the increase was not a measure of more
misconduct being committed by officers. Rather, they said
settlements for the fiscal year that ended June 30 had been driven
up by a combination of factors, including a sharp rise in the
number of cases resolved and a spate of publicity about police
misconduct that made it difficult for the city to negotiate from
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a climate where there is so much publicity about police
cases, we are more reluctant to take cases to juries,'' said Lorna
Bade Goodman, a senior attorney with the city's Law Department.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the amount paid out in settlements rise in the last
fiscal year, but the number of new brutality claims seeking damages
from the city increased by 10 percent, to 2,324, the highest number
in a decade, according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Police Department contend that the surge in
claims activity is evidence of widening public dissatisfaction with
a law enforcement agency whose use of force is already the subject
of a federal investigation. Indeed, the number of new brutality
cases filed last year far outpaced the general trend of legal
claims overall against the city, which rose by less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The swelling settlement figure for police brutality cases
nevertheless did reflect an overall increase in the amount the city
paid to resolve lawsuits and other legal claims last year. The city
paid a record $405 million to resolve such cases, the majority of
them personal injury claims stemming from accidents like sidewalk
slips and incidents of medical malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said the tally for resolving brutality cases had
grown so sharply because the number of cases settled, 739, had
increased by 30 percent last year. The $40 million was paid out
both in cases that were settled through negotiations before trial
as well as those that ended with a court judgment.
</P>
<P>
   City lawyers said more cases were resolved because of a new
early settlement policy that the city expected would save money
over the long term by quickly negotiating legal claims as they come
in and before they become mired in court delays. The new policy was
among the recommendations made by an accounting firm,
PricewaterhouseCoopers, which studied the city's claims processing
procedures last year.
</P>
<P>
   A second factor in the higher claim costs, city officials said,
was that several large brutality cases had been settled in a single
year. For example, the family of Anthony Baez, who was choked to
death by a Bronx police officer in 1994, received $2.55 million
this year in one settlement, according to the comptroller's office.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, the city agreed to pay $2.75 million to an
electrician who said that, while walking to work in Greenwich
Village on his birthday in 1996, he was beaten by police officers
because he fit the profile of a black suspect they were seeking.
The department has described the incident as a tragic mistake, not
an act of brutality, but never disciplined the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goodman, speaking generally, said there were many cases in
which the city paid damages even though it did not believe the
officers were guilty of wrongdoing. ``In cases where there is a
sympathetic plaintiff with a bad injury,'' she said, ``we will
often settle, regardless of whether it was caused by the officer,
because we don't want to go to the jury and risk a large award.''
</P>
<P>
   George A. Grasso, the Police Department's deputy commissioner
for legal matters, said that many of the cases settled this year
were several years old _ too old, he maintained, to be of any value
in measuring the level of police misconduct now.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, said that the increase in new brutality claims
filed last year was evidence that a penchant for brutality
continues among too many police officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0467 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-MUSEUM-COLLECTIONS     09-30 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-COLLECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVATE COLLECTIONS ROUTINE AT MUSEUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Wash.)  (With NY-MUSEUM-OPENING, SENSATIONS-REVIEW) 
(mk) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brooklyn Museum of Art's particular mix of art
and commerce _ an exhibition of art that is owned by one private
collector and partially financed by an auction house _ may not pass
muster at City Hall, but it violates no hard-and-fast rules in the
precincts of the museum world.
</P>
<P>
   Although a few major museums have restrictions that would have
kept the exhibit, ``Sensation,'' out of their galleries and
prevented an auction-house sponsorship, the Brooklyn Museum and
other institutions are free to show any private collection without
fear of violating an industrywide ethics code. The Association of
Art Museum Directors, whose 175 members lead the largest art
museums in North America, says nothing about the subject in its
code of professional practices, though it does encourage museums to
develop some policy guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Policies vary, and many museums do single-owner shows,'' said
James Welu, the president of the association and the director of
the Worcester Art Museum in Worcester, Mass. Welu dismissed the
charge, made on Wednesday by senior City Hall officials, that the
Brooklyn Museum was conspiring to inflate the value of the artwork
with Charles Saatchi, the British advertising executive who owns
the works, and Christie's, the auction house that is sponsoring the
show.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota, Deputy Mayor Randy Levine and the
city's corporation counsel, Michael Hess, picking up on criticism
in the art world, said the museum was participating in a ``scam''
that would increase the value of the collection. The Brooklyn
Museum extracted no promises from Saatchi that he would not sell
these works, though he has said he has no plans to sell them. And
when ``Sensation'' leaves Brooklyn in January it will travel to the
National Gallery of Australia in Canberra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they are not aware of how important collectors are in
the appreciation of art, not just today but historically,'' Welu
said. Typically, he added, a third to a half of a museum's
collection is given by private collectors. Sometimes more.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi is not the typical collector, however. He is well known
for buying many works by young, cutting-edge artists, exhibiting
their work in his and other galleries, creating buzz and then often
selling the works. A year after ``Sensation'' played at the Royal
Academy in London, Saatchi put works by the same artists up for
auction. The proceeds went to charity, but many Britons nonetheless
accused him of manipulating the market and that makes people in the
art world here uncomfortable. Saatchi owns 1,500 works of art, many
by these same artists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, unlike the Museum of Modern Art, which does not present
single-owner private collections unless they are promised to the
museum, most museums do so frequently, often with no strings _ or
very skimpy ones _ attached.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Museum of Art is currently exhibiting two
private collections, ``The Artist as Collector: Masterpieces of
Chinese Painting from the C.C. Wang Family Collection'' and
``Native Paths III: American Indian Art from the Collection of
Charles and Valerie Diker.'' Next spring, the National Gallery of
Art in Washington will show more than 70 American paintings from
the collection of Mr. and Mrs. Barney Ebsworth. Earlier this year,
the Seattle Art Museum put the Virginia and Bagley Wright
collection of modern art on view.
</P>
<P>
   Some works in the Wright collection have been given to the
Seattle museum, but it frequently exhibits private collections
without any promises of an eventual donation. So does the Met. Even
if they cannot get an ironclad commitment, however, most museums
set their sights on a gift of some sort when they do these shows.
``The museum doesn't disguise its hopes and aspirations with
collectors,'' said Harold Holzer, the Met's chief spokesman, adding
that each exhibition agreement is hammered out on a case-by-case
basis. The National Gallery, meanwhile, requires a gift of ``a
significant work or works'' when it mounts a single-owner show.
</P>
<P>
   Saatchi has not promised to donate anything to the Brooklyn
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The museum directors' code says nothing about restrictions on
the sale of works in a show, and Welu said he knew of no museums
that set limitations. The Met, however, said that it does insist
that nothing exhibited be sold during a show or for a period,
ranging from six months to two years, after the show.
</P>
<P>
   The Met and the National Gallery also avoid auction houses as
sponsors for exhibitions, though Welu said that many museums had to
look to corporations involved in the art trade for aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
