A2808 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DEUTSCHE-SAKURA-BANK-     09-30 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-SAKURA-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN BANK WILL ENTER JAPANESE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Deutsche Bank AG teamed up Thursday with
Sakura Bank Ltd. of Japan in an effort to take advantage of Japan's
liberalized market for underwriting bond and stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, currently the world's biggest bank in terms of
assets, will get access to Sakura's formidable corporate clients,
which include the giant Mitsui group and Toyota Motor Corp. Sakura,
Japan's fifth-largest bank, is hoping to draw on Deutsche Bank's
expertise in offering corporate securities.
</P>
<P>
   Sakura's shares surged on the news. They initially jumped 100
yen to 838, their highest level since July 1997, before easing
somewhat to close at 800 yen, or $7.53, still a gain of 62 yen, or
8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The move is the latest in a series by Western financial
institutions to expand their presence in Japan, which has become
more open to foreign involvement as the government lowers the
barriers that had barred commercial banks from underwriting
securities.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Merrill Lynch acquired a substantial part of the
defunct Yamaichi Securities. Citigroup has formed an alliance with
Nikko Securities. And both Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank have
teamed up with Japanese partners in the asset management business.
Earlier this week, an American-led investment consortium won the
right to buy the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Deutsche Bank-Sakura agreement would give the
German bank much better access to the Japanese corporate market
than it had before. ``It is a very significant entree into Japan,''
said John Leonard of Salomon Smith Barney in London. ``Sakura has a
very good set of corporate connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese financial markets are changing rapidly because of a
series of measures that have steadily reduced regulatory barriers
and made the country accessible to foreign institutions. Until
recently, Japanese commercial banks were strictly prohibited from
selling securities. Those prohibitions have largely disappeared,
but most Japanese banks have little experience or skill in
investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Japanese corporations are increasingly eager
to raise money through stock and bond offerings rather than by
taking out traditional loans.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank and many of Europe's other big banks lost hundreds
of millions of dollars in the Asian financial crisis because they
had been among the most aggressive lenders to what seemed like
high-growth markets in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that experience, and the long bleak decline in Japan
itself, Deutsche Bank executives have continued to view Asia as an
important market and they have maintained a big staff. The bank
already employs nearly 1,000 people in Japan and has a fairly good
reputation in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche formed a fund venture last year with Nippon Life
Insurance Co. and announced a joint venture with Kokusai Securities
Co. in mutual funds and other forms of asset management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
