<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2809 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-MORRIS-     09-30 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-MORRIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LUBBOCK _ On Oct. 26, 1996, Sammy Morris caught a pass at Kyle
Field in the fourth quarter and ran 81 yards for a touchdown that
lifted Texas Tech past Texas A&AMP;M 13-10.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world, it seemed, was at his feet. Morris was a redshirt
freshman, ready to follow Bam Morris and Byron Hanspard in a line
of top-notch running backs at Texas Tech during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-0 and 212 pounds, Morris was an excellent runner, receiver
and blocker. In eight games in 1996, he rushed 29 times for 226
yards and caught 13 passes for 221 yards, averaging 10.6 yards
every time he touched the football.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five months have passed since that play by Morris against
Texas A&AMP;M. He has touched the football a grand total of six times
for 79 yards _ two fewer than he gained on that memorable touchdown
at College Station.
</P>
<P>
   Academic problems combined with a bureaucratic foul-up and an
injury early this season have gutted Morris' career at Texas Tech.
That he will play Saturday against Texas A&AMP;M is testimony to his
perseverance, a change in his outlook on life and maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes think that all these bad things have happened, and
I've made it through them so now the good times are going to
start,'' Morris said. ``What I'm doing now is trying to escape the
past and not even worry about it. I'm not going to dwell on it. I'm
going to live for today and live for tomorrow, not on what happened
in the past.'' &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Until the last 18 months, Morris' past was not pretty.
</P>
<P>
   On the 1996 day Morris took the pass from Red Raiders
quarterback Zebbie Lethridge and rumbled into the end zone late in
the fourth quarter against A&AMP;M, he knew there was a good chance the
academic hammer was about to come down.
</P>
<P>
   Already on probation, Morris was informed in late October that
he was in more scholastic trouble. There were problems in a
required academic study course in which he was enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policy was if you had two absences, you were withdrawn
(expelled) from the university,'' Morris said. ``I knew that, but I
didn't know that two tardies counted as an absence. So I had one
absence and two tardies. The week before (the A&AMP;M game), there was
a lot of back-and-forth over it. It all came down after the A&AMP;M
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about that a lot. All this has happened because I
was tardy for class a couple times. I guess there's lessons to be
learned there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine days after the highlight-reel play against A&AMP;M, Morris'
career went to freeze frame. He was expelled from the university
for academic reasons and missed the final four games in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Morris regained admission to Texas Tech but did not help himself
during the spring semester in 1997, when he failed to make
sufficient grades to be eligible for the '97 season. In 1998, he
was ruled ineligible by the NCAA because his 1996 course load was
deemed unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   An academic adviser had prescribed a course of study for Morris
that did not meet guidelines. Another lost year for Morris.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Morris remained in school and applied himself. He
is scheduled to receive a degree in communications from Texas Tech
this December. Morris was named to the Big 12 Commissioner's Honor
Roll for the fall semester in 1998 and earned the Red Raiders'
academic effort award after last season.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 17, Morris' wife, Leslie, gave birth to the couple's
first child, a daughter named Kiera. A few days ago, Morris still
had the beaming grin of a first-time parent when talking about his
daughter. He even found humor in the fact Kiera was sleeping no
more than two hours at a time through the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at her, and whatever has happened to me in the past
doesn't seem important at all,'' Morris said. ``I know what's
important now.''
</P>
<P>
   The journey from an immature young college student who paid
little attention to anyone but himself (``I was living my life only
for Sammy,'' Morris said) to a mature young husband and parent who
will leave Lubbock with a college degree is a rewarding story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy Morris is one of the neatest guys I've ever been
around,'' said Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes. ``He means a lot to
this team, with all he's been through. He never complained, never
made an issue out of anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy was the victim of somebody else's mistakes. Educators
telling him to do this, this and this, and he did this, this and
this, but he still was ruled ineligible. I've got great admiration
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dykes points to Morris' strong family background as one reason
for his unyielding effort to make something of himself. Morris'
parents, Samuel and Orinthia of San Antonio, built a groundwork
that he was able to fall back on during the rough times.
</P>
<P>
   But Morris believes his life changed in the spring of 1998, when
he and teammate James Easterling decided to start attending church.
Morris says that since then, he has found an inner peace that was
lacking in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say that that part of my life was B.C. _ before
Christ,'' Morris said. ``Since then, it's been W.C. _ with Christ.
All I did before was my own thing, and it wasn't working that way.
I knew I needed to look somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Morris has needed that inner strength this season. After working
hard in the classroom and staying in shape even though he hadn't
played in nearly three years, he suffered a bruised shoulder in the
opening game this season. Before the injury, he rushed three times
for 11 yards and caught three passes for 68 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to go out there in the first game and get boogered up
like that, you know, that was sort of par for the course,'' Dykes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Morris sat out the next two games, but he practiced this week
and is expected to play against Texas A&AMP;M. Ricky Williams, the star
running back for the Red Raiders, will miss the rest of the season
after reinjuring his left knee in practice this week.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has tremendous admiration for Morris. They were able to
play together for less than one half after both were injured at
Arizona State in the opening game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those
`I'm-going-to-keep-doing-it-till-I-get-it-done' type of guys,''
Williams said. ``He had to stay out of school for so long, but he
bounced back on his feet. The way he's handled all the adversity is
a great lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   The injuries to Williams and Morris are part of the reason Texas
Tech is 1-2 and coming off a devastating 21-14 loss to heavy
underdog North Texas two weeks ago. Morris and Williams watched the
game from the sideline in street clothes, and Morris could scarcely
contain himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sitting on the sidelines watching that, I told Ricky, `Man,
I'm going to go get my pads on,''' Morris said. ``That would have
been silly, but I gave it a thought. I wanted to help out.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, too, wanted to help out against Texas A&AMP;M. He tested
his ailing knee in practice this week and aggravated the injury. He
will have season-ending surgery soon, casting another pall over
Tech's fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Morris wants to finally get back in the swing of
things, both to help the Red Raiders get untracked and to show what
he can do during what's left of his career. He says he has had a
goal of playing in the NFL since he was in second grade, and time
is running out to demonstrate what he's capable of.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his inactivity, Morris was named by ESPN's Mel Kiper as
the top-rated fullback in next year's NFL draft, something that
floored Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard that, I thought somebody was lying to me,''
Morris said. ``That's pretty amazing, not having played for two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the touchdown reception and run nearly three years ago
remains in the minds of NFL analysts. For Morris, the play against
Texas A&AMP;M is a pleasant moment from his past and a nagging reminder
of what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about it pretty often,'' Morris said. ``I use it as a
motivational thing. In 1998, I was kind of down during the week
before the team played A&AMP;M. I'd think back to what happened that
day.''
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't dwell on it. He says he has seen the tape of the
play only two or three times, and that by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad watches it (the tape) all the time,'' Morris said. ``If
he has it on when I'm walking through the room, I'll sit and watch
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris would like nothing better than to do something memorable
again this week. After all he has been through since the last time
he played against the Aggies, it seems he's due for something good
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad to be back,'' Morris said. ``Whatever happens,
happens. I know now there is a plan. God has a plan, and I continue
to seek his ways. It's not trusting only what I see, but what's in
my heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd love to get another highlight play against the
Aggies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
