<SLUG> BC-ROCKET-TCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETDYNE'S CLEANUP DATA SURPRISES ACTIVISTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA MASCARO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. -- The Department of Defense, not NASA,
conducted most of the rocket engine tests at Rocketdyne's field
lab, an official said, fueling the space agency's contention that
the military is not contributing enough toward cleanup costs.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Elliott, NASA's project manager for the cleanup, said the
agency conducted only 23 percent of the rocket engine tests at the
Santa Susana Field Laboratory from 1949-83, while the Defense
Department performed 77 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't the biggest customer out there,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   The information was presented Wednesday night during the
quarterly meeting of the work group monitoring the cleanup. It
surprised activists, who said they hope to have the military
provide further information about activities at the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always led to believe the Santa Susana Field Lab was
used by NASA to develop the engines to the moon,'' Joesph K. Lyou,
an activist and work group member said Thursday. ``We really need
to establish contacts with (Defense Department) to find out what
happened out there over time.''
</P>
<P>
   A representative from Sen. Barbara Boxer's office said the
California Democrat would be willing to work with California Rep.
Elton Gallegly and other local officials to establish contacts with
the military on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   A report issued last fall said NASA had been over-billed by
$16.4 million for its share of cleanup and that it should try to
recover costs from other parties, including the Department of
Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Army Corps of Engineers, who are handling the
site for the Defense Department, did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday night, Elliott said the decades of engine testing
sent more than 500,000 gallons of a possible cancer-causing
chemical -- more than Rocketdyne has estimated -- into the
groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical trichloroethylene -- TCE -- was used as a solvent
to flush the rocket engines before and after they were tested and
until 1961 was collected in an earthen-lined pit at the site. After
1961, it was collected for reuse until being phased out by 1984,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No drinking water wells are believed to be contaminated with the
chemical, and Rocketdyne has pumped more than 1.5 billion gallons
of water from its sites as part of cleanup since the mid-1980s,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the contaminated groundwater has long been a concern for
regulators overseeing cleanup at the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the water at Rocketdyne is contained and confined
essentially to the Rocketdyne site, it's always a shame when you
lose a resource,'' said Gerard Abrams, an official from the state
Department of Toxic Substances Control, whose agency handles
chemical cleanup. ``It's always a concern because groundwater is an
important resource; it's not a resource you want to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
