<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-IPO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE BANKER HAS IPO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY  JASON Z. COHEN 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Digital Insight, an online banking service
provider, is set to go public this morning after its initial public
offering was priced Thursday night at $15 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The company priced its IPO a dollar above the high end of its
estimated $12 to $14 price range, a move that hints at strong
demand, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the stock market as a whole has performed poorly
recently, some of the stronger IPOs nevertheless have shown strong
gains, said Tom Taulli, a columnist with Internet.com.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Insight's 3.5 million share IPO, underwritten by Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, raised $52.5 million for Digital Insight. The
IPO leaves the company with a market capitalization of $212
million, including shares it holds.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Insight said it has contracts with 380 small banks,
credit unions, and savings and loan associations to provide
Internet banking, online loan approval and other banking services
over the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Taulli said the market for outsourced technical services is one
he expects to grow in the next few years as companies decide to
focus on their business and hire outside firms to handle online
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes more sense to outsource something like that,''
Taulli said. ``Smaller institutions don't have the budgets to do
that, but they know they have to provide those options to their
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   In its registration statement filed with the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission, Digital Insight reported a net loss of $3.6
million for the six months ended June 30, on pace to surpass the
company's 1998 net loss of $4.4 million for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always iffy to come out in a volatile or choppy market,''
said Gail Bronson, senior analyst with Calabasas-based IPO Monitor.
``A lot of would-be IPOs were held back in the summer, and smartly
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Estimating how Digital Insight will perform today on its initial
day of trading is too difficult, Bronson said, because it would
require guessing the mood of day traders and institutional
investors.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
