<SLUG> BC-UNDERWRITING-REPORT-ART-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERWRITING OF STOCK AND BOND ISSUES SLOWED IN SEPTEMBER
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So much for the post-Labor Day rush on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The primary business of investment banks _ underwriting sales of
stocks and bonds _ is slowing in the second half of 1999, not
accelerating as some bankers and traders had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Securities firms and banks issued $473 billion of stocks and
bonds in the third quarter, a 3.5 percent increase from $456.8
billion in the third quarter of 1998, but a marked decline from the
first two quarters of 1999, according to Thomson Financial
Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   September had been expected by some to be an especially busy
month as corporations hurried to sell bonds before fears about year
2000 complications scared off investors and drove up borrowing
costs. But that pickup did not occur; rather, the quarter ended on
a downbeat, depressed by concerns about rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most remarkable thing was the continued weak state of the
corporate bond market, despite the very strong fundamentals,'' said
Jeff Chandler, a managing director at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``A lot
of borrowers are sitting back and demonstrating that they do have
the luxury of time and can sit back and wait until next year if
they want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Worries that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates again
next week continued to hang over the market, Wall Street executives
said. But if the Fed makes no change and sets off a rally in bond
prices, the anticipated rush to tap investors for loans before
year-end could materialize in October, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, said Mark Seigel, a managing director at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., ``things will slow down as we approach
year-end.'' In the wake of the financial crises that roiled the
bond markets in the last two years, Seigel said, investors have
shown a decided preference for bonds issued in large amounts by
companies with strong credit ratings, like the $8.6 billion
offering by Ford Motor Co. in early July.
</P>
<P>
   Riskier high-yield bonds, known as junk bonds on Wall Street,
were a much harder sell. Junk bond issuance was just $2.2 billion
in September, the lowest total since July 1995, said Richard
Peterson, an analyst at Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch again led all securities firms in total
underwriting volume. In the third quarter, Merrill Lynch handled
about 17 percent of all stock and bond volume. Citigroup's Salomon
Smith Barney unit ranked second, followed in order by Goldman Sachs
Group, Credit Suisse First Boston and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   Those rankings are important to investment bankers because they
use them as weapons in battles for underwriting assignments. But,
in the end, the most important measure is the fees those
assignments generate because some deals are much more lucrative
than others.
</P>
<P>
   In general, investment banks earn fatter fees from stock issues,
especially companies' first-time offerings, than from bond issues.
That is why firms that have strong franchises in distributing stock
tend to rake in more fees.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs took in $339 million in disclosed fees in the
third quarter, or about 15 percent of the industry total of $2.3
billion, according to Securities Data. That put Goldman ahead of
Merrill Lynch, which took in $284 million in disclosed fees. Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter ranked third, with $262 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fee revenue correlates closely with how the firms stacked up in
stock underwriting, which held up better in the quarter than did
the bond business. Firms handled about $27 billion in new stock in
the quarter, more than double the $13.7 billion a year before, but
well below the $46.7 billion in the second quarter of 1999, which
was full of initial public offerings by Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 147 initial offerings in the quarter, 71 of them, or
nearly half, came in the Internet sector, Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, there is an appetite for new ideas and new issues and
it's particularly strong in technology and communications,'' said
Tom Tuft, co-head of equity capital markets at Goldman, Sachs. ``A
lot of deals are getting done despite the fact that there's been a
lot of choppiness in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuft said he expected a full calendar of stock offerings in
October and November, then a slower-than-normal December. ``Most
people are focused on getting deals done before Thanksgiving,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Merger and acquisition activity rose by 43 percent, to $766
billion in the third quarter, from $535 billion a year earlier,
based on the value of the announced deals.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter ranked as the leading adviser, ahead
of Goldman, Sachs. Most of the action occurred in Europe, home of
the targets in four of the five biggest deals announced. Morgan
Stanley was also the leading adviser in U.S. deals, which declined
12 percent to $315 billion, from $358 billion a year before.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
