<HEADER>
A2823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-N.Y.-ART-DEALER-ARRES     09-30 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-ART-DEALER-ARRESTED-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART DEALER SAYS ARREST IS AN ATTACK ON RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After being led from her eponymous Fifth Avenue art
gallery in handcuffs late Wednesday and spending a sleepless night
and the better part of a day in custody, the art dealer Mary Boone
assailed the police Thursday for arresting her on charges of
illegally distributing ammunition that was part of an exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outrageous attack on the artistic rights to express
themselves,'' Ms. Boone said after her arraignment about 8 p.m.
Thursday at Criminal Court in Manhattan, still in the sleeveless
orange dress and high-heel shoes she was wearing when she was
arrested around 6 p.m. Wednesday. ``It's all a First Amendment
issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Boone, 47, who was proclaimed `Queen of the Art World'' on
the cover of New York magazine in the 1980s, is one of the city's
most flamboyant and outspoken art dealers. She was arrested after
the police were told that she was offering gallery visitors live
9-millimeter cartridges as keepsakes of a one-man show by the
sculptor Tom Sachs. The police seized the ammunition, which Ms.
Boone had placed in a glass vase on the reception desk of her
gallery at 745 Fifth Ave., and a sculpture consisting of four
shotguns and two pistols.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Boone was arraigned on charges of possessing an exposed
rifle and possessing and disposing of ammunition. She faces up to a
year in jail and $2,000 in fines if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors dropped three charges that the police had filed
against Ms. Boone _ resisting arrest, criminal possession of a
weapon and possession of stolen property (a wooden barrier in the
exhibition that the police said was the property of Con Edison).
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Thompson, a spokeswoman for the Manhattan district
attorney's office, would not comment on the reason those charges
were not pressed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Boone, declaring that she had not slept in 36 hours, spoke
briefly to reporters Thursday night and said the cartridges being
distributed from her gallery were not live, operable rounds.
Prosecutors, however, produced ballistic tests that they said
showed the bullets were live.
</P>
<P>
   City officials continued to defend Ms. Boone's arrest Thursday
and denied that it was related in any way to Mayor Rudolph W.
Giuliani's ongoing battle with the Brooklyn Museum of Art. Police
officials said that Ms. Boone had been arrested and booked rather
than issued what is known as a desk appearance ticket, ordering her
to appear in court at a later date, because department policy
mandates the arrest of all people accused of illegal weapons
possession.
</P>
<P>
   Legal scholars said Ms. Boone's argument that the cartridges and
shotguns were protected artistic expression stands on shaky ground.
Amy Adler, a New York University law professor who specializes in
First Amendment issues, said that courts have generally held that
art barred for being obscene can be protected by the Constitution
but that acts that potentially pose a threat to public safety do
not enjoy that privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can go out and commit a murder and say that was
performance art,'' Ms. Adler said. ``It could be art, but it's
still illegal.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, the Police Department's chief spokeswoman, said
Thursday that the arrest occurred after a reporter for The New York
Post asked police officials to determine whether it was legal for
the gallery to distribute live ammunition. The Post had received a
complaint about the show and told police officials that a reporter
visited the gallery and had taken one of the bullets to the Federal
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms for analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The police sent two detectives from the Midtown North precinct
to investigate the report about 5 p.m. on Wednesday, officials
added. During the 45 minutes that police officials say Ms. Boone
kept the two detectives waiting, they wandered into the main part
of the gallery, where they noticed a cabinet on a wall holding the
guns that were a part of Sachs' exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The detectives confiscated the bullets and a number of Sachs'
works on the suspicion that they could be either explosive or used
as weapons, officials said. A decision was made to arrest Ms. Boone
once investigators determined the guns could be used, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Boone appeared composed Thursday night after spending 26
hours in jail. She chatted with a man accused of robbery while
waiting in a dingy courtroom for her arraignment. A young woman
arrested on charges of selling marijuana and placed in a holding
cell with Ms. Boone said she was ``very nice'' and ``sweet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
