<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2943 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-30 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros have made a habit of rising above obstacles this season.
That resiliency has put them in position to make magic numbers a
part of their vocabulary for a third consecutive year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If they had their choice of hocus-pocus, the Astros surely would
have made the Cincinnati Reds disappear weeks ago, and the New York
Mets also would have vanished. But at last scan, there was no David
Copperfield on the Astros' roster.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Astros' best route to a magic number of zero
is to create a little magic of their own during the final
regular-season series in Astrodome history. That series begins
tonight when they open a three-game series with the spoiler-minded
Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are locked in a first-place tie with Cincinnati atop
the National League Central Division after splitting a two-game
series with the Reds this week. Both teams lead the Mets by two
games in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, Reds and Mets finish the season against sub-.500
competition, but if their opponents seem equally woeful, it's just
an illusion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 76-83 record, the Dodgers have an $80 million payroll
and a roster dotted with superstar-caliber players such as Kevin
Brown, Gary Sheffield and Raul Mondesi. They have won nine of their
last 12 games and were picked by many to contend for the World
Series when the season began.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodgers are a scary team,'' Astros first baseman Jeff
Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   A case could be made that the Brewers, who host the Reds, and
the Pirates, who visit the Mets, have overachieved to compile their
mediocre records. The Dodgers clearly have the best talent among
the three teams; then again, the Pirates and Brewers won three-game
series from the Astros last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly appears on paper that we have the toughest
series,'' Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said Thursday.
``The Dodgers are a dangerous team with a lot of talent. They've
just underachieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we went to Pittsburgh and Milwaukee and got knocked
around. We were in the driver's seat a couple of weeks ago, and we
got ourselves into this mess. We have no one to blame but
ourselves. A team trying to win a championship has to play like
champions, and we didn't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we still have a good deal of control over our own destiny,
and we need to take care of ourselves. Our biggest game is
tomorrow, and after that our biggest game is Saturday. Our goal is
to win these last three games, and if that's not good enough, then
it's not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Astros wouldn't mind a little assistance from the
Brewers and Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Reds have the advantage,'' Astros closer Billy
Wagner said. ``Hopefully, the Brewers will play them the way they
played us.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Brewers fold and the Astros struggle against the Dodgers,
the wild-card berth is still a possibility, depending on how the
Mets fare against the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   But Hunsicker would prefer to see his team add to its collection
of division titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to win the division,'' he said. ``It always has
been. It would be silly to suggest we're trying to get in as the
wild card. We want to win the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you ever want to ask anyone else to do your job
for you. If we had done our job, we wouldn't be in this situation.
That's one of the things a team has to guard against. There's a
difference between playing to win and playing not to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's crucial victory notwithstanding, the Astros picked a
bad time to fall into a rut. But that tends to happen late in the
season when the bodies of position players are aching and pitchers
become arm-weary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three big games coming up with the Dodgers,'' second
baseman Craig Biggio said, ``and we need to try to win them. We
don't know what's going to happen as far as the playoffs are
concerned; we're just trying to win our division, and to do it
three years in a row is unbelievably difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more difficult than they ever imagined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
