<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2948 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-MUSEUM-OPENING-1ST     09-30 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-OPENING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURATI VIEW CONTROVERSIAL ART EXHIBIT IN NEW YORK  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS: Lower-cases `pointilist' and `cloissone.' Adds second z to
`terrazzo.' Insert in 7th graf, bgng The crowd, clarifies purpose
of the gathering. Deletes part of last graf of 1st take. In 2nd
take, inserts new 13th and 14th grafs, bgng Asked if, and adds two
grafs at end.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nibbling shrimp and baby lobster tails, talking on
cell phones and solemnly contemplating such works of art as a sink
and plumbing nestled in what looked like a musician's case lined in
red velvet, New York's culturati gathered proudly Thursday night at
the Brooklyn Museum of Art in defiance of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
bruised esthetic sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a gift from the mayor to provide this enormous
publicity,'' said Peter Norton, who developed the anti-virus
computer program that bears his name and is now a major collector.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hubbub is a lot of nonsense, but you can't buy that kind
of publicity,'' Norton said. ``I said they'd have to open five new
ticket tables.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people, of course, gathered in front of the now-famous
painting, ``The Holy Virgin Mary,'' which is festooned with
elephant dung and has become the centerpiece of the dispute between
the city and the museum. Almost unnoticed in a corner was the work
that stirred protest in London: a large portrait of Myra Handle, a
child murderess done in a pointilist style of tiny children's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Norton, for one, was quite taken with the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised at how pretty, how lyrical, how sympathetic it
is,'' he said. ``If you get beyond the knee-jerk reaction, it's not
offensive. It has the glowing quality of cloissonne or terrazzo.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at the event, a preview benefit for contributors, was
a sea of dark suits, a few worn daringly without ties, and lots and
lots of little black dresses. Many people seemed to get stuck
around the art in the rotunda, filled with Rodin sculpture,
arguably the best work on view.
</P>
<P>
   Listening in on conversations, it seemed the reviews of
``Sensation'' were mixed. Some people said they loved that shark in
the formaldehyde, while others said they didn't think the cow cut
in 12 sections worked as well.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Grant, the actor, strolled by all but unnoticed with the
artist Sam Taylor-Wood, whose painting ``Wrecked'' is a take on the
Last Supper with the central Christlike figure a topless woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw some pieces that I liked, some pieces I don't like,''
said Michael Bloomberg, the business-news mogul. ``I don't
understand why there is a fuss about this. To me there is nothing
sacrilegious about the art.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the civil libertarian, was among those present
already bubbling over with plans for a protest rally on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the buzz in the museum,'' he said. ``You hear a lot of
people saying, `What's the big deal,' and maybe they're being
sensitized to the increasing authoritarianism in the city. Maybe
there's a silver lining in the way New York City is being tested.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city filed a lawsuit in state Supreme Court in
Brooklyn Thursday, seeking to evict the museum. The suit contends
that the museum violated its lease by imposing a special $9.75 fee
for admission to the exhibition and by promoting the commercial
interests of the private collector who owns the artwork in the
show.
</P>
<P>
   The city's lawyers also appeared at a routine hearing in
Brooklyn federal court Thursday, where the museum has filed suit
against the city.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The museum's lawyer, Floyd Abrams, was asking Judge Nina Gershon
to schedule a hearing when Michael Hess, the city's corporation
counsel, announced that the city had filed its own suit.
</P>
<P>
   Hess contended that since the city had brought suit in state
court, the federal suit filed by the museum should be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Gershon said she would consider the city's request, and
told both sides to submit papers by Oct. 4 on all the issues in the
case, including on whether she should dismiss it. The judge will
hold another hearing on Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's most widely discussed work, Chris Ofili's
``Holy Virgin Mary,'' was ensconced behind a Plexiglas shield in a
small alcove, with a guard posted nearby, in an apparent effort to
forestall any overt acts of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Four more of Ofili's works, all executed in his favored medium,
elephant dung, are also on view. All display his hallmark technique
of supporting the main body of work on two footlike pedestals of
dried pachyderm product, which is said by collectors to lose its
smell after it has aired out for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit also contains several pieces by Damien Hirst, who
works mostly in dead fish and animals. These include a shark, a
sliced-up cow, a lamb and a bisected pig in formaldehyde-filled
cases, and a Rube Goldberg-like device in which maggots feed on a
dead cow's head and give rise to flies, which are eventually zapped
by an electrical device called an ``insect-o-cutor.'' This last is
said to be a meditation on mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Basking in the publicity that the controversy has generated, the
museum played host to hundreds of reporters and photographers
Thursday morning for a first look at the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to see so many members of the press interested in
art,'' Arnold Lehman, the museum's director, said dryly, welcoming
the unaccustomed horde.
</P>
<P>
   But the embattled curator quickly turned serious, saying:
``Public funding of the arts is an investment in the values and the
ideals embodied in the First Amendment of the United States
Constitution. I hope that people will choose to see this
exhibition. I also hope they have the right to choose not to see
this exhibition. That is what democracy in America is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's something else I'd like to say,'' he added. ``The
Brooklyn Museum is more than just one work of art that incorporates
animal dung.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lehman staunchly defended Ofili's choice of artistic
material, saying that the use of animal dung is venerated in many
African cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they tell us is not a story of blasphemy, but of
reverence,'' he said. ``But it is in a language that is foreign to
many of us raised in the tradition of Western culture. Having these
sacred objects in our museums teach us lessons of tolerance,
understanding and diversity. If people do not make the effort to
understand, if people do not exercise tolerance and mutual respect,
then we all suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought the controversy would increase ticket sales,
Lehman, who has said he became interested in the exhibit when he
saw the long lines it generated in London, replied: ``Hopefully,
ticket sales will be explosive. This evening we were expecting
hundreds of people. Now we're expecting a couple of thousand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with a museum filled with people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani continued to fulminate against the exhibition
Thursday from Bakersfield, Calif., where he was on a political
fund-raising jaunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the motivation is commercial
motivation. You'd have to be a fool not to see that,'' the mayor
said of the dispute that he himself stirred up. ``This is
essentially what you do to promote some kind of commercial
enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Dolman, a managing director of Christie's, the auction
house that is helping sponsor the exhibit, demurred, rebuffing City
Hall's contention of a scheme to pump up the prices of the artwork,
which is part of the collection of Charles Saatchi, the British
advertising executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of art is determined by supply and demand,'' Dolman
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2952 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-MARS-ORBITER-1STL     09-30 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-ORBITER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFUSION OVER TWO MEASUREMENT SYSTEMS CAUSED MARS ORBITER'S LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to recast lede, correct and define newton and poundal
units of force in 2nd, 19th, 20th and 22nd graphs.)  (th) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Scientists lost a $125 million spacecraft as it
approached Mars last week essentially because they confused feet
and pounds with meters and kilograms, NASA said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   An internal review team at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, in
a preliminary conclusion, said that engineers at Lockheed Martin
Corp., which had built the spacecraft, specified certain
measurements about the spacecraft's thrust in poundals, an English
unit, but that NASA scientists thought the information was a metric
measurement known as newtons.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting miscalculation, undetected for months as the craft
was designed, built and launched, meant the Mars Climate Orbiter,
as it was called, was off course by about 60 miles as it approached
Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the cautionary tale that is going to be
embedded into introductions to the metric system in elementary
school and high school and college physics till the end of time,''
said John Pike, director of space policy at the Federation of
American Scientists in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed's reaction was equally blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction is disbelief,'' said Noel Hinners, vice president
for flight systems at Lockheed Martin Astronautics in Denver. ``It
can't be something that simple that could cause this to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The finding was a major embarrassment for NASA, which said it
was investigating how such a basic error could have gone through
the a space mission's checks and balances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is not that the data was wrong,'' said Edward
C. Stone, the director of Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena,
Calif., which was in charge of the mission. ``The real issue is
that our process did not realize there was this discrepancy and
correct for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts also wondered how something so basic could have
gone undetected for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time I checked I could sort of visually detect the
difference between a foot and a meter,'' Pike said. ``This is kind
of the very first thing in Physics 101 or Engineering 101. This is
the only significant program failure that anyone's ever heard of
that's due to this.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure could raise questions about whether NASA and its
contractors are skimping on safety to cut costs. The Mars Climate
Orbiter, the first spacecraft designed to study the climate of
another planet, was exceedingly inexpensive by NASA's standards. It
is part of a new strategy to fly more but less expensive missions
to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   That limits the damage done by the failure of any single
mission. ``There is not a single mission in the program that is
critical to the overall program,'' said Stone.
</P>
<P>
   But Pike said, ``Obviously the question they are going to have
to ask is maybe it was a little too cheap. The question that will
have to be asked here is whether in cutting costs, they cut
corners.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure is also another black eye for Lockheed, the nation's
largest military contractor, which in the last year or so has
suffered several failures of rockets and missiles it has developed.
These failures led the company to restructure its operations and
change management in its space business.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials said they are checking to make sure the same
error does not occur in the Mars Polar Lander, which is now en
route to Mars and scheduled to reach the planet on Dec. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Two separate review committees have already been formed to
investigate the loss of the Mars Climate Orbiter _ the internal Jet
Propulsion Laboratory peer review team, which made Thursday's
preliminary findings, and a special review board of experts from
the laboratory and elsewhere. An independent NASA failure review
board will be formed shortly.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known with certainty what happened to the Mars Climate
Orbiter. At first there was speculation that it crashed on Mars or
burned up in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   But the review team now tends to think that the spacecraft is
now orbiting the sun, a Jet Propulsion Laboratory spokesman said.
Under this theory, the spacecraft approached too close to Mars and
overheated, causing the engine that was being fired to bring the
craft into orbit to stop functioning, so the Orbiter continued on
into space.
</P>
<P>
   NASA and Lockheed officials said the full details of how the
mistake occurred were not known. But, basically, Lockheed was
providing the Jet Propulsion Laboratory with data on the amount of
force imparted to the spacecraft by its thrusters, which are fired
periodically. This was measured in poundals, Hinners said.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists at Jet Propulsion Laboratory assumed the figure
was in newtons and incorporated it into computer models that are
used to calculate the spacecraft's position and direction. A newton
is the force needed to accelerate a one-kilogram mass one meter per
second per second. A poundal is the force needed to accelerate a
one-pound mass one foot per second per second.
</P>
<P>
   The computer models supplement other data about the spacecraft's
position, Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Since one poundal equals about 4.4 newtons, it would seem that
such an error would be readily detected, but Hinners said this was
not the case because the thrusters contributed only a little to the
orbit. ``The firings would have been a very small piece of a larger
number,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The miscalculations put the spacecraft off course by only about
60 miles out of a journey of roughly 416 million miles, Stone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
