<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDUC-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES TOUGH LOVE FOR STUDENTS WHO ARE FAILING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., N.C., N.J., Fla., Calif., Wis.)  (rk) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALISADES, N.Y. _ President Clinton Thursday told governors and
executives at a conference examining educational standards that
students who are held back because they fail to vault newly raised
bars should be treated with tough love.
</P>
<P>
   The president insisted, for example, that each of the 24
governors who arrived here for the two-day National Education
Summit ``look dead in the eye some child who has been held back''
and say, ``This doesn't mean there's something wrong with you, but
we'll be hurting you worse if we tell you you're learning something
when you're not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll basically be participating in a fraud,'' the president
continued, as if addressing a student himself, ``which ultimately
will cost you more personally, psychically, and of course,
eventually, financially, than any pain that comes in the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, in fact, the unwelcome prospect of causing such pain
that had brought the 114 leaders together. Led by Louis V.
Gerstner, the chairman of IBM, the group gathered to discuss the
rapidly changing educational landscape, in which every state but
Iowa has either adopted or drafted expectations for what students
should know or be able to do in at least some grades and subjects.
</P>
<P>
   As states begin to install tests to measure that knowledge,
millions of students who fail the exams are expected to be held
back. Thousands, in states including New York, already have been.
</P>
<P>
   But if the conference, which began Thursday afternoon with the
president's address, is intended to grapple with the new
expectations for children, the participants made clear that adults
were to be held accountable as well.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the conference ends on Friday afternoon, the
organizers hope that the participants, who include the leaders of
the two biggest teachers unions, will endorse a statement of
actions they intend to take. For example, a draft that was
circulating Thursday asked 10 states to start pilot programs
linking teachers' pay to such factors as their skills in the
classroom, their own education and the performance of their
students.
</P>
<P>
   Though many professionals have long been paid according to their
specialties, their expertise and the degree to which they are in
demand, teachers have strenuously resisted similar efforts. They
have feared that their salaries would fluctuate either because of a
principal's whim or because the most logical measure of their
success, student test scores, are often related to factors outside
of teachers' control, like poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The National Education Association, the country's largest
teachers union, recently endorsed a pay-for-performance experiment
in Denver. The union's president, Bob Chase, and his counterpart at
the American Federation of Teachers, Sandra Feldman, said Thursday
that they did not oppose expanding such a program, but they advised
proceeding with caution. How, for example, would schools fairly
define good teaching, they asked.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Feldman said states should look to examples like North
Carolina, which ties teachers' bonuses, of as much as $1,500 a
year, not to the performance of individual classes, but to the
performance of entire schools. It was not clear which states, if
any, would agree to start a pilot program.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of such gatherings _ this one included the
governors of New Jersey, Florida and California and the chief
executives of United Parcel Service, DuPont and Prudential Life
Insurance _ is often to move beyond rhetoric to the reality of
schools and classrooms. The speakers here sometimes had difficulty
doing so, calling, as Gov. James B. Hunt Jr. of North Carolina did,
for ``a national passion to have an excellent teaching force,'' but
offering few suggestions for how to reduce class sizes and
otherwise ease teachers' burdens.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The speakers Thursday included state superintendents and the
leaders of school board associations, but no rank-and-file teachers
or principals.
</P>
<P>
   Though the last gathering of governors and chief executives,
convened by Gerstner in 1996, succeeded in making ``standards'' a
rallying cry for educators and politicians, it remains to be seen
what the legacy of this gathering will be.
</P>
<P>
   In the draft of the closing statement, the participants would
agree that districts should steer hundreds of millions of dollars
spent on teachers' professional development to courses directly
tied to each state's standards in English, mathematics, social
studies and science. That would, in many districts, be a radical
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dirty little secret'' of professional development, one
organizer said, has been that some districts have paid little heed
to teachers' education, sometimes rewarding teachers for taking
what in effect are vacations to foreign countries or national
parks.
</P>
<P>
   The participants would also agree to press for programs that
would help failing students before they are held back or denied
diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   But forging any broader consensus may prove difficult: the
governors and educational leaders have deep differences on issues
like publicly financed vouchers to private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The draft of the closing statement, for example, endorses
``choice,'' often a synonym for vouchers, only within public school
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want `choice' to be the distraction,'' said Gov. Tommy
G. Thompson of Wisconsin, an organizer of the conference, who has
supported a voucher experiment in Milwaukee. ``Therefore, it's not
going to be mentioned or discussed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
