<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2966 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-JUDGE-ABORTION-KAN &LR;      09-30 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-ABORTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION LAW BACKERS THINK FEDERAL JUDGE WILL RULE AGAINST
MEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Key backers of Missouri's newest abortion
law think the measure probably will be struck down by U.S. District
Judge Scott Wright. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The officials, including the Senate sponsor of the law, said
they were pessimistic about prevailing in district court not
because they thought the new law was flawed, but because of
previous rulings by Wright. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senate sponsor Ted House of St. Charles said Wright ``has
consistently supported the abortion industry. Judge Wright has
never met an abortion regulation that he liked.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House said he shared the sentiment of other anti-abortion
leaders who expected to lose the first legal round in district
court. A trial to decide whether the statute is constitutional is
set for March 27. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not giving up at the trial level, but we knew from the
beginning that we have to be in this for the long run,'' House
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents said they had a better chance before a
federal appeals court or, if the law got that far, the U.S. Supreme
Court. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Bednar, legal counsel for Gov. Mel Carnahan, criticized
predictions by abortion foes who thought Wright would reject the
measure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are a bit unfair to Judge Wright,'' Bednar said.
``The fact of the matter is they have a bill with serious
constitutional problems. To try to blame it on the judge they got
is dodging the issue.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wright declined comment on predictions of how he will rule. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The law is already on hold because of the federal lawsuit in
Wright's court. Arguments and appeals on the issue could delay it
from taking effect for two years, officials said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Backers say the law will ban what they call ``partial-birth''
abortions by labeling them as infanticide. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed by a clinic that provides abortions in St.
Louis and a doctor who performs abortions, said that the new law
was so broad it would ban most abortions and that it failed to
include a health exception for mothers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lou DeFeo, lobbyist for the Missouri Catholic Conference and one
of the drafters of the law, said he thought that Wright would
reject the measure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Previous rulings by Wright on abortion cases, as well as other
abortion rulings in district court in Kansas City, led him to that
conclusion, DeFeo said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If the horses ran one way in the past they will likely run
that way in the future,'' said DeFeo, a lawyer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sam Lee, an anti-abortion lobbyist who called Wright ``the
darling of Planned Parenthood,'' said he would be shocked if Wright
did not reject the law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Lee said history showed that such a setback would not be
fatal to the legislation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lee said that Wright had been reversed on several abortion
cases, including his rejection of a 1986 Missouri law that included
a ban on abortions in public health facilities. The U.S. Supreme
Court upheld that measure in 1989 in the case of Webster vs.
Reproductive Health Services. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court in 1992 reversed Wright's rejection of
another Missouri law that required special insurance payments to
cover elective abortions, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City attorney Arthur Benson, who is helping to represent
plaintiffs in the lawsuit, cited last Friday's ruling by the U.S.
8th Circuit Court of Appeals, which rejected partial-birth abortion
bans in three states. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that after the Eighth Circuit rulings on Friday
that the chances of this law being sustained at the trial-court
level went from slim to none,'' Benson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Missouri law is simply unconstitutional,'' he said. ``It
doesn't matter whether we are talking about the trial court or the
appeals court.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Cherrick of St. Louis, a special assistant state attorney
defending the law, did not comment on predictions that Wright will
reject it. Cherrick said he would ``try to persuade every court
that our position is correct.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The law under fire triggered weeks of debate in the Missouri
legislature earlier this year. Carnahan vetoed it but the General
Assembly overrode the veto last month, just the third override in
Missouri this century. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still more abortion arguments may surface during the 2000
session, which begins in January. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan has urged lawmakers to pass a partial-birth abortion
ban that includes a health exception for the mother. Opponents said
that they had no interest in passing such a measure and that the
health exception would make the ban meaningless. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   House said that legislative efforts to keep Planned Parenthood
from getting state family-planning funds _ the object of a separate
lawsuit _ triggered legislative arguments most every year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DeFeo said the Missouri Catholic Conference remained committed
to an ``abortion-free society'' but was unsure what bills it would
urge lawmakers to approve next year to help achieve that goal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2334EDT &QL; 
