<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASHCROFT-CARNAHAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATIONS TO ASHCROFT, CARNAHAN DRIVES SPARK ALLEGATIONS OF
PARTIALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Was Republican Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri acting as an
impartial juror when he voted to remove President Clinton in
February? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say they have new evidence suggesting he was not. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Was Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan, a Democrat, making an impartial
judgment when he vetoed a late-term abortion bill this year? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not, Republicans say. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The skirmish over judgment is the latest issue in the U.S.
Senate race between the two. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The charge against Ashcroft was based on a $2,000 payment that
Ashcroft's Spirit of America Political Action Committee received
from the defense fund of Linda Tripp, who provided prosecutors
tape-recorded evidence against the president. The payment, for the
purchase of a fund-raising list, came on Feb. 9, three days before
Ashcroft voted to cast Clinton out of office. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Ashcroft completely disregarded his responsibility to
hear the evidence as a fair and impartial juror,'' Missouri
Democratic Chairman Joe Carmichael charged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashcroft had an ethical responsibility to disclose, before the
end of the trial, his relationship with Tripp and the money he
received from her,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The PAC received two other payments from Tripp's fund, on April
8 and May 10. The three payments totaled almost $2,500. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Hancock, executive director of the Missouri GOP, said
Ashcroft disclosed the information as the law required. He pointed
out that Ashcroft's thoughts about Clinton were clear from the
beginning of the impeachment trial and that the payment in no way
compromised the senator. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``John Ashcroft was decisive in this case,'' Hancock said. ``He
was one of the first senators in the country to say Clinton's
behavior was reprehensible.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the Constitution defined the impeachment trial as
a political proceeding, not a criminal trial. Several senators
voiced opinions about the case before casting their final
impeachment votes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it unusual for fund-raising lists to be sold to
direct-mail groups, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If Democrats think that a $2,000 list swap influenced John
Ashcroft's feeling about Bill Clinton's behavior with Monica
Lewinsky, then they don't know John Ashcroft very well,'' Hancock
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Democrats came up with the charge to counter
Republicans' accusation last week about Carnahan. The GOP pointed
out that the governor accepted $14,000 in campaign contributions
from abortion-rights groups while a bill banning ``partial birth''
abortions sat on his desk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan eventually vetoed the ban on the late-term procedure.
The General Assembly overrode his veto, making the bill a law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a federal judge has issued a restraining order that
will keep the law from being enforced until at least March, when a
review will be conducted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan, a staunch abortion-rights supporter, had vetoed
similar legislation earlier in his administration. He has said
there was no link between the contributions and his action this
year and that he welcomes donations from abortion-rights groups. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I do many actions as governor, and I do them based on my
responsibility, my duty and what I think is right,'' Carnahan told
The Associated Press. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
