r w BC-NIXON-LAWSUITS-KAN &LR;      09-30 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIXON-LAWSUITS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI ATTORNEY GENERAL BACKS ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP ON SUITS
AGAINST POLLUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon and a dozen
other attorneys general are siding with an environmental group
asking that the U.S. Supreme Court let people seek court
enforcement of pollution-control laws. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon appeared Thursday at a news conference called by Friends
of the Earth. The group is appealing a lower court ruling that it
says undermines the Clean Water Act. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Earth and other groups had sued Laidlaw
Environmental Services for letting a hazardous-waste incinerator
release mercury into the North Tyger River at Roebuck, Va. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the lawsuit was filed, Laidlaw stopped the polluting, but
then a judge fined the company $405,800. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Virginia overturned the
fine, saying that a fine paid to the government did not serve as a
remedy for a private group's complaint. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the ruling meant that a company, if it is sued by a
private group, can avoid a fine by simply stopping its pollution
when a lawsuit is filed. Often, those lawsuits are filed privately
because government won't or can't take action against polluters,
they said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Very simply, citizen suits provide a necessary tool for both
private individuals and states to deal with significant
environmental problems,'' Nixon said. ``They take away the excuse
for politicians and their elected officials not to act.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon filed a brief on behalf of 13 states saying that citizen
lawsuits ``fill the gap in Clean Water Act enforcement left by a
lack of government resources.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, citizen lawsuits have stopped pollution caused by
runoff from hog- and chicken-rendering operations, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a necessary and vital part of the regulatory
process,'' Nixon said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But some corporations say environmental groups have gone
overboard with expensive, prolonged lawsuits that involve minor or
already corrected violations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizen suits are valuable in certain cases, but this is much
ado about nothing,'' said Donald Cockrill, who will argue the case
before the Supreme Court for Laidlaw, now known as Safety-Kleen
Inc. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cockrill said lawsuits were justified if the pollution actually
was harmful and if the state or the federal Environmental
Protection Agency refused to act. In the case in question, the
levels of mercury were far from harmful, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cockrill said the main issue for the court to decide should be
whether a citizens group has standing in court to seek financial
penalties that are paid to the government, although he said there
is no guarantee the ruling will resolve that point. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2337EDT &QL; 
