<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-ARREST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN INDIANA KILLINGS IS CAPTURED IN INDEPENDENCE, MO. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TANYANIKA SAMUELS  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Independence, Mo., police early Thursday morning arrested an
Indianapolis man wanted for questioning in the death of his wife
and baby son, whose bodies were found in a freezer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John K. Adams, 24, has not been charged with killing his family,
but he is wanted on two armed robbery charges in Indiana. He was
being held without bond at the Independence jail. On Thursday
afternoon, investigators from Indianapolis were on their way to
Independence to question him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of Adams' wife and son were found Sept. 22 in a
freezer in the family's home in Indianapolis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday in Independence, while on routine patrol, Police
Officer Aaron Gieszen noticed a van parked in a secluded area
behind a power substation at Kiger and Lee's Summit roads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect he (Adams) had just pulled off I-70 and was looking
for a place to sleep back there when the police officer found
him,'' Independence Police Chief Gary George said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A check of the license plate showed that the vehicle was
reported lost or stolen, said Detective Sgt. Terry Storey. Gieszen
called for backup. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adams was sleeping in the van when police approached. A computer
check revealed that Adams was wanted in Indianapolis. Police
confiscated a handgun at the scene, George said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who since his arrest has threatened to harm himself, is
under a suicide watch, the chief said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 22, Indianapolis police went to arrest Adams on two
counts each of armed robbery, criminal confinement and carrying a
handgun without a license in connection with holdups at two
restaurants, according to Sgt. Doug Schessel of the Marion County
Sheriff's Department in Indiana. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adams wasn't there, but police entered his home and found two
bodies in a freezer. They had been wrapped in blue plastic
tarpaulins and bound with duct tape. The bodies were later
identified as those of Adams' wife, Robin Schafer-Adams, 24, and
their 10-month-old son, John Ramseys Adams. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The woman had been shot to death and the baby had been
strangled, according to the Marion County coroner's office.
Authorities think the bodies had been in the freezer as long as
three months. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
