<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0494 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-LIKHACHEV-NYT &LR;      09-30 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LIKHACHEV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DMITRI LIKHACHEV, 92, GUARDIAN OF RUSSIA'S HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Dmitri Likhachev, a Russian literary scholar revered as
a guardian of national culture and a voice of reason and moral
authority, died Thursday in a hospital in St. Petersburg. He was
92.
</P>
<P>
   During the past decade of turbulent change in Russia, Likhachev,
a gentle, elegant man who spoke with the measured eloquence of the
pre-Bolshevik intelligentsia, was frequently sought out by
politicians and commentators as a referee in the churning debate
over history.
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin, who consulted Likhachev on cultural and
historical issues, was ``deeply grieved'' by his death, said a
spokesman Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, as Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev
loosened the Communist Party's grip on culture and history,
Likhakhev was enlisted as chairman of the newly established Soviet
Cultural Fund, a foundation that sponsored cultural and restoration
projects with active support from Gorbachev's wife, Raisa, who died
Sept. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1906, the son of a St. Petersburg lithographer,
Likhachev witnessed the 1917 Russian Revolution, the civil war and
the subsequent economic and political upheavals that destroyed the
society he was born into.
</P>
<P>
   While a student at Leningrad State University in 1928, he was
arrested and sentenced to exile in the Solovetsky Islands, the most
notorious of the early labor camps. Like so many arrests at the
time, the reason was spurious: Likhachev was with some students who
were celebrating an anniversary, and a friend sent them a telegram
that pretended to be congratulations from the pope. The entire
group was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   From his four years in the camps, Likhachev gained first-hand
knowledge of the brutality of the Soviet regime. In an incident
that would haunt him through his life, he was selected to be shot
in a random execution in 1929 in retribution for a mass escape. He
spotted his name on the list and hid. For the rest of his life, he
recounted in an interview years later, ``I have had to live two
lives: my own and the life of a man whose name I do not even
know.''
</P>
<P>
   In his final years, he also recalled how he made use of the
experience, listening carefully and with fascination to the tales
and the language of the common criminals who were mixed in with
political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   As a scholar, Likhachev was known for his work on Russian
medieval literature. He returned from the camps to a job as a
literary editor, and went on to become a researcher at the
Institute of Russian Literature and a professor of history at
Leningrad University. In 1970 he was made a full member of the
Soviet Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   In his last years, Likhachev was a scholar-in-residence at
Pushkin House _ the Institute of Russian Literature in St.
Petersburg _ where he received a steady stream of visitors in a
modest but handsomely decorated second-floor office with a view of
the SS. Peter and Paul fortress.
</P>
<P>
   Likhachev was honored abroad for his work, and was made a
corresponding member of the Austrian, U.S., British and Italian
academies of arts and sciences.
</P>
<P>
   At home, where he was regarded with deep affection and awe by
fellow intellectuals, he was presented last year with the Order of
St. Andrew, the first person to receive the czarist-era medal since
1917.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the end of an era,'' said Vladimir Gusev, director of
St. Petersburg's Russian Museum, in a television interview Thursday
night. ``I hope it is not the end of the era of cultured people. I
hope he was not the last of the Mohicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he never was a political dissident like Andrei
Sakharov, the physicist who won a Nobel Peace Prize, Likhachev,
like Sakharov, became a reference point for Russians who, after the
fall of communism, were left trying to retrieve a cultural heritage
that had been distorted by the communist experience.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed in 1985 by Moscow News, a newspaper that was then at
the forefront of Gorbachev's campaign for ``glasnost'' or openness,
Likhachev emphasized the importance of culture and history in the
preservation of national consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should regard history from the `observation platform' of
our times,'' he said. ``And this platform is not immobile; it
constantly rises higher and higher, opening ever new horizons
before us. That is why the science of history can never be canned,
or provide us with the ultimate truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other members of the Russian intelligentsia, Likhachev was
deeply disappointed by the violence, greed and vulgarity that
surfaced in Russian society after the fall of communism.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last year, he recalled how even his fellow
inmates in the Solovetsky camp refused to associate with murderers.
In modern Russia, he noted, people regard ``killers'' _ he used the
English word _ as professionals like any other.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed this on decades of communist rule that had subjected
people to a twisted version of history. ``Morality was perverted,''
he said. ``Marxism reduced history to the most ignoble of
motives.''
</P>
<P>
   But he remained a staunch defender of Russia's new freedoms, and
dismissed popular nostalgia for the stability of the Soviet era.
``Imagine how it was here 10 years ago,'' he said, recalling the
days of bugged telephones and informers who used to lurk outside
his office door.
</P>
<P>
   In his last years, Likhachev continued to lobby the Russian
government on behalf of educational projects like the financing of
a national television station devoted to culture.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference last year, he stressed the moral imperative
of maintaining and raising Russia's cultural standards. ``A lot of
jealousy is the result of people not realizing themselves
culturally,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he was also critical of showcase projects, like the $350
million reconstruction of the Cathedral of Christ the Savior in
Moscow, which he described as looking ``something like a prefab
kit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Spending so much money on a huge cathedral in the center of
Moscow makes me embarrassed before the many parts of the country
where there is not a church for hundreds of kilometers,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-30-99 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990930.0495 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2973 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SPRINT-MERGER-KAN &LR;      09-30 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MERGER-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Sprint to dedicate campus today amid rumors of a possible merger  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH and TED SICKINGER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprint Corp. today dedicates its huge new Overland Park campus
amid rumors of a possible merger with rival MCI WorldCom Inc. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Company officials won't cut ribbons because workers have been
moving to the campus since July. But thousands of area employees
and civic leaders are wondering if Sprint Chairman William Esrey
will cut a deal instead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That question hangs like a cloud over a ceremony celebrating the
opening of the first buildings on the projected $920 million office
campus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a universal sense of holding one's breath,''
said Robert Marcusse, president of the Kansas City Area Development
Council. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sprint is the area's biggest private-sector employer, most
voracious user of office space, a generous community donor and a
major source of civic pride. But Sprint also is big game in a
worldwide telecommunications feeding frenzy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that we are highly
sensitive to this,'' said Mary Birch, president of the Overland
Park Chamber of Commerce. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information is in short supply for the company's 15,000 area
employees because Sprint management has yet to make any statement
on its talks with MCI WorldCom, internally or publicly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Regulators forbid companies to deny merger talks when they are
proceeding because that might mislead investors. But companies can
simply refuse to comment _ indefinitely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Esrey is expected to make a brief statement to the media after
the ceremony Friday, but he may simply repeat the company's refusal
to ``comment on speculation.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The potential effect of a Sprint//MCI WorldCom deal on area
employment is difficult to gauge and would ultimately depend on how
a deal was structured, how much MCI WorldCom paid for the company
and what conditions regulators applied. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot allow any merger to happen in this (long-distance
telephone) industry that turns back the clock on competition,''
U.S. Federal Communications Commission Chairman William Kennard
said Thursday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But most observers agree that a deal would result _ at least in
the short term _ in a diminished area payroll, decreased demand for
local office space and weaker ties to the community. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After building their company through scores of acquisitions, MCI
WorldCom Chairman Bernie Ebbers and his team have a reputation as
aggressive cost cutters, and would be looking to realize big
savings to offset any premium that they paid for Sprint. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's corporate headquarters staff might be quick to feel the
pain. Most analysts speculate that in the event of a merger,
Sprint's management team would leave the combined company. They
also think MCI WorldCom would quickly cut redundant legal, finance
and marketing positions to realize the maximum savings in the first
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The greatest operational overlap of MCI and Sprint is in their
long-distance and data operations. Both companies have sales and
marketing staff to serve the business and residential market, and
staff to support their respective networks, many of whom would be
vulnerable as the company melded operations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In February, MCI WorldCom agreed to outsource all of its
application development, maintenance agreements and infrastructure
services to Electronic Data Systems of Plano, Texas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, MCI WorldCom has almost no presence in the
wireless market and would probably see little reason to move Sprint
PCS's fast-growing operations out of Kansas City or cut its
employment significantly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sprint PCS now employs about 3,300 employees in the city, plus
about 1,000 contract workers. Employment growth has been explosive
_ the company employed 328 in Kansas City at the end of 1995 _ but
is leveling off. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sprint also has local operations in 19 states, with little
overlap with MCI's operations. Sprint North Supply and Directory
Publishing might also be relatively unaffected by the move, if the
combined company didn't decide to sell the company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When WorldCom acquired MCI last year for $40 billion, the
company began cutting costs immediately. By December, MCI WorldCom
announced that it would cut 1,850 workers, or 2.5 percent of the
payroll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 170 of those jobs were in MCI's home territory of
Washington, D.C., Virginia and Maryland. WorldCom's cuts were
deeper in other markets, such as Dallas, where the company
eliminated 300 jobs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom also has been digesting huge amounts of real
estate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before closing the deal with MCI, WorldCom bought a giant tract
in northern Virginia with plans for a major corporate campus for
its Internet-access division. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom owns 534 acres in Loudoun County and is building
1.3 million square feet of office space. The office park could
ultimately accommodate as much as 7.5 million square feet, said
Larry Rosenstrauch, the county's director of economic development.
That's nearly twice the size of Sprint's new campus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As its Loudoun County campus grows, MCI WorldCom has been
shifting some workers there and is exploring the possible sale of
MCI's longtime headquarters. The MCI campus is expected to have
4,500 workers by the end of the year, and ultimately could house
30,000 workers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom pursued its suburban locale while passing on a
generous subsidy offer from Washington, D.C., to build a new $100
million headquarters office in the city. Richard Monteilh,
executive director of the D.C. Chamber of Commerce, said
negotiations died soon after WorldCom officials took over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger came along and that's when things stopped,''
Monteilh said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But WorldCom never planned to pull up its Mississippi roots for
the Virginia suburbs. In fact, the MCI WorldCom in May moved into a
new 420,000-square-foot headquarters complex on 84 acres in
Clinton, Miss. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom's acquisition deals have tended to stall _ at least
temporarily _ the construction projects of potential merger
partners as the companies work out details. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Gardner, spokesman for the Missouri Department of Economic
Development, said MCI canceled a major expansion of a service
center near St. Louis after WorldCom announced its offer to buy
MCI. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months later, the combined MCI WorldCom announced that
it would build a $50 million expansion of its National Account
Service Center. The project is expected to create 1,300 jobs and
keep about 1,000 existing jobs in the St. Louis area, Gardner
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the merger, this project was seen as important
enough to complete,'' Gardner said. ``We see an analogy with
Sprint, that a project as significant as (the Overland Park campus)
would be seen as an opportunity that makes good business sense to
keep.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
