<HEADER>
A2976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-2TA     09-30 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 THE STUDIED, THE BUOYANT AND THE SILLY  (ART ADV: Photo is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By   GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ This is a city that disguises itself well; it is
Marcello Mastroianni on the outside and Gidget underneath. No
matter how full the streets are with perfectly attired men cycling
to work, no matter how decorous the homes and offices, Milan is a
city whose people are capable of egregious transgressions of
urbanity.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday evening, on the second day of the spring 2000
collections, a photography exhibition called ``Beauty in Progress''
opened at a local gallery. Soon after the event started, there was
noise and commotion: someone important was apparently about to
arrive. Naomi Campbell!
</P>
<P>
   Although the American fashion editors inside simply wanted to
get out and move along, those who stayed for Ms. Campbell's
entrance witnessed their Italian counterparts screaming and
stumbling over one another in pure excitement.
</P>
<P>
   The giddiness was just a prelude to events two days later, at
the collection of Giorgio Armani, the man who has long stood for
the cool grown-up aspect of the Italian personality. Armani is now
showing in a new space, a sleekly converted Nestle factory he
bought.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its layout and also perhaps because of the show's
late start, celebrities were paraded down the runway to their
seats, the chic masses already in their high chairs to behold them.
The crowd was not subdued. There were cheers for Tina Turner and
Sophia Loren and even more song and dance for Ricky Martin.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard not to feel somewhat sorry for Glenn Close _ a woman
who would have found her way into an Armani suit even if the man
had never taken pencil to sketch pad. But as she entered, she was
ignored by the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   When the collection came through on the backs of approximately
75 models, you had to wonder how many of the looks were conceived
with Ms. Close and women like her _ Armani's mainstay _ in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Printed fabrics were to be the heart of the collection, Armani
had said at his showroom this week. There were ethereally beautiful
painted silk skirts and pretty, painted shantung cigarette pants.
But these were not clothes to project earnestness, either at the
Oscars or a stockholders' meeting. Jackets were typically short,
open, revealing. Pants were short-waisted.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Armani has been incorporating more color into
his collections. No one can fault him for refusing to cling
eternally to beige, but his exuberance seemed too studied and
misguided this time out. There were tie-dye cashmeres, limes and
fuchsias set against black, Kandinsky-inspired prints paired with
sequins, or sequined minis over print skirts teamed with black
bras.
</P>
<P>
   On and on went the fuss. There was nothing spontaneous in these
final pieces, which is to say there wasn't all that much that felt
truly youthful, and surely, that was supposed to be the point of
the whole affair. After it ended, all streamed out to the former
factory's cleanly appointed anteroom to celebrate Armani's new
fragrance, which, by the way, is called Mania.
</P>
<P>
   Jil Sander managed a fine job of turning out a collection that
possessed a levity that was unforced. As always, her fabrics lure
you in closer and closer. She had culottes of sueded polyester
fleece, long-sleeve shirts of paper cotton, a double-face leather
wrap skirt. There were rayon-silk skirts with cascading folds in
front, even a few inside-out cotton prints.
</P>
<P>
   After the show, Ms. Sander said she was inspired by the ``warm
weather in Hamburg,'' her hometown. It is Ms. Sander's personality,
high minded, confident, uneffusive, that has often led casual
observers to call her clothes ``intellectual,'' which happily isn't
what they're about. It would be hard to make that mistake with this
collection, in particular, which seems aimed at a woman who can
take quiet pleasure in life without the need of an psychotherapist
to accomplish it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If there is a man in Milan who might want to let go of his need
to have everyone believe he is the Brainiest Man in Fashion, it is
Gianfranco Ferre. The invitation to his show came with a
coffee-table book in which he pays homage to himself.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with the words, ``As everyone knows, that unabashed
and patient traveler, Alberto Moravia ... '' Is it stating the
obvious to say that his architectural clothes were equally
pretentious and silly? Lampshade dresses? Gold-painted breasts?
</P>
<P>
   Over at Genny, where Belgian Joseph Thimister is in charge,
there were exquisite skirts that achieved their goal of fluid
movement. There were airy black-ribbed skirts of papery silk and
lovely neutral chiffons. There was plenty to desire, even if the
show at times felt a bit somber because of lugubrious music. Also
included in the collection was a series of fluorescent clothes, but
they somehow lacked the sense of party-tonight-in-Los Feliz _
surely their only purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Taking flashy clothes a bit too seriously had other precedents
in Milan this week. Designer Alessandro Dell'Aqua, who a few
seasons ago sent out invitations on flesh-toned underwear, has
never been known for underplaying sexuality in his clothes. This
time, his frame of reference, like Tom Ford's at Gucci, was early
1980s disco.
</P>
<P>
   The scrunched leather patterned high-heel boots he showed had
fashion editors and buyers disturbingly titillated. Listening to
supremely tasteful women suggest they want to look like Heather
Locklear in ``Dynasty'' has the effect of hearing someone like
Daniel Boulud say he only eats Tater Tots at home. You sense it's a
lie. At any rate, you know you could never get away with that kind
of thing yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Narciso Rodriguez also immersed himself in the early Reagan
period, but his interpretation never let you forget that he is the
man who designed one of the world's best-known wedding dresses (for
Carolyn Bessette Kennedy). He worked in black and white, metallic,
gauze and sequins, but his lines were clean, more structured.
Rodriguez did not feel the need to sacrifice his larger vision of
how a woman should look to some notion of soigne vulgarity.
</P>
<P>
   There were fresh ideas, largely free of retro references, in the
collection of Mila Schoen. The label has been here for quite some
time, but is now produced by a team of 12 designers, many of them
recent graduates of St. Martin's College of Art and Design in
London. Jackets, skirts and tops were cut economically in a manner
reminiscent of Geoffrey Beene. Seams had a purpose. Lines followed
the body's curves. There were bold geometric prints and
sophisticated flesh-tone beaded gowns.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the audience suddenly lacked that bedraggled, midweek,
someone-save-me-with-another-espresso look. They were up, eager to
see what would come next. Even the models looked enthusiastic,
maybe because they finally didn't look as though their next stop in
Milan was a flight to Danceteria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
