<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS FALL FURTHER BACK AS BRAVES WIN IN 11 INNINGS, 4-3  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Through all the agony and angst of the last 10 days,
the New York Mets had not faced anything quite this gut-wrenching.
At no point in this brutal stretch had so much been riding on a
single outcome as in Thursday night's game with the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   But after coming back three times at Shea Stadium, the Mets were
beaten, 4-3, in 11 innings, and with the last weekend of the season
at hand, the Mets are two games behind in the National League
wild-card race with three to play.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets lose to Pittsburgh Friday night, and Houston and
Cincinnati win, the Mets will be eliminated just 12 days after
holding a four-game lead in the wild-card race. Even if the Mets
sweep the Pirates in three games this weekend, the Astros or the
Reds would have to lose twice for New York to force a one-game
playoff on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who cannot seem to make anything easy lately,
ratcheted up their madness meter a few notches Thursday night. They
extended a taut game with the Braves into extra innings, riding
through an early deficit, a disappointing effort from their
bullpen, a dramatic game-tying home run by Edgardo Alfonzo and a
brilliant two-inning relief effort by Armando Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   But as if they were trying to desperately hold sand in their
hands, they watched the game slip through their fingers in the 11th
inning, bit by bit, until there was little more than dust left of
their season.
</P>
<P>
   With rookie Octavio Dotel on the mound in just his fifth relief
appearance, Brian Jordan opened the Braves' 11th with a triple over
Shawon Dunston's head in right field on a play in which Dunston
appeared to misplay the fly. Jordan scored on Ozzie Guillen's short
sacrifice fly to center.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton, who made the slightly off-line throw home,
kneeled in the grass after the run scored, as if acknowledging that
the Mets were terribly close to bowing out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets trailed by 3-2 in the bottom of the eighth because
their bullpen, so solid for so much of the season, had unraveled in
the top of the inning. Turk Wendell allowed a leadoff single to
Keith Lockhart. That brought Chipper Jones to the plate and
left-handed John Franco to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Franco had gone eight appearances without yielding a run, and
had allowed just two hits in his last six. Manager Bobby Valentine
had tried this trick once before, bringing in a left-hander to face
the switch-hitting Jones, who is thought to be better from the left
side. The last time the Mets tried it, Jones belted a home run to
win the first game of a series last week in Atlanta. This time he
hit a single that scored the tie-breaking run.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Ventura cut off the throw from left, but did not
immediately look to second, so Jones advanced there. Ryan Klesko
followed with a single that put Jones on third and Jordan walked to
load the bases. Franco was replaced amid boos.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and none out, the Mets were on the brink
of losing almost any chance at the postseason with one swing. But
Pat Mahomes relieved and got Andruw Jones to ground into a double
play when Ventura stepped on third and Chipper Jones was caught in
a rundown between third and home. Guillen ended the threat with a
flyout.
</P>
<P>
   There were two out in the Mets' eighth when Alfonzo went to the
plate. He has been in a slump since his extraordinary 6-for-6,
three-homer performance in Houston more than a month ago. And he
was just 1 for 11 on this homestand. But reliever Mike Remlinger
sent a 2-1 slider to Alfonzo, who sent it into the left-field
bullpen. The score was tied, 3-3, 48,364 roared and the Mets lived
on.
</P>
<P>
   The managers battled with their closers in the ninth, Benitez
retiring the side to set the stage for the bottom of the ninth.
Manager Bobby Cox of the Braves put in his stopper, John Rocker,
who struck out Mike Piazza on a checked swing. An infuriated Piazza
argued the call with the home plate umpire, Phil Cuzzi, until
Valentine retrieved him.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rocker struck out Ventura and Hamilton, forcing extra
innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
